<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS CAN'T FIND HER RHYTHM AND IS OUSTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ The surface was still green, hard and
quick. The lines were still white. But the tennis that Serena
Williams produced in this Grand Slam event bore little resemblance
to the tennis she produced on her way to the title at the U.S. Open
in September.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no surprised stumble along the baseline after
match point on the final weekend; no phone conversation with Bill
Clinton and his daughter, Chelsea. Williams made sure of that on
Monday in the fourth round of the Australian Open, when she beat
herself as much as Yelena Likhovtseva beat her.
</P>
<P>
   The final score was 6-3, 6-3 and Williams, seeded third, was off
rhythm nearly from the start against the 16th-seeded Russian, who
has an all-court game but rarely had to make full use of it against
her gaffe-prone opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Williams made 32 unforced errors: an average of nearly two per
game. And it was altogether appropriate that her last shot of this
surprisingly short match was a backhand that struck the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for me to have lost this match,'' she said.
``I couldn't find my rhythm throughout the match. It was strange. I
was moving well in practice and not making any errors, but I just
couldn't find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, there might be another Williams
still in the draw to keep the family's hopes alive. But Serena's
older sister, Venus, withdrew from this event shortly before it
began, citing a wrist injury, and now there will be no beaded,
seeded Floridians to occupy the opposition and the
autograph-seekers for the rest of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Serena was not certain that she would even play in this event at
one stage in December. ``I just changed my mind,'' she said last
week. ``I thought that if I didn't come that maybe my ranking would
slip because I saw that Mary Pierce was coming up behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   That at least is no longer a worry. Pierce was upset in the
fourth round by Ai Sugiyama on Sunday. But in a sense, Williams'
indecision about playing here was reflected by her indecision on
the court. She was pushed to three sets in her opening match by
Amanda Grahame, a little-known Australian, and though she played
better in the third round against Sabine Appelmans, she resumed
struggling again today after taking a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' she said. ``I just started making too many
errors. Maybe I started thinking too far in the match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
