<SLUG> BC-MUJERES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIVA LA FEMINISTA: WOMEN'S LIVES ARE SLOWLY IMPROVING IN MACHO
MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYA MIZRAHI  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Not long ago, the Mexico City government tried to
make a switch. It called for a one-day experiment in which all
married women would exchange jobs with their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, husbands were asked to clean house, wash dishes, do
laundry and take care of kids.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that would have been unthinkable only a few years
ago, when Mexico's middle class was the confirmed center of
masculine privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But things are slowly changing in this homeland  &QL; 
of machismo.
</P>
<P>
   For example, beginning in August, 900 policemen in Mexico City
lost their authority to write traffic tickets. That authority was
given only to policewomen, who were deemed less corruptible by the
city's police chief.
</P>
<P>
   And consider some numbers: 50 percent of the people now
graduating from universities in Mexico are women, and half a dozen
women occupy high-ranking posts in Mexican governments, including
Rosario Robles, the first female mayor of Mexico City _ the biggest
city in the world _ and Rosario Green, Mexico's foreign relations
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The changes perhaps were best summed up by Monica Almazan, a
policewoman patrolling the Condessa neighborhood: ``Finally, we
have the opportunity to show the men that we can take on a job
which is supposed to be for men only. We now have the chance to
prove ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Is feminism taking root in the hard soil of Mexican culture? The
answer is complicated because it depends on what kind of feminism
you mean. But it is accurate to say that a Mexican women's movement
is emerging on the American model, with women making some gains in
industry and government, while still blocked by institutional and
cultural barriers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that the struggle for women's rights in
Mexico is nearly as old as the country itself. &QL; 
GROWING INDEPENDENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It can be seen today in the growing independence of
working-class women along the border, and in a National Women's
Commission that is confronting stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Or in Mexico's efforts to improve family planning, because
unwanted teenage pregnancies are high and legal abortion is
restricted tightly.
</P>
<P>
   More women are entering legislative bodies and demanding more
laws to ban job discrimination and provide more money and health
care to women in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And in pop culture, women are flocking to male strip shows that
feature some of the country's biggest soap-opera stars, prompting a
Catholic priest in Guanajuato to admonish on the radio, ``Rush to
confession!''
</P>
<P>
   The events, and the history behind them, defy outside notions of
a nation content with machismo.
</P>
<P>
   Among what loosely might be called the Spanish aristocracy of
Mexico and, in a vastly different way, among its peasants and
working women, Mexico has been a cradle of feminism for the entire
Western Hemisphere. &QL; 
FIRST FEMINIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Mexicans and feminists everywhere celebrated the 300th
anniversary of the death in 1695 of Sor (Sister) Juana Ines
(EDITORS: ACCENT over ``E'' in InEs) de la Cruz, often acknowledged
as the ``first feminist of the Americas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sor Juana lived from 1651 to 1695 and now is regarded widely as
Mexico's greatest writer, akin to Shakespeare in the
English-speaking world. Her published works include more than 120
sonnets and ballads, many more short poems, three one-act dramas,
two comedies, more than two dozen prologues to plays and numerous
songs, carols and hymns.
</P>
<P>
   Her most popular work, however, is the poem that begins:
``Hombres necios que acusais (EDITORS: ACCENT MARK ove ``A'' in
acusAis) . . .'' _ ``You foolish men who accuse women . . .'' The
poem is memorized by literature students across Latin America
because it strikes at the heart of male attitudes toward women.
</P>
<P>
   But Sor Juana's best defense of women's role is found in a more
obscure work, a response to a bishop who had written a letter
attempting to silence her. (This work and the poem, ``Philosophical
Satire,'' are translated and edited by Electa Arenal and Amanda
Powell in ``The Answer/La Respuesta, Including a Selection of Poems
(by) Sor Juana Inez de la Cruz,'' City University of New York
Press).
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sor Juana was an aristocrat. More commonly, the tough
work for equality was performed by women who were literally in the
trenches, the ``soldaderas'' (soldiers), who included many officers
in their numbers and fought in the revolutionary armies of Pancho
Villa and Emiliano Zapata (their story has been preserved in a book
by Elizabeth Salas, ``Soldaderas: Mitos e Historia.''. Even today,
as soldiers in the largely Mayan independence movement in Chiapas
state, women take up arms, not least for the fact that Indian women
still may be sold into marriage for the equivalent of $400.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades after the revolution, there were women such as
Benita Galeana, a grass-roots leader who led the first squatter
land-takeovers in Mexico City in the Depression years of the 1930s.
She was arrested 60 times and almost lost her eyesight from hunger
strikes while fighting for Mexican women's suffrage, which was
finally won in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the companera (TILDE OVER ``N'' in compaNera) in the
braids speak,'' was the cry in the 1930s when Benita Galeana would
come to address the crowds in Mexico City. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRIMER FOR FEMINISTS
</P>
<P>
   In 1940, she wrote her autobiography, ``Benita,'' which became a
primer for the women's movement. Her book and her legacy were
rediscovered in the 1980s, when Mexican women formed a coalition to
fight for democracy and an end to violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   Benita Galeana was able to unite working- and middle-class women
for the first time despite profound philosophical differences
between the two groups concerning the role of men and class in the
struggle. But even she wasn't able to bring the movement to the
point that the Mexican government would identify its own interests
with those of the women's movement. That took nearly three
generations of factory women, the foot soldiers of a blue-collar
cultural insurgency in Tijuana that is slowly spreading from the
border south into the rest of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by economic crisis, the immigration to the United
States of male heads of household and the demand for female
employees at border factories, these women, like Rosie the Riveter
of World War II America, were the first to break en masse into
Mexico's male-dominated industrial workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Their relative autonomy, accelerated by liberal U.S. social
attitudes and economic benefits that have drifted across the
border, has granted working-class women an unusual degree of
domestic clout and social freedom, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forces of progress are stirring themselves up much more
along the border,'' said Susan Tiano, a sociology professor at the
University of New Mexico and author of ``Patriarchy on the Line,''
a book on the effect of the ``maquiladoras'' on border gender
roles. ``Some amazing changes happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Women in Tijuana come and go as they please, working night
shifts and shopping at 24-hour supermarkets. Women hit the discos
on weekends, with or without male escorts. Some wear tight pants
and miniskirts. Unmarried mothers are not pariahs.
</P>
<P>
   There are serious social problems for women in the border
workplace. Low pay (the average wage is around 80 cents an hour,
and independent unions are discouraged), sexual harassment and
gender barriers to higher-paying jobs prevent factory women from
raising their status.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, including a number of U.S.-owned factories and
border-region ``maquiladora'' manufacturing plants, force job
applicants to take pregnancy tests and will hire them only if the
exams are negative. And although women's role in the workforce has
doubled to 30 percent since 1980, female workers still earn 25
percent less than men in the same jobs, says Elena Azaola, a social
anthropologist.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is widely acknowledged that blue-collar women are
creating a new female archetype to reckon with in Mexican society,
and that has been lost neither on the government nor on
middle-class women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, known by
its Spanish acronym PRI, and its standard-bearer, President Ernesto
Zedillo, taking note of the fact that 70 percent of Mexicans who
are illiterate are women, announced a new social-service program
aimed primarily at women and girls. &QL; 
LEGISLATIVE GAINS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish acronym
PRD, which focused heavily on women's issues in the past
presidential campaign, has been contributing to the rise of women
in Mexico's legislative bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 elections, the party doubled its number of female
deputies in the lower house to 30, giving it the largest percentage
of female elected officials of any of the three major parties
represented in the 500-seat Mexican parliament.
</P>
<P>
   All of these changes contributed to the creation of a National
Women's Commission, intended to confront double standards. In 1998,
it launched an American-style advertising campaign questioning
whether society could advance if comments such as these were
allowed to go unchallenged:
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the director. I wonder how she got there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband can do what he wants, because he is a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you pregnant? I told you to take care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the campaign offered statements affirming a new
attitude:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the director, and I did not sleep with anybody to get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to sleep around to be a man, and I also use
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Machismo will not make for a smooth adjustment to any changes,
but some see change as inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican man idolizes women as `the Mother,' and he will
not tolerate her being contaminated,'' said Alejandro Radchik,
president of the Psychoanalytic Society in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a society where `la casa chica' _ the little house for
the mistress _ is common, not because the husband no longer loves
his wife but because, once she becomes the mother of his children,
sex becomes a dirty act that will contaminate her,'' Radchik said.
</P>
<P>
   `The Mother is her own worst enemy. She is the one educating her
sons, the Mexican men, to be macho and preparing her daughters to
be good mothers and housewives.''
</P>
<P>
   How about the future? Many women believe there is good reason to
hope. With women representing 53 percent of Mexican voters,
presidential candidates campaigning for what is hoped could be the
most competitive democratic election in Mexican history in July,
middle-class women could achieve a measure of political power _
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, (the Mexican man) will react by trying to belittle
her and by being condescending,'' Radchik said. ``When this
attitude does not lead to his desired effect, he will acquiesce to
this new feminine authority.'' &QL; 
Contributing to this article were Republic librarian Joanne Dawson,
Republic artist Jeanne Hernandez, Republic staff writer Richard
Nilsen, Ideas editor Dave Wagner and contributing members of the
Associated Press. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
