<HEADLINE>
RAMS SHADE TAMPA BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ This whole dream of a season was slipping away and
Ricky Proehl knew it. It was the fourth quarter, ``and we've been
explosive all season and when you look up at the scoreboard and
it's 6-5,'' said the St. Louis wide receiver, ``you just feel so
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was coming easily. ``They seemed to know what was
coming,'' Rams quarterback Kurt Warner said of the Buccaneers, and
never more so than earlier in that fourth quarter when Tampa Bay
defensive back Brian Kelly saw the St. Louis formation, signaled
back to his safety, and confidently stepped inside Torry Holt's
slant pattern and picked off a Warner pass.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis eventually won this tractor pull of an NFC
Championship Game, 11-6, Sunday and clinched the city's first Super
Bowl appearance, but with just under five minutes left, the
scoreboard was frozen in that 6-5 baseball mode, and the Rams'
once-explosive offense seemed dead.
</P>
<P>
   And Warner's big sister for this magical season, Cinderella,
seemingly had left the Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had the ball on the Tampa Bay 30 but Rams kicker Jeff
Wilkins's leg was hurting and St. Louis needed many more yards
before even a field goal could be attempted. All game long the
Bucs' ``Cover-2'' zone pass defense had stolen the Rams' passion _
the deep ball _ and forced Warner to dink and dab underneath. But
even those short passes now were suspect because Tampa Bay was
reading the Rams' formations and jumping those routes.
</P>
<P>
   It was third and 4. The play called, said Proehl, was named
``585-H'' and it called for Proehl to run an 18-yard route to the
left sideline. But the play's primary target was Marshall Faulk
coming out of the backfield for the short pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there had been a TV timeout before the play,'' Proehl went
on, ``and Kurt and I were able to talk in the huddle before the
play. Kurt said, `If the safety comes (on a blitz) from the middle
of the field, we're going on a fade.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Proehl lined up on the left. He had 35 catches this season and
25 of them had been for first downs, so the veteran was clearly a
clutch, possession receiver. But he had yet to catch a touchdown
pass.
</P>
<P>
   When he lined up, Proehl noticed that ``their guy (Kelly) was
`squatting,' expecting me to run a slant or a hitch.'' But, at the
last instant, Proehl noticed that a Tampa Bay safety indeed was
coming on a blitz, just as Warner had warned, ``and I adjusted to a
fade route deep.''
</P>
<P>
   As Warner saw the safety coming, ``I didn't think I'd have
enough time to look anywhere, and I knew Ricky was adjusting to a
`go' route,'' said the Rams QB. ``So I threw it deep to Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the only time all game that any St. Louis receiver had
gotten behind a Tampa Bay defender, ``and I just knew I had to
catch the ball. But their guy hit me a little just as the ball got
there, and I think I juggled it a little,'' said Proehl. To be
precise, the tip of the ball was sticking out of the crook of one
arm and seemed ready to fall to the ground until ``I was able to
grab it and get it back home'' and cradle the ball for a TD.
</P>
<P>
   And home erupted. The dome exploded in noise as the Rams finally
took a lead of more than 2 points this day, their margin all the
way to 5. And if it seemed the Bucs, with rookie Shaun King at
quarterback and conservative offensive coordinator Mike Shula
calling the plays, would be unable to score, all that changed when
King looked for Karl Williams from the Rams' 44 with 1:31 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on him pretty good,'' said veteran Rams cornerback Todd
Lyght, ``but my feet got crossed up in his and I fell and he just
kept on running.'' He caught King's pass for a 22-yard gain to the
Rams 22. ``I wasn't feeling good after that play, but I just knew I
had to make up for it. I had to come up with a big play to stop
them,'' Lyght said.
</P>
<P>
   Bucs defensive end Warren Sapp was on the sideline, watching the
drama build and the anxiety tighten for all. ``The kid (King) has
taken us from behind to win five games,'' said Sapp, ``and I was
sure he was going to do it a sixth time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyght never did make a big play to atone for his tripping and
falling. But St. Louis defensive end Grant Wistrom did, sacking
King for a 13-yard loss on the next play, setting up a
second-and-25. And then the Bucs, the replay official, former
referee Jerry Markbreit, and an oh-so-close decision cut off so
much of the drama that was building.
</P>
<P>
   King completed a 15-yard pass to Bert Emanuel that set up a
more-manageable third and 10 from the 22 with 51 seconds left.
Tampa Bay then used its last timeout _ after squandering its second
timeout for a silly replay challenge earlier in the fourth quarter
that would have given them only 5 more yards if it were upheld, and
it wasn't _ and it seemed that if that timeout were not taken the
replay official might not have had time to challenge the catch.
</P>
<P>
   But, with the timeout, Markbreit was able to study the play and
signaled to referee Bill Carollo to take another look. After
looking at the play, ``It was apparent that the player, as he was
catching the ball, he used the ground and the tip of the ball hit
the ground. By rule, you cannot use the ground, or have assistance
from the ground, to make the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   It made no difference, Carollo went on, that Emanuel's knees may
have hit the ground before the tip of the ball did, just as it made
no difference that Emanuel seemed to have possession of the ball
even though the tip of the ball touched the ground. ``Because the
ball hit the ground, by rule it's an automatic incomplete pass,''
said Carollo.
</P>
<P>
   Now faced with a third and 25 with no timeouts, King fired
incomplete passes on third and fourth downs. And Ricky Proehl
grabbed the George Halas trophy awarded to the NFC champion and
dashed around the Trans World Dome. ``I've been waiting 10 years
for this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Kurt Warner led a victory lap around the field, exulting
that ``this has been a dream of a season, except for one more win
next week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
