<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-JAGUARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE TAMES JACKSONVILLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ It was one of the most painful days in Tom
Coughlin's football life, but he had to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans, champions of the American Football
Conference, are better than his Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us three times this year,'' said Coughlin, ``so I
have to take my hat off to them. They are a very good football
team. They deserve to be going to the Super Bowl. We just didn't
play the quality game we had to play today to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team played a pretty game, but Tennessee was more
resilient, making the bigger plays on both sides of the ball on the
way to an impressive 33-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, formerly the Houston Oilers, are making the first
trip to the Super Bowl in franchise history, and they dominated the
second half, outscoring Jacksonville, 23-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we led, 14-10, at the half,'' said Coughlin, ``I felt
very good about our chances. I thought we were going to win. We had
energy in our locker room at the half. I had no idea what was about
to happen was going to happen. I just didn't think anything like
that could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans deserve to be going to Atlanta. They have beaten the
best the NFL has to offer. They whipped St. Louis during the
regular season, then beat Buffalo, Indianapolis, and Jacksonville
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy being the underdog,'' said Titans defensive tackle
Josh Evans, who made the biggest play of the game when he and Jason
Fisk sacked Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell for a safety in the
third quarter. That helped swing the game Tennessee's way,
particularly when Derrick Mason returned the ensuing free kick 80
yards for a score that put the Titans up, 26-14. ``Every week
people think we are going to lose, and then we win. I hope they
make the same mistake in the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville, behind an electric sellout crowd, looked like the
better team in the first 28 minutes. It led, 14-7, when the first
sign of trouble appeared.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer than two minutes left in the half, Jaguars punt
returner Reggie Barlow fumbed inside his 10, and Al Del Greco
knocked home a 34-yard field goal with 20 seconds left to reduce
the lead to 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it, but I still felt good at that point,'' said
Coughlin. ``But then those kinds of things continued. Penalties,
dropped passes, fumbles, terrible play on our kickoff coverage.
Those kinds of things haven't happened that way to us all year.''
Jacksonville had six turnovers and nine penalties for 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Steve McNair carried the Titans when Jacksonville
shut down Tennessee running back Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an idea that Jacksonville was going to do everything on
defense to stop George,'' said Titans offensive coordinator Les
Steckel. ``So we had Steve throw a little more, and run more than
he had, and he made some great plays.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair ran nine times for 91 yards, scoring two touchdowns. He
also threw a 9-yard touchdown pass in the first quarter that tied
the game at 7.
</P>
<P>
   But the second half was the game.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 14-10, Tennessee waltzed 76 yards in six plays, scoring
on a 1-yard sneak by McNair with 9:24 left in the third. Two
penalties vs. the Jaguars gave the Titans 43 of those 76 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Then, trailing 17-14, the Jaguars were backed up on their 1.
``We called a play we worked on in practice for a situation just
like this,'' said Brunell, who did not have a good day. ``We had
the play. They gave us the defense we were looking for. But we made
a mistake, and I couldn't get the ball away. It happened to us all
day. Bad reads, dropped passes, missed blocks, that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell was sacked in the end zone by Evans and Fisk. ``The guy
in front of me tried to kill me,'' said Evans. ``He came hard down
the line at me, and I beat him with a swim move and had the
opening.''
</P>
<P>
   That gave Tennessee a 19-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point we were still in the game,'' said Coughlin. ``We
were only 5 points down, the game was still in reach. But the
kickoff return made things different. We worked on that all week.
We had great respect for this Mason kid, and he still took it all
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason rolled 80 yards for the score with the ensuing free kick,
opening a 26-14 bulge heading into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The tenacious McNair capped off the great win with a brilliant
51-yard run straight up the middle to the Jacksonville 1, and he
sneaked over on the next play for the final touchdown with 6:59
left.
</P>
<P>
   McNair was 14 of 23 for 112 yards. Brunell, who had receivers
open all day and either couldn't get the ball to them or had them
drop it, finished 19 of 38 for 226 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Taylor of Jacksonville had the edge over George. Taylor
carried 19 times for 110 yards, George 25 times for 86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was smash-mouth football out there,'' said Titans tight
end Frank Wycheck, ``but they couldn't stop us from marching down
the field. We set our minds to do that, and we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a game that's going to stick with us all year,'' said
Coughlin. ``And it's going to be painful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
