<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANT STEP FOR TITANS QB 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ They are the Sons of the Houston Oilers,
which makes quarterback Steve McNair a direct descendant of George
Blanda, Dan Pastorini, and Warren Moon.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans _ with their Oliver Stone uniforms and AFL
Mayflower bloodlines _ are going to Super Bowl XXXIV, also known as
Yahoo Bowl I. They will be led by a QB worthy of his Texan
forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's often-hideous AFC Championship Game, a
mistake-packed thriller on the shores of the St. John River, McNair
led the Titans to a 33-14 victory over the favored hometown
Jaguars. He sealed the deal with a 51-yard keeper followed by a
1-yard TD plunge with seven minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Oft-critiqued for his dearth of touchdown passes and 300-yard
passing games, the 26-year-old, third-year starter has emerged as a
player who gets the job done. He can throw the ball as far as
anybody on the planet, but Tennessee's short-passing game utilizes
his mobility more than his cannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out there just to play football,'' said the Missouri
native. ``We can strike with the passing game, we can strike with
the running game . . . whatever they take away. I've been through a
lot from start to finish: back surgery, not winning the Heisman,
not throwing for so many yards like so many other quarterbacks.''
McNair had surgery for a disk injury earlier this year, and in
1994, after a record-setting career at Division 1-AA Alcorn State,
finished third in voting for the Heisman Trophy behind Rashaan
Salaam and Ki-Jana Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But regardless of what numbers I put up on touchdown passes or
300-yard passing games, we're winning. That's what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes that criticism kind of bothers you mentally. I threw
for over 4,000 yards every year in college, but coming here we had
a different game plan and mentally I had to get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair was not immune from the fumbles and foibles that plagued
players on both squads in this Super Bowl semifinal. He was
intercepted once and lost a fumble. But as Jacksonville's Mark
Brunell melted in the Florida sun (the Jaguars QB was exposed in a
stunning second-half sequence of bad decisions and misplays),
Tennessee's QB took the hits and stood tall to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been suffering from turf toe (big toe, left foot) and wore
a boot all week in practice, but the deepest pain Sunday came from
the helmet of Jacksonville defensive end Tony Brackens (he was the
guy Bill Parcells wanted instead of Terry Glenn). McNair took a
pile-driver shot to the chest, got the wind knocked out of him, and
hit the deck at Alltel Stadium. Nashville cats back home shuddered
at the sight of backup Neil O'Donnell warming up in the bullpen as
three trainers attended to the Titans starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me in the chest and I lost my breath,'' said McNair.
``With that, you just have to be patient and it comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   His breath came back. He threw one touchdown pass and ran for
two other scores. He was a modest 14 of 23 for only 112 yards
passing with a long gain of 15 yards. That's less than an average
half for Drew Bledsoe, but Bledsoe has all the mobility of Al Gore.
McNair can run. McNair can make plays. He ran for 91 yards on nine
carries, including the 51-yard clinching sprint in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Estimable Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin said, ``He's a strong,
strong, physical football player. He's very difficult once he comes
out of that pocket. We had guys with their arms around him a couple
times and they couldn't bring him down.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, there's a phrase for the strategy teams toss at
the Titans. It's called the Dare McNair game plan. It seems to be
failing in this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We throw high-percentage passes and Steve was good with his
decisions,'' said Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher. ``You have to
surround your quarterback with good people and we've done that. For
him to get to the Super Bowl in his third year as a starter, he
should get more respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago Doug Williams led the Redskins into the Super
Bowl, which produced a media-day question that still ranks with the
worst of all-time. A reporter asked Williams, ``Doug, how long have
you been a black quarterback?''
</P>
<P>
   Williams led the Redskins over the Broncos, winning the MVP
Award. McNair already has started hearing the ``black QB''
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a quarterback in the Super Bowl, that's the way I see
it,'' he said. ``I don't get into variations of how people think.
Organizations these days look for people to go out and run a team
and get the job done, regardless of color. There are some great
black quarterbacks in the NFL, but this is something we all dream
of, black or white.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
