<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFCCHAMPIONSHIP-A     01-24 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. LOUIS DEFENDERS ARE BATTERING RAMS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The St. Louis Rams got to the Super Bowl Sunday the
old-fashioned way. They played defense.
</P>
<P>
   For four quarters they played the kind of defense in the NFC
Championship Game that leaves your elbows bleeding and your fingers
gnarled and your body dehydrated. They played the kind of defense
that suffocates an opponent and, in the end, gives life to your own
offense.
</P>
<P>
   That is what was needed to beat the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, proud
owners of the NFL's highest-rated defense, and that is what was
supplied. Suffocating defense. A champion's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they couldn't beat us with 6 points,'' said Rams
defensive tackle Ray Agnew, who once played that position in New
England and will play it in Sunday's Super Bowl against the
Tennessee Titans because he and his mates played so well Sunday
that the Buccaneers could not score a touchdown despite starting
drives at the Rams' 20, 45, 42, and 49 as well as from their own
31, 32, and 34.
</P>
<P>
   On the day, Tampa's average drive began on its 39, meaning on
average it had to go only 61 yards to a touchdown. It never got
there, losing, 11-6, because no one was going to beat the explosive
Rams' offense without scoring a touchdown no matter how good their
own defense was.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week all the talk was about what Tampa Bay's defense could
do,'' Agnew said. ``No one mentioned our defense. We knew we had to
match their defense and we knew we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Buccaneers know they could too because they did. The
Rams played the Buccaneers' game and won. They beat the best
defense in the league at its strength, which led Pro Bowl
cornerback Todd Lyght to make light of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed today that we are the best (defense in the NFL),''
Lyght said, not long after he had slipped and fallen on what
appeared to be a crucial third-down play on Tampa's final drive.
Lyght's slip allowed rookie Shaun King to complete a 21-yard pass
on third and 7 that temporarily put the ball at the Rams' 23 with
85 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   We say temporarily because one play later Grant Wistrom sacked
King for a 13-yard loss and two plays later King was nearly sacked
again on third down and forced to throw the ball away, leaving his
team facing fourth and 23 from the St. Louis 36 with 41 seconds to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Rams had played defense all day, they were not going
to fail to make one more play, which they did by covering King's
receivers so closely he ended up throwing the ball out of the back
of the end zone as the crowd at the Trans World Dome roared its
salute to its suddenly Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we showed the NFL and the world something today,''
said defensive tackle D'Marco Farr. ``The Bucs thought their
defense was going to come in here and walk all over us. We held
them without a touchdown and proved to everyone that we're a pretty
good defensive team, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said Tampa Bay had the best defense but as everyone can
see they're going home. Stats do not mean anything. All that
matters at the end of the game is who has more points. It doesn't
matter what the stats say. You have to go out and perform.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Rams' defense did, limiting the Buccaneers to 203 total
yards with an average gain of just 3.6 yards (to 4.8 yards per play
by the Rams). Most important, they stuffed Tampa's powerful running
game down its throat. In 23 carries, the Bucs' backs averaged just
3.3 yards a carry, gaining only 77 yards on the day to join a list
of 17 previous opponents who could not produce a 100-yard rusher
against this defense nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bucs' defense did more harm to the Rams' running
game and thus forced St. Louis into the kind of defensive struggle
it wanted to avoid, in the end it could not do as much harm to its
adversary as St. Louis did to King and Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs, for example, intercepted three Kurt Warner passes
while St. Louis grabbed only two from King, but the Rams made the
biggest play when Dre Bly picked off a King throw midway through
the fourth quarter with St. Louis trailing, 6-5, and returned it to
the Tampa 48. Six plays later, Warner completed a beautiful fade
route pass to seldom-used Ricky Proehl for a 30-yard touchdown over
cornerback Brian Kelly and the Bucs' fate was sealed because the
Rams' defense sealed in their offense for the remainder of the day.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis finished with five sacks to Tampa's none despite the
fact the Rams threw 43 times to Tampa's 29. And the Rams got two of
those sacks in Tampa's final possession after Proehl's touchdown,
sacks that knocked the Bucs back a total of 18 yards when they
could ill afford to lose 18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   That is what championship defense is all about. Knocking people
back when it is most needed. Knocking them back the way the Rams
did all day but did most of all over the game's final 4:44, when
Tampa had the ball and was struggling to find some way to do what
St. Louis had just done on the best defense in football.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers struggled to score a touchdown and they failed
because the defense nobody thought much about stopped them when
they had to. Stopped them where the Bucs had failed to. Stopped
them short of the end zone one last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trapped into playing their kind of game with our
turnovers and their stopping our running game,'' Rams coach Dick
Vermeil said. ``Give them credit for that but we played an
outstanding defensive game. The pressure that rookie (King) was
under. We hit him. We hit him pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   They hit him and Mike Alstott and Warrick Dunn and the Bucs'
receivers time and time again. They hit them harder and more often
than Tampa's defense hit Warner or St. Louis's receivers. Not by
much, perhaps, but by enough to be going to Atlanta to begin
preparations for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just made plays in pressure situations,'' Bly said after
having made perhaps the biggest one of all with his interception
that set up the winning score. ``We knew we could make plays on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they did, forcing three turnovers, scoring a safety, and
battering the Bucs regardless of where they started. Normally a
team that has to go only 61 yards on average to score, scores a lot
of touchdowns. Sunday the Buccaneers didn't score any.
</P>
<P>
   That may not mean the St. Louis Rams have the best defense in
football, but it did mean one thing. It meant they're the only
defense in the NFC that's going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
