<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRADA, AMERICAONE OPEN DUEL 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The natives here almost can't take it
anymore. The wait is excruciating. Like children sleepless at 2
a.m. Christmas morning, it seems an eternity before the opening of
presents.
</P>
<P>
   And the presents on this waterfront, where natives prowl by the
thousands daily watching the action, take the form of two black,
sleek _ nay dangerous looking _ 75-foot International America's Cup
Class racing boats.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealand sailing team hasn't sailed in anger since May
1995, when its ``Black Magic'' swept the America's Cup series
against the United States, 5-0, in one of the most lopsided wins in
history. The Kiwi boat won all 25 marks in five races, and gained
time in all 30 legs.
</P>
<P>
   So, from the shoreside throng to the TV watchers far from the
waterfront, natives here _ who anticipate another 5-0 sweep _ just
want the thing to get going.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the celebrating for months has been for the challengers,''
said Byron Serle, whose family strolled Sunday along the Viaduct
Basin seawall that looks across at all the competitors' docks.
``It's time to start some celebrating for our home team.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the remaining two challengers _ Prada of Italy and
AmericaOne _ it is far from over. And some huge questions remain as
the challenger finals of the Louis Vuitton Cup get under way.
</P>
<P>
   If New Zealand is beaten, will the Cup next go to Europe, to be
sailed on the Mediterranean coast, or to the breezy port of San
Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   The further import of the question is this: Should Paul Cayard
win it all here and take the Cup to San Francisco, then no other
American syndicate could challenge for the Cup until some non-US
team took it to another country to put the United States in the
role of challenger again.
</P>
<P>
   If Prada goes all the way and takes the Cup to Cote d'Ur or some
such port, then after 151 years, the America's Cup finally will
make its debut in Europe. Most observers believe this would
stimulate a huge European regatta that would pull in Germany,
England, and Scandinavia along with France and Spain, who have been
involved right along.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a European Cup would give top US sailors who would
like to challenge for the Cup again the opportunity to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would like the chance to challenge again,'' said
Dewey Isdale, commodore of the New York Yacht Club whose Young
America Challenge derailed after its initial boat broke apart in
rough Hauraki Gulf seas in November. ``It just depends on what
happens and where the Cup ends up. We would love to come back
here.''
</P>
<P>
   So, even as the Kiwis are waiting for bigger things, much hangs
in the balance as the challengers take to the racecourse Monday for
Race 1 in the best-of-nine series.
</P>
<P>
   Like a couple of Super Bowl teams, Prada and AmericaOne have
been analyzed, picked over, and number-crunched since the day both
qualified for the finals two weeks ago. They even have been
psychoanalyzed in trying to determine which team is more aggressive
and which is likely to crack under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The widest consensus is that Prada holds a very slight speed
edge, while Cayard and crew sail tougher and steadier and remain
unflappable no matter what comes their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is going to come down to whose head is in the
game,'' said Bill Koch, the 1992 America's Cup winner who has made
a close analysis of the two teams and boats.
</P>
<P>
   In the semifinals _ the most important races since October _
Cayard's AmericaOne won eight straight races, said Koch, whereas
Prada lost three critical matches under pressure. ``Experts now
give AmericaOne a slight edge. The sole reason: experience.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Koch, who sailed a race with Cayard last series,
``(Tactician John) Kostecki and Cayard really have their act
together. They don't get sucked into going off on your own looking
for windshifts. They know how to stay in front and match-race.
That's important.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added ``the Italians' big weakness is not covering
downwind. If they get their act together, cover downwind, and don't
get rattled under pressure, Prada could win it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
