u s BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      01-24 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANK RAMS FOR KEEPING BUCS OUT OF SUPER BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The nation of sports journalists turns its grateful
eyes to this town, says ``thank you,'' and sighs heavily.
</P>
<P>
   If the St. Louis Rams had not come through late in the fourth
quarter Sunday in the NFC Championship Game, the scribes would have
to explain all this week how it was that the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
made it to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't words in the language sufficient to have described
it. Shakespeare would have busted his quill. Darwin and Einstein
would have declared the natural laws immutable, and denied that the
Bucs were even in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The only adequate expression would have been found in the NFL's
own pretentious affectation, the use of Roman numerals:
</P>
<P>
   All records of Sunday's game at the Georgia Dome could simply
read, ``Tennessee Titans vs. X.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Rams delivered us. Not to mention themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if anyone was screaming for the St. Louis-Tennessee
matchup. Certainly not Super Bowl broadcaster ABC, whose executives
by this morning should be scraped off the Manhattan sidewalk below
their windows.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bucs? The worst half-bad team to ever reach this
pinnacle? Whose offense not only didn't score a touchdown, but gave
up two points on a bad snap? Who started a rookie quarterback who
still lives with his parents? Whose offensive linemen are unknown
to most of their mothers?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive unimpressive thing about the Bucs is
that they are so bad they were able to suck the entertainment right
out of the Rams, the 14-point favorites who came into the game with
an offense ranked 34th, just behind the 33-car field in the
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams won. Eleven to six.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't a pro football score. It's a work shift at state
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at the tapes and they look at the tapes,'' Rams
coach Dick Vermeil said, ``we will say, `Jeez, there was a lot of
things that we could have done or should have done.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like pursue amnesty. Declare bankruptcy. Merge with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Anything but this.
</P>
<P>
   This was sumo wrestling for the heavily garbed. But that's not
fair to sumo wrestling, whose matches rarely go more than 20
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty seconds into this one, St. Louis quarterback Kurt Warner
had already thrown an interception to a defensive lineman, and
Tampa was in the midst of screwing up its first of many
opportunities for an easy touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the third hour approached in this one was there
glimpsed a flicker of pro football majesty. But for fans of the
Seahawks, it came with a bittersweet little twist.
</P>
<P>
   Former Seahawk Ricky Proehl, mostly lost this season in the
Rams' receiver rotation of speedsters, made the play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting the Bucs in a blitz on a third-and-four at the Tampa
30-yard line, which allowed him to match up on a single defender,
Proehl changed his route and headed straight to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Warner lofted a fade pass that intersected with Proehl, defender
Brian Kelly and the end zone sideline simultaneously. All Proehl
did was make the biggest catch of his 10-year career, as well as
his first TD of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of contact,'' said Proehl, who appeared in 24
games for the Seahawks in 1995 and 1996, starting seven, before
being released. ``He had his hand in there, and I think I pinned
the ball against my hip or side.''
</P>
<P>
   One splendid play, and that was the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that both defenses didn't play well, and
occasionally spectacularly. But the playoff game last week at the
Trans World Dome was won by St. Louis over Minnesota 49-37, and
even the Bucs beat Washington 14-13 the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was not only a drudge match, it nearly dropped the
final safe on the head of the NFL in this cartoon of a season.
</P>
<P>
   Little did Seahawks fans know that back on Thanksgiving weekend
at the Kingdome, they nearly witnessed the making of an unmade
champion. Tampa beat the Seahawks 16-3 despite just 156 yards of
total offense.
</P>
<P>
   That was the game in which a tackle by Seahawks defensive end
Phillip Daniels broke the clavicle of Bucs quarterback Trent
Dilfer. That ushered in the, ahem, era of rookie Shaun King, a
second-round draft choice from Tulane who should never have beaten
the Seahawks that day, and had no business scaring the bejeezus out
of the Rams at home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was at the end of the game, throwing the ball 36
yards into the end zone with a chance to go to the Super Bowl with
a lucky catch.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen, but that didn't mean the shaken Rams weren't
fearful until the toss hit the turf and their stupendously
improbable 15-3 season could take a bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching that last pass ... it was in slow motion,'' said
D'Marco Farr, the Rams defensive tackle from the University of
Washington who had five tackles and a sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``What flashed through my mind was training camp, and all the
work it took to get from there to here. And if that pass was
completed ...''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Farr didn't want to see it, the sports journalistic
nation didn't want to write it.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the cosmic whammy held off, just in time for many to
savor the fact that the Rams, who never made the playoffs in the
'90s, are in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best I've ever been was 8-8,'' said Proehl, offering an
attribute that should have made him a Seahawk for life. ``I've
never had a sniff of the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Breathe deeply, Ricky. In Tennessee-St. Louis, some may smell a
Super Bowl stinker.
</P>
<P>
   But it could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
