<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GOLDEN-GLOBES-NYT &LR;      01-24 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-GLOBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN BEAUTY' WINS 3 GOLDEN GLOBE AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Box-office giants mixed with independent-film
newcomers at the 57th annual Golden Globe Awards on Sunday night at
the drizzle-drenched Beverly Hilton Hotel, with established stars
like Jim Carrey, Tom Cruise and Denzel Washington joining relative
movie newcomers like Hilary Swank, Janet McTeer and Angelina Jolie
among the winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' a scabrous comedy about dysfunctional
suburbanites that is considered a front-runner for the Academy
Awards, won for best drama. In something of a surprise, the
enormously popular, computer-animated ``Toy Story 2'' won for best
comedy or musical, perhaps edging it toward an Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of independent film sensibilities with the Hollywood
mainstream was a dominant theme among movies in 1999 and it was
well in evidence on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carrey won for best actor in a comedy or musical for ``Man on
the Moon,'' a studio film that, like ``American Beauty,'' had an
independent-film sensibility. Cruise, one of Hollywood's biggest
stars, won for his supporting role in an independent film, Paul
Thomas Anderson's ``Magnolia.'' Ms. Swank won for best actress in a
drama for ``Boys Don't Cry'' and Ms. McTeer for best actress in a
comedy or musical for ``Tumbleweeds,'' both independent films. And
Ms. Jolie won best supporting actress for playing a sociopath in
``Girl, Interrupted,'' another studio film with the feel of an
independent effort.
</P>
<P>
   A more traditional Hollywood film, ``The Hurricane'' from Norman
Jewison, about the wrongful imprisonment of the boxer Ruben Carter,
won Washington his award for best actor in a drama. He was joined
onstage by Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Shut out of the Golden Globes on Sunday night were such films as
``The Insider,'' ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' and ``Being John
Malkovich,'' all of which had been considered strong Oscar
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant trend of the evening, though, might well
have been in the television awards _ normally overshadowed by the
Globes' better-known movie honors _ which were dominated by cable
channels, particularly ``The Sopranos'' on HBO, at the expense of
the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' about a dysfunctional Mafia family in New
Jersey, won for best dramatic series, and awards went to two of its
lead stars, James Gandolfini and Edie Falco, and to Nancy Marchand
as supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   Another HBO series, ``Sex and the City,'' won big, too, taking
the award for best comedy series and for best lead actress, Sarah
Jessica Parker. HBO's ``RKO 281'' won best movie or mini-series,
Peter Fonda won best supporting actor in a series or movie for
Showtime's ``Passion of Ayn Rand,'' Halle Berry won best actress in
a television movie or mini-series for HBO's ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge'' and Jack Lemmon won best actor in a television movie or
mini-series for Showtime's ``Inherit the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one television award went to a network show: Michael J.
Fox, who has Parkinson's disease and recently announced that this
would be his last season on ABC's ``Spin City,'' won for best actor
in a television comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the establishment I once rejected,'' said Carrey in
accepting his second consecutive best-actor Globe. (He won for
``The Truman Show'' last year, another comedy.) ``I am the Tom
Hanks of the Golden Globes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanks, who Carrey joins on the very short list of the
highest-paid movie stars in Hollywood, won two Academy Awards in a
row (for ``Philadelphia'' in 1994 and ``Forrest Gump'' in 1995) and
Carrey had expressed a sense of rivalry with Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cecil B. De Mille Award for lifetime achievement went to
Barbra Streisand. Recent winners of the award have included Jack
Nicholson, Shirley MacLaine and Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes, the British stage director who brought the
Tony-winning ``Cabaret'' to Broadway, won best director for his
first motion picture, ``American Beauty,'' which also won best
screenplay honors for Alan Ball.
</P>
<P>
   The award for best foreign-language film went to ``All About My
Mother,'' from the Spanish director Pedro Almodovar, who had the
audience in stitches with a stream-of-consciousness acceptance
speech. ``Just look at me and see how happy I am,'' he said, later
refusing to end his speech when the prompter flashed ``adios,''
saying he didn't know what the word meant.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker seemed stunned when she was named best actress in a
comedy, beating out favorites Calista Flockhart (``Ally McBeal'')
and Jenna Elfman (``Dharma and Greg'').
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon also drew a laugh when someone shouted ``Ving'' at him as
he walked to the podium. This referred to a famous Golden Globes
incident in 1998 when an emotional Ving Rhames accepted his award
for best supporting actor and announced he was going to give it to
Lemmon, whom he hardly knew but whom he admired and who was in the
audience. He dragged the startled Lemmon onstage.
</P>
<P>
   When he heard the shout on Sunday night, Lemmon responded, ``In
the spirit of Ving Rhames, I'm going to give this award to Jack
Lemmon.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This year's assortment of nominees was more interesting than in
most recent years because there was no real favorite in any
category, so those who wondered what might end up winning the
Oscars in March were looking more closely to Sunday night's
ceremony for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the films touted as early Oscar favorites _ ``American
Beauty,'' ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' ``The Insider,'' ``The
Hurricane'' _ were among the Globe nominees. And even many of those
films seen as possible dark-horse Oscar candidates _ ``Being John
Malkovich,'' ``The Straight Story,'' ``The End of the Affair,''
``Boys Don't Cry'' _ were contenders.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Globes are handed out by the Hollywood Foreign Press
Association, a group of 84 journalists who cover entertainment. Not
long ago the awards were considered little more than a joke, but
not so today. The event has increased greatly in profile and
importance since 1996 when it began to be broadcast on NBC and its
audience skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   The oft-stated reason is that the Golden Globes are predictors
of the upcoming and much more important Academy Awards, which are
voted by members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences. In fact, what luck the Globes have had in predicting the
Oscars has largely come because of the dual nominating system of
the Globes, in which separate sets of nominees are named for
dramatic films and for comedy or musical films, so the association
has 10 nominees to the Oscar's five and thus twice the chance of
stumbling upon the eventual Oscar winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
