<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-JAGUARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERDOG TITANS EARN RESPECT WITH AFC CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ No one, it seems, was willing to give the
Tennessee Titans any respect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite beating Jacksonville twice in the regular season and
outlasting the Buffalo Bills and Indianapolis Colts in the
playoffs, the nomadic Titans entered the AFC Championship Game
Sunday a 7-point underdog to the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   No problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans remedied their season-long respect problem the same
way they handled this game at Alltel Stadium: They took it.
</P>
<P>
   The underappreciated, and now Super Bowl-bound, Titans broke
open a close game by using a safety and an 80-yard punt return to
score nine points in 17 seconds during the third quarter in
coasting to a 33-14 victory before a disbelieving and disgruntled
crowd of 75,206 mostly Jaguars fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only regret,'' offered Titans defensive coordinator Gregg
Williams as wild celebration broke out around him on the field
seconds after the game, ``is that we don't play them a fourth
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Titans will meet the NFC champion St. Louis Rams
next Sunday in Super Bowl XXXIV at the Georgia Dome in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've prepared for a lot of things over the years; I didn't
prepare for this, so bare with me,'' an emotional Titans coach Jeff
Fisher said after the franchise that moved from Houston to
Tennessee three years ago advanced to its first Super Bowl. ``We're
there, but we're not finished yet. The goal is to win the
championship and be the world champions.''
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected outcome left the Jaguars trying to explain what
had gone so wrong on a day they expected only their best. They
turned the ball over six times. They committed nine penalties for
100 wrong-way yards. They dropped four passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frustration, yes. Disappointment, yes. The whole day is
frustrating,'' Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give (the Titans) a lot of credit. Any team that can come in
here and beat us twice (at home) in one year, I take my hat off
to.''
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't taken his hat off to them, the Titans'
opportunistic and aggressive defense undoubtedly would have taken
it from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the times to do it, we did today,'' Jaguars quarterback
Mark Brunell said of the turnovers and other miscues that choked
the life from Jacksonville's comeback hopes. It was unfortunate.
Bad reads. Bad blocking. Bad throws. You can't afford a game like
this, especially against a team like the Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans made up for being outgained (360 yards to 289),
outpassed (216-112) and outnumbered _ they lost free safety Marcus
Robertson and wide receiver Yancy Thigpen to first-half injuries _
by making big plays. Lots of them.
</P>
<P>
   --There was Steve McNair's 9-yard touchdown pass to Thigpen on
third down to tie the score at 7 in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   --There was Robertson's interception of a Brunell pass after the
Jaguars had driven to the Titans' 6-yard line in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   --There was Steve Jackson's recovery of a muffed punt to set up
a Titans field goal just before the half.
</P>
<P>
   --There was McNair lowering his head and ramming his 225-pound
body into the end zone to give Tennessee a 17-14 lead in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   --There was the defense twice stopping the Jaguars on downs in
the final 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   --There was McNair exploding up the gut for 51 yards on a
third-down scramble to set up his 1-yard TD that pushed the Titans'
lead to 33-14.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest plays on this day of big plays came in that
17-second span of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After Jaguars linebackers Kevin Hardy and Lonnie Martz teamed up
to force and recover a fumble by Titans tight end Frank Wycheck at
the Jacksonville 1-yard line, the Jags appeared to have regained
the momentum in a game where it had swung dramatically in both
directions.
</P>
<P>
   But on second down, Josh Evans, the Titans' 288-pound defensive
tackle, mauled his way past Jaguars guard Zach Wiegert and wrapped
his huge arms around Brunell's legs. Before Brunell could get rid
of the ball, Jason Fisk, the Titans' other defensive tackle, was
all over him for a safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just clubbed him to the inside and swimmed over him,'' Evans
said of the double move that gave him a clear path to Brunell.
``That was a momentum driver for us. We knew after the fumble we
had to get out there and make a play.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team like Jacksonville is so confident. Once we start doing
stuff like that, it seems like they started getting down,'' Evans
added. ``To them, they felt like they should blow us out and beat
the hell out of us. Once we started throwing punches back at them,
they started to give. We just have more heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Offered Brunell, the left-hander from the University of
Washington: ``I think there were a number of turning points, and
certainly that was a big play for them. Unfortunately for us, we
had the right play on, we had the right protection. We just got
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-point play gave Tennessee a 19-14 lead with 5 minutes,
13 seconds remaining in the third quarter. But the opportunistic
Titans were not done yet.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Mason took the ensuing free kick _ a punt by Bryan
Barker _ and returned it 80 yards for another score. Quicker than
Coughlin could tug on the bill of his cap and sputter, `What's
going on here?'' the Titans had a 26-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out of the huddle saying, `This has got to be a
touchdown.''' Mason said. ``We've been so close the last two weeks.
We needed one, and we got one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans got it this time because Mason's special-teams mates
opened what he called ``a ridiculously huge hole.'' He then juked
past one Jaguar and Isaac Byrd took care of Barker, which allowed
Mason to veer back into what was then a vacant middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   It was all Titans after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that pretty much put a dagger in their heart,'' Mason
said. ``I shot a look at their sideline, and I don't know if they
really wanted to regroup after that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Coughlin: ``Our special teams were non-existent in terms of
our coverage. They were able to return kickoffs and punts despite
the fact that about everything we did through the week in practice
was to stop that. We knew we would have to neutralize their
outstanding field position. Obviously, we did not get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans did, for the third consecutive time against the
Jaguars and the third week in a row in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it is the Titans, and not the favored Jaguars, who
are off to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy this moment finally came for this team,'' said
McNair, who passed for only 112 yards but ran for 91 and two
scores. ``This team really dedicated themselves and deserves this
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, they might even get some respect now.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
