<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGON STATE EMBARRASSES HUSKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Huskies not only laid an egg Sunday, they
scrambled it and poached it. Looking for sunny side up? You
couldn't find it in the locker room, where the disposition was
somber and the outlook grim.
</P>
<P>
   A team that built its personality around hard work took the
afternoon off, allowing Oregon State to frolic all over KeyArena
and post a 74-57 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was an inexplicable development to all involved. The Beavers
are more accustomed to dragging their feet out of enemy territory,
going 3-34 in their previous 37 Pac-10 road games.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, even if overmatched, usually defend the homecourt,
losing their last two KeyArena games in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   And Washington had never lost to Oregon State in Seattle during
Bob Bender's seven years here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a whole lot of answers for you,'' the coach told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   His players didn't either, failing to come up with responses
during and after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what to say,'' junior guard Greg Clark said.
``We flat out got embarrassed, we really did.''
</P>
<P>
   With emphasis on flat. Washington answered the opening tip with
no hint of urgency or intensity, and Oregon State rolled to leads
of 8-0, 19-3, 31-9 and 45-18.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has a tradition in which fans stand at the start of a
game until the Huskies score. The few that stuck it out didn't sit
down until Deon Luton drained a 3-pointer nearly five minutes after
the opening tip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's got the pride? Who's got the pride?'' Bender shouted at
his players during the first timeout. ``They're dictating
everything!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the pride? Where?'' he shouted during the second
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Bender himself was not an endearing sight. With the Beavers
racing to the rack and the Huskies backpedaling, Bender rode the
referees, wondering about calls in a public display of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers tore it up, inside and out, Clifton Jones collecting
unlucky numbers for the Huskies _ 13 points and 13 rebounds.
Ramunas Petraitis is hard to pronounce and defend, the Lithuanian
scoring 17 points to lead Oregon State. And Deaundra Tanner, the
Beavers' director, supplied several key baskets on his way to 13
points.
</P>
<P>
   Washington countered with two scoring leaders, the familiar name
belonging to Deon Luton, who had 12 points. Surprisingly, David
Dixon did too. The 280-pound junior college transfer had gone
0-for-10 in his UW career before finally showing his advertised
power moves.
</P>
<P>
   None of his blows were enough to startle the Beavers, who
resisted a surge that got the Huskies within 59-49. Oregon State
scored the next 12 points to secure the win and prompt the
curiosity about Bender's team.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies are 6-12 overall and 1-5 in Pac-10 play, losing five
conference games in a row for the first time in five years. The
streak could very well grow to six on Thursday when Washington
plays at No. 2 Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a team on its heels,'' Bender said. ``If there
are some guys with heads down, can we get 'em back up? If not, we
have to go to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Personnel and playing-time changes loom with Dixon, Marlon
Shelton, Bryan Brown and Ben Coffee figuring more prominently.
Senque Carey will still have his significant role at the point, but
he needs to find a way to be more productive _ for the second
consecutive game, the sophomore guard was scoreless in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's struggling, no question,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Bender harped on the togetherness theme in his post-game review,
the importance of which apparently is lost on the Huskies, who
can't get it done individually but try to anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's down, everyone's upset, everyone's trying to figure
out what's wrong, why we're losing,'' Dixon said. ``If we come
together, I don't think anyone in the conference can beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, without defense and team play, the Huskies are a game
out of last place.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Moore can be reached at 206-448-8013
</P>
<P>
   or jimmoore &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
