<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON BRUINS' FAR-LESS-ORDINARY JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He is still only 20 years old, hardly a grizzled
veteran, but Bruins center Joe Thornton has changed a lot since he
was first introduced to Boston fans after being drafted with the
No. 1 pick three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter was simulcasting part of the event, which was
taking place in Pittsburgh in June 1997, and Thornton was able to
greet his newest fans immediately. But even before that day, the
expectations for Thornton _ both reality-based and fantastically
silly _ were difficult for anyone to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Thornton has had to work through all kinds of
situations. There was the expectations vs. reality scenario, there
was the rookie getting his feet wet scenario, there was the
rookie's first slump scenario. On top of that, there were injuries,
benchings, and lectures from the coaches. At one point last year, a
frustrated Thornton said he wasn't sure exactly what message he was
supposed to be getting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the on-ice challenges, Thornton had to learn
basic lifestyle skills such as proper nutrition, working out
regularly, and one of the most difficult _ learning to deal with
fame.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, he's maintained his sense of humor, his modesty,
and his purpose. When he discusses being a better player now, he
knows exactly what he is talking about instead of guessing how it
might be someday.
</P>
<P>
   There is still much to be learned, but Thornton has mastered
enough by now that he's no longer confused by the demands of his
job. Thornton still has some inconsistencies to iron out, but it's
clear that coach Pat Burns is right when he says Thornton can be as
good as he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's latest challenge is assuming a greater role in
double-shifting. With center Jason Allison out of commission after
wrist surgery, Thornton and Anson Carter have had to carry the bulk
of the center duties. For example, in Saturday's 4-3 overtime loss
to the Florida Panthers, Thornton played 25 minutes 47 seconds over
29 shifts. The only forward who played more was Panthers superstar
Pavel Bure, against whom Thornton played much of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton centered the top defensive line with left wing P.J.
Axelsson and right wing Rob DiMaio. He also rotated with several
other players, such as playing on a line with Steve Heinze and Joe
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Thornton is well ahead of his sophomore season.
Through 48 games, Thornton has 12 goals and 39 points. It took him
81 games last year to get 16 goals and 41 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get better real quick,'' he said. ``I think I'm
pushing myself each and every day right now. I'm getting a lot of
ice time, so I can't complain about that. I just want to keep
bettering myself each and every day and just hopefully be a (much
better) player at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter and Thornton both said when Allison was sidelined they
knew they were going to have to assume a good amount of the
offensive responsibility. Thornton said he's OK with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a key player like Jason goes out of the lineup, a lot of
us have got to pick up our games,'' said Thornton. ``I've got a lot
of weight on my shoulders right now and I just want to go out there
and help the team win as much as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Burns is going to have to play Thornton more than
ever. That also suits him just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good out there,'' he said. ``I feel strong. I like
being on the ice all the time. It's been pretty good for me so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton admitted that he has had to juggle his mindset slightly
to handle the dual roles of shutting down the other teams' top
lines while trying to generate offense. Burns has often said the
two go hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like playing against Bure,'' said Thornton. ``He likes to
sneak back there (in order to get open). You've got to be a little
cautious when he's out there. Robbie and P.J. are good offensive
players as well, so if we get the puck in the other team's end a
lot, they can't get any offensive chances on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have a tough road the rest of the season, and the
push to make it to the postseason is on. Thornton said the fact
Boston earned 5 of a possible 6 points on its three-game road trip
has it back on track _ especially the point against the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We outshot them, we were in their end a lot, and we played
right with them,'' he said. ``We knew it was going to be tough. I
think we're pretty happy we got the point.''
</P>
<P>
   The same likely could be said of Thornton himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
