<HEADLINE>
`SOFT' SONICS COLLAPSE; GRANT, PAYTON BLAST TEAMMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ There were times when Sonics coach Paul Westphal
violently slammed his water bottle near the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Sonics were dominated Sunday in a 94-77 loss to
the Toronto Raptors, Westphal showed restraint. It was clearly
difficult and safe to assume his words might have been fierce, too.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing held back Gary Payton and Horace Grant. They were
the ones uncut and uncensored before the Sonics left Air Canada
Centre.
</P>
<P>
   They are tired of this.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of hustle. The lack of rebounding. The lack of help,
dedication, desire and heart on the Sonics. Essentially, Grant and
Payton are exhausted, mentally and physically, and sick of being
associated with a ``soft'' team.
</P>
<P>
   So the two guys most revered for being warriors said as much
after the Sonics dropped their second straight game on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of sugar-coating this (expletive),'' Grant said.
``If the big guys don't get in there and rebound, we're not going
to win. Anybody can score given the opportunity but it takes a real
man to go down there and rebound and play defense and have some
heart doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been reading our press clippings too much. That has to
stop. Period. Right now, we're not hustling. Guys want to score.
You don't win championships like that. You don't win games like
that. This is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton vehemently agreed, alluding that the team's recent
seven-game win streak was a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of guys on this team are not playing,'' Payton said.
``Either we're going to have to do something about it, or these
guys are going to have to sit down. We can't win with just me doing
everything, then a couple of guys coming here and there. We've got
to have consistency every night, and we don't have that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starting five is just ridiculous, from me to everybody,''
Payton said. ``Every now and then we play good, and want to come
back and revert to this (stuff). That's not the sign of a good
team. That's the sign of a team that got satisfied, and we're going
to fool around and go on another losing streak. We have to
understand we haven't proven anything. We've got some good wins,
but this defeats what we did when we had a seven-game streak. We've
got another big game (Monday against the New York Knicks) that we
need, and we don't even know how we're going to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton and Grant did not say specific names. However, some of
their comments clearly had to do with power forward Vin Baker. At
6-foot-11, Baker is not a consistent force down low.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from shaky defense, Baker is often out of position for
rebounds because he lags on the perimeter looking for outside
shots.
</P>
<P>
   One example would be when Baker found himself in a mismatch
against 5-foot-3 Muggsy Bogues. Instead of posting Bogues under the
basket, Baker shot a fadeaway jumper and missed.
</P>
<P>
   Baker finished with just six rebounds in 35 minutes on a day
when the Sonics were beaten 53-34 on the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all you need to know,'' said Westphal, who spoke
abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Sonics appeared confused running their offense,
which is partly why they tied a season-low for points. Those inept
qualities are nothing new but were hidden during the team's winning
streak because of Payton's stellar play and Grant covering for
teammates in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no hustle,'' said Grant, who is always assigned to
defend the opponents' best post player. ``It takes every guy out
there to hustle, not just a couple of guys. If one guy breaks down,
it just breaks down our defense. ... But it's stopping now. If I
offend someone after (Sunday), if they don't get in there and
rebound, (forget) it. The hell with it. Guys know who they are.
They should look themselves in the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton was slightly less diplomatic. The 6-foot-4 point guard
said this team needs toughness from several players. Baker stands
out because he signed a seven-year, $86 million contract last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys down low have got to play basketball. When I go to
the basket teams are trying to beat me down,'' Payton said.
``They're trying to make a statement saying we don't want him to
come back in there. Our guys don't do that. Somebody will come in
there for a wide-open layup and we let them. Put them on their back
sometimes and make them understand they can't go in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the scouting report probably is if you go to the basket
you can get to the basket. That's the way we play. We play soft all
the way around. We've been working on defense for three months and
we don't know nothing. We don't know how to switch. We don't know
how to get through picks. We don't know nothing. And a good team
will beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors (21-19) are talented. But they are a young and
inexperienced group the Sonics should beat. If anything, the Sonics
had been proficient in beating the weaker teams.
</P>
<P>
   But following a 111-86 loss at Boston with a subpar showing
against Toronto is perhaps what led to the verbal diatribe.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 53-43 at halftime, the Sonics trailed by as
many as 17 points in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics showed fight only after Westphal inserted Chuck
Person for Baker with 3:15 left in the third. Person, Payton,
Grant, Jelani McCoy and Emanual Davis were mostly responsible for
getting the Sonics within 78-71 with 7:18 left in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck is 35 years old and if he comes in and outhustles the
young guys, that's a shame. A crying shame,'' Payton said. ``These
young guys on our team are only 20, 23, 24 years old. If he comes
in and outhustles them, they should be ashamed. ... Don't come in
there lackadaisical, let people push you around and don't get
rebounds. What are you out there for? But that's the way we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton and Grant said they did not say anything to the media
that they haven't said behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't want to respond, you're not taking your job
right,'' Payton said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
