<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE STATUS HOT TOPIC WITH CELTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There is no snow here. The Celtics got out of Charlotte,
N.C., and its wintry grip and landed here early Sunday, where the
weather was exponentially better. Rick Pitino can only hope the
basketball is as well.
</P>
<P>
   The team plays Monday night in the new American Airlines Arena,
where the Heat have been, well, tepid. (Miami played in Houston
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night.) Miami hasn't been in its new digs for even a month
and already has lost to Chicago, New Jersey, and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   But Miami's problems are not high on Pitino's list. He has other
things on his mind, such as the status of Paul Pierce. Boston's
best all-purpose player pulled his left hamstring Saturday night
and played only 11 minutes vs. the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics without Pierce are not a pretty sight. He missed
seven games in December with an ankle sprain and they went 1-6 in
that span. They were 0-2 last year when he was out. If you add
Saturday night's performance, the team is 1-9 in games Pierce
either missed or was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the team had two days between games and
Pierce said he did not think his injury was serious. The rest
should help him. But it won't help Eric Williams, who is going on
the injured list (knee), possibly Monday or Tuesday. Adrian Griffin
(sprained ankle) isn't ready yet, but he will be activated to take
Williams's roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely need the time with all the injuries we have and
everyone being hurt,'' forward Antoine Walker said. ``Hopefully,
we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, who has been out since Jan. 8, is due to return to
practice Monday. He may even be activated, although Pitino said
Griffin won't be able to play immediately. He's still limping
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two weeks, Griffin said he spent 6-9 hours a day
in rehab, working in 2- to 3-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of rehab,'' he said. ``But it also was tough. You
wish you could be out there contributing, and you can't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
