<SLUG> BC-BKC-NAVY-HOLY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY TORPEDOES HOLY CROSS 
</HEADLINE>
 CROSS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER _ These are tough times for Holy Cross men's
basketball. Misfortune has clung to the Crusaders like a wet,
undersized T-shirt: Injuries often have kept them from practicing
at full strength, and have led coach Ralph Willard to use five
starting lineups involving 12 players.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a victory Sunday against Patriot League foe Navy
would have been a confidence-booster. Early in the second half, it
appeared the locals might pull off the upset against the third-best
team in the league; Holy Cross had outscrapped Navy, and with 17:29
to go trailed by only 3.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Crusaders' luck soured. Navy's John Williams sank a
3-pointer. Holy Cross's Josh Sankes, the team's best center, picked
up his fourth foul and went to the bench. Navy staged a 37-10 run,
attacking the undermanned Crusader interior.
</P>
<P>
   So much for momentum-builders. Holy Cross never threatened
again, and Navy went on to an 81-49 rout before a Hart Center crowd
of 2,173 (many of them stuck around to cheer on the home team even
when the outcome was well in hand).
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped Holy Cross to 6-11, 1-3 in the league, and
marked its sixth loss in eight games. Sankes and Jared Curry led
the Crusaders with 9 points each. Curry added a team-high seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Willard knows when his team returns to full stength, it could be
formidable. It recorded wins against Providence and
Alabama-Birmingham this season.
</P>
<P>
   But will it return to full strength? Two starters, Juan Pegues
and Patrick Whearty, have each missed 11 consecutive games. Guard
Ryan Serravalle (4 points Sunday) has missed 10 games with knee
problems, while Curry has missed eight with back problems.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad that one player who didn't make the roster _ James
Stowers _ was invited back when the injuries hit. He flew from his
native Florida and joined the team at the Hoosier Classic in
Indianapolis and scored 14 points against UAB.
</P>
<P>
   If Holy Cross could be so fortunate the rest of the season. ``We
have so many injuries you can't simulate a good five-on-five in
practice,'' said Willard. ``When you get in game situations, it
just seems like they keep running athletes at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Crusaders played tough defense on Navy pivot Sitatha
Savane, and it limited the Senegalese senior's effectiveness. But
when Sankes went to the bench with foul trouble, Savane took
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 10 points during the Midshipmen's surge and finished
with a game-high 22, with team highs in rebounds (6) and blocks
(5). His free throws with 5:42 left made the score 64-36.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
