<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-GROH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SETTLE ON GROH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The New York Jets will name Al Groh their
coach Monday and also will announce that former coach Bill Parcells
will remain in an advisory capacity for the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Groh, who has coached under Parcells for more than 15 years, was
linebackers coach of the Jets the past three years and defensive
coordinator with the Patriots when they went to the Super Bowl
under Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Groh was the personal choice of Parcells after Bill Belichick
resigned from the position less than 48 hours after becoming coach
Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, by a contractual arrangement he had with late Jets
owner Leon Hess, moved into place as head man when Parcells retired
following the final game of the regular season against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   However, two days later, Belichick resigned and subsequently
filed a grievance with National Football League commissioner Paul
Taglaibue trying to free himself from the Jets to accept an offer
as coach and general manager of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Tagliabue ruled against Belichick, saying he had a
contract for the next three years with the Jets and he could not
coach in the league during that time unless allowed to do so by the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots offered New York two draft choices, neither in the
top two rounds, to pry Belichick loose, but the Jets rejected the
deal. Reportedly they still are looking for a first-round and a
middle-round pick as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and new Jets owner Robert Wood Johnson IV met with Groh
over the weekend, the first time Johnson had met Groh. But after
the meeting, Johnson decided to go along with the strong
recommendation by Parcells, who considered Groh the best available
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   There was no movement on the Belichick issue over the weekend,
which is fueling speculation that the Patriots are losing interest
in Belichick and turning their attention toward such candidates as
University of Miami coach Butch Davis and reportedly Jacksonville
defensive coordinator Dom Capers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said in the last couple of weeks that he wants to stay
at Miami. There also have been reports Davis might be the next
coach in Dallas, where he served on Jimmy Johnson's staff when the
Cowboys won two Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Crennel, longtime defensive line coach with the Giants,
Patriots, and Jets under Parcells, left over the weekend to become
defensive coordinator with Chris Palmer in Cleveland, leaving New
York depleted on the defensive side of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Belichick was the coordinator, Groh the linebackers
coach, and Crennel the line coach. The Jets' offensive staff is
expected to stay intact, with the possible exception of coordinator
Charley Weis, who testified on behalf of Belichick in the grievance
hearing and is very close to Belichick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      01-24 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS EXPLORE PLAN B 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There were no talks over the weekend between
the Patriots and Jets regarding compensation to free Bill Belichick
from his contract with New York, so New England began to formulate
an alternative regarding its coaching situation.
</P>
<P>
   With Jacksonville being knocked out of the playoffs Sunday, the
Patriots have asked for permission to speak to Jaguars defensive
coordinator Dom Capers about their coaching job, according to two
sources close to the Patriots. And New England will interview
former Pittsburgh director of football operations Tom Donahoe for
the general manager's job Tuesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's attorney said Sunday &UR;  &LR; night he expects to file an
antitrust suit against the NFL Monday in federal court in New York.
Jeffrey Kessler said commissioner Paul Tagliabue's decision Friday
was ``a travesty'' and said Belichick's legal team will pursue all
avenues to make sure the coach is free to seek jobs without it
requiring compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler also will seek a temporary restraining order against the
Jets that would allow Belichick to negotiate with another team.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots or another team can work out compensation, the
lawsuit would be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Capers-Donahoe likely would come as a team, having worked
together for three years in Pittsburgh (1992-95) when Capers was
defensive coordinator under Bill Cowher and Donahoe was director of
football operations, a position he held until he was fired at the
end of the season, losing a power struggle with Cowher.
</P>
<P>
   Donahoe has been highly sought after. He could take the GM job
in Miami and work with another friend, Dave Wannstedt. But Donahoe
is attempting to see if he and Capers would be attractive to teams
looking for a coach-GM tandem. Another team that might be
interested would be New Orleans. Dallas also has a coaching
vacancy, but is reportedly looking for someone more offense-minded.
</P>
<P>
   By talking with Capers and Donahoe, the Patriots may be sending
a message to the Jets that they could get nothing for Belichick if
they don't play ball. There is also speculation that University of
Miami coach Butch Davis is moving up on their list.
</P>
<P>
   Capers's Jacksonville defense didn't have the best of games in a
33-14 loss to Tennessee in Sunday's AFC Championship Game. But
Capers is known for being tough and instilling discipline, and he
has experience leading a team into the playoffs. His resume is
similar to Belichick's in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   Capers was 31-35 from 1995-98 in Carolina, but was fired after
going 4-12 and replaced by George Seifert. He landed as Tom
Coughlin's defensive coordinator in Jacksonville and upgraded an
already decent defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have scheduled a news conference for Monday to announce
they've signed Al Groh to a five-year deal to be their new coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots own the 16th pick in the first round and are trying
to hold on to it, figuring they could get a top offensive lineman
or Wisconsin running back Ron Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have backed off on former Kansas City coach Marty
Schottenheimer, who also would require compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
