<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IS HELL FOR BUCS ON TWO FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Tampa Bay Buccaneers love to talk about war.
They say pro football is more than a game and more than a
billion-dollar industry. It is 60 nationally televised minutes of
blood sport. They say they have the scars, broken bones, and
chilling stories to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't necessarily agree with that. I think Warren Sapp would
rather land on the turf at Trans World Dome than the sand at
Normandy Beach. But let's use the Bucs' battle terminology to gain
an understanding of their 11-6 NFC Championship Game loss to the
Rams Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one enemy in every war, but the Bucs had two
working against them here. The enemies worked the same way running
backs Mike Alstott and Warrick Dunn should have worked. That is,
they did damage inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   Public Enemy No. 1: The NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Public Enemy No. 1A: Mike Shula.
</P>
<P>
   The first one, the outsider, is obvious. In the final 51
seconds, the league's officials affected the outcome of the game.
This should never happen. The NFL has a replay policy which states
that, in the final two minutes, officials automatically control and
review questionable calls. I don't think there is anything in the
rules that gives the officials the right for absurd nitpicking,
which is what they did Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a minute remaining and the Bucs facing a
second-and-22 at the Rams 35, Tampa quarterback Shaun King threw a
pass receiver Bert Emanuel caught at the 23. Emanuel caught the
ball, but replay official Jerry Markbreit (one of my all-time
favorites, by the way) challenged the catch. I wouldn't have had a
problem if Markbreit had said that the ball hit the ground.
Instead, he said he thought Emanuel used the ground to help him
make the catch. Even after replays, it was hard to say that
definitively.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bucs coach Tony Dungy realized that the completion was
being challenged, he used his final timeout of the game.
Essentially, the officials affected his game management as well
because he used a timeout even though their review was going to
stop the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used the ground to assist that catch,'' referee Bill
Carollo said. ``And because the ball hit the ground, by rule it's
an automatic incomplete pass.''
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be war? In war, a soldier doesn't plant a
claymore mine and then have an official step in and say, ``Well,
that doesn't count because you were too far out of your bunker when
you positioned the claymore.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, I should tell you one of my deepest sports
secrets: In the last minute of any game, I become a borderline
hypocrite. I may scream for a penalty in the second quarter and
hope that the same penalty is ignored in the final 60 seconds.
Sometimes, I wish there were a playground-type, self-policing
system in the final minute. If someone is guilty of blatant
cheating, you call it. Everything else? Please, swallow the
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   As you can imagine, the officials' intrusion took the glimmer
out of an overall dreadful game. Instead of third and 10 it was
third and 23. There were two incompletions and the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they told me it wasn't a catch,'' Emanuel said, ``I was
like, `I can't believe it. Why?' All they told me was that the
replay official said I didn't catch it. There's no doubt in my mind
that I did.''
</P>
<P>
   For those Rams fans who are waiting for me to say, ``The Rams
were simply the better team Sunday,'' well, I can't say it because
I don't believe it. I think the Rams were fun to watch in the
regular season and just as entertaining in their divisional playoff
win over the Vikings. But they played two playoff teams in the
regular season and lost to both of them. One of the losses was to
their Super Bowl opponent, the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't played a defense like us all year,'' Sapp said of
the Rams. ``If they didn't learn from what we did to them, I
guarantee you that they will have some major problems with
Tennessee in the Super Bowl. I guarantee you that.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they will have the opportunity to have problems. The
Bucs will not have that luxury, in part, because Shula is their
offensive coordinator. Now, there are two very good things about
Shula. One is that he went to Dartmouth. Another is that his father
is one of the greatest coaches in the history of the game. But
neither fact has anything to do with calling good plays.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Bucs had drives that began at the Rams' 20,
45, 42, and 49 and could not score a touchdown. Alstott and Dunn
combined for 21 rushing attempts, which is about 20 attempts short
of where they should have been. I don't know if I was seeing things
after the game, but Shula's play-calling was so conservative his
entire body seemed to be leaning to the right.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Sapp sat at his locker with a wad of tobacco
stuffed in his mouth. He would say a few words and then spit,
littering a white towel with tiny brown drops. He was hurt and he
was angry. He talked about war. It's one thing to talk about a war.
It's a bit more painful to acknowledge how you lost it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
