<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-JAGUARS-HN     01-24 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-JAGUARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ When the gun sounded Sunday and the first
Super Bowl appearance in franchise history was assured, it was a
magical moment for the Tennessee Titans, a team that suffered
through four tumultuous years as lame ducks in Houston and
vagabonds in Tennessee.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Titans were Oilers, they were called the biggest
chokers in NFL history. After their 33-14 victory over the
Jacksonville Jaguars in the AFC Championship Game, you can call the
Oilers/Titans a Super Bowl team for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   No one could blame them for the unabashed emotion they showed in
a postgame celebration during which some grown men cried as the
enormity of their accomplishment began to seep in.
</P>
<P>
   They are the last original AFL team to reach the Super Bowl, and
they are the first team in NFL history to sweep three games from an
opponent in a season with the third on the road. When they tangle
with St. Louis _ a team they defeated 24-21 on Oct. 31 _ they will
try to join the Oakland Raiders and Denver Broncos as the only
wild-card teams to win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say we're just a bunch of ordinary guys
doing an extraordinary thing,'' guard Bruce Matthews said after
earning his first trip to the Super Bowl in a 17-year career. ``The
circumstances we've played under the last few years have defined
this team. We're battle-hardened, and it shows in our character.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans owner Bud Adams, who co-founded the AFL in 1959 with
Kansas City Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt, was presented the Lamar Hunt
Trophy by _ who else? _ Lamar Hunt. The trophy goes to the AFC
champion each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken me 40 years to get this far, and at least I won't
have to go to the Super Bowl in a wheelchair,'' said Adams, 77.
``We have great fans in Nashville, but we had great fans in
Houston, too. We miss our Houston fans, and we appreciate their
support through the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston fans suffered through one disappointment after another,
but once the franchise changed its name, logo, colors and uniforms
and moved into its new stadium and practice facility, the Oilers
were transformed from frogs to princes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we've all died and gone to heaven,'' offensive
tackle Brad Hopkins said in the jubilant Titans dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they're just going to the Georgia Dome in Atlanta. And
no one can say they didn't earn the trip to Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind the Jaguars 14-7, the Titans scored 26
consecutive points before an Alltel Stadium crowd of 75,206. The
Titans forced six turnovers and followed the leadership of
quarterback Steve McNair, who overcame a severe case of turf toe to
rush for two touchdowns and throw for another.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only misgiving is that we won't be able to play them in the
Super Bowl,'' said Titans defensive coordinator Gregg Williams,
whose team allowed 16, 16 and 14 points in playoff victories over
Buffalo, Indianapolis and Jacksonville. ``They're so arrogant, they
continue to go to their money people even when nothing's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity breeds contempt, and the Titans and Jaguars don't
like each other. Many of the Tennessee players thought the Jaguars
were too cocky entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they were pretty arrogant,'' Titans linebacker Barron
Wortham said. ``You know, if you haven't learned anything from two
butt-whippings, then you're going to get a third one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans outscored the Jaguars 94-47 in three games, forcing
13 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their hearts were in it, but their bodies couldn't take the
pounding we were giving them,'' Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans march on Atlanta with a 5-0 record in games against
teams with at least 13 victories. They defeated 14-2 Jacksonville
three times and 13-3 St. Louis and 13-3 Indianapolis once each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always the underdogs, but we continue to prove the
naysayers wrong,'' Wortham said. ``When you experience adversity
like we did, it makes you hungry. It makes situations like that
almost second nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans are eight-point underdogs against the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've prepared for a lot of things over the years, but I've
never prepared for anything like this,'' Tennessee coach Jeff
Fisher said. ``This team's special. They've overcome so many
distractions. I wouldn't wish those four years on any team. We'll
reflect on those four years after next week. Our goal is still to
be world champion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans' seventh consecutive victory was earned the hard way.
The Jaguars scored a touchdown on their first series on Mark
Brunell's seven-yard pass to tight end Kyle Brady. The Titans
responded when McNair threw a nine-yard TD pass to Yancey Thigpen.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville moved in front again when reserve running back
James Stewart broke loose for a 33-yard touchdown run for a 14-7
advantage. At that point, the Jaguars had the upper hand, but there
was a huge momentum change when Reggie Barlow fumbled Craig
Hentrich's punt and Steve Jackson made a diving recovery at the
Jacksonville 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had to settle for Al Del Greco's 34-yard field goal
that pulled them within 14-10 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``No defense plays harder than ours,'' Fisher said. ``They
challenged the receivers and attacked the ball. Our secondary
played as well as I've ever seen them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys we'd have to weather an early storm, and we
did. The key was coming back to score after they went up 7-0. In
the second half, we could see a little loss of enthusiasm on their
part. We were able to take advantage of the momentum swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans blew open the game with a 16-point third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That fumbled punt was a big play,'' Wortham said. ``They were
shocked. The guy dropped the ball, and everything changed. I don't
know if they quit then, but we kept pounding them. I thought they'd
do a better job of taking it to us, but they just seemed to lose
steam.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars could do nothing right in the third quarter. It was
just the opposite for the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   On their first series, they took advantage of a 15-yard penalty
for a late hit on McNair by defensive end Tony Brackens and a
28-yard interference penalty against cornerback Fernando Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who led the Titans with 91 yards rushing _ five more
than Eddie George _ scored on a one-yard sneak. Del Greco's extra
point boosted the lead to 17-14.
</P>
<P>
   The next time they got the ball, the Titans lost it when tight
end Frank Wycheck fumbled at the one-yard line. That led to a
safety when Brunell was sacked in the end zone by tackles Josh
Evans and Jason Fisk to make it 19-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did all that roaring, but their bite sure wasn't
vicious,'' Titans defensive end Jevon Kearse said. ``The more hits
we put on Brunell, the slower he got up.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Derrick Mason broke open the game when he returned the
free kick after the safety 80 yards for a touchdown to make it
26-14.
</P>
<P>
   McNair finished the scoring with another one-yard sneak in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing this team can't accomplish,'' Fisher said.
``When people told us we couldn't beat them three times, we didn't
even bat an eye. Right now, our goal is to win the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
