r s BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     01-24 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WAIT IS OVER: TITANS ANSWER DESTINY'S KNOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Just as Bum Phillips swore that they would
do, the Houston Oilers kicked down the blanketty-blank door to the
Super Bowl yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Dan Pastorini was nowhere around. Bum neither,
for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   They are the Tennessee Titans now, which proves that the Federal
Witness Relocation Program really works. In Nashville, Tenn., Bum
and Earl's old team has forged a new beginning and, as of
yesterday, made a semblance of peace with its past.
</P>
<P>
   After all those years of frustration, of losing to the Steelers
and the Raiders and blowing a 32-point lead in Buffalo, owner K.S.
``Bud'' Adams' team has finally answered destiny's knock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years Mr. Adams has been trying to get here,'' head
coach Jeff Fisher said, after the Oilers-turned-Titans had silenced
the Jacksonville Jaguars, 33-14, in the AFC Championship Game.
``Forty years _ that's what this is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon of earnest, if not flawless, redemption,
quarterback Steve McNair, running back Eddie George and a swarming,
ball-hawking defense punched the franchise's ticket for Super Bowl
XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   More than four years have passed since Adams first announced
that he planned to spirit the Oilers out of Houston. But what was
roundly tsk-tsked as a rich fool's threat turned into a hastily
fabricated reality.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis, indignant that it was viewed as only a temporary home,
gave the Oilers a hunka-hunka chilling shoulder. In one game at the
Liberty Bowl, only an alleged 17,071 showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we settled there, it was like Tennessee was going to be
the land of milk and honey,'' guard Bruce Matthews, 38 and in his
17th NFL season, said. ``But as we learned, those first couple of
years were pretty lean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff sold you on the hope that things would get better. The
guy doesn't say much. But when he does say something, he means
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Fisher, the Titans have built a big-play defense bent on
pressuring the quarterback. On offense, Fisher summed up the
philosophy as ``Run the football, throw high-percentage passes and
have a quarterback who's mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys critics, take note: ``Dare'' McNair had only four
200-yard passing games all season and none in the playoffs. Yet,
he's headed for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's a winner,'' Matthews said. ``He shows you that
football games don't always have to be won by the guy who throws
the prettiest spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's the most unconventional quarterback I've
ever seen, but he's the most unconventional I've played with. No,
wait _ Bucky Richardson was pretty unconventional.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews smiled at the memory. After 17 seasons, after the Ed
Biles years, the Jerry Glanville years and the ] Buddy
Ryan-as-angry-coordinator years, after Richardson and Warren Moon,
after lockers in four different home stadiums in four seasons,
Matthews was smiling a lot yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the NFL's eternal axioms has been that no team can beat
another three times in a single season. The Titans debunked that in
the Jaguars' own back yard. The blemishes on Jacksonville's 15-3
season came at the hands of Tennessee, twice at Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The four years of wanderings, from Memphis to Opry-ville, from
one practice field to another, schooled the Titans well, the
players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what defines our team,'' Matthews, the 17-year veteran,
said. ``Those four years are what we're all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through a lot of stuff. My brother was talking the
other day and said, `You know, you guys are battle-hardened,' and
we are. We haven't experienced any luxuries until this year.''
</P>
<P>
   With 75,206 screaming in their ears, McNair and the Titans
seldom seemed ruffled. McNair tried to force a big play to George
early in the second quarter and was intercepted. But the Tennessee
defense responded, and safety Marcus Robertson made a diving
interception of a Mark Brunell pass in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was dominated by the vagabond visitors. Lining
up Jevon Kearse opposite his usual left side for one snap, the
Titans smothered Brunell for a safety in the third period. When
Derrick Mason ran the ensuing free kick back 80 yards for a
touchdown, Tennessee had a 12-point lead and the ``Music City
Miracle,'' the kickoff-lateral that saved the day against Buffalo
two weeks ago, became just a footnote.
</P>
<P>
   There are fans in Houston who will never forgive Adams _ or the
new ``Oilers'' _ for this. The Astrodome is empty. The ``Luv Ya
Blue'' signs are long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they can enjoy what we've done,'' Matthews said. ``I
still live in Houston in the off-season, and I know there are a lot
of fans there that still pull for this team. I'm happy for them
today.''
</P>
<P>
   After 17 seasons, Matthews is headed to the Super Bowl. After 40
years, owner Bud Adams, one of the AFL's founding fathers, has
finally seen his team answer destiny's knock.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Bum promised.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
