<HEADLINE>
MAVS' WIN, REACH NELSON MILESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Don Nelson finally got the keys to the
prestigious 900 club.
</P>
<P>
   After being denied entry into the exclusive club Saturday by an
emotional loss to the New Jersey Nets, Nelson was able to post his
900th-career victory last night with a 99-91 triumph over the
Detroit Pistons. He joins Lenny Wilkens (1,165), Pat Riley (973),
Bill Fitch (944), Red Auerbach (938) and Dick Motta (935) as the
only coaches to win at least 900 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks overcame an eight-point deficit in the fourth
quarter, and now start a five-game homestand tomorrow against the
Golden State Warriors. But Nelson and company werestill savoring
last night's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my 900th win and I don't mean to underplay that,'' said
Nelson, the coach and general manager of the Mavericks. ``But it
was won the way it should have been won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard-fought game; I'm all sweaty. There were a lot of
decisions that went in the game and a lot of different strategies.
I guess if I'm going to remember that one, that's what I'm going to
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson will also remember seven key points guard Greg Buckner
scored in the fourth quarter. Buckner, a defensive specialist,
isn't normally an offensive threat. But the rookie from Clemson
found himself wide open a couple of times, and buried critical
jumpers that helped the Mavericks go home with a 14-26 record.
Buckner wound up 3-of-4 from the field and finished with eight
points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Finley told me that I have to shoot to get the respect
of the guys in this league,'' said Buckner, who came in averaging
2.9 points and shooting 38.5 percent from the field. ``Tonight I
had to make the shots because they were leaving me open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams double off me because I don't shoot that much, and I'm a
rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-fought victory eased some of the pain from Saturday's
loss to the Nets, which prevented the Mavericks from going 3-0 on
the road trip. In the game against the Nets, the Mavericks blew a
five-point lead with less than four minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hurting from that Jersey game emotionally,'' said
Cedric Ceballos, who had22 points and 10 rebounds last night. ``I
hadn't seen that locker room that quiet in awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the bus ride \Rafter the Nets game\S, the plane ride, the
bus ride today was quite, even the locker room today was quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about back-to-back games, when you have a bad
loss you can always come back and shake it and get a win. But we
should have had a sweep on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 80-72 early in the fourth quarter, the Mavericks clawed
their way back and eventually took an 88-87 lead on a 19-foot
jumper by Buckner. Another basket by Buckner pushed the Mavericks
ahead for good _ 90-89 with 2:27 left.
</P>
<P>
   After a bucket by Ceballos, Bucnker drained a 17-footer to give
the Mavericks a comfortable 94-89 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame them for leaving him, because he's not known to
be a shooter,'' Nelson said. ``He's known to be a defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we saw him make shots in the summer league, and I think
it's a confidence thing. He's got the heart of a lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill of the Pistons did not play because of a bruised hip,
and Jerry Stackhouse led the Pistons with 33 points.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mavericks who made strong contributions includes Erick
Strickland (16 points, six assists), Shawn Bradley (14 points,
eight rebounds), and Finley (18 points, 10 rebounds, six assists).
But the night clearly belonged to Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love winning,'' Ceballos said. ``It's much better than
losing.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
