<HEADLINE>
BROWSER BEWARE ON SUPER BOWL SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The abundance of dot.com commercials on this
year's Super Bowl telecast might bring ABC generous advertising
dollars, but it could also have a backlash _ first, enticing
viewers to leave the TV to check out a Web site, and also jamming
Internet use that could affect access to the network's Enhanced TV
content.
</P>
<P>
   There are 250,000 spots available for Enhanced TV, which offers
additional game stats through a data base in the TV production
truck, interactive polls and games in which you guess play calls
against others across the country. It will be accessible through
ESPN.com, NFL.com and Superbowl.com, as well as Disney's GO.com
site.
</P>
<P>
   Enhanced TV executive producer Jonathan Leess says the
technology has been ``tremendously successful'' when used during
ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' and ESPN's Sunday night package, 39
telecasts in all since September, but ``we don't know the kind of
Internet use there will be on a Super Bowl Sunday ... that's the
fear I have right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ETV research shows a typical user stays logged into the service
for an average of 37 minutes. More than 2.2 million have tried the
service since September's regular-season launch.
</P>
<P>
   __Magic Johnson plans to launch an African- American-geared
portal for entertainment, retail and community known as
UrbanMagic.com sometime in April, according to a special report on
minority sites in a recent issue of The Industry Standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was heavily recruited by other black portals, but I wanted
to do my own thing,'' Johnson told the magazine. ``We'll make some
money, but we'll also do some good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
