<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4418 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     01-24 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS' TRIP TO SUPER BOWL LEAVES BAD AFTERTASTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have to admit I'm surprised.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't think I would feel so resentful if the St. Louis Rams
made it to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   I never flinched once during this fairy tale of a season for the
ex-L.A. Rams. I shared the same sense of wonderment as everyone
else watching the worst NFL franchise of the '90s find a truffle
and a quarterback out of a Disney story go from mini-football to
NFL MVP.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no bile or anger, at least not until Sunday, when
all of the negative emotions arrived at the same time like the
onset of food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   I metaphorically felt like John Hurt in that scene from
``Alien'' when the bug pops out of his chest, except the acrid
monster emerging from my soul has had several face lifts.
</P>
<P>
   I should have expected this. Before Sunday's NFC title game
against Tampa Bay began, Lawrence McCutcheon was introduced as an
honorary captain and the crowd responded with a murmur. It was
foreshadowing, and Tampa Bay only made the sense of dread worse by
bitterly hanging on until the very end.
</P>
<P>
   Each visual thereafter left a deep gash. Sideline camera pans on
cheering Melonheads, hearty fans no doubt, but they never saw
Deacon Jones and Merlin Olsen converge on a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs camera finds Georgia Frontiere on the sidelines, the
woman whose husband perished with a poorly-written will, the owner
of the team who never saw Jon Arnett or Dick Bass run the football,
much less knows who they are.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range Fox camera pans on Rams celebration, which happens to
be accompanied by the stadium PA playing Ray Charles' ``Georgia.''
The stomach knots.
</P>
<P>
   Camera goes close-up on the former dinner theatre queen as she
accepts a trophy and, momentarily, appears to start singing. This
is for the coach, she warbles. That would be the coach she almost
fired a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Proehl has a microphone in his face, and while I wonder
why his not-altogether-secure catch of the game-winning touchdown
counted and Bert Emanuel's two-hand catch on the game's climactic
play didn't, he says ``St. Louis fans are the best.''
</P>
<P>
   At which time I just lose it.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a few part-time politicians who didn't anticipate the
resolve of Carroll Rosenbloom to leave the Coliseum or the
shrewdness of John Shaw negotiating a buyout of his Anaheim Stadium
lease, no one in Los Angeles or Anaheim did anything to cause the
Rams to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   Long before there were Dodger fans, there were Ram fans, and
they treated the team well for 49 years. The Rams were treated a
lot better than a franchise with one NFL title (in 1951) and one
Super Bowl appearance probably deserved.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, 86,080 watched the Rams beat George Halas' Bears. There
were crowds of 85,865 and 93,751 in 1953, five crowds between
68,690 and 90,535 in 1955, and three crowds of more than 100,000 in
1957 and 1958.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were supported during the dismal '60s before George
Allen's arrival, and faithfully in the '70s despite heart-wrenching
playoff losses. The 1974 Rams averaged 76,456 fans a game. A crowd
of 62,538 sat through torrential rain to see the Rams lose a 1977
playoff game to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams drew well in Anaheim, too, at least until ownership
punted the concept of winning. In their first 12 years in Anaheim
(1980-91), which included two fan-unfriendly strike seasons, the
Rams played before crowds of 60,000 or more 35 times.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way: There are more Los Angeles Rams in the
Pro Football Hall of Fame than there are L.A. Dodgers in baseball's
shrine. From the recently passed Tom Fears to Eric Dickerson, and
including one Pete Rozelle, the one-time Rams publicist and G.M.
and NFL commissioner, who I have to believe might have stopped the
Rams from moving if he had still been commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any resentment over the Rams here is no greater than
the bitterness Brooklyn Dodgers fans and Oakland Raider fans felt
when their teams left home for Los Angeles. As a kid, I luxuriated
in the joy of the Dodgers' 1959 World Series, and as an adult, I've
advised any New Yorker still feeling any pain to get over it.
</P>
<P>
   So this is karma.
</P>
<P>
   My question is, when is karma going to visit Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frontiere had the good fortune to meet and wed Carroll
Rosenbloom, and for her husband's will to leave the franchise in
her hands instead of those of his son, Steve.
</P>
<P>
   She inherited the team just as it was not only making the
financially rich leap to Anaheim but finding its way into its first
Super Bowl. When a subsequent ticket controversy emerged from that
Super Bowl, new husband Dominic took the fall.
</P>
<P>
   When the city of Anaheim decided to build the Pond, they had to
go through Georgia's consigliere, Shaw, who negotiated buyout
language, having realized before most that a team's greatest
resource is the flexibility of its lease.
</P>
<P>
   When St. Louis officials fumbled a chance at an expansion team,
they began looking at other teams, and there was Georgia, who
always has an eye out for new suitors.
</P>
<P>
   And now she gets an all-expenses-paid trip to the Super Bowl,
not on merit but via total serendipity.
</P>
<P>
   Because the players hated Vermeil last year, and he only
returned because management didn't want to pay off his contract.
Because trading for Marshall Faulk was financially cheaper than
signing a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Because they didn't know what they had in Kurt Warner, who
Cleveland passed over in the expansion draft. Because the new
offensive coordinator was fired by Washington. Because the NFL
legislates parity, and the Rams caught Dallas, Green Bay and San
Francisco all descending at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure this resentment will pass soon enough. Life moves much
too quickly these days to gnaw on the same bone, a la Brooklynites.
And I'm truly happy for Vermeil, scout McCutcheon, publicist Rick
Smith, Todd Lyght, Marshall Faulk and even Shaw, a likeable fellow
once you get past his employer.
</P>
<P>
   Give me a week and one more win for Jeff Fisher's Titans, and
I'm sure I'll be fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
