<HEADLINE>
THIS NEVER LIVES UP TO THE HYPE EITHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Quiz: The 20-minute Super Bowl halftime show
provides ample time to a) run outside to toss around the football
before the second half starts, b) run to the bathroom, c) just run
away from the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are some who actually look forward to non-football
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   To please this attention-deficit demo, this year's
Disney-produced halftime show in Atlanta pulls together Toni
Braxton, Phil Collins, Christina Aguilera and Enrique Iglesias,
along with 125 drummers and percussionists, a full 80-person
symphony orchestra and a choir.
</P>
<P>
   All singing the soundtrack of ``Toy Story 2,'' no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   For old-time's sake, here's a look at the de-evolution of the
Super Bowl not-so-spectacular:
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl I: The University of Arizona and Michigan bands
played at the Coliseum. Ooooh, pinch me.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl X: The bicentennial marked the first of four
sugar-coated ``Up With People'' presentations during a 10-year
period. Teeth-capping costs made this show too prohibitive after
SBXX.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XI: A Disney-produced show with the theme ``It's a
Small World.'' It's also a small budget: The L.A. Unified All-City
Band was the star attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXI: A Disney-produced ``Salute to Hollywood's 100th
Anniversary'' wasn't much flashier, using a compilation of
L.A.-area high school drill teams and dancers. Now !ital!that's
Hollywood entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXVII: Michael Jackson at the Rose Bowl. C'mon
everyone, grab your crotch.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIII: You don't remember last year's ``Soul, Salsa
and Swing'' show with Stevie Wonder, Gloria Estefan and the Big Bad
Voodoo Daddy?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. No one else does either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4420 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HEAT-HNS &LR;      01-24 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HEAT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Miami was suckered in. The Rockets came out clanging, and the Heat
fell for it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami went merrily along Sunday night with the game plan that
seemed to be working, having no idea what was about to hit it. Then
the Rockets bombed the Heat into a 101-88 collapse at Compaq Center
that was not that close.
</P>
<P>
   After making one of their first 11 3-pointers, the Rockets
ripped 12 of their next 13, turning Matt Bullard into a
point-a-minute machine and one of the league's most tenacious gangs
of defenders into a sieve.
</P>
<P>
   Just 17 days after they were routed in Miami, the Rockets rolled
to a 20-point fourth-quarter lead. They extended their winning
streak to six, the longest current roll in the NBA. And they almost
_ not quite, but almost _ made their horrible start to the season
look like a setup itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much talent on this team,'' Rockets center Hakeem
Olajuwon said. ``It was just a matter of time. This team has a lot
of weapons. We do not just beat you one way. That's very unusual.
The record (16-24) is deceiving. Teams come in and know it will be
a tough game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was the Rockets' first of the winning streak in which
no one claimed a personal career best. But Bullard had a
season-high 24 points, making nine of 16 shots and six of 10
3-pointers. It was the most points he had scored in his eight
Rockets seasons. His career best of 28 came with the Hawks in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Shandon Anderson had 12 rebounds, one shy of the career
best he established Thursday. And the Rockets had their most
prolific 3-point shooting game of the season, sinking 15 of 31
treys, the most 3s made in the NBA this season and an
accomplishment made more remarkable by their 1-of-11 start. Cuttino
Mobley had 18 points in 25 minutes off the bench, nailing four of
six 3s.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the first quarter, it was 22-16 and we were
ahead,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said. ``It was really fool's gold.
They had every shot they wanted. They just missed them. It was just
a matter of time before they started hitting them. We did not play
hard, and they played great, absolutely great.''
</P>
<P>
   They played well enough to earn what Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich called the ``most satisfying victory of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had played Portland tough previously before
recording a breakthrough win Tuesday. But they trailed by as much
as 27 against the Heat in Miami on Jan. 6 and had lost eight
straight games against the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   And since beating the Knicks in Game 7 of the 1994 NBA Finals,
the Rockets had lost 10 in a row to Riley-coached teams. They also
had lost 17 consecutive games to Florida teams since taking the
1995 title with a sweep of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can win,'' Rockets guard Steve Francis said. ``All we have
to do is keep playing hard, and the sky's the limit for this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved we can play with the best in the East and the best
in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, averaging 25 points, 10.2 assists and 5.8 rebounds in
the first five games of the Rockets' streak, was limited to 10
points, nine assists and four rebounds. But in many ways, he keyed
the Rockets' offensive onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was so determined to prevent a Francis attack that Riley
ran a second defender at him throughout the game, trying to force
Francis to go to his left and give up the ball. Though the Rockets
expected it, Francis was given treatment the Heat normally does not
give even to Allen Iverson, Stephon Marbury or Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the plan was to help Tim Hardaway defensively. Hardaway
played in just his second game since missing 26 with a jammed knee.
But the Heat also dared the Rockets' shooters to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told me before the game, `They're going to come out and
double-team, so don't try to force it. Just look for the open guy.
Take advantage of it, and try to pick it apart,''' Francis said.
``I think we did a great job of finding the open man and finishing.
Those guys, every time I turned around they were throwing a
3-pointer in.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of failing to get Riley to double-team Olajuwon or
Charles Barkley, Tomjanovich said he expected Miami to try to get
the ball out of Francis' hands and had his shooters ready to burn
the Heat for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a team that tries to get players that are
good enough that people have to do something to get the ball out of
their hands,'' Tomjanovich said. ``But usually playing Miami, even
if we had big players, they don't double-team in the post. So we've
got these good shooters, and usually against these guys we never
get our shooters into their game because (Miami) is going
one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``But because we do have a penetrator now, they did double
there. We made 15 3-pointers. We worked on some of the things we
thought they were going to do, and sure enough they did, and our
guys were ready for it. I can't tell you how well these guys
executed the swinging of the ball on the double teams out on the
wing. I just feel real good about our guys taking the game plan and
executing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, there is a lot to feel good about these days, to the
point that even the oddest explanations seem plausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was,'' Kenny Thomas said of the Rockets'
hot shooting. ``Maybe we had some chili somewhere we shouldn't have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
