<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
``What kind of surrealistic nonsense is this?'' asks Howard Cosell
as Anita Bryant, Huey Lewis and the News and Boyz II Men team up to
sing the National Anthem in the first Millennium Bowl. Surreal is
right. Nonsense? NFL Films doesn't think so. Steve Sabol's knack of
editing archival NFL clips with computer-generated ``Forrest
Gump''-like special effects has resulted in a fascinating piece of
fantasy. Watch Ronnie Lott cover Lynn Swann and Joe Montana avoid
Jack Lambert as the Pittsburgh Steelers of the 1970s battle the San
Francisco 49ers of the 1980s in a two-part mythical ``Matchup of
the Millennium.'' The first half is ``played'' at Candlestick (or
3Com, if you want to get technical), with the second half at Three
Rivers. And, yes, Cosell is there, interviewing Richard Nixon.
``Millennium Bowl'' first half, ESPN2, 4:30 p.m. (repeats on ESPN
Friday at 5:30 p.m.) ESPN2 has the second half Monday, Jan. 31, at
5 p.m. 
TUESDAY 
The Lakers have the night off. Catch Harvard-Westlake's Russell
Lakey instead. Prep basketball: Harvard-Westlake at Crespi, Fox
Sports Net 2, 7 p.m. (replays Wednesday at 1 p.m.) 
WEDNESDAY 
Arizona tries to pull itself together. Arizona State isn't a great
place to start. College basketball: Arizona at Arizona State, Fox
Sports Net, 7 p.m. 
THURSDAY 
Check the Pac-10 standings: The unlikely unbeaten Trojans won't
duck any trouble against the 13-3 Ducks. College basketball: USC at
Oregon, Fox Sports Net, 7:30 p.m.; UCLA at Oregon State, Fox Sports
Net 2, 7 p.m. 
FRIDAY 
Memo to NBC when it comes to the 2000 Summer Olympics: You see,
they can show live sporting events from Down Under. Australian
Open: Women's final, ESPN, 6:30 p.m. (ESPN has the men's final
Saturday at 7 p.m.) 
SATURDAY 
Mike Tyson's trip to England the past few weeks has been quite
educational. ``Everybody in America is so money hungry,'' he told
reporters as he dodged women's rights protesters who can't believe
the government allowed the convicted rapist into the country so he
can rejuvenate Manchester's economy. ``It's like a rat race,'' he
continued, ``and even when you win, you are still a freaking rat.''
By the way, have you seen the size of the rats in England? Boxing:
Mike Tyson vs. Julius Francis, Showtime, 8 p.m. 
SUNDAY 
In an event so conducive to X's and I's and V's, how is it Roman
Gabriel never made it to the big show? And Bill Romanowski did?
Super Bowl XXXIV: St. Louis vs. Tennessee, Channel VII, III p.m. 

