<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-MAGIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS LOSE TO MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At least we know where they've been hiding ``The
Gong Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad nobody could find the mallet.
</P>
<P>
   So without a weapon required to gong them off the Staples Center
floor, the Clippers were allowed to finish Sunday's routine. With
weeks of rehearsal kicking in, they shifted their transition game
into high gear, smoothly going from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
   Conquering the squad representing Loss Angeles was the Orlando
Magic, a cast of glorified stunt doubles that had lost 13 of its
last 15 games. But Orlando (18-24) now claims two road victories in
as many nights, including a 102-89 victory over the Clips (10-30)
before a studio audience of 10,312.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who continue performing like a team of density,
now have eight consecutive defeats, 12 in their last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Some numbers: Clips forward Maurice Taylor scored 19 points and
had a dozen rebounds. Derek Anderson had 20 points, center Michael
Olowokandi had 13 rebounds and 12 points, with Lamar Odom
contributing 18 points and 3 momentum-killing first-half fouls.
</P>
<P>
   And now the defining numbers: The Clippers committed 18
turnovers that were converted in 24 Orlando points.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Armstrong had 17 points and Tariq Abdul-Wahad added 15
points to lead the Magic, who _ in concert with the Clippers _
defined the difference between scrappy and scrap.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Sunday's center matchup suggests that one of the most
underrated hoop hotbeds on the planet is England. OK, that's a
ridiculous notion, but the Magic and Clippers do start pivot men
who grew up in the UK. Orlando center John Amaechi (Penn State) was
born in Ohio, but was raised in Manchester, England. Clips center
Michael Olowokandi (Pacific) was born in Nigeria and raised in
London. And while, Olowokandi _ the first pick in the 1998 NBA
Draft _ has greater name recognition in the United States, he
admits Amaechi is the man in England. ``The name John Amaechi is
synonymous with British basketball,'' said Olowokandi, who doesn't
know the 29-year-old Amaechi personally. ``All the basketball
publications over there have him on the cover.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The silver lining in last week's losses to Sacramento and
Minnesota was the mini-renaissance of veteran point guard Eric
Murdock. The first-year Clipper, whose participation this season
has been compromised by a bum knee, scored 11 points and had 5
steals while having his way with Sacramento hotshot Jason Williams.
Against the Timberwolves, he came off he bench for a dozen points
and 4 assists. ``I've felt good the last week or so,'' said the
31-year-old Murdock, who realizes the team struggles without his
graybeard savvy. ``I'm going to be active on defense, I'm going get
some steals,'' Murdock, who led the NCAA in steals while at
Providence College, said. ``I'm going to hit shots and be
aggressive going to the hole. I'm trying to create shots for my
teammates, not myself.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   It was definite that backup center Keith Closs was indefinitely
suspended after missing Saturday's practice, but Coach Chris Ford,
who spoke with Closs by phone Sunday, didn't expect him to be at
Staples Center for the Orlando game. Ford said he and Closs would
meet this morning before the team leaves for San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-NFC-LEDE-HNS &LR;      01-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
ST. LOUIS _ Tampa Bay was right: Defense does win championships.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But it won't be the Buccaneers' NFC-leading defensive unit
heading to the Super Bowl to play the Tennessee Titans. Instead, it
will be St. Louis' after the Rams scratched out an 11-6 victory in
the NFC Championship Game on Sunday before 66,496 at the Trans
World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams (15-3), who moved from Los Angeles in 1995 and will be
making their first Super Bowl trip in 20 years, made big play after
big play on defense, limiting the Bucs (12-6) to a pair of field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week, all we heard about was Tampa's defense,'' Rams
defensive tackle D'Marco Farr said. ``We didn't say anything, not
to the coaches, not to the other players, but it got to us. It was
like, `Hey, we can play, too. If we get into a slugfest, we're not
going to bend.'''
</P>
<P>
   They were definitely in a battle.
</P>
<P>
   Rams quarterback Kurt Warner, who threw five touchdown passes
Jan. 16 to beat Minnesota, struggled at times Sunday. Warner was
26-of-43 for 258 yards with three interceptions, only one of which
was converted into points. He was picked off by Steve White at the
St. Louis 20 on the opening play of the game. The Rams then held
the Bucs to 13 yards on six plays, and Martin Gramatica kicked a
25-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The other two interceptions netted Tampa Bay nothing but
frustration, with one drive stalling after five plays and the other
after three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was in an Oliver Stone movie,'' Farr said. ``It
was 11-6. There were noses bloodied at the end of the game. You
just can't write a better script than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that St. Louis would have minded scoring a few more points
and winning in a less dramatic manner. But the Rams found
themselves trailing 6-5 when they got the ball with 8:01 to play.
They had managed only one drive of more than six plays in the
second half and only three all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Their drive began at the Tampa Bay 47, and the Rams moved to a
third-and-four at the Bucs' 30. The plan was for a short pass
outside to Marshall Faulk, but the Buccaneers blitzed and Warner
found Ricky Proehl in man-to-man coverage against Brian Kelly.
Proehl, who caught six passes for 100 yards Sunday, made a leaping
catch in the end zone, fighting off Kelly for his first touchdown
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams failed on a two-point conversion pass, but they had an
11-6 edge with 4:44 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came down, his (Kelly's) hand was in there, but I
pinned it against my hip and kept my body between the defender and
the ball,'' Proehl said.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay threatened on its final drive, with a questionable
call helping to end its season. The Bucs drove to a first down at
the St. Louis 22 with 1:25 to play, but rookie quarterback Shaun
King (13-for-19 for 163 yards, two interceptions) was sacked at the
35 by Grant Wistrom. King then connected with former Rice standout
Bert Emanuel on an 11-yard pass, but the catch was ruled an
incompletion after a video review, leaving the Bucs with
third-and-23 and 47 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was apparent that the player (Emanuel), as he was catching
the ball, he used the ground and the tip of the ball hit the
ground,'' referee Bill Carollo told a pool reporter after the game.
``It was one continuous motion. He wasn't down by contact.''
</P>
<P>
   King then threw two more incomplete passes, including a Hail
Mary that was batted down in the end zone, and the Rams were headed
to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay kept St. Louis' No. 1-ranked offense out of the end
zone for most of the day. The Rams scored on a first-quarter field
goal _ a 24-yarder by Jeff Wilkins _ that tied the game at 3 with
4:17 remaining in the period.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis then added a safety only seconds into the second
period after the snap from Bucs center Tony Mayberry flew over
King's head and into the end zone. King kicked it out of the back
of the end zone and took the safety, giving the Rams a 5-3 lead,
which they took into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys played well, tackled well, and we did what
we thought we could do,'' Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy said. ``We
just gave up one big play (the touchdown to Proehl) at the wrong
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially considering that the 14-point underdog Bucs took the
lead on their first drive of the second half. King led his team on
a nine-play, 66-yard drive, highlighted by a third-and-eight pass
to Jacquez Green for 32 yards. A facemask penalty on the play gave
the Bucs the ball at the St. Louis 12. They eventually reached the
five but could get no closer, and Gramatica kicked a 23-yard field
goal for a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough feeling, difficult to be that close to a
Super Bowl and not get it done,'' Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's stifling defense blanketed the Rams' deep-threat
receivers and surrendered only short gainers underneath the
coverage until Proehl finally broke free for the decisive score.
</P>
<P>
   ``They trapped us into their type game a little bit,'' St. Louis
coach Dick Vermeil said. ``We don't see the slanting, stunting
scheme with quick people like they have very often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' offense, which averaged slightly more than 400 yards
per game this season, was limited to 309. Faulk, the league's
Offensive Player of the Year, carried 17 times for 44 yards. Isaac
Bruce caught only three passes for 22 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough battle,'' Bruce said. ``We had to fight for
everything we got. They didn't give us anything out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams will face the Tennessee Titans on Sunday in Super Bowl
XXXIV. Tennessee handed St. Louis one of its three losses this
season, beating the Rams 24-21 at Nashville, Tenn., on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
