<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 03:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4426 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-IOWA-CAUCUSES-SFCHRON     01-24 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CAUCUSES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES HEAT UP IOWA RACE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  DES MOINES, Iowa _ With Vice President Al Gore and Texas
Governor George W. Bush holding huge leads in voter polls, an army
of presidential hopefuls fanned out across the frigid farms and
hamlets of Iowa as voters prepared to officially raise the curtain
on the 2000 presidential contest tonight.
<P>
   sub graf &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Ten months before the November election, the Iowa vote _ held
in thousands of schools, meeting halls and homes beginning at 7
p.m. tonight (CST) _ will serve to further winnow the field of
presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome will provide mo- &LR; ir,5l,6p6  &LR; mentum, or deflate
expectations, for candidates heading into the New Hampshire primary
on February 1 and to the crucial Super Tuesday contests on March 7,
including the California primary.
</P>
<P>
   sub graf &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bush and Gore enter the caucuses guarding formidable 2-to-1
leads in the latest polls in Iowa, where just 200,000 voters _
about one in 10 _ are expected to come out to the caucuses. Their
choices haven't been a consistent harbinger of the party nominees
on either side, selecting the eventual winner only three times
since 1976. Democrats here in 1992 gave Bill Clinton just 3 percent
of their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the stakes are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   new graf &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Iowa has boosted some people, and it's also eliminated a lot
of folks,'' said Hugh Winebrenner, political historian at Drake
University.
</P>
<P>
   In a final round of furious campaigning, a fired-up Gore urged
supporters at a union meeting in Newton last night not to be
complacent. Challenger Bill Bradley, who has spent more time and
money in Iowa than any Democrat in history, continued to battle
against concerns about his health and the perceptions that he has
lost momentum.
</P>
<P>
   sub graf &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Yesterday, despite a ringing endorsement by the Des Moines
Register, the state's largest newspaper, and a promise to remain
``in this campaign for the duration,'' Bradley all but conceded
tonight's contest, calling Iowa ``a difficult state to penetrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a confident Bush, pressed again on the issue of
abortion, said he would support the current anti-abortion plank in
the Republican platform. Yet despite his wide lead, the GOP
front-runner, who has spent 30 days and $1.6 million in TV ads in
Iowa, knows he must meet enormous expectations when tonight's votes
are counted.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Steve Forbes, hoping for a strong second-place showing
with Arizona Senator John McCain not on the Iowa ballot, aired a
new TV ad attacking Bush and continued to insist that he is the
``true conservative'' in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who has doubled Bush in both time and money spent in
Iowa, must contain an upstart challenge from conservative Alan
Keyes. Now third in the polls, Keyes' impassioned speeches have
electrified Iowans, often attracting bigger crowds than either Bush
or Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   GOP commentator Gary Bauer also needs a critical boost, and Utah
Senator Orrin Hatch said he must be a strong fourth to continue.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Nonstop Visits
</P>
<P>
   Even with frigid weather putting a chill on last week's
appearances, candidates flew, bused and walked the ice-shrouded
terrain nonstop into the final hours. Iowa, said Bush with a grin,
is a test for candidates and voters alike _ ``a look-see, what we
call a tire-kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, their homespun appeals _ some eloquent, some
absurd _ provided glimpses of both the candidates' strengths and
the voters' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Some standout moments:
</P>
<P>
   _In bone-shattering 5-degree weather, wind-chill 20 below,
Bauer's press conference outside the golden-domed state capital in
Des Moines to address the nation's ``moral crisis.'' Bauer,
battling not to finish last, watched his words freeze in mid-air as
a handful of reporters and camera crews buried in hats and mittens
captured the moment, clearly believing the only real looming crisis
was frostbite.
</P>
<P>
   _Bush, inching his way down the Main Street in Grinnell , Iowa &LR; 
 &LR; (population 9,000), as mobs of cameras and reporters climbed on
cars, elbowed old ladies and trampled other ``real people'' who
came to see the candidate. ``There's more of you people than there
are of us,'' sniped one frustrated Grinnellian to the media hordes.
``You guys are like a bunch of maggots.''
</P>
<P>
   _Bradley, the former basketball and Olympic great, patiently
taking questions about his health from senior citizens. ``I wish
you'd put us at ease,'' said one 66-year-old Muscatine resident to
the New Jersey Democrat, who has suffered bouts of irregular
heartbeats. Bradley announced a bowling outing to show off his
stuff, and his campaign spokesman joked that he would get back on
the court, ``five on one, just to show off.''
</P>
<P>
   _Gore, standing in front of a shiny green and spanking clean &LR; 
 &LR; John Deere tractor parked in a heated barn on the Manz family farm
in Perry and showing he knew just how long he had to keep up the
rigorous campaign pace. ``The fight is going to take place right
here in Iowa 99 hours and 7 minutes from now,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Iowans See What Fuss Is About
</P>
<P>
   All this political activity was not taken lightly by the
citizens of Iowa. Bundled up, with kids in tow, they turned out to
see, hear and touch the presidential hopefuls. And they came armed
with tough questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowans have a culture of being very one-on-one. They see these
candidates and say, `You're equal to me, and I'm equal to you,'''
said Peggy Elliot, an attorney and City Council member in Grinnell.
``It's a very strong community. We like what we have, and we want
to keep it. There's a very strong level of organization.''
</P>
<P>
   There were thoughtful, concerned people like Ruth Harris, a &LR; 
minister in Des Moines, who sat at the back of the city's &LR;  historic
Val Air Ballroom to watch Bradley speak on issues of &LR;  health care.
When he finished, Harris, an independent voter, was &LR;  convinced.
``It's great to see someone who would be a real &LR;  leader, take a
stand and go against the grain,'' she said.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  And there was Matt Smith, a conservative, churchgoing man who
farms 1,500 acres of corn and soybeans near Marshalltown and who
came to the Best Western Hotel in town to hear Bush at a GOP rally
.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he cares deeply about issues such as abortion and
education and bringing back dignity to the White House. He said he
has considered Forbes, Bauer and Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a thousand questions that must be addressed, and you
have to have a man who is right in his heart,'' he said. But in the
end, he said, Bush will get his vote because ``how do you do
anything if you can't get elected? I know he connects with ordinary
people.''
</P>
<P>
   It was those ``ordinary people'' whom candidates - surrounded &LR; 
by consultants, spokespeople and press entourage - worked &LR;  mightily
to reach.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   That was one reason why hamlets like Grinnell, with its old &LR; 
brick downtown, friendly bakery, and ``come on in coffee shops &LR;  was
swamped with politicians this week.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes showed up for a chili dinner, his third visit; Keyes &LR; 
stopped by to pump up the conservative vote; Tipper Gore came &LR; 
Saturday to meet with caucus leaders.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, trailed by two packed media busses, descended on the &LR; 
town Friday for a `Main Street walk.'' As he poured coffee for &LR; 
seniors at the Cunningham Drug Store fountain, he urged them to &LR; 
not to pay attention to the polls.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `Monday, January 24, 7 p.m.,'' he reminded them, time and &LR; 
again. And while media pundits suggest he's the GOP candidate &LR; 
who's got it made, Bush argued to Iowans, ``the only time when &LR; 
you've got it made..is when people show up at the caucuses.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Gore, like Bush, appeared not to take anything for granted,
batting back the suggestion from Bradley that he represents
``entrenched power,'' not the power of change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting for people is what the Iowa caucuses are all about,''
yelled Gore at a meeting at Iowa Western Community College.
``Fighting to save the family farm is not entrenched power. That's
about fighting for people!''
</P>
<P>
   But with the political tug-of-war down to the wire on television
and in the field, Iowans such as Mary Dean Rasmussen, 71, suggested
it all may come down to last-minute decisions.
</P>
<P>
   She sat at the counter of Cunningham's Drug Store, under the
``Cappuccino, 39 cents'' sign as Bush himself refilled her coffee
cup. A nice young man and a nice sales pitch, Rasmussen said with a
twinkle in her eye, but she still ``wasn't sure'' if he would get
her support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all good,'' she said of the candidates. ``If they can
only follow through ... .''
</P>
</TEXT>
