<HEADER>
A4523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-CO     01-24 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Japanese still in denial over WWII atrocities
 &HT;    (For release Jan. 26, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am thumbing through Life magazine's 1950 ``Picture History of
World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   On Page 92 are two shocking photos of a Chinese man being
bayonetted by Japanese soldiers. In the first, a soldier is running
a sword through the victim, who is blindfolded and tied to a post.
In the second photo, another Japanese soldier is running a bayonet
into the chest of the man.
</P>
<P>
   What sent me to looking into the book is the continuing denial
by many Japanese that the so-called ``Rape of Nanking'' _ a brutal
slaughter of thousands of Chinese civilians in 1937 _ was an
exaggeration. Last week, those of that attitude held an unpopular
one-day conference in Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   This denial of a Nanking slaughter followed on the heels of a
Japanese publishing house's decision last May to cancel publication
of a translation of ``The Rape of Nanking'' by American author Iris
Chang.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of soothing through apology, Japan remains reluctant
to own up to its atrocities of World War II. At this late date, an
apology is not necessary; just an acknowledgement will do.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about any misgivings he might have had in ordering
atomic bombs dropped on Japan, Harry Truman reportedly responded:
``I'm still waiting for them to apologize for Pearl Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they didn't, and they won't. But that's all right; at
least they admit they participated.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who insist the Holocaust did not occur either.
No amount of grisly photographs or German-kept records will
convince them, because they do not want to be convinced.
Nevertheless, the German government has acknowledged the genocide,
displayed contrition and paid reparations to survivors.
</P>
<P>
   It's different with the Japanese. They are reluctant to own up
to anything. It took until October 1998 for Japan to publicly
acknowledge (and apologize) for its brutality toward the Korean
people (women forced into sex slavery and other crimes) during the
period of occupation from 1910 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, the Japanese don't appear prepared to
acknowledge their other atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Tillman Durdin, a veteran foreign correspondent for The
New York Times, was eyewitness to what occurred in Nanking, then
the Chinese capital. Part of his story for the Times read: ``Just
before boarding the ship for Shanghai, the writer watched the
execution of 200 men. The killings took 10 minutes. The men were
lined against the wall and shot. Then a number of Japanese, armed
with pistols, trod nonchalantly around the crumpled bodies, pumping
bullets into any that were still kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems the issue over the Rape of Nanking is muddied in
nuance. Much of the world accepts that as many as 300,000 were
slaughtered in Nanking. Those who disagree never do say how many
they think were slaughtered but denounce the higher numbers as
``myth.''
</P>
<P>
   So, let's assume 300,000 weren't killed; would they accept
150,000? 75,000? What will they acknowledge? Something happened in
Nanking; too many saw it. Pick a number, it still adds up to an
atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   (The number of Vietnamese civilians slaughtered by American
troops in My Lai ranges from 100 to 200 and we acknowledge it as an
atrocity. That's roughly the same amount as the Times's Durdin saw
in just 10 minutes in Nanking.)
</P>
<P>
   Japan's World War II aggressions are steeped in brutality. Look
no further than the vivid Life picture history of the war. On Page
337 is a photograph of a Japanese executioner about to behead a
blindfolded and bound Australian pilot in New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   All this happened at least 50 years ago; the Rape of Nanking,
the Bataan Death March, the flagrant dismissal of the Geneva
Convention rules of war, and still Japan is reluctant to admit its
heinous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Own up to it, Japan! If you don't want to apologize, don't. But
at least admit to the crimes your predecessors committed. We can
argue about precise numbers later.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
