<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX     01-24 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bush brothers battle it out on death row
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like rival NASCAR drivers revving their engines, the Bush boys
are gunning for the trophy. And it will be a dangerous race, you
may be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Not, of course, for the governors themselves, Jeb in Florida and
George W. in Texas, but for the inmates on their death rows. George
is the points leader by far, but Jeb, not to be done in by an
enervating case of brotherly penal envy, has tuned his own killing
machine to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   After the states were cut loose by the Supreme Court to resume
capital punishment in 1976, Texas rushed to the lead and has held
it for years _ racking up 201 deaths by the end of '99. That was
more than a third of all the executions in the country, and Texas
is now in the midst of a 15-day spree that will kill another seven.
</P>
<P>
   In his mere five years as governor, George W. Bush has presided
over more than half of those executions _ 112 before the current
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not unique in this role. Texas politics sometimes
degenerates into contests in which candidates try to outbid each
other in the number of people they promise to execute.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, a self-described compassionate conservative and a
professing Christian, has been an especially happy executioner, not
only shrugging off a record rate of execution but opposing
legislation that would have spared mentally retarded defendants and
vetoing a bill to upgrade his state's notoriously awful public
defender system.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has legendarily executed men represented by attorneys who
were drunk or on drugs in court and, in one case, a convict whose
lawyer slept during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   All this puts little brother Jeb at a disadvantage. Florida,
with 44 executions since '76, is third among states after Virginia,
and trails Texas 393 to 458 in the number on death row.
</P>
<P>
   But putting the pedal to the metal, Bush called a special
session of the Florida Legislature this year, which dutifully
enacted legislation to speed up the execution process, with the
goal of cutting the time between conviction and execution to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it took an average of 7 1/2 years to free the 87
people sentenced to death but found to have been wrongly convicted
since '76. Two in Florida served 12 years before another man
confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Actual guilt or innocence is of decreasing importance to
legislatures and courts impatient with appeals, including even,
shamefully, the Supreme Court. Congress voted to crimp the federal
appeals process in 1996 and President Clinton signed on. (No
surprise. Running for president in 1992, he theatrically flew back
to Arkansas to oversee the execution of a retarded man.)
</P>
<P>
   The new rules in Florida don't mean Jeb can catch up with
George, or even overtake Virginia, but they will let him make more
of a race of it.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, a 1997 study pegged the murder rate in the 38 states
with capital punishment at 6.6 per 100,000. In the 12 others and
the District of Columbia, it was 3.5. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 0928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
