<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-CAPITAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL IS EDUCATION CAPITAL, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study from McGill University asserts that the North
American city most densely packed with scholars lies not across the
Charles, but across the St. Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Experts from the Canadian university's Planning Office said that
Montreal has edged out Boston for the highest concentration of
university students. Using data from the 1996 census, McGill's
Planning Office reported that Montreal has 4.38 students per 100
residents _ compared to 4.37 students per 100 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   If true, that statistic could be hard to swallow in Boston,
which, as a McGill press release diplomatically puts it, ``is often
admired as the intellectual capital of North America.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials said they did not set out to compete with
Boston's burnished academic image. But when they crunched the
numbers, they were surprised to discover that Montreal came in
first _ a boast that is likely to prove useful to city officials
trying to broadcast the availability of educated workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ecstatic,'' said Real Del Degan, a spokesman for the
McGill Planning Office. ``I've had colleagues who have been to City
Hall since the study came out, and the guys are in a wonderful
mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal is home to four universities with more than 30,000
students each: McGill, the University of Montreal, Concordia, and
the University of Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics have raised a few eyebrows south of the 49th
parallel, especially in cities where higher-education officials
have ranked themselves higher on the list than McGill did.
</P>
<P>
   A dense population of university students can improve a city's
image to burgeoning businesses, said Michael A. Gerber, of the
Atlanta Regional Consortium for Higher Education, which released
its own ranking last spring.
</P>
<P>
   But a review of McGill's claims seemed to inspire little fear in
Boston City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that students are going to stop coming to Boston
anytime soon,'' said John Dorsey, a spokesman for Mayor Thomas M.
Menino. ``A lot of these schools are household names for people
from the time they're growing up. Boston is synonymous with higher
education.''
</P>
<P>
   By McGill's calculations, Montreal and the
Boston-Worcester-Lawrence area are neck-and-neck at the top of the
list, with the Denver-Boulder-Greely area third with 4.1 university
students per 100 city residents, the Minneapolis-St. Paul area
fourth with 3.24, and the Norfolk-Virginia Beach-Newport News area
fifth with 3.09 students per 100 citizens. The study excluded
two-year colleges and community colleges, and took into account
large suburban expanses as well as city centers.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors _ and the resulting rankings _ seem wrong to
Gerber. His Atlanta-based Consortium came up with entirely
different rankings last spring in a survey that included two-year
colleges and excluded suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Boston came first in his survey, with 4.3 higher-education
students per 100 people; New York came second, with 4.0 per 100;
and Atlanta came third, with 3.72.
</P>
<P>
   Because his study focused only on American cities, it has no
ranking for Montreal. However, Gerber said he's sure it would not
have come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has no reason to worry, he said. ``If you've got brand
identity to begin with you don't have to worry so much about these
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observers doubted whether a high per-capita student
population was any kind of a measure of academic excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to compare the academic research and
development in Boston with the academic research and development in
Montreal,'' said John Hoy, president of the New England Board of
Higher Education. ``We'd just wipe them off the map.''
</P>
<P>
   And at Boston University's Sherman Union, students said they
doubted any city could rival Boston's academic brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you're at the center of where everything goes,''
said Jaime Jenkinson, a 19-year-old freshman from Cedar, Minn.
``You're sure that the most brilliant people who ever walked the
face of the earth are literally two blocks from you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
