<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4594 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TESTICULAR-CANCER-LIF     01-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTICULAR-CANCER-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP ATHLETES NOT IMMUNE TO TESTICULAR CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photos of Lance Armstrong, Ken Dennard and Scott
Hamilton) 
 By SCOTT IRWIN 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro athlete Ken Dennard was the picture of good health. At
6-foot-8 and 250 pounds, the 23-year-old was a lean, muscular
forward starting a career in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one week before the Kansas City Kings' training camp began
in 1982, he discovered a tiny lump in his left testicle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was about the size of a BB and it didn't hurt,'' said
Dennard, who played on the Duke team that reached the 1978 NCAA
finals. ''When I felt it, I knew it wasn't supposed to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletes have a keen awareness of their bodies, so Dennard
didn't hesitate. He consulted with the Kings' trainer, who referred
him to a urologist. The urologist told him he should undergo
surgery immediately to have the testicle removed.
</P>
<P>
   Dennard balked before the urologist explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told me that nine times out of 10 it's malignant,'' Dennard
said. ''When you hear that, of course, you go numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennard was stricken with testicular cancer, a disease that is
still fairly rare. The American Cancer Society estimates that 7,400
new cases will be diagnosed this year. But while it represents only
1 percent of all male cancers, it's the leading cause of cancer for
men in their 20s and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Testicular cancer can strike even the healthiest young men.
Figure skater Scott Hamilton had it, as did professional baseball
player John Kruk. Lance Armstrong, who recently won the Tour de
France, had an advanced case of it. And Green Bay Packers punter
Josh Bidwell was recently diagnosed with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Testicular cancer, for some reason, seems to be on the rise,''
said Dr. Ed Whitesides of Urology Associates of Southeastern North
Carolina. ''It used to be about three to five per 100,000 men; now
it's more like eight to 10. No one knows why.''
</P>
<P>
   Men should conduct self-examinations once a month, say
urologists and oncologists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't stress how important that is,'' said Dr. Mary Raab, an
oncologist at the East Carolina School of Medicine. ''It's so
important. Women start doing a breast check when they begin
menstruating. At the same time, boys should start checking
themselves as early as age 13.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennard, a volunteer for Coaches vs. Cancer, often counsels
victims and speaks publicly on battling testicular cancer. He
credits early detection with saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''You should not be ashamed of your body,'' he said. ''You have
to take care of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennard had the testicle removed, then went through 20 sessions
of radiation therapy. The radiation cured him of cancer, although
it damaged his digestive system.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation, a common form of treatment that follows surgery, is
primarily used to treat cancer that has spread from the testicle to
lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   Breakthroughs in platinum-based chemotherapy drugs have helped
increase the survival rate of men with testicular cancer to 95
percent, Raab said. The American Cancer Society estimates that 300
people in America will die of testicular cancer this year.
</P>
<P>
   As with radiation, some patients treated with chemotherapy have
long-term side effects, such as kidney damage and nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Because he didn't detect his testicular cancer early, pro
cyclist Armstrong had to endure months of chemotherapy in 1996. The
cancer spread to his lungs and brain, and he underwent surgery to
remove a testicle and lesions from his brain. Doctors gave him a 50
percent chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong did survive, and he went on to win one of sports' most
demanding events last summer. His recovery, like Dennard's,
illustrates that with treatment, victims of testicular cancer can
go on to live normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a man who came from the depths of chemotherapy . . . and
came out on top,'' said Karl Hausmann, who heads the Lance
Armstrong Foundation, which raises money for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Tour de France ''really brought back some feelings
of thankfulness,'' Dennard said. ''His recovery was even more
courageous because of where his cancer had spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennard also returned to competitive athletics after surgery and
treatment. He played 30 games for the Kings during the 1982-83
season, then another two years for the Denver Nuggets and in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Like many men who survive testicular cancer, Dennard started a
family. He now has a 4-year-old son, Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Chemotherapy can result in a temporary reduction in sperm count,
Raab said, but in most cases that rate returns to normal. Because
of the sensitive nature of testicular cancer, many men need
counseling in addition to the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Especially in the younger population, when the cancer often
strikes, this is a threat to their manhood or masculinity,'' Raab
said. ''Some of these young men go through a tough time. They feel
it's almost like they're being castrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennard, who now owns an investor-relations firm in Houston,
said attitudes have changed since the Kansas City Kings' publicly
announced that he suffered from ''cancer of the lower intestine''
rather than reveal where the cancer really was.
</P>
<P>
   ''More men are sensitive to their feelings than 20 years ago,''
he said. ''My counsel is, 'Don't let fear paralyze you,''' he said.
''It's OK to feel fear _ just don't let it control you.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Scott Irwin writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
