<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4595 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-KIDS-LEARN-MULTICULTU     01-24 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-LEARN-MULTICULTURALISM-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS NEED TO LEARN THAT DIFFERENT DOESN'T MEAN BAD
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes b/w photo of a multicultural group of toddlers) 
 By LAURA TAXEL 
 c.1999 Laura Taxel 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)   All the
Difference in the World: Living In A Multicultural Society
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was in school we learned that this country was a melting
pot, a society of immigrants on the way to becoming as uniform and
homogenized as milk. We touted the fact that we were Americans,
never noticing that the image _ blonde haired, blue eyed, white
skinned, and male _ clearly left a great many of us out of the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   We all sang Christmas carols at holiday time, whether it was
part of our family's tradition or not. We weren't taught that some
people might not want to give up their cultural identity, or that
other groups were kept marginal, barred from the mainstream, with
no chance of ''melting'' in. Prejudice got a cursory mention.
</P>
<P>
   But the message today's children are getting is different.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're making a fundamental shift in how we portray our
national past and the make-up of this country,'' said Tim Mitchell,
multicultural coordinator for the Cleveland Heights-University
Heights school system in Ohio. ''We're looking at who has been left
out. We want to present a more inclusive and accurate reflection of
the fact that we live in a multicultural society.''
</P>
<P>
   Multicultural is a word most parents didn't grow up hearing, but
now it's a concept we need to understand. ''Diversity is not only
about differences of skin color or ethnicity,'' said Fay Sholiton,
trustee of National Council of Christians and Jews.
''Multiculturalism looks at all divisions of gender, class,
economic status, age, and ability that exclude people in our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   What children need to learn is that different doesn't mean bad.
It's natural to notice differences, and kids tend to group
impressions under two basic headings, ''like me'' and ''not like
me.'' They'll point out and comment, usually in an embarrassingly
loud voice, on what they see.
</P>
<P>
   I've cringed when my boys described someone as fat, or old, or
crippled. But James Banks, professor of education and the director
of the Cehter for Multicultural Eduction at the University of
Washington, Seattle, who has written extensively about
multiculturalism over the past twenty years, disagrees. He tells
his students that if they don't see that he's black, something's
wrong. ''It's what you do,'' he says, ''with what you see.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Professor Banks, learning to live with diversity is
a 'demographic imperative'. ''We are becoming a nation without a
clear majority.'' The U.S. Department of Labor predicts that by the
year 2000, 1 out of 3 Americans will be a person of color, 83
percent of the new entrants to the workforce will be women and
minorities. 34.9 million people will be age 65 or over. Banks, like
many educators, feels that all children need to know how to deal
with diversity in positive ways.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must reach children at an early age with messages about
understanding, respect, and amity among people,'' says Sandi
Holmes, program specialist with the National Council of Christians
and Jews. ''As schools and institutions begin to change how they
define and describe our society, individuals need to do that too.''
</P>
<P>
   Families can start by discussing their own heritage. That's
important because children need a clear sense of identity in order
to recognize and respect that in others. 'Them' vs. 'us' attitudes
often reflect low self esteem and lack of confidence. ''Everyone
belongs to some kind of group,'' says Sholiton, ''and it's
important to encourage pride in one's own identity, while at the
same time dispelling intolerance through understanding the culture
of others. That's how we can each begin to recognize what we have
in common as human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Children acquire their judgments from adults and the biased
messages of television, books, and movies. The prejudices they copy
are rooted in fear and misunderstanding. If parents want their
children to develop an appreciation for differences, they should
find ways to expose them to a wide world of people. Challenge
children's stereotypes with information. Include many different
kinds of people among your own friends, read stories that show
different groups in a positive light, sample the foods, festivals
and customs of other cultures .
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coles, a Harvard professor, child psychiatrist, and
author of over 50 books including ''The Moral Life of
Children,''and ''The Spiritual Life of Children,'' urges parents
and educators to share their own experiences of being ostracized
with children and to talk about fear and dislike of otherness.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of us,'' he says, ''have experienced the pain of prejudice
when we are not favored by someone who matters to us. All of us
have been singled out for our differences. And all of us have
dismissed someone or some group as not worthy of our concern and
compassion. Let children know there are always things that make
people different from one another. Prejudice is when we place value
judgements on what we observe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Multiculturalism is not a subject to teach, but something to
be talked about in a natural way. What's needed is not only
cultural literacy but a moral literacy that emphasizes the respect
and kindness we must practice if we're to live together. This a
movement not only of the mind but of the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   When my twin boys were eight years old, I took them to a
heritage festival held each year in our city. Twenty-four different
nationality groups had displays, featuring native products and
handicrafts. It was a delight to watch the kids eat Thai satay and
Greek souvlaki with the same enthusiasm they usually applied to a
hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   They boogied to the beat of African drums, and swayed to the
tunes of a Bohemian brass band. They were at ease in shorts and
T-shirts, wandering among people dressed in saris, turbans, and
kimonos. Although everything was unfamiliar, my boys felt at home.
For them, the new image of America as a mosaic, not a melting pot,
isn't an idea whose merits are still being argued by politicians
and academics. It's a fact. I asked Nathan what he thought about
the event. ''It's good,'' he said. ''It could help stop dis...,
dis..., what's that word for when people are against each other?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Discrimination,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could end that because all these different people get to
show off who they are and all their wonderful things, and we get to
find out that they're people, just like us.''
</P>
<P>
   For More Information:
</P>
<P>
   National Association for the Education of Young Children
1-800-424-2460 Free brochure, ''Teaching Young Children to Resist
Bias: What Parents Can Do,'' and multicultural materials for
teachers
</P>
<P>
   The National PTA, 700 Rush Street, Chicago, IL 60611 Free
brochure, ''What to Tell Your Child About Prejudice and
Discrimination'' and other materials about dealing with bias
