<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why can't I do time-lapse refinishing?
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ The man on the television was refinishing a
dresser and it was beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make the finish remover do the work,'' he advised. Before my
eyes, old finish floated away from a dresser. The dark, nasty tide
of yellowed varnish and discolored stain receded, revealing the
lush, fine-grain hardwood beneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why look at that! Brazilian bonchacudawood. You don't see this
very often because its importation is banned under three
international treaties. That means this piece we picked up for $18
at Repoman's Used Furniture Barn and Mower Repair is probably worth
close to $62,000.
</P>
<P>
   He gently wiped the piece with a towel, collecting finish that
puddled off as though it were nothing more than mud that
unaccountably was tracked on the dresser by mischievous children.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, my project, a $15 headboard, stood sulking in a
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to accept change, it clung tenaciously to an ugly finish
that unconvincingly attempted to tart up the pine beneath it as
some sort of exotic hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   If successful in my project, I would take this $15 piece of wood
and turn it into something you would be glad to pay $25 for. All it
takes is skill, determination and $87 worth of dangerous
petrochemicals, any one of which, if mishandled, could turn my home
into an EPA Superfund site.
</P>
<P>
   ``There!'' he said. ``By letting the remover do the work, all
that's left is some sanding to get out those glass rings and plug
the bullet hole put there by someone who had tried to refinish this
before me.''
</P>
<P>
   The avuncular figured in the work apron began sanding and the
picture faded out to indicate the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   As an aficionado of home-improvement television, I love
time-lapse photography. Without it, you would have five or six
shows devoted to the fine points of sanding. The host would spend
the half-hour rubbing the furniture, muttering darkly to himself
and revisiting the mistakes he made throughout his life. Sanding
demands inner peace. The finish remover can't always do the work.
</P>
<P>
   Time-lapse photography is what makes home-repair television what
it is _ the only place where projects go smoothly, nobody's clothes
are stained and things don't come to a screeching halt for second
and third trips to the hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   Watching this makes me happy. Particularly when I leave my own
projects behind to painlessly view People Who Know What They're
Doing getting things done neatly.
</P>
<P>
   Nor am I alone. The last time my cable company rearranged its
channels, I discovered vast new areas of television including Home
&AMP; Garden Television, a channel dedicated to all home improvement
all the time. Every time I surfed by it, somebody else on the
screen was neatly doing jobs that would turn most homes upside down
for the better part of a week. A channel of other people
accomplishing things painlessly 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a wonderful age.
</P>
<P>
   When the program ended, I returned to my labors. I had hoped my
own fade-out from the project might have accomplished something. It
had not.
</P>
<P>
   There are two neat things about furniture refinishing that they
don't tell you about on TV. The first is that no job works
according to plan. You discover wood that is entirely different
from what you thought. The stain turns out to be nothing like the
can label. What was labeled ``Ye Olde Forest Pine'' looks like ``Ye
Olde Stealth Bomber.'' Things happen to alter your plans
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Like writing, you just start working and be watchful for what
emerges.
</P>
<P>
   The other cool thing is, unlike any other home improvement,
imperfection works for you. Holes, discoloration, worn spots,
bumps, odd spots of old finish that won't come off ... all give it
character. It's antiquing. I've read about people firing shotguns
at dressers and beating them with chains. It gives them
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   You can't have enough authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   My headboard now is done. The finish remover didn't do the work
for me. It looks very, very authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
