</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As old barns disappear, so do the rich stories that fill them
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When the lunch bell rang, about half the students
dashed to the cloak room to grab their sack lunches.
</P>
<P>
   The other half rushed for the cafeteria next to our schoolhouse,
a brick building that held grades one-12.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I ate in the cafeteria. The food was fantastic. My
opinion was shared by no one. At least no one admitted it.
</P>
<P>
   My school's herd mentality held that cafeteria food _ cooked and
served by great country cooks _ was not fit to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Kids with the sack lunches looked down on cafeteria students,
who often felt obligated to complain about food better than many of
them ate at home.
</P>
<P>
   One time, in the fifth grade, three of my friends talked me into
bringing a sack lunch the next day. That decision resulted in a
paddling.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this paddling, which was not my first or last,
when I read a story in the New York Times about the steady
disappearance of old wood barns across America.
</P>
<P>
   The story quoted Iowa farmer John Berdo, whose family has farmed
for seven generations, as observing that ``old barns are as
obsolete as the manual typewriter in the computer age.''
</P>
<P>
   Old wood barns are rapidly being replaced by metal storage
buildings that are bigger, less expensive to build and cost less to
maintain. They also lack the character and style of old wood barns.
</P>
<P>
   Old wood barns also will not hold the huge combines, tractors
and other over-sized equipment that have become mainstays of modern
farming.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that more than half of the nation's wood barns have
been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cost of repairing old wood barns, which can include
up to $20,000 for a new roof, old barns also are disappearing
because family farms are disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   My fifth-grade friends wanted me to bring a sack lunch one
particular day so we could eat our lunches in the old Lacy barn
about a mile west of the school. A couple of the boys had built a
fort out of hay bales in the barn.
</P>
<P>
   When the lunch bell rang, we grabbed our sacks from the cloak
room and ran for the barn.
</P>
<P>
   The fort was great. It had a tunnel to get inside the fort,
which had hay-bale battlements on top.
</P>
<P>
   The Lacy barn, which we more or less had permission to use as
long as we didn't break any bales, also had a rope hanging from a
block and tackle attached to the roof beam. We could swing from one
side of the barn to the other and drop down inside the fort, just
like Errol Flynn, Douglas Fairbanks, Tarzan or the Three
Musketeers.
</P>
<P>
   We made swords from wood laths and took turns attacking or
defending the fort. Someone finally realized that it may be time to
return to school. No one had a watch, but we reluctantly agreed. We
ran back to school.
</P>
<P>
   To our surprise, we got back only in time for the final school
bell.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with playing hooky, we were marched into the principal's
office where we each were told to empty our back pockets, bend over
and take our punishment.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much of a paddling. I think the principal also would
have preferred swinging across the Lacy barn and attacking our
hay-bale fort.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a Colorado vacation a few years ago, I made a
detour to see if my old school house was still standing. It was,
but it was vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The old Lacy barn was gone. In its place was a subdivision
called Lacy Estates.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that the old wood barns are disappearing. Metal
storage buildings will never generate as many good memories.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
