<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Height hang-ups
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ I come from a long line of short folks.
Grandmother Parker was 4 feet 10, and Granddaddy, before arthritis
bent him over, stood a whopping 5 feet 6. My mother barely made it
to 5 feet, and my father was 5 feet 7. So how did it happen I was
the tallest kid in the first grade (except for Artie Kuminski who
didn't count because he'd been sick and was already 7 going on 8)?
</P>
<P>
   Being tall was really cool because teachers always had neat jobs
for tall kids _ like washing blackboards. The chipped spatterware
basin and raggedy sponge, power symbols of a 6-year-old, were all
mine because even though Artie was taller, he was allergic to chalk
dust.
</P>
<P>
   Once the teacher learned I could be trusted with thumbtacks, she
added bulletin boards to my job specs. Pumpkins in October, elves
in December _ I did it all. Come spring, it was a cardboard
punch-out of purple iris, butter-yellow daffodils, and a pudgy,
crepe-paper bunny with one ear that flopped over. I tried sticking
it back up with a white tack that matched the fur but Ronald Gorsky
copped the tack and put it on Phyllis Hoffstetter's chair and made
her
</P>
<P>
   cry.
</P>
<P>
   In choir, since I was tall, I never had to stand in the front
row, which was important to me because my petticoat always seemed
to be hanging a couple of inches below the hem of my chintz
pinafore and grubby Bobby Kinkaid would break into sing-song: ``I
see London, I see France, I see Lizzie's underpants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid!'' I yelled just before I slugged him. ``Don't know the
difference between a slip and underpants.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, the gym teacher let me help her string up the volleyball
net, which was a big deal because I was never much good at
athletics. Helping out made me feel special.
</P>
<P>
   I was as ill-coordinated as I was tall, and my two big feet were
my own worst enemies. It seemed like one was always getting in the
way of the other, and as if neither was connected to my brain. When
I ran, my father likened the motion to that of an out-of-control
wind-up toy with an overstressed mainspring.
</P>
<P>
   Mother sadly confessed to her lady friends that her daughter had
the biggest feet she'd ever seen on a woman _ 7AAAA by the time I
was 11. With obvious embarrassment, she would remark to all within
sight of my flippers that no one in her family had big feet (hers
were 3B) so mine must be my father's fault (his were 8AA). I
learned to sit on my feet instead of letting them hang out for
comment _ particularly around the relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But then, sometime before my 12th birthday, an odd thing
happened _ I stopped growing. Suddenly, there were no more hems to
let down or barely scuffed shoes to send to the Salvation Army. My
11-year growth spurt had come to an end and by the time I hit high
school, short guys were asking me out because I didn't tower over
their pompadours when we danced.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, I became the one in the front row of class pictures, and
the one who watched parades between tall folks' armpits. Now I was
the kid who, when the football game got exciting and everybody
jumped up for a better look, was left standing on the seat yelling,
``WHAT HAPPENED?''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I've learned to accept the fact that at 5 feet 3,
no one is ever going to describe me as ``willowy,'' and that my
feet are no longer considered a regressive trait inherited from the
yeti. But there's still a problem.
</P>
<P>
   What I've been thinking about a lot lately is the probability
that my son Kristofor (6 foot 4 with feet the size of a Nash
Rambler) and his lovely wife Amy (also tall) will one of these days
produce an heir, a veritable Gulliver who will no doubt refer to me
as ``Little Grandmother,'' a designation I shall resent as well as
resemble.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, in an attempt to level the playing field, I've put
the children on notice. Offspring will call me ``Stretch'' or
everybody's out of the will.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
