<SLUG> BC-DAVID-ARQUETTE-IN-SCREAM-3-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP THE `SCREAM'-ING: DAVID ARQUETTE'S FINAL ROUND WITH `SCREAM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of David Arquette with Neve Campbell in a
scene from ``Scream 3.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    As far as David Arquette is concerned, the secrecy surrounding
``Scream 3'' was a pain in the ... eyes.
 &HT;    ``I got a script with red stripes down the middle of the pages,
just like everyone else got,'' the actor says. ``It was really hard
to read the script. You had to strain your eyes.''
 &HT;    The red lines were an anti-photocopying measure, only one of
many adopted by the production in the wake of widespread plot leaks
for ``Scream 2'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``It was a little bit of a drag,'' Arquette adds, ``and you
don't know if a `Scream' movie is really important enough to do
that. But they're (reacting to) the situation on `Scream 2,' where
people were trying to get the story off the Internet.
 &HT;    ``They are taking all the precautions they can this time,'' he
says, ``though people will talk about it anyway and try to figure
out what's going to happen before the film comes out. You really
can't stop it.''
 &HT;    Given that this is the third _ and allegedly final _ installment
in the ``Scream'' saga, it's impressive that people are still so
eager to find out what's going to happen in the new film, which
will open on Feb. 4.
 &HT;    Don't expect us to give away much, but it's no secret that
Arquette reprises his role as good guy Deputy Dewey, while
Courteney Cox Arquette _ more on that later _ and Neve Campbell
once again portray ambitious reporter Gale Weathers and luckless
murder magnet Sidney Prescott, respectively. The setting is
Hollywood, on the set of ``Stab 2,'' a sequel to the
movie-within-a-movie of ``Scream 2.''
 &HT;    Arquette, speaking by cellular telephone while driving his car
in Los Angeles, takes a stab at setting up ``Scream 3'' without
giving anything away.
 &HT;    ``You've got a movie within a movie,'' he says. ``In the second
one they made a movie of the first film, and it kind of played on
that. In this one, they take it a step further. A lot of `Scream 3'
takes place behind the scenes of a movie being shot.
 &HT;    ``Parker Posey plays Courteney's character in this one,'' he
adds, ``and Matt Keeslar plays Dewey.''
 &HT;    Getting an alternative take on his own popular character was a
lot of fun, Arquette says.
 &HT;    ``Matt's really funny,'' he says, ``and he's a good actor. It
was neat to see other actors walk around in our old costumes and
basically play our characters.''
 &HT;    Otherwise, Arquette will talk only in generalities.
 &HT;    ``Neve's character is still haunted by the murder of her mother
and also by the first murders,'' he says cautiously. ``It's all
still scary and exciting, and everybody is covered with blood
again.''
 &HT;    Whether Dewey is dead or alive after the final drop of blood is
spilled remains to be seen, but just as the ever-limping character
won Gale's heart in the earlier films, so Arquette walked off with
the girl in real life. Arquette and ``Friends'' star Cox met while
making the first ``Scream'' (1996), and they wed on June 12, 1999.
 &HT;    ``We got married right before we did `Scream 3,' so this is our
first movie as husband and wife,'' the actor says. ``It was great.
We had actually done another movie, `The Shrink Is In,' just before
`Scream 3,' when we were still engaged. So we were actually very
fortunate and got to spend the whole summer together.
 &HT;    ``It's hard to make time for each other in this business,'' he
adds, ``so the fact that we can work together just makes it so much
easier.''
 &HT;    As for marriage itself, count Arquette among the believers.
 &HT;    ``It is everything I ever wished for,'' he says ardently. ``I'm
very honored and respectful of my marriage. Courteney's special, in
her personality, her sense of humor. We have fun together and with
our friends and family _ I'm really happy.''
 &HT;    Only a few years ago, Arquette wasn't so happy. The son of Lewis
Arquette, grandson of Cliff Arquette _ better known as Charlie
Weaver of the old ``Hollywood Squares'' _ and sibling of actors
Patricia, Rosanna and Alexis, he fought through a substance-abuse
problem that nearly destroyed his life and his fledgeling career.
 &HT;    ``Everybody has their learning experiences,'' he says softly.
``You just have to be the best person you can, learn from your
mistakes and not repeat them as you move on with your life.''
 &HT;    Professionally, Arquette has been working steadily since his
film debut in ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (1992). His subsequent
credits include a mix of major releases and independent features,
among them ``Wild Bill'' (1995), ``Beautiful Girls'' (1996),
``Johns'' (1997), ``Dream with the Fishes'' (1998), ``The
Alarmist'' (1999) and ``Never Been Kissed'' (1999), as well as two
previous ``Scream'' frightfests.
 &HT;    The actor, who on the ``Scream 3'' soundtrack performs a song
with his band Ear2000, will next be seen in the aforementioned
``The Shrink Is In,'' a romantic comedy produced by his wife. She
plays a therapy patient who assumes the identity of her
psychiatrist, then falls for another patient (Arquette).
 &HT;    After ``Shrink'' wrapped and the shrieking stopped on ``Scream
3,'' Arquette headlocked ``Ready to Rumble,'' a road movie in which
he and Scott Caan play obsessive wrestling fans who worship the
talents of The King (Oliver Platt), a dethroned champ. Both
``Shrink'' and ``Rumble'' will be released sometime in 2000.
 &HT;    ``Just working in this town is an accomplishment in and of
itself,'' Arquette says. ``I'm working, so I'm pretty happy with
where my career is right now.
 &HT;    ``I just want to keep doing work I believe in and enjoy.''
 &HT;    Right now there are no other projects on Arquette's dance card.
He's taking some time off, reading scripts and relaxing at home in
Los Angeles with Cox Arquette.
 &HT;    Don't count on his turning up in a ``Scream 4,'' however.
 &HT;    ``We were all happy to do this one, but there was also a feeling
for a lot of us that we're done with it now,'' he says. ``We kind
of wanted to finish this one and put it to rest.
 &HT;    ``If the studio does more `Scream' movies, that's up to them.
But I don't think the rest of us will do them anymore.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Scream 3,'' consult the
Dimension Films Website at www.dimensionfilms.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
