<SLUG> BC-SANDRA-BULLOCK-IN-GUN-SHY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONE STAR: SANDRA BULLOCK CAN TAKE OR LEAVE THE A-LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Sandra Bullock with Liam Neeson in a
scene from ``Gun Shy.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Deep in the heart of Texas, Hollywood's sweetheart spends her
time sitting on her rickety front porch, with a beer in one hand
and a rawhide bone in the other.
 &HT;    At Sandra Bullock's house in Austin, people read Texas Monthly,
not Variety. They wear tank tops, not beaded gowns. And personal
trainers ... well, don't get her started.
 &HT;    ``When I need any exercise, I just go jump in the lake with my
dogs,'' Bullock says. ``At night I just like to sit outside, drink
a beer and listen to great blues music. For the first time in my
life, I can breathe.''
 &HT;    Oh, she's still a movie star _ her latest, ``Gun Shy,'' opens
nationwide on Feb. 4 _ but the star of ``Speed'' (1994) and ``While
You Were Sleeping'' (1995) is a long way from Tinseltown.
 &HT;    ``When I lived in L.A., right after the success of `Speed,' I
never went out to dinner,'' she says. ``I never saw my friends _ Iwas hiding out. I would sit around reading the trades. I was
suddenly worrying about what other people were doing _ I was
operating from a base of fear.
 &HT;    ``I even had road rage,'' she says, laughing. ``My spirit was
being crushed. I had to get out.''
 &HT;    So Bullock beat a retreat, buying a house in Austin and settling
down.
 &HT;    ``I tell you, my new attitude even makes these interviews
easier,'' the actress says during a chat at a Los Angeles hotel,
looking absolutely stunning in a gray, clinging sweater/dress, her
long, straight hair falling loosely on her shoulders and bangs
shading her eyes. ``I woke up this morning and thought, `I have
nothing to lose, nothing to prove.' It made me feel, for the first
time in a long time, free as a bird.''
 &HT;    It was only a year ago that Bullock announced that she'd be
taking an extended break from show business.
 &HT;    ``I felt I was burned out,'' she recalls. ``Dried up. Seriously,
I wanted to concentrate on my family and friends. My heart was very
full with other things _ I felt done with acting, finished.''
 &HT;    Famous last words. When the script for ``Gun Shy,'' a black
comedy about a drug-enforcement agent (Liam Neeson) on the verge of
retirement, arrived at her production office, Bullock couldn't
resist cracking it open. One thing led to another, and suddenly she
was producing the film and co-starring with Andy Lauer, Mitch
Pileggi, Oliver Platt and Dusty Kay.
 &HT;    ``It has always been a dream of mine to be Liam Neeson's arm
candy,'' she says, laughing.
 &HT;    She gets a little more serious in ``28 Days,'' due out in March.
Betty Thomas' drama casts Bullock as a newspaper reporter forced
into rehab by alcoholism.
 &HT;    ``I really intended to take a year off, but these two projects
were just too good,'' Bullock says, laughing. ``I actually did make
it to the eighth month of my time-off plan, which is the longest
break I've had in several years.''
 &HT;    Ever since Bullock drove that big bus in ``Speed'' ( 1994), she
had been working nonstop. And she'd been a big star, despite her
share of clunkers _ ``Two If By Sea'' (1996), ``In Love and War''
(1996) and the disastrous ``Speed 2: Cruise Control'' (1997) _ in
the intervening years.
 &HT;    ``I still find that the strangest part of stardom is going to a
department store to shop for bras,'' she says, giggling. ``You're
in the fitting room, struggling with the straps, and all of a
sudden someone pops their head over the stall and screams, `Sandra
Bullock, I love you!'
 &HT;    ``I'm all naked and tangled, going `Oh, thank you so much for
dropping by.'''
 &HT;    Actually, Bullock says, she's not that upset by her spotty track
record lately _ ``Hope Floats'' (1998) was her only recent hit.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, the best part of the last couple of years has been
the criticism I've gotten, because it's brought things back to a
more normal level,'' the actress says. ``Now it's nice and quiet. I
can go back to scratch and start building things up again. Everyone
is off my back.
 &HT;    ``Honestly, I found it paralyzing _ the good heat that has been
on me for the last few years has been the most frightening thing in
the world,'' Bullock admits. ``This instant fame is just something
I couldn't understand. It wasn't warranted, and it was for all the
wrong reasons _ it was for something that I had no control over.
 &HT;    ``I mean, who knew `Speed' was going to work? It was a movie
about a bus.''
 &HT;    With her fame came intense scrutiny in an industry which rarely
spares its own, especially if they happen to be female.
 &HT;    ``Hollywood loves to pit women up against each other,'' Bullock
says. ``For instance, I just saw a magazine cartoon with Cameron
Diaz literally sitting on top of a squashed Julia Roberts. The
little blurb said, `Cameron has the edge.'''
 &HT;    She frowns.
 &HT;    ``That's so insulting and degrading,'' she says, fuming. ``Here
are two incredibly powerful, beautiful women who are opening films
where they said women couldn't open films. Let's be happy about
that fact, and not pit them against each other.''
 &HT;    It wasn't that long ago that Bullock was in Diaz's spot as ``the
next Julia Roberts.''
 &HT;    ``And how annoying that must have been for her,'' the actress
says. ``Poor Julia. But you'll notice Julia is always on top, which
is a great testament to her. She broke the mold _ that's why she
deserves to sit where she sits.''
 &HT;    Nowadays, Bullock says, she's less interested in duplicating the
$300 million success of ``Speed'' than in gaining control over her
own career. That's why she produced ``Hope Floats,'' ``Practical
Magic'' (1998) and ``Gun Shy.''
 &HT;    ``As an actor,'' she says, ``sometimes you feel like a throw
pillow they toss in the corner as decoration. I want to be the
architect.''
 &HT;    So is the woman many hail as the nicest person in Hollywood
learning to be a bit less nice?
 &HT;    ``Just because you assert yourself doesn't mean you have to stop
being nice,'' she says. ``You don't have to be a bitch to get your
point across. I've said no this year more than I ever have in my
life.''
 &HT;    Which is why, after she's through promoting ``Gun Shy,'' she'll
be heading back to Austin _ where, yes, her ``A Time to Kill''
(1997) co-star Matthew McConaughey happens to live nearby. But
Bullock denies the persistent rumors that they're romantically
involved.
 &HT;    ``Sorry, we're just friends,'' she says cheerfully. ``No major
agenda there.''
 &HT;    In fact, Bullock is rather proud of not having any major agenda
at all.
 &HT;    ``I want to ground myself in the next year,'' she says. ``When I
drive onto my property and see my lake and my dogs running around,
it just boosts my spirits. I finally have a place I can call home
at the end of the day.
 &HT;    ``I feel like I can finally breathe.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
