<SLUG> BC-SINGER-CHRISTINA-AGUILERA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CHRISTINA AGUILERA WANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Christina Aguilera.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Her song was called ``Genie in a Bottle,'' but Christina
Aguilera seems to have gotten more than three wishes out of it.
 &HT;    Six months after ``Genie,'' the first single from her debut
album, took the 19-year-old pop singer to pop stardom, she's scored
a second No. 1 hit with ``What a Girl Wants'' and watched her
self-titled album bow atop the Billboard charts, selling more than
5 million copies so far.
 &HT;    An alumna of the same ``Mickey Mouse Club'' class that produced
Britney Spears, two members of 'N Sync and actress Keri Russell,
Aguilera will be part of this year's Walt Disney-produced Super
Bowl halftime extravaganza, dueting with Enrique Iglesias.
 &HT;    Oh, and she's also nabbed two Grammy Award nominations,
including Best New Artist.
 &HT;    ``Oh my gosh, it was so unbelievable,'' Aguilera says. ``I was
the first name after they announced the category, and I was dying.
I was shocked _ I wasn't expecting it at all, just because I'd only
had one single out this year, `Genie in a Bottle,' and I didn't
think that's all it took. So I was really excited.''
 &HT;    A few names later came Spears, Aguilera's friend since their
``Mickey Mouse'' days but nonetheless often portrayed as a rival
princess of the teen-pop scene.
 &HT;    ``I know the press and whatnot have always wanted to make this
sort of rivalry between Britney and I,'' Aguilera says, ``I guess
because of certain similarities. But, come on, we are very
different artists. People will see more and more how different we
are, so maybe that will stop this idea that we're competing with
each other.
 &HT;    ``I'm just so proud of her for making it this far,'' the singer
adds. ``I can honestly say that, because we were really close on
the show, too. I've always known her to be a really sweet girl. And
it's funny, because on the show me and Britney were never compared
with each other, even though we were the youngest on the show.''
 &HT;    Aguilera began performing almost before she could walk. Her
mother recalls a 2-year-old Christina lining up her stuffed
animals, setting out a towel as a stage and belting out songs into
a baton that served as her ``icophone.''
 &HT;    Music, in fact, provided her with a refuge, first from the
family's frequent moves _ her father, an Ecuadoran-American, was an
Army sergeant _ and then from her parents' divorce when she was 5.
 &HT;    ``Singing was always my outlet, my form of release,'' explains
Aguilera, who has a stepbrother, stepsister and half-brother from
her mother's second marriage. ``Maybe it made me feel connected to
myself, even though my surroundings kept changing. I think singing
was something I grasped as an outlet from a lot of times in my
childhood that weren't exactly pleasant.
 &HT;    ``It was hard growing up.''
 &HT;    After the divorce, Aguilera's mother took the future singer and
her sister Rachel, now 13, back to Pittsburgh to be near her
family. There she encouraged her older daughter's singing, exposing
her to singers such as B.B. King and Etta James, whose song ``At
Last'' Aguilera covers in concert.
 &HT;    The young singer lost her first ``Star Search'' competition at
age 8, but her performance got her onto ``The Mickey Mouse Club's''
talent list, and a few years later she was on the show.
 &HT;    That didn't make growing up any easier, however.
 &HT;    ``I was always living a different sort of lifestyle than my
peers, which created certain alienation and whatnot at certain
times,'' she recalls. ``It was weird, just because I was in school
one minute, in math class with my peers, and then they would go
home and see me on television.
 &HT;    ``It would create weird situations for me, a lot of no-win
situations.''
 &HT;    Aguilera remembers friends constantly, half-tauntingly asking
her to sing for them.
 &HT;    ``If I'd break down and finally sing for them, they'd be like,
`Oh, she's showing off again,''' she says. ``And then if I wouldn't
do it, it would be like `She's too good to sing for us.'
 &HT;    ``It was hard,'' the singer says. ``It made me introvert into
myself, into my music. It created this drive that I was going to
prove to myself that I was going to make this dream happen. I put
all my energy and focus into my goal.''
 &HT;    Aguilera lived a relatively normal life throughout high school,
but she was also on the radio with ``Reflection'' from the Disney
film ``Mulan'' (1998), and she had a hit duet in Japan, ``All I
Wanna Do,'' with native pop hero Keizo Nakanishi.
 &HT;    Signed to RCA Records, Aguilera found making her first album all
but overwhelming.
 &HT;    ``I was 17 when I was recording, and it was my first time away
from home, in Los Angeles, up against all these big record-company
heads, people who are 20 years my senior, and it was really tough
sometimes to get my opinions or ideas across,'' Aguilera says. ``I
definitely knew what I wanted, but it was a little tough.''
 &HT;    It's the songs other than the hits on ``Christina Aguilera''
that really show what she's capable of. Torchy ballads such as ``I
Turn to You'' and the album-closing ``Obvious'' _ which Aguilera
says is a particular favorite _ reveal a big, mature voice that
draws as much from the classic singers she grew up listening to as
it does from contemporary favorites such as Whitney Houston or
Mariah Carey.
 &HT;    And while ``Genie'' and ``What a Girl Wants'' are the money
songs right now, Aguilera says the ballads ``really allow me to let
go a lot more. On a slow song, you get to get into it more, you
have more time to take your time with it and really stretch your
notes and whatnot. I think that's when an audience gets to see what
I'm about as a vocalist.''
 &HT;    Of course, Aguilera realizes that some of her fans are less
interested in her voice than in her frequently bared midriff _
which remains svelte, despite her declared love of fast food.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I'm on stage, belting my heart out through a song,
and all some guys can do in the front row is say `Take it off!'''
Aguilera says, frowning. ``It's like, why do I work so hard to be
the best vocalist I can be when I've got people that really just
stare at my tummy?
 &HT;    ``So it can be a little bit of a disadvantage,'' she says, ``but
I'm also a performer. I'm an entertainer, and when I'm onstage I do
come across as a bit sexual sometimes in the way that I dance, move
my hips or whatever. It's all part of being a performer and an
entertainer to me, and my sexuality is part of that.''
 &HT;    Despite tabloid rumors to the contrary, Aguilera says she's too
busy to date _ though she admits to regular crushes. It seems
plausible, since she's at work on an all-new, Spanish-language
album, as well as a holiday album for release at Christmas 2000.
She has another tour in the works and, yes, a few more typical
teen-age things as well.
 &HT;    ``Right now I'm a teen,'' she says, ``and besides singing I'm
still the same old girl that loves going to the movies and loves
going to shop, loves to go dancing _ you know what I mean?
 &HT;    ``But my artistry is really important to me, too,'' she adds.
``That's why I want to fight a little bit being categorized with a
lot of premanufactured teen acts.
 &HT;    ``I want to make sure that people take it seriously as something
that's not just a come-and-go thing.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Christina Aguilera, consult her
official Website at www.christinaaguilera.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
