<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4626 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JANE-KRAKOWSKI-IN-ALL     01-24 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JANE-KRAKOWSKI-IN-ALLY-MCBEAL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 `ALLY' CAT: THERE'S MORE TO JANE KRAKOWSKI THAN `McBEAL'S' ELAINE  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jane Krakowski in a scene from ``Ally
McBeal.'') 
 By MICHAEL LOGAN  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even Jane Krakowski finds it hard to believe what's been
happening in her life these days.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has she become one of the most popular attractions on
``Ally McBeal,'' a fan favorite as the snoopy, sex-obsessed
secretary Elaine, but she's recently finished playing Betty Rubble
in ``Viva Rock Vegas,'' the upcoming big-screen prequel to ``The
Flintstones'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough, the Broadway-musical veteran is
heading into the studio to record her first solo album, due out in
May, the same month the film opens. And, best of all, the
30-year-old actress finds herself madly in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always pinching myself,'' Krakowski says. ``I am always
saying, `How the hell did I get here? Whose life am I living?'''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Parsippany, N.J., just a short bus ride from
Manhattan, Krakowski has been a show-biz pro since she was 15, when
she was cast as precocious T.R. Kendall on the daytime soap
``Search For Tomorrow,'' a role that would earn her two Emmy
nominations
</P>
<P>
   She then set her sights on Broadway, appearing in the hit
musicals ``Starlight Express'' (1984) and ``Grand Hotel'' (1989).
The latter, directed by Tommy Tune, won her rave reviews and a Tony
nomination _ but, after the show closed, no more substantial stage
offers were forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Krakowski admits, she panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a dry spell that lasted several years,'' she recalls,
``and, as a result, I sort of lost my confidence. I'm still
reluctant to fully trust any success that comes my way.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not kidding. Though ``Ally McBeal'' was an instant hit,
Krakowski spent her first two years on the Los Angeles-based show
living the life of a visitor from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rented my apartment, my furniture, my car,'' she says. ``I
even rented my television. I had real trouble with the dreaded `C
word' _ commitment. I still do.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with the show still drawing big ratings in its third
season, she can't bring herself to buy a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at least I'm out of my apartment and renting a house,''
she says with a self-deprecating laugh. ``And I finally own a TV. I
bought one for myself when I turned 30 _ I figured I should give
something back to the institution that's been so good to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I own a car now, too,'' she adds, ``but that's because I
did a promotional spot for Mazda and they gave me one. I am sooo
pathetic!''
</P>
<P>
   She's less afraid of the ``C word,'' too. Two summers ago,
Krakowski fell head-over-heels for London-based lyricist Charles
Hart, whose credits include the Andrew Lloyd Webber musicals
``Phantom of the Opera'' (1986) and ``Aspects of Love'' (1989). The
two have been having a transatlantic love affair ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Krakowski says, she'd first met Hart nearly a decade
earlier, backstage at ``Grand Hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came with my `Starlight Express' director, Trevor Nunn,''
Krakowski recalls. ``Trevor was going on and on about my
performance _ `Oh, well done, dahling! Well done!' And there's this
unbelievably gorgeous man standing behind him, who never said
anything to me. That was Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even look him in the eye because he was so
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, much to Krakowski's surprise, Hart left a note
at the stage door, asking her out. The two dated for a few weeks,
then he returned to London.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't see each other again until 1998, when Krakowski and
an old friend, actress Camryn Manheim of ``The Practice,''
vacationed together in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camryn wanted to go to London and I wanted to go to Paris,''
Krakowski recalls, ``so we made a deal that I'd go where she wanted
if she went where I wanted. We hit London first. I called Charles
and invited him to tea and, well, we've been together ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camryn and I never got to Paris!''
</P>
<P>
   The actress admits that a long-distance relationship can be
quite a strain: Because of her tight shooting schedule for ``Ally
McBeal,'' Hart usually flies to Los Angeles to spend time with her.
Occasionally they meet halfway, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss him so much when he's gone,'' she says, ``but it's just
so amazing when we're together that the separations are bearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make it through this commuting period, I think we'll be
able to go the long haul,'' Krakowski adds. ``I adore him. He's
definitely the one.''
</P>
<P>
   If her big-screen debut goes well, that commuting period might
be close to an end. Early buzz says that she steals ``Viva Rock
Vegas'' right out from under the noses of a formidable cast which
includes Mark Addy, the chubby stripper from ``The Full Monty''
(1998), as Fred. Kristen Johnson of ``Third Rock From the Sun''
plays Wilma, with Stephen Baldwin as Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which tells how the Flintstones and the Rubbles first
met and became best friends, also stars Joan Collins and Harvey
Korman as Wilma's parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole experience was so incredible it was surreal,''
Krakowski gushes. ``Harvey is, like, my all-time idol, and Joan
Collins is, like, Joan Collins! We have this dinner-party scene
where we're all together and, between takes, Joan was asking how I
get my eye-liner to do what it does _ and I'm thinking, `Oh, my
God, Joan Collins is asking me for beauty tips? This is sooo
bizarre!'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still this little kid from Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell, who played Betty in the first ``Flintstones''
film, has been very supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she heard I'd been cast,'' Krakowski recalls, ``she sent
a huge bouquet of flowers with a card that said, `From Betty One to
Betty Two, Yabba Dabba Doo!' A week later, she brought me on her
show and gave me pointers.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was available to provide tips on playing her pushy,
calculating alter ego on ``Ally McBeal,'' but Krakowski says she
didn't need much help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little of Elaine in everybody, at least in our
fantasies,'' she says. ``I think we all secretly want to be her.
She doesn't edit herself, she doesn't apologize for who she is or
what she does, and she gets away with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it took a while for ``Ally'' watchers to warm up to
her character.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year our show was on the air, people would come up
to me on the street and groan, `Oh, we have an Elaine in our
office, too,''' Krakowski says. ``And then they would roll their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people come up to me with great pride and say, `I'm the
Elaine in our office!'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Logan is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Ally McBeal,'' consult the Fox
Broadcasting Website at www.fox.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
