<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The closer you look, the better it getsBy Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the holidays came and went and you still don't have
a DVD player, drop in on a friend and check one out. DVD was one of
the two hottest gift items, and it's time to find out why.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other big gift item, the digital camera, DVD takes on a
favorite pastime, movie watching, and adds so many dimensions that
it creates a fresh, new excitement.
</P>
<P>
   It provides video pictures of unmatched sharpness and detail and
a stream of sound that extends the viewing experience, making even
familiar films worth a new look.
</P>
<P>
   It lets you do a lot of little things like stop the movie and
analyze scenes, see extra footage and watch the director discuss
the movie in some instances. It offers many other extras impossible
with cumbersome videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   But what really sells DVD is this: The videos look and sound
gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   I was aware of those features just from reading about them and
sneaking a peek into the sound rooms at my local HiFi Buys, but my
personal, hands-on experience revealed some surprises, too. I
discovered that even regular audio CDs sound better on the DVD
player _ so much better that I pulled my CD player and stored it in
the bedroom, where I may put up a small music system. I now play
DVD and CD on the same machine, such as my Toshiba SD-3109, which
has two separate disc trays. A nice net gain.
</P>
<P>
   Even better news is that if you have a reasonably up-to-date
sound system and a TV in the 30-inch range, you can step up to the
DVD experience at moderate cost.
</P>
<P>
   The players range from about $200 to about $800, with very good
machines in the middle at about $400, the cost of the Toshiba 3109
that I bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higher-priced machines do have noticeably higher quality, in
even better pictures and sound, better mechanical operation, and
storage of discs,'' said Michael Brough, a specialist at a HiFi
Buys store.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the machines such as the Sony DVP-CX850D, which sells
for $799 at HiFi Buys, actually store and organize up to 200 discs,
an entire library at your fingertips, Brough said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony, like some others, will display on the TV screen the
whole library of discs, organized in ways to be located easily and
played at will.
</P>
<P>
   But even on the lower end, where I live, there is a very clear
difference in performance when compared with videotapes played on
the same audio and TV equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The noticeably superior CD playback was a tipoff as to why DVDs
perform so well. The DVD player, with its new electronics, does
more with the information from the disc, and the super supply of
extra information on the latest DVDs provides the amplifier and TV
with a torrent of picture and sound.
</P>
<P>
   While many people try to sell DVD superiority with the
excitement of movies featuring careening trains and fiery
explosions, it turns out that even the subtle sounds of crickets in
the night, the rustle of silk and the fine voice quality also add
pleasure and dimension to ordinary movies.
</P>
<P>
   Also for devoted listeners, the thrill of the audio is in the
way small things are highlighted, contributing to a sense of
presence _ like the swish of the brush against the jazz player's
cymbals, the eloquence of the tiny piccolo against the full voice
of the 100-piece orchestra and even the whir of a fan in the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   The good news on this front is that the choice of DVD movies is
no longer limited, as it was in 1996 when the medium was brand new.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Freeman, Atlanta regional media manager of Best Buy, says
his local outlets have found DVD discs to be among the hottest
items, with floor space constantly expanding for discs and
shrinking for videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to have an inventory of 3,000 titles by the end of
this year,'' he said, ``and even though action movies have been our
best sellers, the appearance of Disney animation titles has
practically moved the focus from the home theater to the family
room.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the DVD player, the best quality of performance
depends on a good amplifier and the proper array of speakers.
</P>
<P>
   With DVD playback in Dolby digital, it is very important to have
a quality center speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center speaker, for most movies and audio CDs, presents
the voices, and without it there is a definite gap or hole in the
sound,'' said Brough of HiFi Buys.
</P>
<P>
   Read the label describing the features on the DVD player. One
desirable feature is the ability of the DVD to produce a Dolby
digital signal, especially if the amplifier is an older model
without its own Dolby decoder.
</P>
<P>
   With Dolby, the sound can come from up to six speakers,
including the center, two main front speakers, two rear speakers
and a powered subwoofer that gives the richness our ears have
become accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   On the TV front, most people prefer the biggest screen they can
afford, often the projection TVs in the 50- to 60-inch range.
</P>
<P>
   Other DVD fans, like Freeman, lean toward the tube TVs, though
smaller at a maximum of 36 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The brightness and clarity of the tube machine more than make up
for the smaller size.
</P>
<P>
   With the push to reduce the inventory of analog TV sets and
replace them with inventories of digital TV sets, sales on
projection TVs now have them available in the $1,500-$2,000 range,
with tube sets at $800.
</P>
<P>
   DVD titles come in various formats, among the most popular being
the letter box or wide-screen format, which to some eyes looks
better on a big screen.
</P>
<P>
   For fans who dote on the technical aspects of video, and
especially DVD, there is plenty of material on the Internet to
slake your appetite.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most helpful is www
</P>
<P>
   .dvddemystified.com, which carries 100 pages of frequently asked
questions and answers about DVD, its technical history and other
details for beginners and veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
