<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stowaway keyboard wins awards, support for innovation
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Out of the thousands of products displayed at the
Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas earlier this month, only a
few win awards from the show sponsor, the Consumer Electronics
Association, as outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Stowaway Portable Keyboard won two: an Innovation award for
cres own right, should satisfy the requirements of anyone who isn't
getting paid to use it.
</P>
<P>
   A 250-page manual takes the edge off the complexity, although it
would be nice if it included a tutorial. There is also the standard
aggravation of any Adobe program, which is to say they were all
originally created for Macintosh and Adobe prints one manual for
both platforms, giving side-by-side instructions for both machines
where there is a difference in a given operation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the photo-editing programs I've seen have provening
means to allow more light to strike a specific portion of the
image, thus darkening it; it's usually done by putting the hands
together in such a way that light falls only on the desired area.
Dodging is just the opposite, done by wiggling a piece of cardboard
on a stiff wire over the area to be lightened.
</P>
<P>
   Photoshop's dodging and burning tools work in an intelligent
manner. If you hold the dodging tool over an area of shade, the
entire area _ not just the part of it directly under the tool _ is
lightened, gradually revealing the detail you wanted to bring out.
The burning tool will take a light shadow and bring it all the way
to black if you desire. If you use the tools judiciously, the
results appear perfectly natural.
</P>
<P>
   Cropping is another simple matter here. It can be done through a
dialog box, but the easy way is with the cropping tool. Simply
outline the area you want to keep, hit return and you've got it.
While this is the way all programs ought to work, it frequently
doesn't seem to happen that way.
</P>
<P>
   Every program of this sort has some filters to make a picture
look more like a painting, or like anything but a picture.
Photoshop LE, however, has dozens of them, nearly all of them
infinitely adjustable in their effect. You can even change the
source of light in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Photoshop Limited retails for $95. It's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
