<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors watching Willie B.
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's favorite gorilla, Willie B., is battling
pneumonia. The great ape took sick several weeks ago, when many of
the zoo's 23 gorillas also caught colds or the flu. The others got
better, but the 41-year-old Willie, who is elderly for a gorilla,
got worse and developed pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Willie is being kept indoors where he's mostly resting. Gail
Eaton, Zoo Atlanta's marketing director, says the keepers give him
peanut M&AMP;M's as a reward when he takes his medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton explains that ``gorillas have very similar bodies to
humans. They are susceptible to many of same upper respiratory
infections, like colds and flu, that affect people.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry about making your pets sick. Eaton says their
bodies aren't enough like ours to share germs.
</P>
<P>
   2 KIDS' BOOKS HONORED
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud, Not Buddy'' and ``Joseph Had a Little Overcoat'' have won
the most prestigious awards in children's literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bud,'' by Christopher Paul Curtis, won the John Newbery Medal
for outstanding writing. ``Joseph,'' by Simms Taback, won the
Caldecott Medal for outstanding illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bud,'' published by Delacorte Press, 10-year-old Bud
Caldwell runs away from a foster home and begins a journey in
search of his father. His only clues are old flyers left by his
dead mother that point to a legendary jazz bandleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph,'' published by Viking, is based on a Yiddish folktale
of a resourceful tailor who transforms his worn-out overcoat into
smaller and smaller garments. The book is illustrated in
watercolor, gouache, pencil, ink and collage.
</P>
<P>
   Check them out for yourself and see what you think!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
