<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I need your help in finding the date for the
next Bud Light Bullnanza in Las Vegas. I need this information as I
am trying to plan my wedding. We also need to get information on
price and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   _Jeanie C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Oct. 26-29 at Thomas &AMP; Mack Arena. The Bud Light Cup Series
works like NASCAR with bull riders accumulating points in yearlong
competitions in 29 cities. Bullnanza is held four times during the
year. The season-culminating event will be held in Las Vegas.
Participants are the top 45 bull riders in the world. Tickets are
sold by Professional Bull Riders Inc., at (719) 471-3008 as well as
by tickets.com at (888) 464-2468. Ticket prices begin at $36.50
</P>
<P>
   Q: I keep seeing newspaper articles about parents losing their
tax deduction because their babies were born after the New Year. I
heard there is a stipulation in the tax code that allows babies
born within the first few days of the new year to claim them on the
previous year's taxes and that there is also a new stipulation this
year for families of multiples to get an additional $1,000 tax
credit. _N. Landing
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, but a tax credit for a qualified child as a dependent
can only be taken in the year in which the child was born or alive.
There is no grace period, says Internal Revenue Service's Kenneth
Vargas. The 1998 tax credit for a qualified child was $400; for
1999, $500. So yes, if you have twins, the total deduction for 1999
is $1,000. But no, not an extra $1,000. Nice try. To ask other
tax-related questions ('tis the season), call the IRS at (800)
829-1040.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the universe, by definition, consists of everything that
exists, and the universe is expanding, what is the universe
expanding into? Does this have something to do with ``curved
space''?
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael N.
</P>
<P>
   A: Common-sense question without a common answer. Those who
study the universe's expansion say this question is not ``part of
our science right now.'' (Science-speak for ``We really don't
know.'')
</P>
<P>
   But you are correct: The answer has something to do with
``curved space,'' the fusion of space and time. Craig Wheeler,
University of Texas astronomy professor (and great guy), is writing
an entire book on the subject. Official title? ``Cosmic
Catastrophes: Supernovae, Gamma-ray Bursts and Adventures in
Hyperspace.'' Wheeler notes, ``Einstein's equations for curved
space and gravity allow astronomers to describe the expansion of
the universe without needing to refer to what it is expanding
into.'' (Convenient.) The medium into which expansion occurs would
have to have a higher dimension (beyond front to back, side to
side, and up and down). Scientists agree they have no perception or
need right now for such a dimension, Wheeler adds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you heard if the TV station that had the all-day New
Year's Eve celebrations from around the world is going to be
selling a video of all the different places? That would be great to
have as a keepsake of the New Year 2000. _ M. Nielson
</P>
<P>
   A: Loved those fireworks from Paris to Miami? Call (800)
CALL-ABC to purchase a two-hour tape of New Year's Eve coverage
(obviously condensed). The price? $14.95, plus shipping and
handling. Remember, videotape only lasts for a decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any ideas on how to easily peel hard-boiled eggs
(or how to boil them to make them easy to peel)?
</P>
<P>
   _ Fran Werner
</P>
<P>
   A: Using fresh eggs? The American Egg Board warns fresh eggs may
be difficult to peel. Eggs stored for a week to 10 days before
cooking usually peel more easily. The board's recommended cooking
method? Place eggs in a single layer in a saucepan. Add enough tap
water to come at least 1 inch above eggs. Cover and quickly bring
just to boiling. Turn off heat. Let stand, covered, about 15
minutes for large eggs (add time, up or down, by about three
minutes for larger or smaller eggs). Immediately run cold water
over eggs or place in ice water until completely cooled. To remove
shell, crackle it by tapping gently all over. Roll egg between
hands to loosen shell, then peel, starting at large end. Hold egg
under running cold water or dip in bowl of water to help ease off
shell. (By the way, a hen requires 24 to 26 hours to produce an
egg. Thirty minutes later, she starts all over again.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: There is a roadrunner that patrols our neighborhood. Is there
anything we can put out to help him get through the lean winter
months?
</P>
<P>
   _Dave and Ladine Conley
</P>
<P>
   A: Happen to have a plate of spiders, lizards and snakes? That's
what gets a roadrunner salivating, according to ornithologist Cliff
Shackelford at Texas Parks and Wildlife. Oh yes, the creepy
crawlers need to be alive. Roadrunners prefer to kill and eat their
own dinners. Natural predators? Roaming cats and cars (and Wile E.
Coyote).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I bought a house where the former owner went wild with
contact paper. All the cupboards are lined with the stuff. It's
fairly easy to peel off, but what about the sticky residue? I've
tried rubber cement thinner (my favorite solvent), but it's not
working very well. I need to unpack my dishes! _Martha Grenon
</P>
<P>
   A: Try Goof Off, available at hardware stores. Other popular
remedies include wallpaper remover, mineral oil, fabric presoak
(let rest for a bit) or a hair dryer to soften the adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need the answer to a trivia question for students at the
University of Oregon. How many high-tech businesses are there in
Austin? _Anne B.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The area's current high-tech job base is 125,000 workers in
2,000 companies, or about 20 percent of all Austin-area jobs,''
says Angelos Angelou of Angelou Economic Advisors Inc. By the way,
Oregonians are welcome to vie for some of the expected 24,600 new
tech jobs in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you once more tell us what to do with those Christmas
poinsettias so they will bloom again? I know you're supposed to put
them in a dark place, but what else? _M. Grenon
</P>
<P>
   A: Poinsettias are tropicals that do not like temperatures below
65 degrees, and must be well-drained. Prune your poinsettias,
leaving a few leaves and branches. Let the plants enjoy full sun
and heat. In mid- to late August, pinch the poinsettias back to
make them fuller, and in September, place them in the shade (not in
a closet). In October, give the plants as much sunlight as
possible. Look for blooms to begin forming at Thanksgiving, with
full blooms by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Susan Lucci the daughter of Phyllis Diller? We received
some little-known facts from a friend, and that blew my wife away.
_Jack Geis
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe the two are sisters in plastic surgery, but they're
definitely not mother and daughter, according to Robin Chandler of
ABC publicity. Lucci's parents are alive and well and living in
Florida. Q: Could you please tell me what to use to cover my velvet
clothes that I purchased this winter? I cover my leather jackets
with old cotton dresses.
</P>
<P>
   _S. St. Martin
</P>
<P>
   A: Good method. Protecting beaded or crushable fabrics with a
cotton item (I use old T-shirts) works well. The natural fiber
allows the clothing to breathe and provides a cushion while hanging
in the closet. Do not forget to moth-proof, also. Should the velvet
develop deep wrinkles, Karen Martin of Silk Road suggests tossing
the clothing in the dryer (alone and on a low setting) for a few
minutes or gently steaming in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar:
</P>
<P>
   _ Good news for readers interested in the limited edition of
``Porfirio Salinas'' by Ruth Hunnicutt Goddard. A few books
(regular binding for $100 or leather for $150) as well as the video
``A Man Born to Paint'' ($55) are available from Goddard's
daughter, Jeanne Joan Taylor. Call Taylor at (281) 376-7199.
</P>
<P>
   _ Want your Valentine's card to stand out? Consider sending a
love note with a special cancellation. Loveland, Colo., post office
volunteers hand-stamp valentines with a sweet postmark and romantic
rune: ``Cupid aims his fiery dart, With masterful ambition, Sending
Loveland valentines, In annual tradition.'' To have your honey's
letter postmarked, address and stamp it, enclose in a larger
envelope, and mail to: Postmaster, attn.: Valentines, Loveland,
Colo. 80538-9998. Going Texan this year? Try the cancellation from
Valentine. Send valentines (stamped and addressed) to: Postmaster,
Valentine, Texas, 79854-9998. Both accept more than one 'tine for
you heartthrobs _ even a box of wedding invitations. Deadline for
delivery by the big 14 is Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail: jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
