u l BC-NETWATCH25-COX     01-24 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A smart way to target women
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you believe what you see on television, even the
most technophobic women have made peace with the Internet thanks to
a site called iVillage.com.
</P>
<P>
   A slew of TV commercials for the woman-oriented Web site feature
ordinary women telling heartwarming tales of how, thanks to
iVillage.com, they got advice about nutrition or learned about
computers or what to expect when they were expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, no Web site is going to solve all your work, family,
money and relationship problems, but the site's mix of articles,
community topics and shopping tips really is a good way for women
to get started on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The woman-only Web site is one of a growing handful that
honestly pay attention to what their readers are doing and
thinking, as rival Web site Oxygen put it in its ``smart talk for
smart women.'' Borrowing a page from Web magazine Salon, this new
generation of women's Web sites knows the women and teen-age girls
who visit their sites have IQs above room temperature. They also
know how to involve their readers, and that's an exciting and
welcome change from many content sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   IVillage.com is a mix of the conventional and the offbeat, with
a something-for-everyone approach that will probably bring a
variety of women to the site, just as the ads say.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's predictable, other times surprising. Tuesday
night's online chat with Hillary Rodham Clinton was a definite
coup, but iVillage really shines when it offers readers a chance to
comment on what they've read or voice their own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   The company began life on America Online, a place where talking
back and voicing opinions has always been an integral part of the
user experience. Clicking on iVillage's compilation of the 100
greatest books, the reader has no idea whether to expect a litany
of gothic novels or cookbooks. Happily, it's neither.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list is ``Gone With the Wind,'' followed by ``To
Kill a Mockingbird,'' ``A Prayer for Owen Meany'' and ``Atlas
Shrugged.'' The book list is cleverly linked to Amazon.com and
peppered with member comments about the books and how a novel has
influenced a particular reader.
</P>
<P>
   To get the most out of iVillage, go beyond the start page with
its run-of-the-mill tips on romance, kids and money and check out
the book club, careers and election 2000. For women who want to
sample what the Web has to offer without straying too far away from
the community and structure of AOL, this is a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   While iVillage has been around for a while, Oxygen
(www.oxygen.com) is a fairly new site from a powerful collection of
women executives, the most notable being Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen, which will also be a cable TV channel, combines the
traditional modes of online interactivity, such as chat and message
boards, with multimedia applications, such as video storytelling.
When users click on a story, a second browser window pops up and
the story is told through streaming video, a cutting-edge technique
not found on many Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Oxygen's users will probably be frustrated with the time
it takes for these ``video articles'' to load, but most of the
stories are worth the wait. It is a sign of the eventual merger of
TV and Internet technology that users are likely to see in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   If iVillage suffers a little from being too mainstream aiming
squarely at Mrs. America _ Oxygen scores points for targeting women
of all ages and offering a more offbeat selection of subjects.
Mothers who think and their daughters will appreciate Oxygen's mix
of articles and attitude. Users aren't just asked to post comments
but to submit whole stories on a variety of subjects. For example,
it incorporated the ``Girls On'' Web site into its ``family'' of
sites. ``Girls On'' lets teen-agers offer their own opinions on
film, movies, TV, books and a variety of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen's reader contributions and iVillage's member comments
feel similar to the way women talk to each other face-to-face. Some
comments are thoughtful and witty, others are just silly, but their
authors all use the interactive medium of the Web to express their
ideas for an audience of peers.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these sites have a long way to go before they build the
reputations earned by sites like Salon and Slate, but those two
publications could take a lesson from the myriad opportunities
Oxygen and iVillage offer for reader input. They both make good use
of content and community that's missing in a lot of online
publications, especially those aimed at women. Online women's
magazines are a different kind of medium designed for a different
kind of woman _ one who likes to talk and not be talked down to.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
