<HEADER>
A4657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TECH-KIDGEAR25-COX     01-24 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-KIDGEAR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Your own animation studio
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The purpose of Disney's Magic Artist Studio
($29.99 for Mac and PC; disney.go.com/disneyinteractive/) is
anything but black and white. Is it an animation tutor? A drawing
and painting program? Usually when a product tries to cover too
many bases it ends up lacking in all of them. Not so here. While
the anim-
</P>
<P>
   ation tutorials are basic and the creation of cartoon scenes is
limited to placing looped character movements and canned
soundtracks into pre-drawn scenes, kids seem to love it. And the
painting, drawing and text features are powerful for a program
aimed at children (our test kid was well on his way to producing
his own newspaper featuring Mickey and the gang). It's easy enough
to assemble and save slide shows of favorite creations to show off
to family and friends. Be warned, though ... you could be starring
in one of these epics. Magic Artist Studio lets young Rembrandts
import and doctor photos, making you look potentially, well, Goofy.
</P>
<P>
   STEP INTO THE RING
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some WWF Wrestlemania action? Look no further than
Toymax's WWF Slamcam ($70; www.toymax.com). The Slamcam is a
digital camera for the PC that allowsusers to put themselves in the
middle of the action. The camera is simple. Once you aim and shoot,
you can superimpose yourself as a fan in the crowd, on the body of
a referee or (ouch!) the receiving end of a Steve Austin headlock.
The camera also comes with its own software, which allows you to do
fun, if not strange, photo effects like adding hair or replacing
limbs with chicken legs and fish flippers. The software also
contains templates for fan ID cards, posters and calendars. While
the Slamcam is a digital camera, it's only to be used with the
Slamcam software. This makes photographing your mom's birthday
party rather difficult, unless, that is, you wanted a picture of
her pinned to the mat by the British Bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TECH-MEDIA25-COX     01-24 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net's riches not limited to giants
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not just the giants such as America Online that
are profiting from the Internet. Lots of small business also have
learned how to harness the Net to their advantage. Read about 12
regular people who struck it rich on the Internet in the February
issue of Yahoo Internet Life. One of those profiled is Atlanta's
own Jeff Johnson, along with Michael Waters. They hit it big with
their e-commerce site called Underneath.com. It sells underwear.
</P>
<P>
   In its February issue, DigitalSouth picks what it says will be
the 50 hottest technology companies in the South in the coming
year. Among the picks are Atlanta's Derivion, which makes Internet
billing software. Other local picks include eTour, Insupply.com.
Intelligent/Digital, Novient and RealEstate.com.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   MacSoft has announced it plans to ship a Mac version of ``Unreal
Tournament'' this month. It's a first-person action game.
``Unreal'' was first developed for the PC by Epic Games. This
latest version is a sequel to the original. ``Unreal Tournament''
sells for around $50.
</P>
<P>
   Also new for the Mac is ``Civilization: Call to Power.'' This
game also is a sequel to a powerful and popular original. Indeed,
the first ``Civilization'' is among the most popular games
developed. ``Call to Power'' features more technologies, buildings
and wonders. It also expands the playing area to the ocean floor
and outer space. Graphics and game play are improved, too. ``Call
to Power'' retails for about $50.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   So much news, so little time. If you're looking for a
sophisticated aggregator of news from across the Web, check out
Excite Newstracker.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Internet Life gave this site its highest rating as
metasearcher of news and publications. It searches nonstop and is
easy to customize, says the magazine. You'll find Excite
Newstracker at nt.excite.com.
</P>
