<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, Jan. 25,
2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTORS-AWARDS _ Nominees for the Directors Guild Awards are
announced Monday. These are the strongest indicators of Oscar
frontrunners; the DGA winner almost always wins the Oscar, and his
movie often wins best picture. Possible candidate for Living cover.
(Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN _ Observations on the television industry from
a leading commentator. This week: Midseason shows. (Holloway,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-SLEEP _ Sleeping as soundly as a baby is not what it used
to be. Pediatricans and researchers are finding that problems
facing children, ranging from hyperactivity to bad grades at
school, can sometimes be traced to sleeping disorders. And
sometimes the solution can be as easy as removing tonsils that my
be impeding air flow and leading to snoring and interrupted sleep,
say doctors at Children's Healthcare of Atlanta that's just
expanded its sleep lab clinics. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SLEEP-FIRSTPERSON _ A night at the sleep lab, and Justin
Farmer's experience. (Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   SLEEP-TERMS _ Description of sleep disorders that typically
affect kids, from apnea to sleep walking to night terrors.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WEB _ Internet site on macular degeneration; five great
fitness videos. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 5.
</P>
<P>
   FLU-ANTIBIOTICS _ The cold and flu season brings an increased
use of antibiotics just as surely as December brings heavier
jackets. The difference is, the heavier jackets actually help.
``Antibiotics only work on bacteria. The flu and colds are
viruses,'' says Kim Massie, regional pharmacy manager for
UnitedHealthcare. That's not to say antibiotics are useless for
winter miseries. But they're widely overused, research shows.
(Dayton Daily News). 26. WITH ILLUSTRATION and PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLU-DRUGS _ This is the first flu season when Americans have
access to drugs that treat most forms of influenza without many
side effects. So naturally the Food and Drug Administration already
has found it prudent to issue a warning on the drugs' misuse.
(Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FLU-TIPS _ Despite recent advances in drugs for influenza,
treatment of colds and the flu is essentially a matter of
suppressing symptoms. Medical doctors and pharmacists recommend
using over-the-counter medications that target a person's specific
cough, congestion, aches and pains, runny nose or fever.
Naturopathic and herbal practitioners approach colds and flu from
another direction, accelerating the immune system response that
causes the unpleasant symptoms. Their therapies tend to be gentler,
although herbal medicines also can have unwanted side effects.
(Dayton Daily News). 13.
</P>
