<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN25-C     01-24 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Second season' brings a crop of new contenders
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A television executive once compared scheduling
to playing checkers in a speeding motorboat. You line up all the
pieces only to have them fly off the board or slide onto other
squares.
</P>
<P>
   With the holidays behind us and the February sweeps around the
corner, we're heading into that TV time known as midseason or
``second'' season. Network honchos have to do something to fill the
holes left by all the fall failures, so the hype-and-optimism
factory is burping and churning once again.
</P>
<P>
   Two midseason biggies already have arrived _ and both have been
tentatively embraced by viewers. In the early going, CBS's ``City
of Angels,'' a Steven Bochco hospital drama with a mostly
African-American cast, and Fox's outrageous family sitcom,
``Malcolm in the Middle,'' are cruising.
</P>
<P>
   Midseason has been around since the early '70s, when the
networks stopped ordering 35 episodes (it's now down to 22) and
failures became more rampant. As long as there are hours to fill,
replacement series will abound. It used to be considered the kiss
of death to be relegated to midseason and miss out on all the fall
promotion, but not anymore. Some observers _ especially producers _
believe midseason series have an advantage because the competition
is less intense. Bochco, who's never shy about complaining, didn't
object to his January premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that midseason is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a crock,'' counters Preston Beckman, NBC's vice
president for program scheduling. ``Before I did scheduling I
worked in research, and at one point I looked at the probability of
success with midseason vs. fall. To the shock of most people, I
found that the chances of success are greater in fall than
midseason. The bottom line is a good show in a good time period
that's marketed well will succeed regardless of when it's
introduced.''
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to Beckman, his study didn't examine the
types of shows that succeed in midseason. Shows that are unusual
and may need a bit more time for viewers to figure them out seem to
have a better shot in the January-March season. ``The Wonder
Years,'' with its unusual narration from the grown-up kid hero,
debuted in January, and the totally bizarre ``Twin Peaks'' arrived
in April.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman disagrees, but it's possible that NBC's midseason drama
entry last year, the soft-focus family show ``Providence,'' might
not have caught on in the fall crush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be situations where you hold back the premiere of
a show because you look at your schedule and can't find a time
period where you think it can succeed,'' Beckman concedes, noting
that ``Freaks and Geeks'' might have done better if it had waited
for its current Monday time slot rather than debut in the fall on
Saturdays. ``But this business is really more random and chaotic
than we all want to think. Shows will pop up at all times of the
year, and some work. You just don't know. We're great
after-the-fact experts.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of the proposed newcomers succeeds, perhaps it will be a
scheduling fluke. But maybe not. In January, February and March,
viewers aren't alternately preoccupied with back-to-school madness
and holiday preparations. Although Central Texas seems to be
afflicted with perpetual summer, many parts of the country are
imprisoned by bitter cold _ thus encouraging folks to sample new
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the upcoming programs are good, and many haven't even
been sent out for preview. Networks say that's because they don't
have airdates yet, but it may also be because executives don't want
the bad ones reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick look at a few.
</P>
<P>
   ABC
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' _ A psychiatric hospital drama produced by former
``Chicago Hope'' star Peter Berg. A total unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clerks'' _ A cartoon comedy (based on Kevin Smith's '94 indie
film) about four lazy friends who become comic book heroes in their
own minds. Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   CBS
</P>
<P>
   ``Grapevine'' _ Based on a '92 summer series (which the network
feels was ahead of its time), a Miami-based sitcom about four
people who share their self-absorbed thoughts with the audience.
Too whiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' _ A mob drama based on real-life undercover agent
Joe Pistone, starring Jason Gedrick and Titus Welliver, that was
pulled off the fall schedule because of concern over violence (now
supposedly toned down). The original was good.
</P>
<P>
   NBC
</P>
<P>
   ``The Others'' _ Do you see dead people? The folks in this
sci-fi drama do. The pilot, coming Feb. 5, was uneven but had a
couple of good scares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy'' _ A really stupid animated comedy based on the unhappy
relationship between David Spade (creator and voice actor) and his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, the Devil and Bob'' _ Animated series with voice-overs by
French Stewart (Bob), James Garner (a scruffy-looking God) and Alan
Cumming (the Devil) about a Detroit car worker who must prove why
mankind should be saved. Mildly offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battery Park'' _ Described as a ``Barney Miller'' type show,
this comedy starring Elizabeth Perkins as a cop captain comes from
Gary David Goldberg (``Family Ties,'' ``Spin City''). Unknown.
</P>
<P>
   FOX
</P>
<P>
   ``The Opposite Sex'' _ Drama about three teen boys in all-girl
prep school. How original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titus'' _ Sitcom built around little-known stand-up
Christopher Titus about (what else?) a dysfunctional family. Do we
need more of these? No.
</P>
<P>
   WB
</P>
<P>
   ``DC'' _ Good drama from Dick Wolf about twenty-something
roommates working in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brutally Normal'' _ Debuting Sunday (Jan. 24) at 8, a comedy
about (yet again) four high school chums struggling through
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   UPN
</P>
<P>
   ``The Beat'' _ Disappointing drama from Barry Levinson and Tom
Fontana about young undercover cops in NY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
