<HEADER>
A4667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TECH-GADGETS25-COX     01-24 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GADGETS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stowaway keyboard wins awards, support for innovation
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Out of the thousands of products displayed at the
Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas earlier this month, only a
few win awards from the show sponsor, the Consumer Electronics
Association, as outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The Stowaway Portable Keyboard won two: an Innovation award for
creative design and Best of Show honors in the computer hardware
category.
</P>
<P>
   The Stowaway is a collapsible keyboard for users of handheld
organizers such as the Palm Pilot series, the Handspring Visor
series and others.
</P>
<P>
   When stored, the Stowaway folds to about the size of a pocket
organizer, 3.6 inches by 5.1 inches and only 0.8 of an inch thick.
It weighs 7.9 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   But it folds out accordion-style to become a full-size QWERTY
keyboard with extra keys to call up functions such as calendars,
address books, memos and to-do lists. When attached to the pocket
organizer, the Stowaway reduces the need for the stylus handheld
organizer users normally use to choose options on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stowaway is set up, it has a plug into which the
handheld organizer is set. No connecting wires are required. The
keyboard lies flat and the organizer stands up like the screen of a
laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The keys travel the same distance as a normal computer when
pressed, so the Stowaway has the feel and response of standard
office keyboards. It lies flat on a desk, so no wrist supports are
required.
</P>
<P>
   It's made of durable glass-filled polycarbonate and aluminum and
requires no batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The Stowaway was developed by Think Outside Inc., a startup
company based in Solana Beach, Calif. Both Palm Computing Inc. and
Handspring Inc. have been working with Think Outside to develop
Stowaway versions for their products.
</P>
<P>
   For additional information on the Stowaway, visit the Web site
at www.thinkoutside.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
