<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-EXECUTION (San Antonio) _ Leta Ann Jones Wilkerson was
killed nine years ago by 17-year-old Glen McGinnis during a
robbery. Because of his age at the time of the murder, McGinnis'
scheduled execution Tuesday touched off a wave of international
protests last week, including a direct appeal from Pope John Paul
II to Gov. George W. Bush. By LISA SANBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COPS-TRIAL-NEIGHBORS (Bronx, N.Y.) _ Some residents of the Bronx
neighborhood in which Amadou Diallo died in a hail of police
bullets say the shooting would not have happened if local beat
police _ rather than the four members of the city's elite Street
Crime Unit _ had been the ones who encountered the 22-year-old man
that night. By MELISSA GRACE.
</P>
<P>
   COPS-TRIAL-CAMERA (Albany,N.Y.) _ Cameras, or at least one
camera, might be allowed into the upcoming Diallo case after all.
With courtroom seating at a premium in the Albany County Courthouse
and cameras barred from chronicling trials in New York, the state
is seriously considering a closed-circuit transmission of the
proceedings, at least to another courtroom, so more people can
watch. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIDIAN-THEORY (San Antonio) _ A colorful New Orleans
electronics expert, private eye and business promoter _ like a
mischievous twin of Forrest Gump _ is back on the fringes of
history, this time in connection with controversy over the 1993
federal siege OF THE Branch Davidian compound near Waco, Texas.
Gordon Novel, 61, is the originator of allegations that federal
agents fired upon David Koresh's followers as the compound was
bursting into flames. By DICK J. REAVIS.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMMUTER-MARRIAGES (Albany, N.Y.) _ The trials and tribulations
of commuter marriages are being revisited and re-examined these
days, especially in light of the arrangement of Bill and Hillary
Rodham Clinton and open speculation on the state of the first
couple's relationship. The Clintons' commuter marriage is the talk
of the therapist community, and the tongue-wagging is not positive,
according to Maureen Sullivan, a clinical social worker with a
private therapy practice. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-TEA (Albany, N.Y.) _ Read the tea leaves and the message
is clear _ green is best. Green tea's long history is steeped in
its medicinal powers and studies continue to uncover more of its
health benefits. Green tea leaves are the least processed of all
the teas, preserving the natural active substances of the leaf. By
LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HKO-VERMONT (Burlington, VT.) _ Winter suddenly got colder and
darker up here. When the administration at the University of
Vermont pulled the plug on the men's hockey team Jan. 14, a light
went out for thousands across the state. By BUZZ GRAY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.,
wants to make sure that women who are victimized once won't be
victimized twice, or three times. She is drafting a bill to protect
immigrants who testify in criminal exploitation cases from being
deported. In a world of sound bites and talking points, how many
politicians actually do something _ with absolutely no self-serving
rhetoric? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Quantities of studies inform
us that it's getting harder to get around town, almost anywhere in
America. Even areas merely holding their own in population are
nevertheless finding their roads and highways more congested as
more autos take to the road. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
