<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEDARS-STAR-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUDOS FOR KUDOH  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Youki Kudoh is available FREE OF CHARGE
to purchasers of this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY
by e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Youki Kudoh isn't exaggerating when she says she's the Madonna
of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Discovered on the streets of Tokyo at age 12, Kudoh immediately
threw herself into a full-time career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at 12, I knew I wanted to be financially independent,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her first film was the Japanese cult hit ``The Crazy Family,''
in which she played a crazed pop star. That performance quickly led
to a recording contract and real-life pop stardom.
</P>
<P>
   By age 22, Kudoh had released 11 major albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, I think it's 11,'' says Kudoh, now 27. ``I've lost
count.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, she abandoned acting entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that actors didn't sing, and singers didn't act,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   But parts in Jim Jarmusch's ``Mystery Train,'' Kayo Hatta's
``Picture Bride'' and an Australian black comedy called ``Heaven's
Burning'' lured her back to the movies _ and brought her to the
attention of American casting agents.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she snagged Hollywood's ultimate part for an Asian
female: Hatsue in the hot new film ``Snow Falling on Cedars,''
directed by Scott Hicks (``Shine'') and costarring Ethan Hawke.
</P>
<P>
   Kudoh plays the lost love Hawke is still pining for when
Japanese-American relations turn sour in Puget Sound, Wash., during
World War II. (The film is adapted from David Guterson's
best-selling 1994 novel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected I would get cast in an American studio
film,'' Kudoh says. ``I had just gotten married, and I didn't want
to work in a foreign country. But after I read the book on a
camping trip, I decided I must be in the film. I sent a video
audition, even though I knew it was a long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   After auditioning for Hicks, Kudoh read with would-be co-star
Ethan Hawke, who told her not to be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was very, very, very nervous,'' she says, laughing.
``When we made the film, I discovered he is a total gentleman, very
quiet. And he really loves Uma! He's always expecting her call.''
</P>
<P>
   Kudoh may release a record in the U.S. next year, but she's not
sure about her next acting move. She thinks she might have been
spoiled by ``Snow Falling on Cedars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very poetic film,'' she says. ``I haven't read a script
in two years as good. So I'll wait for another part that talks to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
