<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-ART-KRUGER-FEATURE-LA     01-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-KRUGER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE IN-YOUR-FACE ART OF BARBARA KRUGER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
 
 
 
 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you wend your way through the emotional gantlet that is the
Museum of Contemporary Art's ``Barbara Kruger'' exhibition, you
enter a long, narrow room where human rage is literally bouncing
off the walls At the far end, six projected talking heads spew
wounded accusations and nasty invective at unsuspecting onlookers.
The verbal onslaught stops you dead in your tracks. The dim
lighting underscores your sense of psychological dislocation.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few seconds, the room seems to be closing in, and the
epigrams splashed across its interior _ some angrily menacing,
others coolly mocking _ make you feel as if you'd accidentally
strayed onto a shooting range with a bull's eye pinned to your
back.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's words, not .38-caliber rounds, that constitute
the fusillades in a Barbara Kruger show.
</P>
<P>
   Funny words. Provocatively ugly words. Discordantly truthful
words that usually emanate from an ambiguous speaker (``We'') and
explode outward before lodging themselves in an amorphous ``You.''
</P>
<P>
   Words that seem to have been lifted, oozing anxiety and
resentment, from a festering collective unconscious. Words that
make you question. Words that make you want to run for your life.
</P>
<P>
   What sort of mind would devise this assaultive audio-visual
funhouse? Who is this woman whose barbed maxims (``I shop therefore
I am,'' ``Your body is a battleground'') have been smeared across
T-shirts and tote bags as if they were toothpaste ads?
</P>
<P>
   And does she truly believe that if we see our fears and biases
hauled kicking and screaming to the surface like this, we may
someday repudiate them and learn to treat each other decently?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she truly does.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is something interesting in the Golden Rule, in
terms of `Do unto others as you would have others do unto you,'''
Kruger says in her warm, forthright manner. ``That's an old
chestnut, but it really works.''
</P>
<P>
   That might sound like a pretty plain-vanilla message coming from
an L.A.-based artist considered a paragon of pop-culture
sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind, however, that Kruger's vision, for all its
subtlety, is in some ways a monochromatic one. What's black and
white and read all over? Why, just about any of the 70 works in
``Barbara Kruger,'' which runs through Feb. 13 at the MOCA's Geffen
Contemporary space on the edge of Little Tokyo in downtown Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Socking viewers right between the eyes, these images and objects
may seem strangely familiar: A woman holding a magnifying glass,
bracketed by the caption, ``It's a Small World'' and the
smile-inducing tagline, ``but not if you have to clean it.''
</P>
<P>
   A picture of a goofy, bug-eyed hand puppet with the doubtful
injunction, ``Buy me _ I'll change your life.''
</P>
<P>
   A grainy photo of a panicked bridegroom surrounded by his
laughing friends, spatially subdivided by an inscription that reads
like a fortune cookie with an attitude: ``You construct intricate
rituals which allow you to touch the skin of other men.''
</P>
<P>
   Most succinctly, a billboard hovering in downtown Melbourne,
Australia, with this all-purpose aphorism: ``Don't be a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of Kruger's quarter-century career, these and
other distinctive fusions of image and text etched in a tilted
Futura Bold typeface have become almost as recognizable in
contemporary art circles as a Fortune 500 logo. They've appeared on
billboards and in bus shelters, on gallery walls and coffee mugs.
</P>
<P>
   A former commercial graphic designer, art director and picture
editor for Mademoiselle and House and Garden magazines, Kruger, 55,
has eagerly co-opted the tools of consumer culture to coin her
trademark visual epigrams. She takes the inaudible sign language
previously used to sell Edsels and refrigerators, slices it into
visual sound bites and weaves it together with images to form her
neo-constructivist collages.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 years, Kruger has produced a number of
large-scale installations, inflating her words and pictures to the
scale of architectural environments that take up entire walls or
rooms. MOCA's exhibition also includes her early photo collages and
another series focusing on images of public figures such as Marilyn
Monroe and Malcolm X.
</P>
<P>
   Having come of age artistically during the first wave of
feminism in the 1970s, Kruger has devoted much of her career to
exploring Madison Avenue and Hollywood's depictions of sexuality
and identity, the cliches and archetypes that are beamed daily into
our brains.
</P>
<P>
   While her art is designed to get in your face and upside your
head, once you step back and take a deep breath you realize that
Kruger wants to engage her audience rather than simply confront it.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of her work implicitly interrogates the powers
that be and the moral status quo, Kruger rejects ``political'' as a
description of her art. Her targets, it appears, aren't politicians
or institutions per se, but bigoted stereotyping, self-righteous
moralizing and serial cruelty in any form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really almost never use the term political,'' she says. ``I
do make art about power, for sure. But whenever people say
`political' I usually ask, `What do you mean by that?' Because it
tends to narrow the discourse. And I think that all ways of using
or changing notions of power can happen in a million ways everyday.
I think that we can change those, quote, politics, in our everyday
lives, just by how we conduct ourselves with other human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, despite her accessibility and popularity, Kruger hasn't
always been welcomed by major U.S. museums. MOCA's show, which
covers her career from 1978 to the present, is her first-ever major
solo exhibition in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This museum (MOCA) has always been the one museum to really
support me,'' Kruger says evenly. ``For me it was such a gift to be
able to work in that space. It's the best space in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she has kept an apartment in New York's TriBeCa
neighborhood for decades, Kruger now spends 10 months of the year
at her Los Angeles home. At times she misses ``the density in New
York,'' the way ``people are packed together, passing each other on
the street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a forced socialness, which I think is good for
people,'' she observes.
</P>
<P>
   But she says she's grown partial to L.A., its warm winters and
disjointed landscapes. We're also the city that inadvertently
coined the phrase that resounds throughout ``Barbara Kruger'':
Can't we all just get along?
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how would that look on a coffee mug. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``Barbara Kruger.'' &QL; 
Where: The Geffen Contemporary of the Museum of Contemporary Art,
152 N. Central Ave., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: Through Feb. 13. Museum hours are 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesdays
through Sundays, 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. Thursdays. &QL; 
Admission: $6 adults; $4 students, seniors; free for MOCA members
and children under 12. Admission is free to all every from 5 to 8
p.m. Thursdays. Call (213) 626-6222. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
