<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4761 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-HEALTH-ROBONURSE-KANS     01-24 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ROBONURSE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THERE A ROBOT IN THE HOUSE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LISA GUTIERREZ  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her name is Flo and she is a nurse unlike any you have ever met.
</P>
<P>
   She can perform ``nurse'' duties. Remind you to take your
medicine. Take your vital signs and even e-mail them to your
doctor. If she does a good job, though, don't bother patting her on
the back, because Flo doesn't respond to such positive
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   She is a robot, a robo nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers from the University of Pittsburgh and Carnegie Mellon
University in Pennsylvania have created Flo, a personal service
robot, to serve as nurse and companion to elderly and housebound
patients. Still a prototype, Flo is not available yet to the
public. Researchers working to equip her with other humanlike
skills _ like being able to open jars or bottles for arthritis
patients _ expect her to evolve greatly in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   All of which sounds very ``Jetson''-esque, but not everyone
likes the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may open cans. It may remind someone on the screen to take
their medications. But it cannot hold a hand. It cannot make eye
contact. It cannot touch,'' says Carol Bentley, a nurse currently
caring for a housebound 60-year-old Shawnee Mission woman with
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she (her patient) were in her last moments, she can feel my
hand, she can feel my presence. If the family can't be there, I can
be here, one human being with another. I am not a machine. I am a
warm, caring human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Flo or not, technology is already changing the way health
care is delivered to the homebound. Giving a whole new meaning to
the words ``house calls,'' doctors can listen to a patient's
heartbeat long distance and even regulate a pacemaker through a
phonelike device.
</P>
<P>
   TV screens set up in a patient's home can allow a nurse in an
office miles away to monitor symptoms or help a diabetes patient
read the tiny, hard-to-see hash marks on an insulin syringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think this (technology) is going to be commonplace
soon,'' says Carol Smith, a professor in the School of Nursing at
the University of Kansas Medical Center, who consulted on the Flo
project last month.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose expertise is home health care, recently received a
multimillion-dollar grant from the National Institutes of Health to
research how to use ``telehealth'' monitors in the homes of rural
elderly patients who use ventilators or hook themselves up to
catheters overnight.
</P>
<P>
   She and Flo's designers believe that robots could make life
easier for one of the fastest growing populations in America _
elderly people. About 6.5 million senior citizens need assistance
with their daily living activities, according to the Assisted
Living Federation of America in Fairfax, Va. That number is
expected to double by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Flo, who stands about 4 feet with big, goggle eyes,
Groucho-esque metal eyebrows and a computer screen for a tummy, is
helping researchers understand how autonomous mobile robots _ think
robot maid Rosie from the ``Jetsons'' or R2-D2 from ``Star Wars'' _
can interact with humans to improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Nursebot _ Flo's official name _ can follow an
elderly patient around the house, preventing them from getting
lost. Using the Internet and Flo's two-way screen, patients can
communicate with their nurses and physicians. Flo can even call for
help in case of a medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As baby-boomers age, they are computer literate ... they have
already embraced computers and they are not going to see this as
out of the ordinary,'' predicts Cindy Keim, a registered nurse and
director of operations for Home Health Plus of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   All this new technology ``allows patients to be independent and
function at their highest level, which people want to do,'' Keim
said. ``They don't want to be in a position where they can't take
care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an agency's point of view, instead of sending a nurse 20
miles away, they can actually call and talk to their patient, and
see more patients in a day. You don't want to put all your patients
on this, though. You would never be able to do this with patients
who are not stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Keim admits that one challenge of using all this new technology
is helping some seniors over their fear of high-tech tools. And
when nurse Bentley considers the worth of Flo and other high-tech
kin sure to come, she wonders how expensive robots will be and
whether everyone will have access to them. (There's no word yet on
how much Flo would cost.)
</P>
<P>
   No matter how smart you make a pile of nuts and bolts, it still
can't replace the flesh-and-blood nurse, insists Bentley, who works
for Elder Care of Kansas City. And even Smith, the researcher,
agrees on that point.
</P>
<P>
   The last few weeks Bentley has been taking care of Christine
Braughton, a widow with ovarian cancer so weakened by chemotherapy
treatments that she has been bedridden since last August.
</P>
<P>
   Braughton spends her days lying on a bed in her living room, in
the company of home-health nurses during the day and nuns who
volunteer to stay with her overnight. She does not like the idea of
robot nurses.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, a robot can't cook, Braughton points out. And
what kind of companion would it be ``because you couldn't talk with
them,'' wondered Braughton, whose own voice now is weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever tried to hug a metal box, Christine?'' Bentley
asked her patient. ``Unless it was a refrigerator?'' And both women
laughed.
</P>
</TEXT>
