<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PORTFOLIO LOAFS, ANOTHER IS WAY TOO AGGRESSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like your advice on a portfolio for my wife and
myself as we enter retirement. I am 58 and will retire soon. I have
been a teacher for 34 years, and will retire with a state pension
of $2,500 a month. My wife is 54 and not working. We plan to draw
$600 a month from her IRA for a five-year period. At age 62 I will
receive $255 a month from Social Security, and my wife will receive
Social Security of $465 a month when she reaches 62. At present we
have 20 percent of our mutual fund investments in equity funds and
the rest in money markets. My wife has $19,000 in Fidelity Dividend
Growth fund, $12,000 in Fidelity Disciplined Equity, $5,000 in
Vanguard Wellington, $6,000 in Vanguard Index 500, $23,000 in
Fidelity Cash Reserves, and $84,000 in Vanguard Prime Money Market.
I have $14,000 in Fidelity Dividend Growth fund and $102,000 in
Fidelity Cash Reserves. We also have $135,000 in a liquid advantage
account at our bank.
</P>
<P>
   D.F., Huntington Beach, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would do the arithmetic a little differently, coming up
with a total of $344,000, or 86 percent of your savings, in money
markets and other cash investments. You have built a staggeringly
conservative portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say it may not work to some extent. I guess I
just hate to see so much money loafing, and loafing so mightily.
</P>
<P>
   I presume that your plan is to use the withdrawals from your
wife's IRA during the first five years of retirement to bring your
income to $3,100 a month, which is satisfactory to your needs.
</P>
<P>
   In four years, when your Social Security kicks in, your
dependence upon this would be somewhat lessened, and in eight years
your combined Social Security benefits would, in theory, take the
place of the IRA withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   There would be a three-year period during which you would need
to take some of the yield from your savings to meet living
expenses, and after you would probably have to continue drawing
some to counter inflation, but the pool would continue to grow
modestly, providing you further protection against inflation in the
later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   I am always loath to suggest that people who have built
ultra-conservative portfolios change their ways. I assume that
since your total portfolio is likely to return 5.5 percent to 6
percent, and since inflation hasn't been that high for some time,
you would be able to cruise through retirement with the portfolio
chugging along safely ahead of the ravages of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would likely be true _ except that if you
expect to continue maintaining a $3,100-a-month lifestyle, you will
soon be spending some of it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at the picture in eight years, when your wife
qualifies for Social Security, bringing your total income from
pension and combined Social Security to $3,220.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose that inflation averages 3.5 percent a year during
those first eight years, that your portfolio remains at a $400,000
balance, and that it returns a portfolio average of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To keep step with inflation, you would need $4,082 a month to
maintain a standard of living equivalent to what $3,100 a month now
buys.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, you would be drawing $862 a month, or $10,344 a year, from
your retirement portfo-lio. The effect of this is that after the
withdrawals, the growth of your principal would shrink to 2.91
percent _ no longer keeping pace with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The real trouble comes later on. Let's jump 10 years into the
future. By then you would need $5,758 a month to maintain the
current $3,100 monthly spending power, meaning that withdrawals
would run at a rate of $2,538 a month _ more than the portfolio
would produce.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in Social Security payments would help, but not enough
to solve the problem. Even if you still had $400,000 in the
portfolio, making such withdrawals would mean that the fund would
be depleted in a little more than 15 years _ and you'd have no
capacity to increase withdrawals to offset future inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that you really can't afford to be so
conservative. Do some research into CDs, intermediate-term bond
funds such as GNMAs, and other reasonably conservative fixed-income
investments, seeking at least to pull your anticipated portfolio
returns into the 7 percent range, at which point you would have a
much better chance of making your strategy work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are 65, and we have these investments, totaling
$308,000: $11,000 in US Savings Bonds, $15,000 in CDs, $18,000 in
Gabelli Westwood Balanced fund, $10,000 in Gabelli Westwood Equity
fund, $23,000 in Gabelli Asset fund, $13,000 in Janus fund, $33,000
in Janus Worldwide fund, $14,000 in T. Rowe Price Dividend Growth
fund, $19,000 in T. Rowe Price Equity Income fund, $4,000 in John
Hancock Sovereign Investors fund (an IRA), $5,000 in Sound Shore
fund, $8,000 in American Century Ultra fund, $40,000 in USAA Income
Strategy fund, $28,000 in USAA Income Stock fund (another IRA),
$44,000 in Vanguard Index 500, and $23,000 in Vanguard Health Care
fund. Our only debt is a $1,000 monthly mortgage payment. Would you
suggest any changes in our investments?
</P>
<P>
   J.W., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, perhaps you could merge with D.F., the writer of the
letter above, and come out with a fairly well-balanced portfolio
between you.
</P>
<P>
   I tally a bit more than 21 percent of this portfolio on the
fixed-income side (with your balanced fund as half equity and half
fixed income). That's putting too much reliance upon the market for
most people your age.
</P>
<P>
   You say nothing about your financial position aside from this
portfolio, but unless you have an income stream from other sources
that is well in excess of your current needs, you are taking too
much risk.
</P>
<P>
   Such a portfolio might be appropriate for a person who wouldn't
need for the funds within a 10-year period, and I'd be more
comfortable if that number were 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, double the fixed-income side of the portfolio, and
indeed, go further, taking it to 50 percent or more, looking for
the same kind of investments I suggested for D.F.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a widow, age 89, and I have $350,000 in CDs. My monthly
Social Security is $914, I have a $156 monthly pension, and I earn
$200 a month. Do you think I should put some of my CDs in the
market? My concern is that I may need long-term health care and
will not have enough assets to cover the cost. I do not want to be
a burden on my daughter. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   L.L., Woodland Hills, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the stock market is a place that's simply too
dangerous at this point. In the near term, a chance of a
significant loss is as strong as that of any substantial gain. In
fact, I'm hoping for a fairly long period of moving sideways, which
might bring earnings and potential earnings into a better alignment
with stock prices. Going sideways isn't anything that will help
you. And remember, that's what I'm hoping for, not what I fear.
</P>
<P>
   For a person in your situation, CDs look mighty good to me right
now. Entering this week, the nation's highest rate was 7.42 percent
for a jumbo ($100,000 or above) five-year CD. The best rate on a
one-year jumbo was 6.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you can achieve such rates, and hold the accounts to $100,000
each so that they enjoy federal insurance, that route is safer, and
quite possibly more rewarding, than joining hands with the very
tired bull that has been driving Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is to keep careful tabs on the best rates,
which many Sunday newspapers publish each week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
