<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-PROFILE-ARKAN-BOS &LR;      01-24 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-ARKAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-BIT CRIMINAL _ OR PATRIOT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ One night last spring, when NATO fighters had bombed
the electricity grid for the umpteenth time, the lights at the
Hyatt Hotel went out yet again, and the Tea House lounge was
plunged into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   When, a few moments later, a generator kicked in and the lights
came back on, Zeljko Raznatovic sat as he had before, a drink in
his hand, a laugh on his lips. The only difference was that, in the
darkness, two bodyguards had sprung from chairs to his side.
</P>
<P>
   If Raznatovic sensed danger in the dark, he did not show it,
then or ever. ``I am not afraid of your CIA,'' said the man better
known as ``Arkan.'' ``They cannot kill me here.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if they had wanted to, they could have. Arkan lived
openly during the Kosovo war. He was a creature of habit, his
patterns, such as the nightly rounds of drinks at the Tea House,
well established. His regular duo of bodyguards, one of them
usually a woman, provided little deterrent against professional
assassins _ as events of last weekend proved.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan, 47, was gunned down on Jan. 15 in the lobby of the
Inter-Continental hotel in Belgrade. One of the bodyguards who had
leapt to Arkan's side in the darkness last year was cut down with
him, as was another man in the perpetual hotel-hopping entourage.
</P>
<P>
   For all his talk about Western governments conspiring to kill
him, much of it aimed at adding to his mystique, Arkan was never as
vulnerable to the outside world as he was to the society that
spawned him.
</P>
<P>
   That a stickup man turned gangster turned paramilitary leader
turned war criminal would become a celebrity in Serbia is a symptom
of a deeply dysfunctional society, as good an explanation as any
for why what remains of the former Yugoslavia is a pariah in the
Western world.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan was a postmodern gangster. Historically, the biggest and
the most notorious organized crime groups in the world, such as the
Italian Mafia and the Chinese triads, began as nationalist militias
that morphed into criminal organizations after their raison d'etre
melted away.
</P>
<P>
   With Arkan and his Tigers paramilitary unit, it was just the
opposite. They were a bunch of hoodlums given a political mandate
to kill by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in his regime's
campaign to create an ethnically pure Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest way to drive out any segment of a civilian
population is to terrorize them, and the best way to terrorize
people is to summarily execute some of them, be they men, women or
children.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan and the Tigers were accomplished ethnic cleansers, first
in Croatia, then in Bosnia, and finally in Kosovo, although by the
time Serb forces rolled into Kosovo last year, Arkan saw no need to
accompany them. He had long ago traded his camouflage fatigues for
Armani suits. His nightly cocktail circuit in Belgrade was not so
much about establishing an alibi in Kosovo as it was about reaping
the rewards of a criminal empire he built when he wasn't doing
Milosevic's dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Slovenia, the son of a senior officer in the Yugoslav
air force, Arkan dropped out of school at 17 and a few years later
was robbing banks in Western Europe. He was suspected of being
among those who assassinated exiled Yugoslav dissidents in various
European capitals in the 1970s and '80s. He was arrested in Belgium
for bank robbery and given a 15-year prison sentence in 1975, but
escaped four years later.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities throughout Europe kept arresting him, but Arkan kept
escaping, from jails in Holland and Germany, from police in Sweden
and Italy. Arkan had friends in high places in the Yugoslav secret
police, which helped him slip across borders and return to Serbia
without fear of extradition. Indeed, his nickname was drawn from
one of the many passports he obtained with the help of the secret
police.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being one of Interpol's most wanted men, he was able to
return to Belgrade in 1986 and open a cake and ice cream shop
across the street from the stadium that was home to Serbia's most
popular soccer team, Red Star Belgrade. Arkan became chairman of
the team's fan club and found recruits for his criminal gang, and
later the Tigers, among the rowdies who peopled the cheap seats.
</P>
<P>
   War crimes prosecutors say that in 1991, Arkan and the Tigers
slaughtered civilians in the Croatian town of Vukovar, including
some 250 people who were dragged from a hospital and shot.
Prosecutors say Arkan and his Tigers repeated the slaughter of
civilians in Bosnia, aiding and abetting Radovan Karadzic, the
Bosnian Serb leader, and Bosnian Serb General Ratko Mladic, both of
whom, like Arkan, were indicted for war crimes but have not been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In much of Serbia, many people acknowledged Arkan was a
gangster; but he was also seen as a patriot, someone who did
nothing different from what the Croats did to Serbs in Croatia and
what Bosnian Muslims did to Serbs in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Arkan fathered nine children by three wives. His third wife,
Svetlana Velikovic, is a pop singer known as Ceca, and their 1995
wedding was treated as a celebrity event. Once, on a live call-in
TV show, a caller admired a piece of jewelry she was wearing. When
the caller asked Ceca if it was inscribed with certain lettering on
back, a startled Ceca replied that it was. The caller then said it
had been stolen from her by Arkan. The line immediately went dead.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yugoslav dinar all but collapsed, the true currency in
Belgrade these days is conspiracy theories, and there is no
shortage of them when it comes to who killed Arkan. Opposition
parties have blamed the Milosevic regime, saying it had the most to
gain by silencing someone who literally knew where the bodies were
buried. Others suggest gangland competitors did him in.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that Arkan was distancing himself from
Milosevic and cozying up to Serbian opposition leaders, including
Zoran Djindjic, and Montenegro President Milo Djukanovic, a bitter
Milosevic foe. That Djindjic and Djukanovic saw nothing wrong with
striking up a relationship with Arkan raises questions about why
the Clinton administration believes those two leaders hold the key
to ousting Milosevic and building a better society in what remains
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Klein, head of the United Nations mission in Bosnia,
spoke for many when he said crying for Arkan would be like crying
for Adolf Eichmann, the Nazi war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   But there were tears shed for Arkan at his funeral Thursday in
Belgrade. He was dispatched from this world in a ceremony befitting
the national hero he styled himself as.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Arkan sat on a couch in the Drawing Room, a small,
plush lounge at the Hyatt, watching Manchester United battle Bayern
Munich for the European soccer championship on a widescreen TV.
While his father had fought as a partisan against the Nazis, Arkan
cheered for the German team and heaped abuse on the English team,
even though Britain and Germany are part of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British are bombing us,'' he reasoned. ``The Germans are
harmless.''
</P>
<P>
   On one of the walls, a smaller TV set was tuned to CNN, its
sound turned down as everyone focused on the big game. Suddenly,
without consulting the two dozen people who were glued to the
soccer match, Arkan grabbed a remote control and hit the mute
button on the big screen and turned up the volume on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   As he listened to correspondent Christiane Amanpour report that
The Hague tribunal had indicted Milosevic, Arkan's jaw stiffened
and his eyes narrowed. He could not mask his contempt for Amanpour,
who had made a devastating documentary about him. As if that was
not bad enough, Amanpour's husband, US State Department spokesman
Jamie Rubin, was on TV every day, defending the bombing of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   After describing Amanpour in language that is unprintable, Arkan
turned the game's sound back on, tossed the remote aside, settled
back into the comfortable couch and dismissed as ridiculous the
charges lodged against his president and patron.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's crazy,'' Arkan said. ``He's no war criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, having seen what happened to Arkan, it could be that
Karadzic and Mladic might prefer the justice that awaits them at
The Hague than the kind doled out in the lobby of the
Inter-Continental.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
