   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   IN SOUTH CAROLINA, GOP TAKES OVER FROM RACIST DEMOCRATS OF
CENTURIES PAST. One hundred years ago, Sen. Ben ``Pitchfork''
Tillman, a South Carolina Democrat, stood on the floor of the U.S.
Senate and described his state's strategy for keeping blacks from
exercising their 15th Amendment right to vote. His words: ``We have
scratched our heads to find out how we could eliminate the last one
of them. We have stuffed ballot boxes. We shoot them. We are not
ashamed.'' ``If Tillman were alive today, it is very likely that he
and his ilk would tone down their racial rhetoric, but they might
become registered Republicans,'' columnist Vernon Jarrett writes.
Witness the controversy over the Confederate War Flag that now
waves over South Carolina's capitol dome. In this commentary,
Jarrett reports on how the presidential frontrunners stand on this
issue and offers an historical context to bolster his argument that
the flag must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH FOR PRESIDENT? DEFINITELY NOT _ An admitted fan of CNN,
MSNBC and the ``Jim Lerher News Hour,'' columnist James Garcia
likes to think he is a step ahead of the public in being able to
anticipate political trends. In this commentary, Garcia offers his
opinion on the presidential frontrunners. ``Like most Americans,
I've narrowed my list to ... Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Vice
President Al Gore, Sen. John McCain and former Sen. Bill Bradley.
Where I split with most Americans is that I'm ready to drop a name
from that short list: Bush,'' Garcia writes. He goes to explain why
he thinks Bush is off-base on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   FOR ME, THE NEW YEAR IS AN OPEN ROAD. One of columnist Bill
Maxwell's resolutions for the New Year is to travel more both in
the United States and abroad. ``For me, travel is spiritual
nourishment, especially when I do not have a strict plan,'' he
writes. ``I love to travel intuitively, to let things happen, to
find a smooth place in a rough sea or a piece of level ground on
craggy terrain. The trick is to find balance in a foreign place.''
In this article, Maxwell recounts his travel adventures of last
year _ including his trip to Gaza city, where he was arrested for
taking pictures of the Palestinian Authority's intelligence
building _ and explains why today's budding journalists need to hit
the road as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES DOES NOT DISCRIMINATE. Diabetes is the sixth leading
cause of death in the United States, affecting 16 million
Americans, writes Theresa Kim in this article from A. Magazine. Of
the afflicted, an estimated one-third are undiagnosed. A National
Institutes of Health Study reports that the rates of
Asian-Americans with diabetes are double, and nearly triple, that
of Caucasians. In this article, Kim defines diabetes for the
average reader, cites the alarming statistics that show an increase
in the numbers of Asian-Americans suffering from it and reports on
the work of many health organizations that are involved in the
Asian-American communities.
</P>
<P>
   THE WIND BENEATH HER WINGS. On the Pine Ridge Indian
reservation, where the unemployment rate hovers at 70 percent and
the county within the reservation (Shannon) has been proclaimed the
poorest county in the United States, role models are hard to come
by. SuAnne Big Crow, however, counts as one. SuAnne was a model
teen-ager who lived her life to the fullest and was proud of her
Native-American heritage. Teens and adults looked to her for
inspiration. Unfortunately, her life was cut short when she was
killed in an automobile accident. Her legacy lives on with The
SuAnne Big Crow Memorial Boys and Girls Club. In this fascinating
feature, columnist Tim Giago explains why SuAnne will never be
forgotten among Native-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  The following photos are available electronically:
</P>
