<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-24 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGARDING THE BATHS NOT TAKEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You only have one bathroom?'' a friend asked, after looking
around our house. She seemed shocked.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. We have only one bathroom. And it's not even a great
bathroom. It's basic.
</P>
<P>
   My friend couldn't believe that we had moved willingly from a
house with two and a half bathrooms to a place with just one.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could I, at first.
</P>
<P>
   Now I look back on those years we lived in the
two-and-a-half-bath house as a kind of lavatory golden age. I know
I'll never again have so many bathrooms. At least I have my
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half bathrooms were more bathrooms than I'd ever
dreamed of, or would have dreamed of, if I'd dreamed about
bathrooms, which I didn't, until we scaled down from two and a half
to one.
</P>
<P>
   Now I think about bathrooms all the time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm far from alone in this. There's a kind of plumbing frenzy in
the air. In these prosperous times everybody's going nuts over
bathrooms. They're not just conveniences anymore, they're status
symbols, more numerous and fancier than ever. Isn't this how the
decline of Rome started?
</P>
<P>
   Three and a half bathrooms. That's the norm these days for a new
five-bedroom house, says property developer John Ciccolo. That's
norm as in ``average.'' Many people want more, a bathroom for every
bedroom, plus another on the first floor, and not the traditional
puny half bath, but a full bath.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest room is getting bigger and bigger, says Ciccolo, to
hold all sorts of fixtures, accessories, and equipment. Whirlpool
baths. Giant shower stalls that accommodate two or three people,
even a crowd. Multiple shower jets at various levels. Steam baths.
Saunas. Pedicure benches. Skylights. Radiant under-floor heating.
Dressing rooms. Make-up benches. Linen storage. Towel warmers.
Granite counter tops. Marble walls. Bidets. And silent, streamlined
toilets, artfully camouflaged or, preferably, hidden from view
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   All I wanted was a new sink. I had to have the best. I may have
imagined that a really nice sink would transform the dismal
bathroom in our new house and make me forget about the one and a
half baths we'd lost.
</P>
<P>
   Off I went to Splash, a bath emporium so upscale that no prices
are displayed. It's like a museum of plumbing. People mill around,
gaping at the latest in bathtubs and bidets, waiting for a
receptionist to summon them to a sales representative. It's best to
phone ahead for an appointment. Walk-ins may have a long wait.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was my turn, I had examined every detail of every
sink in the place. I knew exactly what I wanted. I wanted to flee
Splash as quickly as possible. But first, I needed a sink. ``Good
choice,'' said the salesman when I told him what I wanted. He
consulted a catalog. ``You're lucky,'' he said. ``It's in stock:
$435.''
</P>
<P>
   Now for the faucets. ``Ooh, excellent choice,'' he said, looking
in the catalog. ``They're $857.''
</P>
<P>
   I was speechless. ``They're German, the finest made,'' the
salesman said. ``Your friends will be so impressed when they see
these faucets.''
</P>
<P>
   I told him we don't have that sort of friends. He recommended
some faucets in the $200 range. I wrote a check. He handed me a
yellow rubber duckie, the store mascot. I made fast tracks for the
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I made a mistake. If I'd bought those $857 imported German
faucets, it's possible my friend would have been so dazzled by them
she would have overlooked the fact that we have only one bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   My real mistake, I think, was not going to Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
