<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITONS DIVIDED OVER TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Many Brits are pleased as punch with themselves these
days, as American celebrities increasingly ditch the States to take
up residence here in the capital of Cool Britannia.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna had bought a home and intended to educate her daughter
here. Tom Cruise and his Australian wife, Nicole Kidman, have
settled in St. John's Wood, near Regents Park, lauding the civility
of London over the madness of Hollywood. Woody Allen reportedly
will soon abandon his muse, Manhattan, for London.
</P>
<P>
   This has led many commentators here to remark on how London is
far more livable than big American cities like New York or Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But not every American celeb is welcome here.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   The former heavyweight champ's arrival here to train for a fight
with a local underdog named Julius Francis has been one of high
drama and low farce. Because of his rape conviction and ear-biting
history in the ring, Tyson's entry into the country had to be
cleared at the highest levels of government and was challenged in
court by a feminist group. Tyson prevailed in court, and celebrated
by going out to the exclusive New Bond Street shopping district and
dropping more than $1.5 million on a bracelet and watch studded
with diamonds and sapphires.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tyson horrified Middle England, that imaginary barometer of
mainstream British opinion, by saying he was thinking about moving
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more at home here than I do at home,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   While most people seem either appalled or apathetic that Tyson
is here, there is a small but vocal minority who see him more as a
misunderstood rebel than an ex-con. Hundreds of fans have been
drawn each day to the posh Grosvenor House Hotel, across from Hyde
Park, where Tyson is staying in a pair of adjoining suites which go
for $3,200 a night. The hotel's $16,000-a-day Park Suite has been
converted into a gym.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Tyson was given a hero's welcome in Brixton, the
heart of London's black community. Local politicians had said Tyson
should stay away. The people said otherwise, mobbing him and
chanting his name. The crowds became so frenzied that Tyson had to
take shelter in a place he normally doesn't go to willingly: a
police station.
</P>
<P>
   One can only imagine what Middle England made of the sight of
Tyson addressing an adoring throng by megaphone from the window of
the Brixton police station.
</P>
<P>
   But as 18-year-old William Jeffrey explained after he jostled to
get a glimpse of Tyson, many people in Brixton identify with Tyson
as someone who has faced the animus of the white establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police stop me all the time, when I haven't done anything
wrong,'' the teenager said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was allowed into the United Kingdom last week despite a
law that bans anyone with a felony conviction from entering the
country. The British home secretary, Jack Straw, who next to Prime
Minister Tony Blair is arguably the most powerful man in the
nation, made an exception, saying too many small businesses in
Manchester, the northern English city where the fight is scheduled
for next Saturday, stood to go bankrupt if the bout was canceled.
Straw's decision set off a storm of protest and the ill-fated legal
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Brits don't like boxers. They finally have a
world heavyweight champion in Lennox Lewis. Muhammad Ali, who got
an even bigger reception when he visited Brixton last year, was the
near unanimous choice of British sportswriters as athlete of the
century in the year-end polls.
</P>
<P>
   But while Ali is revered here as a great athlete of great
principle, especially for his refusal to fight in the Vietnam War,
Tyson is widely seen as a vile and venal man. But Tyson's most
vocal critics are middle-class whites, a fact that engenders
support for him among minorities here who, while not defending
Tyson's past, can identify with being demonized.
</P>
<P>
   The Grosvenor, which is usually peopled by old money from both
sides of the Atlantic, has been transformed into a Fawlty Towers
episode. One day, a group from the Socialist Women's Party holding
placards denouncing Tyson and chanting ``Take rape seriously, no
respect for Tyson!'' had to be hustled out of the hotel's opulent
marble lobby. Tyson's bodyguards got jumpy and had to be restrained
from beating up the hotel gardener when they spied him snooping
around the bushes outside.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Tyson long, meanwhile, to break the law. In the
wee hours of the morning, he went jogging in Hyde Park. The police
informed his handlers it is illegal to enter Hyde Park after
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's roadwork led one Metropolitan Police officer to resume
the crowing over London's superiority to Tyson's native New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how tough Mike Tyson is,'' said the copper,
standing near the Grosvenor, ``he wouldn't go running in Central
Park at 3 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is chief of the Boston Globe London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
