<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-STRAINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROUD GERMAN PARTY MAY BE A VICTIM OF THE KOHL SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ As Helmut Kohl struggles for his legacy, and as his
Christian Democrats struggle for survival as a major party, the
political landscape of Germany has changed forever, even as the
campaign financing scandal caused by Kohl rages on.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide on Thursday of Wolfgang Huellen, who headed the
Christian Democrats' parliamentary finance office, gave a more
human aspect to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger question, analysts say, is whether the Christian
Democrats who have ruled Germany for most of the time since the end
of World War II have mortally wounded themselves as a political
force.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has admitted to taking at least $1 million in unreported
donations from 1993 to 1998, when he was defeated in his attempt
for a record fifth term as chancellor and stepped aside as party
leader. He said the money had been used to pay party expenses, and
that he gave his word not to identify the donors, although such
secrecy is a blatant violation of campaign finance laws enacted
under his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will fight for my honor, and part of my honor is keeping my
word,'' Kohl said Thursday, after his forced resignation as the
party's honorary chairman. Kohl has characterized the scandal as a
witch hunt. It has triggered a criminal investigation and
parliamentary hearings in an effort to establish if his
administration traded favors for cash.
</P>
<P>
   While Kohl insists that the cash was good for the party, and
that the party was good for the country, politics in which the ends
justify the means seem to have ended in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, another German politician went to prison saying he
could not understand why he was being held accountable for the way
politics used to work. Egon Krenz, the last communist leader of
East Germany, was imprisoned in connection with border guards
killing people trying to flee from East to West.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz says he did nothing wrong, and insists that the end,
protecting the sovereignty of East Germany, justified the means,
shooting unarmed civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Krause, deputy director of the German Society for
Foreign Affairs, a Berlin-based think tank, has voiced doubt about
predictions that the Christian Democrats would implode because of
the finance scandal. But he said Kohl has placed the party in ``the
worst trial'' of its 55-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kohl did not change with the times; he did not modernize the
party,'' Krause said. ``He did away with good, bright people. They
were pushed aside and they were replaced with people who obeyed
Kohl, who did not contradict Kohl.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause said Kohl, the man who presided over the collapse of the
Berlin Wall, had borrowed a page from the communists when it came
to creating a party structure in which there was one boss, and in
which dissent was not tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He centralized the party leadership, not with the same methods
of the communists, but with the same results,'' Krause said. ``The
party needs transparency and new people who have seen something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have had success in recent German politics have been
parties and politicians able to change traditional positions,
abandoning what they once considered nonnegotiable principles in a
pragmatic trade-off for real power.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bill Clinton and Tony Blair before him, Gerhard Schroeder
moved his Social Democrats from left to center, and he ended the
conservative Kohl's 16-year tenure. Likewise, Germany's Green Party
abandoned one of its core planks, pacifism, to back the war in
Kosovo and remain junior partner of Schroeder's ruling coalition.
The Green leader and the foreign minister, Joschka Fischer,
defended the first deployment of German troops since 1945 as a
necessary response to ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say Kohl had never adapted, and had prevented
his party from doing so. He began as a provincial politician in the
Rhineland, the prosperous western state next to the border. For 25
years he ran the nation's biggest party _ and for 16 years its most
powerful office _ with all the parochialism and insouciance of a
rural constituency office. Ronald Reagan, George Bush, Francois
Mitterrand, and Mikhail Gorbachev were charmed by Kohl's
informality. Margaret Thatcher, however, found it repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine Germany without the Christian Democrats,
whose conservatism and conventionality have made it the most
popular and dominant party for decades. Founded in 1945 with the
encouragement, and some would say at the direction, of the Allies,
the party has led the federal government, either alone or as the
senior partner of a coalition, from 1949 to 1969 and from 1982
until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts have suggested that the Christian Democratic
parties that sprang up across Europe after World War II are losing
their relevance in a more politically sophisticated Europe,
especially since their role as a bulwark against communism became
meaningless after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democratic Party was a dominant force in postwar
Italy until 1993, when a corruption scandal initiated its
self-destruction. Such a fate now threatens Germany's Christian
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Hajo Schumacher, a journalist for Der Spiegel whose stories
alleging Kohl's corruption of German politics used to be dismissed
as left-wing propaganda, says the party is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one in the leadership that is not tainted by
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Krause, the analyst, says the party will survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 600,000 party members,'' he said. ``There are good
people with new ideas among them. They need to be given a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunter Nooke, a Christian Democratic member of the Bundestag,
Germany's parliament, could be one of those to rise above the
scandal. Nooke has been a party member for just three years. He
says predictions of the party's demise are exaggerated, and are
usually partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that ever happened, it would be horrible for German
democracy,'' he said, adding that is the reason he believed it
would not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Germans, he said, know that democracy has transformed their
society and would be reluctant to do anything rash to undermine it.
</P>
<P>
   Nooke says the answers for his party's survival lie within.
Offering what could become a mantra, he said, ``Only the party can
emancipate itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
