<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-TWEENS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     01-24 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TWEENS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... to kids.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Frank's network, appealing to younger kids has previously
been the exclusive province of the Nickelodeon channel, which is
beefing up its music programming to meet the demand of these new
consumers. Albie Hecht, president of film and TV entertainment for
Nickelodeon, voices the throw-up-your-hands sentiment echoed by
many adults. ``I think times have changed in general and we've all
just adjusted. I recently made a compilation of Beatles songs, and
it struck me that the innocence of that pop music just doesn't
happen anymore. We've all adjusted from `I wanna hold your hand' to
`Hit me, baby.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ali's mother, Linda Gallagher, agrees. ``It's what the world is
like,'' she says. ``Short of home schooling, there's nothing to do.
I don't want to be Church Lady. You just try to set a great example
at home, cross your fingers, and throw them out into the world.''
Linda Gallagher has never even listened to the lyrics. ``All I know
is they're probably not saying `kill your parents.' It's, like,
`la, la, la, love is in the air,' right?''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. But interestingly, Ali doesn't listen to the lyrics
either. Asked what ``Baby, One More Time'' and ``Genie in a
Bottle'' are about, Ali says that _ despite the fact she can recite
all the words _ she ``doesn't really pay attention to what they're
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Nickelodeon's Hecht believes that ``kids at each age
hear and see what their developmental level is adjusted to. At 6,
they're not translating the lyrics or the suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jacobs Brumberg, however, parsing the lyrics may be
immaterial. A quick glance at the magazine layouts (Britney
Spears's recent Lolita-style spread in Rolling Stone showed her in
a strapless push-up bra, tight white briefs, and towering pumps,
surrounded by dolls and stuffed animals in her bedroom at home),
the come-hither videos, and provocative live shows bears out Jacobs
Brumberg's assertion that ``what girls learn from this phenomenon
is that female power resides in the ability to attract the opposite
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Channel, which has functioned as a virtual
clearinghouse for the teen pop stars, and which features them
prominently in music specials and video programming, puts a rosy
spin on the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young kids look at them as big Barbie dolls,'' says Tina
Treadwell, executive director of talent development and music
specials for the Disney Channel, whose target age is 9 to 14.
``They want the outfits. The older kids are starting to feel a
sense of commonality. When Britney came out with the `Baby . . . '
video, she's in a school environment with the shirt and the little
skirt, the whole parochial thing. Yeah, she gave it a little bit of
rebel by tying her shirt up. But she was like an extension of the
cheerleading squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but this particular cheerleader happened to be on her
knees, asking in no uncertain terms to be roughed up by an
ex-lover. ``It's an interpretation,'' Treadwell insists, echoing
songwriter Kipner. ``If we're not projecting our adult awareness,
`hit me' could mean `with your love,' or `with your dynamic
personality.' It's not what we might put on it. These are young
people trying to express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but they're not. These are young people desperate to make it
in show business, willing to defer to the powerful men who can make
their dreams of stardom come true. Deborah Gibson, now 29 and
working in musical theater, remembers it well. ``Oh, they tried to
put that image on me, too. The male record executives always want
to put young girls in sexy clothes. It probably goes back to
caveman days.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson fought tooth and nail to record her own songs and
preserve her identity. At 16, she says, ``I really wasn't in touch
with my sexuality enough to jump,'' as her handlers were urging her
to do, ``from point A to point D. I didn't want to skip B and C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are tender years,'' says Gibson. And that goes for both
the ambitious young stars and the starry-eyed kids who adore them.
``You don't get them back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
