<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-SEEING-BOS &LR;      01-24 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SEEING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HOMES OF MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SEEING THROUGH PLACES 
Reflections on Geography and Identity 
By Mary Gordon. Scribner. 254 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is a staircase recalled from childhood simply a blend of wood
and light encased in memory, or does it hold far greater things _
joy and confusion and a certain color, say, or fear and intrigue?
Cloistered within the castle of the imagination, Mary Gordon has
spent much of her writing life describing interiors: the melancholy
hues of an introspective youth; the somber, even drab, tones of
Irish Catholic family life; the shadows of a father who promised
mystery and then died too young. These are all themes of her own
life narrative, and yet they have each appeared in various guises
throughout her fiction _ in several novels and a collection of
stories, she's created a milieu of such moody texture it could
scarcely belong to anyone else. In ``Seeing through Places'' she
returns to the palpable stone and shingle of that reality, sifting
through the detritus of the past in order to comprehend the
blueprint of the present.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Proustian notion, of course, romantic even as it's
hellbent on being anti-sentimental. So it doesn't surprise one that
Gordon spends the finest part of each of her days in the company of
Proust _ armed with her coffee and toast and dog, she faces the
dawn of a working life by reading 10 pages, every morning, from the
master. Precious few madeleines here, though: What we have instead
is the daunting house in Queens where her maternal grandmother
lived, to where she and her mother would return after Gordon's
father died when Mary was 7, and where a young intellectual's soul
and spirit would have to fight domestic ghosts _ those of shame,
ennui, and alcoholism _ in order to take flight.
</P>
<P>
   With each of its eight essays organized around a tangible
external influence, whether Gordon's physical world of play as a
child or her relationship with several priests, ``Seeing through
Places'' has set itself up as an architectural warren of memories.
It doesn't always work. The commanding first essay, ``My
Grandmother's House,'' creates a world thick with consciousness _ a
kitchen smelling of ricotta and cinnamon, a sick room with a far
less consoling ambience _ and yet Gordon's subsequent efforts to
maintain that depth often feel like the tacked-on wing of a house.
(Revealing what may be her own unease at this construction, she
continually posits rhetorical questions that end, oddly, with
periods instead of question marks, a desultory error that turns
them into muddy sentences instead of lofty inquiries.) But the real
story within these artifices is Gordon's autobiography, which is
what the reader wishes to glean. One scans the thematic conceit of
the book _ the neighbors in the house next door, the Catholic
retreats she accompanied her mother on, her later trips to Rome _
searching for the dark emotional reality that was taking shape.
This rich and more amorphous realm is what Gordon would transform
into fiction, from the suffocating bonds of familial love and duty
to the multilayered disappointments of a bad first marriage. Here,
such potential treasures are like too many fine possessions in a
cramped apartment: You want to see them shown off, under good
light, to far better effect.
</P>
<P>
   So my complaint is structural: Gordon's life narrative needed no
such add-on buttressing to support it. But so much sadness and
lonely alienation lurks within these pages _ hinted at, described
deadpan or stoically _ that perhaps she believed those confidences
required some superimposed edifice. What we find is a girl born in
oppressive though not uncommon circumstances. Gordon's father was
57, her mother 41; their marriage was not a happy one, but then joy
does not seem a commodity in great supply in the extended family
tree. When Gordon's mother left her own parents' home to marry, at
the age of 39, her father handed her a card with these words of
counsel: ``You will work till the day you die.''
</P>
<P>
   There are moments of grim cruelty all over the place in this
young life, only some of them unintentional; the very climate of
that house on the border of Long Island and Queens, where Gordon
would return for weekends even after she'd started college, seemed
surfeited with desolate withholding. In a cooking collaboration,
her grandmother continually let Mary the child burn her little
pastries in the oven, then taunted her with her own superior
efforts; when Mary the adolescent harmlessly back-talked her
mother, the woman slapped her. Watching her bedridden grandmother
die of stomach cancer, Mary, then 12, was inducted to change her
colostomy bag. But perhaps the oddest shock here comes from a
charismatic priest whom both her parents had befriended; the man
worshiped Mary's father, greatly admiring his mind and his
intellectual pursuits. When Gordon was a teenager, some years after
her father's death, she found a letter the priest had written her
mother just after the funeral. ``Say nothing to me of your grief,''
he had written. ``You, at least, had a child of his loins. I have
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   What is further surprising about such revelations is Gordon's
equanimity in recording them. Not for her the line of martyr; she
gave up that dream fairly early, along with an unquestioning
adoration of the lives of the saints and her belief in the supreme
cleansing of the confessional. For this was a child whose
introspection led her into dangerous alleys of freethinking _ of
art and literature and her own curiosity _ in preference,
eventually, to the more accepted corridors of religious passion. A
freshman at Barnard in the mid-'60s, she quickly traded in her
conservative woolens for bell-bottom jeans and found herself
chanting antiwar slogans instead of the rosary. Those days turned a
lot of would-be bankers and housewives into firebrands and seekers,
but the actual spiritual transformation she must have made _ from
pious Catholic girl to collegiate literary star _ is one Gordon
mostly skirts. Did it rock her world or break her heart, to give up
her utter devotion to religion's ordered universe? This
fragmentation is glimpsed near the end of ``The Architecture of a
Life with Priests,'' and it may be the most touching moment in the
book _ when the air itself seemed to change and the skies opened a
little, revealing neither overarching metaphor nor a judgmental
deity, but, simply, the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   Good writers of fiction do not choose their path casually; to go
there is to step away from reality in order to manipulate it, to
mold it into something deeper or higher. And it is usually a
disappointment to view the writer's ``place'' as though it might
present a key to the work: a room in Key West, say, or in Truro, or
on the Upper West Side. What you generally get when you look there
is four walls and a typewriter or computer screen; what matters, of
course, is the daily dose of Proust and the internal rhythms of
private song and the abiding passion to fill the page. Accordingly,
the presence residing within ``Seeing through Places'' is far more
vital than the room it seeks to describe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
