<HEADER>
A4785 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-GLASS-2TAKES-BO     01-24 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GLASS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLASS ON `AKHNATEN' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philip Glass's ``Akhnaten'' is a famous opera by a popular
composer. There is a recording on Sony Classical, and two scholarly
books have been devoted to the work. Nevertheless, no one in the
world has seen a production of ``Akhnaten'' in 11 years _ it's been
that long since the final performance of the original production in
Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Lyric Opera's production of ``Akhnaten,'' which opens
Wednesday in the Shubert Theatre, is the third staging in the
work's history. The first was Achim Freyer's production in
Stuttgart; the second, seen in Houston, London, and at the New York
City Opera, was by David Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   Glass will not be in the Lyric's audience opening night,
although he plans to see a performance later in the run; he's
touring Australia with his ``Dracula'' music. Before heading for
the antipodes, he came to the phone to talk about ``Akhnaten''
(1984), the third work in his trilogy of ``portrait operas''
devoted to figures and issues that changed the world _ Einstein
(``Einstein on the Beach,'' 1976, ``science, technology and
ecology'') and M. K. Gandhi (``Satyagraha,'' 1980, ``politics:
violence and non-violence''). The subject of ``Akhnaten'' is not
only the Egyptian ruler from the 14th century BC but also
``religion: orthodoxy and reaction.'' Collectively the three works
created a major redefinition of opera and marked important
evolutionary steps in Glass's style; the works aroused interest,
praise, condemnation, and controversy. What is unquestionable is
that they also brought a whole new generation into the opera house
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Glass says the idea of creating a trilogy was not his at all.
``The conductor Dennis Russell Davies was behind that. In those
days, he was moving around among opera houses. We had done
`Satyagraha' in Rotterdam, and then he became music director in
Stuttgart. They expected him to bring a new work with him, and he
asked me to think about one. I came up with the idea of Akhnaten
after stumbling across Immanuel Velikovsky's book `Oedipus and
Akhnaton.' Finally in 1989, all three operas were done together,
twice, over two weekends. People came from all over Europe and the
theater was completely packed. The productions by Achim Freyer were
really beautiful, although I wasn't as crazy about `Einstein' as I
was about the other two, but no one could have expected that any of
us involved in the original production would be _ we were too
committed to what we had done to accept something different so
easily. Then, as so often happens in Europe, the whole opera house
administration changed, and the new people decided they were not
going to do the trilogy anymore, even though it had been such a
great success with the public. The three operas never came together
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass admits he hasn't had much luck with trilogies. ``Since
then, of course, I did a second trilogy, this one based on works by
Cocteau. Two parts of it were performed in Boston.'' (``La Belle et
la Bete'' was presented by BankBoston Celebrity Series, and
`Orphee' by the American Repertory Theatre; the dance-opera ``Les
Enfants Terribles'' has not been seen here). ``No one has been able
to perform this trilogy together yet. Even if you consider the
works separately, it seems you have to wait about 10 years for any
piece to get into the next cycle of productions. Most companies
feel that if they are going to go to the trouble of putting on
something different, then they want to do a premiere. There's
something to be said for that _ I've been one of the beneficiaries
of this process!''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Akhnaten,'' Glass arranged an unusual double premiere in
Stuttgart and in Houston. ``With `Akhnaten,' I wanted two
productions coming out about the same time so that that the opera
could get off the ground in different versions, so that people
would not make the mistake of confusing the production with the
opera. There is an essential `Akhnaten' behind any individual
production that can be interpreted in different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass does count himself lucky that ``Akhnaten,'' unlike some of
his other major operatic works, was recorded. ``The recording is
still available and it is rather good. One of the things I've
learned in this funny opera business is that a composer should
place as much priority on getting a recording made as he does on
rushing around trying to the get the opera produced. A recording is
what will eventually bring people back to the work. I wrote two
operas with Doris Lessing (`The Making of the Representative for
Planet 8' and `The Marriages Between Zones Three, Four and Five')
and because neither one of them was recorded, it has been a real
problem trying to get them done again. . . . In a certain way, a
recording of an opera is a lot more important than a production!''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back to his search for ``Akhnaten,'' Glass recalls a
drive down New York's Major Deegan Expressway with his young son,
now 27. ``He asked me who Major Deegan was, and I had no idea. It
turned out he ran the munitions dump during the La Guardia days. In
other words, he was a complete nobody who got a highway named after
him because he was a friend of a politician. In this country, we
honor politicians and soldiers, but the thing America is known for
in the rest of the world is its music, painting, sculpture, and
literature. Imagine naming an airport after Jackson Pollock! What
this got going through my mind was that I was interested in people
who changed the world through ideas, not through force of arms or
politics. I stumbled across Akhnaten through Velikovsky's book and
that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that I moved on to Freud's `Moses and Monotheism.' We
don't really know whether Akhnaten was the guy who was the first
monotheist, but what an astonishing idea it was for this
18th-dynasty pharaoh to get rid of the whole pantheon of gods and
replace it with just one, identified with the sun _ not really the
sun, but the principle of the sun, the abstractness of the sun. The
Egyptians were very upset with him and the opera shows him being
overthrown, which may have been what happened. Akhnaten came from a
very conservative society, and for thousands of years, nothing much
happens, just one faceless pharoah after another, and then you go
to the Cairo Museum and walk into a room, and suddenly there's a
face, a human face. What an astonishing event this person must have
been in that culture, every bit as astonishing as Einstein or
Ghandi were in the 20th century _ even more astonishing, because
Akhnaten challenged every aspect of that culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Velikovsky, who published his book in 1960, was an amazing,
eccentric, and prescient figure. ``He was a very great intuitive
thinker who sometimes had trouble getting his facts together,''
Glass says. ``Many of his theories that people thought were
crackpot are now accepted; in his time he was dismissed as a
charlatan and an idiot. From Velikovsky's book, my first idea was
to write a double opera, an Oedipus opera and an Akhnaten opera
happening at the same time. During that very avant-garde period,
the way I was going to do it was to write one of them in two acts,
the other in three, so that while one of them was having its
intermission, the other one would still be going on. There's a
first libretto for this around somewhere. But the more I worked on
Akhnaten the more I got interested in him, and the less interesting
Oedipus became, so I said, `Why not get rid of this Oedipus
character?' Everything that is interesting about Oedipus is in the
Akhnaten story. Unloading the double opera problem released my
energy entirely to do `Akhnaten,' and to focus on what I was really
interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   What was there about Akhnaten's story that particularly
interested Glass? ``It was the fact that the history was in such
fragments. I got this idea of doing an opera made out of pieces,
like an Egyptian vase found scattered in pieces on the floor. I
thought of myself as looking at the pieces of history scattered
about. I liked the idea that I was like an archeologist in that
way; I didn't have to invent anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-AKHNATEN-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     01-24 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AKHNATEN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... invent anything.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are several unusual and interesting technical aspects of
``Akhnaten.'' One of them was a matter of choice: Glass's decision
to entrust the title role to a countertenor. ``Akhnaten is such a
fabulously interesting and bizarre character _ how would I present
him in the opera house? I wanted in one stroke to set him off as
completely unique. Deciding to make him a countertenor did that.
Further, I had the idea that we wouldn't hear him sing until the
third scene, when this amazing sound comes out. Oh my God, this was
such a device, to set him off in that way. (The British
countertenor) Paul Esswood went over the whole vocal part with me,
because I didn't know that much about countertenors and had no idea
of how to write for them. Through his help, I was able to write a
singable countertenor part. He also looked at details of
orchestration, and showed me how the voice would work with them. He
is a very kind man, and I owe him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A second aspect is the absence of violins in the scoring. ``That
was a great stroke of luck, although I didn't realize it at the
time. The opera house was closed for renovations at that time, so
we had to perform in the playhouse next door, where they had room
for only 45 musicians in the pit. This was where we had to do it,
and I wasn't going to give up the commission. The simplest thing to
do was to get rid of the violins. I don't think I really understood
what was going to happen, but I wound up with a very dark
orchestra, with violas acting like the first violins, creating a
brooding, dark sound which became emblematic of the whole piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Akhnaten himself is associated with the shining sound of the
trumpet; the score also has an elaborate part for percussion _
neither brass nor percussion was featured in ``Satyagraha.' ``The
orchestras for the trilogy complement each other, which works out
well from the practical point of view when it comes to rehearsal.''
</P>
<P>
   The score contains several episodes that ought to appeal to the
Lyric's backbone, the mainstream operatic audience, including
Akhnaten's ``Hymn to the Sun'' (which is sung in English _ the rest
of the opera's libretto, assembled by Glass, Shalom Goldman, Robert
Israel, and Richard Riddell, is sung in Akkadian, Egyptian, and
Hebrew; there is also some spoken text in English, drawn from
Frommer's tourist guide to Egypt). There is a ravishing duet
between Akhnaten and Nefertiti, and a remarkable trio at the end of
the first act for Akhnaten, Nefertiti, and Queen Tye. ``I worked
out that trio with Paul Esswood so that when you listen, you might
not be able to tell who is singing which part, mezzo, soprano, and
countertenor; doing the cross-writing was very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   In an amusing postscript to a lively conversation, Glass spoke
briefly about his next operatic project. ``I'm working on `The
Penal Colony,' based on Kafka, which will open in Seattle in
August. Herbert Perry, who was in `Orphee,' will be in it, and it
will be directed by JoAnne Akalaitis _ you will remember her
because she did so much work at the American Repertory Theatre.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed I did remember her for that _ but I also remember her as
the wife of Philip Glass. ``I've had such a long relationship with
her as a composer,'' he replied, ``that I sometimes forget I was
married to her! We have two children, but our real and lasting
relationship is an artistic one. I did a lot of Shakespeare with
her, and wrote the music for all her Mabou Mines pieces back in the
'60s and early '70s. We haven't done an opera together since 1983,
when she did `The Photographer.' She's a very interesting woman. .
. .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
