<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-LONDON-2TAKES-BOS     01-24 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-LONDON-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREETING THE MILLENNIUM OUTSIDE THE DOME 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A thousand years ago, at the last millennium,
Romanesque churches and cathedrals were going up all over Europe,
all dedicated to the glory of a Christian God and the sacrifice of
his son.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Britain has marked the new millennium with a
$1.6 billion dome, paid for with National Lottery money, dedicated
to the glory of absolutely everything. Looking like a giant skull
pierced with spikes, the Millennium Dome's interior is a sprawling
mess divided into ``Zones'' that are superficial nods to every
aspect of life on planet Earth: ``Body,'' ``Mind,'' ``Talk,''
``Play,'' ``Money,'' and so on, all linked by stairs and catwalks,
and interspersed with commercial enterprises from McDonald's to
oyster bars.
</P>
<P>
   The art and architecture of those Romanesque churches had
purpose: The nave directed you to the altar; the statues encouraged
you to venerate saints. The Millennium Dome's most disturbing
aspect is its utter lack of purpose and direction, its namby-pamby
unwillingness to take any stand on anything _ including design.
</P>
<P>
   During my week and a half in London, just after New Year's, the
Dome made headlines every day, in every British paper, virtually
all the stories reveling in nastiness. Critic Adrian Searle got the
ball rolling last fall, writing in ``The Guardian'' that ``It has
beenmy millennium fantasy that the artist Christo will gift-wrap
the Dome for New Year's Eve, and that we mustn't unwrap it until
about August 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions swirling around the unwieldy structure is
its fate after its scheduled one-year stint as mega-attraction.
It's not a space that lends itself to many uses. You can see it as
the Disneyesque theme park it already resembles, or maybe a
convention center, or maybe just a colossal objet, like the Eiffel
Tower, which was also intended to be temporary. Meanwhile, at least
on the day of my visit, the predicted crowds were not queuing up to
pay the Dome's $32-a-person entry fee.
</P>
<P>
   It's vast _ more than three times the size of the Colosseum in
Rome, and, the promotional literature tells you, big enough to hold
1,495 blue whales, although you can't imagine why they'd want to
live there. Despite the size, I can't recall ever being in a more
cluttered or claustrophobic environment. Dozens of designers
contributed to the interior; visual discord is the result. The
exterior, for all the eccentricity of those mastlike spikes
anchoring what is the world's largest roof, is more unified, thanks
to the Richard Rogers Partnership, the chief architects. And the
approach via the new North Greenwich underground station is a
marvel of comfort, convenience, and good design. Exiting the train,
you find yourself in a hall clad in gleaming dark-blue mosaics: Now
here's something that does evoke the mystical interior of a
Romanesque church.
</P>
<P>
   There is a paltry public-art component at the Dome, a few works
by such distinguished Brits as Richard Wilson and Anish Kapoor.
Most are swamped by their surroundings; even the super-friendly
guides (who outnumbered the paying customers when I arrived)
couldn't direct me to the art. An unmissable exception was Antony
Gormley's 80-foot-tall ``Quantum Cloud,'' a figure poised on the
remains of a jetty in the Thames, composed of 3,500 square steel
tubes, a bristling mass that magnetizes into a human being at the
center. Gormley's Everymen are big without blustering: His 65-foot
``Angel of the North'' looms protectively over the A1 highway in
the north of England, where 90,000 people drive past it each day.
``Quantum Cloud'' has been dubbed ``The Hedgehog,'' but to my mind,
it's a dazzling dissection of matter and man.
</P>
<P>
   You'd hardly know from the Dome, which is earnestly
multicultural, that there's still an official Church of England.
And the idea that the millennium celebrates a particular religious
event is all but buried. The ``Faith Zone'' represents every
religious sect with more than three believers, and spirals to an
exhausted conclusion in an oval room by the American artist James
Turrell. Turrell has spent 20 years turning an extinct Arizona
volcano into a maze of tunnels, pools, and places to watch the
moon. His Dome piece is typical in its perceptual disorientation _
you're sitting in it, yet you can't judge its size or even its
shape _ but Turrell's usual serenity is undermined by the sound of
the carnival chaos outside.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Rest Zone,'' meanwhile, reads like a corruption of a real
Turrell. It's a huge, curvy white womb room where you sprawl on
undulating, couchlike walls. Changing lighting effects and a
soothing soundtrack of gongs and echoes complete the atmosphere.
``Rest'' is what I felt the need of half an hour into my Dome
experience. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A bevy of collectors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, advertising mogul Charles Saatchi, he of the
recent ``Sensation!'' sensation, was one of the few significant
contemporary collectors in London. Now there are many, thanks in
part to the cultivation efforts of the Tate Gallery, which has to
think ahead to filling its vast new Tate Modern, opening in May on
the South Bank of the Thames. (I'll write separately about the
Tate, which is poised to become the most exciting new museum in
Europe.)
</P>
<P>
   There are dedicated collectors on a sub-Saatchi stratum, too.
One of them, Gordon Campbell Gray, owns One Aldwych, the erstwhile
Edwardian newspaper building he's converted into one of London's
top new hotels, and filled with a collection of 368 (and counting)
artworks he selected himself, after ditching three art consultants.
The hotel lobby is dominated by Andre Wallace's sculpture ``Boatman
With Oars,'' a chunky figure wedged into a bathtub-size boat,
grasping 10-foot oars that stretch into a giant V. Sitting right on
the floor, the ``Boatman'' becomes a fifth at a table otherwise
seating four. You wonder what conversations he overhears.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of what Campbell Gray owns he's bought directly
from artists: He's an habitue of open studio events in London's
East End. ``I have almost no artists anyone's heard of,'' he says
proudly, pointing to several postindustrial, rather gloomy
Sheffield townscapes by Richard Bartle: Campbell Gray's patronage
has enabled Bartle to give up his day job as a roofer and paint
full time. In One Aldwych's Indigo Restaurant is a particularly
daring choice, given the context: Tracey Davidson's ``Toast for
breakfast, toast for lunch, toast for tea and more . . . '' _ 192
slices of burnt toast sunk into wax, an homage to Davidson's youth,
when her father was in prison and her mother so short of money she
fed her children toast at every meal.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of fine food at Indigo, and to work it off,
One Aldwych offers a spa and pool where another provocative artwork
is installed: Pol Bury's relief of white arrows on a blue ground,
some with poor posture and bulgy midriffs, as if in need of a
workout, and one that's supermodel perfect. It's the only work
Campbell Gray has ever bought at auction: He paid about $10,000 for
it at Sotheby's, on a whim. ``I'm not safe to be let loose in an
auction house,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
