<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-LONDON-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     01-24 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-LONDON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LONDON: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around the corner from One Aldwych is the newly and glamorously
refurbished Royal Opera House at Covent Garden. Across the street
from the hotel is the Courtauld Gallery, which contains, among
other things, one of the world's great caches of Impressionist and
Post-Impressionist art, including Manet's ``Bar at the
Folies-Bergere.'' The Courtauld is housed in Somerset House, one of
England's most important 18th-century Georgian buildings, currently
under a restoration scheduled for completion in this millennial
year. (In architectural terms, the Brits took the millennium more
seriously than any other country, raising more than $6 billion for
various construction and restoration projects.) The facade of
Somerset House impresses; the vast courtyard is even more dazzling,
surrounded by majestic wings that were the first home to the Royal
Academy of Arts, which opened in 1780.
</P>
<P>
   In 1837, the Academy decamped to the 18th-century splendor of
Burlington House, on Piccadilly, where it's remained ever since,
steadily outgrowing its reputation for stodginess during the 23
years it's been led by exhibitions secretary Norman Rosenthal.
During Rosenthal's tenure, spectacularly popular shows ranging from
``Monet in the 20th Century'' (organized by Boston curator Paul
Tucker) to ``Sensation!'' to ``Africa: The Art of a Continent''
have drawn record crowds. (The irony of staging the most
comprehensive-ever examination of African art in a British building
that reeks of Empire occurred to not a few observers.) The smaller
of the two current shows at the RA is ``Amazons of the
Avant-Garde,'' up through Feb. 6, and transferring to New York's
Guggenheim Museum in June. It's a stab at catching up with the
women artists of early-20th-century Russian art, overshadowed by
male colleagues the caliber of Kasimir Malevich. The women in the
show _ Alexandra Exter, Natalia Goncharova, Liubov Popova, Olga
Rozanova, Varvara Stepanova, and Nadezhda Udaltsova _ were no
slouches, either. Their experiments with Cubism, Futurism, and
Suprematism were bold. Goncharova's ``Evangelists'' series of gaunt
Biblical figures, darkly outlined in the manner of Rouault, were
deemed sacrilegious by the Moscow censor. Popova, working in an
extremely sophisticated variation of Cubism, was the most
experimental, the least tied to her Russian roots. Rozanova, the
only one of the six who never visited Europe, developed the purest
abstract style of them all. As impressive as their individual
accomplishments as painters is their existence as a group of women
artists who would inspire others decades later. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Royal treatment &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Academy's nod to the year 2000 is ``1900: Art at the
Crossroads,'' in London through April 3, and moving to New York's
Guggenheim in May. Through more than 250 paintings and sculptures,
the curators take a focused look at the years just before and after
the Paris World's Fair, the biggest international event of 1900,
one that showed off a brave new world of art and technology that
was not already accessible on the Internet and television, as the
world of the Millennium Dome is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art at the Crossroads'' is a great counterpoint to the current
``ModernStarts'' exhibition at the Museum of Modern Art in New
York, although nowhere near as imaginative as the MoMA show, which
brings photography, advertising, industrial design, furniture, and
even a subway entrance into the mix, to show cross-currents in the
art and design world of 1880-1920. ``Crossroads'' may open with
Rodin's iconic ``The Kiss,'' but it's dominated by figurative
painting in many guises, a great deal of it academic, some of it
edging up to abstraction. It's fun to see what was prized a century
ago _ established masters such as Cezanne, upstarts like Picasso
and Kandinsky, and artists who now seem like nonentities.
</P>
<P>
   Artists from 28 countries, from Iceland to Japan to Australia,
were represented at the Paris Fair. Pluralism is likewise the RA
show's theme, along with the idea that Impressionism wasn't the
sole parent of Modernism, that there wasn't a tidy progression of
styles.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow Homer's dignified starlit close-up of a sailor, ``The
Lookout _ All's Well,'' on loan from the Boston Museum of Fine
Arts, holds up well against Alfred Guillou's overwrought 1892
``Farewell,'' in which two drowning lovers draped on an overturned
boat meet for a final kiss. She's already lost her blouse, poor
thing, perhaps a painterly ploy to attract turn-of-the-century
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In a room of portraits _ the show is arranged thematically _ one
of the most radical is Russian painter Michail Vrubel's ``Portrait
of Nadeschda Sabela-Vrubel at the Piano,'' composed of discrete
splotches of paint, thickly laid on, barely describing a figure.
Next to it hangs Sargent's ``Mrs. Carl Meyer and Her Children,''
recently shown in Boston, which, except for its bird's-eye
perspective, is all silken conservatism by comparison; it reminds
you how unadventurous Sargent could be.
</P>
<P>
   The wackiest work in the show is Leon Frederic's giant triptych
``The Stream,'' in which hundreds of naked babies tumble forward
from an idyllic landscape of waterfalls and birch forests. The
oddest label accompanies Henry Ossawa Tanner's ``The
Annunciation,'' in which the angel is represented only by light and
the Virgin slouches casually. Tanner's is the only label I noticed
with any biographical material: It identifies him as an
African-American, which seems a self-righteous touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossroads'' ends with a room of self-portraits from the age
that saw the dawn of psychoanalysis. Most radical of all,
surprisingly, is by that arch-academic, Jean-Leon Gerome, whose
``Optician,'' an ad for that profession, shows the artist's eyes in
a pair of disembodied glasses. The painting was later praised as a
forerunner of Surrealism by none other than Salvador Dali.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
