<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-WATSON-BOS &LR;      01-24 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WATSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR `ANGELA'S ASHES' EMILY WATSON SHELVES HER `MAD SCREAMER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yes, Emily Watson says, she's playing a pained
character again: Frank McCourt's struggling mother in the film
version of ``Angela's Ashes,'' based on McCourt's recollections of
growing up poor in Limerick, Ireland. But this time there's a big
difference. Since bursting upon the film world in 1996, as the
devout, tormented wife of a paralyzed oil-rig worker in ``Breaking
the Waves,'' Watson proceeded to portray a woman smothered by
Ireland's civil strife in ``The Boxer'' and the late cellist
Jacqueline du Pre, beset by emotional pressures and multiple
sclerosis in ``Hilary and Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   To exorcise those heavy-duty roles and the psychic toll attached
to them, Watson has come to refer to them as ``mad screamers.'' But
Angela McCourt, trapped in endless rain and poverty, constantly
struggling to keep her kids fed, is the opposite of a screamer,
says Watson, fighting jet lag while soldiering through a round of
interviews. Soon she'll phone her husband, writer-actor Jack
Waters, at their home in London, where she snatched a few hours of
sleep before heading to Manhattan from a shoot in Budapest. Angela
is loaded with strong feelings, Watson continues, ``but they're
never expressed, they're not revealed. There's no explosion.
There's no kind of emotional payoff. It's just a slow burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is true to life,'' Watson says. ``You know. You don't
get your third act for Christmas. You don't get a big dramatic
climax in real life. And this is a true story. It travels a very
direct and pure route from the pain of Frank McCourt about his own
life. No producer has meddled with the honesty of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge working with the children. Angela had seven
children altogether. Three died. When you ask me if Angela was a
defeated woman, I have to say yes and no. She has a nervous
breakdown at the word go, really, when she loses her first child,
and then struggling to keep her head above water. The material is
so powerful, it's bewildering. At the end of the day, Alan (Parker,
the director) would say, `Great work,' but something would be
nagging at the back of your mind. Then you'd think, `Oh yeah, my
baby died.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela does keep her family together. She manages somehow to
feed them and keep them alive. She's very human, very fallible. She
has a very strong mother-fighting-for-her-children instinct. Her
life is very much a life of self-sacrifice for her children. And
then her husband just sort of drifts out of their life. There's not
even a goodbye. The biggest challenge was trying to convey all
Angela was feeling without the outbursts. With no outbursts. It's
interesting because everything in the book is perceived from
Frank's point of view. Her perception comes from somebody else. So
in a sense I had to take her away from Frank and make her my own.
Tens of millions of people have an idea of Angela, and you can
never compete with that. You just have to approach it from a point
of, well, this is how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other challenges attached to the specifics of
personifying a character with whom millions of readers strongly
identify. Watson, costar Robert Carlyle, and director-adapter
Parker realized they would not have the luxury of working things
out on the set or improvising because they were acting with
children, for whom things had to be clear, defined, and direct.
Almost all the work of character formation, therefore, had to be
done off the set in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point of departure for a role is the sound of the voice.
That, and the kind of physical energy,'' Watson says. ``I went to
Limerick, just trying to connect. I struggled for a few days to
find the rhythm. There's a rhythm of Irish construction, and it's
very different from English. The Irish just have a turn of phrase.
It's just never prosaic in any way. So it was literally finding the
physical voice, not as mimicry, but because within the sound of the
physical voice is encapsulated almost everything you need to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   What Watson didn't foresee was how tired she'd get at the end of
a day of shooting that required her to hold baby twins in her arms.
Also, there was the real-life Angela's tobacco habit: Every day,
Watson smoked 40 Woodbines, Angela's favorite brand.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, whose face can encompass an enormous range of
expression, is also prominent in Tim Robbins's current ``Cradle
Will Rock,'' playing a jobless, homeless street person who ends up
singing the lead in Marc Blitzstein's 1937 social-protest opera _
and making theatrical history when the show goes on in the face of
government efforts to shut it down. Watson loved the passion of the
project and the passion of the era. ``I'm surprised that more
Americans don't know the story of censorship in America in the
1930s,'' Watson says. ``Every city was doing plays about
up-to-the-minute events. There was all this upheaval and unrest,
and the theater was right there dealing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain irony, Watson is the first to admit, in her
having been catapulted to prominence by a series of roles depicting
women struggling against their surroundings. ``I had a very happy
childhood,'' says Watson, who grew up in the north of London. Her
mother was a teacher, her father an architect. ``I had a particular
combination of being quite protected, and in a liberal and
imaginative atmosphere. In a way, I feel safe. I'm able to take it,
as it were, in very difficult situations. I think you have to allow
yourself the possibility of being absolutely floored and not
protected by something.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Watson doesn't look forward to working the sunny side
of the street for a bit. She plays the title role in Alan Rudolph's
upcoming ``Trixie,'' describing it as ``a would-be private
detective in Chicago who's several sandwiches short of a picnic.''
The film she's shooting in Europe, ``The Luzhin Defense,'' based on
a Nabokov adaptation, finds Watson playing a character she
describes as ``a bit of a first for me, a nice girl, from a
chess-playing Russian emigre family living in the Italian lake
district. I fall in love with John Turturro's unsuitably wild,
crazy, genius chess player. He's the mad screamer in this one. It's
nice to have somebody else do it!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
