<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR OF LOVE AIMS TO MAKE GORE THE DEMOCRATIC NOMINEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Despite the risk, organized labor is going all out for Al Gore
_ in New Hampshire and across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that labor supporters have been out in force for
Monday's Iowa caucuses may be contributing to the huge lead Gore is
holding over Bill Bradley, his rival for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   As Hugh Winebrenner, a political specialist at Drake University
in Des Moines, said in a recent New York Times interview, ``The
Democratic Party in Iowa depends on the activism of organized
labor. Labor will play a very significant role in the caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor officials say that Iowa has 184,000 union workers; that
means that one out of every seven workers is union-affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign aides have acknowledged that labor is playing
a significant role in Iowa. As one spokesperson said, ``Their
organized clout is real.'' He said that Bradley had tried to enlist
their support,``but they went the other way. We respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore is expected to win in Iowa, the stakes are higher for
him, and for organized labor, in New Hampshire, where only one out
of 10 workers is a union member.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore victory in New Hampshire would be viewed as a victory for
organized labor and working families. If Gore loses, it may viewed
by his opponents and some political pundits as a big loss for
labor.
</P>
<P>
   But national labor officials, including John Sweeney, president
of the AFL-CIO, believe it's worth the risk to make a big
commitment to Gore even in New Hampshire, where organized labor is
not as strong as in other New England states.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown Gore closing the gap on Bradley there,
if not moving slightly ahead. Much of Gore's momentum comes from
his performances in debates against Bradley. But labor's efforts
may also be paying off. Activists from Massachusetts, Maine, and
Connecticut have gone to New Hampshire to canvass on behalf of the
Gore campaign, and they believe their efforts have contributed to
his recent edge.
</P>
<P>
   As one Massachusetts labor activist pointed out, about 20
percent of the New Hampshire residents who are union members
actually belong to locals headquartered in Massachusetts, and the
vast majority of them are expected to back Gore. In addition,
political activists from national as well as local AFL-CIO offices
have been working in New Hampshire on Gore's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rogers, political director for the Massachusetts
AFL-CIO, noted that Sweeney's commitment to Gore began early, has
intensified in recent weeks, and will continue throughout primary
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been moving some volunteers up there for the past few
weeks,'' Rogers said, ``and the response among unions based on our
phone banks is very good. The union density in New Hampshire is not
as strong as it is in Massachusetts, so that limits us to a certain
extent.''
</P>
<P>
   On a national level, labor leaders have been viewing the growth
of union membership to 16.5 million in 1999 _ an increase of
265,000 workers from the year before _ as a growth in political
clout for the 2000 election. Sweeney himself predicted that, with
this increase, the nation is ``going to see the largest and most
significant activity that grass-roots workers have exercised in any
political election.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is working to counter huge corporate spending on
its apparent chosen candidate, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a survey from the Center for Responsive Politics, a
political think tank, businesses contributed $666.6 million to
candidates and parties in the 1998 election, while unions
contributed $60.8 million, an 11-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO attempted to counter this spending mismatch by
bringing more working families into the political process. That
mobilization helped Democrats gain five seats in the House in the
1998 election, and prompted Sweeney to say that those elections
ushered in ``a new era of people-powered politics.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Sweeney and other labor leaders are also aware that if
Gore loses in states where labor is even stronger than in New
Hampshire, states such as Massachusetts, it could further diminish
the political clout of organized labor, as well as demoralize
unions and working families backing Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Gore loses New Hampshire, organized labor is not
going to throw in the towel. Gore is still expected to win the
Democratic nomination. And what Sweeney and other labor leaders are
looking toward is the Gore-Bush showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor's active involvement in the 2000 election sends
a strong message that its growing numbers for Gore may carry as
much political weight as the number of dollars filling Bush's
campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
