<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORAL LEADERSHIP CALLS FOR TAKING A STAND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Confederate flag in South Carolina and
ballot access in New York may be totally unrelated issues in the
real world. But in the supercharged atmosphere of presidential
politics, they have found a common target in George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   And the Republican front-runner's efforts to dodge both weaken
his own vow to usher in an era of moral leadership in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   To the Texas governor, a growing controversy over the
Confederate banner is a mine field. Whatever his personal feelings,
he has repeatedly refused to say whether South Carolina should
continue to fly the flag over its statehouse. It's a local issue to
be decided by South Carolinians, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The flag that represents slavery and racism to millions of
Americans represents something else _ heritage _ to many of the
voters that Bush is wooing in South Carolina's Feb. 19 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by some New Yorkers to keep Arizona Sen. John McCain,
Bush's main competitor for the GOP nomination, off the March 7 New
York primary ballot also are a local issue, Bush contends.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, pass the buck to someone else, he insists.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Bush is correct. The people of South Carolina,
through their elected state officeholders, should have the right to
decide what to put atop their state capitol.
</P>
<P>
   And the people of New York, within constitutional restraints,
should be able to set the criteria that political candidates must
meet to qualify for the ballot in their state.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's ``local issues'' dodge also is pretty thin.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, New York has one of the toughest _ if not the
toughest _ ballot access laws in the country. Bush supporters there
are largely behind the effort to disqualify McCain's petitions in
17 of New York's 31 congressional districts, and if they are
successful, Bush would largely benefit.
</P>
<P>
   So it's disingenuous of Bush to try to suggest that he is a long
arm's length removed from a ``local'' ballot fight.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has repeatedly vowed to avoid ``negative'' campaigning. But
what's more negative than an effort to keep your main GOP opponent
off the ballot in one of the largest states?
</P>
<P>
   In hundreds of campaign speeches around the country, moreover,
the Texas governor has vowed to usher in the ``responsibility'' era
in the United States and set a high moral leadership tone in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   He ends virtually every speech by raising his right hand and
promising to uphold the ``dignity'' of the nation's top office.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to providing moral leadership and dignity in
the Oval Office than keeping the presidential hands off White House
interns, telling other young Americans to behave and vowing to lock
up criminals who fail the responsibility test.
</P>
<P>
   An aspiring moral leader also is someone who practices fair
play, who is not afraid to win _ or lose _ in a fair election and
doesn't pretend to look the other way while an opponent is being
victimized by unnecessarily restrictive rules.
</P>
<P>
   And he or she shouldn't be afraid to take a public stand on
divisive issues.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's Confederate flag is being singled out partly
because of that state's early role in the presidential nominating
process. But remnants of the Confederacy _ symbols of racism to
some and history to others _ are prominent throughout the South.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate battle flag is a dominant part of the Georgia
state flag, and a memorial to Confederate heroes is one of the
largest monuments on the grounds of the Texas Capitol in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain, who had ancestors who fought for the South during
the Civil War, has been as uncomfortable as Bush on the Confederate
flag issue.
</P>
<P>
   Historic monuments have their place. But flying the Confederate
banner atop a state's most important public building is going too
far. It's an affront _ intended or not _ to millions of Americans
whose Southern heritage was one of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   As indicated earlier, South Carolina has a right to keep the
flag atop its statehouse. But presidential candidates also have a
moral obligation to tell us what they think about it, because it's
an issue of much more than local importance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
