<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUS SHIFTS TO THE LEGACY OF CARDINAL JOHN O'CONNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For New York's Catholics, the big news out of Rome
this week was that there was no news at all.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone had assumed that Cardinal John O'Connor, the
city's, and possibly the country's, most controversial cardinal in
more than 30 years, would be leaving his post.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he seemed to be giving a farewell address last
Saturday at a gala to celebrate his 80th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will soon be evicted,'' he joked to the hundreds of
religious and political luminaries who turned out at a midtown
ballroom in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by noon Tuesday, the time when popes traditionally announce
personnel changes, O'Connor still held the keys to St. Patrick's
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   With his declining health, O'Connor is clearly approaching his
final days as cardinal. That has prompted many observers, Roman
Catholic and otherwise, to reflect on the future of the New York
Archdiocese, especially in a city where Catholics now consist not
so much of Irish and Italians, as was the case in O'Connor's youth,
but of Latinos and Asians, who see themselves little-reflected in
the church's higher orders.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, when he was appointed to lead the archdiocese _ a
realm that includes 2.3 million Catholics in New York City, the
surrounding suburbs, and up through the Hudson Valley _ O'Connor
has cut an imposing, at times contradictory image.
</P>
<P>
   --He has vigorously condemned abortion and gay and lesbianism,
but has set up AIDS clinics and anonymously volunteered in them,
washing patients' hair and emptying bedpans.
</P>
<P>
   --He has riled liberals by linking himself with conservative
political causes, but he has marched with labor unions and
advocated an increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   --He has pushed the church to acknowledge, and apologize for,
its history's darker episodes, yet he has engaged in deception over
some of his own political positions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor has submitted his resignation in each of the last five
years, but the pope has turned it down. Recently, though, the
cardinal has been ailing. After surgery for a brain tumor, he was
too weak to attend several Sunday Masses and stumbled twice when he
did.
</P>
<P>
   A cardinal loses his voting rights in the Vatican councils upon
turning 80. Maybe this time, some were guessing, the pope would let
him go.
</P>
<P>
   Rome's silence this week means he will stay, but nobody knows
for how long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
First, not lasting, impression
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor made it clear he would be a very public cardinal from
the moment he ascended to the post 16 years ago. Unlike nearly all
his predecessors, who spent many years in New York before assuming
the helm, O'Connor had been a bishop in Scranton, Pa., and before
that, vicar of the US armed forces. Perhaps because he was new, he
made bad impressions right off.
</P>
<P>
   First, he compared abortion to the Holocaust, an argument that
many Jews considered tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he lashed out at Geraldine Ferraro, the local Democratic
congresswoman who was running for vice president, for her advocacy
of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Ferraro had provoked the attack, telling a
reporter that Catholic dogma was not monolithic on the question.
O'Connor fired back: ``Geraldine Ferraro has said some things about
abortion, relative to Catholic teaching, that are not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he intended it, his remarks were widely
interpreted as an endorsement of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   This impression was reinforced when he agreed to distribute a
voters' guide on local school-board elections prepared by the Rev.
Pat Robertson's Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, through his press spokesman, declined to be
interviewed for this story. But he admitted to The New York Times
in 1993 that he ``possibly'' made mistakes early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got off to a bad start,'' recalled Margaret O'Brien
Steinfels, editor of the lay Catholic magazine Commonweal. ``He was
a cultural conservative, and New York is the most culturally
liberal city in America. But then he made one of the most
spectacular comebacks imaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   The comeback was made largely through his budding friendship
with the Jewish mayor of New York, Edward I. Koch.
</P>
<P>
   In his midtown law office last week, Koch recalled of O'Connor,
``He told me his major role would be to strengthen ties between
Catholics and Jews. Time and time again, he'd say he was
spiritually a Semite, meaning a Jew. He'd mention in his sermons
that Mary and Jesus were Jews, most of the apostles were Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he went to Jerusalem and, setting aside his prepared
speech, apologized for the Church's history of anti-Semitism. He
was the chief advocate in persuading the Vatican to recognize
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He also turned around many of his liberal critics with his
support for labor, though this should not have been a surprise.
Growing up in a working-class neighborhood of Philadelphia, he saw
his father give fiery pro-union speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Nat Hentoff, the Village Voice columnist who wrote a positive
biography of the cardinal a few years ago, recalled their first
meeting. It was during a strike of Catholic hospital workers. ``I
was waiting outside his office,'' Hentoff said, ``and I heard him
yelling, `Over my dead body are there going to be scabs in my
hospital!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hentoff contrasted him with Cardinal Francis Spellman, who ran
the archdiocese with an iron fist from 1937 to 1967. ``When the
gravediggers in a Catholic cemetery went on strike, Spellman
drafted seminarians to go dig graves,'' he said. ``Spellman himself
pushed the first shovel.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's approach to his job has been very different _ partly
because the times are different, partly because he is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Powerhouse' legacy
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's nickname was ``The Powerhouse.'' The city's
Democratic Party was run out of political clubhouses. The party's
ticket for the top offices _ mayor, comptroller, and City Council
chairman _ always included one Catholic and one Jew, and Spellman
picked the Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Hentoff noted, ``Spellman could stop any legislation in the
State House that he didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Spellman died, in 1967, New York's Catholic
population had shifted and Democratic politics had changed. No
archbishop could have such power as he had, so his handpicked
successor, Cardinal Terence Cooke, took on a quieter, more pastoral
role, rarely speaking out in public, attending mainly to the
growing number of poor immigrants filling the pews.
</P>
<P>
   When Cooke died in 1983, and O'Connor got the call from Rome,
the atmosphere had changed again.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Macciarola, president of St. Francis College and a former
deputy mayor to Koch who had many dealings with the cardinal, said,
``With O'Connor, you got the sense that the pope had sent a
representative, at a time when he was demanding a higher level of
orthodoxy than before.''
</P>
<P>
   As a tone-setter, O'Connor started his reign by speaking out
strongly against abortion and gay and lesbianism in a city where
most Catholics were highly tolerant toward both.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time went on, as he grew more comfortable in his
position,'' Macciarola continued, ``you saw more reflection, a more
pastoral approach to his job.'' Hence his work with hospices, AIDS
clinics, and unions.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, O'Connor has become a more admired, even
trusted, figure. However, he has continued to draw criticism and
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Key omissions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when President Clinton offered clemency to
long-jailed members of a Puerto Rican nationalist terrorist group,
he cited O'Connor among those who had influenced him on the issue.
O'Connor rebutted this and attacked Clinton for being soft on
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal released the text of a letter he had sent US
Attorney Janet Reno, asking her merely ``to review'' the prisoners'
cases, not to shorten their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   However, New York Daily News columnist Juan Gonzalez revealed _
reluctantly, because he likes the cardinal _ that O'Connor had
omitted ``two key words'' in reciting his letter to Reno: He had
asked Reno to review their cases ``for pardon.'' As Gonzalez noted,
a pardon, which would wipe a person's criminal slate clean, is even
more forgiving than Clinton's offer.
</P>
<P>
   A more serious question about O'Connor's legacy concerns
Hispanics in another sense. Every archbishop or cardinal in the
history of the New York Archdiocese, including O'Connor, has been
of Irish or Italian descent, yet Dominicans, Puerto Ricans,
Haitians, and Asians are nearly the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern that the city's Catholic Church has not been
attentive to this new wave of immigrants,'' said Walter DelGrado,
head of the Audubon Partnership, a Dominican business group in
upper Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times poll last month indicated that while two-thirds
of all Catholics in the archdiocese have a favorable view of him,
fewer than half of its Hispanic Catholics do, mainly because they
pay little attention to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the influx of immigrants, the Catholic population in this
city is going to be growing again,'' said William Stein, a Catholic
historian who writes for City Journal. Whether the next cardinal
has much influence over them could depend on who _ or, perhaps
more, what _ he is. ``It would be interesting to see a cardinal
who's a power,'' Stein added, ``the way they used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
