   SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ In a decision that pleased
people who complain that money is corrupting American politics, the
Supreme Court ruled on Monday that state governments have the power
to limit campaign contributions to candidates in statewide
elections. The 6-3 decision in a closely watched case from Missouri
upheld the power of that state, and by extension other states, to
impose ceilings on how much individuals can give to office-seekers.
It also removed any lingering doubts about the legitimacy of the
$1,000 cap on contributions to candidates for federal office. By
Linda Greenhouse.
