<P>
   COKE-JAPAN (Walnut Creek, Calif.) _ For years, Japanese
consumers have had two Coca-Colas to choose from _ identical except
for their packaging, but at vastly different prices. There is the
locally bottled brand, labeled Coca-Cola, and ``American Coke,''
labeled Coca-Cola Classic _ bottled in America and shipped abroad.
Despite the thousands of miles American Coke has to travel, it is
usually cheaper than Japanese-made Coke. That price gap is at the
heart of a complex legal confrontation between Coca-Cola and two
small California exporter now nearing trial in a federal courtroom
in San Francisco. The stakes are high. Coke makes more money per
can in Japan than it does anywhere else in the world. And the
lawsuit could have vast implications for the way Coca-Cola does
business with bottlers around the world. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MERGER () _ Consumer products giant Procter and Gamble
announced it had called off merger talks with Warner-Lambert and
American Home Products Monday because of too much press
speculation. In particular, the company blamed leaks over the
three-way talks for the sharp decline in its stock price, which has
fallen about 10 dollars since news of the discussions emerged on
Wednesday last week. (Summary from wires) By Dana Canedy.
</P>
