<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-HEART-BOS &LR;      01-24 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART DOESN'T SKIP A BEAT IN SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Dr. Robert Lancey of UMass Memorial Health
Care in Worcester, Mass. was ready to perform a quadruple bypass
operation on 75-year-old Olga Andujar. As he opened up her chest,
his assistants extracted a vein from her leg, which was about to be
used to reroute blood past a blockage in a diseased vessel.
</P>
<P>
   But the operation then deviated dramatically from the norm.
Lancey did not hook up Andujar to a piano-sized heart-lung machine,
which temporarily stops the heart, often for an hour or more as it
oxygenates and pumps blood through the body. Instead, Lancey sewed
the vein to a beating heart, a feat he could not accomplish were it
not for a one-inch square plastic device.
</P>
<P>
   The device compresses the blocked vessel so it doesn't bleed,
and stablizes the surrounding area so the surgeon can graft the
healthy vessel to the blocked one. All the while, the heart thumps
normally.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, called ``off-pump'' or ``beating-heart'' surgery,
is one of several minimally-invasive methods now being used to
minimize the trauma and side effects of bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   After a bypass operation, a third to half of patients suffer
from cognitive problems ranging from short-term confusion and
memory loss to major strokes. Some studies have suggested that
these problems stem not from the surgery itself, but from stopping
the heart using the heart-lung machine.
</P>
<P>
   As blood is pumped outside the body and recirculated by the
machine, inflammatory changes occur in the body's tissue linings,
which can lead to dangerous fluid buildup. And as the machine
artificially oxygenates the blood, bubbles and debris enter the
circulation, which activate platelets that can form clots, blocking
small blood vessels, which can potentially trigger a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians say beating-heart surgery is best for older and
sicker patients, who may suffer the most serious side effects from
being on a heart-lung machine.
</P>
<P>
   The technique, which Lancey started doing 18 months ago and now
uses in 90 percent of the bypass operations he performs, is one of
the latest advances in heart bypass surgery. But, ironically, it's
also a throwback to the days before the invention of the heart-lung
machine: operating on a beating heart.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that of the approximately 360,000 coronary bypass
operations performed annually in the US, beating-heart devices are
used in about 18 percent of all cases. But since the technique has
only been widely used within the past three years, there have been
only a few studies, most of them small, that have compared the
outcomes of beating-heart surgery to those of conventional bypass
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The data so far indicate that patients that have the procedure
have shorter hospital stays and recovery periods.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lancey said the procedure is difficult to master.
``It's a mindset change. Surgeons are used to working on a heart
that doesn't move,'' he said. Because the heart pulses in all
different directions, it makes the operation particularly tricky,
Lancey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more difficult; probably my blood pressure goes
higher when I do it,'' said Dr. Sari Aranki, a cardiac surgeon at
Brigham and Women's Hospital in Boston. Of the 800 patients at the
Brigham who undergo bypass surgery, the off-pump technique is
reserved for the 50 to 80 sickest or oldest ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One heart surgeon at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in
Boston, Dr. William Cohn, invented one of the several surgical
tools for the beating-heart technique using $5.99 Stop and Shop
soup spoons as a model.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn and Beth Israel patented the product, and Genzyme Corp., a
Cambridge, Mass. biotechnology company, bought the right to license
the technology and started selling it in 1998. Other companies,
including Cardiothoracic Systems, Inc., in California and Medtronic
Inc., in Minnesota, also have cardiac stabilizers on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Before the heart-lung machine was invented in 1953, some
surgeons tried to accurately stitch vessels onto a moving heart,
but most considered it too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In bypass surgery, a segment of a vein from the leg and part of
a chest artery are sewn onto a coronary artery above its blocked
portion, and then to the normal part of the artery below the
obstruction. Blood then ``bypasses'' the blocked part, like a road
detour around a construction site.
</P>
<P>
   While a few daring surgeons worldwide, in South America and
Europe, have tried techniques that kept the heart beating during
surgery, it wasn't until the early 1990s that American physicians
became interested in the technique.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, an earlier version of the off-pump surgery was
nicknamed ``keyhole surgery,'' because a small incision was made on
the front of the chest and a surgical tool was used to stablize the
area of the heart where the surgeon sewed the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a lot of people jumped on the
``minimally-invasive'' bandwagon, said Beth Israel's Cohn, even
though early results were not very good, and it limited surgeons to
working on a single coronary artery. ``But it exposed us to
techniques on a beating heart, and we all realized that it was a
technologically possible hurdle,'' said Cohn.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, who has a metal shop in his basement, was intrigued with
the idea, and went to Johns Hopkins in 1996 to watch a couple of
the keyhole operations in which doctors used a device that looked
like a bent tuning fork, but he thought the surgery looked too
technically demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there must be a better way,'' Cohn said. So, he
bought a bunch of soup spoons, stayed up until 2 a.m. in his metal
shop cutting different holes in them, and started doing surgery on
pigs with his hand-made stabilizer.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme, like other companies, has hosted workshops for heart
surgeons to learn to use the device.
</P>
<P>
   But long-term studies still need to be done. For example, it is
unclear how long the grafts sewn on a beating heart will hold up.
``A lot of people are saying beating heart surgery will be the rule
rather than the exception. But I'm still waiting for the data,''
Cohn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
