<HEADLINE>
RESPONSIBLE FUNDS SHOW GOOD RETURNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Did you boycott Texaco when you heard about the tapes?
Did you start riding your bike when Houston's air became the
filthiest in the nation?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you don't take things quite that far, but you did stop
smoking after a loved one died of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Or did you feel better about buying Barbie dolls because
Mattel's top executive is a woman? Or cancel HBO because of the
cable channel's late-night adult programming?
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, we all use our ethics and values to guide
financial decisions. We spend money with companies that validate
our beliefs and avoid those that don't.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses know this and they spend billions of dollars to
market themselves as diverse, charitable, family-friendly,
environmentally conscious or any other trait that their target
consumers esteem.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years, small money-management firms have dug
beneath companies' public personas to see if they really are good
corporate citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual funds they run screen stocks for environmental
responsibility, consumer protection, fair employment policies and
health-conscious products, as well as financial performance and
earnings potential.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MARKET TAKES CONCEPT SERIOUSLY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has socially responsible investing been taken
seriously by Wall Street, which had dismissed the concept as losing
money to do good.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, that has been far from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by the Social Investment Forum, a trade group,
found that $2.16 trillion _ or one of every $8 invested in the
United States _ is invested using socially responsible guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Domini Social Equity, an index fund that tracks a socially
screened index of 400 stocks, has three- and five-year returns that
beat the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these funds do well because they tend to invest in
nonpolluting industries, such as technology and health care. And
value stocks that they avoid, such as tobacco manufacturers, have
fallen out of favor in the past few quarters of this bull market.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar, a mutual fund tracking company based in Chicago,
awarded 14 percent of the 80 socially responsible funds it follows
its highest rating of five stars, compared with just 10 percent of
all mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard, the nation's second-largest fund group, announced
plans last month to start a new index fund tied to a group of
stocks screened for their companies' social and environmental
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Socially responsible investing now has an air of
respectability, for lack of a better word, that it didn't have 10
years ago,'' says Emily Hall, a Morningstar editorial analyst.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, this method of stock and fund picking has been
associated with the polar opposite groups that espouse it. Some
investors have been turned off by liberal agendas condemning guns
and animal testing or conservative Christian vitriol against
abortion and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   And the ``holier than thou'' moniker doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   But socially responsible funds are starting to make it clear
that they are not a part of a monolithic movement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PROUD OF WHAT THEY OWN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a different idea of what is good and what isn't
and we're starting to see more funds clearly define themselves on
the socially responsible spectrum,'' says John Montgomery, manager
of the five-star Bridgeway Social Responsibility, a large-company
growth fund based in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Humane Society of the United States announced
last week it has teamed up with Salomon Brothers Asset Management
to launch a no-load portfolio for people concerned with animal
welfare issues.
</P>
<P>
   Niche funds that target a specific issue will make socially
responsible investing more relevant to a wider range of investors.
By being able to target values and skip over an array of issues
that are not a concern, investors will be more likely to put their
money where their beliefs are.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to get started in socially responsible investing is
through mutual funds. First, you need to know what you value and
what you disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Then, you have to decide if you want to reward companies for
having certain products or policies by making an investment, or do
you want to punish them by screening them out of your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of your convictions will also help you determine if
you want to become a shareholder activist and push a company to
adopt or change its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you need to decide if your ethical commitment includes a
willingness to pay more for your beliefs. On average, these funds
are smaller and charge more than the average fund.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeway Social Responsibility is an exception. It's an
actively managed fund with a total expense ratio of 1.5 percent and
a pledge to donate a portion of its profits to charity every year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you decide, examine funds and their investing
philosophies. Visit their Web sites and research them through at
www.morningstar.com, www.domini.com, www.socialinvest.org or
www.crosswalk.com.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, decide if the fund is a good investment. The rules of
responsible investing still apply. Whatever fund you choose, it
needs to be a good fit with your overall portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, socially responsible investors are shareholders who
take seriously their duties as part owners. They don't ignore their
consciences to concentrate on making as much money as possible
because they want to be proud of what they own.
</P>
<P>
   By having their undivided attention, Corporate America will be
better off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shannon Buggs invites comments and column ideas, but cannot offer
specific financial advice about individual situations. E-mail her
at shannon.buggsat)chron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
