<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE MANAGERS BETTER, STUDY SHOWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The old conventional wisdom is women aren't good
managers. They aren't tough enough. They don't play team sports, so
they have no idea how to work together in a common effort. Women
have a particularly hard time managing women, since one woman
doesn't like to work for another.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new conventional wisdom emerging. In a new kind of
workplace where employees are expected to use their brains as well
as their brawn, women make better managers. They relate better.
They coax better performance, instead of demanding it. They are
better able to motivate, not simply give orders.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect the truth is, men and women can be equally capable.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is evidence that in some specific kinds of
situations, women do make superior managers. The evidence isn't
conclusive. But it does bear thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   That's the conclusion of a study by three academics _ Nigel F.
Pierce and Nikala Lane of Cardiff University in Great Britain and
David W. Cravens of Texas Christian University in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SALES WAS THE ARENA EXAMINED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three studied the effectiveness of female sales managers at
an unnamed large British commercial directory publisher that
employs about 1,000 sales people. The trio interviewed both sales
people and their managers at a sample of its 102 sales offices.
</P>
<P>
   They chose the company because it used behavior, rather than
outcome-based, sales management. In outcome-based organizations,
sales people are not given specific direction by managers and are
primarily paid commissions. Behavior-based companies look not just
at sales but at establishing closer relationships with their
customers. They rely heavily on salaries for salespeople and
closely supervise them.
</P>
<P>
   The study compared results between teams headed by male and
female sales managers in a number of different areas. Here's what
they found:
</P>
<P>
   _ Female sales managers were much more likely to try to control
the behavior of their team. That was reported by both male and
female sales personnel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales teams led by female managers displayed higher job
involvement and lower job ambiguity _ a stressful situation in
which a person lacks clear direction about the organization's
expectations. They also felt less conflict about their roles in the
company, less job anxiety and displayed lower burnout rates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Female-led sales teams reported significantly higher levels of
job satisfaction and commitment to the company, and employees were
less likely to quit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FEMALE-LED TEAMS EXCELLED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sales teams led by females had higher levels of effectiveness.
There were substantial differences in work outcomes and sales unit
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Female sales people are likely to be more effective when
working for a female than a male sales manager. However, both male
and female sales people reported higher job satisfaction and
commitment to the organization when working for female, rather than
male, bosses. Surprisingly, male salespeople were less likely than
females to quit when they worked for a female, rather than a male,
sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this study has its limits when attempting to apply
its lessons everywhere. It's one company in another country.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of bias. The authors of the study
found none, but that doesn't mean it didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company might have been _ consciously or
unconsciously _ favoring female sales managers. Top managers might
have given female sales managers better people or better
territories, which could produce the finding of apparently superior
performance by female sales managers.
</P>
<P>
   Or conversely, the bias might have worked the other way. Only
the very best females got promoted to manager positions. If that
were the case, women should do a better job than male managers.
After all, males with much lower intrinsic skills would be promoted
to supervisory jobs, since they did not face the same high barrier
to promotion.
</P>
<P>
   However, if the findings are correct and universal, they lead to
some interesting thoughts. It used to be gospel that the macho
world of sales was one where women did not fit. But the rise of a
different kind of sales climate, where buyers and sellers are more
partner than adversary, could mean that macho is out and that the
traditionally female skill of nurturing is in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
