<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUE LIFE OF `MR. DEATH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Fred A. Leuchter Jr. is an unremarkable
looking man. Thinning hair, thick glasses, overeager. Under
ordinary circumstances, you'd never give him a second glance. But
none of the circumstances attached to the life of Fred A. Leuchter
Jr. are ordinary. Leuchter is the subject of Errol Morris's new
film, ``Mr. Death,'' and if you think that title may perhaps be a
little tabloid-y, consider the life and works of the man. Until the
early 1990s, he made a nice living as a self-taught execution
specialist, designing, maintaining, and repairing electric chairs,
gas chambers, lethal injection systems, and gallows. As capital
punishment was stepped up, Leuchter's death-chamber business grew.
</P>
<P>
   Leuchter saw himself as a modern Dr. Guillotine, offering a
quick, clean death instead of a messy one. Then he tripped over his
own hubris. In 1988, a neo-Nazi being brought to trial for
violating Canada's anti-hate law by denying that the Holocaust
happened called on Leuchter to bolster his defense. For a fee,
Leuchter went to Auschwitz, measuring what was left of the gas
chambers, looking for traces of cyanide gas in the bits of wall he
illegally chipped out and took away in plastic bags. Leuchter,
newly married, took his wife on the only documented honeymoon in
Auschwitz. Leuchter concluded that the Holocaust couldn't have
happened. His report was never allowed in court. But it received
wide circulation. Leuchter became a neo-Nazi poster boy.
</P>
<P>
   Leuchter also ruined himself. States where he had death-chamber
maintenance contracts let the contracts lapse. He was too much of a
hot potato. But not, however, for Morris, who tracked Leuchter down
by calling upon his skills as a private investigator, a job he
worked at before the filmmaking began and which provided key
elements in ``Vernon, Florida'' and Morris's breakthrough film,
``The Thin Blue Line.'' In
</P>
<P>
   1992, Morris persuaded Leuchter to be interviewed, one reason
being Morris's wish to test his new interviewing device, which he
calls the Interrotron and allows eye contact between subject and
interviewer. Leuchter talked willingly for hours, Morris says. On
and off, over the next several years, as this or that bit of
funding became available, Morris assembled the film piecemeal,
adding as well various experts and bits of documentary footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I shot that initial interview in 1992, I went down to
Tennessee with Fred and shot those scenes with Fred in the death
chamber at this new Tennessee prison outside Nashville. Fred was
already persona non grata by then. The warden did not want to be
photographed with Fred. And to ensure that no one who worked at the
prison would be seen with Fred, they locked us inside the death
chamber with Fred the entire day. We were able to send out for
pizza and sandwiches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those 20th-century lessons _ don't get in bed
with Nazis. Fred never learned it,'' Morris says, in the living
room of the Cambridge house he shares with his wife, art historian
Julia Sheehan, and their son, Hamilton. ``In my first film, `Gates
of Heaven,' there's a character, Floyd McClure, who operated an
unsuccessful pet cemetery,'' Morris says, ``but he kept talking
about his motivation. `Find a need and fill it,' he'd say. There's
Fred's story in a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's saying about this society, and secondarily about
Canada, is that Fred actually looks reasonable when he's saying,
`Well, if you're going to fry people, isn't it better that their
eyeballs don't fly across the room and hit the wall? If you're
going to kill people.' And as far as Canada goes, Fred doesn't
appear altogether unreasonable when he sits up there and says,
`Look, if I didn't do this, this guy wouldn't have a completely
fair trial.' Look at all the self-described Freds in the movie:
Fred the humanitarian, Fred the Florence Nightingale of death row,
Fred as the man who took the ouch out of the death penalty, Fred as
civil libertarian, Fred as champion of the underdog, Fred as
objective scientist, culminating with Fred as pariah. Quite a
Whitman Sampler!''
</P>
<P>
   Irony is always an ingredient of Morris's films. One of the
ironies here, among many, is that if Leuchter had simply stuck to
his death job, he likely would have continued to prosper. It was
when he hitched his reputation to neo-Nazi Holocaust deniers that
he undid himself. ``You know, every single movie that I've made is
about subjective stuff, as well as objective stuff. Or the
interplay between the two,'' Morris says. `` `Fast, Cheap &AMP; Out of
Control' was pretty much a movie about how people saw the world. I
guess the objective stuff in that movie was the objects of desire,
whether they be topiary animals or mole rats or circus animals.
Here's it's Fred's fantasies about himself. If you like, it's an
extended dream about himself. If you were to be unkind, a
narcissistic dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of growing-up story. You know, growing up is when
your childhood fantasies collide _ and collision is exactly the
right world, an auto wreck of major proportions _ with the world.
And it becomes necessary to modify them accordingly if one is to
survive. Of course, you can go on, but the danger is that people
stop talking to you, you have no friends, you have no career, you
have no real place in the world. And I think it's just such a very
very funny and very sad story. Fred functioned OK as a
self-described execution technologist. But when he moved onto a
larger stage, the stage of world history, he got himself into big
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asked very often whether I like Fred, and the answer is,
yes, I like Fred. There's something strangely endearing about the
man. Sometimes I wonder, am I just being taken in? Am I missing
something? Like, for example, the whole point? Am I being as
self-deceived as my protagonist? Which, I might add, is entirely
possible. But liking Fred is not tantamount to condoning what he's
done. Because the movie doesn't demonize Fred, there have been
complaints, to which I am not entirely unsympathetic. If you say
that Fred isn't an anti-Semite, or at least certainly not a
conventional anti-Semite, if you say he's not the devil incarnate,
that becomes in some quarters unacceptable. Two days before the
movie was to be screened at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art,
they got phone calls from the Museum of Tolerance, insisting that
my film be withdrawn! But this is not a movie about how Fred is
Satan. It's not a movie whose goal is demonizing Fred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself as refuting (Holocaust denial) because I
don't really take it seriously enough. I don't think that the
movie, properly considered, is an attempt to refute Holocaust
denial. Although I became convinced in the course of making the
movie that it was essential to make it clear in the movie that Fred
was wrong. If you like: wrong, wrong, and wrong. By the end of the
movie, he's actually convinced that he has the expertise to do
almost anything. Even though he does not. He becomes convinced that
he can pass judgment on historical matters of which he has little
or no knowledge. At that point, the movie, at least for me, becomes
truly absurd, ridiculous. I was taken to task in a review that said
it was clear that I wanted Fred to be perceived as Everyman. The
reviewer said, `We are not all like Fred.' My answer is yes and no.
I would pose a slightly different question. Are we capable of
deceiving ourselves about what we do? And my answer is most
certainly yes.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Leuchter is keeping a low profile. Morris is sworn
to secrecy by Leuchter on the subject of Leuchter's whereabouts,
but says that Leuchter is no longer in the death business. ``He
says he's working on the world's fastest modem that would
`revolutionize communication as we know it.' You know my line about
the one thing that would revolutionize communication as we know it?
Silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that silence fills Morris's days. He describes his working
life as a hodgepodge, working on a lot of things at the same time.
Every couple of years a movie gets made. Right now, Morris is
working on a TV series for Bravo and Channel 4 in the United
Kingdom. ``It's called `First Person,' just that, people telling
their stories, but in a television half-hour. Like, if a
psychiatric hour is 50 minutes, a television half-hour is 22 or 23
minutes. I just interviewed a guy who invented a keyboard the size
of a credit card, an ex-CIA operative, and an aerospace technician
who built a creature called Robo-saurus. It's this huge 60-foot
robotic dinosaur that eats cars.'
</P>
<P>
   Morris has carved a niche for himself as a maker of TV
commercials. In the last year he has done commercials for Honda,
IBM, Dell Computers, and Datek, an on-line brokerage. Also Levi's.
``That was their so-called truth campaign, which I think was a
little too truthful in the long run. They wanted to do a series
with real kids, unscripted spots where kids were in fact honestly
talking about themselves. There was one spot about group sex,
another about truancy, another about homosexuality, another about
drug abuse, and so forth. What really amazed me was the spot that
became the most controversial of the lot was the one that involved
capitalism. Even with my fondness for irony, there are things that
even I can't begin to imagine. There was one spot where this young
woman spoke about how you have to work for what you get. Rush
Limbaugh loved it. NPR excoriated me.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is currently represented on the tube with what he calls
the ``beer-amid'' commercial for Miller, the one where a guy sends
beer cascading down a pyramid of champagne glasses and says, ``If
the French know so much about champagne, how come they never
figured out a way to put it in cans?'' No small part of the obvious
pleasure he takes in it comes from its yahoo component. One of the
things Morris and Sheehan share is an against-the-grain
perspective. It extended to their marriage, which they happily
agree was as anti-romantic as marriages get. ``We went to the
Brooklyn criminal courts building,'' Sheehan says. ``We were
married in a judge's chambers, between two prostitution cases he
was hearing that day. Next to his desk was an American flag in a
pot. In the pot was rat poison. We couldn't have scripted it
better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
