u e BC-BOOKS-CIVIL-BOS &LR;      01-24 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CIVIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGGINSON'S JOURNAL FURTHER COLORS WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE COMPLETE CIVIL WAR JOURNAL AND SELECTED LETTERS OF THOMAS
WENTWORTH HIGGINSON 
Edited by Christopher Looby 
University of Chicago Press, 393 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
WHERE DEATH AND GLORY MEET 
Colonel Robert Gould Shaw and the 54th Massachusetts Infantry 
By Russell Duncan 
University of Georgia Press, 179 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Colonel Thomas Wentworth Higginson took command of the 1st
South Carolina Volunteer Regiment in November 1862, he saw it as
not a military posting but as ``the beginnings of a momentous
military experiment.'' For the unit that Higginson was to lead for
19 months comprised black soldiers _ mainly former slaves, both
freed and escaped.
</P>
<P>
   And Higginson knew _ as Christopher Looby, a professor at the
University of Pennsylvania, writes in his introduction to the new
collection of Higginson's writings _ that the unit's ``real mission
was one of propaganda,'' of ``blazoning forth'' what he described
as ``the military availability of the colored race.''
</P>
<P>
   Higginson, then 39, was a natural choice for the command. He was
from a prominent old Massachusetts family with abolitionist
sympathies, and in the years just before the Civil War was one of
the ``Secret Six'' who had funded John Brown's antislavery
activities in Kansas and later at Harper's Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Higginson was to draw on the journal for his
classic account, ``Army Life in a Black Regiment,'' but its entries
and his letters to his wife and other family members have a
sharp-eyed vitality and an untempered certainty of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Just three days after taking command at a camp near Beaufort, S.
C., Higginson wrote that ``it needs but a few days to show the
absurdity of doubting the equal military availability of these
people, as compared with whites.'' The black soldiers, he observed,
had ``as much average comprehension of the need of the thing'' as
white ones; they also possessed as much courage and (a judgment
that might surprise a modern reader) ``as much previous knowledge
of the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Higginson was also a sensitive observer of his men during
off-duty hours. That same evening, as he walked through the
encampment, Higginson came upon a group sitting around a campfire
listening to one of their fellows tell them how he escaped from his
slave master. Higginson recorded _ as he would do frequently _ the
dialect and locutions of the narrator and the reactions of his
listeners. But he also candidly recorded his own reactions. ``This
very narrator,'' he wrote, ``is one whom you would point to as he
hoed lazily in a cotton field, as one the light of whose brain had
gone out.'' But his actions demonstrated ``caution, foresight (and)
patient cunning'' _ leading Higginson to conclude that if he were
``to get into the enemy's country, I should be only too glad to put
myself as a child into (his) hands.''
</P>
<P>
   As Higginson became more familiar with his troops, and even more
confident of their ability, he complained that ``their best
qualities will be wasted by merely keeping them for garrison duty.
For partizan warfare they are admirably fitted,'' liking adventure
and having ``a great deal of dash and abundant resources.''
</P>
<P>
   And later, in a comment reflective of the deeply held beliefs of
the abolitionists, Higginson wrote that ``machines cannot make
soldiers like mine.'' And ``the better soldiers they become, the
more they are spoiled for slaves. I see that the latest rule
proposed in the rebel Congress is to sell by auction all slaves
taken in arms _ but no rational man would buy them; they know too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Higginson's 1st South Carolina did not see
major action _ certainly nothing on the scale of the 54th
Massachusetts Infantry, another black unit whose bloody assault on
Fort Wagner is immortalized in that greatest of national monuments,
the Saint-Gaudens monument across from the Massachusetts State
House.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Higginson makes little mention of the 54th or of its
commander, Colonel Robert Gould Shaw. He visited the 54th when it
arrived in South Carolina, but does not mention meeting Shaw. And
when Shaw is killed at Fort Wagner, Higginson gives it but a brief
mention in a letter to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Shaw, in a letter home to his mother after
Higginson's visit, speaks admiringly of him as one who ``put his
whole soul into his work'' and a man of ``open-heartedness and
purity of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's letters _ as vivid and filled with a sense of mission as
Higginson's _ were published in 1994 as ``The Blue-Eyed Child of
Fortune.'' Their editor, Russell Duncan, has now written a fine
biography of Shaw, and together with Higginson's journal and
letters it provides an insight into the sense of misson that
animated men who not only fought a war but espoused a cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
