<HEADLINE>
DRYPERS HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see Drypers-Latin-America) 
 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston-based Drypers has focused its international expansion
efforts primarily in Latin America. Key events are highlighted
below.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1987: Walter Klemp, Terry Tognietti and Dave Pitassi form
diaper company Veragon Corp., which makes Drypers diaper line.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1992_ Drypers Corp. is created out of the merger of
Houston-based Veragon, VMG Enterprises of the Pacific Northwest and
UltraCare Products of Marion, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   _ June 1993: Drypers opens diaper production facility in Toa
Alta, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   _ March 1994: Drypers goes public.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1995: Drypers acquires diaper manufacturer Seler in Buenos
Aires, Argentina, for $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ December 1996: Drypers buys Pannolini de Mexico, a
Guadalajara-based diaper maker, for $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ February 1997: Drypers acquires a 51 percent ownership in
Chansommes do Brazil, the makers of the Puppet line of diapers.
</P>
<P>
   _ April 1998: Drypers buys Chansommes diaper lines and its
manufacturing facility in Moji Das Cruzes, Sao Paulo, for $15
million. It names that operation Drypers Limited do Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   _ January 1998: Drypers teams up with Wal-Mart International to
provide the retailer with a private-label diaper, Cozies.
</P>
<P>
   _ April 1998: Latin American children's program superstar Xuxa
Meneghel agrees to endorse Dryper diapers in Brazil, contributing
to a 26 percent increase in sales for the year. Dryper estimates
its share of the disposal diaper market in Brazil and Argentina at
12 to 15 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ August 1998: A fire at Drypers' Argentine operations causes
$25 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   _ January 1999: Brazil's real devalues by 35 percent, reducing
Drypers' net income by $1 million in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ March 1999: Drypers invests in a start-up diaper operation in
Cali, Colombia, and begins manufacturing diapers there in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
