<SLUG> BC-DRYPERS-LATIN-AMERICA-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRYPERS OVERCOMES CHALLENGES TO IMPROVES ITS BOTTOM LINE IN LATIN
AMERICA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Wash.) 
 
(Eds.: Also See Drypers-chart) 
 
By JENALIA MORENO 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOJI DAS CRUZES, BRAZIL _ At lightning speed, mammoth sewing
machines shoot aloe vera or baking soda into the lining of
disposable diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Another machine spits out ink that decorates diapers with the
lipstick kisses and signature of Brazilian superstar Xuxa.
</P>
<P>
   The last assembly line in this factory makes a no-frills diaper
called Baby Pop (short for Popular) that's decorated only with
ladybugs on the waistband.
</P>
<P>
   The economy diaper line is Houston-based Drypers' effort
to &UR;  &LR; react to the effects of Brazil's devaluation of its currency,
the real.
</P>
<P>
   The January 1999 devaluation was one of a series of events in
Latin America that soiled Drypers' earnings. The change in the
value of the real alone caused the cost of raw materials to
increase by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the disposable diaper maker was reeling from
an August 1998 fire that destroyed its Argentine operation and a
price war in Mexico that gutted its sales.
</P>
<P>
   Drypers has survived the beatings and learned important lessons
about international markets along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The string of negative events forced it to restructure its
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, Drypers suffered its biggest losses from the fire.
It then saw its sales fall because of the reduced buying power from
the currency devaluation of its customers in neighboring Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   So Drypers moved some of its Argentine production to its
factories in Malaysia and Mexico. The factories in those locations
allowed it to stay out the price war and beef up its overall
production. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; It reduced its work force in Argentina by not replacing
retiring employees, cutting 17 people from a total of 97.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, the company increased efficiency by shutting down its
oldest production line. That meant that employees who examine
individual diapers for rips and defects threw out fewer
``fraldas,'' as they're called in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   After the devaluation, officials at this mountainside factory
immediately started working to launch a new, cheaper brand of
diapers. Three months later, they were manufacturing Baby Pop.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Pop's price helped struggling parents in the wake of the
devaluation. A package of 16 large diapers sells for about $1.50,
compared with $2.50 for competing economy brands.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Pop quickly gained popularity and now accounts for 30
percent of the company's sales in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of Drypers' premium line of diapers _ the ones with aloe
vera and baking soda in the lining and Sesame Street characters on
the waistband _ run about $4 in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its efforts to combat its troubles in Latin America, the
problems there still led to the corporation losing $780,000 in the
third quarter of 1999, compared with a profit of $1.5 million for
the same period of a year before. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Its share price has fallen to 2 3/16 Friday, down from a
52-week high of 4 4/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not thrilled with the profitability that's coming out of
South America, but at least the bleeding has stopped,'' Walter
``Wally'' Klemp, Drypers chairman and chief executive officer, said
at the company's headquarters in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Although Drypers blamed its loss on problems in its South
American operations &UR;  &LR; _ the company does not disclose how much of an
operating profit or loss it earns in each region _ &UR;  &LR; that hasn't
made Klemp shy away from the region, because he predicts big
profits from it in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do well, we'll be a $2 billion company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the company reported $332.6 million in revenues, $118.9
million from its international operations. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; About a quarter of Drypers' sales come out of Latin America, so
to reach its $2 billion goal, it must continue to focus on the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions have improved since this time last year for the
diaper maker. Mexico's diaper price war is over, Drypers has
rebuilt its plant in Argentina into a new and better facility, and
Brazil has survived its economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the triple whammy hit Drypers when it was a
relative newcomer in the Latin American market.
</P>
<P>
   The baby products company expanded into Latin America in 1995,
first entering Argentina, the most stable economy in the region at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   It followed with Mexico in 1996. The country offered a large
population and it was quickly recovering from the 1994 peso
devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Drypers entered Brazil, mostly because of its enormous
population of 164 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to say you're a major player in Latin America
without being in Brazil,'' Klemp said.
</P>
<P>
   The move southward originally was made so Drypers could avoid
relying exclusively on the U.S. market, where it was pummeled in
1995 by a price war with diaper giants Kimberly Clark Corp. and
Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.
</P>
<P>
   Skyrocketing pulp prices were another reason the company's
profits plunged at the time.
</P>
<P>
   However, Drypers surprised its critics by staging a remarkable
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, it teamed up with grocery stores such as Kroger
and mass merchandisers such as Kmart &UR;  &LR; to make private-label
diapers, which are similar to a generic brand in that they're
cheaper for the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   However, they typically don't have the store name on the
package, like generic brands.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1998, Drypers started a $10 million national
advertising campaign that helped it increase its domestic sales by
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, Drypers aligned with retail giant Wal-Mart to
make the private-label diaper line Cozies.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it licensed the Sesame Street characters, which now appear
in advertisements, on packaging and on the diaper waistbands of its
premium Drypers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The moves proved successful, and Drypers has registered sales
gains nearly every quarter. For the three months ended Sept. 30,
it's revenues totaled $94 million, compared to $86 million for the
same period of 1998 and $80 million for that quarter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've proven time and time again we have what it takes to
survive some pretty awful stuff,'' said Klemp, who dreamed up the
company over coffee with his two partners in a Vancouver, Wash.,
diner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent world economic turmoil, Klemp is determined to
continue focusing on the international marketplace to fuel the
company's growth. Even after the Latin American woes began, the
company invested in a manufacturing facility in Cali, Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   However, that likely will be Drypers' last expansion for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to consciously pull ourselves back,'' Klemp said.
``We're having to say the opportunity is out there to double our
company size, but financially that's not the smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst John Rogers agreed that the company must focus on
improving its earnings, which he describes as far from stellar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've put all the building blocks in place and now they
really have to capitalize on those investments,'' said Rogers, of
D.A. Davidson &AMP; Co. in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Drypers mut increase its international sales because the U.S.
market isn't growing. Not only is the fertility rate in the United
States stable at 2.5 children per woman, but nearly every American
baby wears disposable diapers instead of cloth diapers _ which
means there is no opportunity to switch mothers from cloth to
disposables.
</P>
<P>
   Both domestically and internationally, diaper makers face the
problem of customer turnover. That's because a mother uses diapers
for only a couple of years _ until her child becomes potty-trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reinvent ourselves ever two years because there's
mothers leaving the market every year,'' said Graciela Picazo,
Drypers' marketing director in Guadalajara.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest marketing problem is competing with the Goliaths of
the industry, Irving, Texas-based Kimberly Clark and
Cincinnati-based Procter &AMP; Gamble. Those competitors sell a broad
array of products, so they are less vulnerable when a particular
market faces economic problems or one product's price fluctuates.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to gain market share in the United States is to
steal some of the business from someone else _ either Kimberly
Clark and Procter &AMP; Gamble or small players.
</P>
<P>
   That's tough to do with the giants when the two big consumer
products companies spend millions annually marketing their famous
diaper lines, Huggies for Kimberly Clark and Luvs and Pampers for
Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``How this company can ever, ever, ever compete with Procter &AMP;
Gamble, I just don't see how it's possible,'' said Marvin Roffman,
president of the Philadelphia-based money management company
Roffman Miller Associates, who follows Procter &AMP; Gamble's stock.
</P>
<P>
   While Drypers trails its huge competitors in the United States,
where it was a latecomer, it has gained a foothold in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brand identity is less important in these markets,'' said
Klemp. ``They're more focused on getting a diaper that works for
the lowest possible price''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Drypers arrived in Latin America when disposable diapers
were becoming more accepted and more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were able to get into those markets early, before they
developed, and became a significant player,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America and the Caribbean are important to baby products
companies because of the region's higher fertility rate of 2.9
children per mother.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers there did not use disposable diapers for decades because
they were considered a luxury item, but that has changed, with more
mothers entering the work force and wanting goods that make their
lives easier.
</P>
<P>
   It is still common to see babies wearing cloth diapers. However,
even cloth diapers are too expensive for many in the region, where
the income level can be as low as a few hundred dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's vast areas with vast populations that use virtually
zero diapers today,'' said Joe Tanner at Dryers' operation in
Vancouver, Wash. ``It's always hot. (Babies) don't wear anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Latin America's higher fertility rate, coupled with the low
penetration rate of disposable diapers, means the market is growing
by 10 percent annually in number of diapers sold.
</P>
<P>
   Drypers controls 12 to 14 percent of the disposable diaper
market in Argentina and Brazil. In Mexico, it has about 2 percent
of the market because it does not yet have national distribution
there.
</P>
<P>
   Drypers became successful in Latin America by adapting to the
market there. It hired marketing experts from the region who had
worked at top consumer products companies there and also learned
from companies it bought that were already established in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Drypers hired Brazilian children's program host Xuxa
(pronounced Shu-Sha) as its spokeswoman shortly after she had her
daughter, Sasha. The company's Xuxa brand accounts for 30 percent
of its sales in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The product is especially popular in Xuxa's home state of Rio de
Janeiro and the northeast region of Brazil. Many residents in the
northeast, descendants of Indians, are captivated by her blonde
hair and blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Another adaptation to the Brazilian market was to sell diapers
in smaller packages. Like its competitors, Drypers sells packages
of 10 to 18 diapers instead of the jumbo packages of 50 diapers
common in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for the customer to double the out of pocket
(costs) and just have a 1 or 2 percent (price) advantage,'' said
Sofia Mata Martin, Drypers marketing director in Sao Paulo, as she
examined the diaper shelves at Carrefour, the French-owned
supermarket chain &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian consumers just don't have the money to buy the bigger
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Some day the economy will improve, so buyers will have more
money in their pockets _ and that is likely to mean that Drypers'
sales will improve. Drypers is watching the market and ready to
react.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market will move to jumbo packages,'' Martin said. ``It's
not the time yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
