<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``So I Am Glad'' by A.J. Kennedy (Knopf, $23). The shade of
Cyrano de Bergerac enters the life of a cool Scottish maid. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Gloaming'' by Alice Elliot Dark (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$23). Stories that suggest a whole universe in a single incident. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fasting, Feasting'' by Anita Desai (Mariner/
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $13). A novel of youth, at home in India and
in the United States. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of No Country I Know: Selected Poems and Translations'' by
David Ferry (University of Chicago Press, $14). In his own work and
interpretations of classics, the poet's powers have deepened. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortune's Rocks'' by Anita Shreve (Little, Brown, $24.95). A
page-turner about a girl who has a tragic affair with an older
man. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne Morrow Lindbergh'' by Susan Hertog (Nan A.
Talese/Doubleday, $30). In search of a living moral example, the
biographer finds a woman who married the century's dominant public
hero but who craved privacy and silence. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Flu'' by Gina Kolata (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25). A
masterly recounting of medical history, and a good mystery story
about the pandemic of 1918-19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
