<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4820 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-TWEENS-BOS &LR;      01-24 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TWEENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOLITAS WITH A BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many young American females, Ali Gallagher is slightly
obsessed. She's a passionate music fan, a 24-7 lover of pop. She
wakes up to her favorite songs on ``Kiss 108.'' The Boston radio
station's music plays in the background while Ali works. If she
needs to be on the computer at home, there's always a music disc in
the CD drive. A lifelong dancer, Ali choreographs her own moves to
hit tunes. She spends most of her disposable income on her
fast-growing CD collection.
</P>
<P>
   Ali Gallagher is 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Mandy Moore and Britney Spears and Christina
Aguilera,'' gushes Ali, a fifth-grader at the Countryside School in
Newton, Mass. She's not alone. Somewhere on the order of 27 million
children ages 8 to 14, a brand new consumer group known to
marketers as tweens, helped Spears and Aguilera collectively sell a
staggering 14 million albums last year. Newcomer Mandy Moore _
whose debut CD, ``So Real,'' was released on Dec. 7 and has already
shipped half a million copies _ is following close behind.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous, blond, and nubile all, the current female pop stars
dominating the charts have a number of things in common. They are
themselves teenagers. They sell music to even younger fans. They're
singing about sex. And most of their songs were written by
middle-aged men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it to me / I'm so addicted to the loving that you're
feeding me / Ohhh / Can't do without it, this feeling's got me weak
in the knees/Oh, baby / Body's in withdrawal every time you take it
away / Ohhh/Can't you hear me callin'? / Begging you to come out
and play? / Aw, yeah . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   The song is called ``Candy,'' and the singer _ 15-year-old Mandy
Moore _ seems a bit confused about whether she's craving a trip to
the Sweet Shoppe or to Lover's Lane. But then ``Candy'' has little
to do with Moore's desires at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hooked up with two producers, Tony Battaglia and Sean
Fisher. Well, they kind of found me,'' she says. ``They basically
wrote the songs on the album.'' Moore, who lives at home with her
parents, confirms that she hasn't experienced everything that she
sings about. ``But it's stuff I could experience. Most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't, of course, the first generation of pretty young
songbirds to have their careers shaped by powerful older men. From
Lesley Gore's classic adolescent angst and Brenda Lee's lovesick
ballads in the 1960s to the fresh-faced dance-pop of Tiffany and
Debbie Gibson in the '80s, the industry's male powerhouses have
paved the way for young girls to express adolescent yearning in
song. This, however, is the first generation of female teen singers
to emerge as unabashed bona fide sex symbols _ down to their
fashions, their makeup, and their lyrics. Perhaps more important,
these young stars are the first group of female idols to be
marketed so aggressively to teen and preteen girls.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, young girls _ pop stars and fans alike _ are
naturally sexual, grappling with their own physical and emotional
awakenings. They're growing up in a postfeminist culture that
allows an unprecedented freedom of expression; many of them have
parents influenced by the free-spirited '60s and '70s. But their
``liberated'' culture also carries a very real potential for
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   When 17-year-old Spears begs her ex-boyfriend to ``give me a
sign, hit me baby one more time,'' she's expressing the fantasies
of the Swedish songwriter/producer Max Martin, who has penned hits
for the Backstreet Boys and also works with the Norwegian duo M &AMP; M
(both girls, ages 15 and 16) and Swedish ex-model Jessica Folker
(first single: ``Tell Me What You Like''). Moore's hit ``Candy''
was dreamed up by no fewer than four grown men (Jive, Dennis Rich,
Dave Katz, and Tony Battaglia). Similarly, when Christina Aguilera,
19, alerts her suitor, ``If you want to be with me / Baby, there's
a price to pay / I'm a genie in a bottle / You gotta rub me the
right way,'' she is giving voice to the sentiments of the
songwriting team of Steve Kipner and David Frank (Pam Sheyne is
also credited).
</P>
<P>
   Kipner, a seasoned songwriter whose previous hits include
``Let's Get Physical'' for Olivia Newton-John and ``The Hardest
Thing'' for 98 Degrees, has learned that ``that sort of shock value
is something you need to make people pay attention. Obviously
there's a sexual connotation in `Genie.' But it doesn't have to be
construed in a sexual way. It could also be `you've got to impress
me.' To be honest, Christina wasn't so sure about it. But Ron Fair
at RCA said he had to have this song. Now, Christina signs her
autographs `From Genie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest trend in pop: older men writing sexy scenarios
for lovely teenage girls to sing. And younger kids are lapping it
up. These tweens have cash to burn: 10-to-14-year-olds now account
for about 9 percent of all CD sales. They're buying these fantasies
because the defining feature of tweendom is the nearly fanatical
impulse to aspire up _ to look older, act older, be older. ``We
asked 12-year-olds what age they would be if they could be any age,
and the answer was 17,'' says Michael Wood, vice president of
Teenage Research Unlimited, a market research firm based in
Northbrook, Ill., that specializes in the youth market. ``That's
who they're taking their cues from.''
</P>
<P>
   Teenage Research Unlimited conducts a twice-yearly study on teen
trends, lifestyles, attitudes, and product and media behavior, to
which more than 100 high-profile companies _ among them Disney,
ABC, the NFL, and a handful of record companies _ subscribe.
``Because of the strong numbers,'' Wood says, ``you've got people
who never targeted this age coming on. Look at Tommy Hilfiger,
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, all trying to capitalize on this new consumer.
Behind the scenes, you've got record companies recognizing the size
of this demographic, not only for record sales but for the
merchandising side as well. You talk about kids growing up fast . .
. a lot of it is based in commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Commerce, as it translates for the impressionable tweens,
represents something more complex than the exchange of goods. And
music is much more than simple entertainment. It's a way to help
define who they are. ``It's not new to have children caught up in
pop-culture styles, fashion, or music,'' says Cornell University
historian Joan Jacobs Brumberg, author of ``The Body Project,'' a
history of American girls. ``What's new is that the girls are
younger than ever, and they have disposable income.'' The ages of
these artists, she says, makes them ``infinitely more seductive.''
And there's no question in her mind that the adult image projected
by the current teen stars has an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every social science study done and every historical account
suggests that girls are maturing earlier than ever before. Some of
it is good _ the result of improved nutrition and decline in
infectious disease. But we have a lot of 9-, 10-, and 11-year-old
girls who are precociously sexual, who are interested in adult,
erotic things. If very early on you are encouraged by the culture
to be sexual _ not necessarily sexually active, but engage in
sexualized behavior, with language and clothes _ it changes you,''
says Jacobs Brumberg. ``It changes the nature of romance. Girls who
really get into this are seduced by the idea that their appearance
is the critical thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that's being given fresh life by those with a
vested interest in perpetuating it: the movers and shakers in the
recording industry. ``I don't think that middle-aged men in the
music industry necessarily understand what's best for a developing
girl,'' Jacobs Brumberg says.
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, understand what's best for the bottom line.
Today's tweens represent the largest number in that age group in
two decades. By 2010, as the tweens morph into teens, there will be
more teenagers alive than ever before _ just shy of 35 million.
Teens spent $153 billion in 1999, an increase of 8.5 percent over
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The tweens, and their induction into the ranks of music
consumers, present new challenges for people like Betsy Frank, vice
president for research and planning at MTV networks, which includes
MTV, VH1, and Nickelodeon. ``At MTV, whose target audience is 12 to
34, we're winding up with kids who are younger than you'd expect
them to be,'' says Frank. ``So yes, there's been lots of discussion
about whether kids are growing up faster, whether they're going
through some things sooner. I think certainly the popularity of
Britney Spears over the last year has not been seen before. It
presents some unique challenges for how to appeal to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
