<SLUG> BC-STRESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYS TO STOP THE STRESS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stress test: Los Angeles, morning rush hour. Traffic is finally
moving on the 101. The driver behind you is tailgating at 70 mph,
talking on a cell phone and checking the hairdo in the rearview
mirror. Do you:
</P>
<P>
   (A) Slam on your brakes, gesture wildly and then pull up right
on the car's tail.
</P>
<P>
   (B) Honk, shake your fist and scream unprintable obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   (C) Fire shots at the car.
</P>
<P>
   (D) Signal, change lanes, let the tailgater pass and bask in the
knowledge you're not as dumb as the other driver?
</P>
<P>
   If the correct answer is clearly D, why do traffic studies
constantly peg Southern California drivers as the rudest and most
aggressive in the nation?
</P>
<P>
   We're stressed _ jaw-clenching, neck muscle-cramping,
are-you-out-of-your-bleepin'-mind? S-T-R-E-S-S. And most of us _
especially in the middle of the L.A. freeway system _ are clueless
about how to get rid of it or not let it kill us.
</P>
<P>
   There are some simple ways to take the edge off, but first let's
look at how people get stressed out.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that the pressures of life in the big city
keep most people boiling in a constant stew of stress hormones best
suited for storming Omaha Beach during World War II. The hormones _
adrenaline, for example _ increase alertness and divert blood from
vital internal organs to muscles, the so-called ``fight or flight''
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The body is saying you've got to deal with this situation
somehow _ you have to resolve it or leave it,'' said Jean Hardesty,
an Encino psychologist who studies the effects of stress at the
University of California, Los Angeles. ``If you're being chased by
a lion, hopefully you run fast enough and you get rid of that
stress right away.''
</P>
<P>
   If fight-or-flight hormones stay elevated, stress becomes a slow
poison. Blood pressure rises, causing strain on the heart; rigid
muscles can cause back pain. The perpetually stressed also often
suffer from severe headaches and gastrointestinal stress _
including ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like putting your car in neutral and pushing the
gas pedal to the floorboard,'' Hardesty said. ``You're using up
your body faster and not going anyplace or resolving anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, most people need to relax, but it's not that easy,
especially in a city that prides itself on leading the world's
movers and shakers, said Linda Daniels-Hernandez, a licensed
clinical social worker at Kaiser Permanente Medical Center in
Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so production-oriented. We try to pack so much into
every day,'' Daniels-Hernandez said. ``We need to think about not
doing so much, to prioritize what's really important. I know a lot
of people who sit at their desk and eat lunch. They don't even take
a real break. Getting away from your desk, just walking around the
building and getting fresh air for 15 minutes can make a tremendous
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are more stress-busting techniques:
</P>
<P>
   _ Breathe: A technique called ``cleansing breaths'' is the
cornerstone of any stress-reduction plan. It's also something you
can do in any situation. Take a deep breath, hold it for a few
seconds. Imagine the stress leaving your body as you exhale. This
also floods the body with oxygen, which also feels good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Progressive relaxation: This technique works best with the
help of a therapist or friend, Hardesty said. ``You go head to
toe,'' she explains. ``Tense up your forehead muscles, hold it for
three or four seconds and then relax it. You go right down the body
to your toes, clenching and relaxing. Imagine your stress melting
away.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Spot relaxation: If you don't have time to go head to toe,
concentrate on the muscles that hold tension _ frequently the jaw,
shoulders and neck. Hardesty said just relaxing the jaw, letting it
drop as if you just nodded off, will release loads of tension.
Again, this only works if you visualize the stress leaving your
body.
</P>
<P>
   _ Switch sides of your brain: If you write computer code or fix
car engines _ exercising the left brain _ try to do something
social when you get home. Right-brainers who spend the day in
social situations may want do something more solitary _ taking a
bath, making a salad or playing the piano.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just say no: Think before accepting new tasks. Do you have
time?
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't sweat things you can't control: If someone is driving
badly, ``Let it go, let it go,'' advises Daniels-Hernandez. ``Don't
take it on. You don't have control over other people, only your
reaction to them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Exercise: Take a walk. Use the stairs instead of the elevator.
Join a tae kwon do class. Getting a workout doesn't have to be a
big production. Daniels-Hernandez offers this urban example:
Instead of battling for a parking place close to where you're going
_ a stressful situation _ park in the farthest space. There's no
stress, and the walk will do wonders for your stress level and your
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Visualize: Stuck in traffic? Use the time to think about
something else. The color of the sky. Blades of grass popping
through the edges of the freeway. Play your favorite music. Listen
to a book on tape. Breathe.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Hardesty said, is experimenting: ``Everyone needs to
find what works for them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
