<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GREEN-TEA-HNS &LR;      01-24 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-TEA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YOU CAN BANK ON THE GREEN STUFF. TEA, THAT IS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By LISA STEVENS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Read the tea leaves and the message is clear _ green is best.
</P>
<P>
   Green tea's long history is steeped in its medicinal powers and
studies continue to uncover more of its health benefits. All tea
comes from the camellis sinensis bush, a flowering evergreen
indigenous to China and India, but green tea leaves are the least
processed of all the teas, preserving the natural active substances
of the leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Monks used green tea as a mild mental stimulant and
traditionally it has been used to treat coughs, colds and
respiratory ailments. Today, research shows green tea may help
protect against many cancers, including lung, liver, pancreatic,
stomach, colon, mouth, throat, kidney, breast and skin.
</P>
<P>
   Green tea's natural chemical compounds, called polyphenols, are
powerful antioxidants. The primary polyphenols in tea are called
catechins, which protect against damaging forms of oxygen known as
free radicals. Catechins increase activity in the blood to help
lower cholesterol and regulate blood sugar and insulin levels.
</P>
<P>
   The more green tea you drink, the better, because it is full of
vitamins and minerals.
</P>
<P>
   A cup of green tea can give you a good dose of vitamin C, about
as much as you'll find in a lemon. It also contains several B
vitamins. Five cups of green tea a day provide 5 to 10 percent of
the daily requirement of riboflavin, niacin, folic acid and
pantothenic acid, 5 percent of the daily requirement of magnesium,
25 percent of potassium and 45 percent manganese. A cup of green
tea also contains 0.1 milligrams of fluoride, an amount higher than
in fluorinated water, helping protect against cavities.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO MAKE A CUP OF TEA
</P>
<P>
   You can plop a tea bag in a mug with some water and microwave it
a minute or two if you don't care much what your tea tastes like.
But to make a flavorful and aromatic cup, follow these suggestions
from Linda Smith of Divinitea in Schenectady, N.Y.:
</P>
<P>
   _ Always use fresh, filtered cold water. Do not use water that
has already been boiled.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rinse the cup and/or pot with hot water before adding the tea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Place tea in cup or pot, add water and then cover. If making
black tea, let the water come to a boil and boil for 1 minute to
ensure the water is at the proper temperature. Allow black tea to
steep for 3 to 5 minutes, depending on your taste. Green tea
requires water that is only 165 to 185 degrees. Bring the water to
a boil, remove from heat and let sit for a minute to cool down.
Pour water over tea and steep for only 1 to 2 minutes. Green teas,
if allowed to steep too long, can become bitter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
