<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-WEAVER-FEATURE-L     01-24 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WEAVER-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 50, SIGOURNEY WEAVER PROVING IT GETS EASIER TO DO IT ALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the course of her 20-year film career, Sigourney Weaver has
played tough and shown her smarts, displayed some potent chemistry
with monkeys and Mel Gibson and, above all, established a screen
persona that is a potent combination of steely resolve and icy
remoteness. Warmth has never been her thing. Her husband, New York
theater director Jim Simpson, teases her for typically playing
women that you'd ``walk across the street to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, herself, is not one of those women. In fact, she says
she's not a serious person at all. Not that there's anything wrong
with being serious, she hastens to add.
</P>
<P>
   But when push comes to shove, Weaver describes herself as a
mother first, an actress second and ... well ... an idiot third.
Gravity, she says simply, is not her style.
</P>
<P>
   And now, just as she has passed her 50th birthday (and given her
astounding beauty, it's safe to say that Weaver is aging most
gracefully), the three-time Oscar nominee is getting the chance to
show the world just how stupid she can be. In ``Galaxy Quest,''
Weaver dons a blond wig and catsuit to play a washed-up sci-fi TV
actress who helps save the universe.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-10 Weaver displays expert comic chops (and a fair
amount of skin, as her character's uniform becomes comically
tattered as the movie progresses), proving her contention that she
can make people laugh if given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always regretted having had such a serious career when
comedy is the one thing I feel I'm good at,'' Weaver says. ``The
response to `Galaxy Quest' has definitely been interesting. I think
I've surprised a lot of people who didn't think I had it in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver's role in another new film, ``A Map of the World'' (which
returned to theaters last week after a brief Oscar-qualifying run
in December), is more in line with her overall body of work.
There's comedy here, too, in this story of a mother trying to cope
with everyday parental responsibilities and an unspeakable tragedy,
but the humor is arch and rueful, not the kind of stuff that's
going to appeal to audiences looking for mindless entertainment.
Weaver's performance is typically outstanding and earned her a
Golden Globe nomination and a great deal of Oscar buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Map of the World'' (which is adapted from Jane Hamilton's
best-selling novel) also earned Weaver the opportunity to explore
another facet of her personality _ motherhood _ previously unseen
in her work. It's the first time she has played a mother on screen
_ a big deal for Weaver, given how devoted she is to her 9-year-old
daughter, Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sigourney is a mother; I've seen her in action,'' says Scott
Elliott, who directed ``A Map of the World.'' ``She's not a society
woman or Hollywood mom. She's someone very much in the thick of the
day-to-day responsibilities of raising a daughter. And she really
seems to love it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She does love it,'' adds Julianne Moore, Weaver's ``Map''
co-star. ``I think the fact that we're both mothers is one reason
the film works so well.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Weaver's character, Alice, an acerbic school nurse
and a mother of two young daughters, endures and, at times, almost
embraces a litany of trials. She is wrongfully accused of child
abuse, sent to jail and, if that's not enough, witnesses an
inconceivable accident that produces a mountain of grief and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stops just short of Job,'' Weaver jokes about Alice's fall
from grace. ``Nevertheless,'' she adds, ``it's a very universal
story. Every mother will be able to empathize with Alice.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver says her experiences as a parent completely informed
every facet of her performance in the film and often paralleled
what she was experiencing on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a low-budget film, so we typically had to move fast
and get through as many scenes as we could in a day,'' Weaver says.
``So the spontaneity of family life and the spontaneity of the way
we had to work was very similar. Sometimes, you're simply too tired
to think so you just have to do it. It may not end up perfect, but
it can be a very joyous experience because its so involving.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver came to motherhood relatively late in her life; she was
41 when Charlotte was born. Prior to that, she used to look at her
friends who were mothers and marvel at their patience and
self-sacrifice. ``I had known them before, and they weren't always
that way,'' Weaver says, laughing. She wondered how one became so
selfless so fast. It didn't take her long to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great joy about being a parent is that it realigns you
totally to care for someone who is not yourself,'' Weaver says.
``Before I became a mother, I was basically nurturing myself or my
career or my husband, and all of a sudden there's this little
person and the rest just seems to fall away, as I think nature
intended it to do. You never look at life the same way again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she seem to be looking at her career the same way, now
that she has played a mother in ``Map'' and a goofball in ``Galaxy
Quest.'' Her next film, ``The Breakers,'' has her playing Jennifer
Love Hewitt's mom in a broad comedy about a mother-daughter con
team who pull outrageous scams on rich men in Palm Beach, Fla.
Weaver and Hewitt will don numerous disguises and personas in the
comedy, which will begin shooting in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of wonderful comic possibilities,'' Weaver
says. ``And I'm playing a mother again, even if it is a grown
daughter this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Weaver is terribly bothered by playing the mother of a
young woman on screen. Turning 50 last October doesn't seem to have
produced any sadness or soul searching. She celebrated her birthday
at a party held on the same night as her 15th wedding anniversary,
and for Weaver, the big 5-0 was almost an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to be 49, you see how young 50 is,'' Weaver says.
``I always thought that it would be tougher. I've known the
occasional person who's turned 50 and I'd think, `Oh, God, that's
the beginning of the end there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't feel like that. It feels like you're inching
toward perhaps some sort of ... I don't know ... mastery. And
that's not a bad place to be at all.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
