<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4883 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-24 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AT LAST: A POLITICIANS WHO DOES MORE THAN TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., wants to make
sure that women who are victimized once won't be victimized twice,
or three times. She is drafting a bill to protect immigrants who
testify in criminal exploitation cases from being deported.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of sound bites and talking points, how many
politicians actually do something _ immediately and with absolutely
no self-serving rhetoric? On one recent morning, I buttonholed
Feinstein after a press conference on her bill to protect consumers
from unknowingly buying previously totaled used cars.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein hadn't heard of the case of Lakireddy Bali Reddy, the
Berkeley landlord accused of illegally importing and sexually
exploiting young women from India. I told her that women who might
testify against him have not been offered immunity from deportation
by the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   She got it immediately and quietly sprang into action. Feinstein
called over her field representative, Deborah Mesloh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of a landlord in Berkeley who is accused of
importing and sexually abusing young women from India,'' she said,
while Mesloh took notes on a yellow legal pad. ``I want to make a
very strong appeal for them to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should go straight to the top, to (INS Commissioner
Doris) Meissner. These women should be able to get refugee status,
because if they go back to India they face a terrible stigma.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this was for my benefit. It was for the women's benefit.
I stood there taking notes, astonished at Feinstein's seriousness,
efficiency and comprehension of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, a spokesman for Feinstein called to make a
clarification. He said that, because of current law, it may be hard
for the women to get refugee status. Therefore, Feinstein is
working on a bill that would prevent the deportation of immigrants
who testify against their exploiters.
</P>
<P>
   As yet, the scope of the bill, or the kind of crimes it would
cover, is being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   But Dianne Feinstein is on the case, along with her close
friend, the INS commissioner, so something will be done to protect
these women from being triply victimized.
</P>
<P>
   Any woman who testifies in a sexual molestation case may find
herself doubly victimized, whether by invasive cross-examination or
stigmatization.
</P>
<P>
   If a young Indian woman is deported after testifying in such a
case, the triple victimization would be unimaginable to most
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding from the affidavits is that the parents of
these girls sold them so that they could send money home,'' said
Hina Shah, a staff attorney for the Asian Law Caucus in San
Francisco. ``Their fate may not be very good if they're sent back
to India. If sexual molestation occurred, there may not be any
family members willing to take them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as a Pakistani friend, whose husband is from India, put it
over morning coffee, ``If they go back, they're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   My friend told a story about an Indian woman who found two
sexually abused girls whose families wouldn't take them back. The
Indian woman eventually adopted the girls. They were among the
lucky few.
</P>
<P>
   Americans should not feel too superior, though. Last week,
public health researchers at Johns Hopkins University reported that
one-third of the women in the world, across all countries and
cultures, had been beaten, raped, coerced into sex or otherwise
seriously abused.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy to bring an end to that. It is possible to keep
deportation, and possible death, from being imposed on victims of
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``tip of the iceberg'' keeps coming up in the case of
the Berkeley landlord and the young women he allegedly imported.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is the tip of an iceberg that may be the tip
of a bigger iceberg, namely all immigrants who are afraid of
testifying in court. Feinstein hopes to address such fears, and fix
that flaw in our legal system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
