   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   US-AFRICA (Undated) _ Richard Holbrooke vows that the United
States is serious this time about Africa, turning over the UN
Security Council this month to Al Gore, Jesse Helms and tons of
Africa specialists. But how deep is the US commitment? By Sam
Allis. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-STRAINS (Berlin) _ Former chancellor Helmut Kohl
acknowledges that he took illegal contributions. Former East German
leader Egon Krenz is sentenced to five years in jail over deaths of
people trying to escape to the West. In both cases, their defense
was similar -- the ends justified the means. By Kevin Cullen. 1100
words.
</P>
<P>
   PROFILE-ARKAN (Belgrade) _ The story of Arkan, Yugoslavia's
dreaded paramilitary leader and post-modern gangster, and the
society that created, celebrated and eventually destroyed him. By
Kevin Cullen. 1450 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (London) _ Londoners have been crowing as
American celebrities take up residence in a city they see as more
liveable than New York or Los Angeles. But there's one wannabe
Londoner the British seem eager to keep out -- Mike Tyson. By Kevin
Cullen. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
