<HEADLINE>
TUPPERWARE PARTY MEETS TO ELECT THE NEXT U.S. PRESIDENT  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Jan. 24 _ Iowa Caucus)   (This timely 550-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINGO, IOWA _ It is a perfect winter's morning _ the sun
sparkling off the snowy fields, the sky a perfect blue with just a
brush stroke of cloud across the horizon. Out in the woods, the
deer are scudding through the snow, and two red-tailed hawks are
circling lazily through the oak and hickory trees.
</P>
<P>
   But John Parsons has no time to watch the wildlife today. He is
clearing the snow from his drive in his bright green John Deere
tractor.
</P>
<P>
   This is democracy at work, Iowa-style.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight (Monday), Parsons and his wife, Jenifer, will welcome a
dozen or so of their neighbors to help choose the next president of
the United States in the first electoral event of the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   Like a hundred or so others across Iowa, they will be holding a
caucus to decide who they think should be the candidate, in their
case for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the grass-roots level,'' he says. ``This is the bottom
of the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   What will be going on Monday, on this bottom rung, will be the
first stage in the process of choosing representatives who will
finally, at the party's convention in August, choose the Democrats'
man.
</P>
<P>
   It is a peculiarity of the U.S. system that Iowa gets to choose
first, ahead of far larger states. ``I don't know how Iowa ever got
to be first,'' says Parsons with a grin. Asked if it makes any
sense, he says simply: ``Somebody's got to be first.''
</P>
<P>
   He is backing Al Gore, the front-runner for the Democrats and
likely victor. ``He's always been a strong supporter of the
environment,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, a wiry man with a grizzled beard and a ready laugh, is
the park ranger here at the Ashton Wildwood Nature Reserve, a
hundred hilly acres of woods thick with deer and wild turkey.
Outside the window, purple finches, goldfinches and bright red
cardinals peck at the seed he has set out.
</P>
<P>
   It is a world away from Washington, D.C., and the popular image
of power in America, propelled by television advertisements,
thousand-dollar lunches and corporate jets.
</P>
<P>
   But the solid heritage of rural democracy is fading. Only a
hundred or so of the caucuses out of 2,100 are still held in homes.
The rest are in schools, churches, community centers, American
Legion halls and fire stations, the infrastructure of civil society
that is spread across this large, flat state.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Iowa was mainly agricultural; now, the small farmers are
in retreat, and from Ankeny and Bondurante and a hundred other
towns, suburbs are sprouting into the cornfields speckled with
snow.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those gathered around the tables at the Parsons' will be
farmers; the rest are in business, commuting into Des Moines or
Newton, where there is a big Maytag factory making dishwashers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parsons was still at church Sunday, but much of the work
had already been done. Loads of cookies are stacked on paper plates
under tin foil in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Today (Monday) they will move back the solid wooden furniture in
the front room, and extend the dining room table. There will be
coffee, though Parsons doesn't drink it himself. He will eat the
cookies, though. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this timely 550-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
