<HEADER>
A4902 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-24 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRAFFIC RELIEF AT THE PUSH OF A BUTTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Quantities of studies inform us that it's getting
harder to get around town, almost anywhere in America. Even areas
merely holding their own in population are nevertheless finding
their roads and highways more congested as more autos take to the
road.
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly true for Albany, where we cling for dear life
to the magical 100,000 population figure and the federal largess
that accompanies it. Authoritative reports detail the growth in
traffic over the decades. Absent the surveys, drivers would know
from personal experience how often they have to sit and wait in a
long line for the light to change to green.
</P>
<P>
   All manner of devices are promised in the near future to
measurably reduce these annoyances, for that is what they are. On
our worst days, our problems are not in the running compared to New
York City or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Appreciating that modest size does not in every circumstance
equate with a disadvantage should not mean, however, that we settle
for what we've got when something better is readily available.
</P>
<P>
   While we await the installation of high-tech super smart
devices, software, fiber-optics and video cameras that will
accurately gauge traffic flow, adjust the duration of traffic
lights accordingly and redirect traffic away from jams, we can turn
to technology available today to upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is adjusting the lights so that at a given moderate
speed a driver will be able to proceed for blocks upon many blocks
without having to stop at nearly each intersection.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, in fact, that is already happening. Only
recently, a hardly comprehensive personal survey found that one
could proceed through as many as three traffic lights without
having to stop. While that is not the perfection, it is still very
much an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   How disheartening, then, to find that immediately after that
first red light, the second was only a block down the road. Some
more tinkering is in order.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that Albany was notorious for a system that
guaranteed a car would have to come to a halt at every
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   To account for this peculiar situation, Albany residents, long
experienced to living in the fiefdom of an entrenched political
machine, found the explanation in politics. It was widely believed
that the frequency of traffic stops was part of a fix. The machine,
the reasoning went, wanted to reward its special supporters in the
auto repair and gas station trade. Forcing cars to pull up at every
block or second block guaranteed heavy wear and tear on the brakes
and the tires, along with the consumption of extra gallons of
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The misalliance between the City Hall machine and certain repair
shops was also said to account for the long life potholes enjoyed
in season.
</P>
<P>
   As equivocal as that explanation appears given the absence of
iron-clad proof, its wide acceptance says something about our
culture.
</P>
<P>
   At all events, that took place in long-gone bad old days. Here
we are in the year 2000, and those sorts of things no longer
happen, if they ever did. Consequently there should be no
impediment to staggering the lights and speeding up traffic as an
everyday sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   The temperament of drivers would be infused with a beneficial
dose of internal calm. Road rage would be mitigated. While we would
remain a city standing on our tippy toes to come up with 100,000
souls, we would be a happier community.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the fewer stops would lead to a measurable
reduction in the hundreds of tons of bad stuff, like carbon
monoxide and hydrocarbons, put into the air we and our families and
friends inhale each year.
</P>
<P>
   By using up less fuel, we would help our nation's balance of
trade. Importation of oil has helped take that imbalance to a
record high.
</P>
<P>
   Adding up all the savings, each driver is sure to pocket
something in the neighborhood of $300 a year, money which could be
spent in the state lottery or in the state-sanctioned casinos that
are being planned.
</P>
<P>
   In short, those people with their finger on the traffic button
have the opportunity to create so much good, for so many, so
quickly. All they need to do is to do it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
