<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BUYS-WHITEHOUSE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUSH IS THE CANDIDATE OF THE LEAR JET SET'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES - George W. Bush, the leading Republican candidate
for U.S. President, has built his political career on donations
from a small group of wealthy corporate donors, a new report
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   All of the candidates have raised large sums from business and
all are subject to charges of pandering to corporate interests. But
Bush is particularly vulnerable to charges of buying the election.
</P>
<P>
   He has raised a record $67 million already, far more than any of
his opponents, Democrat or Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accuse him of letting big business run the state while
he was Governor of Texas. And after the fund-raising scandals of
the Clinton Administration, the seamy side of campaign finance is
finally starting to raise America's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Texans for Public Justice, a lobby group, calculates that Bush
received $3 million from just 100 wealthy businessmen and women for
his Texas Governor's campaigns in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small group of business tycoons were instrumental in putting
George Bush in the Governor's Mansion,'' said Craig L. McDonald,
Director of Texans for Public Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A disturbing number of these profiteers made a fortune off
government handouts or by bending or breaking regulatory rules.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no limits on campaign donations in Texas state
contests. ``Bush raised $10 million from just 207 donors who gave
at least $25,000,'' says the report.
</P>
<P>
   Top of the list of donors are Charles and Sam Wyly, who gave
Bush over dollars 200,000 for his two campaigns. Their firm,
Maverick Capital Fund, received a state contract to invest
University of Texas funds in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Other donors sought reforms to limit damage payouts in civil
lawsuits, a reform which was subsequently agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Other donors include Kenneth &AMP; Linda Lay, of the energy giant
Enron; Ray L. Hunt, heir to the family oil fortune; Robert
Mosbacher and James Baker, former officials in the administration
of Bush's father, President George Bush, both of whom became paid
consultants to Enron (Baker was secretary of state during the Gulf
War); Jim Bob Moffett, who runs Freeport-McMoRan, which operates
the world's biggest gold mine in Indonesia; George and Richard
Wackenhut of the giant prison and security company Wackenhut, which
has large contracts with the state of Texas; and members of the
very wealthy Bass family, who financed one of Bush's earlier
ventures in the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is the candidate of the Lear Jet set, not the minivan
crowd, and people need to know that,'' said McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign rejects this, arguing that Bush does not grant
favors to contributors and that Bush's sweeping election victories
prove he has support across the state, not just amongst
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans know that Governor Bush has received broad-based
support from people of all walks of life across the state for his
agenda of improving public schools and cutting taxes,'' said a Bush
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the large donors also feature in the list of Bush's
Pioneers, each of whom promised to raise $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In federal campaigns there is an individual limit of $1,000 on
contributions to candidates. But more can be given to Political
Action Committees, and in some companies, many individuals combine
to give money to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``What George W. Bush and his money men are really `pioneering,'
is the next generation of the political arms race, where the sky's
the limit on spending and on special-interest money in our
presidential primaries,'' said Donald J. Simon, acting president of
the lobby group Common Cause last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate list of the top career donors to Bush, the
Campaign for Public Integrity put Enron at the top of the lost with
more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Close behind were credit card company MBNA, Vinson and Elkins, a
large Houston law firm, and the Bass family. The same names, along
with Ernst &AMP; Young, Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley, Bank of America
and Goldman Sachs, figure on a list of top donors to Bush's
presidential campaign compiled by the Center for Responsive
Politics. &QL; 
