<HEADLINE>
WILL IOWA CAUCUS PRODUCE ANY SURPRISES?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Iowa Caucus, Monday, Jan. 24)   (This TIMELY 625-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Al Gore and George W. Bush, the front-runners for
the Democrat and Republican nominations for U.S. president, both go
into today's (Monday's) Iowa caucuses as the favorites to win.
</P>
<P>
   The first event of the U.S. electoral season will see thousands
of voters trooping along to fire stations, community halls,
churches, schools and each others' houses tonight (Monday) to vote
for their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The results are sometimes hard to interpret or measure; the
significance, in a state that is hardly representative of America
in the 21st century, is uncertain in the broader context. But for
both candidates, victory would mean the first step on the road to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the Democratic challenger to Vice President Gore,
received an unexpected fillip Sunday when the Des Moines Register
endorsed his candidacy. The state's leading paper said that it had
found the choice very difficult, but on balance, the former
basketball player and U.S. senator was their man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task involves looking for the leader whose ideas and
approach to governing most closely match the needs of the times,''
said the paper. ``That's where we give the edge to Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   But the opinion polls have less good news. A poll in the
Register gave Gore a comfortable 56 percent, rising from 54 percent
earlier this month, while Bradley had slipped from 33 percent to 28
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger has been weakened by indecision about whether and
how to respond to criticism from Gore, and by reports of his own
heart problems, which while not life-threatening undercut the image
of a vital and healthy former athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're behind,'' said Bradley at the weekend. ``Maybe
we'll surprise a few people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore now has the advantage over Bradley in New Hampshire
according to several polls, but given the difficulties of measuring
opinion it is probably too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Less surprising was the Register's decision to endorse Bush, the
Governor of Texas. He seems set for a wide victory in Iowa: the
only element that remains to be decided is his margin of victory,
which could have a big impact on the New Hampshire primary in a
week's time, the next big campaign event.
</P>
<P>
   In the northeastern state Bush is behind Senator John McCain,
his main Republican challenger, according to most polls, but again
realistically it is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the billionaire publisher, seems assured of second
place for the Republicans in Iowa. Third place is a much tighter
race, but Alan Keyes, the Christian conservative broadcaster and
the only black candidate, was making a strong showing.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion has been one of the key issues in a religious,
conservative state, and Keyes has run some very strongly worded,
clear advertisements on television.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, another Christian conservative, was fighting for
third place with Keyes, but his campaign looked to be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has the support of 43 percent of likely Republican
participants, the poll says, a little down from the last such
sounding. But Forbes is stuck at 20 percent; Keyes and Bauer are
all at 4 percent. So is McCain, the senator from Arizona, even
though he has not campaigned in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The number of voters from both parties who are either not sure
or uncommitted remains well above 10 percent. One of the biggest
dangers for all the candidates is that voters will assume that the
result is a foregone conclusion and fail to turn out.
</P>
<P>
   There are many nicer places to be on a cold winter's night than
the local American Legion post, arguing about politics. &QL; 
