<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-OH-WHY?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA, NEW HAMPSHIRE: NO LONGER JUST `RIDICULOUS' TESTS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Iowa Caucus, Monday, Jan. 24)   (This TIMELY 1,025-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just 12 years ago, a certain U.S. senator by the
name of Al Gore dismissed the presidential selection process that
takes place in the Midwestern state of Iowa this evening (Monday)
as ``an arcane procedure that produces crazy results.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, he said of the small local gatherings known as the Iowa
caucuses, ``a ridiculous test'' and he ignored the whole charade,
proceeding directly to what he then regarded as the more sane and
sensible primary election in the Northeastern state of New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it need hardly be said, Gore has rethought his view of
the Iowa caucuses, the first formal leg of the four-yearly race for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Now vice-president of the United States and favorite for the
Democratic Party's nomination, Gore has the might of the party
machine behind him and claims to have learned his lesson: ``You
gotta come here and campaign here, you gotta work hard here,'' he
says in the Southern demotic he adopts when he wants to present
himself as a man of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Lavishing time, money and attention on this small, sparsely
populated state may indeed be the way to win in Iowa, and in New
Hampshire, too, and everywhere else. But whether Iowa and New
Hampshire are the most appropriate places for Americans to start
choosing their president is quite another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was surely right the first time: it is ``ridiculous'' that
these two states get to vote for the party nominees before anywhere
else, and so set the tone for what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore's original comments showed, there have long been
misgivings about the preeminence of these two states in the
selection process, largely because they are so untypical of the
United States as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   They are smaller, wealthier, more rural and more white _ much
more white _ than most other states. Yet no candidate wants to
attack their preeminence while he needs their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa and New Hampshire, of course, have a host of well-rehearsed
arguments for keeping the system exactly as it is, which range from
the conservative _ ``We've always done it this way and it works'' _
to the patronizing: ``Our voters are especially well informed and
take their responsibilities especially seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   A more down to earth justification would be that these two early
rounds have not had much bearing on the final choice: crisscrossing
Iowa and New Hampshire is more a rehearsal for the election proper,
a test of stamina and political resilience that weeds out the
no-hopers, allowing the rest to proceed to the later rounds.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate who wins in Iowa, in fact, has almost never emerged
at the end of the primary process with his party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does every Iowan or New Hampshirite accept that their states
are untypical. Neither state is nearly as rural as it used to be;
many thousands of people have moved from the land to the cities and
work in the new tech or service sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants from Mexico and former Yugoslavia have moved in to
Iowa to work in the giant meat packing plants (otherwise known as
slaughter houses); drugs, crime and racial tensions have
proliferated in a state unaccustomed to such problems.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, too, claims to be ``typical'' in the decline of
manufacturing jobs, the boom generated by the high-tech sector, the
widening gap between rich and poor and the competition for land
between development and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments, though, stretch the point. The fact is that for
all the changes they have experienced in the past 12 years, these
states may be demographically even less representative of the
country than they were.
</P>
<P>
   Both have lost population in that time, while the Southern
states have gained. The proportion of nonwhites, especially
Hispanics, in the population as a whole has increased, while these
states have remained more than 95 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, they are conservative. What is more, the election
timetable has evolved in such a way as to boost the influence of
the early primary states, for this year at least.
</P>
<P>
   Many states advanced their primaries this year, compressing the
main part of the season into just a few weeks. By March 15, 28
states will have chosen their nominee, including those like
California, New York, New Jersey and Texas, with large numbers of
delegates to the nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa brought its caucuses forward by three weeks, and New
Hampshire followed suit. The result is that _ despite intensive
campaigning by the candidates _ voters have hardly woken up to the
idea that an election campaign is in progress, and the compression
of the season means that there is less time for a lesser known
candidate to become more widely recognized or for a candidate
disappointed in an early primary to regroup and recover.
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that if and when the voters do wake up _
to find that the nominations have been decided almost without them
_ they will call foul and force a change in the timetable in four
years' time.
</P>
<P>
   For this year, though, Iowa and New Hampshire are dictating both
the pace and the issues of the campaign, and they are the concerns
of farmers, pensioners and the relatively well off.
</P>
<P>
   While other issues _ those of urban poverty, race and trade _
will undoubtedly make themselves heard in the weeks to come, the
contest could be effectively over by then.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will any other state attract the same attention or money
from would be presidential nominees as Iowa and New Hampshire. This
year there is simply no time.
</P>
<P>
   If a shorter primary season leaves more time for the
presidential campaign proper, then perhaps some will deem that not
much has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   But as Iowans prepare for their caucuses, the impression is of a
contest that was over almost before it began, where the party
establishments dictated the terms and where a gifted outsider _
like President Bill Clinton _ would have had neither the time nor
the geographical space to present his case to the people. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 1,025-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
