<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-IOWA (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Results, color and analysis from
the Iowa Republican caucuses, where polls suggest that Texas George
W. Bush is ahead of rivals Steve Forbes and John McCain. By R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-IOWA (Des Moines, Iowa) _ We analyze the results from the
Iowa Democratic caucuses, where polls suggest that Vice President
Al Gore is well ahead of former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley. By
ALAN BERNSTEIN and PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   CAUCUSES-PROFILE (Waterloo, Iowa) _ Up to 1,000 Republicans and
Democrats file through the front doors of massive West High School
here to attend their respective caucuses. As is the case across
Iowa, Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush are the
best organized, but local politicos say there may be a few
surprises. This industrial town, still recovering from the economic
abyss of the 1980s when unemployment reached 20 percent, is a
microcosm of all the optimism mixed with uncertainty that Iowans
bring to the 2,100 precinct caucuses statewide. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ We look at how George W. Bush
plans to parlay his predicted Iowa victory into another win in New
Hampshire, where Arizona Sen. John McCain is running a strong
challenge in the Republican presidential contest. By R.G.
RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-POLL (New York) _ Most women believe the Republican Party
best serves the interests of men, according to a new survey of more
than 3,000 women by Women.com Networks Inc. and Good Housekeeping
magazine. The November 1999 survey conducted online and via
telephone assessed the political behavior and beliefs of American
women. By The Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CAMPAIGN-CONTRIBUTIONS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court
rules that states can impose limits on campaign contributions to
political candidates. In a 6-3 vote, the court says Missouri did
not violate free-speech rights when it capped individual
contributions at $1,075 for state races. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONFEDERATE-STATUE (Anderson, Texas) _ On Tuesday, an Anderson
man will go before the state historical commission with his
proposal to erect a Confederate statue in front of the Grimes
County Courthouse. The man's efforts have been blasted by black
ministers and others who believe the statue symbolically looks to
the past as an unwarranted reminder of slavery. And the passionate
skirmish could force Gov. George W. Bush to face a debate at home
that he has sidestepped in his presidential bid. By JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-CRIME-LAWSUIT (North Richland Hills, Texas) _ A drug raid
that led to a fatal shooting at the home of a true-crime author in
a Fort Worth suburb has resulted in a lawsuit, a flurry of
speculations and an entanglement on the World Wide Web. The raid
occurred Dec. 15 at the home of Barbara Davis, author of ``Precious
Angels,'' a story of the 1997 murder trial of Darlie Routier, who
was convicted in the slaying of her two young sons. Davis believed
that Routier was innocent and was one of her biggest supporters. By
EVAN MOORE.
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE-DENTISTS (Combs, Texas) _ The gleaming 35-foot motor home
parked next to Dishman Elementary is becoming a familiar sight at
schools in the Rio Grande Valley. Shortly before classes began one
Wednesday, the brand-new motor coach pulled up to the school
building and 79 students were escorted by the school nurse into an
on-board, state-of-the-art dental clinic. For many poor children in
South Texas, these visits were their first encounter with a
dentist. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   RYLANDER-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ She's been mayor of Austin,
author of a diet book and now she's state comptroller. What else
has Carole Keeton Rylander set her sights on? By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRYPERS-LATIN-AMERICA (Moji Das Cruzes, Brazil) _ A line of
inexpensive diapers being produced in Brazil by Houston-based
Drypers marks the company's effort to absorb the effects of the
devaluation of the Brazilian currency, the real. The 1999
devaluation was one of a series of events in Latin America that
soiled earnings. Drypers has survived the economic beatings and
learned important lessons about international markets along the
way. By JENALIA MORENO (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ To some extent, we all use our ethics
and values to guide financial decisions. We spend money with
companies that validate our beliefs and avoid those that don't.
Businesses know this and they spend billions of dollars to market
themselves as diverse, charitable, family-friendly, environmentally
conscious or any other trait that their target consumers esteem.
But only recently has socially responsible investing been taken
seriously by Wall Street. By SHANNON BUGGS (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Houston) _ There is evidence that in some
specific kinds of situations, women do make superior managers. The
evidence isn't conclusive. But it does bear thinking about. That's
the conclusion of a study by three academics _ Nigel F. Pierce and
Nikala Lane of Cardiff University in Britain and David W. Cravens
of Texas Christian University in Fort Worth, Texas. By JIM BARLOW.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-MILITARY (Quito, Ecuador) _ We examine the role of the
military after a weekend rebellion forced out President Jamil
Mahuad and briefly ushered in a military junta. The coup leaders
eventually decided to give way to Mahuad's vice president, and
Gustavo Noboa, a low-key lawyer, was named president of Ecuador on
Sunday. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ As Hillary Rodham Clinton prepares
to move from a flirtation with the New York Senate race to an
irreversible commitment, she is dogged by gossip about the shaky
state of her marriage. This is inevitable; as a superstar, she is
an object of curiosity. Her task now is to throw up enough issues
dust to cloud speculation about her private life and to get voters
to detour to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's own personal problems. She's
already started, attacking his temper and mild pro-choice position,
but it won't be easy. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ The Confederate flag in South
Carolina and ballot access in New York may be totally unrelated
issues in the real world. But in the supercharged atmosphere of
presidential politics, they have found a common target in George W.
Bush. And the Republican hopeful's efforts to dodge both weaken his
own vow to usher in an era of moral leadership in the White House.
By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
