<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-COMMENT-HEALTHCARE-BO     01-24 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENT-HEALTHCARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REAL COST OF AN HMO CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN SAGER AND DEBORAH SOCOLAR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care's distress is the latest and loudest
warning yet that health insurance and care in Massachusetts are in
crisis. While serious, the problems can be addressed _ but not
without a direct dollar cost today to all who work or do business
here, a fact easily ignored in the current debate.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Which pocket will we pay from? If Harvard
Pilgrim Health Care sells itself to a for-profit insurer, consumers
will bear even higher premium costs. If it defaults, doctors,
hospitals, and Wall Street all raise the prices they charge us. If
state-subsidized private loans rescue it, we pay higher premiums
and possibly higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   None of these three options is ideal. But something must be
done; our health maintenance organizations and hospitals are too
big and too important to let fail.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is to help Harvard Pilgrim address its short-term
revenue problem, and its middle-term management problem, without
worsening patients' long-term cost and coverage problems. The
further challenge is to do so in a way that builds a foundation for
improving the system.
</P>
<P>
   The first option, a takeover by a for-profit insurer, would cost
the most, both in dollars and in compromised care. Finding the
extra money required to pay stockholders would mean raising
premiums even faster than they are go
</P>
<P>
   ing up now _ the equivalent of spraying gasoline on a fire. And
doctors would have to squeeze care to pump profits through the
money pipeline to Hartford or Minneapolis. Quality would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on a for-profit takeover allows state government to wash
its hands of a problem that its inaction helped create, freeing it
to repeat its mistakes, rather than learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   The second option, default, would destabilize many hospitals and
doctors. It would prompt Wall Street to raise the cost of much
capital loaned in Massachusetts _ a cost that would quickly be
passed on to consumers. This at a time when Massachusetts health
care costs are already stratospheric.
</P>
<P>
   At $6,100 per person this year, Massachusetts has the world's
costliest care _ more than 30 percent above the US average.
Statewide health spending this year will reach $38 billion, almost
double the total state budget.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost was headed sharply up even before the Harvard
Pilgrim crisis. Annual 8 to 15 percent premium increases will total
perhaps 25 to 40 percent over the next three or four years. This
would force many employers and workers to drop health insurance,
leaving hundreds of thousands more people without coverage here,
even before the next recession.
</P>
<P>
   The third option, a state-supported bailout, means that
taxpayers face some risks. As undesirable as this is to many, it is
preferable to the other two options.
</P>
<P>
   State grants should not be needed; a state-supported loan
guarantee for Harvard Pilgrim's short-term financing should
suffice. While it would impose a small dollar risk on taxpayers, it
would probably amount to the most modest cost increases for health
care consumers, and best move us toward durably affordable care.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, unless state government faces some financial exposure,
however small, it will not have reason to protect HMOs from the
cost of their own mistakes in the future. And it won't protect us
from the cost of those mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A workable solution must reflect a thorough understanding of how
we got to where we are.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO, hospital, nursing home, and drug industries blame their
problems on low revenue. Anti-hospital groups blame excess
hospitals and beds. Some economists blame patients for resisting
HMOs' restrictions on care. Anti-government factions blame
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   These explanations are largely untrue. The main problem is high
cost, not inadequate revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Massachusetts health spending so high? In part, it is
because we face legitimately higher costs in such areas as research
and physician training. Mainly, however, it is because our doctors
use more elaborate and costly services than the norm. This reflects
both the teaching hospitals' dominance and a huge number of doctors
_ 64 percent above the national average.
</P>
<P>
   No villains drove Massachusetts hospital spending to 42 percent
above the US average in 1998, while hospitals cut nurses but had to
hire more clerks to collect money owed by HMOs. Costs rose and
quality fell when Massachusetts gambled on price competition,
managed care, and hospital closings to contain costs during the
1990s. All failed.
</P>
<P>
   A decade of intense price competition has not contained cost.
The few HMOs or hospitals competing in each region of the state
often merged or low-balled prices to build regional monopolies.
Powerful hospitals have tried to engineer their survival behind
smokescreens of competition rhetoric, often at the expense of
smaller institutions. Many needed hospitals are in very bad
financial shape because they cost more than we are able to afford.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing close to a free market exists in health care. Many
wealthy hospitals survived, while many efficient and needed
hospitals closed. Costs rose while access deteriorated. Further,
managed care bred strange new layers of private bureaucracy faster
than it contained clinical cost. Our state's share of people
enrolled in HMOs is 79 percent greater than the nation's, but our
health costs exceed the national average by 30 percent, or $9
billion, this year.
</P>
<P>
   To compete by price, HMOs increasingly relied on bribing
hospitals and doctors to withhold care, thus angering and
frightening patients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How do we get out of the mess highlighted by the Harvard Pilgrim
debacle?
</P>
<P>
   Government-financed care for all would facilitate covering
everyone and controlling costs, reducing administrative and
clinical waste. But that seems unlikely to pass soon. Here is a
nine-step alternative:
</P>
<P>
   First, in exchange for financial security, HMOs and hospitals
must accept careful and sustained public oversight _ including caps
on administrative spending and limits on revenue growth. Both must
accept uniform industry-wide accounting. HMOs must completely and
accurately report monthly on reserves, revenues, and accrued costs.
Instead of relying on mergers and price increases, HMOs should test
new ways to work with their physicians to spend finite dollars
better.
</P>
<P>
   Second, state government must identify the hospitals, beds, and
emergency rooms required to protect the public's health now, and as
baby boomers age. It must also identify hospitals facing financial
distress.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the state should create a new security fund, financed by
a 0.25 percent assessment on all hospitals' revenue, that would
offer emergency aid to distressed but needed hospitals. The state
should also help endangered hospitals with debt refinancing, and
seek receivership authority to stabilize failing but vital
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, the state must guarantee adequate (but capped) revenue
for all needed hospitals, as long as they are operated efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth, HMOs, which have failed to win lower prices from drug
producers, should support government negotiation with drug makers
for statewide discounts. Government should also press drug makers
to contribute, in cash or in capsules, prescription drugs for
people who cannot afford even discounted prices. Drug makers can
afford it. Even after financing research, their profit margins are
the highest in the country, 39.4 percent of equity in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth, the role of government and the role of competition in
health care should be reversed. It is futile to continue to use
market competition to contain cost, and government to protect
quality. Instead, let government contain cost and let HMOs,
doctors, and hospitals compete by quality and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on either competition or government alone is reckless.
Had our Navy relied solely on battleships _ and not also deployed
aircraft carriers _ in the 1930s, the Battle of Midway would have
been only an unopposed Japanese occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh, state government must assure coverage for everyone.
That requires briefly slowing the rise in payments to caregivers.
Less than half of one year's increase in statewide health spending
would buy conventional coverage for all 625,000 people now
uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth, state government must wake from its 10-year health care
siesta and work with all parties to design and test solutions.
Federal action may come too late for our state. (Critics of
government programs in Canada or England should recognize that
waiting times there for elective surgery reflect economies too weak
to finance care at US levels, not flaws in their health care
systems.)
</P>
<P>
   Ninth, pay doctors fairly, without incentives to give too little
or too much care. Freeing them from financial risk allows them to
think clinically. But we should also hold doctors accountable for
spending our money carefully.
</P>
<P>
   All this will require many years of continuous engagement, not
just occasional postcards, from business, workers, and especially
state government. Without a free market, government's absence makes
anarchy inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   We should begin these changes now, during the fat years of our
state's economy. We already enjoy the dollars and the doctors, the
competence and compassion, to take good care of all who live here.
If we heed the wake-up call from Harvard Pilgrim's crash, we can
avert the crisis in coverage, cost and caregiver survival that
looms before us all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alan Sager and Deborah Socolar are co-principals in the Access and
Affordability Monitoring Project at the Boston University School of
Public Health.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
