<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A storehouse of knowledge
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By C. Merrell Calhoun
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   A gentle giant in spirit and outlook, that was my father.
</P>
<P>
   He was gentlemanly, gracious, big hearted and soft-spoken, but
oh so strong in mind and body.
</P>
<P>
   He led by example, and I learned from the deft patience of his
teaching and in the reflected glow of his wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   And through his leadership and camaraderie as a father, I
learned the meaning of being a son truly blessed.
</P>
<P>
   My classrooms were his '37 Chevrolet pickup truck, the sales
floor, stockrooms and loading docks of Calhoun's Market in our
hometown of Talbotton, Ga., our churches and meeting halls, and the
shady banks of the area's myriad ponds and streams.
</P>
<P>
   I'll forever treasure the many early mornings of my pre-teen
years when we journeyed together to Columbus in the Chevy pickup
for our regular visits to the city's curb markets, grain mills and
wholesale grocery emporiums.
</P>
<P>
   We were there for the replenishment and expansion of his store's
rich and varied inventories.
</P>
<P>
   The Farmers' Co-Op, located beneath the railroad viaduct, was a
veritable horn of plenty for every imaginable fruit and vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the Cosby-Hodges Milling Co. and other bulk
granaries supplied the heavy demand for flour, meal, chicken
``scratch'' and animal foods.
</P>
<P>
   On the town's western border near the shores of the
Chattahoochee River stood the venerable Sol Loeb Co., the region's
mecca for just about every canned food, staple, spice and flavoring
yet produced.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, at those and other adventurous stops, my father
would shrewdly negotiate lower prices or discounts for volume
purchases, and compute the savings in his head.
</P>
<P>
   And it was there that I absorbed his priceless lessons in
frugality and economics that have stayed with me throughout my
life.
</P>
<P>
   Our solitary truck rides _ indeed, joy rides _ to and from these
Columbus vendors lent added hours of quality time for a seemingly
endless stream of questions and answers on every subject. You might
call it ``home-schooling on wheels.''
</P>
<P>
   In moments like these, Father's zany, off-the-wall sense of
humor would also surface.
</P>
<P>
   While some folks today might call it corny, I remembered it as
breakthrough comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are your feet smelling and your nose running?'' he might ask.
``Or are your feet running and your nose smelling?''
</P>
<P>
   The unforgettable jokes and stories, intermingled with more
serious dialogue, became the glue of permanent bonding.
</P>
<P>
   Once back at the store in Talbotton, it was always a thrill to
help with the off-loading of the merchandise ... then to unpack it,
price-mark it, put it on display in the bins and shelves ... and
finally to pitch its purchase to the incoming customers and deliver
it by bike to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sort of start-up course in Distributive Education, as
it were, carefully monitored by the master teacher himself.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (C. Merrell Calhoun lives in Atlanta. This story is excerpted
from his privately published book, ``Flashbacks: A Boy Grows In
Talbotton,'' written for his children.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(at)lcc.net.) A photo of the
writer is optional. If your article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
