<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-24 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE ON THE EDGE  
 DOGFIGHTER BUTTERFLIES  
 HIGH-FLYING ASTRONOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like pioneers on the plains, species that are threatened or
endangered have long been thought to take a circle-the-wagons
approach. That is, a population headed toward extinction responds
by contracting inward, reducing its range to a central core. Those
left on the periphery, in less favorable habitats, are thought to
have less chance to survive.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study of 245 endangered or recently extinct species
around the world, everything from giant pandas to tiny mollusks,
shows that this idea does not necessarily hold. And the finding has
major implications for conservation biology.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by researchers from Kansas and Oklahoma and reported
in the journal Nature, compared present-day distribution of the
species with their historical ranges. About two-thirds of the
species had greater than expected portions of their populations on
the periphery. And 91 species had all of their population on the
periphery; only 5 had all in the core.
</P>
<P>
   Not unexpectedly, the researchers point to humans as the major
reason for this. Habitat destruction and pollution, among other
things, can overwhelm the natural tendency of a population to
contract inward. The creatures that survive are those on the edge,
at high elevations or otherwise isolated in pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the study may cause some conservation biologists
to reconsider where they focus their efforts. The researchers note
that peripheral areas used to be known as the ``land of the living
dead,'' but now they may be viewed as the places to keep species
alive. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali aside, some butterflies do not really float. M.
heliconiaria, for instance, a nocturnal Central American butterfly,
dives, sputters, darts and swoops, all to avoid becoming a bat's
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Just how it figures out the location of the bat is the subject
of a study reported in Nature by two Canadian scientists. And the
result is surprising: M. heliconiaria is the only known butterfly
that has ultrasonic hearing. It picks up a bat's echolocation
signals and maneuvers quickly out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied live specimens of the butterflies and
discovered that they have tiny ears that move with the wings. When
the butterflies were exposed to ultrasound, they responded by
climbing steeply, spiraling and otherwise swooping around, in no
predictable fashion. The researchers note that this maneuverability
is of selective advantage in a dogfight with a bat.
</P>
<P>
   Most butterflies, of course, seldom get in such dogfights. Most
are diurnal, active during the day, when bats are back in the
belfry. In fact, the researchers say, fossil evidence suggests that
it was intense pressure from bats that aided most butterflies'
evolution as daytime creatures about 50 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For a butterfly without ultrasonic hearing, being active during
the day offered an evolutionary advantage, allowing it to avoid
bats and float to its heart's content. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers with the Southwest Research Institute may be
forgiven if they seem to have developed a certain Chuck Yeager-like
swagger lately. A program that puts astronomers in the back seat of
high performance military-type jets is now operational.
</P>
<P>
   The program is designed to collect data about planets or
asteroids during occultations, or the passing of one of these
bodies in front of a star. Using a plane enables astronomers to
observe more of these events and also practically eliminates the
possibility that cloud cover will spoil the viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have made airborne observations for years, of
course, but mostly from larger or slower aircraft. The Southwest
Research Institute program uses two NASA jets, a high-altitude
weather plane and a modified F-18.
</P>
<P>
   Although they do not actually fly the planes, the astronomers
have had to go through some flight training, including learning how
to eject.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1627EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
