<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-COMMUTER-MARRIAGE-2TA     01-24 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUTER-MARRIAGE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTONS AREN'T THE ONLY COMMUTER COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gary McLouth, a college professor and the at-home
spouse in a commuter marriage, wasn't prepared for the fallout from
the job his wife, a lawyer, took in New York City eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   McLouth was suddenly alone in a rambling old colonial house in
near Albany with Sam, his wife's cat, a feline both distressed and
spiteful about the new arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cat was really mad at me for what was going on, and the
cat was throwing up, and I had the cat in a box, carrying it around
this big house,'' McLouth said. His wife's once-lush houseplants
began withering on the vine, too, under McLouth's amateur care.
</P>
<P>
   The cat and the plants weren't the only ones suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very depressed about commuting,'' said his wife,
Providence Baker. ``I'm tired, stressed and unhappy about being
away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last May, Baker has commuted to lower Manhattan, where she
works as deputy counsel for New York state Division of Housing and
Community Renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Baker got caught in what she called a political battle and was
fired last spring after 18 years in the state attorney general's
office, where she managed the tort unit. Baker took the New York
City job because she couldn't find anything locally at the same
level of responsibility or salary.
</P>
<P>
   McLouth and Baker said the grind of the commute and spending
weekdays apart has strained their 12-year marriage and caused them
to become uncharacteristically sullen and snappish with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us expected it to be this difficult,'' Baker said.
``We've changed in ways we don't like. We're both unhappy and
generally frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   The trials and tribulations of commuter marriages are being
revisited and re-examined these days, with the eyes of the world on
the arrangement of Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton and open
speculation on the state of the first couple's union.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Hillary Clinton _ the putative U.S. Senate
candidate who needed to establish New York residency _ moved into a
$1.7 million Dutch colonial at 15 Old House Lane in Chappaqua,
Westchester County. For now, the President Clinton's permanent
address is 1600 Pennsylvania Ave.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' commuter marriage is the talk of the therapist
community, and the tongue-wagging is not positive, according to
Maureen Sullivan, a clinical social worker with a private therapy
practice in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Hillary moved into the house and they started living
separately, it raised all kinds of red flags for me,'' Sullivan
said. ``I think the Clintons are still avoiding dealing with the
real intimacy and betrayal issues they have as a couple, and living
apart doesn't begin to heal a deeply wounded marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan believes commuter marriages can survive and even grow
stronger despite a long-distance relationship. ``It takes a solid
and established marriage that has a high degree of trust built into
it to make a commuter marriage work,'' said Sullivan, who is
currently counseling a couple struggling with issues that have
arisen from commuting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marriage has to be the priority and not the job,''
Sullivan said. ``Marriage is always hard work, and a commuter
marriage is even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   For 11 years, Kathy Doolittle, a bank administrator, flew
between her home in Schodack in eastern New York and her job in
Buffalo. Her husband, Larry, a lawyer, stayed behind to raise a
niece the couple takes care of and to tend to domestic duties.
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle's weekly Friday return from Buffalo sent a ripple of
fear through the house: ``Clean up. The wicked witch of the West is
coming home,'' her niece and husband joked.
</P>
<P>
   The Doolittles _ she's now a banking consultant and her husband
is retired _ haven't had to juggle the commuter arrangement since
1992. Not that she loathed everything about the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job was invigorating to me professionally,'' said
Doolittle, whose 25-year marriage survived the weekly shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't like the hermit-like existence she had, though. ``I
stayed in a hotel for 10 years, and I got tired of living that way,
even room service,'' she said. As a result of being isolated,
Doolittle said she spent 12 hours at the office most days and
brought work back to the hotel. ``There was nothing else to do. It
made me a lot more introverted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, though, the sacrifice paid off. The couple _ who
are middle-aged and do not have children of their own _ recently
sold their Schodack home of 25 years and are moving to a
condominium in Florida. They also have a weekend place in Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were lucky in that we both adjusted well to living
independently,'' Doolittle said. ``I wouldn't do a commute like
that at this stage of my life, although it made sense at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying flexible and taking it one month at a time has worked
for Betsy Lopez-Abrams and her husband, Andy Viglucci, who has
commuted for the past five years between Albany and his job in
Puerto Rico as editor of the San Juan Star newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty damn routine now, and we take plane delays and the
rest of it as it comes,'' Viglucci said.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Viglucci was based in San Juan and his wife
stayed at their Albany row house, raising their daughter, Cara, now
a junior at Princeton University. Periodically, he would fly home
or she would fly to San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just adapted to it. I never felt like it was a big
strain,'' said his wife, a former newspaper reporter and editor in
Puerto Rico, where she grew up and where the couple raised their
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't plan their commuter marriage. In 1993, Viglucci
retired from newspaper work and they relocated to Albany (where
Viglucci has roots). He only came out of retirement because the
editorship package was too good to refuse _ airline food
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years, Viglucci has restructured his job in a
way that gives him the best of both worlds. He works in San Juan
one week each month and then works from Albany by phone, fax and
e-mail the other three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not typical, but it works for us,'' said Lopez-Abrams,
who has been married to Viglucci for 20 years. ``My women friends
kept asking me how I could stand Andy commuting. I told them I'm
doing what I please and I don't have to cook every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALBANY, N.Y.: x x x cook every day.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The logistics can be daunting in maintaining residences and jobs
in two different locales.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, the attorney, tried renting an apartment in
Hastings-on-Hudson in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was $1,500 a month in rent and that was crazy for two
or three nights a week,'' Baker said. ``I tried to decorate the
apartment and make it feel homey, but I was miserable there
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few months, Baker has been staying with friends at
their Manhattan apartment. ``My friends insist I'm not imposing,
but I don't know how long I can stay with them,'' Baker said. For
now, she leaves Schodack at 5 a.m. Mondays and commutes to
Manhattan by train. She reverses the routine on Thursday nights. A
four-day workweek was part of the job package.
</P>
<P>
   Although she worked late most nights in Albany, and her husband,
an associate professor of communications at the College of Saint
Rose, sometimes taught night classes, Baker missed cooking
late-night meals for the two of them in her big kitchen. And going
out to restaurants with her husband or getting together with their
friends. (The middle-aged couple has three grown children.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple, day-to-day things we enjoyed as a couple are gone,
and I really miss it,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   On the home front, McLouth has had to face the harsh revelation
that his wife carried the load domestically. ``Prov (Providence)
was the decorator, the cook, the creative force around the house,''
McLouth said. ``I'm lucky if I can keep the cat alive and not kill
any more plants. Then there's the house budget, the car repairs,
the dry cleaning, all the consumer middle-class stuff that doesn't
get advertised. But I'm stressed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   McLouth's work on a novel hasn't progressed, either. ``I thought
this extra time alone would help my writing, but it's done the
opposite. I can't concentrate and I'm unhappy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, the therapist, saw that ache of absence between the
couple as a good sign. ``If you have a good marriage, you're going
to miss your partner,'' Sullivan said. ``And good marriages can
survive a commuting relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a mother of two, who has been married for 17 years,
may be facing the commuting conundrum herself one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is interested in moving down South,'' Sullivan
said. ``I can't imagine it working, with him down there and me
staying here. Neither of us would be happy with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1632EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-HOLOCAUST-012     01-24 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-HOLOCAUST-0125-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOLOCAUST AUTHOR ADMITS CONTROVERSIAL REPORT 'FLAWED'
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A controversial historical writer who denies as a ``big
lie'' that Jews were slaughtered in gas chambers at Auschwitz
admitted in court Monday that the study upon which he originally
based his contention was substantially flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, David Irving said he still believes that no Jews
were gassed at Auschwitz because he is unimpressed with evidence
supporting the traditional account.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are entitled to at least one unambiguous, not
read-between-the-lines, document that would give us a clear smoking
gun,'' Irving testified Monday. ``That document does not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving is suing Emory University professor Deborah Lipstadt and
her publisher Penguin Books for libel over assertions made about
him in her 1994 book, ``Denying the Holocaust: The Growing Assault
on Truth and Memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt portrayed Irving, 62, as a prominent and dangerous
``Holocaust denier,'' who believes the systematic murder of 6
million Jews by the Nazis during World War II never took place. She
also depicts him as an extremist who manipulates, distorts and
falsifies history for his own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Lipstadt's attorneys are trying to prove that Irving either has
lied or ignored evidence available to him when he has denounced
accepted accounts of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the overwhelming body of documents, physical
evidence and eyewitness accounts of the mass killings at the
infamous Nazi concentration camp, Irving said he could not accept
the accepted conclusion that the Nazis systemically killed as many
as 2 million Jews in gas chambers at the camp and then burned their
bodies in specially built furnaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't agree with this,'' Irving said. ``There are other
arguments that are just as plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving, who has never visited Auschwitz, said it was more likely
that the structures identified as gas chambers were used as
air-raid shelters or as places to administer poison gas to corpses
to kill typhus-carrying fleas and lice.
</P>
<P>
   Irving bases his assertions about Auschwitz on a 1998 report by
Fred Leuchter, an American with expertise in execution facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Leuchter concluded that the residual traces of hydrogen cyanide
_ the killing agent in the Zyklon B pellets used by the Nazis _ in
the buildings identified as chambers were too low to support the
contention that people were put to death inside. He also noted that
hydrogen cyanide levels were much higher in the nearby de-lousing
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Leuchter studied Auschwitz to provide evidence in a Canadian
court case of a man accused of publishing material that denied the
existence of gas chambers at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the Canadian case disallowed the report because he
ruled the Leuchter lacked the necessary qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Richard Rampton, who is representing Lipstadt
and Penguin, dismissed the Leuchter report as ``bunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Rampton argued that it would be expected that residual levels of
hydrogen cyanide in the gas chambers would be lower than in
de-lousing rooms because it takes 22 times more cyanide to kill
lice than it does to kill people.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent analyses of the Leuchter report have attacked the
study's methodology as well as its conclusions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rampton said that Irving has persisted in basing his
assertions on the Leuchter report, even though the historian knows
it is faulty.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches, press conferences and other public statements,
Irving has portrayed the study as conclusively discrediting the
existence of gas chambers at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say publicly what you know to be untrue about the Leuchter
report,'' Rampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Irving acknowledged that the report was seriously flawed, but he
said he still believes that its findings about the poison residue
was an important breakthrough. ``I accept that the Leuchter report
was flawed, but its findings have been replicated,'' he said.
``It's been superceded.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which is expected to last until March, will continue
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new study shows that claims attacking the Holocaust
have reached a widespread audience but have so far failed to
convince many people.
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish Committee on Monday released a survey of 11
countries during a Holocaust education conference in Stockholm this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that interpretations of World War II events
varied from country to country but few people denied the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent survey, conducted in Sweden in December, found
that 86 percent of 1,000 people had heard these claims but only 1
percent believed it possible the mass slaughter of Jews during
World War II never happened.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys, which began in 1992, found that 70 percent of
Australians, 67 percent of the French, about 60 percent of Germans
and Austrians, and about 50 percent of Britons and Americans had
heard about Holocaust denial.
</P>
<P>
   The highest proportion of people who said it seemed possible the
Nazi extermination of 6 million Jews never happened was in East
Germany, with one out of every 10 believing this.
</P>
<P>
   Seven percent of Britons and Austrians, 5 percent of French, 4
percent of Australians, 2 percent of Russians and 1 percent of
Americans and Poles said it was possible the Holocaust did not
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
