<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SURVEY: MEN RELAX, WOMEN WORK OUTSIDE OF SCHOOL
 &HT;    (400&AMP;add)
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add also suitable for textbox or graphic.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the formal workday ends, many women keep
working and many men veg out.
</P>
<P>
   That Dagwood-and-Blondie pattern emerges as early as the senior
year of high school, according to a survey published Monday by
researchers at the University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, UCLA researchers asked 364,546 freshmen at 462
four-year and two-year American colleges and universities to fill
out questionnaires about their activities _ beyond school and a
paid job _ during their senior year of high school.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers examined 261,217 responses selected as a
balanced sample that mirrors all of the 1.6 million seniors who
entered college last year.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The boys were 15 times as likely as the girls to report
spending six hours or more a week playing video games.
</P>
<P>
   By smaller margins, they also were more likely than girls to
report spending that much time exercising or playing sports,
watching TV and partying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The girls were twice as likely as the boys to report spending
six hours or more a week on housework and child-care.
</P>
<P>
   By smaller margins, they were also more likely than boys to
report spending that much time studying, taking part in student
clubs or groups, or performing volunteer work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of the problems working women face, you
see the same pattern,'' said Linda J. Sax, who directed the survey
by UCLA's Higher Education Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women tend to multi-task, taking on a lot of different
responsibilities simultaneously all their lives, whether they're
students trying to balance their course work and extracurricular
activities, or career women trying to balance their paid jobs and
responsibilities at home.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she said, a lot of men seem to spend a lot of
time chilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that men are releasing their stress, while women
concentrate on activities that produce stress,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That would help explain another of the findings from the latest
of the annual surveys of college freshmen that UCLA began in 1966:
While 39 percent of this year's first-year women said they felt
overwhelmed ``frequently'' in the past year, that was true of only
20 percent of the first-year men.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA plans to post a free summary, and information on how to
order the full report, on the Internet at
www.gseis.ucla.edu/heri/heri.html.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Activities that college freshmen reported took up six or more
hours a week during their senior year of high school:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Exercising, sports: 42 percent of girls, 59 percent of boys.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Studying: girls, 37 percent; boys, 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Partying: girls, 26 percent; boys, 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Watching TV: girls, 24 percent; boys, 35 percent
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Student clubs, groups: girls, 16 percent; boys, 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Housework, child care: girls, 14 percent; boys, 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Volunteer work: girls, 11 percent; boys, 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Playing video games: girls, 1 percent; boys, 15 percent.
</P>
