<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4961 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EXPLOSIVE-ART-NYT     01-24 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXPLOSIVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARNESSING A MOLECULE'S EXPLOSIVE POWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is both beauty and beast: a cube-shaped molecule that
chemists regard as beautiful and that may also be the most powerful
nonnuclear explosive ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few grams of this powdery white substance, called
octanitrocubane (ONC), have been synthesized, and it has not been
completely tested to determine its physical and chemical
properties.
</P>
<P>
   But the chemical's creators have high hopes for it. It might one
day become the basis of an ultrapowerful military explosive, a
rocket fuel or drugs effective against some types of cancer. In
laboratory experiments, compounds based on similar cube-shaped
molecules have shown some ability to bind to cancer cells and
destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from certain that ONC, which is very costly to make,
will find practical uses. But its creation, which was announced in
the current issue of Angewandte Chemie, a leading international
journal of applied chemistry, was hailed as a triumph of chemical
synthesis.
</P>
<P>
   The synthesis, which took nearly 20 years to complete, was
achieved by Dr. Philip E. Eaton, a professor at the University of
Chicago, and his assistant, Dr. Mao-Xi Zhang.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a tiny pinch of ONC required a long succession
of difficult steps toward a chemical goal inspired by Plato, the
ancient Greek philosopher. Plato taught that existence is dominated
by form, and that the five regular polyhedrons known to
mathematicians _ the 4-sided tetrahedron, the 6-sided cube, the
8-sided octahedron, the 12-sided dodecahedron and the 20-sided
icosahedron _ have symbolic significance. (A regular polyhedron is
a three-dimensional form whose faces are all regular polygons; the
cube, for example, is made up of 6 regular polygons called
squares.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Plato, the tetrahedron represented fire, the cube
symbolized earth, the octahedron stood for air, the icosahedron
represented water, and the dodecahedron symbolized the universe.
</P>
<P>
   To a few chemists, the platonic solids, as these five forms are
called, posed an intriguing challenge: Would it be possible to
create molecules modeled on the platonic solids, using a carbon
atom to define each corner?
</P>
<P>
   Carbon atoms can be made to join with one another or with
different atoms in any number of ways; some 18 million distinct
chemical compounds, most of them containing carbon atoms, have been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some arrangements that are difficult or impossible
to construct. In a string of carbon atoms, adjacent atoms tend to
link together forming angles of 109.5 degrees. If that angle is
forcibly changed to squeeze carbon atoms into some desired pattern,
the electronic bond between the atoms may be strained, and the
electronic linkages between atoms may be impeded or blocked
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Some molecules based on the platonic solids are thus ruled out.
For example, it is probably impossible to synthesize tetrahedrane,
a carbon-based molecule with four faces. Since each face would be
an equilateral triangle, each corner atom would make a bonding
angle with the other three corner atoms of 60 degrees, an angle far
smaller than the 109.5 degrees carbon bonds prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Cubane, a cube-shaped molecule with a carbon atom at each of its
eight corners (and a hydrogen atom attached to each carbon), was
also thought to be too difficult to synthesize, because the bonding
angle of 90 degrees between any three adjacent carbon atoms in its
structure would be too strained.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1964, Eaton achieved the seemingly impossible synthesis
of a small quantity of cubane, a molecular cube of eight carbon
atoms with a hydrogen atom linked to each carbon.
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge was to substitute other atoms for the eight
hydrogen atoms attached to cubane's corners. With financial support
from the Army, which was seeking a more powerful military explosive
than any available, Eaton and his colleagues embarked on a program
aimed at removing the hydrogen atoms attached to a cubane
molecule's corners, and substituting nitro groups in their places.
</P>
<P>
   A nitro group is a molecular fragment consisting of a nitrogen
atom bonded to two oxygen atoms. Many carbon-based compounds
containing nitro groups, TNT and nitroglycerine among them, are
explosives, and it was reasoned that a cubane-based compound
containing as many nitro groups as possible would be an especially
powerful explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling their way a step at a time, Eaton's team eventually
succeeded in replacing four of cubane's eight hydrogen atoms with
nitro groups, thereby creating a compound called tetranitrocubane.
Later, the chemists found a way to substitute six nitro groups for
hydrogen atoms, yielding hexanitrocubane.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, developing increasingly complex synthesis
techniques, the team added yet another nitro group, yielding
heptanitrocubane. At that point, only one nitro group needed to be
added to complete the substitution of nitro groups for hydrogen
atoms at all eight corners of the cubane framework.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton said the final stage was reached by bubbling ozone gas
through an ultracold solution of ingredients that included a
seven-nitro version of cubane (heptanitrocubane). When this witch's
brew turned blue, Eaton knew he had arrived at the goal _
octanitrocubane.
</P>
<P>
   ``After nearly 20 years of chasing ONC,'' he said, ``we've
finally developed the necessary new chemistry to make it, and have
done so. It's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Calculations show, he said in an interview, that ONC is 15
percent to 30 percent more powerful than the most powerful military
explosive now in use: HMX.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton and his associates plan to synthesize a family of many
peculiar molecules related to cubane. ``We hope to expand the
horizons and possibilities of organic chemistry, but it may be slow
going,'' he said. ``Funding agencies these days are much less
interested in the pursuit of fundamental chemistry than in
practical applications. People don't always realize how important
basic scientific research is as the basis for future
applications.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
