<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HEALTH AND FITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUTCOMES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Giving Blood Before Surgery Helps &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many patients preparing for surgery donate their own blood in
the hope of avoiding transfusions from strangers. But a new Mayo
Clinic study has found that the procedure, known as autologous
donation, is generally effective only for people with moderately
low red blood cell counts.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in this month's edition of the Mayo Clinic
Proceedings, examined 165 patients who had undergone hip
replacement surgery. What the researchers found is that only those
patients whose red blood cell, or hemoglobin, counts fell within a
certain range _ 11.4 to 14.7 grams per deciliter for men, and 13.2
to 14.7 grams per deciliter for women _ managed to lower their risk
of receiving blood bank transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   For those patients, the drop in red blood cell count caused by
the autologous donation triggered the body's mechanism for making
new red blood cells. As a result, they were able to increase their
total blood cell supply by the amount they were expected to lose
during surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Patients with lower levels had trouble generating enough new
cells; patients with more normal levels didn't lose enough when
donating their own blood to trigger the make-more alarm _ in
effect, all they accomplished was shifting some of their blood from
their body to a transfusion bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a lot of blood in you, you gain very little from
the procedure,'' the study's lead author, Dr. Gregory A. Nuttall,
said in an interview. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plotting Detours on the Map of the Brain &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An old brain may have a harder time learning new tricks, but as
a result may be less likely to be fooled, according to a study that
used a computer model of the mind's functioning to come up with
this counterintuitive finding.
</P>
<P>
   The main thrust of the research by Dr. Todd Braver and Dr.
Deanna Burch, a husband-and-wife team of psychologists at
Washington University in St. Louis, was establishing the usefulness
of their computer model, which mimics the way information is routed
among different areas of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``One advantage of a model is that you can do stuff that you
can't do in humans, like damage the brain,'' said Braver. So after
gathering baseline data on the computer's ability to pick out the
letters ``AX'' from a series of two-letter combinations, the couple
ran the simulation again after altering its equations in a way they
thought would replicate effects of aging on the workings of
dopamine, a brain chemical that carries messages.
</P>
<P>
   The damaged model scored lower in general, but managed to do a
better job of avoiding one particular kind of mistake. The
researchers then put groups of healthy young and old people through
the same paces and got the same result.
</P>
<P>
   The younger people were better able to recognize and respond to
what Braver called ``contextual clues,'' recognizing quickly that
if the first letter was not A, it did not matter what the second
letter was. But when the test began with a lot of ``AX'' sequences,
that same contextual reflex led the younger people to start to
expect all As to be followed by Xs, leading to more mistakes and
lags when the pattern changed. By contrast, Braver said, the older
minds' diminished ability to recognize and remember context led
them to be misled less often. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THERAPIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expert Advice to Bald Men: Get Over It &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do antibalding treatments work? That depends in part on how
success is defined, according to an article last week in The
Lancet, a medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Julian H. Barth of the General Infirmary at Leeds in
England, wrote that recent research appears to establish that
finasteride and minoxidil, known more commonly as Propecia and
Rogaine, do help stabilize hair loss and in some cases reverse it.
</P>
<P>
   But when the men in one trial involving Procepia and a placebo
rated the value of the treatment, the response from those who got
the drug were not much more enthusiastic than from those who did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Until one remedy or another offers a clear alternative to hair
loss, Barth wrote, the only sure way of reducing dissatisfaction is
the oldest way: ``Men should be encouraged to come to terms with
their hair loss.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RISKS &AMP; REMEDIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less Risk to Liver From Hepatitis C &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tests performed on blood taken from Air Force servicemen a half
century ago and frozen appear to show that the long-term risk of
liver disease from hepatitis C is lower than has been commonly
feared.
</P>
<P>
   Because hepatitis C is a slowly progressing illness that has
been studied intensely only in recent years, no one is certain just
how much of a risk it poses in otherwise healthy people over the
course of their lives. The question has been especially pressing
because available treatments are expensive and can cause serious
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Georgetown University School of Medicine tested
for hepatitis C in the thawed blood samples that had been taken
from more than 8,000 men as part of streptococcus study at the Fort
Francis E. Warren Air Force Base in Wyoming from 1948 to 1954.
Seventeen of the samples tested positive, a rate similar to that
found among current recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at later medical records, the researchers found that
11.8 percent of those with the disease had liver disease, a figure
that was higher than the 2.4 percent found among the uninfected,
but far lower than indicated by earlier studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our data represent an accurate estimate,'' the authors
wrote last week in the Annals of Internal Medicine, ``the current
concern that progression to liver disease is common or inevitable''
may be unfounded. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That Second Bypass, and How to Avoid It &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Implanting a substance known to slow cell growth into coronary
bypasses could cut down on the rate at which they clog up and need
replacement, British researchers reported Monday in Circulation,
the journal of the American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   In bypass operations, a stretch of a healthy vein from elsewhere
in the body is grafted onto a coronary artery to detour blood
around a choked-off passageway. But something about the procedure
often sets off abnormally fast growth of cells within the graft,
leading eventually to a new blockage.
</P>
<P>
   Up to half of all bypasses fail within 10 years, and 20 percent
of bypass operations are now performed to replace failed grafts,
said the study's lead author, Dr. Sarah J. George of the University
of Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could find a way to block that abnormal layer from
growing, it could make the grafts last longer,'' Dr. George wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She and her colleagues focused on molecules called matrix
metalloproteinases, which help speed the growth of cells, as when
scar tissue is formed. Earlier studies had found that a substance
called TIMP-3 could block the activity of metalloproteinases and
help destroy cells that formed.
</P>
<P>
   The research team first implanted TIMP-3 cells in graft tissue
in a laboratory culture, and found that it produced 84 percent
fewer cells in two weeks than untreated tissue. Then they implanted
TIMP-3 in graft tissue in live pigs. Those receiving the inhibitor
produced 58 percent fewer new cells over the next 28 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
