<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-HKO-VERMONT-HNS &LR;      01-24 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-VERMONT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCANDAL PUTS PRIZED VERMONT HOCKEY TEAM IN THE HOT SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BUZZ GRAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGTON, Vt. _ When the administration at the University of
Vermont pulled the plug on the men's hockey team Jan. 14, winter
suddenly got colder and darker here.
</P>
<P>
   With one somber proclamation by university President Judith
Ramaley, the magic vanished. Not just in the dorms and study halls
of the 209-year-old institution, but in the shops and stores in the
downtown open-air mall, in the string of fast-food restaurants
along Route 7, and in the service stations that fly the green and
gold banner of Vermont hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still shocked. It hasn't really sunk in yet,'' said Todd
Corbett, an attendant at the Mobil Station near the 425-acre campus
overlooking Lake Champlain. ``I'm sure when Friday and Saturday
nights roll around, I'll realize there won't be hockey anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The final 15 games of the Catamounts' season were canceled after
a hazing scandal involving several players. The action came after a
panel of investigators appointed by the university determined that
players had lied to the panel, a finding based on information,
reported to be a videotape, that the university obtained on Jan.
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we were criticized for not doing enough,'' Vermont
athletic director Rick Farnham said. ``Now we're being criticized
by some for being too harsh. The message is: Two wrongs never,
never, never make a right.''
</P>
<P>
   The repercussions have been felt throughout the state,
especially in Montpelier, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad thing for the university hockey program,''
Gov. Howard Dean, a longtime fan, said in a statement after school
officials suspended the season. ``But it's a good thing for
establishing a tenor that hazing will not occur.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Nancy Chard, head of the Senate Education Committee,
backed the university's decision. If the school hadn't acted as it
did, she was planning to hold hearings in her committee. That
wouldn't be good for the state university, which relies on the
Legislature for yearly appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to reduce the harm that might have come to them if
they had not done this,'' Chard said about the university's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Division I hockey programs in the Northeast, maybe
the nation, this would be perhaps the last that anyone would expect
to find embroiled in scandal. Vermont has been a glowing example of
all that is good about college hockey during the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Gutterson Field House, where the Cats play, is not merely a
hockey rink surrounded by 4,000 occupied seats. It's practically a
shrine that bursts to life with the rhythmic beat of the college
band, the dancing mascot, and catchy chants from the student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most uplifting environments you can be in,''
said Margaret Corson, president of Friends of UVM Hockey. ``We hear
it from everybody who comes here to watch a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutterson is a gathering spot, a crossroads for generations and
genders. It's the home of the most popular sports team in a state
that has no major-league franchise. There is a 20-year waiting list
for season tickets to Vermont home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest show in town,'' said Peter Maher, who
described himself as an avid fan since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Maher spoke as he walked through the Hall of Honor at Gutterson,
a place decorated with photographs of Vermont's greatest legends,
including current NHL star John LeClair.
</P>
<P>
   There's no place quite like Gutterson. Most of the seats are
stacked high at each end of the field house. Spectators file in
through a narrow passage at one end. Vendors sell home-baked goods,
and senior citizens whistle through their teeth when they don't
like a referee's call.
</P>
<P>
   The Gutterson glitter is gone. The arena sits eerily silent now.
The season has come to an abrupt halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think we like this?'' sports information director Gordon
Woodworth said. ``You think we like losing close to $250,000 in
revenue for the remainder of the season? Of course we don't. But
I'll tell you one thing, the action taken here will send a wake-up
call to every campus across the country. If it doesn't, it
should.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling of Vermont's season started slowly. In September,
a 19-year-old goalie, a walk-on, was told he could try out for the
team. Corey LaTulippe, who grew up in Williston, just east of
Burlington, didn't figure to have much of a chance of beating three
other goalies on full scholarship, but he was living out a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got caught up in an ugly hazing incident that mushroomed
into a lawsuit and lies and finally the suspension of the remainder
of Vermont's season. While school officials still refuse to divulge
all that they learned in the investigation, citing the federal
Family Educational and Privacy Rights Act, it's known that all nine
freshmen, including LaTulippe, were told to report to a veteran
player's off-campus apartment for an initiation party on Oct. 1.
There, the freshmen were subjected to various forms of humiliation
and degrading acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that hazing took place, and that some players were
not completely honest about it, are deeply disappointing to me, to
our athletic staff and to our entire university community,'' said
Ramaley, the university president.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the administration or coaching staff were unaware
of the potential for hazing. That's why a zero-tolerance policy on
hazing is distributed to all student-athletes at the beginning of
the school year. The evidence suggests that the policy was ignored
by some members of the hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   LaTulippe dropped out of school and hired a lawyer, Gail
Westgate. She sent a letter to Ramaley on Oct. 28, in which she
cited specific allegations of misconduct against her client at the
party. The university responded with an internal investigation by a
private law firm but did not disclose the results. It appeared then
that the matter might fade away. But when LaTulippe on Dec. 10
filed a federal civil lawsuit naming the university, Ramaley, coach
Mike Gilligan and three players as defendants. That's when the
flames spread.
</P>
<P>
   The damages sought by LaTulippe were not specified, but The
Associated Press reported that when investigators from the school
sought to interview him, he refused unless he was paid $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   None of the players are talking to the media about the issue
because of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of disgusting to say the least,'' Alice Furman said
about the details of the hazing. ``I've been a big fan of Vermont
hockey for years. It's hard for me to understand why some players
would act in that way. Are they that uncivilized? What were they
trying to accomplish?''
</P>
<P>
   But Furman, a clerk in a department store at the University Mall
next to campus, is not so turned off that she won't root for the
Cats next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope this (suspension of the season) clears everything
up,'' she said. ``I'd hate to see something like this leave a black
mark on the team forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
