<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-BRADLEY-LOSES-FIZZ-IN     01-24 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-LOSES-FIZZ-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH IS, GORE HASN'T GOT RIVALS FOR DEMOCRATIC NOMINATION  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This eloquent 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW MARSHALL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ When Bill Bradley admitted last week that he had
experienced recurrences of a heart problem, the contender for the
Democratic presidential nomination sought to minimize it, blaming
the irregular heartbeat on too many cream sodas.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that Bradley, as the electoral season opens,
has bigger issues to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Like those sodas, his campaign _ which once seemed so refreshing
and fizzy _ is now a little flat.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a few weeks ago as if Bradley might overtake Al Gore,
the vice president and front-runner for the Democratic nomination,
and do it in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But the polls _ which may well be wrong _ say no; and they also
point to possible disappointments for Bradley in New Hampshire next
week, and even in Massachusetts in March.
</P>
<P>
   The much-heralded ``insurgent'' candidates, Bradley and Senator
John McCain for the Republicans, are both staring defeat in the
face, as the establishment _ represented by Gore and George W. Bush
_ steams ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign headquarters in Des Moines, a former aerobics
studio in the suburban University area, was humming with activity
at the end of last week.
</P>
<P>
   The hallway was thick with stationery, scattered around in boxes
or stacked irregularly on shelves. Sandwiches and apples were still
scattered around from lunch (there was no cream soda in sight).
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the room stood a board where staffers marked every
success in winning over a precinct, ringing a small bell to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   But a few blocks south, the Gore campaign has its own building,
with office after office. It does not hum: it buzzes, with dozens
of staff coming and going all the time.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 50 people here, twice as many as in Bradley's
office; Gore has four times as many field workers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradleyites are quietly dedicated: the Goreans are
singlemindedly zealous, chanting ``We Love Al Gore!'' at staff
meetings every morning.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Bradley looks like a magazine office; Fort Gore like a
thriving insurance business. Staffers sit in front of Microsoft
Access databases of voters, staring at the one field which really
matters: Yes, No, or Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Britons Isabel Campbell and Sam Dowling, both with experience in
the House of Commons, have joined the Gore campaign as observers.
Both express their surprise at the scale and intensity of the
campaign. ``Just to see the organization is incredible,'' says
Dowling. ``It's so high energy. His very young team seems to be in
perpetual motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has campaigned hard and well, but some of his advisers
think he failed to respond quickly and brutally to accusations from
Gore about his health care proposals; indeed, he has sometimes
seemed impervious to the idea that there was any opposition. But
others fear that when he did answer back, he spoiled his pristine
image.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley has also suffered from the media cycle. A month
ago, he was new; now, Al Gore is the new new thing, his campaign
apparently revitalized and re-engaged.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of brute strength, Gore had the unions and their
organized muscle, which mobilized the campaign, while Bradley
struggled to get his structure in place.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a previous campaign, dismissed what he called ``the
small state of Iowa,'' but he knows better now. Bradley said of the
current contest, ``We knew all along that Iowa is a state that
rewards entrenched power,'' which is true but didn't win many
friends.
</P>
<P>
   The medical questions have only added to his problems _
ironically, given that the one thing every Democrat could agree on
was that Bradley's heart was in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   The voters in Des Moines and New Hampshire, and indeed across
much of the country, do not seem to be in the mood for insurgent
candidates this year. The economy is robust, and no one wants to
jeopardize it.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Bradley's insurgency is hardly a rounded rejection of
everything that has gone before; he is no Che Guevara.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hardest things for both him and McCain this year has
been to calibrate their campaigns between rejection and embrace of
the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, still strong in New Hampshire, is also watching his
campaign fizzle: in South Carolina, which he dearly needs, he is 20
points behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But if Bradley fails, it represents a shift that goes beyond one
year's election. In the 36 years since the death of John F.
Kennedy, the only Democrats to win the White House have been
Southerners, Jimmy Carter and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a Tennessean, and very much from the same stable as Bill
Clinton in terms of political orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The liberal and intellectual wing of the Democrat party _
predominantly Midwestern and Northeastern _ has many great names
stitched onto its tattered battle flag, honorable men who never
made it to the presidency, for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Adlai Stevenson, Bobby Kennedy, Hubert Humphrey, Michael Dukakis
and all the rest are there _ and Bradley may have earned his
place. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
