<P>
   &UR; TUPPERWARE PARTY MEETS TO ELECT THE NEXT U.S. PRESIDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Monday, Jan. 24 _ Iowa Caucus) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent of London &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MINGO, IOWA _ It is a perfect winter's morning _ the sun
sparkling off the snowy fields, the sky a perfect blue with just a
brush stroke of cloud across the horizon. Out in the woods, the
deer are scudding through the snow, and two red-tailed hawks are
circling lazily through the oak and hickory trees.
</P>
<P>
   But John Parsons has no time to watch the wildlife today. He is
clearing the snow from his drive in his bright green John Deere
tractor.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight (Monday), Parsons and his wife, Jenifer, will welcome a
dozen or so of their neighbors to help choose the next president of
the United States in the first electoral event of the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   This is democracy at work, Iowa-style... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-TUPPERWARE-VOTERS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRUTH IS, GORE HASN'T GOT RIVALS FOR DEMOCRATIC NOMINATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent of London &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ When Bill Bradley admitted last week that he had
experienced recurrences of a heart problem, the contender for the
Democratic presidential nomination sought to minimize it, blaming
the irregular heartbeat on too many cream sodas.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that Bradley, as the electoral season opens,
has bigger issues to deal with. Like those sodas, his campaign _
which once seemed so refreshing and fizzy _ is now a little flat.
</P>
<P>
   The medical questions have only added to his problems _
ironically, given that the one thing every Democrat could agree on
was that Bradley's heart was in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Al Gore is the new new thing, his campaign apparently
revitalized and re-engaged... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-BRADLEY-LOSES-FIZZ-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `BUSH IS THE CANDIDATE OF THE LEAR JET SET' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent of London &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES - George W. Bush, the leading Republican candidate
for U.S. president, has built his political career on donations
from a small group of wealthy corporate donors, a new report
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Texans for Public Justice, a lobby group, calculates that Bush
received $3 million from just 100 wealthy businessmen and women for
his Texas Governor's campaigns in 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is the candidate of the Lear Jet set, not the minivan
crowd, and people need to know that,'' said McDonald... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-BUSH-BUYS-WHITEHOUSE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL IOWA CAUCUS PRODUCE ANY SURPRISES? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Monday, Jan. 24 _ Iowa Caucus) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY ANDREW MARSHALL, The Independent of London &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Al Gore and George W. Bush, the front-runners for
the Democrat and Republican nominations for U.S. president, both go
into today's (Monday's) Iowa caucuses as the favorites to win.
</P>
<P>
   The first event of the U.S. electoral season will see thousands
of voters trooping along to fire stations, community halls,
churches, schools and each others' houses tonight (Monday) to vote
for their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But the results are sometimes hard to interpret or measure; the
significance, in a state that is hardly representative of America
in the 21st century, is uncertain in the broader context.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're behind,'' said Gore's Democratic challenger Bill
Bradley over the weekend. ``Maybe we'll surprise a few people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-LITTLE-IOWA-BIG-CAUCUS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IOWA, NEW HAMPSHIRE: NO LONGER JUST `RIDICULOUS' TESTS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Monday, Jan. 24 and Jan. 31 _ Iowa, N.H. Caucuses) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,025 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY MARY DEJEVSKY, The Independent of London &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just 12 years ago, a certain U.S. senator by the
name of Al Gore dismissed the presidential selection process that
takes place in the Midwestern state of Iowa this evening (Monday)
as ``an arcane procedure that produces crazy results.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, he said of the small local gatherings known as the Iowa
caucuses, ``a ridiculous test'' and he ignored the whole charade,
proceeding directly to what he then regarded as the more sane and
sensible primary election in the Northeastern state of New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it need hardly be said, Gore has rethought his view of
the Iowa caucuses, the first formal leg of the four-yearly race for
the White House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-IOWA-OH-WHY?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
