<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4979 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-CELLS-EVOLUTION-N     01-24 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CELLS-EVOLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A METHOD TO TRACK EVOLUTION _ OR IS IT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Great Britain)  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By BRENDA FOWLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though they have lodged in human cells for more than a billion
years, the mitochondria have never quite given up their own ways.
Believed to be bacteriumlike organisms that were swallowed up by
the ancestors of human cells, mitochondria, organelles that process
energy in cells, have retained their DNA, distinct from the genetic
material in the cell's nucleus. Unlike the nuclear DNA, a pastiche
of genes from both parents, the mitochondrial genome has long been
assumed to replicate itself by cloning, passing solely through the
maternal line.
</P>
<P>
   The clonal inheritance of mitochondrial DNA, along with the fact
that it mutates much faster than nuclear DNA, has made it an
important tool in the study of the evolution of people and animals.
For example, evidence from mitochondrial DNA has been used to back
the theory that modern humans originated in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, several articles have challenged the
assumption of clonal inheritance in mitochondria, suggesting that
fathers, not just mothers, might be contributing mitochondrial DNA
to their offspring, a process called recombination.
</P>
<P>
   Among other findings, researchers found that in mice, fathers
contributed mitochondrial DNA to their offspring at a frequency of
one in 10,000 and that, contrary to popular belief, the
mitochondria in human sperm can enter the egg during fertilization.
Most recently, in research published in the journal Science, three
scientists concluded from a statistical analysis of a pattern of
genetic inheritance that the DNA in mitochondria, like that in the
nucleus, undergoes a shuffling process known as recombination,
possibly involving the mixing of DNA from both parents.
</P>
<P>
   The findings have yet to convince most researchers who study the
genetic inheritance. Still, a succession of findings has been
jarring, sending some researchers into their labs to test the
claims and look for more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly has attracted a lot of attention and gotten some
people pretty concerned because of the claims that they directly
make that all of this mitochondrial research now has to be
reconsidered,'' said Dr. Lynn B. Jorde, a human geneticist at the
University of Utah. ``They're issuing a strong challenge now and
the question is what is the strength of their challenge. Many of us
feel that it is not really that great, especially as we look at
their data and re-evaluate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest assault on the assumption that mitochondrial DNA
does not recombine, Dr. Philip Awadalla of the University of
Edinburgh, and Dr. Adam Eyre-Walker and Dr. John Maynard Smith of
the University of Sussex in Brighton, England, found evidence that
recombination in mitochondria had interfered with a distinctive
pattern of genetic inheritance known as linkage disequilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   In linkage disequilibrium, one allele, a specific DNA variation
at one site on the genome, occurs with another allele at a
different site at a rate that is higher than expected by chance
alone. The further away the sites lie from each, the more likely it
is that recombination will redistribute them, just as two raisins
at opposite ends of a loaf of bread have a better chance of ending
up in two different slices of bread than do two that are next to
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the researchers found that both alleles occurred in the
same individual less often as the distance between the sites
increased. ``This is expected if there is genetic recombination but
hard to explain in any other way,'' the authors concluded.
</P>
<P>
   But Jorde said he and Alan Rogers, an anthropologist at the same
university, had found problems with the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The method they used to measure linkage disequilibrium can be
influenced by other things than recombination,'' like the frequency
with which a given variation occurs in the population being
studied, Jorde said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that needs to be done is to repeat this on
much larger sample sizes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Eyre-Walker said his group had addressed the
question of allele frequencies but acknowledged that they might not
have covered all the ``subtleties in the statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now got a big push to analyze more data, and get some
money to do some new sequencing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bryan Sykes, a human geneticist at Oxford University, said
his laboratory had run similar tests on many data sets but had not
found evidence of recombination. Though he acknowledged that
recombination might be possible, he noted that two papers on the
subject had been brought under sharp challenge.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that Sykes and others are skeptical of paternal
contribution to mitochondrial DNA is that it has failed to turn up
in studies of families, where recombination would presumably appear
obvious: An offspring's mitochondrial DNA would contain parts of
the mitochondrial DNA from both parents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he and others are reluctant to rule out the possibility
that recombination can occur. The alacrity with which they have
addressed the possibility illustrates how much is at stake for them
if it turns out to be a factor in mitochondrial clocks. The
question is how frequently it occurs.
</P>
<P>
   While Eyre-Walker acknowledged that mitochondrial recombination
might be rare, he said that as far as he knew ``there had been no
work to find out what happens to a phylogenetic tree if you put a
little recombination into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
