<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ASTRONOMY-PAPERS-     01-24 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTRONOMY-PAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE JOURNALS PUBLISHES 53 MOST IMPORTANT PAPERS OF THE 20TH
CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It is somewhat depressing, at age 91, to reread the work of 36
years ago, when the juices in a brain, now made largely of
overcooked brussels sprouts, were flowing more rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   So begins Dr. Jesse L. Greenstein's remembrance of a paper he
had first published in the July 1, 1964, issue of The Astrophysical
Journal concerning the likely energy source of the distant,
shockingly luminous objects called quasars.
</P>
<P>
   The paper and remembrance appear in a new, 1,283-page compendium
of what have been judged the 53 most important papers to appear in
The Astrophysical Journal and The Astronomical Journal in the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Affectionately known as Ap.J. and A.J., the journals are the
most respected and important in astronomy. They have chronicled
astronomy's journey from the turn-of-the-century debate over
whether the Milky Way made up the entire cosmos to the present view
that Earth's galaxy is one obscure smudge of stars and gas hurtling
apart from billions of others in the wake of the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   With each paper there is an accompanying article placing the
original contribution in context and bringing its implications up
to date. Some of the accompaniments are by original authors, some
by astronomers of more recent vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeremiah P. Ostriker of Princeton, for example, comments on
an October 1937 paper by Dr. Fritz Zwicky of the California
Institute of Technology that provided the first evidence that the
universe might be full of a strange kind of ``dark matter'' _ a
mysterious substance that still baffles astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   That date, notes Ostriker in his comment, meant the original
paper was published ``six months after my own birth, and so, no
doubt, conceived before I was.''
</P>
<P>
   The century's best were chosen by a panel of astronomers led by
Dr. Donald E. Osterbrock of the University of California in Santa
Cruz. Behind the exercise was more than a desire to hand out blue
ribbons, according to Dr. Helmut A. Abt, who stepped down as editor
in chief of Ap.J. last year, after nearly 30 years in the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are tempted to think that most of the important
results were derived in the past decade or two,'' Abt wrote in the
introduction to the volume. But, he went on with a veteran's
measured ire, ``it is sometimes surprising to discover how many
basic results were obtained many years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   One early debate involved the size of the universe. Astronomers
knew that a crucial clue lay in the nature of what they called the
spiral nebula, of which a prominent example was an object called
Messier 31 in the constellation Andromeda. Were they wisps of gas
and dust in the cozy confines of the Milky Way or ``island
universes,'' meaning whole galaxies themselves, lying far away?
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, the astronomer Edwin Hubble set that question to rest
in a paper in Ap.J. titled ``A Spiral Nebula as a Stellar System,
Messier 31.'' Based on about 350 photographs taken with the
100-inch and 60-inch reflecting telescopes at Mount Wilson in
California, the largest telescopes of the day, the paper showed
that the nebula's spiral arms contained swarms of faint stars,
including variable stars and novas, and that it was much too
distant to be contained in the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This paper clearly ended all doubts that the spiral galaxies
were extragalactic,'' wrote Dr. Arthur D. Code of the University of
Wisconsin in a commentary. The finding also made it easier to
swallow Hubble's next big discovery, in 1929, that all those other
galaxies are rushing apart from one another _ the hallmark of the
Big Bang that most astronomers now believe gave birth to the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   A whole series of papers explored starlight: how the energy of
nuclear fusion reactions fuels the brilliance of stars and builds
up heavier and heavier elements from the hydrogen, helium and other
small change left over from the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   When these stars explode as novas and supernovas, they spread
those elements through the cosmos. Without the heavy elements
generated in stars, Earth and everything on it, including people,
would not exist. Or as Joni Mitchell sang at Woodstock: ``We are
stardust.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the great names associated with that work and appearing
on the contents page of this collection are those of Fred Hoyle,
William Fowler, E. Margaret Burbidge, Geoffrey Burbidge, Donald D.
Clayton and Stirling Colgate.
</P>
<P>
   Greenstein's paper was written with Dr. Maarten Schmidt of the
California Institute of Technology, who had discovered that quasars
were billions of light-years away, and therefore (because they
appear so bright) burning with the energy of hundreds of billions
of suns. Greenstein and Schmidt concluded, rightly as it seems now,
that the energy source for these beasts could only be tremendous
amounts of matter pouring into a compact object that is now called
a black hole.
</P>
<P>
   Other spectacular moments on the highlight reel include the
discovery of the Big Bang's afterglow by Dr. Arno A. Penzias and
Dr. Robert W. Wilson and Dr. Eugene N. Parker's gutsy, but correct,
prediction that the sun throws off a supersonic stream of
particles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, in the space age, the term `solar wind' is a scientific
byword and not entirely unknown to the daily newspapers,'' Parker
wrote in his commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The commentaries and the discursive, almost Victorian feel of
the old papers make this collection, called the American
Astronomical Society Centennial Issue, surprisingly readable and
always engrossing.
</P>
<P>
   How does it feel to be named one of the 20th century's best?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have many big honors, but they are local in time, here one
decade and forgotten the next,'' said Clayton, who is an
astrophysicist at Clemson University. ``This honor will go into the
history books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
