<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Jan. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An intense storm about 200 miles off the middle Atlantic coast
will buffet eastern New England and the middle Atlantic shoreline
with wind gusts to 45 mph. A swath of moderate to heavy snow is
most likely from eastern Maine southward to Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Milder air from the Atlantic should change snow to rain or sleet
over Cape Cod, Mass., and the Islands. A lighter snow will spread
inland across central New England and should also affect the New
York City region. However, a slight shift in the track of the storm
could lead to either heavy snow and strong winds or a dry day in
the Northeast Corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure in eastern Michigan will promote snow showers
around the central Great Lakes and into the western Ohio Valley. A
surge of very chilly air will reach into the Mississippi Valley on
gusty winds from the north. The Southeast will be cooler but
bright, as fresh breezes from the northwest direct drier air into
the region.
</P>
<P>
   A large area of high pressure in the Plains should move little
during the next two days. Sunny and seasonable conditions are
likely in northern sections, but clouds will advance into southern
parts of the Plains on Tuesday afternoon. A stream of moisture from
the Pacific will cover the Southwest as a cold front progresses
into the region.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will taper to showers along the California coast, but heavy
rain is expected in eastern sections. Snow levels will lower, but
recent wet and mild conditions may lead to flooding and mudslides
in parts of the lower Sierra. The Northwest will stay dull and damp
with readings near seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Alaskan Mirror
</P>
<P>
   In winter the temperature pattern in Alaska often mirrors that
of the eastern United States. This past week a deep chill has
gripped much of the East with subzero readings reported as far
south as North Carolina. Meanwhile, unusual warmth has swept into
interior Alaska, where the temperature in Fairbanks rose to 29
degrees on Sunday, or 30 degrees above normal. During winter, warm
air reaches Alaska when a bulge in the jet stream directs milder
winds from over the Pacific Ocean. In a seesawlike fashion, the jet
stream will then typically dip far to the south near the longitude
of eastern North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
