</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SCIENCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEVER SAY DIE': A LONG LIFE, OR ONE THAT JUST FEELS LONG
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(fb) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All right, ``Never Say Die,'' the title of Tuesday night's
``Scientific American Frontiers,'' is hyperbolic, but it signals a
real quest by researchers to discover ways to prolong the physical
and mental well-being of humankind.
</P>
<P>
   As Alan Alda, the series' amiable host, discovers in
conversations with scientists, who perforce are carrying out most
of their experiments on rats, mice and worms, the means may be near
at hand to add decades to the Bible's authorized life span.
</P>
<P>
   The least surprising route is to eat less, but make sure that
what you eat is highly nutritious. Roy Walford, of Venice, Calif.,
is credited with finding that laboratory mice live up to twice
their normal age if their caloric intake is cut in half, and
monkeys who watch their diets stay younger longer. What has worked
on those lucky creatures seems to work, too, on humans. Walford,
who is 75, figures that 10 years on his diet should have already
added 15 or 20 years to his life span.
</P>
<P>
   Less familiar to viewers is the research being done on the
workings of human cells and things called telomeres that are
attached to chromosomes and can affect symptoms of aging like
cataracts, gray hair, wrinkled skin, arthritis and even cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of California at Los Angeles (California seems
particularly attractive to seekers of eternal health), a team is
working to extend the life of the elderly to the limit, about 120
years; the hope is that if a 100-year-old comes down with an
infection, he will have a better chance of surviving it. In a few
years, Alda reports, what he calls ``an immune system boost'' could
become routine for everyone over 60. Another Californian, a
biologist, Cynthia Kenyon, made mutant worms live twice as long as
normal _ four weeks instead of two _ by fiddling with genes and
hormones. That inspires Alda to envision the possibility of ``a
long-life pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile researchers in Massachusetts are working at replacing
human body parts much like an auto repair shop does with car parts.
The spare parts would be grown from an individual's stem cells,
which would be a way to get around the shortage of organs for
transplant and rejection problems.
</P>
<P>
   The hour ends with those rats again, providing evidence that
mental activity keeps their brains working well into old age. So
there's some advice from Alda: ``Your brain starts to go away if
you don't use it every day.'' That's if you remember to keep your
calories down.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTIFIC AMERICAN FRONTIERS: `Never Say Die'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Tuesday of PBS
</P>
<P>
   John Angier and Graham Chedd, executive producers. Produced by
the Chedd-Angier Production Co. in association with Scientific
American magazine; Alan Alda, host. WITH: Roy Walford, Cal Harley,
Cynthia Kenyon, Michael West, Marilyn Albert and William Greenough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
