A4990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-TRIAL-CAMERA-HNS     01-24 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-TRIAL-CAMERA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STATE CONSIDERS CLOSED-CIRCUIT BROADCAST OF DIALLO TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Cameras, or at least one camera, might be allowed
into the courtroom where four police officers face charges of
killing a 22-year-old Bronx man.
</P>
<P>
   With courtroom seating at a premium in the Albany County
Courthouse and cameras barred from chronicling trials in New York,
the state is seriously considering a closed-circuit transmission of
the proceedings, at least to another courtroom, so more people can
watch.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for the state Office of Court
Administration (OCA), the intense interest in the case of four New
York city police officers accused of murdering Amadou Diallo in the
Bronx, coupled with the physical inability to accommodate all the
interested press, let alone the general public, could prompt the
installation of at least one television monitor.
</P>
<P>
   This would be the first time since cameras were again shut out
of New York's courtrooms in 1997 that such a closed-circuit
arrangement would be made, an OCA official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seriously looking at all the options and considering it
as a strong possibility,'' OCA spokesman David Bookstaver said
Friday. ``We are looking into all the variables that would go into
closed-circuit coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great public interest and great media interest in the
trial and we have a finite number of seats'' in the courtroom of
state Supreme Court Justice Joseph C. Teresi, Bookstaver said. ``We
will do our best to accommodate the various constituencies who want
to watch or cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Court TV has filed a motion with state Supreme Court to be
allowed to televise the case. The city is preparing to file a brief
supporting the cable network's efforts, Albany Mayor Jerry Jennings
said. A ruling is expected in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a state appeals court voted to move the trial of the
four officers _ on murder and reckless endangerment charges _ from
the Bronx to Albany for a trial starting Jan. 31. The court held
that extensive media coverage of the case had made it impossible to
pick a fair jury anywhere in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, who lived and died in the Soundview area of the Bronx,
was hit by 19 bullets early in the morning of Feb. 4, 1999, in the
vestibule of the two-story apartment building in which he lived.
</P>
<P>
   The officers who shot Diallo said they believed he was armed and
dangerous. Police reports after the shooting said no weapon was
found and that Diallo had no criminal record. The four plainclothes
officers from the Street Crime Unit reportedly were looking for a
serial rapist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1719EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER25-COX     01-24 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: The caucuses of Madison County
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The presidential hopefuls were making one more pitch before
tonight's Iowa caucuses, even though there wasn't much suspense
about the outcome. Both George W. Bush and Al Gore were urging
supporters to turn out and vote despite polls showing their hefty
leads in the state. Bill Bradley was brushing off any suggestion
that a poor showing could mean the end of his White House bid. He
told ABC a lengthy primary battle would strengthen the eventual
nominee. John McCain has not campaigned in Iowa, concentrating on
next week's New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   HAZE OF SMOKE OVER CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore denied on Monday that he smoked marijuana regularly,
even daily, with a Tennessee friend as late as 1976, as the man now
contends. The question came up when a reporter said to Gore at a
diner: ``It's been reported that after you came back from Vietnam
you were smoking on a daily basis.'' Gore responded, ``No. When I
came back from Vietnam, yes, but not to that extent. ... This is
something I dealt with a long time ago. It's old news.'' The
Tennessee man, John Warnecke, was quoted by the online magazine
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   PRETTY NICE MID-WINTER DAY
</P>
<P>
   The weather shouldn't be a problem in Iowa for today's
presidential caucuses. It's chilly across the state, but that's to
be expected _ since it usually is in winter. The forecast was
calling for highs in the teens in northeast Iowa, and some light
snow is possible. In the southeastern part of the state, it'll get
up to the low 40s _ considered downright balmy for this time of
year.
</P>
<P>
   OK FOR STATES TO CURB CAMPAIGN CASH FLOW
</P>
<P>
   States that put limits on campaign contributions were given a
green light Monday by the Supreme Court. The justices reaffirmed
the rights of the states to impose those limits in an effort to
deter corruption. The 6-3 decision in a Missouri case means there's
no longer any doubt about the legitimacy of the $1,000 cap on
contributions to federal candidates: The donation limit is not a
violation of free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK KNOCKOUTS A REAL POSSIBILITY
</P>
<P>
   If the front-runners, Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al
Gore win both the Iowa caucuses tonight and the New Hampshire
primary eight days hence you might as well turn out the lights. The
losers may fight on through some subsequent contests but most
political observers say they believe that for all practical
purposes the nominations will be certain.
</P>
<P>
   NEW HAMPSHIRE TO HIMSELF FOR A DAY
</P>
<P>
   With everyone else in Iowa, John McCain took advantage of his
last day as the lone candidate in New Hampshire, focusing on
portraying himself as a more qualified leader than George W. Bush
and launching a TV ad touting his war service and knowledge of
foreign policy. To dispel notions that Bush might push him out of
the contest, McCain said he was sure to stick with the race at
least through Super Tuesday, March 7, when more than a dozen
states, including Georgia, New York and California, hold their
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   PLEAS FOR THAT `EXTRA EFFORT'
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley urged campaign crowds at Iowa campus rallies to
``make that extra effort in the next 24 hours'' and help him try to
spring a surprise in tonight's caucuses. ``If you think in these
times of unprecedented prosperity that there are things that we
must do that will set us on the right path for generations to come,
then I hope you will go to caucus for me tomorrow night,'' he told
hundreds at the University of Iowa. At Iowa State, he said he's
``going to surprise a lot of people across this country tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   FORBES ON THE EDGE
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes has got to do well tonight. His camp has long said
that Forbes, a distant third behind George W. Bush and John McCain,
must get a healthy share of the uncommitted vote. But the Des
Moines Register dealt him a blow. It endorsed Bush and published a
recent poll showing that Forbes, despite spending more than $25
million, has not budged from his 20 percent standing in the polls.
On the other side, the Register endorsed Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   DROPOUT WATCH IN UTAH
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, ``sounding like a presidential candidate who
knows he cannot win, nearly cried about his brother killed in World
War II as he thanked Iowa voters for turning just out to listen to
him before tonight's precinct caucuses,'' The Salt Lake Tribune
reported. The home-state newspaper said ``Hatch seems to realize
his'' campaign ``will come to an end soon.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PERILS OF AN EARLY CONCLUSION
</P>
<P>
   In the week before the first caucus, a poll by the Shorenstein
Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy found that
two-thirds of the voters were paying only a little or no attention
to the campaign, and that 70 percent said they had no favorite
candidate. If the race is declared over before they tune in, many
political observers suggest it could only further voter
disaffection and the decline in turnout.
</P>
<P>
   DUKAKIS _ REMEMBER HIM?
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dukakis returned to New Hampshire to campaign for Al
Gore, an old rival from the 1988 campaign. ``'Banging on doors in
Nashua was great fun. The people were terrific,'' he said. Dukakis
said he met a lot of old supporters. ``I met with a lot of people
who were good to Mike Dukakis,''' he said. ``There were a lot of
hugs and kisses, and reminiscing.'' Dukakis said this is his first
time back out _ not having campaigned for anyone in the Democratic
primaries in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   HEY, WHAT ABOUT ALASKA?
</P>
<P>
   With all political eyes turned to the grange halls and church
basements of Iowa, Alaska is trying to get a little piece of some
action. Today, registered Republican voters in Alaska are going to
venues across the state to vote in what is called a ``nonbinding
straw vote.'' The party's official presidential endorsement comes
in the summer at the state convention.'' The 1996 event was pretty
irrelevant: Some 9,000 voters turned out and Pat Buchanan edged
Steve Forbes 33-31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   FOR OTHERS, THOUGH, ONCE IS NEVER ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Flying around the country with an entourage and meeting new
people is great and all, but John McCain says plans to make this
his first and last presidential run. Unless he pulls an upset and
wins the White House, that is. ``I would never do this again. I'm
too tired,'' he told reporters on his campaign bus Sunday, as he
fueled his energy with several fists full of candy and his
umpteenth cup of coffee. ``I think it's fun once. I don't see how
it's fun twice.''
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA DEMOCRAT DEFECTING
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats in Congress are losing one of their own _
something sure to cheer the Republicans who hold a slim majority.
Rep. Virgil Goode, a second-term conservative Democrat from
south-central Virginia, plans to become an independent. House
Democrats reacted cautiously, with Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
saying he was ``heartened that he chose not to affiliate himself
with'' the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ASK NOT WHAT HE REMEMBERS, ASK ...
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan's daughter, Maureen, says she doesn't know if her
father even remembers being president anymore. She says her
father's Alzheimer's is worsening. But, she told NBC today the
important thing is that millions of other people remember what
Reagan did for the country.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTING FOR MORE THAN WILDLIFE
</P>
<P>
   HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo, whose father, Mario, was a
three-term governor of New York, said he's considering running for
the same office. ``I want to focus on the presidential (election),
then look at all the options,'' Cuomo said after a Sunday hunting
outing with two state legislative leaders in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING ABOUT HOW TO TALK
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's campaign got caught in a contradiction about
how the candidate will be made available in the future for
questioning on the issues. One spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker, said
formal meetings between reporters and Bush were being cut back
because they can harm ``the message of the day.'' Later, Bush
communications chief Karen Hughes said no, Bush would continue to
be available, but on an informal basis that befits the ``much more
drop-in, much more drop-by'' campaign style of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
