<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-SYMPHONY-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAHLER'S `RESURRECTION' SYMPHONY: BALTIMORE'S NEW MAESTRO EMBARKS
WITH MAHLER 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: Word in bold face can be set in italics.) 
(fb) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Perhaps the Baltimore Symphony Orchestra wanted to
make its new music director, the Russian conductor Yuri Temirkanov,
feel right at home amid the snows of winter. Or perhaps it is
having a hard time getting the full attention of Temirkanov, a busy
international maestro who is also the music director of the St.
Petersburg Philharmonic back home.
</P>
<P>
   Why else introduce a new music director midway through the
season rather than at its beginning? Not for either of those
reasons, said John Gidwitz, the orchestra's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I offered him the position three years ago, he said he
couldn't possibly take it, because he didn't have a week free until
2000,'' Gidwitz explained. ``So I said, `What are you doing in
January 2000?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Temirkanov is giving the orchestra generous amounts of time,
Gidwitz added: five weeks this season and 12 weeks plus tours in
future seasons. Temirkanov is also to open the orchestra's next
season and future seasons in alternation with St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   However odd the timing of his inauguration, the repertory was
guaranteed to make a splash: Mahler's burly ``Resurrection''
Symphony, performed on Thursday and Friday evenings and Saturday
morning at Joseph Meyerhoff Symphony Hall. The choice was doubly
interesting because Temirkanov is known in the West chiefly for his
splendid work in Russian repertory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the reasons he wanted to come here, to be able to
conduct other things,'' Gidwitz said of the maestro, who still
speaks little English. ``He does so much touring with the St.
Petersburg, and everyone wants to hear them in Russian music. But
he is not simply a great  &UR; Russian &LR;  conductor, he is a great
conductor, period.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be little argument on the basis of the performance
on Saturday. True, a sympathy for Mahler comes as no surprise from
this denizen of Shostakovich's world, which is, after all, modeled
partly on Mahler's. But the change of pace brought elements of
Temirkanov's mastery into clearer relief.
</P>
<P>
   What struck a listener here, as before in Shostakovich,
Rachmaninoff and Tchaikovsky, was Temirkanov's immense patience.
This is a quality perhaps insufficiently sought or valued among
conductors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in Shostakovich's Seventh Symphony or in Mahler's
``Resurrection,'' few conductors show more care for or confidence
in the long line of the music.
</P>
<P>
   Temirkanov does not try to manufacture excitement at every
moment, choosing instead to savor atmosphere, color and detail. And
he steadfastly avoids anticlimax, preferring to let a movement or
even a whole big piece build to a single majestic peak that
subsumes the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is that if that single event fails by even a little
in its timing or impact, the effect of the whole will suffer, too,
or misfire altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But here Temirkanov carried a listener along on a leisurely but
captivating stroll through the first four movements and built to a
glorious climax in the choral culmination of the fifth, shattering
in its emotional impact because it brought the whole, long journey
into a new, sharp focus in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Such a revelatory experience _ not to be expected of any maestro
every week or in all repertory _ makes clear that while music may
work only in the present, that present can somehow also incorporate
the past. It is a mysterious process not unlike that when the
present reworks the past, as one rehears and re-evaluates a
performance in memory, moments, hours or days after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve such powerful results took excellent work from the
orchestra, the Baltimore Symphony Chorus and the vocal soloists,
Janice Chandler and Nancy Maultsby.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra, which was directed from 1985 to 1998 by David
Zinman, clearly remains in fine shape overall, and Temirkanov has
already begun to shape its future, overseeing five sets of
auditions in the whirlwind days leading up to his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   So his commitment appears to be all that any orchestra could
want, and his repertory and style seem an interesting complement to
Zinman's.
</P>
<P>
   But it is in the nature of complementarity that Zinman's areas
of special interest and expertise _ older, newer and American music
_ may not prove particular strengths of Temirkanov.
</P>
<P>
   However that may be, the Baltimore Symphony has used a
portentous turn of the calendar to its advantage, entering its own
fascinating and, to judge from the beginning, exciting new era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
