<HEADLINE>
AUDIT REVEALS $6.3 MILLION IN ILLEGAL DONATIONS UNDER KOHL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Suggesting a system of secret financing far greater
than previously acknowledged, an audit of Germany's Christian
Democratic Union on Monday revealed more than $6.3 million in
illicit contributions under former Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, by Ernst &AMP; Young, offered no new clues on the sources
of the payments, which Kohl has refused to reveal. But it showed
that the $1 million that the former chancellor has admitted
receiving between 1993 and 1998 followed earlier and much larger
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing a test of our existence,'' Wolfgang Schaeuble,
the party leader said. However, in a clear change of political
tack, he indicated that Kohl remained central to the party's
future, and praising Kohl's achievements, urged him to remain in
the heart of the party and ruled out any lawsuits against him.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Schaeuble suggested that the party might try to use
legal means to compel Kohl to obey the law that says the source of
any contribution over $10,500 must be declared. But party leaders
are leery of pressing the issue because the former chancellor's
popularity remains high among many Germans.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the party faces a delicate political dilemma: It
must assuage the anger of young party activists by showing
determination to clear up the scandal while not vilifying the man
at the root of it because he is revered by the party old guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be ridiculous if we tried to sue Helmut Kohl to
reveal information he has,'' Schaeuble said. ``We hope that Helmut
Kohl remains in the center of our party.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``We hope that Mr. Kohl chooses to speak openly of
what he knows. We also hope to find an explanation for this
situation through our investigations. We do not, however, plan to
pursue any civil legal action against Mr. Kohl.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthias Wissmann, the party treasurer, said the auditors found
$1.1 million from unexplained sources on party accounts for the
period from 1993 to 1998. This sum is slightly higher than the $1
million that Kohl has admitted receiving in that period while
refusing to name the donors.
</P>
<P>
   But the audit, ordered in haste after the party's financing
first came under close scrutiny last November, also revealed an
additional $5.2 million in mysterious contributions for the period
between 1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   This earlier period corresponded to that of German unification,
when Kohl was eager to extend his party's power into the formerly
communist east of the country and needed money to do so. It was
also a time of frenzied business activity, with many West German
firms scouring the east for possible acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The sums identified Monday did not include about $7 million that
the party branch in the state of Hesse has said it found in
overseas bank accounts without being able to explain its source. In
all, the Christian Democratic party has therefore admitted to the
existence of more than $13 million in illicit funds.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble said that the party had decided to take legal action
against an accountant named Horst Weyrauch, who was close to Kohl
and a central figure in party finances during the Christian
Democrat rule that ended in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The findings of the auditors point towards unacceptable
conduct on the party of the Christian Democratic Party,'' he said.
``We will exhaust all legal means to get Mr. Weyrauch to tell what
he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the party has decided to try to circumvent
attacking Kohl by forcing his closest financial aide to reveal what
he knows. The calculation is clearly that this approach will carry
a lower political price.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the party forced Kohl to give up his post as honorary
chairman. But the former chancellor, who says his honor precludes
him from identifying people to whom he promised anonymity, has
since received an ecstatic reception at a party meeting in Bremen.
</P>
<P>
   While many younger Germans have been appalled by Kohl's conduct,
older and more conservative members of the party are angry at what
they see as a conspiracy to discredit a great statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeuble said that, ``All Germany falters when the Christian
Democratic Union, the party of the middle, falters. Germany needs
Christian Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   His statement clearly reflected widespread concern that if this
party of the moderate right that had governed for 33 postwar years
should begin to disintegrate like the Christian Democratic party in
Italy, more nationalist and extremist movements of the right would
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Kohl maintains his silence, the party seems likely to
suffer. Speculation is rife that he took money in exchange for
business favors, although he has resolutely denied taking bribes.
All the money, Kohl has said, was used to reinforce the party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
