<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: WITH TYLENOL AND CHILDREN, OVERDOSING IS
PERILOUSLY EASY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let me start with the bottom line: the pain and fever reliever
acetaminophen, popularly called Tylenol, its first over-the-counter
trade name, is a very safe drug for children as well as for adults.
But as with any medication, the dose makes the poison. And with
acetaminophen, which has properly replaced aspirin as the drug most
often given to infants and children, there is a relatively small
window of safety.
</P>
<P>
   In infants and small children, studies have indicated that the
toxic dose is less than twice the recommended dose. Studies have
also shown that it is very easy to mistakenly give children too
much acetaminophen and, as a result, endanger their lives and their
health.
</P>
<P>
   Acetaminophen was actually introduced into the pharmacopeia
before aspirin. But it was not sold without a prescription before
1960, and until quite recently it played second fiddle to aspirin
as a treatment for pain and fever. Unlike aspirin, acetaminophen
does not relieve inflammation and thus is less effective in
relieving pain caused by inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   Then researchers discovered that aspirin, given to children with
flu, chicken pox or any viral illness, could increase the risk of
the potentially fatal Reye's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   To be safe, pediatricians now strongly caution against giving
aspirin to children or young adults (up to 20) with fever,
regardless of its cause. As hoped, the incidence of Reye's declined
sharply since acetaminophen replaced aspirin for children.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of acetaminophen is that, unlike aspirin, it
does not cause gastrointestinal irritation or bleeding. And a study
of 28,130 children given acetaminophen failed to find such serious
side effects as kidney failure or allergic shock, which in rare
cases can result from aspirin use.
</P>
<P>
   But as Dr. James E. Heubi (pronounced HIGH-bee), pediatrics
professor at the University of Cincinnati, said in an article last
month in Contemporary Pediatrics, ``Despite its recognized safety
in appropriate therapeutic doses, there are at least three
circumstances in which acetaminophen may be toxic:''
</P>
<P>
   _ When an intentional overdose is taken by someone who is
suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   _ When an unintentional overdose is given, as in multiple doses
of acetaminophen in excess of the amount recommended on the label.
</P>
<P>
   _ When an inadvertent overdose is given to a child who is
treated with acetaminophen for a fever and with a cough-and-cold
preparation that contains acetaminophen.
</P>
<P>
   An excess of acetaminophen at any age can seriously damage the
liver and cause liver failure and death. Attempts to commit suicide
by taking too much acetaminophen are now usually thwarted by an
antidote called N-acetylcysteine, or Mucomyst, which can prevent
serious liver damage when given within 24 hours. Still, what Heubi
calls ``therapeutic misadventures'' by the well-intentioned still
occur and can result in the need for liver transplants or death.
</P>
<P>
   Although relatively few cases of liver damage caused by
accidental overdoses of acetaminophen in children have been
published or reported to health agencies, Heubi believes that the
official number of 55 is probably a ``gross underestimate'' of the
total.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal observation, based on conversations with
physicians at liver transplant centers,'' he said, ``is that
doctors often see liver failure associated with multiple excess
doses of acetaminophen, though most cases are not reported in the
literature or to the Food and Drug Administration, and that many
less severely affected patients go unreported as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Acetaminophen is sold in many forms: concentrated drops for
infants, a less-concentrated liquid and chewable tablets for
children and higher-dose tablets and capsules for adults. Besides
Tylenol, brand names include Feverall, Panadol and Tempra. There
are also generic and store brands. In addition, varying amounts of
acetaminophen are found in combination products sold to treat
coughs and colds in children and more than a dozen such products
for adults.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways children can end up with dangerous amounts
of acetaminophen in the blood. Let's say a child has a fever from a
respiratory illness. The child may be given too much of the
concentrated infant drops or of the liquid marketed for children
or, in the case of an older child, tablets meant for adults. Or, in
addition to an appropriate dose to reduce fever, the child may be
given a cough and cold medicine that contains more acetaminophen.
</P>
<P>
   When an overdose reaches toxic levels, a child will become
lethargic and nauseated and will vomit. By then, liver damage may
have already occurred. In cases of serious damage, the child should
be immediately taken to a hospital that does liver transplants.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the risk of overdoses, Heubi recommends that parents
use only the liquid version for children of all ages. It is crucial
to follow the label, use no more than recommended based on weight
and age, and give no more than five doses within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   However, Heubi noted that the label language on many
over-the-counter products like acetaminophen might ``exceed the
reading comprehension of as many as 50 percent of parents.'' A
study by six pediatricians at the University of Rochester revealed
that mothers were often mistaken in what they considered an
appropriate dose of acetaminophen. And in another study among 100
people who were told a child's weight and given dosing instructions
by weight, only two in five were able to determine the correct dose
and only two-thirds were able to measure the dose correctly. Thus,
had the drug actually been given, 70 percent would have been given
the wrong dose.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of acetaminophen overdoses would also be reduced if
parents recognized fever as a way the body controls infections.
Unless it is higher than 102, a fever is best left untreated. And,
for high fevers, rather than giving too much acetaminophen, sponge
baths should be used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
