<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT LOOMS AS BIG PRIZE IN 2000 ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Sean Loughlin is a correspondent for the Washington Bureau of
the NYT Regional Newspapers Group.) 
(nk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the likelihood that the next president will
appoint new justices, the Supreme Court looms as a flash point in
the 2000 race and could draw both diehard conservatives and
liberals to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Activists of every ideological stripe are already telling their
followers one of two things: either their cherished rights are in
jeopardy or their long-sought goals are within tantalizing reach.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Christians talk openly of their desire to reverse
Roe vs. Wade, the court decision that legalized abortion. Abortion
rights advocates warn of the same thing. Proponents of gay rights,
government aid to parochial schools, affirmative action and
expanded police powers believe the nation's highest court has the
potential to be either a cherished ally or formidable foe _
depending on how future justices rule on these contentious matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the sleeper issue of the campaign,'' said Clint Bollick,
litigation director at the conservative Institute for Justice.
``Whoever is elected president will have a twofer: He will not only
have the presidency, but the judiciary as well. It is of enormous
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   That point was underscored last week in Iowa by Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, the Republican front-runner, who criticized Roe vs.
Wade, saying it had usurped the rights of state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court could be particularly significant this year _
as compared to other election years _ for several reasons. First,
after almost eight years of Democratic rule in the White House,
Republicans are desperate to get another chance at shaping the
federal judiciary, especially the ideological bent of the nation's
highest court. The open-seat race for the presidency gives them
their best chance.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there are several justices whose advancing years have
court observers speculating that as many as four vacancies could
occur over the course of a two-term presidency. The average age on
the nine-member court is 66. The three oldest members are Justice
John Paul Stevens, Chief Justice William Rehnquist and Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor, who this year turn 80, 76 and 70 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the nine-member Court has emerged as sharply divided on
several key issues, such as states rights, and 5-4 decisions have
become commonplace. A new justice could quickly alter that balance.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Court recently accepted some high-profile cases.
Decisions on partial-birth abortion and gay rights could dominate
the headlines this summer just as the conventions heat up the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be one of the issues that divides the two
candidates very starkly,'' said Kate Michelman, president of the
National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. Michelman
said her group would highlight the importance of the Supreme Court
in coming months through mass mailings and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next president holds in his hand the future of the Supreme
Court, the future of Roe v. Wade and the future of a woman's right
to choose,'' she said. ``This is not going to be abstract. This
will have an impact on American lives.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Supreme Court as a campaign issue has engaged
political activists, some are not so sure it will resonate with the
general public. They believe voters will respond to candidates'
personalities and pocketbook issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's something that becomes a front-burner issue
for the general electorate,'' said Ralph Reed, a Republican
political consultant and former director of the Christian
Coalition. ``It's something that's primarily communicated within
your base.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential contenders are already grappling with questions
about the Supreme Court. At debates in New Hampshire and Iowa, the
men vying for the Republican presidential nomination have been
queried about whether they would appoint pro-life judges to the
bench. Bush has said he would not impose a litmus test, but
Michelman believes he would favor judges opposed to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As they criticize Democrats, other GOP candidates have also
acknowledged the importance of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country will drastically change if Al Gore or Bill Bradley
becomes the president of the United States,'' said Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah. Speaking to reporters in New Hampshire, Hatch, the
chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which considers all
federal judicial nominations, continued: ``Many of these liberals
want to use the court ... to pass their agenda that they could
never get through Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen.
Bill Bradley were recently asked whether either would appoint the
first Hispanic to the nation's highest court. While both men spoke
of their commitment to diversity, neither made that pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court appointments are one of the true legacies any
president can leave. Justices serve lifetimes appointments. Their
rulings can touch on virtually all aspects of American life,
ranging from where parents send their children to school to privacy
protections in an increasingly technological world.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Neas, president of the liberal People for the American
Way, put it this way: ``The next president could nominate as many
as three or four Supreme Court justices, and that could determine
what the law of the land will be for a couple of generations.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is in the Washington Bureau of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
