<SLUG> BC-DIRECTORS-AWARDS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Directors Jonze, Mendes among award nominees
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two first-time directors (Spike Jonze and Sam Mendes) and other
lesser-known filmmakers are this year's nominees for the Directors
Guild of America awards, announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The nominees:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frank Darabont for ``The Green Mile,'' a mystical death-row
drama. It's the second film Darabont adapted from a Stephen King
story; the first, 1994's ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' earned him
his first DGA nomination.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jonze for ``Being John Malkovich,'' a literally cerebral
fantasy about a group of people who want to live permanently in the
title actor's brain.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Michael Mann for ``The Insider,'' a drama about the struggle
between a ``60 Minutes'' producer and his network to broadcast an
expose about big tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mendes for ``American Beauty,'' a suburban black comedy that
won the director a Golden Globe on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  M. Night Shyamalan for ``The Sixth Sense,'' a film of his own
screenplay about a psychiatrist and a ghost-seeing boy, which
turned into one of the year's surprise box-office hits.
</P>
<P>
   While they've been honored with awards from other critics'
groups, Neil Jordan (``The End of the Affair''), Milos Forman
(``Man on the Moon''), Anthony Minghella (``The Talented Mr.
Ripley'') and Mike Leigh (``Topsy Turvy'') didn't make the grade.
Nor did Paul Thomas Anderson, whose ``Magnolia'' continues to
divide audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Shyamalan could be considered an honorary first-timer, though
this is his third film. His culture-clash drama ``Praying With
Anger'' made only the festival rounds, while his cloying Catholic
drama ``Wide Awake'' was barely released in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The DGA award is announced March 11. The DGA winner almost
always takes home the directing Oscar as well. Since 1949, the DGA
and Oscar have differed only four times in their choice of
director.
</P>
<P>
   The winning director's film usually gets the best picture
statuette as well. Last year, Steven Spielberg won the DGA and an
Oscar for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' but his war drama lost the top
Academy Award to ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscars are March 26.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
