<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quindlen: Rocker free to talk like a jerk
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna Quindlen weighs in on the athlete's foot-in-mouth disease
that plagues John Rocker in her Newsweek ($3.95) column this week.
She makes the refreshing observation that athletes are no more or
less than ordinary human beings. Unfortunately, she adds, we have
elevated athletes to a position high above mere mortals and excused
them for everything from drug use to sexual assault. In the case of
Rocker, she says, he was exercising his right to talk like a jerk.
``Why in the world does anyone think this man is worth listening
to, much less worth excoriating. His career has the shelf life of a
carton of milk; like most professional athletes he is one torn
rotator cuff away from obscurity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Talking: Tina Brown's experiment with a multiple-imaged,
European-style cover at Talk ($3.50) is over. The new issue
features a single image of Leonardo DiCaprio and a more traditional
design inside. It's an improvement, but the magazine still has the
appearance of a cafeteria line. This month's articles include
everything from the typical celebrity interview with DiCaprio to a
troubling article by Lucinda Franks on the sex lives of middle
school kids. In between are articles on Wilt Chamberlain, Helen
Morris (Mrs. Martin Scorsese) and Carla Del Ponte, the woman who is
trying to bring Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to justice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hell hath no fury? In an article bound to spark debate, U.S.
News &AMP; World Report ($3.95) presents a different view of Hades than
the fire-and-brimstone version of 18th-century revivalist Jonathan
Edwards. Correspondent Jeffery L. Sheler discusses a recent article
in the Jesuit magazine La Civilta Catolica that speculates that
Hell is not a place but a ``state'' where a person suffers from the
deprivation of God. Conservatives disagree, but a poll conducted by
U.S. News &AMP; World Report indicates that 53 percent of Americans
believe in the less fiery revised version.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Primary primer: With the political campaigns heating up, The
New Yorker ($3) focuses on George W. Bush, Bill Bradley, the New
Hampshire primary and the also-ran Republicans. Nicholas Lemann
delves into Bush's life and decides that the real story is more
than one of redemption. The governor's ``Texas-size sense of fun is
an essential part of his appeal,'' Lemann says. Columnist Joe
Klein, meanwhile, examines the dim futures of Gary Bauer and Alan
Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary giant: Doubletake ($10) offers a fascinating,
previously unpublished interview with the late Walker Percy. Amid
the author's musings on philosophy and literature is the revelation
that his favorite TV show was ``The Incredible Hulk.'' Says Percy:
``It united two great literary traditions: rotation (hitting the
road, dropping out, adventures) and the good monster (Beauty's
beast), who is also Lancelot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: With the exception of The Globe ($1.59), the
supermarket tabloids are strangely silent on the matter of Ted
Turner and Jane Fonda's marital separation this week. Using unnamed
sources, The Globe reports that Turner took 50-year-old Frederique
D'Arragon to his New Mexico ranch aboard his private plane. Blurry
photographs purportedly show D'Arragon boarding the plane with
Turner. ... Benjamin Bratt tells W ($3.95) that his relationship
with Julia Roberts works because he sees her as the woman he loves
instead of a superstar celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
