<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-STEEG-COX     01-24 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-STEEG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL maestro Steeg has toughest job in football
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Worried that no one's coming to your annual Super Bowl
party this year? Too much avocado in the guacamole last year? Not
enough seats in front of the big-screen television?
</P>
<P>
   Try walking in Jim Steeg's shoes for a day. On Sunday, Steeg is
throwing a party for the 21st year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Super Bowl, and more than 70,000 people are
expected to attend the gala at the Georgia Dome. Country music
stars Travis Tritt and Faith Hill and pop diva Tina Turner will
perform.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there also will be a pro football game, which will be
watched by an estimated 800 million television viewers in 188
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't call Steeg a party-planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like going to parties,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As the NFL's senior vice president for special events, Steeg is
the maestro of the Super Bowl, the world's largest single-day
sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   It seems appropriate for the son of a Purdue engineering
professor who helped design the Saturn 5 rocket that landed on the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always talk about dumb jocks in football, so you figure
that you don't need a rocket scientist to run a football game,''
said Robert Dale Morgan, president of the Atlanta Super Bowl Host
Committee. ``Well, in this case, you've just got to be the son of
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Steeg, 49, was born in Boston and raised in Fort Wayne, Ind. He
attended Miami University in Ohio, and later earned an MBA in
finance at Wake Forest, graduating fourth in his class.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for a job in sports, Steeg wrote a letter to every
professional team in America seeking employment. In 1975, he was
hired as an accountant by the Miami Dolphins and within four years
was hired as the team's business manager.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Robbie, who owned the Dolphins then, replaced him with
one of his sons in January 1979, Steeg got the break that changed
his life. Two days after Steeg lost his job, NFL commissioner Pete
Rozelle hired him as the league's first director of administration.
</P>
<P>
   Only 28, Steeg didn't realize the magnitude of the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rozelle didn't even define what the job was going to be,''
Steeg said. ``I didn't know how big the job was or what Pete had in
mind. He either wasn't sure what it was going to be, or he didn't
want to upset the people that were down there working on the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   What Steeg got was the toughest job in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a perfectionist, but I've learned to live without
perfection,'' he says. ``I'm never really satisfied. Surfers know
that the perfect wave is rare. Major-league baseball players know
how difficult and special it is to pitch a perfect game. And deep
down, I realize that 95 percent is still an `A.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Steeg still does his homework. Since Jan. 8, he has been living
in a suite in an Atlanta hotel. Until this month, he spent one week
per month in Atlanta for the past year. A New Jersey resident, he
estimates his Super Bowl team has tallied more than 1,500 nights
here since February.
</P>
<P>
   Steeg begins planning a Super Bowl months before the city is
awarded a bid. The NFL usually awards Super Bowls at least four
years in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them from beginning to end,'' Steeg said. ``You go
through the whole pregnancy and see the birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything that is required to put on the game _ lodging,
transportation, security, entertainment, concessions _ comes across
Steeg's desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim has a similar management style to what Rozelle did,'' said
Bob Best, a member of Steeg's Super Bowl team who has produced the
pre-game show for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rozelle had wonderful ideas, and he found people who would
implement those ideas and build on them,'' Best said. ``Jim has
done that. I never seem to be amazed at the enormity of this event.
He just does an unbelievable job of orchestrating it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Steeg's biggest role is that of troubleshooter. In more
than two decades, he has seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 at Super Bowl XVI, an ice storm hit Detroit three days
before the game, covering streets with ice and backing up pipes at
the hotels.
</P>
<P>
   On Super Bowl Sunday, George Bush's vice presidential motorcade
backed up traffic as it made its way to the Pontiac Silverdome.
Bush had been a college roommate of Lions owner William Clay Ford.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Steeg wrote a memo listing 18 reasons why the
traffic plan failed. Among them were a bus fire and refusal by
police to get out of their cars because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 at Super Bowl XXII in San Diego, the hotel housing the
NFL headquarters didn't have enough hot water for early-morning
showers. Steeg purchased an enormous water heater from the Navy and
had it flown in by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that continues to amaze me is the fact that he has
such a great perspective for the big picture and the long term,''
Morgan said. ``But at the same time, he's concerned about every
single meticulous detail in the here and now. He's globally
thinking about where the game should be played three or four years
from now, and, at the same time, he's concerned that the tickets
don't look exactly right.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 at Super Bowl XXV in Tampa, Steeg was making his final
rounds through a deserted Giants locker room. He discovered the
Lombardi Trophy, given to the winning team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called (Giants general manager) George Young, and I said,
`Are you guys missing anything?' '' Steeg said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 at Super Bowl XXIX in Miami, Steeg received a telephone
call from a parking valet at the NFL headquarters hotel. The
attendant told Steeg that a courtesy car had just been turned in _
from Super Bowl XXVI in Minneapolis, Minn., three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know who had it,'' Steeg said. ``It just got turned
in, and the guy walked away.''
</P>
<P>
   Best and other colleagues say Steeg knows how to throw an
incredible party because he keeps the average fans' interests at
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim, more than anything else, is a sports fan,'' Best said.
``He does the stuff that the average fan on the street would do.
He's in fantasy football leagues and collects trading cards. He's
just a real sports fan.''
</P>
<P>
   And, apparently, a realistic one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be fun,'' Steeg says. ``For the players
and coaches, it's life or death. But we're not electing a
president, and this isn't the end of the earth. It's a football
game. If things don't go right, we'll play it again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
