</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A recent study, co-authored by NMA member Dr. Lisa
Cooper-Patrick, showed that black patients participate in
health-care decisions less than whites because of the race of their
physicians. She said black patients relate better to black
physicians and there is greater chance of miscommunication between
patients and physicians when they are of different races. That
often leads to misunderstandings regarding the cause of certain
diseases and effective treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the study, ``we have an understanding that the better
the doctor-patient relationship, the better the treatment
overall,'' said Cooper-Patrick, assistant professor of medicine and
health policy and management at the Johns Hopkins Medical
Institutions.
</P>
<P>
   (Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
