<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HEALTH-BLACKS-0125-CO     01-24 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BLACKS-0125-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK PHYSICIANS SAY MANAGED-CARE PLAN RACIALLY BIASED
 &HT;    (400&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Managed-care plans nationwide are excluding black
physicians the National Medical Association announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The NMA, the largest and oldest national organization
representing black physicians and health professionals in the
United States, wants Congress to enact laws that will prevent
exclusionary practices based on race.
</P>
<P>
   The association, which has more than 25,000 members, said the
exclusion limits black patients' choice of selecting black
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This practice is not only racist, but ultimately compromises
patient care,'' said Dr. Gary C. Dennis, NMA's immediate past
president.
</P>
<P>
   Some members called for protests by black doctors and patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we need to do is go back to the 60s-style
demonstrations. It has worked in the past for us,'' said Dr. Lenox
S. Dingle Jr., a general surgeon who lives and practices in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the American Association of
Health Plans, said her organization doesn't know enough about the
NMA's claims but would like to find out more and address the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding black doctors would be senseless because it works
against the health plan industry, she added. The industry wants to
have as many patients as possible, and turning away black doctors
would cause it to lose black patients who prefer black physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health plans are in the position to recruit more minority
physicians since they are in demand,'' Pisano said.
</P>
<P>
   When black physicians apply to join HMO panels, managed
health-care corporations often say their services are not needed,
Dingle said. Others are told that ``we have signed exclusive
contracts,'' or ``we have enough (doctors) in your area.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, for example, several doctors confronted the panels
directly through the Maryland Association of HMOs. They were told
that the corporations are not concerned with the racial make-up of
their panels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs also exclude black physicians by claiming they lack proper
credentials, even though the HMOs have not explicitly defined their
criteria, Dingle said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, HMOs claim that there is not enough demand for
black doctors in black communities, Dingle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, some of our physicians have ceased to be able to
practice medicine, others forced to relocate, and others are
discouraged from establishing practices in the (black
communities),'' he added, exacerbating an already desperate
shortage of doctors in black communities.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A recent study, co-authored by NMA member Dr. Lisa
Cooper-Patrick, showed that black patients participate in
health-care decisions less than whites because of the race of their
physicians. She said black patients relate better to black
physicians and there is greater chance of miscommunication between
patients and physicians when they are of different races. That
often leads to misunderstandings regarding the cause of certain
diseases and effective treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the study, ``we have an understanding that the better
the doctor-patient relationship, the better the treatment
overall,'' said Cooper-Patrick, assistant professor of medicine and
health policy and management at the Johns Hopkins Medical
Institutions.
</P>
<P>
   (Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
