A5009 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-WEB25-COX     01-24 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WEB25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet site of the week
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searching for health information on the Internet demands some
basic equipment: not just a computer and a connection, but hands to
manipulate a mouse and keyboard, eyes good enough to read a
monitor, and ears to hear the aural cues in a browser program. But
significant parts of the population have impairments to vision,
hearing or dexterity. Is the Internet _ which could educate them
about their disabilities _ closed to them?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. As the community of Net users expands,
accessibility is becoming as important a consideration for Web
design as it is in the real world. One site where this is elegantly
put into action is the home page of the nonprofit Macular
Degeneration Partnership (www.macd.net).
</P>
<P>
   Macular degeneration is an age-related eye disease that affects
almost 11 percent of the U.S. population ages 65 to 74 and 28
percent of those 75 or older. It's the leading cause of vision loss
and legal blindness in senior citizens. So there's a wide potential
readership for this site, which offers thorough information about
the disorder, research into treatments and community resources.
</P>
<P>
   To make the site friendly to Web surfers whose vision might
already be impaired, the partnership has made several thoughtful
design choices: A text-only choice is labeled on the index page,
the colors are high-contrast but nonglaring, and instructions for
enlarging the font to readable sizes are given for several browser
programs.
</P>
<P>
   _M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
