<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-MOORE-COX     01-24 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-MOORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to stop the McNair bashing
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now maybe they'll shut up about Steve McNair, but
probably not. The only way this miracle of a quarterback for the
Titans can make his critics find something more worthy to gripe
about would be if he spends Sunday inside the Georgia Dome running,
passing and inspiring his team past the Rams to a world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, they'd find something. They'll always find something
when it comes to McNair, and you can blame it on the black
quarterback thing, the small college thing or the defiant thing.
</P>
<P>
   As for the latter, so many folks have made a career out of
blasting McNair that they refuse to remove their blinders. I can't
blame them. They might have to squint after seeing his brilliant
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the bottom line: 12-2. That's the Titans'
record since McNair returned from back surgery earlier this season.
He also ignored an aching toe on his left foot Sunday against the
Jaguars to rush for 91 yards during the Titans' 33-14 romp to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the McNair bashers say their favorite target spent
another game showing he is allergic to the forward pass. He threw
for only 112 yards, but there are a couple of things to consider.
First, McNair is doing what is required in the Titans' offense, and
that is handing off to the gifted Eddie George and getting out of
the way. Second, McNair delivers passes in the clutch. For
verification, check the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jaguars, McNair kept a touchdown drive alive by
dropping into the pocket, using a stiff arm to escape a defender
and rolling to his left for a 15-yard completion. That play was in
addition to his 9-yard touchdown pass to Yancey Thigpen and another
one that was fumbled away near the goal line by Frank Wycheck.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the facts. Many prefer the fantasy that the best
position for McNair and other black quarterbacks is anywhere not
directly behind a center. While kicking and screaming, the NFL has
gone from no black quarterbacks for decades to a few this season,
but the best of the bunch still gets blasted no matter what he does
or how well he does it.
</P>
<P>
   McNair is used to this silliness by now. During his youth in
Mississippi, he was more prolific as a prep quarterback than Archie
Manning or Brett Favre. It didn't matter. Only Alcorn State would
allow McNair to play quarterback only. He became the first player
in NCAA history to gain more than 16,000 yards in total offense.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't matter, either. McNair finished third in the 1994
Heisman Trophy race to running backs Rashaan Salaam and Ki-Jana
Carter. Why? Well, a Heisman voter for an Oklahoma City newspaper
spoke for the masses by writing that McNair would be only the
third-string quarterback at the University of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   During that same stretch, NFL experts said the top three
quarterbacks in the upcoming draft would be Eric Zeier, Rob Johnson
and John Walsh, not exactly legends these days. As for McNair,
those same NFL experts said that Alcorn State didn't play anybody.
That he wasn't really 6 feet 3. That all he did was throw the ball
up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The old Houston Oilers saw something different. They saw McNair
prospering at Alcorn State with no offensive line, no running game,
no special teams, no coaching, one legitimate receiver and an
illegitimate defense. They made McNair the third pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Now those Oilers are these Titans, and they're four quarters
away from joining McNair in laughing last.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
