   BUSH-CAPITAL PUNISHMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As a longtime advocate for prison reform and the
leader of a national anti-death-penalty organization, Charlie
Sullivan has seen the conservative side of presidential candidate
George W. Bush. He's still waiting for a glimpse of the Texas
governor's compassionate side. By JOHN MORITZ. Story will move in
``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-A&AMP;M &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Establishing the George Bush School of
Government and Public Service on the Texas A&AMP;M University campus
was seen as a way to help bolster A&AMP;M's national image as a player
among major institutions of learning, on top of its agricultural
roots, ultraloyal alumni and proud Corp of Cadets traditions. But
since its formal dedication in 1997, the school's early years have
been marked with difficult challenges, an unsought windfall and at
least one embarrassing, nearly comical episode. By BARRY SHLACHTER.
Story will move in ``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the insular TV world of attention-getting
antics, this year's midseason press presentations were actually
quite tame, which may have more to do with success than with the
desperation[ through] that comes from failure. Meaning the success
of Who Wants to Be a Millionaire, of course, as the networks have
retreated from offering their expensive multinight movies for what
is, for the time being anyway, certain slaughter. Accompanied by
TV-MIDSEASON. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story will move in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AILEY-TROUPE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Alvin Ailey is a legend in the modern dance community.
Judith Jamison, whose reputation nearly rivals that of her mentor,
directs the Alvin Ailey Dance Theater and is determined to carry
the Ailey tradition well into the 21st century. By WAYNE LEE GAY.
Story will move in ``e'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EARLY PUBERTY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Parents are naturally worried when they see signs that
their daughters are entering puberty at an early age, and
pediatricians were accustomed to treating this condition by trying
to slow down the process. But recent studies show that early
puberty may not be an abnormality, and that girls may be entering
adolesence a year or two earlier than was commonly believed. By
GRACIE BONDS STAPLES. Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MENSTRUATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ As curses and blessings go, most women see menstrual
periods as a little of each. But, are they necessary when you are
not trying to become pregnant? Five years from now, women will be
having periods only when they want to have them, some doctors
predict. By CAROLYN POIROT. Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PERMISSIVE-PARENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: As American culture grows increasingly kid-centered,
parents seem ever more confused about where to draw the line _ in
meting out discipline, in buying material goods, in granting
responsibility. By LIZ STEVENS. Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle
category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LABBE-COLUMN,
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Language is the one thing that makes humankind unique
among the species on God's green earth. Well, language and souls.
People have them, although judging by the heinous actions committed
by some of them, you'd never know it. And if kids want to be
separated from the herd at the mall, they'd better learn how to use
it. By J.R. LABBE. Story will move in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
