   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   COKE-TROUBLES _ Like IBM and Delta Air Lines, Coca-Cola is
having the kind of trouble that eventually affects all major
corporations: a downturn in fortunes. The ability to reassess and
regroup to prepare their business for future growth is what
separates the successful companies from the laggards. Also
following developments at Coca-Cola Co. (McNaughton/Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-PACT _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth forges pact with
Atlanta-based ISS, takes equity stake in Predictive Systems, an
unusual move for BellSouth. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FED-GUYNN _ Jack Guynn, the president and chief executive
officer of the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta, delivers his annual
economic outlook Monday in a speech in Atlanta. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-MEDIA _ Urban Media, a California Internet company that
just received a slug of $25 million in venture capital, will use
the money to set up its operations center in Atlanta eventually
employing more than 100 people. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KIA-MOTORS _ Fresh off a record year for its car sales, Kia
Motors America just signed a lease for a large distribution and
parts center (320,000 sq. ft. expandable to 500,000 sq. ft.) in
metro Atlanta. In addition to real estate, we'll take a quick
history/look at the U.S. arm of Kia Motors Corp. of Korea.
(Wilbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitutioin).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
