<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METLIFE-CONVERSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME POLICYHOLDERS OPPOSE METLIFE'S CONVERSION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a hearing on the conversion of Metropolitan Life
Insurance Co. from ownership by its policyholders to ownership by
shareholders, a handful of policyholders argued Monday that they
and the company's more than 10 million other policyholders were not
getting a fair shake.
</P>
<P>
   The policyholders, lawyers representing policyholders and some
actuaries, who own policies, questioned Metropolitan Life's
procedures for valuing the company and allocating shares to
policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   They also raised doubts about the company's assertions that
taking MetLife public would not diminish dividends to policyholders
and contended that anti-takeover measures included in the
conversion plan could depress share prices, and thus the value
received by policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe the plan is fair and equitable to
policyholders,'' said Lance S. Gad, a former investment banker and
lawyer who is now a private investor. ``The major fault with the
Met plan is that it fails to offer policyholders the right to buy
stock at the public offering price.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the MetLife plan, policyholders are to be given shares
representing their contribution to company profits in exchange for
their ownership stake in the company. Those who want additional
shares must buy them after the initial public offering at the
market price, which is often somewhat higher than the initial
offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Benmosche, the chief executive of MetLife, and his senior
staff listened silently to the complaints after each of the
executives had given prepared statements repeatedly assuring the
audience of more than 150 people at a hotel that the conversion
plan was ``fair and equitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Benmosche nor the other MetLife executives responded to
the specific points raised by the policyholders. Neil D. Levin, the
state insurance superintendent who had convened the hearing, asked
Benmosche at the end of the meeting to respond. Benmosche said, ``I
do appreciate the input.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to understand,'' he added, ``that we as
management represent all the policyholders. We did the best we
could to be fair and equitable to all policyholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin, whose approval of the conversion is required, asked a few
questions of the MetLife executives but listened to the
policyholders without commenting. He has 60 days to consider his
decision. MetLife policyholders also must approve the conversion.
Voting has been open since late November and is to end on Feb. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
