<P>
   SUPER BOWL COVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-VERMEIL _ ATLANTA _ He walked away because of burnout. He
returned because he was tired of commenting on the NFL for
television and coaching was too much in his blood. Rams coach Dick
Vermeil was one of the four ``old'' guys hired four years ago, and
nobody thought he would succeed. Now he has his team in the Super
Bowl. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-STRATEGISTS _ The Men Who Changed The Game: We talk to the
most innovative strategists in pro football on the offensive and
defensive side of the ball to discuss how they changed the game.
From Air Coryell to West Coast offense, etc., when did these
innovators get their inspiration _ middle of the night, cocktail
napkins _ and what impact did it have on the sport. (Schlabach,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-PICDAY _ ATLANTA _ Every year, Butch John of the Jackson
(Miss.) Clarion-Ledger cringes on Super Bowl picture day. That's
when national TV announcers bring up the question he asked years
ago to Redskins quarterback Doug Williams: ``Have you always been a
black QB?'' To writers, the meaning behind the question was clear _
did it took the mega-event Super Bowl to bring the issue under
discussion. But the Talking Heads have made it a yearly laugh-off.
This is our effort to vindicate John in a picture day advance.
(Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-STEEG _ Jim Steeg, the guru of Super Bowl planning, says
this year's game offers an interesting contrast from year's past.
None of the remaining playoff teams have been to the Super Bowl
since it turned from a big game into THE mega-event. This creates
its own set of problems for Steeg, who must lead these teams by the
hand through the SBowl process. In early January, Steeg brought
team reps to Atlanta to start the education process. Steeg tells us
about his hopes, fears and what he's telling teams down to the most
minor details. (Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-PLAYS _ Short sider on men who will call the plays in
Sunday's game. (Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-AFC-DORSETT _ Tennessee's Anthony Dorsett. (Rosen, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-NFC-FEAT _ ATLANTA _ Feature from NFC camp. (Rogers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-TUE-RAIL _ ATLANTA _ Super Bowl category rail. (Schlabach
with TeamSuper assists. Categories include: Behind the Scenes (just
what it implies); Did You Know (neat little facts); Worth Repeating
(best quote of the day); By The Numbers (two per day) One Year Ago
(Falcons news last year); Celebrity Pick (who will win, score and
why). (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-AFC-RUNOFFENSE _ ATLANTA _ Feature on key cog in AFC run
game. (Stinson or Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-RUNDEFENSE _ ATLANTA _ Feature on key cog in NFC run
defense. (Bunn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-DEFENSE _ ATLANTA _ By the numbers rail for AFC run and
NFC run defense. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-AFC-NOTES _ ATLANTA _ Super Bowl notebook from the AFC
team. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-NFC-NOTES _ ATLANTA _ Super Bowl notebook from the NFC
team. (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-HUMMER _ ATLANTA _ Steve Hummer Super Bowl column.
(Hummer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SBOWL-MOORE _ ATLANTA _ Terence Moore Super Bowl column. (Moore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NON-SUPER BOWL SPORTS BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   FBC-RECRUITING _ College football recruiting has always been a
huge story in the Southeast. The internet has taken it to a whole
new level. Not only are fans logging on day and night to get
updates on the blue chip players; now the prospects themselves are
going into the chat rooms and conversing with fans about their
plans. (Arey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
