<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-MICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICE MAY PLAY ROLE IN BREAST CANCER'S CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Canada)  (mk) 
 By SCOTT HADLY   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ The mouse has long played the role of
victim in lab studies on cancer, but a new research paper suggests
the rodent may actually be the prime suspect in the transmission of
a virus responsible for at least some cases of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A paper published in this month's issue of the British Journal
of Cancer indicates that a virus _ called the mouse mammary tumor
virus _ may be transmitted to humans, and could lead to the
development of breast cancer in women.
</P>
<P>
   More than 44,000 women are diagnosed with breast cancer each
year in the United States and the authors suggest that the
rodent-borne virus could be the cause of up to 40 percent of the
cases in certain areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The paper is bound to raise eyebrows by focusing on a seemingly
unlikely source for some cases of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hypothesis, if true, provides a new insight into the
disease and suggests that a vaccine could be developed to prevent
it,'' said Richard Sage, one of the paper's four co-authors and an
adjunct professor of biology at the University of California at
Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Although for many years cancer researchers did not believe that
viruses caused the disease, scientists now know that several
cancers have viral causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the human papilloma virus can lead to cervical
cancer and hepatitis has been shown to cause liver cancer, for
instance,'' said Sage, an expert on wild and domestic mice.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also found that the highest rates of breast
cancer occurred in countries where Mus domesticus, a certain
species of house mouse, is native or has been introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer statistics show that the incidence of breast cancer is
twice as high in North America and Western Europe as in Eastern
Europe in Asia. While in the past researchers have cited factors
like diet to explain the different rates, the paper suggests that
the rates are related to the distribution of different species of
house mice.
</P>
<P>
   In areas with low rates of breast cancer, the Mus domesticus
species is not found. Where it is found _ in the United States,
Western Europe, Australia and New Zealand _ the rates of breast
cancer are high.
</P>
<P>
   Geography, then, and not diet, seems to have more to do with
increased chances for breast cancer, the authors of the report say.
</P>
<P>
   When Japanese women emigrate to the United States, where Mus
domesticus is found, their rates of breast cancer increase. Similar
findings were made among Soviet Jews: They had low rates of breast
cancer while living in the former Soviet Union, but once they
emigrated to Israel _ where Mus domesticus also makes its home _
their rates increased, the researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   But the study leaves many questions unanswered, and the
researchers emphasize that their work is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the very early days,'' said Dr. Thomas Stewart, a
co-author of the study who works at the University of Ottawa at
Ottawa Hospital. ``This is a hypothesis, but it's all testable.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that scientists from the National Cancer Institute
in the United States and its Canadian counterpart have snubbed some
of the researchers' ideas.
</P>
<P>
   A recently published 1,500-page book on the epidemiology of
cancer by the NCI's chief geneticist completely ignored the mouse
mammary tumor virus, Stewart said. This despite DNA studies that
date back to 1981 showing correlations between the rodent-borne
virus and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are going to be slightly offended by some of what
we've found,'' Stewart said. ``But the evidence is so compelling. I
would say we've found one of the strongest correlations for breast
cancer in the last 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most significant question that needs to be
addressed is how viruses in mice are transmitted to humans, the
researchers said. Although there are some theories, little research
is available in the area. At the very least, the scientists say,
their research poses many important questions that need to be
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of work that hasn't been done yet needs to be done,''
said Sage.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara, Calif., News-Press is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
