<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKS&AMP;SPENCER-APPOINT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKS &AMP; SPENCER APPOINTS A BELGIAN CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Marks &AMP; Spencer, Britain's august but ailing retailer,
broke with a long tradition and reached beyond the nation's shores
Monday to hire a new executive chairman, offering a $22 million
package to lure the Belgian-born Luc Vandevelde from Promodes, a
leading France-based grocery chain.
</P>
<P>
   Vandevelde, who will join the 116-year-old British company on
Feb. 28, is a high-profile emblem of its increasingly desperate
effort to reverse the fortunes that have not only sullied its
one-time image as the flagship of British retailing but also
inspired talk of a takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   With a background largely in food retailing, however,
Vandevelde's vaunted successes at Promodes, which the French
retailing giant Carrefour is in the process of purchasing, may not
translate too easily into turning Marks &AMP; Spencer around. The
company has been fighting a losing battle with rivals like Next PLC
and Hennes and Mauritz of Sweden in the midrange clothing market.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he does bring is a fresh look, because virtually
everybody else there has been at Marks &AMP; Spencer for a long time,''
said Ian Macdougal, a retail analyst with the brokerage firm
Williams de Broe.
</P>
<P>
   In historical terms, Vandevelde's appointment _ agreed on late
Sunday night and announced Monday _ is a big shift in corporate
culture for an organization that until the premature departure last
June of Sir Richard Greenbury, its previous executive chairman, had
been run by a coterie of longtime Marks &AMP; Spencer executives.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership change made little impact on investors Monday and
the company's stock ended down 1.5 percent at 304.25 pence, or
$5.02. While the share price has risen about 4 percent this month
because of takeover talk, it fell last year by 29 percent.
``Vandevelde has still got a lot to prove,'' said Alan Harris, a
fund manager at Charles Stanley &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   That Marks &AMP; Spencer sought an outsider _ and a non-British one
at that _ reflected the extent of the problems at the company,
which owns the Brooks Bros. chain in the United States. Since late
1997, Marks &AMP; Spencer's profits have been sliding as Main Street
Britain decided that the chain's clothing range was simply dowdy
and too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reverse the decline, Peter Salsbury, the chief
executive, ordered increased spending on advertising, new store
layouts and new clothing ranges. He also canceled contracts with
British clothing suppliers, breaking a long tradition of buying
British, to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   But according to a research report issued by Salomon Smith
Barney on Jan. 13, Marks &AMP; Spencer's year-end sales figures, a
closely watched barometer, were ``better than worst fears but
offered no sign of decisive recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has acknowledged that sales were down 2.8 percent
for the 15 weeks to Jan. 8, depressed largely by dwindling demand
for its clothes _ once a hallmark of good value. ``It is hard to
take an upbeat view of the prospects for a rapid recovery,'' the
research note said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company has been looking for a new executive chairman for
over six months. But there was some surprise that it got
Vandevelde, who had been designated for the No. 2 job at the
combined group to emerge from last year's proposed merger of
Promodes and Carrefour, a combination that would create Europe's
biggest retailer and the world's second-biggest after Wal-Mart
Stores.
</P>
<P>
   Vandevelde had been credited with helping strengthen the
Promodes share price sixfold after joining the company as president
and chief operating officer in 1995 following 24 years with Kraft
Jacobs Suchard.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed as chairman of Promodes less than a year ago, he was
credited with helping expand the French group into an international
giant with 6,000 outlets in 16 countries. But, analysts said, he
had bridled at taking the No. 2 slot after the merger with
Carrefour.
</P>
<P>
   Marks &AMP; Spencer said his compensation package included a basic
salary of $1.1 million that could be doubled by performance-linked
bonuses. Additionally, he will receive shares and stock options
totaling over $20 million _ a significant package by British
standards. He will report to Salsbury, the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Marks &AMP; Spencer's decline has inspired increasing speculation
about a takeover bid either from the retail entrepreneur Philip
Green or even from Tesco, Britain's No. 1 supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   Vandevelde declined to discuss how he would respond to such
overtures. ``If someone comes up with a bid, we'll deal with it
when it happens,'' he said. ``Nobody can ever refuse to look at a
bid if it is a serious one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
