<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-LESBIANS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDY FOCUSES ON LESBIANS AND AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Calif., N.Y., D.C., N.J., Fla.)  (js) 
 By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first federally funded study of HIV-infected
lesbians and other women who have sex with women is under way in
five major U.S. cities. The research is an effort to learn more
about the risks facing this little-researched group.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Centers for Disease Control, the three-year
study of 200 HIV-positive women in Baltimore, Los Angeles, New
York, San Francisco and Washington should shed light on the ways in
which women can contract the AIDS virus from a female partner.
</P>
<P>
   Epidemiologists have long believed that oral sex and other
intimate behavior between women is an inefficient way to transmit
the disease. Only two cases of female-to-female transmitted HIV
have been reported to the CDC, and they were never confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers aren't ruling out the possibility of a
female-to-female-borne AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say with absolute assurance that female-to-female
transmission never occurs,'' said Dr. Helene Gayle, director of the
CDC's National Center for HIV, STD and TB Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers should be able to make a stronger case for or
against such an occurrence once the study is completed in
September. Now in the final stage of data collection, the research
is scheduled to be published later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The findings could provide a basis for a more informed message
of HIV-prevention for female sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gayle said the current scarcity of data on the issue is
unacceptable. ``It's been fairly unsatisfying to say it's rare, but
we really hope that this will answer some of those questions,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Women accounted for 32 percent of adult cases of HIV infections
from July 1998 to June 1999, according to the latest figures
compiled by the CDC. New Jersey and Florida led the nation in HIV
infections with 13,259 and 11,625 cases respectively, the CDC
found. These two states also had the most cases of female HIV
infections.
</P>
<P>
   One question for researchers is whether lesbians, bisexuals and
other women who have had sexual contact with a woman at some point
in their lives can contract HIV independent of other risky behavior
like injection drug use.
</P>
<P>
   A December 1998 CDC survey found that 98 percent of women with
AIDS who reported having sex with women had been exposed to another
risk _ injection drug use in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers hope to rule out those other HIV-risk factors
through a sophisticated DNA analysis coupled with face-to-face
interviews _ some of which will be conducted with a woman's sexual
partner.
</P>
<P>
   No previous study has attempted to substantiate female-to-female
transmission of HIV in such a comprehensive manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first federally funded study of a population that
has not been looked at before,'' said Renee Culver, who is
coordinating the Washington study of 50 women at the Whitman-Walker
Clinic. ``One would think its time has come.''
</P>
<P>
   Both gay and straight women over age 18 are being recruited for
the CDC study, potentially broadening the definition of groups that
are at risk of acquiring HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC defines lesbians as women who have had sex with women
but have not had sex with men since 1977. The study, however, takes
into account the fact that not all women who have a sexual
encounter with a woman identify themselves as gay.
</P>
<P>
   The research conceivably could target women who may be married
but are having lesbian affairs. Some may be heterosexuals who
briefly experimented with the same sex, while others may have been
coerced into a homosexual act. Still others may be uncomfortable
revealing their sexual orientation, the study's researchers point
out.
</P>
<P>
   The lesbian community has always questioned the notion that the
risk of HIV between women is low.
</P>
<P>
   When the epidemic first erupted among gay men in the early
1980s, gay women, many of whom cared for their dying gay male
friends, were quick to ask, ``Are we next?''
</P>
<P>
   ``As this epidemic has matured over the last two decades, we are
seeing that it is not only a white, gay male disease but it is a
disease that can affect everybody,'' said Dr. Lisa Weissmann, vice
president of the Gay and Lesbian Medical Association in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Weissmann, an oncologist, welcomed the research as a chance
to shed a myth. ``It's not reasonable to think that this is a
disease that cannot be spread from women to women.''
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Hollingsworth is in the Washington Bureau of the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
