<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Jan. 25 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ Ruling in a Missouri campaign
finance case with important national implications, the Supreme
Court on Monday decisively upheld limits on campaign contributions
and rejected the argument that inflation has rendered
unconstitutionally low the $1,000 limit it upheld 24 years ago. The
6-3 decision left states with considerable latitude either to adopt
the federal limit, still the $1,000 the court upheld in its
much-disputed Buckley vs. Valeo decision, or to experiment with
even lower contribution caps, as a number of states recently have.
By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-CAUCUSES (Des Moines) _ Ledeall on the Iowa caucuses. By
Richard L. Berke. (Editors, see also IOWA-CAUCUSES-ADVISORY, moving
in 30 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Undated) _ The grandmothers of Elian Gonzalez left
for Miami on Monday to meet with their grandson before they return
to Cuba. A family spokesman in Miami said such a meeting would be
welcome, but it appeared the two sides did not agree on where the
meeting should be held. (Summary from wires) By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND-BURMA (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Developing. A handful of
Burmese rebels apparently under the command of 12-year-old twin
boys crossed into Thailand on Monday and took over a hospital in
the Thai border town of Ratchaburi, 75 miles west of here. holding
as many as 800 patients and staff hostage throughout the day. The
black-masked gunmen are from a splinter group of ethnic Karen
rebels that calls itself God's Army. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STARS-BROADWAY (New York) _ Susan Lucci of the soap opera
``All My Children'' recently replaced Bernadette Peters in ``Annie
Get Your Gun'' for three weeks. Kathie Lee Gifford of ``Regis and
Kathie Lee'' is going on for Carol Burnett on Tuesday nights
through Feb. 15, in ``Putting it Together.'' Robert Urich of
``Spenser: For Hire'' has just completed a three-month stint in
``Chicago.'' Not one of these television stars had appeared on
Broadway before. None had the classic up-from-the-ranks training.
None had earned reputations as distinguished actors on film. But in
an age when Broadway has become dominated by mega-musicals and
revivals dependent in part on ticket sales to tourists, this didn't
seem to matter. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-MERGER (Undated) _ Consumer products giant Procter and
Gamble announced it had called off merger talks with Warner-Lambert
and American Home Products Monday because of too much press
speculation. In particular, the company blamed leaks over the
three-way talks for the sharp decline in its stock price, which has
fallen about 10 dollars since news of the discussions emerged on
Wednesday last week. (Summary from wires) By Dana Canedy.
