<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POETRY-DISABILITY-ART     01-24 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POETRY-DISABILITY-ART-810(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DISABLED SOAR ON POETRY'S WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vanessa Cole writes poetry with her toe. She cannot
move her arms or legs. She cannot talk, nod, smell or taste, though
she has a brilliant smile that compels a response, for Ms. Cole's
entire expressive nature is tied up in her smile. And then there is
her poetry, which she writes by pointing her toe at letters on a
plastic sheet that someone holds in front of her foot.
</P>
<P>
   For nine years Ms. Cole, who is paralyzed from a stroke, has
been a patient at the Coler-Goldwater Memorial Hospital, a
municipal hospital for the severely disabled on Roosevelt Island.
And for six of those years she has been in a class taught by
students in New York University's graduate creative writing
program. The class was begun in 1984 by the poet Sharon Olds with
financing from Very Special Arts, a foundation created by Jean
Kennedy Smith to provide arts education for people with
disabilities. The class has 12 patients and a long waiting list.
After a winter break, it starts up again on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At Goldwater patients write about the worlds they have lost,
about the experience of being prisoners in their own bodies. Ms.
Cole wrote in one poem:
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember hunger.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger is a state of mind,
</P>
<P>
   not a valid feeling.
</P>
<P>
   I only get headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes her work has the tough cadence and purity of Emily
Dickinson's poetry. Long before she arrived at Goldwater, Ms. Cole,
who comes from the Caribbean island of St. Vincent, was reading
Dickinson. She keeps a volume of her poetry beside her bed and
occasionally one of the students reads to her from it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cole wrote last year:
</P>
<P>
   Tears from heaven
</P>
<P>
   How many more
</P>
<P>
   on puffs of satin
</P>
<P>
   in a veil of controversy
</P>
<P>
   heaped in a pool
</P>
<P>
   by the lake of no return.
</P>
<P>
   The students had been asked to write about rain without using
the word. And so Ms. Cole, who was a nurse before she had the first
of two strokes in 1990, painstakingly pointed to the letters with
her toe, sometimes grunting with the effort, while her student
teacher, Jennifer Keller, wrote the words on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Cole, Tamika Walker, 26, another student in the class,
is almost completely paralyzed from an auto accident when she was 2
years old. She has been at Goldwater since she was 3. Ms. Walker
breathes with a tube in her throat and controls her wheelchair with
a device she operates with her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Her poems, like many of the patients' work, are filled with
images of freedom, of animals prowling, of birds flying. In one,
``My New Tree,'' she wrote, ``I sometimes dream about being a
bird/when I dream about that I wonder how I can fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the patients' poetry is unformed, some of the prose only
bits and pieces of imagery. But ``every man could speak, if he hath
loved and been well nourished in the mother tongue,'' Ms. Olds
wrote, quoting Keats, when she described the Goldwater program. Ms.
Keller has had some of Ms. Cole's poems accepted for publication in
an NYU literary journal, ``Evolution/Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   At Goldwater, the graduate students get a writing lesson like no
other. This is a place where language is laid bare, where each word
is chosen with excruciating effort, so hard to come by that it must
carry a great weight. There are no fancy literary tropes at
Goldwater, no confusion of critical discourse. The students'
writing is a reminder that story and language, pure and simple, are
the foundations of literature. ``Any teacher of writing will talk
about how much they learn about the craft themselves by teaching
it,'' said Melissa Hammerle, the coordinator of the NYU creative
writing program, which gives the student teachers a $500 stipend
each semester. The university also has writing programs at the
Metropolitan Correctional Center, a federal prison, in hospitals
and in New York City public schools. The classes are paid for by
individual donors and the Park, Starlight, Tomorrow and New York
Times Co. foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Goldwater, the students are up against such naked and
terrible necessity,'' Ms. Olds said. ``They are up against the
craft of how to bear the human.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keller, 29, who is studying poetry at NYU, said: ``When it
is more difficult to speak or pick a word, the stakes go up
exponentially. There is a kind of fidelity to language that comes
from how difficult it is to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cole ``will fight for the words she wants,'' Ms. Keller,
said, ``even when it takes that much blood and sweat to write a
single word. She's a writer. We will fuss over every line break and
every punctuation mark until she's satisfied with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her incapacity, Ms. Cole has a dry sense of humor. ``I
can babble with the best of them,'' she spelled out one day last
semester on her letter chart when a reporter sat down next to her
to talk. How old is she, she was asked? ``N-o t-e-l-l,'' Ms. Cole
spelled, then laughed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One day, Jason Schneiderman, 23, a student teacher, announced
that the topic for the class would be ``transformation.'' To give
the students an idea of what he meant, he read from Ted Hughes'
translation of Ovid's ``Arachne,'' about a girl who is changed into
a spider by the jealous goddess Minerva. Schneiderman read:
</P>
<P>
   And now she is all belly
</P>
<P>
   With a dot of head
</P>
<P>
   She retains
</P>
<P>
   Only her slender skillful fingers
</P>
<P>
   For legs. And for ever
</P>
<P>
   She hangs from the thread that she spins
</P>
<P>
   Out of her belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Okay, so let's write,'' Schneiderman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I d - o - n - t, '' Ms. Cole began to spell out the letters on
her chart. ``I don't like the choice of poems,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keller, sitting beside her, urged her on. ``If you were
going to change into something else, what would it be?'' she asked
Ms. Cole. ``For example, a stubborn, difficult, hard-headed
woman?'' she teased. Ms. Cole smiled. Ms. Keller kept encouraging
her. If she could change into something else, what would it be? ``A
half-decent me,'' Ms. Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My former self,'' she continued, spelling out the words. ``I
will be proud of what I will achieve/ Save, as well as bring, new
life into a healthy world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Keller said: ``This is a really good idea. You're not going
to quit just because it's hard.'' It would serve as a first draft,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room from Ms. Cole sat Joseph Wright, 45, who has
been at Goldwater 12 years and in the writing program about five
years. Wright is tall and athletic looking and speaks in a low
voice that is difficult to understand. Most of the time he is
silent. He said he used to play basketball at City College of New
York with the rapper Keith Sweat. Wright said he was not quite sure
what causes the partial paralysis that robs him of the ability to
walk and control his limbs. He was a security guard, Wright said,
and ``I was walking along 42nd Street, and I woke up in Bellevue. I
tried to get up and walk, and I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright's work is filled with allusions to being homeless: ``I
stayed in a 42nd-Street movie theater for about two weeks, day in
and day out. People staying there with me washed in the bathroom
and ate in the movie viewing area.''
</P>
<P>
   He also writes about the life of a crack addict: ``The part I
couldn't understand was that I spent so much and it didn't do
nothing, just that thirst. Stay out at all hours of the night,
roaming around with people searching for money to get the crack.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with Wright reminds his teacher, Reena Shah, 23, of the
importance of the story. Ms. Shah, who is writing a novel, said
sometimes in her classes at NYU she felt overwhelmed by critical
jargon about structure and imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of times you get away from the basics, the reason that
you write, when you're in a typical graduate student workshop,''
she said. ``The importance of telling a story, how crucial it is,
is something I've learned at Goldwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the workshop on transformation, Wright dictated in a low
voice to Ms. Shah about what he would like to be. ``If I woke up
here as a bird, I'd fly out of here,'' he said. ``As a wolf, I'd
attack somebody. There's a couple of people I would attack without
giving it much thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end he wrote: ``I'm tired of captivity. I'd get
chained up and put in a zoo or something. If I make it I'd just
roam free, though not exactly. I'd have to dodge all the time. I'd
be considered dangerous. I'd have to find someplace away from
people. I'd be such a threat. They'd probably be told to shoot me
at sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year the workshop culminates in a party and a group
reading on the last day of the semester. The students' work is
printed in a pamphlet. This time there was coffee, cake, fruit and
crackers. The students sat in a circle, reading their work or
listening as one of their teachers read it.
</P>
<P>
   Gesille James, the supervising activity therapist in the
recreation services department, began by reading an inspirational
quotation from Eleanor Roosevelt: ``You gain strength, courage and
confidence by every experience in which you really stop and look
fear in the face. You are able to say to yourself: `I lived through
this horror. I can take the next thing that comes along.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the teachers, Lara Payne, read a poem by her student
James Rascoe, who had written about her. Rascoe, 35 and blind from
glaucoma, has been in the program for nearly three years, since he
arrived at Goldwater. His fiancee, another patient at the hospital,
Ruth Taylor Jones, in a wheelchair, was at the party.
</P>
<P>
   A wiry, ebullient figure with dark glasses, he smiled as Ms.
Payne read his poem, called ``Very Well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lara asked me how I was doing. I answered that I was fine.
</P>
<P>
   I asked her how she was doing, and she said, `Very Well,'
</P>
<P>
   with a big smile, a grin, and all 32 gleaming teeth. I'm blind,
</P>
<P>
   but her gleaming teeth would blind me again.
</P>
<P>
   The last person to read was Wright. It was a piece about the
South Bronx and all the young men who have died there. Ms. Shah
read it for him. ``I think back to when I walked in a group in the
past,'' he wrote. ``Unity, the people you hang with all the time _
mainly my brother. My brother passed, but I don't know about anyone
else. I call my sisters twice a week and they say they don't see
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was getting to be a routine: this guy died, that guy died.
It was getting to be like who died today.''
</P>
<P>
   As she read, Wright sat back very still in his wheelchair,
silent, as he usually does, watching the room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
