<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kia selects Georgia county for distribution facility
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kia Motors America's need for new space is good news
for one Metro Atlanta county but bad news for another.
</P>
<P>
   Kia has signed a 10-year lease for space at Newpoint
Distribution Center at I-85 and Ga. 120 in Gwinnett.
</P>
<P>
   Kia currently operates a much smaller distribution facility at
Riverside Business Park in Cobb and will move to Gwinnett in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Irvine, Calif., automobile company needs more space as it
comes off a record sales year and prepares to launch three new
models this year, spokeswoman Teppy Whigington said. ``(Kia) just
needed some extra space (in Atlanta),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kia has 50 workers in its Cobb facility and expects to add to
its work force after the move. The company expects to retain some
workers in Cobb at a new sales office.
</P>
<P>
   The American marketing arm of Kia Motor Corp. of Seoul, South
Korea, Kia Motors America sells Sephia cars and Sportage
sport-utility vehicles. It has several dealerships in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At Newpoint Distribution Center, situated in the triangle
created by I-85, Ga. 120 and Ga. 316, Kia signed a 10-year lease.
It initially will occupy 317,000 square feet in the
451,000-square-foot facility and is expected eventually to lease
the entire building.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta office of Panattoni Development Co. started
construction on the building after Kia signed the lease, said Mike
Demperio, a Panattoni principal.
</P>
<P>
   Kia's five-year lease of a 90,000-square-foot facility in
Riverside along I-20 expires in October, said Scott Raeber, project
manager for Crescent Resources. The North Carolina development arm
of Duke Energy bought the 331 acres of undeveloped land at
Riverside this month.
</P>
<P>
   Kia chose Newpoint because Panattoni had a site ready for the
quick construction of a distribution center, said Mark Kercher, a
Julien J. Studley Inc. broker who represented the car company with
his brother, Ed Kercher. ``We looked under every rock in and above
and below metro Atlanta,'' he said. ``We had to find a pad-ready
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
