A5048 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BELLSOUTH-PACT25-COX     01-24 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PACT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth forges pact with ISS
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. on Monday announced a partnership to
sell computer security solutions with Atlanta-based Internet
Security Systems and, in a separate deal, bought part a small New
York consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Although the $3 million investment in the consulting company,
Predictive Systems, gives BellSouth less than 10 percent ownership,
it amounts to a stake in an ambitious company in an important
sector. Predictive Systems offers help to companies with the design
and management of computer networks. The ISS deal lets BellSouth
offer more services to its huge list of customers, said Donna Lee,
BellSouth president for marketing, in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do view this as a dramatic change but it's in context of
how BellSouth is doing things. This is a directional step,
registering our intent to be a player. There is a $2 billion-plus
market in which we are not participating.''
</P>
<P>
   The target for these services are small- and medium-sized
businesses, Lee said. ``Customers who are big enough to have an
intensity of need but small enough so they don't want to fund this
technical expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   More moves _ including investments _ are likely in the
near-future, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ISS, founded in 1994 by Chris Klaus in his Georgia Tech dorm,
burst from obscurity to become a source of protection for
high-stakes networks like those of the Pentagon, multi-national
banks and other major corporations. ISS is expanding its strategy,
partnering with large telecom companies like BellSouth to deliver
security to thousands of business customers, said Thomas Noonan,
ISS president and chief executive. ``We want to be the man behind
the curtain. This is very consistent with our strategy as we focus
on delivering security, not just as a technology but as a
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Together with ISS, BellSouth will offer a host of products,
including ``firewalls'' meant to keep unwanted electronic visitors
away from a company's networks, as well as software that will
detect intruders and respond to them. The offerings are aimed at
what both companies believe is a large and growing market. For
instance, an Ernst &AMP; Young survey that showed more than half U.S.
businesses do not monitor online activites and have no planned
response to security problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Predictive Systems stake is interesting because Bellsouth
has been cautious about taking an ownership stake in other firms,
so even a small stake looms large as a signal. There has been no
similar investment since the $3.5 billion deal that gave BellSouth
a 10 percent piece of Qwest Communications last April.
</P>
<P>
   Predictive represents a piece of a network consulting market
that is expected to reach $6 billion by 2003, according to analysts
at International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With Predictive Systems, small and privately-held, BellSouth can
get ``the most bang for its buck'' with an equity investment, Lee
said. By contrast, ISS has a market capitalization of about $2.7
billion. ISS closed Monday at $66 a share. A partnership made more
sense than plunking down a pile of money, Lee said. ``With every
partner you decide what's best.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcements were made at the ComNet trade show in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
