<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harvard offers best payback on MBA
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An MBA isn't what it used to be, given that working for an
Internet startup instead of going back to business school can be a
lucrative option.
</P>
<P>
   So which schools offer the best payback for the time and money
that has to be spent to earn an MBA?
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, according to Forbes (Feb. 7). It's Harvard at the
top, based on the net gain in income by 1994 MBA graduates. Emory's
Goizueta Business School ranks 24th in payback, according to
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State and the University of Georgia show up as Nos. 10
and 11, respectively, on a second list of what Forbes refers to as
``mostly regional business schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in Forbes: Investors worried about Lucent Technologies'
recent missteps in anticipating the demand for the latest fiber
optics switch need not fear, the magazine suggests. ``Lucent is
well poised to help lead an optical revolution that will whip
information around the globe at a fraction of today's cost,''
Forbes offers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding the pearls can make the world your oyster
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of beaten down stocks out there. But only a
handful of them are pearls, according to Kiplinger's Personal
Finance (February). The magazine identifies eight stocks it
considers ``exceptional businesses selling at bargain-basement (or
at least relatively inexpensive) prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in Kiplinger's: An interview with Robert Stansky, manager
of Fidelity's Magellan fund.
</P>
<P>
   _And then there are the hot stocks _ technology stocks
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Personal Finance (January/February) looks at 100
stocks that were hot last year _ think technology _ and estimates
long-term growth rates for them. The magazine also adds a caveat
for those who might drool over last year's returns: ``While high
expectations are seductive, they can also be a curse _ and
dangerous for investors to chance.
</P>
<P>
   _Issue of money offers the `ultimate' fund guide
</P>
<P>
   Money (February) makes no bones about its offering: the issue is
labeled as ``The ultimate mutual fund guide.'' Inside are
performance rankings on more than 2,100 funds, lists of top
performers over various time periods, and thumbnail profiles of who
the magazine considers are the best fund managers of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   _Made in the U.S.A. version of prosperity tries to go abroad in
Business Week
</P>
<P>
   Can the New World export the ``new economy''? Yes, says Business
Week (Jan. 31), but not overnight. The magazine looks at what it
takes to create a technology driven, low inflation economy, and how
some parts of the world are starting to adopt the U.S. model.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Business Week: An up-close-and-personal look at Selina
Y. Lo, the in-your-face vice president of marketing for Alteon
Websystems, maker of computer networking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
