u l BC-WOMEN-POLL-HNS &LR;      01-24 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLL SHOWS WOMEN MORE LIKELY THAN MEN TO GET VOTING TIPS FROM
MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``P'' and ``l'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twice as many women as men say spouses are their most
important political influence, according to a survey of more than
3,000 women by Women.com Networks, Inc. and Good Housekeeping
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The November 1999 survey conducted online and via telephone
assessed the political behavior and beliefs of American women. The
survey was conducted by pollster Harris Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Husbands and wives have very different political influences.
When asked their primary political influences, the single largest
group of women point to their mates, followed by their parents (Mom
first).
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, men are most influenced by their fathers _ only
half as many men look to their mates for political opinions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly one-third of women are undecided in the race for
president.
</P>
<P>
   _ George W. Bush leads with 30 percent of women in general,
thanks to his core support from all women 30-64 and Hispanic women
overall. Vice President Al Gore was the only other candidate with
double-digit support from women (18 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ Online women gave the least credence to political party when
asked the importance of party, issues, and candidate impression.
Only 28 percent of online women _ compared to 42 percent in general
_ said political party was very important or important.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 94 percent said issues are very important when
considering whether to vote for a particular candidate, followed by
candidate impression (82 percent) and political party (42 percent).
</P>
<P>
   _ Online women aligned with women in the general public in
identifying the top five issues of greatest importance in this
election year: health care, children/families, education, Social
Security, and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The majority of women do not want to know what goes on in a
president's private life _ particularly young women and African
American women. However, baby boomers and Republicans are more
inclined to want to know.
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted in conjunction with Majority 2000, a
joint-initiative between Women.com and Good Housekeeping to track
the political views and trends of women during the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The survey covered 3,223 women and 3,439 men using traditional
telephone methods and the Internet. The survey of online women was
administered on the Internet only, and the telephone survey
included a percentage of men and women who also use the Internet on
a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com (www.women.com) is a leading Internet network
dedicated to women. Good Housekeeping, founded 114 years ago, is
published by Hearst Magazines, a unit of Hearst Communications,
Inc., the world's largest publisher of monthly magazines, with 16
U.S. titles and 98 international editions distributed in more than
100 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Interactive (http://www.HarrisInteractive.com) is a
leading market research and polling firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
