<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DIET-GUIDELINES-A     01-24 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIET-GUIDELINES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDELINES MIX POLITICS AND CHICKEN SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Science Times)  
(DW) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watch the sodas and do not eat the chicken skin, but if you feel
like having a glass of wine, or two, help yourself.
</P>
<P>
   If the latest revisions to federal dietary guidelines are
included in the final version later this month, that advice would
be part of the government's basic message.
</P>
<P>
   The working version, still subject to rewriting, differs in
several ways from the advice that the government offered in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking difference is that three of the first four
guidelines have nothing to do with food choices but instead deal
with food safety, exercise and weight, all noncontroversial topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this has done,'' said Dr. Marion Nestle, chairwoman of
the Department of Nutrition and Food Studies at New York University
and a member of the 1995 advisory committee on dietary guidelines,
``is shift the focus of the guidelines from food to other factors.
The de-emphasis on food and increased emphasis on other factors is
not a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nestle said there were some admirable changes in the 10
single-sentence guidelines and some that were just continuations of
the government's unwillingness to be more precise about how
Americans could improve their health through the food they eat.
</P>
<P>
   The Dietary Guidelines for Americans, updated every five years
by a joint advisory committee of the Agriculture Department and the
Department of Health and Human Services, are used by the federal
government to plan food programs and by private industry to
dispense nutrition information.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the usual wrangling over the guidelines' wording,
this year both the advisory panel and the report face a court
challenge. A health advocacy group in Washington, the Physicians
Committee for Responsible Medicine, wants to prevent the release of
the final report, because, it says, at least 6 of the 11 members of
the advisory panel have or have had financial ties to the meat,
dairy or egg industries.
</P>
<P>
   A suit, filed in December, also also says the guidelines do not
meet the health needs of members of minorities that are
lactose-intolerant and that the recommendations should make dairy
products an optional source for calcium.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday a federal district judge in Washington will decide
whether to issue a preliminary injunction against the release of
the final guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Other protests, by the food industry, follow a familiar pattern
_ efforts to soften the wording of the guidelines. The
recommendation about sugar in the diet is likely to bring strong
protests from the soft drink industry because the guidelines urge
people to ``go easy on beverages and foods high in added sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   By including the word ``added'' for the first time, the
committee said it was acknowledging the substantial amount of
research that ``nondiet soft drinks displace beverages or foods
that are richer in essential nutrients, such as milk and fruit
juices, in the diets of American children.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Soft Drink Association has its own research to
suggest that soft drinks are not replacing milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific evidence to support any changes in
dietary guidelines on added sugar,'' said Sean McBride, a spokesman
for the National Soft Drink Association.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation on fats has also been changed. The previous
guidelines called for a diet low in total fat, saturated fat and
cholesterol. The new guidelines would recommend a diet low in
saturated fat and cholesterol but moderate in total fat. The
maximum fat intake would remain the same at 30 percent of total
calories, or 65 grams a day in a 2,000-calorie diet, appropriate
for men but high for most women.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nestle finds the recommendation reasonable, but asked, ``Why
not call a hamburger a hamburger or a steak a steak?''
</P>
<P>
   Using the words saturated fat and cholesterol are just
``euphemisms for saying eat less meat and processed food,'' Dr.
Nestle said. Not since 1979 has the government told Americans to
``eat less meat.'' The meat industry objected to that wording so
strongly that it was never included again.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory panel's vice chairwoman, Dr. Suzanne Murphy, a
research nutritionist, said: ``The intent of the report is not to
say what foods are good and what foods are bad. We didn't give
people a list of good meats and bad meats.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead the guidelines tell people to trim external fat and
remove the skin from the chicken. She said the 1995 guidelines
listed sausages, salami and organ meats as fatty meats, but steaks
and hamburgers have still not made the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a misperception that people are eating too much
beef,'' said Mary Young, executive director of nutrition programs
for the National Cattlemen's Beef Association. ``We do believe
Americans should eat more fruits, vegetables and grain but not at
expense of lean meat or lean dairy products.''
</P>
<P>
   Substantially changed from 1990 to 1995 from a prohibitionist
tone to an acknowledgment that consuming some alcohol may be
healthful, the guideline for alcohol has been further tweaked to
specify those who might benefit.
</P>
<P>
   In the working version, it reads: drinking in moderation may
lower the risk of coronary heart disease, mainly among men over the
age of 45 and women over the age of 55.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate consumption provides little if any health benefits for
young people. In addition, the section on the relationship between
alcohol and cancer has been changed to specifically include breast
cancer. A recent analysis shows an increased risk of breast cancer
with alcohol consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, Dr. Nestle said: ``Some of the changes are for the
better; some are not, because the Department of Agriculture has two
roles: to promote the consumption of all American agriculture,
regardless of nutritional value, and promulgate dietary guidelines.
If the guidelines should suggest eating less of something the
department is in conflict.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5054 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      01-24 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRONX SHOOTING DIVIDES A NEIGHBORHOOD ONCE RIVEN BY CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MELISSA GRACE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some residents of the Bronx neighborhood in which
Amadou Diallo died in a hail of police bullets say the shooting
would not have happened if beat police _ rather than the four
members of the city's elite Street Crime Unit _ had been the ones
who encountered the 22-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo, who lived and died in the Soundview area of the Bronx,
was hit by 19 bullets early in the morning of Feb. 4, 1999, in the
vestibule of the two-story apartment building in which he lived.
</P>
<P>
   The officers who shot Diallo _ Kenneth Boss, 28, Sean Carroll,
36, Edward McMellon, 27, and Richard Murphy, 27 _ said they
believed he was armed and dangerous. Police reports after the
shooting said no weapon was found and that Diallo had no criminal
record. The four plainclothes officers from the Street Crime Unit
reportedly were looking for a serial rapist.
</P>
<P>
   The officers have said through their lawyers that Diallo, a
West-African immigrant, was behaving suspiciously and that the
shooting was justified.
</P>
<P>
   Some storekeepers and neighborhood residents said they don't
agree.
</P>
<P>
   A man who said he lives in the apartment building where Diallo
resided, at 1157 Wheeler Ave., was putting out his trash the
morning of Jan. 17. When asked by a reporter if he had seen or
heard the shooting, he said: ``I just heard the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the killing, he said ``It's not right.'' The man, who said he
had been interviewed by the police about the shooting, declined to
give his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an outside unit of police,'' said Phyllis Clarke, owner
of a nearby bakery. ``I don't think it would have happened if it
was the local police; they know the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Baez, who works in a religious artifacts store near the
corner of Wheeler Avenue, agreed. She said shootings were not
normal for the police out of the 43rd Precinct, the local station.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something new,'' said the 45-year-old shopkeeper.
``I've never seen that here. The cops don't harass people, not
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials challenge the assertion that the four officers
were to blame for the shooting. They said that undercover officers,
whose mission is to clean up street crime in progress, are crucial
to fighting crime and often are required to react to dangerous
situations in a split second. They also cite statistics showing a
sharp drop in crime on New York City streets to justify the
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo lived at 1157 Wheeler Ave., a red-brick building on a
quiet, windswept street in the Soundview section of the Bronx.
Around the corner from his former home is a busy thoroughfare,
Westchester Avenue. With an elevated subway track there, Diallo had
a direct route to East 14th Street in Manhattan, were he sold
videos and other street wares.
</P>
<P>
   The vestibule of his home, where he was struck by 19 of 41
bullets fired at him, is about 5 feet by 7 feet. Five concrete
steps lead up from the sidewalk. Written on the walls in indelible
black ink in the entryway are a dozen or so inscriptions to Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   They say: ``Please persecute the murderers'' and ``Rest in peace
Amadou.''
</P>
<P>
   Another says, ``May Allah bless you. You have my condolences
family of Amadou Diallo. It was called for Lord Mustapha Allah,
Allah `U' Akbar will take care of it.'' Diallo, who emigrated from
Guinea, was a devout Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Still another inscription says, ``It isn't good to stay in a
white racist country too long. It's costing us our sons. ... It's
costing us our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year after the shooting, the vestibule of the building
remains pockmarked by bullet holes. Also written in indelible black
ink are police investigator markings logging the number and
location of the holes.
</P>
<P>
   Running up the edge of the outside door of the building, between
the middle and lower door hinges, are four bullet holes. They are
marked ``BH1,'' ``BH2,'' ``BH3'' and ``BH4.'' There are numerous
similar markings inside the door.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, who owns and operates a Jamaican and West Indian bakery
called Manor House around the corner from where Diallo lived, has
been in this country 18 years. She said the neighborhood is an
immigrant destination, with arrivals primarily from Puerto Rico,
the Dominican Republic, Trinidad, Barbados and the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   Another storekeeper said there also has been a large influx of
immigrants from West Africa _ including Senegal and Nigeria _ as
well as such East African nations as Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Yoseph Morales, 75, owns the store where Baez works at
Westchester and Wheeler avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Morales came from Puerto Rico to the United States in the 1940s
and has owned his store for 26 years. He said that when he first
arrived, the neighborhood was mostly Italian and Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a crime-ridden neighborhood. Not anymore,''
Morales said. ``The Police Department cleaned them up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a haven for drugs in the 1960s, 1970s and 1980s, he said.
In the past five years, the police ``cleaned house,'' Morales said,
and now the neighborhood is livable.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, he didn't agree with police tactics used in the
Diallo case and said that if four men approached him at his
doorstep at midnight and he wasn't sure they were police, he would
have run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who they are,'' he said. ``If they came wearing
clothes like that, I'd think it was a holdup or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The four officers were in street clothes and driving an unmarked
car. The shooting sparked widespread outrage throughout the city
because of the number of shots fired and because the officers are
white and Diallo was black. Critics of the department's tactics
claim the police target minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a state appeals court voted to move the trial of the
four officers _ on murder and reckless endangerment charges _ from
the Bronx to Albany for a trial starting Jan. 31. The court held
that extensive media coverage of the case had made it impossible to
pick a fair jury anywhere in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The move concerned some people in the city and the Bronx, who
said the move stripped them of their right to sit in judgment of
police tactics in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   One Soundview resident, who identified himself only as Robert
and as a recent immigrant from the Caribbean, said, ``It happened
in the Bronx, it (the trial) should be in the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Street Crime Unit was greatly expanded _ from about 100
officers to about 400 officers _ some three years ago. That,
critics say, permitted officers with less experience to join. Each
of the officers charged with murder in Diallo's death had been a
police officer since the early 1990s. Only Carroll had been
assigned to the Street Crime Unit for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the officers _ Carroll, McMellon and Boss _ had been
involved in prior shootings, according to a Police Department
spokesman. That is unusual for a department in which more than 90
percent of officers reportedly never fire their weapons in the line
of duty. In those previous incidents, all three officers were found
to have acted properly. In Boss' case, he killed a man reportedly
armed with a shotgun in Brooklyn on Oct. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials deny that unqualified officers are brought into
the unit and say their law enforcement tactics do not target any
population in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Further, they point to dramatic successes in lowering the crime
rate in recent years. Since 1990, when the city's murder total was
2,245 _ an all-time high _ the rate has plummeted. In 1998, 629
people were murdered in New York City, the lowest number since the
early 1960s. Last year it climbed slightly to 667, according to Lt.
Stephen Biegel, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In response to criticisms, Biegel said the Street Crime Unit
officers ``are doing dangerous work, and people are going to look
at them differently.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``There are plenty of people who are grateful that
they can let their kids play on the street where they couldn't a
while back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
