<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-7     01-24 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-730&AMP;ADD-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTS OF WAGING CHECHEN WAR HAVE EXCEEDED RUSSIAN ESTIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Acknowledging that the Kremlin had
underestimated the cost of defeating secessionist rebels in
Chechnya, a senior Russian official said Monday that Russia had
spent 50 percent more on the war in Chechnya last year than
initially planned.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring economic, military and human costs reflect the
intensity of the fighting in the breakaway republic and the
inability of the Russian forces to bring the conflict to an early
close.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's finance minister, Mikhail Kasyanov, who is also first
deputy prime minister, disclosed the cost increase in Moscow
Monday. He said the government had budgeted 3.5 billion rubles
($125 million) for the military campaign of the past several months
but had spent 5 billion rubles ($178 million).
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov did not address future costs. But with the rebels
putting up determined resistance, the expenses are likely to be
high. The Russian military has yet to take Grozny, and thousands of
militants are also challenging Russian troops in the Chechen
highlands.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of carrying out the military campaign is just part of
the expense Russia faces. Even if the Russians subdue Chechnya,
they plan to station an army division and a brigade of interior
troops indefinitely in the breakaway republic to fend off guerrilla
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov's figures also did not include the money that Russian
officials say will be required to rebuild the republic when the war
ends. The cost of rebuilding Grozny alone, which is being battered
daily by Russian artillery and air strikes, will exceed $1 billion,
according to Nikolai Koshman, the Russian government's senior
representative in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The war's increasing price tag is likely to sharpen the Western
debate over providing credits and other forms of economic
assistance to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The West provided billions of dollars in credits to Russia
during the 1994-1996 war in Chechnya. Western governments insisted
that the assistance was needed to encourage economic reform, but
critics complained that the West indirectly subsidized a brutal
war.
</P>
<P>
   After Russia's 1998 financial collapse, Western aid was greatly
reduced and with it the West's economic and political leverage.
Still, critics have urged that Western assistance be suspended and
some form of economic sanctions imposed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Financing is only one of the Kremlin's worries. In Moscow,
Russia's media has begun to aggressively challenge the military's
claim that it is experiencing only minimal casualties, making the
question of Russian losses a centerpiece in an emerging public
debate over the war.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Interfax news agency said that 30 Russian
servicemen had been killed and 70 wounded during the weekend. In
contrast, the official statistics put the toll at 7 dead and 51
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Interfax reported that since fighting erupted in Dagestan in
August 1,152 military servicemen and Interior Ministry troops have
been killed and 2432 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures are roughly consistent with independent estimates,
including an analysis prepared by a former Defense Ministry press
secretary and published in the newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda. That
estimate put the number of soldiers killed at around 1,300 _
roughly twice the official figures.
</P>
<P>
   The rising casualty toll has already lead to one shake-up in the
Interior Ministry command and has stimulated rumors of more to
come.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has troubles on the diplomatic front as
well. The Council of Europe is debating Russia's Chechen campaign
this week amid accusations that civilians have been needlessly
killed and wounded by indiscriminate artillery barrages and air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Lord David Russell-Johnston, the president of the council's
parliamentary delegation, recently visited Chechnya and the North
Caucasus region in a tour that was carefully arranged by the
Russians to avoid combat areas and show off their efforts to
rebuild Chechnya. To the consternation of the Russians, he later
talked by telephone with Aslan Maskhadov, the president of the
breakaway Chechen republic.
</P>
<P>
   Several council delegates suggested that Russia's membership in
the organization be suspended because of its attacks on areas where
civilians reside. A decision on Russia's membership is expected on
Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russian officials have bluntly rejected Western complaints, but
Russia sees its membership in the body as an important symbol of
its acceptance by the West. Monday night, Russia's major television
channels carried extensive reports on the upcoming meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the importance of the issue, Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov plans to attend a council session this week.
Vladimir Zhirinovsky, the nationalist lawmaker who serves as deputy
speaker of the lower house of parliament, is already at the
session. So is Sergei Kovalyov, a human rights advocate who is a
fierce critic of the war in Chechnya and who also opposes Russia's
expulsion from the council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
