<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-VERMEIL-COX     01-24 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-VERMEIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vermeil turns burn-out into a shining season
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What greeted Dick Vermeil on his first day of training
camp was the sun, most prominent. It dominated the sky over Macomb,
Ill., and sent rays onto the practice field as if they were shot
out of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The girls at the refreshment stand could not sell enough water.
The fans who dared tolerate the sweltering conditions hid under
umbrellas. And yet, Vermeil, then age 61, patrolled the field,
shouting instructions and encouragement, as if it were a mild fall
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   That's what stood out with that nondescript Rams team in an
obscure town in middle America in 1997: The senior citizen coach
showed he could stand the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got hot around here sometimes,'' second-year tight end
Roland Williams said. ``Real hot, and I'm not talking weather. We
weren't winning. But coach stayed with it. He didn't stop working.
He took the criticism and kept on working.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the sun is shining on the St. Louis Rams again. Dick
Vermeil's team weathered the tumult, eclipsed the ambitions, and is
in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say about our coach?'' linebacker London Fletcher
asked. ``We've got a great leader, someone who believed in us and
made sure we believed in ourselves. Being in the Super Bowl is
great for the organization, but it's also great for coach Vermeil.
He's earned it. He's the light.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so sunny in St. Louis. After considerable
prodding, Vermeil admits to having gone through a
``What-in-the-name-of-a-beer-and-remote-control am I doing coaching
again?'' period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I thought if I had to do it over again .
. . ,'' Vermeil said. ``I felt this (year) was my last shot. This
is a business of winning games, selling tickets. When it isn't
going well, you know something's going to happen. It's got to. I
know that. If that had bothered me, I wouldn't have come back to
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm glad I didn't (quit). I felt that if I stayed tough,
hung with it, we'd get this thing turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil did more than that: he turned the franchise upside down.
He brought in eight new starters on offense from his first year and
eight on defense. He hired a new kicker and a new punter and a new
offensive coordinator. And through the first two years, of nine
victories in 32 games, Vermeil noticed growth not detectable by the
naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent wasn't as good as it was supposed to be when I got
here,'' he said. ``But we worked at it and worked at it. And then I
started noticing a lot of little things. In rebuilding, a lot of
times, fans and ownership can't notice the small wins within a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose eight straight, and all I talk about is winning,'' he
said. ``I told the team: `I can't tell you when, but it will turn
around.' It starts with the small wins, and then, all of a sudden,
those small wins turn into an explosion _ and you have a winning
team.''
</P>
<P>
   A Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rallied around each other,'' offensive lineman Fred Miller
said. ``We ate together, hung out together, grew together.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, all of that took place this season. In his first two
years back, Vermeil seemed to revert to the ``burn out''
characteristics that prompted his resignation from Philadelphia
Eagles in 1983. He did not spend nights at the office as he did
back then, but Vermeil became too hands-on and ultra-demanding.
</P>
<P>
   His attempt last year at calling offensive plays was a failure;
he was too slow getting them in. He worked the team so hard that
there was a near-mutiny at the end of last season, when the players
threatened a walkout. Defensive tackle Joe Phillips halted the
uprising, but several players did not show for a season-ending
meeting that Vermeil had called.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the Lawrence Philips philanthropy case was a
disaster. Former quarterback Tony Banks was coddled by Vermeil and
once brought his dog to practice. On the field, the Rams were an
accident. And there was no ``light at the end of the tunnel,''
receiver Ricky Proehl said.
</P>
<P>
   Management demanded that Vermeil right things _ fast. He had to
change or leave. Vermeil, who was driven to prove that he could
transform the Rams, made the personal transformation that changed
the team.
</P>
<P>
   He hired as offensive coordinator Mike Martz, a new-wave guru
who designed a St. Louis attack built on speed and aggressiveness.
So successful has Martz been in one season that last week he was
named Vermeil's heir.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil trusted his strong staff of assistants and worked as an
overseer instead of a control freak. He loosened the reins on the
team and promoted an atmosphere of peace and harmony. Of family. He
became Mr. Sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays the background a little more than in the first two
years,'' All-Pro receiver Isaac Bruce said. ``I really don't see
him with my natural eye that much, but I'm sure his input is there.
He kind of stands back and patrols things, like a coach should.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as intense or demanding or emotional,'' Vermeil said.
``I'm still too much of all that. But I'm better at delegating and
better at leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   He has shown that he has become keen at assessing talent, too,
based on the roster moves made by him and Charley Armey, the team's
vice president of player personnel. He got lucky with quarterback
Kurt Warner; no one could have anticipated that he would become the
NFL's most valuable player. But it took discerning judgment to pick
up former Green Bay offensive tackle Alan Timmerman; to hand the
middle linebacker job to a former Division III basketball star,
London Fletcher; and to draft receivers Torry Holt and Az-Zahir
Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things I believe in,'' Vermeil said. ``One is
that players win games. In 1961, I was 24 years old coaching at
Hillsdale High (in San Mateo, Calif.). We won a lot, and I thought
I was a genius. The next year, I lost my quarterback, running back
and my offensive tackle went to Stanford. We won four games. I
realized then that players win games.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing Vermeil said he stands by is assembling the best
possible coaching staff. And using it, as well. ``I owe it to the
players to have the best possible teachers to get out their talent
and push them a little more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although still old school, Vermeil showed that he has caught up
with the times. In the NFL, speed wins, and the Rams have the
fastest offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that it's a game of movement,'' he said. ``And the
better you move, the better you are.''
</P>
<P>
   For a movie version of Dick Vermeil's life, the start would have
to have range and ample gray. And he would have to be able to cry
on cue, for Vermeil has gotten more emotional with age.
</P>
<P>
   In his three years in St. Louis, Vermeil has given his
hankerchief plenty of work. On Sunday, he held back tears as he
talked about Proehl, who caught the game-winning touchdown against
Tampa Bay in the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, he might be a little mushy and quick to force sunlight on
a dicey situation. But when the results are the Super Bowl, who can
argue? Not Vermeil. He took on the challenge after 14 years as a
football television analyst because the bug bit him and he wanted
to prove something to himself.
</P>
<P>
   He has done that, but now he wants more. ``We're not finished
yet,'' Vermeil said. ``We haven't accomplished our ultimate goal.
We set out to win the Super Bowl. And that hasn't been done yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to prove something. I got that off my chest. I can
handle it, keep the game in perspective, provide leadership, handle
the highs and lows. At my age, I want to walk away knowing I can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil can take that walk now. Whatever happens Sunday
against the Tennessee Titans, he has proved his point. At 63, Dick
Vermeil can stand the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
