<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-CONGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN LEADERS URGE CONGO PEACEKEEPING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAURIA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ African leaders embroiled in a regional war in
Congo Monday called on the United Nations to immediately send
peacekeepers to the country despite objections by the United
States, which first wants to see concrete signs that a peace
agreement is holding.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of six African countries on both sides of the conflict
agreed in a special summit at the United Nations that only a quick
deployment of UN troops can end the war that has cost thousands of
lives and made more than a million people refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, who chaired the
meeting, said: ``Because of (Congo's) location and size, and
because of the number of countries involved, the conflict there
could be described as Africa's first world war. The continent
cannot hope to meet the aspirations of its people until this war is
history.''
</P>
<P>
   But Albright said the warring parties must, during week-long
talks at the United Nations, ``detail in a credible fashion their
plans for meeting the commitments they have made'' in the
cease-fire they signed last July in Lusaka, Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   Until that happened the United States could not support
deploying a force of 3.500 peacekeepers, proposed by UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Provided our efforts this week result in renewed impetus
towards implementation of the peace agreement, we will consult with
our Congress and work to achieve a swift council consensus on
authorizing deployment of a . . . UN peace mission,'' Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
   The civil war in Congo stems from the 1994 massacre of 800,000
people in Rwanda and the 1997 overthrow of Zaire's dictator for 32
years, Mobuto Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
   Mobuto was toppled with the support of Rwanda, Burundi, and
Uganda and replaced by President Laurent Kabila, who changed the
country's name from Zaire to Democratic Repoublic of Congo. Kabila
soon broke this alliance and backed a force of 40,000 Hutu militias
who had fled into Congolese territory following their genocidal
attacks against Tutsi in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda, Burundi, and Uganda in August 1998 then supported rebels
in the eastern part of the country seeking to overthrow Kabila, who
has received air support and 10,000 troops from Zimbabwe, Namibia,
and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   The six outside countries, plus the Congo government and various
rebel factions on both sides, have violated the cease-fire since
signing the Lusaka accord.
</P>
<P>
   That deal calls for the withdrawal of foreign forces, the
disarmament and demobilization of the rebel groups into a single
Congolese army, the establishment of a joint military committee,
and the eventual introduction of UN troops, which may be authorized
to use force to achieve these ends.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States wants these violations to end before
sending UN forces. Richard Holbrooke, US ambassador to the UN, who
organized the summit, has cited UN failures in Rwanda and Somalia
in recent years as reasons for America's caution. Persuading a
Congress hostile to UN missions to release funds is another reason,
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Though all pledged to uphold the Lusaka accord, an immediate end
to continued fighting appeared far off Monday as the leaders of the
warring countries, meeting face to face in the Security Council,
lost no opportunity to hurl accusations at one another.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila said the cease-fire would fail until ``an immediate and
unconditional withdrawal of the uninvited aggressor forces.'' These
should be replaced ``systematically by the deployment of UN
troops,'' Kabila said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Congolese people and government expect that at this
special session (the Security Council) will be able to halt the
occupation of part of out national territory by the occupying
forces of Rwanda, Uganda, and Burundi,'' Kabila said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, an angry Yoweri Museveni, president of Uganda,
asserted: ``It is a red herring to talk about the territorial
integrity of Congo. That is not the issue. The issue is that in the
last century only Hitler's Germany and Pol Pot's Cambodia have
competed with our area'' for the worst genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1960, 1.2 million Rwandese, 400,000 Burundians, and
800,000 Ugandans ``have been exterminated by the fascist regimes of
Rwanda and Burundi, by Idi Amin, the monster of Uganda, and by
Mobutu,'' Museveni said.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila had forgotten that Uganda, Rwanda, and Burundi had
supported him to overthrow Mobutu, who ``was threatening another
holocaust in our area.'' Instead Kabila had joined forces with Hutu
militia responsible for mass murder in Rwanda, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's call for the withdrawal of ``aggressor troops'' before
a cease-fire could take hold was firmly met by Albright, who said
``the international community, including the United States, can and
does condemn the violation of the Congo's territorial integrity by
foreign troops, but we cannot compel the withdrawal of those
troops. Nor can we conduct an internal dialogue. But we can help to
make your responsibilities easier to fulfill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
