<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-RYLANDER-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      01-24 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYLANDER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COMPTROLLER MAY HAVE THE METTLE TO MOVE UP LADDER OF
STATEWIDE OFFICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Barely a year on the job, Comptroller Carole
Keeton Rylander is once again mentioned as a potential candidate
for higher office, this time the lieutenant governorship.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that the comptroller's post has served as a
springboard for predecessors, including the late Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock. But while the 60-year-old Republican does little to
discourage the speculation, she claims she's having the time of her
life as the state's chief tax collector, gathering up $20 billion a
year in levies from consumers, businesses and industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the best comptroller this state has ever had, and
let me tell you, it's had some great comptrollers,'' Rylander said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   The job, paying $92,217 a year, is not everyone's idea of fun
and definitely produces enemies along with friends. While raking in
$1 million in campaign contributions, Rylander has shut down scores
of tax-delinquent businesses _ some permanently.
</P>
<P>
   With TV cameras rolling, she brazenly seized cash registers at
Austin's legendary Antone's nightclub as a show was about to begin.
In Dallas and Houston, she strictly enforced tax laws at gun shows.
In Waxahachie, she locked up the assets of a Republic of Texas
activist, who she claimed was a tax dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Her staff of 2,800 workers, with an annual budget of $175
million, also keeps an eye on the state's $49 billion annual
spending. She kept the Legislature in suspense for weeks while she
and her in-house experts calculated how much surplus revenue they
would have _ enough, it turned out, for a teacher pay raise and
some tax cuts. And at the urgent behest of Gov. George W. Bush, her
team led the Texas Funeral Services Commission out of regulatory
chaos last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, her staff is conducting 20 school district audits
that could expose management flaws, induce improvements, and
produce friends and foes in the political grass roots.
</P>
<P>
   While Rylander doesn't shy from the spotlight, Deputy
Comptroller Billy Hamilton, who served under Bullock and successor
John Sharp, is the agency's chief off-stage economics wizard.
Hamilton, some observers say, provides invaluable expertise and
consistent policies at a politically charged agency that never
knows from where the next incoming missile will be launched. Just
this month, it was literally from across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander annoyed another GOP official _ Land Commissioner David
Dewhurst _ by prodding him to disclose out-of-state purchases that
might be subject to the sales and use tax. The unfinished flap, in
which Dewhurst raised the question of unfair and selective
enforcement of an obscure levy, touched off the latest round of
conjecture that Rylander, along with Dewhurst, were angling for
higher office, possibly the same one.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Rylander circumvented the hypotheticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's anything I've enjoyed more than
this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her resume includes stints as a high school teacher, school
board and city council member, Austin mayor, state insurance board
appointee, campaigner for Clayton Williams and Texas Railroad
Commission chairman _ usually the first woman in the elected roles.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, she lost bitter contests for Congress and the
railroad commission. And as early as 1985, when she bolted the
Democratic Party to unsuccessfully challenge a longtime ally,
former U.S. Rep. J.J. ``Jake'' Pickle, D-Austin, her office-hopping
tendency drew brickbats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to understand,'' Pickle said at the time. ``Most
people see it as an act of opportunism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rylander talks only about her current mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love what I'm doing. Being comptroller, there isn't a facet
of the state you don't touch. The whole reason I do anything is to
try to make a difference. I think you can really make a difference
in this office,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond trimming her staff by about 130 workers, Rylander said
she has fulfilled all major campaign promises. Her pledges included
treating taxpayers, even deadbeats, more fairly, and allowing more
businesses to self-audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to harass the good guys. I want to spend my
resources and time going after the tax cheat, which is exactly what
I've done,'' Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   Lately she's been touting ``e-Texas,'' her initiative to gather
ideas on improving resident interaction with government, such as
using the Internet to tap state services, comply with regulations,
pay taxes or obtain driver's licenses. Late this year, an advisory
body will prepare suggestions for lawmakers who convene in 2001,
but Rylander already calls the effort ``really the cornerstone of
my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Some agencies didn't immediately embrace Rylander's effort. This
month, Texas Public Safety Commission Chairman James B. Francis Jr.
instructed staff members to guard against the commandeering of the
agency's powers by e-Texas operatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let them usurp any of your authority. If there's an
attempt to usurp anything other than PR (public relations), let the
commission know,'' Francis told staff members. ``The bottom line
is, you are in charge of driver's licenses. She is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Francis said that Rylander is a ``fine comptroller'' who
is ``doing a great job.'' Nonetheless, he said zealous aides were
``grandstanding'' and ``overstepping their bounds'' while
advocating online driver's license issuance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a program we have been moving forward on and we will
continue to move forward on. This is our statutory authority. This
is not the comptroller's business, and we will continue to do our
job,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said she hasn't encountered resistance to e-Texas,
which will formulate suggestions in public despite initial plans to
keep some deliberations private.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis that Rylander places on ``e-Texas'' also feeds
speculation that she has another office in mind. The scenarios
hinge on Bush ascending to the presidency and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry
moving into the Governor's Mansion, vacating his post as presiding
officer of the Texas Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Political consultant Bill Miller said Rylander may have the
mettle to move up the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's innovative. She thinks outside the box. She does her own
thing,'' Miller said, adding he doubts she would seek the next U.S.
Senate seat that becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her future is based in Texas, in statewide office,'' he
contends. ``She'll make her move on something _ there's no
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairman Molly Beth Malcolm, who
criticized Rylander's brief tenure as comptroller, said it wouldn't
be out of character for Rylander to seek another office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her commitment seems to be to her own advancement rather than
to the good of the people. She has a history of moving from one job
to another before she completes what she's been elected to do,''
Malcolm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has not done a good job as comptroller,'' Malcolm added.
``She totally dismantled the most successful program that was put
in by her predecessor John Sharp, the Texas Performance Review, and
she put in this e-commerce thing that nobody knows what it's going
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rylander won't disclose ambitions beyond her current term, which
ends in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe George W. Bush will be the next president. ...
Therefore, Rick Perry will be the next governor. It's exciting
times,'' Rylander said, ``but I don't think that changes the course
any of what's going on in this shop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
