<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TO INTERVIEW CAPERS, DONAHOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dom Capers and Tom Donahoe, the coach/general manager
duo who may have moved from Plan B to Plan A on the Patriots'
priority list, will interview in New England Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Capers, the Jacksonville Jaguars' defensive coordinator, is
expected to spend much of the afternoon with Robert and Jonathan
Kraft and Andy Wasynczuk. Donahoe will interview in the morning,
but it appears that the two will be interviewed together, as well,
at some point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm very excited and flattered about interviewing in
New England with Mr. Kraft,'' said Capers from Jacksonville, where
the Jaguars were eliminated from the playoffs Sunday by the
Tennessee Titans. ``Being a head coach in the NFL is every coach's
dream and goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may be leaning more toward Capers and Donahoe as
the Bill Belichick situation gets more complicated. Belichick's
attorney, Jeffrey Kessler, filed an antitrust lawsuit against the
NFL in federal court in Newark Monday and also asked for a
temporary restraining order that would allow other NFL teams to
interview Belichick. A judge will make a ruling on the latter this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league has failed on matters of antitrust laws,'' said
Kessler. ``This will prevent the NFL from directing teams not to
talk to Bill Belichick for employment opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Capers spoke well of Donahoe, with whom he worked in Pittsburgh
for three seasons (1992-94); Donahoe was director of football
operations and Capers was defensive coordinator. But Capers
downplayed the suggestion that he and Donahoe would be hired as a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's just speculation,'' said Capers. ``I worked
with Tom and we have a strong working relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Capers left Pittsburgh in 1995 to become head coach at Carolina,
where he went 31-35 in four seasons, leading the Panthers to the
playoffs the second year. He dropped to 4-12 in '98, a season in
which the Panthers had huge problems with quarterback Kerry
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Capers is scheduled to interview Wednesday for the head job in
New Orleans, another place where Donahoe has been mentioned. The
Saints also are considering promoting Charlie Bailey, a personnel
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots and Jets have not discussed Belichick since having
a brief conversation on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On New York radio station WFAN's ``Mike and the Mad Dog'' show
Monday, Bill Parcells said the Belichick issue was not under his
jurisdiction. When asked by cohost Chris Russo whether he would
feel comfortable negotiating a settlement with Kraft, Parcells
said, ``That situation may be going to court. It's not up to us to
work out a deal with them, it's up to them to work out a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets reportedly are seeking a first- and a fourth-round
draft pick for Belichick. The Patriots aren't willing to give up
the first-rounder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
