<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-ENGLAND-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON GETS THE ROYAL TREATMENT IN LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Mike Tyson gathered about a dozen boys and girls to sit
ringside at his workout at the Grosvenor House Hotel on Monday
afternoon. Sitting on the floor with their little heads tilted up
at the ring, the children looked like they were about to hear a
bedtime story.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they saw Tyson try to turn the lights out on a sparring
partner, Leroy Seales. Near the end of the third round, Tyson
ripped a left hook into Seales' ribs and another left to the side
of his head and Seales dropped to one knee.
</P>
<P>
   A grim fairy tale, indeed. The workout was over. Julius Francis,
whom Tyson will fight Saturday at the MEN Arena in Manchester,
England, could be in for a short night.
</P>
<P>
   After the workout the children mugged for the cameras with
Tyson. One little boy wearing a pair of white boxing gloves tried
to take Tyson's head off with a right uppercut, and the former
heavyweight champion lit up with glee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids don't know any difference when you say Mike Tyson was
convicted of rape or got in a fight with a tourist,'' Tyson said.
``They just want a famous guy to show them love and respect and
make them feel like somebody. I was once snubbed by a famous boxer.
It had such a bad effect me. It lasted for so many years. I don't
want to be the cause of someone feeling like that. You feel like
you're dirt. He talked to everybody else but you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's emotions were close to the surface Monday. He was asked
what his favorite tourist attraction in London had been. He said he
had enjoyed Big Ben and Madame Toussaud's Wax Museum, although he
is not a wax figure there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe in the chamber of horrors,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   That dredged up another humiliating experience, which caused
Tyson's mood to shift sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I were in Hollywood and we went into a wax
museum,'' he said. ``We went into the chamber of horrors and there
was a wax dummy of me in a cage. It devastated my wife. They
humiliated and degraded me in front of my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I've been humiliating me,'' Tyson said, choking
back tears as his anger rose. ``You think I don't hate everybody?
You don't think I don't have pain?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, told to take a hike by the Nevada State Athletic
Commission and snubbed by the boxing establishment in New York, has
come to England for the love he feels he cannot get in America.
Despite the fact that some politicians here worked to have Tyson
barred from England because of his 1992 rape conviction in Indiana,
and women's groups protested his presence once he arrived, Tyson
has chosen to ignore them and embrace the fans who embrace him.
</P>
<P>
   He has been given royal treatment. Throngs of fans camp outside
the hotel day and night hoping to get a glimpse of him as he goes
out to run or shop. The newspapers have made him front page news
everyday, covering his every move, often skewering him for
transgressions (past, present, real and imaginary).
</P>
<P>
   His early morning runs in nearby Hyde Park have created a stir,
because no one is supposed to be in the park after midnight. Tyson
was running at 3 a.m. He went to pray at a London mosque and a
near-riot broke out at the door when photographers tried to storm
the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   He walked through the streets of Brixton, a racially mixed
section of London, and a crowd of close to 5,000 people crushed
forward to touch him. He had to seek shelter in a police station.
He escaped by sending a decoy car in one direction and then heading
off in another direction.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Tyson's camp has ever seen anything like it. Shelly
Finkel, his manager and a former rock concert promoter, said he had
hired security personnel who worked for Michael Jackson when he
toured England and they said the crowds around Tyson were greater
than for Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Michael was on the same plane that we came in on,''
Finkel said, referring to the pop star. ``He walked off the plane
and nobody cared.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedgemon Lewis, a veteran trainer who is working with Tyson, was
in the Philippines with Joe Frazier for his fight against Muhammad
Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this, with all the people just
trying to touch the guy,'' Lewis said. ``Even with Joe and Ali in
the Thrilla in Manilla it wasn't even like this. It was close, but
nothing like this.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tyson, who has visited England, but has never fought here,
cannot explain exactly why he is so popular here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an ego stroker,'' Tyson said. ``But I know boxing
history from the beginning until now and until I die. There's never
been a fighter like me as far as drawing the people and worldwide
recognition. But no one wants to tell the American public that,
because they're afraid that people might say what you're doing to
Mike is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you falsely accuse him of rape it is wrong and having
people worldwide think I'm a horrible person when they never read
my manuscript is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I get a fair shake anywhere. The world
basically hates me and just the common people understand my plight.
I fight the same fight they fight. They get persecuted everyday for
being who they are. Not necessarily for being black, but just being
a poor white guy, or a poor Irish guy in Belfast where English
soldiers come and brutalize you at will, because they have the
right to do so and no one can stop them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
