<HEADLINE>
`BUNNS NIGHT' A SCOTTISH RITUAL, COLD OR NO COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's a brave man who wears a kilt on a cold January
day, but doing so is de rigueur this time of year if you're
Scottish, or just want to pretend to be for a night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday is Burns Night. Or, as it sounds when the Scottish say
it, ``Bunns Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Burns, who wrote the words to Auld Lang Syne, remains
Scotland's most famous poet, 241 years after he was born on Jan.
25, 1759, in a small thatched cottage in Alloway.
</P>
<P>
   Burns Night is for Scots around the world what St. Patrick's Day
is for the Irish, a celebration of Scottish identity and culture.
Scotland has a population of just 5 million, but there are about 25
million in the Scottish diaspora, which explains the adage, ``A
Scotsman is never at home but when he's abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Scots living in London often complain about the invisibility
here of things Scottish, saying Scotland too often makes the news
only when something terrible or controversial happens there. Some
say they had never felt more Scottish than when they lived among
the English.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Winfield is a case in point. Born in Scotland, she left
as a child and grew up in South Africa. She married an Englishman,
has three young children, and spent much of the last decade living
in Manhattan before moving to London recently. Living abroad, she
soaked up African and American culture but did little to celebrate
her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, but I'm Scottish now,'' she said, during The Burns Club of
London's annual Burns Night dinner Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove the point, she dug into a plate of haggis,
Scotland's national dish made from what George MacPherson, a Burns
Club official, described cryptically as ``a sheep's offal.'' A
later reading of the Oxford Dictionary revealed that haggis is a
sheep's lungs, heart, and liver mixed with oatmeal and boiled in
the animal's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone could eat the haggis, however, MacPherson had to
stab it with a wee dagger called a dirk. That was after he talked
to it, reciting Burns's ``Address to a Haggis,'' which is
essentially a poem about the virtues of sheep and the people who
eat them. All this is part an elaborate, high-spirited ceremony,
celebrating a heritage many Scots are determined to keep alive,
especially as European integration melts borders and modernization
melds cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kennedy, the Scottish-born leader of the Liberal
Democrats, Britain's third-largest party, said it is popular around
this time of year for politicians, especially those seeking
Scottish votes, to exploit Burns, saying he would have been a
member of their party if he had not died of a heart attack in 1796
at the age of 37.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who was keynote speaker at Saturday night's dinner at
the Hotel Russell in central London, said Britain's two big parties
make something of a stretch to try to claim Burns. One of Burns's
love poems paid homage to ``Maggie'' two centuries before Margaret
Thatcher became a Conservative icon. Burns's most quoted line of
verse, ``My love is like a red, red rose,'' refers to the Labor
Party's symbol.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy, the only Scotsman to lead a major British party,
insists Burns would in fact have been a Liberal Democrat ``because
he means all things to all people,'' something the party's
detractors accuse it of trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the 100 or so men at the dinner donned Highland
formal wear, with kilts of various tartans and a dagger known as a
``skean dhu'' tucked in their socks. All this to honor a man who
was born to impoverished, illiterate farmers and began tilling the
soil like his father before he decided to become a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poetic genius of my country found me at the plough, and
threw her inspiring mantle over me,'' Burns wrote. ``She bade me
sing the loves, the joys, the rural scenes and rural pleasures of
my native soil, in my native tongue I turned my wild artless notes
as she inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's the English translation. In his native tongue,
Lallans, the Scottish lowlands dialect, his admiration for
introspection was expressed as: ``O wad some Pow'r the giftie gie
us, to see oursels as ithers see us.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is a celebration of Scottish literature, food, drink,
and music, Burns Night is not exclusionary. On Saturday night,
there were two tables of Americans, some Nigerians in their native
dress, and assorted Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans invariably messed up the dances, going left when
they should have gone right, and vice versa. But the Scots were
unfailingly patient.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, a Burns Night leaves one with three
inescapable conclusions: Scotch is something best consumed in
moderation, bagpipes are meant to be played outdoors, and the Scots
know how to throw a party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
