<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-TV-STARS-BROADWAY-ART     01-24 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STARS-BROADWAY-ART-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV STARS ARE BROADWAY'S LATEST MARKETING TOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT21 and NYT22 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Susan Lucci of the soap opera ``All My Children''
recently replaced Bernadette Peters in ``Annie Get Your Gun'' for
three weeks. Kathie Lee Gifford of ``Regis and Kathie Lee'' is
going on for Carol Burnett on Tuesday nights through Feb. 15 in
``Putting It Together.'' Robert Urich of ``Spenser: For Hire'' has
just completed a three-month stint in ``Chicago'' and may return
this summer. And on Tuesday night Jack Wagner of ``Melrose Place''
and ``General Hospital'' is stepping into the title roles in
``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Not one of these television stars _ along with numerous others
who preceded them _ had appeared on Broadway before. None had the
classic up-from-the-ranks training that has marked theatrical
careers since the days of Ruby Keeler. None had earned reputations
as distinguished actors on film. Some even had to take vocal
lessons to help them pull off their parts.
</P>
<P>
   But in an age when Broadway, more than ever, has become
dominated by megamusicals and revivals dependent in part on ticket
sales to tourists, this didn't seem to matter. Producers to an ever
greater degree are turning away from Broadway's traditional talent
repositories and toward the ultimate mass-market medium _
television _ to help fill seats and the demanding lead roles that
were previously saved for some of theater's most accomplished
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a consumer product and you're trying to build
market share,'' said Scott Zeiger, the president of SFX Theatrical,
which produced ``Jekyll and Hyde.'' ``A star gives you that
competitive edge.''
</P>
<P>
   While television stars have been trickling into Broadway shows
over the last 20 years, this season and last have been notable for
their sheer number. Last season brought Tony Danza of ``Taxi'' in
``The Iceman Cometh,'' Polly Draper of ``Thirtysomething'' in
``Closer,'' Scott Wolf of ``Party of Five'' in ``Side Man'' (as
well as the film actors Christian Slater and Andrew McCarthy) and
Wayne Knight of ``Seinfeld'' and now ``Third Rock from the Sun'' in
``Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps tellingly, producers do not yet seem confident enough in
these stars to have them originate their Broadway roles. Rather,
the stars are generally brought in as replacements in a rather
brazen attempt to boost ticket sales for a show that is already up
and running.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while movie stars are almost guaranteed to draw crowds
on Broadway, television stars are not necessarily such a sure bet,
some producers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV stars are more transient _ their stardom has a finite
life,'' said Emanuel Azenberg, who produced ``Iceman'' last year
with Kevin Spacey (and made a hefty profit). ``What's the other
woman who was in `Laverne and Shirley'? If you put her on Broadway,
she wouldn't sell a thing. But Lauren Bacall, look, she still packs
'em in.'' (Ms. Bacall is currently appearing in ``Waiting in the
Wings.'')
</P>
<P>
   With years of experience on Broadway _ including a Tony award
for her performance in ``Song and Dance'' and a Tony nomination for
``Sunday in the Park with George'' _ Ms. Peters, who reclaimed the
role of Annie Oakley last week, is widely considered the queen of
Broadway musical theater.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ms. Lucci has spent the last 30 years on the
daytime soap opera ``All My Children'' and, although she gave a
strong audition for ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' had to work intensively
with a vocal coach in preparing to fill Ms. Peters' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gifford is stepping in once a week for Ms. Burnett, who has
had a long career performing on Broadway in productions like ``Once
Upon a Mattress'' (1959) and ``Moon Over Buffalo'' (1995) as well
as displaying her musical theater talent on her long-running
variety show. Ms. Gifford hosts a morning talk show, although she
is a cabaret singer who has performed in cruise-ship commercials
and on her Christmas specials.
</P>
<P>
   Urich played the role of Billy Flynn, which was originated by
James Naughton, who first appeared on Broadway in 1977 and has
since won Tony awards for his performances in ``Chicago'' and
``City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he went to drama school and studied acting with Stella
Adler, Wagner has spent his career on ``General Hospital'' and
``Melrose Place.'' The actors who have played Jekyll and Hyde
before include Robert Cuccioli _ the original _ and Robert Evan,
both of whom paid their dues in regional theater.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some Broadway neophytes have faced lukewarm
receptions. In reviewing Donny Osmond in ``Little Johnny Jones'' in
1983, Frank Rich wrote in The New York Times: ``The young Osmond is
as yet a limited performer whose dancing is more like prancing and
whose expressions range from a mild pout to a broad grin (with few
gradations in between). But he is sincere and does know how to
sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the latest group of imported stars have fared
better. In Newsday, Linda Winer grudgingly commended Ms. Gifford's
Broadway debut. ``Of all the casting stunts in recent Broadway
infamy, the hiring of Kathie Lee Gifford for a Stephen Sondheim
revue would seem to catapult the merely cynical into the legends of
the outright contemptible,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact _ and Howard Stern is going to hate this,'' she
concluded, ``Gifford is professional, conscientious and actually a
little touching.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Broadway newcomers say they have gotten far
more out of the experience than what for them is a comparatively
modest paycheck and publicity. ``I trained like a marathoner for
this,'' Ms. Gifford said. ``I went in like a sponge and said: `Fill
me up. I'm the virgin here.'''
</P>
<P>
   This ``virgin'' experience stands in stark contrast to a time
when the Great White Way seemed to be reserved for the seasoned
masters and symbolized the ultimate prize in legitimate theater: a
reward for years of voice, acting and dance classes, for toiling in
regional playhouses, touring companies and summer stock
productions.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, in his review of Ms. Lucci in The New York Post,
Clive Barnes found her greenness problematic. ``What she lacked,
apart from experience, was much real presence,'' he wrote, ``that
sense of stage charisma that all legendary roles in Broadway
musicals absolutely demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the moment at least,'' Barnes added, ``she shouldn't give
up her day job.''
</P>
<P>
   As more stars infiltrate theater, the call for craft has been
less insistent, some observers say. For one thing, with most actors
using microphones on stage _ to the chagrin of sound purists _ the
art of great vocal projection is no longer essential.
</P>
<P>
   But Broadway producers defend television stars as formidable
talents, fast learners and, in today's market, financial
necessities. ``Having a television star on Broadway is a wonderful
hedge on your bet,'' Zeiger said. It gives you press attention, it
gives you something to market and it helps you cut through all the
other clutter that's out there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Azenberg said Spacey was responsible for
``Iceman's'' profitability. ``He sold the O'Neill out and he saved
us half a million dollars in advertising which we didn't have to
do,'' Azenberg said. ``Stars bring in the people, but also reduce
the costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers also insist they only cast the stars who are up to the
task. ``I think it's great that he's a television star and that
adds whatever it adds,'' Frank Wildhorn, the composer of ``Jekyll &AMP;
Hyde,'' said of Wagner. ``But the reason Jack is coming in is he's
a great singer.''
</P>
<P>
   As far back as 1959, David Merrick presented Jackie Gleason in
``Take Me Along.'' In subsequent years, Broadway has been visited
by stars like Sid Caesar in ``Little Me'' (1962), Gilda Radner in
``The Lunch Hour'' (1980) and David and Shaun Cassidy in ``Blood
Brothers (1983).
</P>
<P>
   Fran and Barry Weissler have made a regular practice of putting
television stars in Broadway shows. Their 1994 revival of
``Grease,'' for example, included everyone from Maureen McCormick
of ``The Brady Bunch'' to Mackenzie Phillips of ``One Day at a
Time'' to Ricky Paull Goldin of ``Another World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used everybody who could walk,'' Ms. Weissler said. ``We
even used the one who threw up the green soup in `The Exorcist' _
Linda Blair.''
</P>
<P>
   And some have come with considerable stage experience, like Tom
Wopat, now in ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' who may be best known for
television's ``The Dukes of Hazzard,'' but who made his Broadway
debut as long ago as 1978 in ``I Love My Wife.'' Also Bebe
Neuwirth, familiar from ``Cheers,'' comes from a solid theater
background and has wowed audiences and critics in ``Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildhorn said television stars have the ability to draw a new
audience that Broadway needs. ``Somebody once told me there are
more people who watch a successful television show over the course
of a season than have ever seen theater in the history of the
world,'' Wildhorn said. ``You're expanding your audience, you're
trying to build a nontraditional audience. And I think that's a
healthy thing to constantly try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically perhaps, it is in large part because of television,
as well as movies, theater veterans say, that Broadway can no
longer compete in producing star power of its own, as it did in the
days when audiences turned out in force to see Ethel Merman, Alfred
Drake or Carol Channing.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, these veterans say, even stage actors who have
repeatedly received critical acclaim, including Audra McDonald,
Kathleen Chalfant, Brian Stokes Mitchell and Cherry Jones, have not
become nationally known. And many of New York theater's most
accomplished progeny _ Nathan Lane, Sam Waterston, Kevin Kline,
Meryl Streep _ have long left Broadway for Hollywood, although they
occasionally return.
</P>
<P>
   Where actors return is often off-Broadway. Last season brought
Calista Flockhart of Ally McBeal and Lisa Gay Hamilton of ``The
Practice'' _ both of whom started in theater.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on Broadway gives stars an aura of seriousness and
legitimacy _ even nobility, in light of the big salaries they are
giving up. Wagner said taking on ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde'' was far from
altruistic. ``I'm doing this completely for me,'' he said. ``You
get a little lazy. I realized I needed something to really pump me
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lucci, who last year finally won an Emmy for her longtime
portrayal of Erica Kane on ``All My Children,'' added: ``I just
love the medium. I loved being on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weissler said both Ms. Lucci and Urich had to audition for
their roles. When Frank Gifford auditioned for the role that went
to Urich, he did not even get a callback. ``He couldn't do it,''
Ms. Weissler said. ``He couldn't sing and he can't act.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weissler said Ms. Lucci gave a strong audition, but needed
vocal training and became a dedicated pupil. ``This is a woman who
really killed herself,'' Ms. Weissler said. ``We knew people would
roll their eyes, but she proved herself to us.''
</P>
<P>
   John McDaniel, the supervising musical director of ``Annie Get
Your Gun'' who is also the band leader for ``The Rosie O'Donnell
Show,'' said: ``I think people were surprised. Audiences stood up
every single show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gifford said she had no problem with the fact that she had
been enlisted as much for her marketing potential as for her
mastery of Sondheim's lyrics. In fact, she said she had recently
written a song about this very reality:
</P>
<P>
   ``You really shouldn't take it so personally.
</P>
<P>
   To them you're not a person, but a personality.
</P>
<P>
   And you SELL.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
