<SLUG> BC-BUSH-A&AMP;M-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
 
A&AMP;M's BUSH SCHOOL GETS OFF TO A ROCKY START 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Next to the Bush Library and Museum, on
land where Texas A&AMP;M University animal researchers bred generations
of pigs, stands the new George Bush School of Government and Public
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing the school was seen as a way to help bolster A&AMP;M's
national image as a player among major institutions of learning, on
top of its agricultural roots, ultraloyal alumni and proud Corp of
Cadets traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says, `The university has arrived,' '' said political
scientist Arnold Vedlitz, who heads the Center for Leadership
within the Bush School, which he also serves as interim assistant
dean.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush School hopes to attain the prestige of such other
presidential schools as Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of
Government and the Lyndon B. Johnson School of Public Affairs at
the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But since its formal dedication in 1997, the school's early
years have been marked with difficult challenges, an unsought
windfall and at least one embarrassing, nearly comical episode.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, and apparently with little or no consultation with
A&AMP;M, the Texas Legislature allocated $2.5 million to the Bush
School in a rider to an appropriations bill last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The windfall worked out to more than $83,000 per student over
two years. But it came with a condition.
</P>
<P>
   The school had to be spun off from A&AMP;M's College of Liberal Arts
and made into a free-standing, degree-granting graduate school with
its own dean.
</P>
<P>
   Then the school's advisory board _ ``handpicked by the Bush
family,'' according to a memo by A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen unearthed
by the Bryan newspaper, The Eagle _ urged the university to replace
the school's founding director, political scientist Charles
Hermann, when the post became a deanship on Sept. 1. Hermann had
been recruited from Ohio State University where he had been
director of the Mershon Center, a respected foreign policy think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Hermann was quite successful getting it started,'' said
Provost Ron Douglas. But the school's advisory committee wanted a
``more prestigious'' dean, ``someone with a greater national
reputation who could recruit a top-flight faculty, attract top
students and raise funds,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   The move unsettled more than a few on the sprawling Southeast
Texas campus.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow Jones Jr., dean of the College of Liberal Arts, which
lost control of the Bush School, complained that the Legislature's
action bypassed the A&AMP;M trustees and president by directly
intervening in campus administration, which he called highly
unusual _ and stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's asinine,'' the plain-speaking Jones said in an interview.
``You wake up one morning and you have a school with 35 students
and $2 million that's suddenly independent _ with no discussion
with the people who worked hard to establish it. It was our worst
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The provost said that the university had planned on a transition
period of several years for it to evolve into a graduate school;
Jones said A&AMP;M had figured on 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   What caused the urgency may never be known.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, chairman of the
Senate Finance Committee, said the rider was added at the personal
request of the late Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bullock was on the advisory committee for the Bush School
and he felt very strongly that it should be unfettered, shouldn't
be under the control of any other school at A&AMP;M,'' Ratliff said.
``I thought he had a good case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff said Gov. George W. Bush never approached him on the
issue. Bullock died on June 18, after himself donating $20,000 from
unspent campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Several A&AMP;M professors have refused to teach at the Bush School
and one changed his mind about a job he had accepted as associate
dean, said George Edwards III, director of the Center for
Presidential Studies, which has become a part of the Bush School.
</P>
<P>
   One of them said it was not, as one published report suggested,
the result of a draft memo cautioning Bush School scholars against
making comments critical of the Bushes and saying that if they did,
no link with the school should be mentioned in the article or TV
segment.
</P>
<P>
   Political Science professor Kim Hill said he turned down an
offer to be an associate dean at the Bush School because of
Hermann's removal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I would not take it because I did not like the way
he was fired,'' Hill said. ``It was done unprofessionally. And the
university was not making the decision on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   The manner led some on the campus to speculate that the move was
made to please the Bush family, Hill said. Hermann has since become
an associate dean in charge of the school's fledgling international
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to me that the (advisory\)committee is made of
people who are close to the Bush family, which does not surprise
me,'' Hill said, adding that he supposed similar situations
occurred during the early years of the Kennedy and LBJ schools.
</P>
<P>
   But these ``advisory groups should not be making academic
policy, certainly not personnel decisions,'' Hill added.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gates, who served as CIA director in the Bush
Administration, was appointed interim dean but has made it clear
that he doesn't want to be considered for the job on a permanent
basis.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said fund raising for the school has lagged and others
say it's hard to select a full-time teaching staff without a
sizable endowment and a full-time dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't provide much vision if you're here only a few weeks
a month,'' Jones said of Gates, who has been traveling back and
forth from his home in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   What has gotten more attention was an almost comical misstep by
the school, whose top administrators issued drafts of a memo on how
its scholars should best avoid embarrassing the Bushes in news
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The October 1998 drafts were never issued but they became public
after a reporter for The Eagle filed a freedom-of-information
request.
</P>
<P>
   The memo drafts, also obtained by the Star-Telegram, said the
professors should not mention any Bush Center link if they offer
``negative'' personal opinions about ``any member of the Bush
family'' or any organization with which a family member is
connected.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
