<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTOS-INTERNET-2TAKES     01-24 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-INTERNET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR DEALERS LOOK TO LAWMAKERS FOR PROTECTION FROM INTERNET
SELLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Texas, Wis., Conn., Ark., Idaho, La., Va., Ky., Neb.) (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Internet companies that sell cars directly to
consumers are encountering stiff opposition from auto dealers, who
are using their influence in state legislatures and with state
regulators to protect their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Car dealers, meeting here at their annual convention, are
worried that they are being undercut or bypassed entirely by the
new services. They also are afraid that automakers might sell cars
on the Internet themselves or through the new Internet services. So
the dealers have begun pushing restrictive laws through state
legislatures to prevent this and have encouraged state regulators
to crack down.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators say that the only complaints they have been
receiving about the services have been from dealers, not consumers.
And consumer advocates say that extra competition will be good for
customers, even though there is mixed evidence on whether consumers
save money buying cars online.
</P>
<P>
   Because of state franchise laws and manufacturers' policies,
Internet services must buy cars from dealers, not directly from
manufacturers. Paying two markups, one for the dealer and one for
the Internet company, is a burden on consumers that does not exist
for many other forms of electronic commerce. This erodes any price
advantage the Internet companies may have.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has left the regulation of auto retailing
to the states, leaving potential gaps in regulation for deals that
cross state lines, said state regulators from across the nation,
who convened at a hotel near the dealers' convention for meetings
over the last four days. ``You could buy a car from a Mississippi
dealer who has his Web site in Iowa and delivers a car in Idaho _
who has jurisdiction?'' asked T. Rex Green, Idaho's supervisor of
dealer investigations. ``I can't justify to my taxpayers running
all the way to Mississippi to chase someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealers have already used their political muscle over the last
12 months to persuade lawmakers in nine states to tighten state
franchise laws, making it virtually impossible for manufacturers to
sell cars except through franchised dealers. Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, the front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination,
signed the toughest such law in the nation last year, and the Texas
Department of Transportation has become the nation's leader in
cracking down on Internet commerce involving cars. Many more states
are expected to consider legislation pushed by dealer groups this
year, with one bill already introduced last week in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   State motor vehicle regulators, acting partly at the prompting
of dealers but also because of concern that businesses could use
the Internet to commit fraud, have become alarmed that Internet
companies may be violating longstanding laws in most states that
require anyone selling a new car or truck to be licensed and have a
franchise relationship with a manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators said that they believed the newest services,
those which actually deliver cars to customers' homes, may violate
laws intended to protect dealers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Top regulators from Wisconsin and Texas said that they had just
ordered CarsDirect.com, an Internet direct seller, to halt
operations in their state. Regulators from Virginia, Kentucky,
Nebraska and Louisiana said that they doubted CarsDirect.com and
similar companies complied with their states' laws; Louisiana
regulators said that they were ``on the verge'' of taking action on
the issue, although they refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Barbour, a spokeswoman for CarsDirect.com, said that the
company was still doing business in every state except Texas and
Arkansas, where the company acknowledges regulatory restrictions.
She declined to comment on any litigation and regulatory complaints
pending against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in Texas also used that state's tough new law in
November to order the Ford Motor Co. to stop using its Internet
site to sell used cars in Houston. Ford has complied, but is suing
the state to reverse the order.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, dozens of Internet companies have
generated sales leads for car dealers, providing abundant
information to consumers about what is available and then sending
the customer to a dealer to close the sale. But a few companies,
led by CarsDirect.com, have recently become car-buying services,
taking prepaid orders from customers, buying cars from nearby
dealers and delivering them to customers' homes on flat-bed trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators reached a consensus here that a model law should
be drafted for each state to regulate car sales over the Internet,
although the details of the legislation have not been agreed upon.
Lobbyists from most state dealer associations attended Friday's
meeting and supported the drafting of such a law.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen regulators said in separate interviews that while
complaints about the new services had been coming from dealers, not
consumers, they believed that consumers could someday be hurt by
insufficient regulation of the new companies. State regulators have
the authority to enforce lemon laws, requiring manufacturers to
take back seriously defective cars, and to fine or even revoke the
licenses of dealers in their states who commit certain frauds, such
as charging a buyer for options that are not actually on a car.
</P>
<P>
   Even a few of the older Internet companies that sell referrals
to dealers are running into regulatory problems. Samuel Hedgpeth,
president and chief operating officer of Autoweb.com, said that
current state laws and regulations favored dealers. Autoweb
unsuccessfully challenged a rule in Texas, for example, that
requires companies to charge a fixed, monthly fee to dealers for
supplying them with sales leads, instead of selling each referral
separately.
</P>
<P>
   The law, Hedgpeth complained, was the equivalent of telling an
ice cream vendor that ``you have to charge the same whether it's
one scoop, two scoops or three scoops.''
</P>
<P>
   The enforcement efforts and tougher franchise laws have been
mainly in the South and Midwest, where dealers' political influence
is particularly strong. Regulators and legislatures in the
Northeast and West have done little so far to address the Internet
car-buying services, with the exception of Connecticut, where the
legislature tightened rules last year against manufacturers'
ownership of dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the bottom line in the current squabble is that
cars are unlikely to get much cheaper anytime soon. Fearful of
angering their dealers and increasingly constrained by state
regulations, domestic and foreign auto makers alike have said in
recent weeks that they have no plans to sell cars directly to the
public through the Internet, nor do they even plan to sell directly
to the Internet companies. Many dealers now sell several brands of
cars, and sometimes retaliate against automakers that offend them
by shifting their energy and advertising spending to a different
brand.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors ran into this problem last year, when it
announced a plan to buy and operate up to 10 percent of its
dealerships, using them partly for Internet sales, only to retreat
quickly in the face of dealers' opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Roy S. Roberts, GM's group vice president for North American
sales and marketing, said here on Sunday that the company now
planned to work so closely with dealers that consumers would not
feel a need for independent Internet services. What the services
``are trying to do is take our customers, and they can only do that
if we don't come together,'' Roberts said. ``We can cut them out.''
</P>
<P>
   GM and other automakers are planning to greatly increase the
number of cars they build to order. This would diminish the need
for dealers to hold huge inventories of cars, one of their main
functions in the current market. Once most cars are custom-built,
customers would be able to order them directly over the Internet.
Dealers are fighting now to make sure that they will handle those
orders _ and that their role is not supplanted by independent
Internet companies, or by the automakers themselves.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   According to J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, the auto consulting firm,
nearly half of all new car buyers now use the Internet for
research, and they tend to be relatively affluent. But only 2.7
percent use an Internet buying service, mostly services which send
sales leads to dealerships. The firm estimates that 10,000 or so
cars, worth about $250 million, were sold online last year, almost
all in the last few months, with the numbers rising rapidly with
each passing month.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates once supported auto franchise laws. The laws
have prevented manufacturers from retaliating against dealers that
sell cars for less than the suggested retail price. The laws also
discourage unscrupulous, unlicensed business people from pocketing
people's money and not delivering a car, which was a problem before
the 1950s, when many franchise laws were enacted.
</P>
<P>
   But now consumer groups worry that the laws are being amended in
ways that hurt customers. ``We do have some serious concerns right
now that dealers are using old franchise laws to inhibit new and
creative ways to sell cars, and most of these new and creative ways
are in consumers' interest,'' said Jack Gillis, an auto retailing
expert at the Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes in this legal battle are enormous. Much of the retail
business now being transacted on the Internet involves fairly
inexpensive goods, like $40 shirts or $20 books; direct sales to
consumers over the Internet are estimated at $10 billion to $15
billion last year. Moving even a small part of the nation's $700
billion a year in new and used automobile sales onto the Internet
would greatly expand the scale and economic importance of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But automakers and entrepreneurs alike have found that moving
car sales online is not easily done because of the regulatory
issues and the political power of the dealers. ``Everybody with a
PC and a background in Palo Alto thinks they're going to
revolutionize the auto industry and retire at 27 with a 180-foot
yacht,'' said James Holden, the president of DaimlerChrysler AG's
Chrysler Group. ``They don't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   One company, CarOrder.com, is trying to get around the
regulations by buying dozens of tiny, rural dealerships in large
states. The company hopes to use the dealerships to order huge
numbers of cars directly from manufacturers for sale over the
Internet. But CarOrder has not yet reached any agreements with
manufacturers, which usually limit shipments to dealerships based
on the size of the communities they serve.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Chodos, a financial consultant in Greenwich, Conn., who
bought a Toyota 4Runner sport utility vehicle that was delivered to
his home on Sunday by CarOrder.com, said that buying over the
Internet was much easier than going to a dealership. He has had a
couple of problems, though. The Toyota arrived with an empty gas
tank, while his order last November for a Lexus LS 400 sedan still
has not been filled.
</P>
<P>
   Chodos nonetheless said that he thought Internet companies
should be able to buy cars straight from manufacturers and charge
even lower prices, adding, ``I'd love to see the day when these
Internet companies can go direct, and the dealerships stick to
service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
