<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-A&AMP;M(2ndTake)-TEX     01-24 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-A&AMP;M(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
COLLEGE STATION, Texas: xxx is connected.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You cannot deny your association with the Bush School if the
media representative is aware of it,'' noted one draft memo from
Hermann. Instead, the scholar should declare the interview off the
record or insist that no mention be made of the Bush School link,
it said.
</P>
<P>
   The memos were sparked by complaints by aides of Gov. George W.
Bush, Edwards said. One call came after Edwards himself analyzed a
Texas Poll during the 1996 presidential race, saying that Clinton
was gaining momentum. The other complaint was made after a speech
professor said the governor was a better public speaker than his
father, the former president, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo that was never issued took on a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   After the Eagle story was reprinted elsewhere, the newspaper
industry magazine Editor &AMP; Publisher ran a lengthy piece on the
issue. It was titled, ``BUSHWHACKED: Bush Clan Chills Press, Profs
at Texas A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush School officials and faculty representatives, including
those who were quoted, now insist that no one had been intimidated
or chilled and that concerns of political interference never
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said: ``I don't think the governor was served well by
his aides. I don't think the university handled things terribly
well. But that shouldn't obscure the fact that, in the end, there
was no censorship and, in fact, there was renewed effort to protect
academic freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said the proposed memo was not issued because it so
obviously violated the spirit of academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relatively minor event that was mishandled by several
people on campus,'' said Vedlitz, who said the spurts of media
attention neglected to mention the school's successes.
Specifically, he cited its work with Houston and other cities to
tackle major infrastructure problems.
</P>
<P>
   What's clear, faculty members say, is that the Bush School must
tread carefully in its formative years _ balancing cordial ties to
a respected former president and his well-heeled supporters with
the need to maintain academic independence to nurture a national
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
