<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5090 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PERMISSIVE-PARENTS-TE ANDOVER BYKIDSA 01-24 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERMISSIVE-PARENTS-TEX </SLUG>
 PARENTS BEING RUN OVER, AND OVER, BY KIDS
ALLOWED TO HAVE THEIR WAY (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients)
By LIZ STEVENS c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kay Hymowitz heard this story not long ago from her neighborhood
florist:
</P>
<P>
   A woman came into the florist's shop with her small child in
tow. The child immediately grabbed a puppet on display and began
playing with it on the floor, dirtying it in the process. The
distressed florist asked the mother to take the puppet from the
child. Instead, the mother turned to the child and said, ``The lady
wants you to put it away.''
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture? A lot, Hymowitz thinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mother is saying to that child, `I can't bring myself to
limit you in that way,' says Hymowitz, author of ``Ready or Not:
Why Treating Children as Small Adults Endangers Their Future _ and
Ours.'' ``Nowhere out there is (the mother) getting the message''
that her job is to curb her child's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As American culture grows increasingly kid-centered, parents
seem ever more confused about where to draw the line _ in meting
out discipline, in buying material goods, in granting
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shied away from using the word permissive (in the book)
because I think it clouds the issue,'' says Hymowitz, a senior
fellow at the Manhattan Institute and mother of three. ``I think
parents are misunderstanding children. They are seeing them as much
more rational and capable than they actually are, and that makes it
much more difficult for them to understand when a child needs
direction and guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parenting authorities have encouraged adults to think of
children as ``self-regulating,'' argues Hymowitz, who believes kids
are anything but. She sees this theory played out in
under-supervised classrooms and in courtrooms where the legal
system has, Hymowitz believes, ``redefined children as adult
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   And she points to the media, which ``give children a picture of
themselves as very sophisticated and knowledgeable, which parents
often buy into.'' Hymowitz's examples: any ``Home Alone'' movie, or
the slews of sitcoms in which the 10-year-old always has a clever
comeback for Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Television plays a tremendous role in encouraging children to
want things and push limits, according to Stevanne Auerbach, aka
Dr. Toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is, as soon as the child is able to watch
television, they get into demanding, `I want this, I want that,' ''
Auerbach says. ``So you're either going to give it to them because
you're frustrated or you feel that you have to because you want
them to be like all the other kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach, author of ``How to Raise a Child With a High P.Q.''
(play quotient), believes guilt has prompted working parents to
become more permissive. ``There are more demands on parents than
ever before,'' she says. ``They're working and they're stressed.
... It's not so much permissiveness as it is confusion. Parents
don't feel power, they don't feel confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach agrees with Arizona educator Sal Severe that parents
need more information today than they used to, especially when it
comes to learning to set limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole phenomenon of giving in to the whining and teasing,
we do see a lot more of it now,'' says Severe, author of ``How to
Behave So Your Children Will, Too!'' ``I call it the parent trap.
It begins when they're 2 or 3 years old, and we give in, and we
rationalize it: `Oh, well, it's just one more cookie.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Severe believes discipline is the key to avoiding permissiveness
and developing harmonious parent-child relationships. But
discipline is not the same as punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discipline is everything we do for our kids to make them feel
responsible and accountable,'' he says. ``Punishment is a tool we
use occasionally to teach them (discipline).''
</P>
<P>
   And the greatest failing of parents when it comes to
disciplining children, Severe contends, is inconsistency: Saying no
to Brittany's request for a candy bar and then, when she's still
begging 15 minutes later, giving in; asking Justin to take out the
trash and then doing it yourself when, an hour later, the trash is
still sitting in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the pattern you're establishing,'' Severe says,
reminding parents that, ``You can be firm but positive at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ennio Cipani, a professor of psychology at the California School
of Professional Psychology, works with children in foster families.
He sometimes suggests that these parents use point systems as
reinforcement for good behavior, such as placing marbles in a jar
``and trading them in for a special activity at the end of the
day,'' he says. ``Or when (kids) don't comply within a period of
time, taking marbles out.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing societal values and realities have confused things,
too. The way moms and dads did things 30 years ago, the goods and
services offered to children, and the range of acceptable behavior
from kids have all shifted significantly. Today's parents are left
with, at best, a fuzzy blueprint as to how to do their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society is very pluralistic in terms of its value system
today,'' Severe says. ``When I was a kid, no matter where I went to
play, the rules were pretty much the same. That made it easy for me
to learn right from wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he adds, some households allow 10-year-olds to watch
R-rated movies and others don't allow 16-year-olds to do so. (And
we've heard of at least two 4-year-olds who received their own TVs
and VCRs for Christmas.)
</P>
<P>
   A lot of permissiveness happens today, Severe says, because
parents ``don't want their kids to not like them; they think
they've got to be their kids' friends. Those are mistakes in my
opinion. You are an authority figure. You always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hymowitz concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be a child's friend and be a parent,'' she says.
``The most important thing parents should be doing is bringing back
that bright line between adult and child. It's not to say you
shouldn't be close and loving, but the message that children should
be getting is that you're the one who knows the world best.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
