<HEADER>
A5094 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     01-24 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF GRAMMAR WERE A HAMMER, SOME PEOPLE WOULD HAVE MANY SORE FINGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daughter: ``Me and Megan are going to the mall.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother: ``That's Megan and I.''
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: ``You coming, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Thus runs a hypothetical but entirely plausible exchange over
the proper use of pronouns. It easily could have been a problem
with subject-verb agreement or a misplaced modifier. English is a
tricky language.
</P>
<P>
   Language is the one thing that makes humankind unique among the
species on God's green earth. Well, language and souls. People have
them, although judging by the heinous actions committed by some of
them, you'd never know it.
</P>
<P>
   As much as some folks want to believe that their dogs, or
horses, or parakeets also have souls, they don't. That doesn't make
the animal any less worthy of respect and decent treatment. But
with apologies to the people at PETA, creatures with feathers, fur,
scales or gills are not our equals. Never have been, never will be.
But that is a topic for an entirely different day.
</P>
<P>
   Animals don't use language. At best, they use signals that
humans anthropomorphize into language because that's what people do
_ ascribe human characteristics to everything.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mitchell, known in some circles as the Underground
Grammarian, talks about this tendency in an early chapter of his
book ``Less Than Words Can Say.'' Before Mitchell gets to his
rightfully indignant rant about the abysmal communication skills of
some people who should have learned better by the time they reached
adulthood _ bureaucrats and educators among them _ he writes about
the misplaced belief that animals communicate through language.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a zebra out on the edge of the herd sniffs a lion in the
tall grass, he does not say to himself in any fashion, `I had
better tell the others.' (Nor would you, for that matter.) He
simply does what is appropriate for a successful zebra to do under
those circumstance. His startled neighbors, startled by what he
does whether they sniff the lion or not, do likewise. That's part
of how they got to be grown-up zebras in the first place. The
zebras who are slow to startle have a way of dropping out of the
herd early in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Why this talk of zebras and lions lurking in tall African
grasses when I started out talking about teens at the mall? It's a
metaphor for children whose lives don't amount to much more than
being one of the herd at the mall because they don't learn how to
properly and precisely communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Street language, bad grammar, horrible spelling, slang _ people
can generally get their messages across in this world even if they
exhibit all these foibles. But the harsh reality is that they
generally don't get very far in life.
</P>
<P>
   It is important for schoolchildren to learn the admittedly
difficult lessons of dangling participles and misplaced modifiers
and subject-verb agreement because those are the rules of
communication in a successful society. Mastery of language
differentiates the leaders from the rest of the herd.
</P>
<P>
   Proper language use means learning the rules of the game.
Mitchell provides an analogy that even the most addle-brained
sports nut could understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Rule in Heaven that language has to be logical,
orderly, and coherent any more than there is some Law of Nature
that requires football players to stay within the lines. You can
grab a football and run to Oshkosh anytime you please; you just
won't be playing football.''
</P>
<P>
   You can speak in garbled syntaxes and muddled tenses any time
you please; you just won't be communicating effectively.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the ultimate goal of teaching children to speak and
write correctly? One of them, Mitchell suggests, is a social goal
``not much different from what we have in mind when we teach them
to use knives and forks at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Children who grow up without having learned to use knives and
forks at the table may be charming and valuable human beings, but
they will often be passed over for promotion. Furthermore, it seems
unlikely that only that portion of their rearing could have been
neglected. When you have lunch with a man who eats his lasagna with
his fingers, you have reason to suspect that he may have one or two
other social deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Being able to use language makes you human. Being able to use
language well makes you a human with a future.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe &LR; star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
