r f BC-URBAN-MEDIA-COX     01-24 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-MEDIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Urban Media building hub inAtlanta
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Silicon Valley startup that offers free high-speed
Internet access is building its national operations hub in Atlanta
and plans to hire at least 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   The company is called Urban Media and struck deals with a
handful of real estate developers and property managers to wire
area office buildings with its fiber optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the buildings the company has signed up so far are in
the Cumberland and Galleria Mall area of Northwest Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Media, based in Palo Alto, is financing its expansion
beyond San Francisco with $25 million in new venture capital. It
was raised from Softbank Venture Capital and Accel Partners.
</P>
<P>
   In part, those funds will help finance a roll out across eight
cities, including metro Atlanta. The company has already hired 30
people to staff a national operation hub at 200 North Point Center
East.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Media chose Atlanta as a hub for two reasons. For one, it
has a great pool of telecommunications engineers. ``We can recruit
for our hub from these companies,'' says Mark Davis, Urban Media's
vice president for engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Atlanta is a great market, with not only lots of small
businesses but businesses that are savvy about the new
telecommunications technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a good growth market for us,'' says Sean
Doherty, Urban Media's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty is among the founders of Urban Media, and also helped
start West Coast consumer Internet provider, Excite At Home.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Media's business plan is simple. It offers businesses in
Cumberland office park high-speed Internet access. And the access
is the carrot the company uses to help sell other digital services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage we offer is quicker connectivity to the
Internet,'' says Urban Media spokesman Phil Hughes. ``We're plug
and play.''
</P>
<P>
   With its free Internet service users also get a Urban Media
branded toolbar on their computers. The toolbar will also
eventually feature icons that, when clicked on, will jump to other
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Urban Media has struck a deal with dot com
Beyond.com, which offers software for sale to companies. Urban
Media will enable quick download of Beyond.com software to users
through its high-speed network and take a cut of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
