<HEADER>
A5097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MOBILE-DENTISTS-HNS &LR;      01-24 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBILE-DENTISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILES OF SMILES: GROUP HITS THE ROAD TO GIVE FREE DENTAL CARE TO
CHILDREN IN SOUTH TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMBES, Texas _ The gleaming 35-foot motor home parked next to
Dishman Elementary is becoming a familiar sight at schools in the
Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before classes began one Wednesday, the motor coach
pulled up to the school building and 79 students were escorted by
the school nurse into an on-board, state-of-the-art dental clinic.
</P>
<P>
   For many poor children in South Texas, these visits were their
first encounter with a dentist. One girl, age 9, had extensive
tooth pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child was in need of a number of root canals, four
extractions, 10 or 12 fillings,'' said Dr. Glenn Thomason, a
Harlingen dentist working in the mobile clinic that day. ``She was
in pain, all four (teeth) were hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   The $250,000 motor home is operated by Dentists Who Care Inc., a
nonprofit volunteer group started by private Valley dentists three
years ago. Their voucher program for free visits to dentist's
offices, called ``Valley Smiles coupons,'' has provided $240,000
worth of dental care to local children during the past school year,
the group says.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, the dentists have hit the road in the mobile
dental lab and examined more than 800 children in Cameron County.
Three and sometimes four days a week, dental clinics are held at
schools in rural areas and small towns where dental care is not
available.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 100 Valley dentists have volunteered to spend
up to three days a year staffing the mobile clinic. They plan to
take it to some of the Valley's hundreds of neighborhoods of
substandard housing, known as ``colonias,'' this summer while the
children are out of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dentists Who Care was formed because there was a huge number
of poor children who weren't being served. The federal government
wasn't serving them, the state wasn't serving them, they had no
dental care,'' said Dr. David Woolweaver, a Harlingen dentist who
directs the program. ``If they show up in a dental office with an
emergency, what are we supposed to do, let them die? So our
dentists were treating them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley dentists have turned out in large numbers _ 104 of the
135 members of the four-county dental society have signed up _ to
close the gap with free dental care for children, said executive
director John Guevara.
</P>
<P>
   Woolweaver said the mobile unit is the latest tool in what the
dentists say is a comprehensive approach to delivering dental care
to poor children whose parents cannot afford health insurance and
who do not qualify for federally funded Medicaid &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services,
there are 138,910 children in the Valley on Medicaid and more than
100,000 children who are uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Valley, ... there are many, many children who fall
through the cracks,'' Woolweaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Many are the children of the working poor or new immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, they don't qualify for Medicaid.
Sometimes, even though Mom and Dad have minimum-wage jobs they make
more than the (qualifying) guidelines,'' Woolweaver said. ``Or they
might have someone who is undocumented in the family, and there is
a fear on the part of folks who don't have documents that if they
start registering for services someone will find them and deport
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The mobile unit visited Dishman Elementary because the school,
north of Harlingen in the rural community of Combes, has a high
percentage of students from poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 79 fourth- and fifth-grade students had experiences
similar to Joshua Rodriguez, a 9-year-old who emerged from the
mobile unit with a smile on his face and a handful of colorful
stickers promoting dental hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit OK. I had some cavities,'' he said, adding
that the motor home was ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of minutes Wednesday morning, the fourth-grader's
teeth had been X-rayed and a complete dental exam performed by
Thomason. Before school let out, Joshua's dental health was
outlined in a report he could take home to his parents, and another
with recommendations will be mailed home.
</P>
<P>
   If the boy's family can't afford a dentist to fill the cavities,
the school nurse can provide him with a Valley Smiles coupon for
free dental care in one of the dentist's offices, Thomason said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the majority of the 79 students had received dental
care in the past, 25 had no dentists, including five with major
problems requiring immediate attention, Thomason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's encouraging to us when we come out in the communities
like this and see that a lot of them are getting treatment, but
there are still a few who are falling between the cracks and that's
really where we're trying to focus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the girl who needed root canals, by the end of
the day a Harlingen specialist with Dentists Who Care scheduled
free treatment at his office the following week. Thomason agreed to
provide free care for the four other students who had serious
dental complications.
</P>
<P>
   School nurses at Valley school districts who send students to
Dentists Who Care say the group offers a new option for students
with dental problems and no place to go.
</P>
<P>
   And in an area where a large percentage of the population lives
in poverty, dental care is often considered a luxury by families
struggling to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of goes with the area, because parents are concerned
with having a roof over their children's heads and food on the
table,'' explained Ana Milan, head of nursing services for the
Brownsville public schools. ``And if a child is walking and acting
normal, they don't worry too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest Census Bureau figures estimate the poverty rate
ranges from 40 percent to 52 percent in the four counties that make
up the lower Rio Grande Valley _ nearly 373,000 residents living in
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in the Valley remains the highest in Texas,
although it has fallen recently to its lowest point in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Brownsville, the largest city in the region, has a school
district with 40,200 students including thousands who need dental
care, Milan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be safe in saying that at least 50 percent of our kids
need dental care. They don't see a dentist on a regular basis and
that would be a very conservative estimate,'' Milan said. ``We
don't have any figures to denote that, but I know we can go into
any school and find kids who need dental care.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan said 15 Brownsville dentists currently volunteer for the
Valley Smiles coupon program, and each one donates three to five
coupons a month so school nurses can send students for free
treatment at their offices. Since the Brownsville school district
began using Dentists Who Care in January 1998, Milan estimated that
200 to 230 students have used the vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it. The students are being taken care of, the parents
are happy, and we are happy to find a way to access'' dental care,
Milan said.
</P>
<P>
   But the volunteer effort does have its critics, including those
who believe the dentists should donate their services at the
various publicly supported community health centers across the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are good brick-and-mortar facilities that the federal
government has invested millions (of tax dollars) in, and if
dentists volunteered their time there each month we wouldn't need a
$250,000 mobile unit,'' said one Valley dentist, who asked not to
be identified.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized Dentists Who Care as a public relations effort
to blunt criticism of the Valley dental community after it
successfully halted a plan to bring a dental residency program to
Harlingen in 1995. Dentists opposed the program because it would
have treated paying customers while serving indigent clients.
</P>
<P>
   But Woolweaver said government solutions to local health-care
problems rarely succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program is a multi-dimensional approach to solving a
health-care problem. Seldom, if ever, does government, whether it's
federal or state, ever approach a problem in the manner we've
approached it, and the reason is because we're the ones who deliver
health care,'' Woolweaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Woolweaver said the mobile dental unit also sidesteps the
problem of getting people to health clinics. Many of the working
poor, he said, have only one vehicle and public transportation does
not extend into rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brick and mortar clinics are well-intentioned, but they can
only supply treatment to a confined area,'' he said.
``Transportation is the No. 1 problem that an indigent suffers
from. So how do they get from here to this fixed-base clinic?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
