<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5099 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ORCHIDS-NYT &LR;      01-24 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ORCHIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EXHIBIT PAYS TRIBUTE TO ILLUMINATING _ AND SEXY _ ORCHIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  (DW) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, while staying at a half-built research
station in the middle of a remote tropical rain forest in Ecuador,
I became desperate to have something other than boiled river water
to drink. Wondering whether I was within driving distance of
anything like a soda, I went searching for the man who would know,
a gruff, musclebound Ecuadorean who was in charge and was, with his
own two hands, fighting back the rain forest to build the station.
</P>
<P>
   I expected to find this man _ who was always intimidatingly
sweaty and shirtless _ in a spartan cabin on grounds littered with
power tools, scornful of my frivolous inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I found him at home in a garden that could only be
called enchanting, filled with wild orchids that he had carefully
collected from the rain forest. The orchids were all epiphytes, or
air plants, which live on top of plants, that he had taken from the
trunks and branches of plants in the jungle to clothe every tree
surrounding his house.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many orchid fanciers before him, he had become addicted,
unable to resist these flowers, full of fragrance and dressed in
fantastically sculptured petals, to the point where he was
constantly in search of more of the distractingly beautiful
species. Even this man, whose job was to tear down the endless
green jungle to make way for science, had fallen hopelessly in love
with its most alluring offering.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the inspirational power of the orchid. (He also helped
me find a soda and for the happy memory of both these I am still
grateful.)
</P>
<P>
   The gorgeous excesses of the world's 25,000 wild orchid species
_ which inhabit an impossible variety of shapes as diverse as
bursting stars, ladies slippers and gaping maws _ have long
inspired extremes of devotion, from the so-called orchid delirium
of England's Victorian age to today's overenthusiasts who cling to
cliffsides to get peeks at new species. Those seeking a simpler way
of seeing what ignites such passion can visit the sixth annual
orchid exhibition, which opened over the weekend at the Smithsonian
Institution in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But orchids have inspired much more than adoration. These same
extremes of shape also forever changed how scientists look at
flowers, sex and the evolution of life.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Joseph Hooker, a famous 19th century English botanist,
remarked that before Charles Darwin, botanists thought that flowers
existed ``in order to beautify the landscape.'' Darwin saw the
peculiarities of orchids in a completely new light, as devices,
honed and molded by natural selection for the purpose of promoting
sexual reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   After publishing his world-changing manuscript, ``On the Origin
of Species,'' Darwin chose as his next book a treatise, hundreds of
pages long, titled ``The Various Contrivances by Which Orchids Are
Fertilised by Insects.'' In it, he demystified the bizarre shapes
of orchids, showing how every twist and turn worked to manipulate
insects, often in nastily deceptive ways, into carrying pollen from
one flower to another, a plant's version of sexual reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin revealed the extraordinary lengths to which orchids would
go to have sex with other orchids, rather than simply fertilizing
themselves as many plants can do. For example, the flowers of
Catasetum plants are arranged as a kind of slingshot, set up to
fire off a giant wad of pollen covered with a quick-setting
adhesive at insects that land on the flower just so, setting off
the trigger. Other orchid flowers have evolved to look like female
bees of particular species, complete with fuzzy bodies, eyes and
wings. These flowers have evolved to arouse the passions of male
bees, which inadvertently pollinate the flowers as they engage in
hopeless attempts to copulate with the pretty petal.
</P>
<P>
   A study published last year in Nature showed that in one
species, these faux females give off a bouquet nearly identical to
the sex pheromones of real female bees, leaving lonely males unable
to resist their wiles.
</P>
<P>
   Still other orchid flowers are built as true traps into which
bees creep in search of food or drawn on by alluring fragrances,
only to get stuck in a room built of petals or to fall into a
bucket-shaped petal full of water. Unable to leave the way that
they came in, the bees eventually discover that the only exit is a
passageway that, when traveled, results in a packet or dab of
pollen being attached to them. Outfitted with its package, the bee
is allowed to go on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael T. Ghiselin, historian of evolutionary biology at
the California Academy of Sciences, said Darwin's inspiration from
orchids on the areal functions of floral forms was so convincing
that it not only bolstered his theories on the powers of natural
selection but changed the thinking of the day on flowers to such a
degree that it spawned several new fields of study.
</P>
<P>
   The huge and still active field of pollination biology, as well
as the rapidly growing study of co-evolution, which is the
examination of how different species evolve together as enemies or
collaborators, both had their birth in Darwin's study of orchids.
</P>
<P>
   The same tome is said to have started scientists thinking about
the huge and hugely intriguing question: why is it that all
organisms, even those able to reproduce by themselves, like many
plants and some animals, go to such lengths to have sex with
others?
</P>
<P>
   Whether one appreciates orchids for the elaborations natural
selection has wrought upon them, or for their beauty, orchids have
made themselves worthy of their adoration by illuminating so much
about the workings of the green world around them. As Darwin
himself prophetically wrote of orchids 138 years ago, ``An
examination of their many beautiful contrivances will exalt the
whole vegetable kingdom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
