<HEADER>
A5101 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-SCOTUS-CAMPAIGN-CONTR     01-24 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-CAMPAIGN-CONTRIBUTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT UPHOLDS STATE LIMITS ON CAMPAIGN FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of campaign finance reform on Monday
hailed the U.S. Supreme Court's decision to allow states to limit
campaign contributions to political candidates as a way to deter
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-3 decision, the justices reversed a federal appeals court
ruling that Missouri had violated free-speech rights when the state
capped individual contributions at $1,075 for candidates in state
elections. About two-thirds of the states impose campaign
contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate John McCain said the ruling
was ``marvelous.'' The Arizona senator has made campaign reform the
centerpiece of his bid for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Although focusing on a state law, the court's decision
implicitly affirmed a federal law that caps individual
contributions to federal candidates at $1,000 and is expected to
add energy to reformers who want tougher limits on federal election
finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the Supreme Court has said what most Americans already
know: that contributions to federal candidates may certainly be
limited,'' said Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., who is pushing
legislation to reform campaign finance laws with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill would limit so-called ``soft-money'' or
contributions made to groups that spend money without any ties to
specific candidates. The measure stalled in the Senate last fall
but both sponsors are expected to renew their efforts this year to
win passage.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called the decision a ``victory'' for
democracy. ``The American people know that our political system
needs to be fixed, and today's decision sets the stage for further
reform,'' the president said in a statement that also urged
Congress to pass campaign finance reform legislation this year.E.
Joshua Rosenkranz, president of the pro-reform Brennan Center for
Justice in New York City, said the ruling was ``a grand slam home
run reformers'' and that the decision said in ``no uncertain terms
that it is the province of the legislature, not the courts, to set
contribution limits.''Foes of campaign finance reform, who say the
ability of candidates to raise large amounts of money is a healthy
and essential part of the democratic process, decried the court's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Foes of campaign finance reform attacked the decision.
</P>
<P>
   James Bopp, an Indiana lawyer who represents the National Right
to Life Committee, the National Rifle Association and other groups
challenging contribution limits, said restricting donations ``will
only serve to keep many people from raising the financial resources
needed to run for office.'' The high court's last ruling on
contribution limits came 25 years ago in the landmark case Buckley
vs. Valeo where the justices held that an individual candidate's
spending amounted to free speech and could not be limited. However,
in looking at the contribution side of campaigns, the court came up
with a slightly different rule. While campaign contributions also
amounted to free speech, they could be limited to $1,000 per
candidate for each election to avoid corruption or the ``perception
of corruption'' that could result from extraordinarily large
contributions by individual donors. The court ruled in the Buckley
case that contribution limits could not have a ``substantial effect
on a candidates ability to obtain funding,'' suggesting that they
might strike down limits if a ``substantial effect'' were shown.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckley case upheld a Watergate-era federal law that applied
only to federal elections. But on Monday, the high court said that
the Buckley decision applied to state laws as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold Buckley to be authority for comparable state
regulations, which need not be pegged to Buckley's dollars,''
Justice David H. Souter wrote for the court. Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer joined Souter.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Clarence Thomas, Anthony M. Kennedy and Antonin Scalia
dissented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's decision has lasting consequences for political
speech in the course of elections, the speech upon which democracy
depends,'' Kennedy wrote in dissent. Thomas, writing for himself
and Scalia, said, ``Buckley was in error and I would overrule it.
`' He said ``Missouri's contribution limits are patently
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the Missouri case was a 1994 law that imposed a
$1,000 limit on contributions by an individual to a statewide
political candidate per election. A built-in inflation escalator
later raised the ceiling to $1,075.
</P>
<P>
   Zev David Fredman challenged the law in 1998 after losing a race
for the office of Missouri state auditor. Fredman argued that as a
first-time candidate with only a small number of supporters who
were willing to make contributions to his candidacy, his campaign
was unfairly hampered by $1,075 cap.
</P>
<P>
   Fredman and one of his supporters, a political-action committee
called Shrink Missouri Government PAC, filed suit in federal court
saying the law violated their First Amendment right to engage in
politics, a fundamental form of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   A district judge threw out the case, but the Eighth Circuit
Court of Appeals agreed with Fredman and the PAC, striking down
Missouri's campaign-contribution limits as violating the
Constitution. In its ruling, the appeals court said that Missouri
had not proved that larger donations corrupted state elections.
</P>
<P>
   But in rejecting that rationale Monday, Souter wrote that
Missouri was not responsible for showing that big donations caused
``actual'' corruption, only that these contributions caused the
``perception'' of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little reason to doubt that sometimes large
contributions will work actual corruption on our political system,
and no reason to question the existence of a corresponding
suspicion among voters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Souter also said that Fredman's argument that the law hurt his
ability to run for office was not enough for the high court to
strike down the statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even assuming that the contribution limits affected Fredman's
ability to wage a competitive campaign, a showing of one affected
individual does not point up a system of suppressed political
advocacy that would be unconstitutional under Buckley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
