<HEADLINE>
SUPPLY OF CONES FOR ICE CREAM TAKES DIP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON HALL   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Call it the great ice cream cone crunch.
</P>
<P>
   A Wisconsin cone company's bankruptcy means the nation's supply
of ice cream cones of all shapes, sizes and textures could reach
dangerously low levels before the summer surge hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound funny to some people, but it's not to me,''
said Dan Shaul, owner of Commissary Supply of Sarasota, sweeping
his hand around his 8,000-square-foot warehouse. ``In six months,
there might not be a cone in this place. For us, it's our life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like walking into McDonald's, and they say, `Sorry, we
don't have buns for your hamburgers.'''
</P>
<P>
   The continent's dominant cone producer, Ace Baking Co.,
announced three weeks ago that it was shutting down its cone
operations. Ace produced about 1.3 million of about 3 million ice
cream cones made in North America last year. On Dec. 27, the
company abruptly announced that it could not pay its bills and was
shutting down its five cone-producing plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were losing money and would eventually go out of
business, but we thought it would happen gradually,'' said Joe
George, president and CEO of Joy Cone Co., now the nation's biggest
cone baker. ``But it was, `Boom!' They just closed. This year,
there's just not going to be enough cones. We're running full
blast, and we can't make up for that kind of shortfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for consumers, the shortage of cones means higher
prices. Two weeks ago, Shaul paid $36 for a case of 800 sugar cones
from Joy Cone, his main supplier. Today, he'd pay $46.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unheard of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Ace's headquarters in Green Bay, Wis., were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   George said prices would eventually settle. ``We're going to be
very careful,'' George said. ``We don't want to give the impression
that we're trying to gouge the market, because we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Vogler, owner of the four Baskin-Robbins outlets in
Bradenton, said his customers would not see a jump in prices
because he did not expect anything but a temporary shortage.
Baskin-Robbins commands enough attention in the industry that it
will get cones even when they are scarce, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vogler is confused by the whole episode anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice cream cones are not exactly a volatile market, are they?''
he said. ``I don't really get it.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
