<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING PIERCE WON'T BE ABLE TO SWING IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Paul Pierce did some light shooting Monday. He wants to
do more, a lot more, but once again his body won't allow him.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the ankle anymore. It's his left hamstring. He still
was feeling pain Monday, and Celtics coach Rick Pitino ruled him
out of tonight's game against the Heat and possibly Wednesday
night's game in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we play our best basketball with him in the lineup,''
Pitino said. ``But we can't use that as an excuse anymore. Time is
running out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics actually play their worst basketball without Pierce
in the lineup. They are 1-10 the last two seasons in games in which
Pierce either was hindered by an injury or missed outright. (That
number has to be qualified somewhat; eight of the games were on the
road.) The record is 1-7 this season, the only victory coming in
the pre-Christmas mauling of Atlanta at the FleetCenter. When he
does suit up and makes it through a game unscathed, the Celtics are
18-14.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce hurt his hamstring going for a loose ball in the first
quarter of Saturday night's loss in Charlotte. He was just getting
over a bad ankle sprain, which caused him to miss six games in
mid-December. He took it easy and iced the hamstring Sunday, and
said the rest and treatment substantially helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels a lot better than it did,'' he said following the
team's workout at the University of Miami. ``I've never had an
injury like this, so I don't know the extent of it, how long I'll
be out. It's a sharp pain in my thigh. If I really stretch it out,
it hurts. And when I bend over, I can really feel it. That's my
whole game right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was in surprisingly good spirits, given his condition.
Teased that he was simply a Southern California softie, Pierce
insisted that his injuries were the result of ``working too hard.''
On his way to the bus, he high-fived several wide-eyed University
of Miami recruits who had been brought over to the gym to see the
big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce also loves to play against Miami. He had 26 points and a
career-high 9 steals in Boston's 96-84 victory over the Heat Dec. 3
at the FleetCenter, indignant that anyone could think Dan Majerle
could contain him. (Majerle had defended Pierce well in a 110-92
Heat victory here Nov. 20.) Pierce had his rookie season high of 31
points here.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's injury comes at a time when the Celtics are undermanned
at the swingman position. Adrian Griffin has missed eight games
with a sprained ankle and tried to practice Monday. Said Pitino,
``Adrian did not look good.'' He's out for a while longer. Eric
Williams will go on the injured list, probably Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Pitino with Walter McCarty and Calbert Cheaney as
likely starters tonight and no one in reserve. Doug Overton may
spend some time at big guard, as he did Saturday, and, in certain
situations, Antoine Walker can play small forward, as he did
Saturday. Pitino said he was not going to bring in an extra body.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitino again talked about getting his short-fused players to
stop whining about calls and aggravating officials. On Saturday,
the coach said some of his players had the ``diplomacy of Stalin''
in dealing with the officials. Monday, he said, ``My problem with
the team is how they handle the officials. They don't show maturity
in handling the officials and they don't know how to get calls. All
they do is alienate themselves and they get screwed every time
because of it. So you never get the benefit of the doubt because of
their attitude. Until they mature in that area, they can learn
valuable lessons of how to screw up.'' The Celtics are averaging
26.3 fouls a game. Only Cleveland (27.7) and the Knicks (26.3)
commit as many. And only the Cavs, slightly, are allowing more
opponent free throws a game than Boston. Meanwhile, Pat Riley is
concerned about his team's inability to get to the line. The Heat
are averaging only 22.3 free throw attempts per game, third-fewest
in the league, ahead of Dallas and the Knicks. And Miami's average
of 16.36 free throw makes per game is second to last, ahead of only
Golden State . . . Griffin participated in his first practice since
blowing out his ankle in Chicago Feb. 8. He agreed with the coach's
assessment. ``I've still got a ways to go,'' he said. ``I tried to
practice a little. I scrimmaged a little. But I'm not there. Still,
I'm not going to know anything unless I get out there.'' Griffin
did say he felt good just playing, ``even though my teammates were
destroying me every time.'' . . . Tim Hardaway has returned to the
Miami lineup after missing 26 games with a jammed knee. Riley said
that Hardaway, who has played in the last two games, had his best
practice Monday since returning . . . The Celtics and Heat have
developed somewhat of a trash-talking rivalry although, as Pitino
noted, everyone does it. ``It's the culture we're in,'' Pitino
said. ``The whole league does it. It's not Miami. It's not Boston.
It's every single team. It's the new culture: Put as many people
down as possible in a given day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
