<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING-10     01-24 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING-1065&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT UPHOLDS LIMITS ON CAMPAIGN CONTRIBUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mo., Vt.)  (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ruling in a Missouri campaign finance case with
important national implications, the Supreme Court on Monday
decisively upheld limits on political contributions and rejected
the argument that inflation has rendered unconstitutionally low the
$1,000 limit it upheld 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision left states with considerable latitude to adopt
that $1,000 limit upheld in the court's much-disputed Buckley vs.
Valeo decision, or to experiment with even lower caps, as a number
of states recently have.
</P>
<P>
   The test, the court said in a majority opinion by Justice David
H. Souter, is not any fixed or indexed dollar amount, but whether a
contribution limit was so low ``as to render political association
ineffective, drive the sound of a candidate's voice below the level
of notice, and render contributions pointless.'' Missouri's $1,000
cap met this test without running afoul of the First Amendment, the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision overturned a 1998 ruling by the federal appeals
court in St. Louis, which declared the Missouri limit
unconstitutional on the ground that it was too low _ $1,000 in 1976
being the equivalent of less than $400 today _ and that the state
had failed to provide ``demonstrable evidence'' of problems
resulting from large contributions. Had the justices agreed with
the 8th U.S. Court of Appeals, the federal campaign finance system,
which also has a $1,000 limit, and those of many states would have
been thrown into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The closely watched case did not call on the justices to
reconsider the Buckley vs. Valeo decision as a whole or even to
address its most widely criticized element, its holding that
campaign expenditures, as opposed to contributions, represent the
highest form of political speech and may not be limited. Many
people have blamed the decision for the tide of independent
expenditures as well as unregulated ``soft money'' contributions
that appear increasingly likely to swamp the political system.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion Monday, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy
declared that ``Buckley has not worked,'' having ``created a
misshapen system'' that has ``forced a substantial amount of
political speech underground.'' Justice Clarence Thomas dissented
as well, declaring in an opinion that Missouri's contribution
limits were ``patently unconstitutional'' and that Buckley vs.
Valeo should be overruled; Justice Antonin Scalia also signed the
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But while the question before the court was limited to the
contribution question, the various opinions Monday contained some
intriguing tea leaves for the future.
</P>
<P>
   A concurring opinion by Justice Stephen G. Breyer, joined by
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, suggested that the court should give
the political branches considerable leeway in sorting out a
difficult question on which ``a legislature has significantly
greater institutional expertise'' than a court.
</P>
<P>
   Within the existing Buckley framework, laws regulating soft
money might well be upheld, Breyer said. Alternatively, he said,
the decision could be reinterpreted ``in light of the post-Buckley
experience'' to make ``less absolute the contribution/expenditure
line, particularly in respect to independently wealthy candidates,
whose expenditures might be considered contributions to their own
campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the precedent did not prove sufficiently flexible, Breyer
concluded, ``I believe the Constitution would require us to
reconsider Buckley.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other members of the court, Justice John Paul Stevens
indicated in a concurring opinion that he, too, would be ready to
uphold limits on money in politics well beyond those upheld in the
Buckley decision. ``Money is property; it is not speech,'' Stevens
said, in a comment that rejected the essential equation of money
and speech that was the analytical foundation of Buckley vs. Valeo.
</P>
<P>
   And Kennedy, in his dissenting opinion, distanced himself from
his two fellow dissenters with a paragraph that startled those who
thought they understood the dimensions of his near-absolutist view
of political speech. ``I would leave open the possibility that
Congress, or a state legislature, might devise a system in which
there are some limits on both expenditures and contributions, thus
permitting officeholders to concentrate their time and efforts on
official duties rather than on fund raising,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent campaign finance decisions, only Stevens and Ginsburg
had indicated a willingness to revisit the Buckley vs. Valeo
dichotomy between contributions and expenditures, so supporters of
limits on expenditures and soft money, while acknowledging that
they still could not count on a majority of the court, detected
significant forward movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality infuses these opinions,'' one such advocate, E. Joshua
Rosenkranz, executive director of the Brennan Center for Justice at
New York University Law School, said in an interview. ``The court
is taking account of what's going on out there. We're in far better
shape than we were before this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicole A. Gordon, executive director of the New York City
Campaign Finance Board, a city agency that administers the public
financing of local political races, said the decision had produced
``a collective sigh of relief from the reform community'' that not
only did the court not reject contribution limits, as some had
forecast, but now appeared open to arguments on behalf of new
limits.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no immediate next test looming for the court,
cases in the pipeline could provide one. Expenditure limits adopted
in 1995 by the state Legislature in Vermont are being challenged in
federal District Court in Burlington. Under the state's limits for
gubernatorial races, for example, the challenger may spend no more
than $300,000 while an incumbent seeking re-election is limited to
85 percent of what the challenger spends.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other members of the majority, Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and Justice Sandra Day O'Connor joined Souter's
opinion, Nixon vs. Shrink Missouri Government PAC, No. 98-963,
without further elaboration. The majority opinion studiously
avoided speculation about the future. Souter, acknowledging the
calls of his colleagues for overruling Buckley vs. Valeo, said:
``The answer is that we are supposed to decide this case.'' He
noted that the broader question was not before the court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
