<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING-2N     01-24 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the court. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The challenge to the Missouri contribution limit, adopted by the
state Legislature in 1994, was brought by a former candidate for
state auditor and a political action committee that supported him.
The candidate, Zev David Fredman, argued that the limit was so low
that, as an insurgent, he could not exercise his First Amendment
right to mount an effective campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fredman's victory in the appeals court threatened to unsettle
many states' contribution limits on two levels: first, under the
notion that inflation should be taken into account in assessing a
limit's adequacy, and second, by demanding a level of evidence of
corruption beyond what the Supreme Court had required when it
upheld the federal limits in Buckley vs. Valeo.
</P>
<P>
   In his opinion Monday, Souter said the 8th Circuit's view that
inflation must be taken into account reflected a ``fundamental
misunderstanding'' of Buckley vs. Valeo as having adopted any
particular level as a minimum. And on the question of evidence, he
said, ``this case does not present a close call.'' Souter said
``there is little reason to doubt'' that large contributions can be
corrupting, or can be seen as such by voters.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of constitutional doctrine, there was considerable
wrestling over how to define the First Amendment standard of review
for the limits in question, an issue on which the Buckley precedent
was imprecise. The majority held Monday that the strictest judicial
scrutiny need not apply to contribution limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
