<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-STRATEGISTS     01-24 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-STRATEGISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams happily adopt go-for-broke passing offense
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About 25 years ago, Bill Walsh was sitting in a
restaurant with an arm around his wife, drawing a passing play on
her back.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's wife turned to him and asked, ``Did it work?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even realize I was doing it,'' Walsh recalls. ``I was
that into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's creativity led to one of football's great innovations _
the West Coast offense. Before he retired as coach of the San
Francisco 49ers in 1989, Walsh had won three Super Bowls and
established a lasting legacy in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, the West Coast offense _ a horizontal
passing game with short, quick routes _ has been a blueprint for
success in pro football.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of creativity in what we were doing at the
time,'' said Walsh, now general manager of the 49ers. ``But we
never thought it would be called the `West Coast offense.' At the
time, we thought it might become the San Francisco 49ers' offense,
but then someone put the label of `West Coast offense' on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh disciples George Seifert and Mike Shanahan each won two
Super Bowls with the 49ers and Broncos, respectively. Seahawks
coach Mike Holmgren, an offensive coordinator under Walsh for three
seasons, led the Packers to a championship three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Walsh's system might not be the vogue offense in the NFL
anymore. This season, another high-flying passing attack with true
roots in the West Coast dominated the league.
</P>
<P>
   It's the old ``Air Coryell'' offense concocted by Don Coryell,
orchestrated to perfection by Hall of Fame quarterback Dan Fouts
and the San Diego Chargers in the late 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the offense that fans will see Sunday, when the Rams
use an amended version against the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of ideas,'' said Coryell, who retired as Chargers
coach during the 1986 season. ``I just pulled out a blank piece of
paper and worked with it. I think every coach has probably drawn
plays on cocktail napkins. We all liked to drink.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Air Coryell'' is not a clone of the Walsh system. The West
Coast offense is a high-percentage passing game that features short
drops and rollouts, a quick throwing release and pinpoint timing
between the quarterback and receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Coryell's aerial circus is designed to stretch the field by
softening up defenses with long passes and then runs. It has more
multiple formations, motions and shifts.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast offense settles for legged-out doubles; Coryell
went for home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don put in such different wrinkles,'' Fouts said, ``that teams
had no clue how to stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, defenses had trouble stopping the Rams, Redskins
and Patriots, all using revamped versions of Coryell's offense. The
Rams and Redskins gained the most yards and scored the most points
in the NFL this season. New England's lack of a running game ended
its early-season success.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, behind NFL MVP quarterback Kurt Warner, running back
Marshall Faulk and receiver Isaac Bruce, scored the third-highest
number of points for a season in NFL history. On Sunday, the Rams
play the Tennessee Titans in the Super Bowl in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing: We have the capabilities to be very
explosive, just like we were in San Diego when we had Fouts,
(Charlie) Joiner, (Wes) Chandler, Kellen Winslow and the others,''
Rams receivers coach Al Saunders said. Saunders is a former Coryell
assistant who succeeded him as Chargers coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chargers were a vertical team (in moving downfield), just
like we are now,'' Saunders said. ``It doesn't matter what the
score is or where we are, we're going to play our style of offense.
Whatever your nature is, if you back down from it, you're not going
to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   While late-night inspiration played a part in the development of
both offenses, Coryell and Walsh concede they were developed
largely out of happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast offense is mislabeled because the system wasn't
contrived anywhere near the Pacific Ocean. Walsh, who was an
assistant coach on Paul Brown's staff in Cincinnati, lost rookie
quarterback Greg Cook midway through the 1969 season. The Bengals
were left with backup quarterback Virgil Carter, a mobile player
who lacked Cook's arm strength.
</P>
<P>
   So Walsh created the offense that became the so-called West
Coast offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a quarterback who didn't have a strong arm, so we were
forced to throw a lot of short, high-percentage passes, which we
hoped would be highly effective,'' Walsh said. ``We had big
receivers but not fast receivers. I think the essence of it was
mixing the short passes with the run, so opponents couldn't stack
up against the running game. Our short passing game was so
effective that it allowed us to start throwing deep.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Walsh took his system to San Francisco, where his
quarterback was Steve DeBerg, who later became a Falcons backup.
DeBerg led the league in pass attempts and completions that season,
but he was replaced by Joe Montana the next.
</P>
<P>
   Montana had the league's highest completion percentage in his
first season and then led the 49ers to a 26-21 victory against the
Bengals in Super Bowl XVI.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The offense) really evolved in Cincinnati,'' Walsh said. ``We
were an expansion team, so we had relatively limited personnel. But
we had to move the ball with it. We wanted to pick up 20 to 30
first downs a game to control time of possession and score about 17
points, just to have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Walsh, Coryell developed his system out of necessity. The
coach at San Diego State in the 1960s, the Aztecs' entire offensive
line graduated in 1967. Coryell was forced to open up his offense
by using a one-back system with three receivers. San Diego State
won 31 games in a row 1967-70.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a fine quarterback,'' Coryell said. ``We knew there was
no way in the world that we could run the football and win. So we
did what I think any coach would do, and that's adjust to our
personnel and branch out. Out of necessity, we really started to go
to spread formations and a lot more motion. It was a lot more
wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   After a five-year stint with the St. Louis Cardinals, Coryell
was hired by the Chargers in 1978. He surrounded himself with great
assistants. Ernie Zampese, who became offensive coordinator for the
Cowboys and Patriots, coached San Diego's receivers; current Rams
assistant Jim Hanifan coached the offensive line; and future
Redskins coach Joe Gibbs coordinated the offense with Coryell.
</P>
<P>
   When those coaches left San Diego, they took part of the offense
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs built his offense around powerful running back John
Riggins and three quarterbacks to win three Super Bowls. Zampese
refined the system with the Rams, who had current Redskins coach
Norv Turner as their receivers coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system has been bastardized so much over the years,'' said
Ralph Friedgen, the Georgia Tech offensive coordinator and former
Chargers assistant who uses part of Coryell's offense.
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen said he dreams up some of his plays in church. ``There
are so many coaches that have tinkered with it. It's not pure
anymore. Coaches get an idea, and they tinker with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Walsh concedes that versions of his offense don't resemble
the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, you refine it, just like we did,'' Walsh said.
``Every man that left here has gone on and refined it and remolded
it. The pass plays probably remained the same, but every man added
his own wrinkle. They're building it around their players. (Vikings
coach) Dennis Green is going down the field a lot more because of
the wide receivers he has in Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to expect something like this to continue to
evolve,'' Walsh said, ``but they do disappear, and something else
replaces it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
