<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     01-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS TROT OUT HOPEFULS IN RATINGS WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Where else but here would Mary Tyler Moore be
trying to have her picture taken with an uncooperative camel? The
animal would have none of this nonsense, particularly with the
bright lights of camera crews surrounding it like gun-toting
marauders. Not wanting to lose this battle in front of flashbulbs,
Moore, having stripped off her wrap and gotten on her hands and
knees, nearly wrestles the poor animal to the ground while trying
to hang on to its neck for a snapshot that wouldn't make this seem
as silly at it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you with People magazine?'' Moore asks one of the
photographers, who shakes his head no, then bursts into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is a legend in the small-screen medium, and she's no
dummy. Her proposed series Mary and Rhoda, was killed and then
stomped on mercilessly by an industry unconvinced that a weekly
show featuring Valerie Harper and Moore would have a life of more
than two episodes, tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``After viewers see what your character has been up to, what
incentives would they have to watch beyond that?'' was a question
posed to Moore earlier in the day. She'd already asked herself the
same thing long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why we found her holding court with reporters well into
the evening, talking up a two-hour Mary and Rhoda movie scheduled
for ABC next month. Along with stars from ABC's midseason series,
Moore attended this network-sponsored gathering held at a former
hotel (and now historic landmark) to promote the network's
four-hour miniseries Arabian Nights.
</P>
<P>
   This explains Moore's run-in with the camel, and why visitors
were also met by jiggling belly dancers, bare-chested men in
Arabian garb offering chicken strips on a stick, and women who
patrolled the place with 7-foot snakes wrapped snugly around their
torsos.
</P>
<P>
   In this insular world of attention-getting antics, this year's
midseason press presentations were actually quite tame, which may
have more to do with success than with the desperation that comes
from failure. Meaning the success of Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,
of course, as the networks have retreated from offering their
expensive multinight movies for what is, for the time being anyway,
certain slaughter. (In the week that ended Jan. 16, ``Millionaire''
shows held seven of the top 10 places in the ratings.)
</P>
<P>
   Over this two-week press tour, where the ratings triumphs of
Millionaire, Fox's surprisingly potent comedy Malcolm in the Middle
and HBO's mob series The Sopranos were discussed and dissected,
what blindsided everyone was this mess over whether the White House
drug office was writing anti-drug messages into some programs'
plots.
</P>
<P>
   After the story broke, executives and producers were bombarded
with questions about the issue that, as it deepened, seemed to be
no issue at all. Before long, attention shifted back to the second
half of the season and whether Malcolm, finding itself in that rare
stratosphere of being liked by critics and viewers, was nothing
more than a freak.
</P>
<P>
   Or whether Wonderland would just freak people out, period.
Created by Peter Berg, the former Chicago Hope actor who made his
entry on the medical drama series by cutting off a guy's leg with a
chainsaw, Wonderland delves into the lives of doctors working in a
hospital's psychiatric ward and emergency room. The presentation
tape screened mostly for background purposes was so emotionally
gloomy that critics wondered whether it was made for viewer
consumption or the personal amusement of Berg, who admits to being
drawn to such salacious material. (His film, Very Bad Things, was a
morbid comedy about the murderous fallout from a bachelor party.)
</P>
<P>
   Many scenes involve chaotic exchanges between doctors and mental
patients. But one scene involves a pregnant doctor (and one of the
lead characters) who is stabbed by a needle while attempting to
restrain a patient. The needle penetrates the unborn child's skull.
Since Wonderland mimics a documentary style of photographing life,
the initial consultation with a doctor is staged, showing a frank,
emotional exchange of what may be if the baby is carried to term.
This news in hand, the husband races through the hospital corridor,
finds the patient lying on a gurney, and tries to choke him to
death.
</P>
<P>
   ABC officials found the episode so disturbing that they asked
Berg to hold it until the third installment, if only to keep
viewers from turning against the series right away. Berg agreed.
``It's a show that really has never been done, at least not in this
way,'' he said. ``It might be a little bit wiser to try and ease an
audience into it. Not shock them quite so much so soon.'' ___ &QC; 
(MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5140 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN(2nd     01-24 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: xxx so soon.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even more troubling, in terms of mainstream salability, is The
Others, slated for NBC next month. Perhaps you've already seen
on-air promos for this series in which men and women discuss their
``gifts'' of communicating with the dead. Just in time to take
advantage of the popularity of The Sixth Sense, the series revolves
around a secret society that helps people contact those ``on the
other side.'' I take it that they do this for free, or for their
own sense of purpose or destiny, much the way Buffy exists to chase
vampires.
</P>
<P>
   One episode, for example, involves a man who can't ``pass on''
until his wife stops blaming herself for his death. The dark,
shadowy touches and complex nature of The Others may put you in
mind of another NBC series, Sleepwalkers, which isn't a good thing,
since audiences never warmed up to the very similar idea of
reaching into a netherworld. Sleepwalkers was canceled after two
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   As for comedies, Titus seems perfectly suited for Fox audience
sensibilities _ jokes that work well in juvenile detention centers.
One of the more promising series is Kyra Sedgwick's Talk to Me. The
footage that was screened showed some sparks, particularly when
Sedgwick's character, a morning-radio talk host, was on the air.
The cast is talented, with Beverly D'Angelo as a conservative talk
host and MAD TV's Nicole Sullivan as Sedgwick's sister.
</P>
<P>
   It will be intriguing to see what kind of reaction NBC's God,
the Devil &AMP; Bob gets. Even though it's animated, God is the
spitting image of Jerry Garcia. He wears a beard and toils around
the house in Hawaiian shirts, jeans and sandals, reminding Bob of
his higher purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Three other animated series are slated for the next few months.
Baby Blues, about a harried family with two kids, is on the WB;
Clerks, an animated version of the movie, also written by Kevin
Smith, airs on ABC; Sammy is David Spade's creation slated for NBC.
It's based on a strained father-son relationship.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he'll be able to bring the outlandishness of
Clerks to network TV, Smith yanked out a piece of paper. ``They
prepared us for this,'' he said. ``The ABC response was (he's
reading the paper) `It looks like we're going to have a good time.
It's a fun show. It's a family show with a lot of ethnic diversity.
And tune in this March.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd burst into laughter, Smith said, ``We knew we
couldn't go for pushing the envelope farther than, say, South Park
has gone. So we're actually forced to be funnier than we were in
the movie. So now we actually have to work for the laughs. But
we're psyched to be giving these characters a longer life.'' ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney's return to ER for the departure of Julianna
Margulies is probably in the works, since the major parties said in
separate interviews on separate days they hadn't even discussed the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney: ``No one's ever talked to me about that.''
</P>
<P>
   John Wells, an ER executive producer: ``I haven't heard a word
from George.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, in town promoting the CBS movie Fail-Safe, said he'd
need about a $2 million payday to return for that one episode.
``Which I'd like to go on record as saying: I'd go back for $2
million an episode,'' he told reporters. ``I'm not an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of returnees, David Caruso, who left us as the star of
NYPD Blue, returned in the role of struggling actor in a TNT movie
called Deadlocked. Has he regretted leaving Blue? ``Only when I'm
not working,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Ellen DeGeneres, back here for the first time since
the cancellation of Ellen. She was promoting her participation in
HBO's splendid If These Walls Could Talk franchise that will deal
with lesbian relationships. Michelle Williams (Dawson's Creek)
stars in one of the segments as a young girl realizing she's gay.
Vanessa Redgrave, who didn't make the panel because of the flu,
plays a gay woman reminded of her societal detachment when her
lover of many years dies.
</P>
<P>
   DeGeneres, who co-stars with Sharon Stone as a couple trying to
have a baby, was jovial and hilarious, sitting most of the time
hand-in-hand with girlfriend Anne Heche, who wrote and directed the
DeGeneres-Stone segment.
</P>
<P>
   Now with a deal to do a variety show for CBS next fall,
DeGeneres is able to look back at Ellen more clearly. ``I was sad.
I was going through a grieving period and there was a little bit of
bitterness, and I made mistakes, publicly,'' she said. ``I look at
it now and know that there should have been a grieving period where
I sit alone in the corner of my basement rocking naked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omigod,'' DeGeneres said, flashing that smile we hadn't seen
in a while, ``I'm revealing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
