u w BC-SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING-HN     01-24 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES UPHOLD CAMPAIGN FINANCE LAWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A divided Supreme Court on Monday upheld the
constitutionality of state-imposed limits on campaign
contributions, saying the restrictions generally do not violate the
right of election donors to speak freely on political matters.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-3 decision, the high court said donation limits help
states achieve the ``important'' goal of preventing the potentially
corrupting influence of big money from entering the political
process. The justices, in upholding a Missouri campaign finance
law, said the state's interest in preserving governmental integrity
trumps the contributors' claim that restricting contributions
reduces their ability to make their views heard during election
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said that in extreme instances a contribution
limit might be so severe as to ``drive the sound of a candidate's
voice below the level of notice, and render contributions
pointless.'' In such a rare instance, the donation limit would be
an unconstitutional limit on free speech, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas places no limits on campaign contributions in races for state
offices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who leads the national effort to
solicit contributions for GOP Senate candidates, played down the
high court's decision while seizing on the rare exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has made clear that limits on candidate
contributions will be struck down whenever those limits impede
effective communication of a candidate's message,'' said McConnell,
who chairs the National Republican Senatorial Committee. The
senator and his committee had submitted a legal brief to the
justices, unsuccessfully urging them to rule contribution limits
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon, who defended the state
law at the high court, lauded the justices' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign limits are an important way to protect the integrity
of the electoral process,'' Nixon said. ``This ruling sets the
record straight that campaign contribution limits can be used to
help protect and reform the electoral process. We can take
pro-active measures to prevent our government from being bought and
sold to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court, with its ruling, extended to state-office
elections its 1976 decision upholding a $1,000 limit on individual
contributions to candidates for federal office. In that earlier
ruling, Buckley vs. Valeo, the justices said restrictions on
contributions did not interfere with donors' First Amendment
free-speech rights, as they remain free to speak in favor of their
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The high court in that case, however, struck down limits on the
amount candidates can spend on their own campaigns, saying such a
financial restriction would unconstitutionally interfere with their
ability to get their messages out.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, reiterating a point it made in the Buckley
case, said state campaign contribution limits are constitutional
because they help dispel the public perception that well-heeled
donors can buy the votes of elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave the perception of impropriety unanswered, and the
cynical assumption that large donors call the tune could jeopardize
the willingness of voters to take part in democratic governance,''
Justice David H. Souter wrote in the court's majority opinion.
``Democracy works only if the people have faith in those who
govern, and that faith is bound to be shattered when high officials
and their appointees engage in activities which arouse suspicions
of malfeasance and corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Souter's opinion in Nixon vs. Shrink Missouri Government
PAC were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Stephen G.
Breyer, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, Sandra Day O'Connor and John Paul
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting justices _ Anthony M. Kennedy, Antonin Scalia and
Clarence Thomas _ countered in vain that money does not necessarily
corrupt the political process and that imposing limits on
contributions unconstitutionally infringes on donors' free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters, who urged the court to overrule Buckley, said
campaign contributions are a form of speech analogous to the
constitutionally protected act of standing on a soapbox and voicing
support for a candidate. Hence, any limit on contributions
restricts the donor's constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   With its decision, the high court upheld the constitutionality
of a Missouri law that limits political contributions from
individuals and committees to $1,075 to candidates for statewide
office, $525 to candidates for state senate and $275 for
state-representative candidates. Shrink Missouri Government PAC, a
political action committee, sought to contribute more than $1,075
to Zev David Fredman, an unsuccessful 1998 GOP candidate for
Missouri state auditor, and challenged the law as an
unconstitutional restriction on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with the committee,
striking down the law as a violation of the First Amendment.
Missouri then appealed to the Supreme Court, saying the state law
merely extended the justices' decision in Buckley to state offices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
