<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DAVIDIAN-THEORY-HNS &LR;      01-24 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIAN-THEORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COLORFUL CHARACTER NOW A FIGURE IN WACO INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DICK J. REAVIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A colorful New Orleans electronics expert, private
eye and business promoter is back on the fringes of history, this
time in connection with the 1993 federal siege of the Branch
Davidian cult compound near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Novel, 61, is the originator of allegations that federal
agents fired upon David Koresh's followers as his cult complex was
bursting into flames. Some 80 people, including a number of
children, died.
</P>
<P>
   Government investigators are looking into the possibility that
at Waco, federal agents might have been guilty of attempted murder,
not negligence.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the Justice Department's special counsel,
former Sen. John C. Danforth of Missouri, and at the order of
Waco's federal district court, experts will re-enact a scenario
intended to prove or debunk Novel's contentions.
</P>
<P>
   But Novel is not the sort of figure whose charges the news media
or the courts are accustomed to taking seriously, and his
background only adds to the furor over the events at the Branch
Davidian compound.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble begins, perhaps, with his birth. Novel says he is
the illegitimate son of showman and songwriter Billy Rose
(``Without a Song,'' ``Me and My Shadow''), who said, ``I sell
ballyhoo, not genius.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Novel says, was a chorus girl. Perhaps if Novel is
given to showmanship, it is because it is in his genes.
</P>
<P>
   His resume says that he was the model, inaccurately portrayed,
as ``Mr. X'' in the 1991 Oliver Stone movie ``JFK.'' He has for
years been widely identified as an assassination conspirator; he
was a bit player in the Watergate scandal; and he has lately been
investigating UFO phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, he also has been an adviser to such notable
figures as carmaker John DeLorean and pornographer Larry Flynt. He
is the sort of fast-talking raconteur who can spin tales that only
space age technology can disprove _ or verify.
</P>
<P>
   The re-enactment, reportedly slated to take place in March at
Fort Hood, ``is worthy of Cecile B. DeMille,'' said former U.S.
Attorney General Ramsey Clark, the lawyer for some of the Branch
Davidian survivors.
</P>
<P>
   A British company, Vector Data Research, will fly a fixed-wing
aircraft at an altitude of about 9,000 feet over an expanse of
prairie upon which federal agents and perhaps others will be firing
weapons of differing caliber, loaded with a variety of munitions.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft will be equipped with a Forward-Looking Infrared,
or FLIR, camera, similar or identical to one the FBI used to film
the finale at the Branch Davidian compound. Dozens of technical
experts and lawyers will supervise the filming and re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   FLIR devices record variations in temperature, producing
black-and-white pictures that look very much like ordinary movie
images.
</P>
<P>
   The infrared videotape at the center of today's debate was
declassified by the FBI in 1994, during the criminal trial of
Branch Davidian survivors. Prosecutors argued that the infrared
videotapes showed that on April 19, 1993, residents of the complex
set three separate fires inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   But in late 1995, while viewing the 90-minute tape, Novel says
he saw something in the videotapes that no one else had noticed:
flashes out of the view of news cameras. Novel alleges the flashes
are ``thermal signatures'' of weapons' fire.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the video flashes are pictures of gun- and
grenade-launcher fire is a critical issue, because FBI officials
have always denied that their agents took shots at anyone on April
19.
</P>
<P>
   The question of federal gunfire and of who may be responsible
also are issues that Danforth is now investigating as a special
counsel to the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation will be litigated this May, when a wrongful death
suit filed against the federal government by Branch Davidian
survivors goes to trial in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who put faith in Novel's interpretation of what
happened is Clark, who is representing plaintiffs in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems clear to me,'' Clark said from his offices in New
York, ``that the FLIR tape shows repeated gunfire, toward and into
the church complex, from positions where only federal people could
have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark puts such faith in Novel's discovery, in fact, that he has
hired Novel as his chief investigator for the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the plaintiff's arguments that government agents tried to
shoot people in the Branch Davidian compound is problematic
because, thus far, there are no witnesses to federal gunfire, and
most observers agree it would be foolhardy to accept Novel's
interpretation without corroboration.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of those who survived the assault on the Branch Davidian
compound were acquitted in 1994 of charges of involvement in the
deaths of four federal agents who died during the 51-day assault of
the cult's holdout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
