<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5145 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-24 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MOMMA AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Egypt _ Movies and plays about America are all the
rage in Egypt lately.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, there are two plays running now _ ``Monica and the
Blue Dress'' and ``Me, My Wife and Monica.'' Then there's the
recent film ``Momma America,'' which was a huge hit. It's the story
of a family in which America is the mother, Egypt is the son, the
Arab world is his brothers and sisters and everything is fine until
a cousin shows up _ Israel _ and a fight breaks out over Momma
America's inheritance. The movie ends with the Statue of Liberty
exploding and the Egyptian being arrested because he looks like a
terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   The latest film, ``Hello America,'' involves an Egyptian who
goes to the United States and is hit by a car driven by the
daughter of a presidential candidate. The candidate offers the
Egyptian anything he wants if he'll just keep the accident quiet.
First the Egyptian demands that the United States force Israel to
give back all the West Bank _ a line that produces loud cheers from
Egyptian audiences. Then he demands that America take its $2.3
billion a year in aid to Egypt and stick it in its ear _ sparking
more wild cheers.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to ``Hello America'' well illustrates the love-hate
relationship Egyptians, and much of the developing world, have with
the United States these days.
</P>
<P>
   While some older Egyptians who came of age in Nasserite times
still resent America, for many younger urban Egyptians America has
never been more of a role model. ``My generation was exposed to
European culture and dreamt of Paris,'' a woman professor in
Alexandria told me. ``My kids dream only of the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent seminar at the U.S. Embassy, an Egyptian economics
professor denounced globalization as the new ``Western
colonialism.'' Asked afterward what his kids were doing, he said
one was a computer scientist and another worked for Egypt's biggest
cellular phone company.
</P>
<P>
   At the same seminar, an Egyptian executive who works for a top
pharmaceutical company confided that he chats regularly via
Internet with a Libyan cabinet minister, who communicates with his
Cairo friends through an America Online account that he maintains
in London. The Libyan cabinet can live without relations with
America but not America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us in the computer business, America is the only example
to follow,'' explains Mohammed Hanno, head of Alexandria's Arabia
Computer Systems. ``France is not an example. Germany is not an
example. I just bought four software disks from Amazon.com. Now you
don't have to go to the States, you can have the States come to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Egyptian-American scientist Ahmed Zewail won the Nobel
Prize in Chemistry last year, it triggered both pride here and a
debate about why he never could have won it if he had stayed in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. gives me a headache,'' an Egyptian economist friend
remarked to me. ``The U.S. is a tremendous country _ you can say or
do anything. I love the freedom of the press, and all the people
who care about whales. You even impeach your president. On the
other hand, it's a miserable place. The U.S. says it stands for
democracy and principles, but then it goes out in the world and
acts on cynical self-interest. People here see the U.S. as either
one or the other, but it's both.''
</P>
<P>
   Egypt is a reminder that Americans have no sense of how much the
world thinks about them, emulates them and resents them. The United
States used to have a big consulate here in Alexandria, the
third-largest city in Africa. The Republicans, led by the likes of
Jesse Helms, closed this consulate in 1993 to save pennies.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it was so sad to see the administration bringing
Helms to speak to the United Nations, where he threatened that if
it was not more compliant with America, the United States would
pull out. Who authorized him to speak for America? When are the
Clintonites going to stop kissing up to this guy? Why don't they
send Jed Clampett from ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' up to the United
Nations too, so we can hear what he has to say about foreign
policy?
</P>
<P>
   America has never needed or been needed by the rest of the world
more than today. America has never had a better chance to promote
its values, democracy and commerce than today. There has never been
a sharper debate about America among youth all over the world than
today. This is not the time for shrinking America's presence
abroad. It is exactly the time to be expanding it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
