<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-PICDAY-COX     01-24 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-PICDAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jokes about an innocent question follow journalist
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the calendar flips to January, if Butch and Jana
John are driving in the car and hear it mentioned on the radio,
they will laugh or maybe roll their eyes. When the phone inevitably
rings, as it did Sunday, Butch will answer, listen and call out,
''Jan, it's the annual story. Yeah, we're revisiting that.''
</P>
<P>
   This revisitation is a bit of revisionist history. A chance to
set the record straight before yet another Super Bowl Picture Day.
No, Butch John never asked The Dumbest Question in Super Bowl
History. Everyone just says he did.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Chris Berman reminded his ESPN viewers of
Super Bowl XXII, in January 1988, ''When Doug Williams was actually
asked, 'How long have you been a black quarterback?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Never happened. John should know. He asked the question, while
covering that Super Bowl as a sportswriter for the Clarion-Ledger
in Jackson, Miss. ''I've been living with that one ever since,'' he
said, ''one of the stupidest questions ever asked at the Super Bowl
which was never really asked.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Sunday night the Washington Redskins arrived to play
Denver, Williams sat with a small group of 12 to 18 writers. Much
already had been made of the fact that Williams was the first black
quarterback to take a team to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''For about 20 minutes, Doug's getting all these questions about
the significance (of Williams' race),'' said John, who had covered
Williams' brother Mike at Grambling, where Williams also starred.
''All these question, blah-de-blah-de-blah. Never let up. Being
from the South, having covered Grambling and his brother Mike, Doug
being a black quarterback was no big deal to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, John spoke: ''This is what I said, verbatim: 'Doug,
it's obvious you've been a black quarterback all your life. When
did it start to matter?' Everybody got a pretty good laugh out of
it. His answer was that it didn't matter 'til he got to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ''That answer was used in the wire services. Also, there was a
little blurb _ no more than a paragraph _ in the San Diego paper
the next day, about 'A question from a well-meaning writer.' From
there, things just kind of shot out of control. By the end of the
week, it was the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially once Picture Day came. TV and radio went with it, and
the story exploded. ''It was like there'd been 500 (media) people
there,'' John said. The day after Williams threw four touchdown
passes to lead Washington to a 42-10 victory and win the MVP
trophy, John told him, ''Doug, I'm the guy who asked you the
question. I didn't mean anything by it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I know,'' Williams replied. ''What happened to you is
basically what happens to us'' _ how athletes can be misquoted, or
taken out of context, especially at a media orgy like the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been nailed pretty good,'' said John, 46, now a news
reporter at the Louisville Courier-Journal. ''If I had it to do
over again, I'd ask it in private, not a group setting. What
bothers me is people will repeat it without checking their facts.
They're so damn eager to repeat that, although very few people put
my name on it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not embarrassing,'' he said. ``It just bothers me that
someone would take something fifth-, sixth-, seventh-hand and turn
it into something else. It's like one of those urban legends. But
I'd rather it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
