<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5150 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-FED-GUYNN25-COX     01-24 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-GUYNN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Fed: Higher rates likely needed to curb inflation
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jack Guynn prefers not to think in terms of ``hawk''
or ``dove'' when it comes to Federal Reserve inflation policy. But
he makes it clear in his public statements that he regards
inflation as the No. 1 threat to the economy, deserving tough
measures to contain it.
</P>
<P>
   Guynn, 57, is president and chief executive officer of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta. As such, he participates in U.S.
economic policy designed to deal with inflation. By rotation, he is
a voting member this year of the Federal Reserve's policy-making
Open Market Committee, which holds its first meeting of 2000 on
Feb. 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Most Wall Street analysts believe the Fed will raise short-term
interest rates at least a quarter of a percentage point at that
meeting as part of a strategy to fight inflation by slowing the
pace of economic growth. It would be the fourth rate boost since
last June.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street observers identify Federal Open Market
Committee members as hawks or doves, depending on whether they are
thought to favor a rate increase _ hawks _ or are likely to
disapprove _ doves.
</P>
<P>
   Guynn has been identified as a ``moderate,'' but in an interview
Monday he made a strong case that inflationary conditions have
reappeared, and it's up to the Fed to do something about it pretty
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the probability that we will see greater inflationary
pressures in the new year and beyond is greater than last year and
the year before,'' said Guynn.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ``good fortune'' that helped the Fed keep a lid on
prices in recent years, such as low commodity prices and cheap
Asian imports, is ``all gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is right square in our lap as policy-makers to get it
right,'' he said. ``The old notion that we can wait until we have
seen two or three months of bad data and then do something is not a
practical, responsible way to conduct policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the lead times for policy changes to act on the economy,
he said delay ``means you're setting yourself up to let inflation
run at an increased rate for six months or nine months or a year
before you get it back down again.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Guynn's position on inflation, which he also
discussed in his annual speech to the Atlanta Rotary Club on
Monday, rattled an already nervous stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts fear that one of Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's
policy motives is to dampen the bull market because of the
stimulating impact it has had on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Guynn said it is clear that ``the extraordinary rise in equities
in recent years has fueled consumer spending.'' But he noted that
the phenomenon is not limited to stocks, since homeowners, in
refinancing mortgage loans to take advantage of lower rates, also
used some of their gains for consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will leave it to my friends to give advice on the market,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guynn is a self-described ``engineer who's risen through the
Federal Reserve System.'' His entire career has been with the
Atlanta Fed, starting in 1964 after completing his undergraduate
college work, and he has held a number of senior management posts.
He became the bank's 13th president on Jan. 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Guynn is an advocate of greater public disclosure by the Fed,
although he said it is too early to comment on the impact of the
Fed's new announcement policy following FOMC meetings, which goes
into effect at next week's meeting. The Fed will no longer announce
a ``bias'' toward higher or lower rates, but will disclose a more
general description of how the FOMC views ``risks'' in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory was and still is that the more financial markets and
others know about what we are thinking, the more quickly they can
adjust. And perhaps the less abrupt adjustments in the economy are,
people (will) have some sense of where we are in our thinking,''
said Guynn.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his thinking comes from the anecdotal information the
Atlanta bank gathers about business and the economy directly from
executives around the Southeast. Guynn thinks that process as
important _ if not more so _ than the economic research the bank's
staff conducts.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives often have a sense of what's coming ``before
it shows up in the data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the policy-making process is to use information
from business people,'' said Guynn. He said this kind of
information will be a big part ``of what I take to next week's
(FOMC) meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
