<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK WHO'S TAKING A SWING AT DIPLOMACY
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't mean to alarm anyone, but in the span of a few days last
week, Jesse Helms appeared before the U.N. Security Council to
offer a ``hand of friendship,'' Newt Gingrich pleaded for an end to
partisan bickering in Washington, and Mike Tyson expounded at
length on civilization and ``the sensitivity of human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's premature to begin raiding the ATMs and hoarding
bottled water again, but I am gassing up the car to be on the safe
side. If the lions get any cuddlier with the lambs, I'm booking a
room at the nearest doomsday cult.
</P>
<P>
   Let us begin with the travels of pugilist Helms, who _ at the
invitation of U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke _ became the first
member of Congress to address the Security Council. (Is the Clinton
administration displaying a wicked sense of humor in the home
stretch, or what? First, the continuous stream of televised images
of Bill as the Stepford Husband. Now, this. What's next, recruiting
Strom Thurmond to shinny up the statehouse dome in South Carolina
to fetch the Confederate flag?)
</P>
<P>
   Helms is, of course, rather well known at the United Nations for
describing it as a haven for ``cry babies,'' among other things.
He's also Big Daddy Deadbeat, the prime supporter of the U.S.
effort to stiff the landlord for nearly $1 billion in dues.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it appears the meeting went smoothly, all things
considered. Helms read from a loose-leaf notebook, joked about
getting an interpreter for his Southern drawl, banged on the table
a few times, and threatened to pull the United States out of the
United Nations unless folks start doing things his way. As
Holbrooke said, ``It was something.''
</P>
<P>
   The warmest reception apparently came from Qin Huasun, the
Chinese ambassador, who allowed that the senator might have a point
about the United Nations needing to show, ahem, ``respect for
sovereignty'' and ``nonintervention in internal affairs.'' You go,
Jesse! Stand yourself in front of that Chinese fellow's tank, which
is, um, none of our business!
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Washington, pugilist Gingrich was practicing the
art of diplomacy at the American Enterprise Institute, a
conservative think tank. As part of what appears to be an effort to
rehabilitate his battered reputation, he delivered a speech titled,
``Reflections of a Private Citizen.'' (I didn't catch Gingrich's
speech myself. I wanted to go, but my mistress couldn't make it, so
I just stayed home with the missus.)
</P>
<P>
   As his companion, Callista Bisek, looked on, Gingrich lamented
that political partisanship is holding Washington back from
embracing a number of grand, visionary, history-changing
initiatives, including _ coincidentally _ a few of his own.
</P>
<P>
   One initiative, it seems, is learning how to get along with
others. There's simply not enough cooperation in Washington, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will pay more and more attention to the
positive role of change and less to bickering,'' he told the
audience. This big idea comes _ as Salon magazine noted _ from a
fellow who once told a group of Republican college kids, ``I think
one of the great problems we have in the Republican Party is that
we don't encourage you to be nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   And rounding out a notable week in peacekeeping was pugilist
Tyson, who _ apparently unbeknownst to the U.N. Security Council _
is threatening to move to London.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is in Great Britain training for a fight with some guy
named Julius. According to The London Times, Tyson finds life in
Merry Olde much more civilized and hospitable than here in the
United States. In fact, on this subject, you might say he was
chewing folks' ears off.
</P>
<P>
   ``America, I don't believe, is developed enough and
sophisticated enough to deal with the sensitivity of human
beings,'' Tyson told a group of boxing writers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Helms, Tyson seems to fancy foreigners. ``You have to
understand that Europe has been around intelligently since Attila
the Hun,'' he told the writers. ``I want to move here ... I feel
more at home here than at home. People haven't had enough chance to
get familiar with me, close to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. There may be something to his last point. Among these
three early contenders for this year's Nobel Peace Prize, pugilist
Tyson has my vote. He seems a tad less punch-drunk.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
