<SLUG> BC-MA-TATTOO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS TATTOOING A FORM OF FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a ruling that may signal the beginning of the end
for the state ban on tattooing, a judge for the first time has
ruled that tattoo artists are practicing a
constitutionally-protected form of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The precedent-setting decision could affect a landmark civil
case about to be argued in Suffolk County, where the American Civil
Liberties Union has asked a different judge to declare the
38-year-old tattoo ban unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected decision by Essex County Superior Court Judge
Allan van Gestel, and the impending ACLU case, have some
legislators warning that the state could experience an unregulated
tattoo free-for-all if a bill to legalize and regulate tattoo
parlors is not passed soon.
</P>
<P>
   Tattooing has been a criminal offense in Massachusetts --
punishable by a $300 fine, a year in jail, or both -- since 1962,
when the Legislature banned it after a hepatitis scare.
</P>
<P>
   A bill currently before the House Ways and Means Committee would
legalize tattooing in Massachusetts, under Department of Public
Health regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ACLU wins its summary judgment motion before the bill
passes, tattoo parlors could legally operate without state
supervision, State Rep. David Tuttle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see the courts rule in favor of the tattoo artists
without us doing something first,'' said Tuttle, (R-Barre). ``It's
a public health issue and we have to do something to protect the
public out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the lawyers in the case admit that van Gestel's sweeping
constitutional ruling, issued as part of pretrial proceedings in a
juvenile rape case, was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Richard T. Meuse of Salem, was arrested last year for allegedly
raping his 13-year-old niece. The Essex County District Attorney's
office also charged that Meuse, an underground tattoo artist, had
illegally tattooed the girl and two other female relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Based on just a short brief by Meuse's defense attorney, Susan
Oker, and no filing by prosecutors, van Gestel threw the tattooing
charges against Muese out of court last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absolute prohibition of all forms of tattooing, a
protected form of expression, except by licensed physicians, not
themselves generally known to be tattoo artists, is substantial
overbreadth,'' van Gestel said in his eight-page ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The judge rejected a traditional argument used by oppponents:
that tattoos only constitute free expression for the wearer, not
the tattoo artist. The recent mainstreaming of the industry, he
said, has more than legitimized the tattoo as an art form.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, van Gestel quoted a web site --
www.tattooartist.com -- which reported that tattooing has evolved
from an ``anti-social activity'' in the 1960s to a ``trendy fashion
statement'' in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Internet report, ``the single fastest growing
demographic group seeking tattoo services is, to the surprise of
many, middle-class suburban women.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge also took note of recent photographs in the Arts &AMP;
Leisure Section of the New York Times, which depicted the opening
of a show called ``Body Art: Marks of Identity'' at New York's
Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accompanying photographs of the opening gala depicted
several of the Manhattan glitterati decked out in their own
fashion-statement tattoos,'' van Gestel wrote in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be tattoo purveyors called the ruling long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If tattooing were legal, we would be offering them the day
after,'' said Gil Delcastillo, the 49-year-old owner of the Jewelry
Gallery, a body-piercing shop in Harvard Square. ``The line would
be out the door, down the street, and around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is not binding on the judge in the Suffolk County
case, where the ACLU is asking that the law be declared invalid
statewide. The suit was filed on behalf of two tattoo artists.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Schwartz, who will argue the case for the ACLU next
month, however, called van Gestel's ruling an ``exciting'' sign
that the state courts are leaning toward legalizing tattoo art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a profound decision that should be followed to
the letter,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
