<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA PLANS TO PRIVATIZE LARGE STATE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Eager to capitalize on a run of
favorable economic forecasts, South Africa is promising to expand
the privatization of its state companies in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The country's efforts, which had focused on restructuring and
privatizing some of the state's many smaller assets, will now be
aimed at the biggest government-run companies _ its electric,
transportation, telecommunications and military-equipment concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, these companies _ Eskom, Transnet, Telkom South
Africa and Denel respectively _ are valued at close to $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sivi Gounden, director general of the department of public
enterprises, said in an interview Monday that ``having reviewed our
efforts on restructuring and privatization over the past four
years, we felt that any acceleration needed to target the big four
enterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the services those enterprises provide,''
Gounden added, ``the number of people they employ and the capital
they require, it's clear why.''
</P>
<P>
   The reach of these companies extends beyond South Africa into
much of the southern part of the continent, and the effects of
their restructuring will undoubtedly ripple across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Telkom, the country's phone company, and South African
Airways, a subsidiary of Transnet Ltd., have sold minority stakes
to foreign investors. In April, the government will lay out a plan
for bringing considerably more foreign capital into the big state
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues the government is grappling with in drawing up
the plan is the considerable debt being carried by some state
enterprises, Gounden said. For example, Transnet, the vast web of
transportation operations controlled by the government, is more
than $4 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   For the companies to attract investors, some of their debt may
have to be assumed by the government, and exactly how much of it to
take on is now under review by economic policy makers. ``If we are
going to draw in strategic equity partners,'' Gounden said, ``we
need to look at the balance sheets and make them attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   How the privatization plans play out with the country's powerful
unions will be important as well. The strong ties between labor and
the ruling African National Congress have shown some signs of
fraying of late, and while the unions know that restructuring is
essential, they plan to follow the process closely, fearing that
jobs could be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't argue against restructuring,'' Mukoni Ratshitanga,
the spokesman for the Congress of South African Trade Unions, said.
While acknowledging that the big state-run companies have problems,
he said, ``the issue for us is how we go about restructuring
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Lindow, the lead South Africa analyst for Moody's
Investors Service, said the government had been laying the
groundwork for selling its biggest assets for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it is very likely that we'll see some of this
happen in the first half of this year,'' Ms. Lindow said in a
telephone interview from New York. ``They know how important it is
to capitalize on the momentum that has built up over the last 18
months. It's time to show that you're really serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Moody's issued an optimistic report on South
Africa's economic prospects, and earlier this month, J. Mark
Mobius, emerging markets chief for Templeton Investment Management,
named South Africa his pick for the top emerging market in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0330 </DOCNO>
