<SLUG> BC-STORM-CANDLES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candles offer light alternative when power goes out
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Small wonder minor baby booms follow big power
outtages: Nothing is quite as romantic _ or flattering _ as
candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   On a less libidinous note, a candle can't power a TV or a video
game or a home computer. It can, however, fire the imagination and
rekindle that most elemental form of entertainment: holding
conversations with the people you live with.
</P>
<P>
   It can also provide enough light to get by with. Recall that
before electricity, people used candles all the time without
thinking themselves deprived.
</P>
<P>
   The average dinner candle gives off only one-seventieth the
amount of light of a 60-watt bulb. But that's enough to read by
without hurting your eyes, says Atlanta ophthalmologist David
Badawi.
</P>
<P>
   So get reacquainted with Poe, or finish that new bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   The National Candle Association recommends common-sense caution:
Never leave a lit candle unattended, and always use a candle
holder.
</P>
<P>
   The average dinner candle gives off only one-seventieth the
amount of light of a 60-watt bulb. But that's enough to read by
without hurting your eyes, says Atlanta ophthalmologist David
Badawi.
</P>
<P>
   So get reacquainted with Poe, or finish that new bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   The National Candle Association recommends common-sense caution:
Never leave a lit candle unattended, and always use a candle
holder.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffry Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
