<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5156 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STORM-PLANTS25-COX     01-24 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-PLANTS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protect plants from subfreezing temperatures
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lend a tree a hand while it's down.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're at it, toss some cover on tender plants because
a week of subfreezing nights lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's winter storm caused extensive damage to trees and
shrubs throughout the metro area and in North Georgia. Some trees
were beset by falling limbs, while ice simply left others with a
sad case of the droops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freezing rain added tremendous weight to the limbs of
evergreen trees such as pine, cedar, Leyland cypress and southern
magnolia,'' said Walter Reeves, horticulture educator for the
University of Georgia Cooperative Extension Service.
</P>
<P>
   He offered these tips for repairing the damage:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make clean cuts: Use a pruning saw or hand pruners to cut
splintered wood back to solid plant tissue. If the break occurred
near another healthy limb, trim the damaged limb back to a point
1/4 to 1 1/2-inch from the good limb.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leave no stubs: If a limb broke close to the tree trunk,
remove the stub because it's a perfect hiding place for insects and
disease.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Maintain the branch collar: Never cut off a limb flush with
the tree trunk. Make your cut at the surface of the raised collar
where the limb emerges, leaving a ``bump.'' Tissue will swell and
enclose the wound within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Support drooping limbs: Slightly bent limbs will recover, but
severely drooping ones need support. Make a ``Y''-shaped crutch
from a fallen branch and prop it under the limb until it regains
its posture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Splint bowed tops: Make a splint from 2-by-2 lumber to
straighten small trees with limber tops. Tie the support to the
trunk in several places using wide nylon belting or old leather
belts. (Pines that lost their tops and most limbs won't recover
because unlike broad-leafed trees, they don't sprout new limbs.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, don't forget to protect tender plants from freezing
temperatures. Overnight lows in the metro area are expected to dip
into the low 20s at least through Friday, according to the National
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Buds on early-spring blooming shrubs and trees such as
forsythia, quince, Bradford pear and Japanese cherry should
tolerate the freeze, Reeves said. But other plants will need help,
such as:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Emerging bulbs: The shoots of spring-flowering bulbs, such as
crocuses and daffodils, should not be harmed, but a light
sprinkling of pine straw won't hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Budding shrubs: Cover camellias and tender shrubs that are
budding, such as gardenias, with black plastic, anchored to the
ground with bricks or stone. Cover hydrangeas on which new growth
has emerged. ``The cold won't kill the hydrangea but could kill the
buds and give you fewer flowers this spring,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winter annuals: Water evergreen plants and winter annuals,
such as pansies, because winds can cause dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
