<HEADER>
A5157 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-STORM-SAFEFOOD25-COX     01-24 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-SAFEFOOD25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Food saftey after the lights go out
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have a $15 roast in your freezer, and the power has been out
since Sunday. Should you pitch it?
</P>
<P>
   According to Judy Harrison of the University of Georgia's
College of Family and Consumer Sciences, ``the old adage, `If in
doubt throw it out,' is still a good rule to go by.''
</P>
<P>
   But you may not need to. Here are some answers to frequently
asked questions, from the U.S. Department of Agriculture, that may
help you figure out what to do with that roast and other foods you
may have had in your refrigerator or freezer while you were in the
dark.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I refreeze food items that have been partly thawed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, providing they still contain ice crystals or have
maintained a temperature of 40 degrees (refrigerator temperature)
or below for no more than two to three days. You will have to
evaluate each item separately. Food that has been above 40 degrees
for more than two hours should be discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will there be any loss of quality in refrozen foods?
</P>
<P>
   A: Possibly. Raw meats and poultry, as well as fruit juices, can
be refrozen without too much quality loss. But the texture of
prepared foods, vegetables and fruits may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about items in the refrigerator?
</P>
<P>
   A: In general, refrigerated items should be safe as long as
power was out no more than four hours. Keep the door closed as much
as possible. Discard any perishable foods such as meat, poultry,
fish, eggs or leftovers that have been above 40 degrees for two
hours or more, and any food that has an unusual odor, color or
texture or feels warm to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   Other foods that should be discarded: opened, creamy-based salad
dressings, opened spaghetti sauce, cut fresh fruits, soft cheese,
opened baby formula, cooked vegetables and refrigerator biscuits.
Foods that should be safe: ketchup, mustard, raw vegetables,
vinegar-based dressings, peanut butter, butter or margarine, hard
cheeses, olives, opened canned fruit, fruit juice and quick breads.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I keep the door shut as much as possible, how long will it
take for the contents of my freezer to defrost?
</P>
<P>
   A: A full freezer will stay at freezing temperature for about
two days, a half-full freezer about one day. Dry ice will extend
the period food will stay frozen.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   If you have specific questions, call your local family and
consumer science agent at your county extension office.
</P>
<P>
   Call the toll-free USDA Meat and Poultry Hotline at
1-800-535-4555.
</P>
<P>
   For further info and for specific information about specific
food products, go to www.usda.gov.fsis and click on
``publications.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
