<HEADER>
A5159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GLOAMING-BOOK-REVIEW-     01-24 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOAMING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IN THE GLOAMING': SETTLING SADLY FOR SECOND BEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alice Elliott Dark's characters live in a privileged world
that's situated somewhere between Cheever's haunted suburbs and
Philip Barry's snooty Main Line. It's a world where people have at
least one country house (if not two: a summer retreat and another
for winter getaways), a world where it's assumed that life will
follow a certain path _ ``marriage to someone like-minded,''
children raised with fondly remembered traditions and adherence to
lots of social rituals that are supposed to keep ``chaos and
breakdown'' at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Of course chaos and breakdown intrude on this world anyway, and
in story after story in this uneven collection Ms. Dark catches her
well-bred, well-mannered characters in moments of extremis, when
their guard is down and they are forced, by illness or mortality,
divorce or disillusion, to re-evaluate their lives.
</P>
<P>
   As in her last collection (``Naked to the Waist,'' 1991), the
weaker stories in this volume tend to rely too insistently on
sudden ironic plot twists to expose her characters' illusions,
twists and turns that underscore Ms. Dark's authorial role as an O.
Henryesque puppeteer. ``The Tower'' pivots around the revelation
that the hero's new girlfriend is the daughter of one of his former
lovers, that she may in fact be his daughter. ``The Jungle Lodge''
concludes with a nasty revelation of sexual molestation.
</P>
<P>
   In her more persuasive tales Ms. Dark does not try to
stage-manage her characters' lives, but instead allows their
stories to unfold slowly, moving backward and forward in time, from
hope back into memory, from confusion back into nostalgia.
``Home,'' for instance, creates an affecting portrait of an elderly
woman named Lil, who has spent her life deferring to _ and
protecting _ her headstrong husband, Gordon, only to find that he
has signed her into a retirement home against her will, removing
her from the house that she has cherished for 50-odd years. It is a
development that will cause Lil to reassess her lifelong habit of
submission and self-effacement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the title story, ``In the Gloaming,'' has all the
ingredients of a made-for-television movie _ it was made into a
1997 HBO film starring Glenn Close and Robert Sean Leonard _ it
transcends the cliches of its subject to become a moving portrait
of a mother and her son, who is dying of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The story, which was selected by John Updike as one of ``best
American short stories of the century,'' limns the nervous, almost
flirtatious banter between the two, as the son tries to tease his
reticent mother into talking about her life, and she parries his
questions while silently reviewing the frustrations of her chilly
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Such empty, disappointing marriages are the focus of several of
these stories. ``Dreadful Language'' chronicles the life of a
painter named Frannie, who makes a safe, conventional marriage
after the love of her life dies in a freak accident. While she
tells herself that a partnership of shared aims _ ``children,
peace'' _ should be sufficient for a fulfilling life, she soon
realizes that she has made the same compromises as her mother, that
she has tried to substitute comfort for emotional connection,
kindness for real passion.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret, the heroine of ``Maniacs,'' has made a similar
mistake. Having resigned herself never to consummate her love for a
man named Jerome _ a man her outgoing sister, Diana, has
desultorily dated for years _ she starts seeing a dull, wealthy
man, who does nothing to disqualify himself as a suitor. Eventually
she marries him, gives up law school and has two children. She
never tells anyone about Jerome, though she saves her teen-age
diaries, chronicling her love for him, in the attic. After all, she
thinks, she is the responsible sister, the one who has defined
herself by duty and self-sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   In these stories Ms. Dark uses her sure knowledge of her
characters' inner lives to delineate the complicated mathematics of
familial love and resentment, particularly the ways in which
husbands and wives, mothers and daughters and closely matched but
competitive sisters vie for control. In the stories where she
trades this earnest, uninflected voice for something more coyly
sarcastic, the results are decidedly less convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secret Spot,'' which recounts a woman's efforts to get
revenge on a rival she suspects of having had designs on her
husband, is a thin, brittle little tale with a disagreeable and
oddly generic heroine. ``Watch the Animals,'' which employs a royal
``we'' voice to convey a community's disapproval of a local
eccentric, provides a thoroughly predictable portrait of a
snobbish, upper-crust town.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dark does not put enough spin or body language on her
observations here to turn them into effective satire; consequently
these stories feel like arch, disposable exercises in conveying an
unsympathetic point of view. They not only disappoint as simple
examples of craft, but they fail to use the author's considerable
gifts of empathy on display elsewhere in this volume.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `IN THE GLOAMING'
</P>
<P>
   Stories
</P>
<P>
   By Alice Elliott Dark
</P>
<P>
   288 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
