<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFC-DORSETT     01-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFC-DORSETT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anthony Dorsett aims to cash in on rare start
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anthony Dorsett got a taste of tailback when he
started playing football.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think I got tired of being hit,'' Tony Dorsett's son
said, ``so I changed position, and everything worked out well for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett will make his second pro career start, in the Super
Bowl, as the strong safety of the Tennessee Titans. The Dorsetts
also will become the first father and son to play in the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony isn't satisfied with that achievement. ``My dad has
a ring and I don't,'' Dorsett said. ``And I'd like to be able to
sit at the kitchen table with him and show off my ring to him, just
like he shows off his to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett was 4 years old, barely aware that his father ran with a
football for a living, when Dallas beat Denver 27-10 in Super Bowl
XII in 1978. Dorsett Sr. also played in the 35-31 loss to
Pittsburgh the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me after we beat Jacksonville the second time that
he would see me in Atlanta,'' Dorsett said. His father missed the
AFC Championship Game because he had commitments at the Hula Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett is replacing Marcus Robertson, who suffered a broken leg
in the second quarter of Sunday's 33-14 win over Jacksonville.
Dorsett had four tackles and one pass defensed in the second half
against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go out there and play well, I might be able to put some
of that to rest, as far as being Junior, but it's always going to
be that I'm Anthony Jr.,'' Dorsett said. ``My dad's a Hall of
Famer, Heisman Trophy winner, Super Bowl winner, Pro Bowler _
everything. Whatever you can accomplish in football, he
accomplished it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett still has a big check-off list. In four years with
Tennessee, he has distinguished himself primarily as a
special-teams player. He is one of two ``gunners'' on the punt- and
kickoff-return units; they line up near the sideline and fight a
double team while trying to get to the return specialist or force
him inside.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Dorsett was named a Pro Bowl alternate. After the
season, he becomes an unrestricted free agent, and he hopes that
his defensive work Sunday will raise his value.
</P>
<P>
   He also started at free safety on Jan. 2 while Robertson was
recovering from facial injuries incurred in a motorcycle accident.
Fittingly, the game was in Pittsburgh, where his father is still an
icon and where the son also attended college, becoming a starting
cornerback his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Hawk'' had five tackles against the Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I go home back to Pittsburgh, (his birthplace)
Aliquippa, I'm still 'Little Hawk,' '' Dorsett said; his father was
``Hawkeye'' because of his exceptional vision. ``It doesn't matter
how big I'm going to get. I'm Anthony Jr., and that's just the way
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett, now 5 feet 11 and 200 pounds, said that it wasn't until
he got to college that he began to appreciate and respect what his
father did as a 185-pound running back _ ``things that a lot of
guys can't even accomplish these days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up,'' he said, ``it was always a case where, 'That's
just my dad.' I never looked at him as being Tony Dorsett.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Dorsett doesn't lack his father's confidence.
``Basically, every time I've had a chance to get in a game and do
something, I've done well,'' he said. ``There hasn't been a
letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said, ``We've got some key backups out here that a lot
of people don't even know about.''
</P>
<P>
   With this backup-turned-starter, they at least always knew the
name.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
