<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GOLAN-HEIGHTS-MOVIE-A     01-24 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLAN-HEIGHTS-MOVIE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PEACE EFFORTS UNFOLD, ISRAELI FILMMAKER RE-ENACTS WAR OF '73
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(fb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAFAH, Golan Heights _ Under torrential rains, Israeli tanks
advanced toward Syrian territory on Monday, exhaling plumes of
smoke into the mist that draped the valley. Then they advanced
again and again _ until it was a wrap.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking shelter in a trailer, an Israeli soldier with a ragged
stump of an arm smoked a cigarette and watched idly. A makeup
artist with mud-caked boots wordlessly touched up another soldier's
chopped-meat face with red food coloring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Die! Die now!'' Amos Gitai commanded through his megaphone as
a body on a stretcher fell back inert. Under his wool cap, Gitai,
one of Israel's few internationally acclaimed filmmakers, smiled.
</P>
<P>
   For an Israeli director, cast and crew to re-enact the traumatic
October War of 1973 at a site of heavy combat is intensely
sobering. But to rev up the old Centurion tanks at the precise
moment that Israel is proceeding toward peace with Syria charges
the movie-making experience with the feeling of a historical
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could happen only once in a lifetime,'' said Shuki
Friedman, the Israeli producer for the Israeli-French-Italian
co-production. ``To shoot the Yom Kippur War on the Golan Heights
while we're talking peace with Syria _ it's like seeing 27 years
flash before your eyes and come to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kippur'' is a deeply personal film for Gitai, 49, who is a
veteran of the war. It is also believed to be the first
feature-length war movie ever made about the 1973 conflict. Every
other Israeli war provoked enough films to constitute a genre,
especially the war of 1967, which produced a sense of euphoric
invincibility in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But that feeling evaporated during the war that began six years
later on Yom Kippur, the Jewish Day of Atonement. Egyptian and
Syrian forces mounted surprise attacks on the Israeli-held Sinai
peninsula and Golan Heights and fought furiously on two fronts at
once. It has never been easy for Israelis to discuss, digest or
move beyond the war that cost them their self-assuredness and more
than 2,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Noach Faran, who commands the reserve military units
that operate the real tanks in the movie, said: ``Nobody wanted to
touch this war before. But when we're facing peace, it's the right
time to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if the peace doesn't work, there will be another war.
And the tank crews in this movie, they'll be doing the fighting for
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Gitai enlisted the army's cooperation because there was no way
to have a shootout without them. No one undertakes tanks maneuvers,
helicopter crashes and massive pyrotechnics near the Syrian border
without the active participation _ and equipment _ of the Israeli
Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no other country would we have received cooperation from
the army to make what is an antiwar movie,'' said Michel Propper, a
French producer. ``But here, as you know, the generals are on the
left.''
</P>
<P>
   The generals also knew Gitai's personal story, on which the film
is based, and they believed that it empowered him to speak with
authority, the producers said.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1973, when the sirens sounded announcing the start of
the war, Gitai was a 22-year-old architecture student in Haifa. He
piled into an old Fiat with an army buddy and drove to the Golan,
where they talked their way into a helicopter rescue unit that
swooped in and out of battles to collect the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we hurried to go to war!'' Gitai's narrator says at the
beginning of the film. ``How impatient we were! My war lasted five
days, 120 hours of blood and tears, chaos and pain, on the Golan
Heights. Something went wrong. So many wounded and dead. That's the
war I'm telling you about now. Their war. My story.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 11, Gitai's 23rd birthday, his unit was flying east to
rescue a pilot downed in Syrian territory when a missile hit the
helicopter. In a fraction of a second, the front exploded, the
co-pilot was dead, the engineer was badly wounded, the aircraft was
trembling and they were all shouting and crying, he said. He felt a
chill on his back, touched it and found his hand covered with
blood. The bullet missed his spine by a fraction of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, who was also shot, steered the helicopter back over
the Israeli line, where it crashed. The engineer was catapulted
from his seat into the engine, killing him. Another soldier, afraid
that they had landed in Syrian territory, tried to run away on what
remained of his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Gitai said, there was silence, ``almost a pastoral
silence, with birds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start of the war, I thought I'd get killed,'' he said.
``But when they shot us, I was kind of relieved because what I had
expected to happen had happened. I watched it all like a scene in a
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   A calm, soft-spoken man, Gitai talked under a tarp at his
re-created battleground, where a steady downpour had turned the
rocky clay earth into a mud swamp. The weather was fitting since he
sought to recreate the Valley of Tears in northern Golan, where the
war's worst battle was fought. After eight hours on a cold, wet
set, he seemed unfazed by the ankle-deep brown puddles and
boot-sucking gunk. As long as the cameras remained dry under their
umbrellas and the bloody severed limbs were kept in baggies, he was
happy with the fictional world he had created and controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the deal with the wounded?'' Gitai yelled. ``Can I get
a stretcher here, please? Shai, get the guy with the arm, not the
guy with the head.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tank crews refused to take directions from the director.
Gitai issued his film direction to their commander, who barked it
to them over an army radio. ``They are like goats, and I'm their
goatherd,'' Faran explained.
</P>
<P>
   Explosions on the hillside did not cause anyone on the set to
jump, but the Golan settlers were initially quite alarmed by the
battle sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The vividness of Gitai's war experience, and the questions it
raised for him, eventually led him to abandon architecture for
filmmaking so he could record and question history and ``touch
nerves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for years, Gitai said he carried his war story around inside
him, unprepared to put it on film. In the late 1970s and early
'80s, when he was making leftist documentaries that were often
censored, he did not want to be seen as using his experience to
show his Zionist credentials, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he started making feature films, he ranged broadly through
subject matter on budgets that would have been too low to produce a
good army movie. The success of his most recent film, ``Kadosh,'' a
haunting depiction of life inside a deeply Orthodox community in
Jerusalem, allowed his French producers to raise enough money _ $5
million _ to make ``Kippur.''
</P>
<P>
   When Israeli-Syrian negotiations resumed, Propper, the producer,
pushed Gitai to start filming immediately. Given the quick
turnaround time of their films, they expect to finish it by May _
``in time for Cannes and, who knows, maybe for a peace agreement,''
Gitai said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
