<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5163 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-TROUBLES-COX     01-24 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-TROUBLES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Experts see job cuts for Coke
</P>
<P>
   By Henry Unger
</P>
<P>
   and David McNaughton
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola is not immune to the ups and downs of
business nor, analysts think, reluctant to use a common solution:
downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   So don't be surprised if even an industry giant like Coca-Cola
cuts a substantial number of jobs, as many analysts expect it to do
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But while downsizing has become a fact of life on Main Street,
analysts think Coca-Cola has been slower than most in taking out
the knife. The rest of corporate America, meanwhile, was cutting an
estimated 5 million jobs in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola got around to studying its entire global business
system early last year, Morgan Stanley analyst Andrew Conway said.
He thinks Chairman M. Douglas Ivester started the review process
about nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Doug Ivester and his team spent many months assessing
global growth prospects going forward in light of the large ramp-up
in personnel between 1993 and 1998,'' Conway said. ``The global
economic crisis and the lower near-term growth prospects demand
that Coca-Cola has a more nimble cost structure.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Wall Street, said John A. Challenger, chief executive of
the Chicago-based outplacement firm Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there are few companies that don't go through some
downsizing periodically,'' Challenger said. Companies, he noted,
``are being driven by Wall Street to produce much higher earnings,
quarter by quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure _ and the planning _ for layoffs doesn't happen
immediately, Challenger said. But he added sometimes one event can
trigger the downsizing, such as a change at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ivester announced his premature retirement on Dec. 6, the
focus has shifted to the executive who will replace him in April,
Doug Daft. But analysts say there is virtually no way for Daft to
have initiated a decision to cut jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company like Coca-Cola is not going to make a move of laying
off people overnight,'' said Manny Goldman, global beverage analyst
with Merrill Lynch. ``Six weeks is overnight. This started under
Doug Ivester.''
</P>
<P>
   So why cut jobs now?
</P>
<P>
   After all, analysts are talking about the possibility of
substantial staff reductions. Some believe Coke will reduce its
29,000-member global workforce by some 2,000 jobs, including 600 in
Atlanta. The last significant layoff in Atlanta was 12 years ago,
affecting only about 200 of the company's employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's earnings have been under pressure the last
couple of years,'' Goldman said. ``When earnings get under
pressure, companies step back and look at the business. They
re-evalute it to improve the business.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, if the company does cut 2,000 jobs, it would save
about $150 milllion a year in labor costs, estimated Bill
Pecoriello, an analyst with Sanford Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   But Pecoriello said the company may be cutting jobs for a reason
beyond cost savings. He cited the consolidation in Coke's bottling
system as a driving force in the expected downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   To understand why the bottling system is crucial, it's first
important to understand how it is organized.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which is based on North Avenue, is essentially a
giant marketing machine. While it produces the syrupy concentrate
used to make Coke, Sprite and other brands, it doesn't put the
carbonation in those soft drinks, nor does it can or bottle the
product. That's done by bottlers around the world that then
distribute the drinks to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, there has been a major consolidation
in Coke's bottling system, with the big operators like
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Enterprises gobbling up many little ones
around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Pecoriello said, ``there are fewer points of
contact with the bottlers and less coordination needed from
Coca-Cola.''
</P>
<P>
   That means fewer employees may be needed. Pecoriello said the
reduction in jobs is likely to be at the field level, where
Coca-Cola's sales and marketing staff may be duplicating work now
being performed by some big bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke has a structure in place to deal with more bottlers than
they have now,'' Pecoriello added. ``Handshaking with bottlers is
much simpler now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
