<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GILLETTE-TARGET-BOS &LR;      01-24 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-TARGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
P&AMP;G DROPS QUEST FOR 2 DRUGMAKERS; GILLETTE SHARES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., which makes everything from Crest
toothpaste to Pepto-Bismol, has ended talks to buy drugmakers
Warner-Lambert Co. and American Home Products Corp., reportedly
after an earlier attempt by P&AMP;G to acquire Gillette Co. was
rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   While some Wall Street analysts think P&AMP;G will now try to buy
another pharmaceutical company, shares of Gillette stock rose 1 7/8
to close at 40 7/8 after P&AMP;G said it would no longer pursue a $140
billion stock purchase of Warner-Lambert and American Home
Products.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a historically weak stock price, Gillette may be in a
vulnerable position, and it may be an attractive target for P&AMP;G,
said analysts who follow the Boston maker of razor blades, Duracell
batteries, and other consumer products. In theory, a low stock
price might mean that Gillette could be bought for a bargain price.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette declined to comment on any speculation about a possible
acquisition. Nor would it comment on a Wall Street Journal story
Monday which reported that P&AMP;G had made an overture to Gillette
that was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Cincinnati-based P&AMP;G said the consumer-products
giant continues to look for acquisition targets, but declined to
discuss the companies it might be interested in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acquisitions are very much a part of our growth strategy,''
said P&AMP;G spokesman Simon Denegri.
</P>
<P>
   With everything seemingly up in the air, Wall Street analysts
sketched out a wide range of possible scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   One had P&AMP;G buying Warner-Lambert's portfolio of consumer
brands, which includes Schick razors, a Gillette rival. Another
suggested that P&AMP;G might consider buying Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. or
Schering-Plough Corp., two pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G chief executive Durk Jager seems intent on making an
acquisition, analysts noted. P&AMP;G sales are growing at an anemic
rate of less than 3 percent a year, and an acquisition may offer
P&AMP;G the best hope of giving sales a big boost. Jager has said that
adding more pharmaceuticals to P&AMP;G's product lines could result in
the annual sales gains of 6 to 8 percent that he is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, a P&AMP;G acquisition of Gillette might also
make sense, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   While P&AMP;G and Gillette sell different products, they sell them
to many of the same retail customers. In simplistic terms, the same
distribution system that delivers Crest toothpaste to a Wal-Mart or
a Stop &AMP; Shop could also deliver Mach3 razors and OralB
toothbrushes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, P&AMP;G had sales of about $38 billion, and Gillette had
sales of just over $10 billion. A combination of the two could
create a global consumer-goods colossus that would have the
leverage and clout to deal with giant retail chains and to more
effectively market a wide array of products. A P&AMP;G strength _
supply-chain management _ also happens to be a Gillette weakness,
noted an investor who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Two things make Gillette an attractive target for a company
large enough to swallow it, said Tony Vento, an analyst who follows
Gillette for Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's stock price is comparatively low, and Gillette owns
the dominant market position in the highly profitable and growing
businesses of razors and batteries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'd love to buy Gillette,'' Vento said of P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Gillette had a market value of about $64 billion,
but that value has declined to just under $44 billion. After
turning in double-digit earnings gains for many years, Gillette has
recently failed to meet Wall Street's expectations, and its stock
has been punished.
</P>
<P>
   Among Gillette's challenges have been stagnant economies in some
key overseas markets and the subpar performance of its stationery
and small appliance product lines, which Gillette is now looking to
sell or discontinue.
</P>
<P>
   Something else could make Gillette an attractive target for P&AMP;G,
said Fredric E. Russell of Fredric E. Russell Management Co., which
has owned shares in Gillette since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Because P&AMP;G and Gillette make such different products, it's
unlikely that an acquisition would raise federal antitrust issues,
he said. Nevertheless, Russell said he expected Gillette to resist
any advances from P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect Gillette to fight very vigorously because
Gillette is worth a lot more than $42 or $43 a share,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In ending acquisition talks with Warner-Lambert and American
Home Products, P&AMP;G cited a big drop in its own stock price since
the news of a possible deal became public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market voted with their shares by selling,'' said Phil
Larkins, a market strategist with Legacy South Inc., which owns P&AMP;G
shares. ``They acquiesced to the desires of Wall Street. I think
they made a prudent decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, P&AMP;G chief executive Jager said, ``We concluded
that the leaks and resulting speculation on a possible transaction
created have created an environment in which we cannot continue
meaningful discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
