<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FORGET IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Words in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The voters of Iowa have spoken. Don't listen.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa caucuses are about as good a barometer of what the
public thinks as that Time Internet poll that named Elvis the
Person of the Century. A sliver of the registered voters in the
30th-largest state in the nation drove to their local school or
town hall Monday night, where the Republicans had a nonbinding
straw poll. The Democrats clustered into ``viable preference
groups,'' which were then translated into ``state delegate
equivalents.'' And on the basis of that, we're supposed to believe
that Bill Bradley's candidacy ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stopstopstopstop. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The American people spent an entire century trying to wrest the
power to nominate presidential candidates out of the hands of the
party bosses, and now we're handing it over to Iowa? A state where
the most popular sporting events involve collegiate wrestling?
</P>
<P>
   If people take the Iowa results seriously, the losers will stop
getting campaign contributions, and the whole show could be over
after New Hampshire votes next week. Later, when  &UR; your &LR;  state has a
primary, nobody will come and write stories about your special
problems or peculiar taste in sports. You will not find George W.
Bush lurking at the corner coffee shop, or be quizzed about your
opinions by a reporter from Newsweek. You will not even see your
city skyline on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the current election timetable frequently point out
that African-Americans are cut out of the decision-making because
neither New Hampshire nor Iowa has many minority voters. While
that's obviously true, I've got to admit that the black residents I
ran into in Des Moines _ and they are three of the nicest folks you
ever met _ felt very strongly that as long as they were in Iowa,
they wanted it to be first.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? It's heady being the center of national attention
for something other than a school shooting. When caucus time
approaches, every special-interest group in the country starts
pouring money into the Iowa media, asking voters to think about gay
rights or teacher salaries or immigration. (This year's
anti-immigration radio ads, which opened with a sort of ``Soylent
Green'' outcry about overcrowding, warned Iowans that if something
wasn't done, their towns would wind up looking ``just like Los
Angeles.'' This does not actually seem to be a pending problem.)
</P>
<P>
   Even The Moscow Times was writing about Iowa this week _ the
Russians were fascinated with the Gary Bauer fund-raiser that
charged $250 for a visit to the eight-bedroom,
four-and-a-half-bathroom home of the McCaughey septuplets.
</P>
<P>
   The legend of the Iowa caucuses is that these are grass-roots
events that show politics the way it's supposed to be, with folks
gathering in the home of a neighbor to have wholesome arguments
about issues and the future of the Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when they were young and innocent,'' says Hugh
Winebrenner of Drake University. ``In '84, they'd say `Mondale
people in the bedroom, and Hart people go into the family room,'
and there'd be politicking and people trying to change minds and
going from one room to another. There were some great debates. Now
that doesn't take place.'' The meetings are now held in public
buildings, he says, and the focus is on getting some kind of a
quick head count that can be reported to the waiting media.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, we the media have corrupted Iowa, although in our defense
I must point out that before the packs of reporters and TV
technicians started showing up, the turnout was so low that nobody
even noticed that the democratic process was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter came in first in 1976 with under 14,000 votes _ one
commentator pointed out that you needed more than that to get
elected to the Town Council in Oyster Bay, Long Island. And the
residents don't seem to mind our crowding in. ``Thank you for
coming to Iowa,'' they keep saying, in a show of universal
politeness that is yet another sign of the state's unrepresentative
character.
</P>
<P>
   If we can't stop having presidential caucuses in January, at
minimum we ought to share the wealth, and rotate the honor of being
first among all the large, rather empty states that otherwise have
to be flooded out to get noticed. Let's hear it for North Dakota in
2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1946EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
