A5168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFC-RUNOFFE     01-24 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFC-RUNOFFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Runyan supplies Bunyan-like force
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many people have thought that the NFL's top offensive
tackles played in the AFC Central the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville Jaguars' Tony Boselli and Leon Searcy have been
regarded as the league's best pair of offensive tackles since
Searcy joined the team as an unrestricted free agent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tennessee Titans offensive tackles Brad Hopkins and
Jon Runyan have played in relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   But the Titans allowed only 25 sacks this season, third-fewest
in the league and 11 fewer than the Jaguars surrendered in 16
games. The Titans' offensive line also opened holes for running
back Eddie George, who rushed for a career-best 1,304 yards this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as notoriety and as far as recognition for doing the
job, it's going to always elude Jon and I, because we're just
blue-collar workers,'' Hopkins said. ``Maybe, if we went and
slapped old ladies around or kicked kids, we'd get in the papers.
We just don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan, 6 feet 7 and 320 pounds, is a budding star in his third
season as the starting right tackle. An All-Big Ten selection at
Michigan in 1995, Runyan left school with one year of eligibility
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Because of concerns about his quickness and pass-blocking
ability, Runyan slipped to the fourth round of the 1996 draft. He
was chosen by the Titans, then the Houston Oilers, with the 109th
pick overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of got under my skin a little bit,'' said Runyan, 26.
``I still haven't figured out why it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan arrived in Houston with the reputation of being a
powerful run-blocker. During his first mini-camp, he bench-pressed
315 pounds only six times, could not do a single dip and showed
little speed.
</P>
<P>
   He improved his strength and speed on special teams as a rookie,
before winning the right tackle job after veteran Irv Eatman
retired before the '97 season. Runyan beat out former Tennessee
star Jason Layman, who was picked two rounds ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Runyan has started 48 games in a row the past three seasons. On
Dec. 20, 1998, he held former Packers defensive end Reggie White
sackless in his final game at Green Bay's Lambeau Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both physical guys, especially Jon,'' George said.
``They just love to play the game. They don't get a lot of
recognition, for reasons I don't know, but they do a great job
run-blocking and pass-protecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Runyan will be one of the the top unrestricted free agents
during the offseason. After falling in the draft, he earned an
average of $252,500 in his first three seasons. He made $1.2
million this season after signing a one-year contract. He stands to
make much more than that next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sit there and complain about not getting any
recognition,'' Runyan said. ``You have to go out and earn respect
just by working hard and playing hard every game. You do that, the
other things will either come or they won't. It all works out in
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
