u w BC-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      01-24 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PUTS FIRST FOCUS ON CUBAN BOY
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Va., Vt., R.I., Ill., Mass., Fla.)  (With CUBAN-BOY) 
(nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress returned to work Monday after a two-month
recess, with House Democrats wounded by the defection of one of
their most conservative members, Virgil H. Goode Jr. of Virginia,
and lawmakers from both parties introducing bills to make Elian
Gonzalez a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could vote on the citizenship bill as early as
Wednesday. Goode said he is switching to be an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's events foreshadowed a campaign-compressed calendar that
is likely to be defined less by momentous legislative
accomplishments than by election-year trench warfare and narrowly
focused bills with popular, even emotional, appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Little floor action is expected until President Clinton delivers
his State of the Union address on Thursday. The Senate has its
first vote on Tuesday, on whether to cut off debate on a bill to
overhaul the nation's bankruptcy laws, legislation that was held
over from last year. The House has no votes scheduled this week.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on Capitol Hill, many of the issues that will dominate
debate _ tax cuts, protecting Social Security, reducing the
national debt _ get their first official airing of the new year
when the Congressional Budget Office releases new estimates on the
federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Budget Committee will hold hearings Tuesday and
Wednesday to review the updated projections, which will be bigger
than anticipated for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The budget office will brief congressional staffers on the
estimates late Tuesday, and the numbers will be officially unveiled
when the office director, Dan Crippen, testifies before the budget
committee on Wednesday. On the same day, the Senate Banking
Committee will hold a hearing on the nomination of Alan Greenspan
to a fourth term as chairman of the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate focus of Congress this week is the fate of the
6-year-old Cuban boy who survived an accident last November that
killed his mother as they and others tried to make their way to the
United States in a boat that capsized. Elian was rescued after
clinging to an inner tube at sea for two days.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic and Republican lawmakers introduced three bills _ two
in the House and one in the Senate _ to grant Elian citizenship or
permanent residency. They said their legislation would put the
decision in the hands of a Florida state judge instead of the
federal Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who sponsored the Senate bill with
five other lawmakers, said he wanted to take politics out of the
decision. But state judges in Florida are elected, and any judge in
the Miami area, where Elian is living with relatives, is likely to
face tremendous pressure to rule that the boy stay in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the lead sponsor of a companion bill, Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla., said, ``Any decision made by a governmental
agency is contrary to his best interest and clearly against his
mother's desires.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill proposed by House Democrats, including Robert Menendez of
New Jersey and Patrick J. Kennedy of Rhode Island, would grant
permanent residency instead of citizenship, to allow Elian to
decide his citizenship on his own when he is older.
</P>
<P>
   But another group of House members, including Charles B. Rangel,
D-N.Y., Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Ray LaHood, R-Ill., introduced a
nonbinding resolution to block the citizenship bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that this 6-year-old boy who lost his
mother in a tragic accident at sea should be reunited with his
father,'' Rangel said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers jousted over the boy's future, House Democrats
suffered a setback to their goal of reclaiming the chamber when
Goode announced he would run for re-election to a third term as an
independent.
</P>
<P>
   On major bills, Goode has voted more often with Republicans than
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Republicans outnumber Democrats 222-211, with two
independents, Goode and Rep. Bernard Sanders of Vermont, who
usually votes with the Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1947EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
