<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-RECRUITING-COX     01-24 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RECRUITING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    College recruiting can become a tangled web on the Internet
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing up in Cullman, Ala., Wesley Britt was an Auburn fan.
Britt grew and became one of the top high school offensive linemen
in the Southeast and attracted attention from a lot of other
schools, in addition to Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   During the recruiting process, the 6-foot-7, 289-pound Britt
backed away from Auburn, and said his final two choices were
Florida and Alabama. But on the Internet, in chat rooms across the
Southeast, it was written that Wesley's father, Tommy Britt, had
gotten into an argument with an Auburn professor. The story
specified where the alleged altercation took place and on which
football weekend the Britts had visited.
</P>
<P>
   Only problem was, the Britts were nowhere near Auburn that
weekend, and Tommy Britt had no argument with anybody at Auburn; he
has yet to meet his supposed antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine,'' said Wesley's mother, Vera Britt. ``There
were all kinds of rumors going around when Wesley backed away from
Auburn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Britts are typical of a family with a child going through
the recruiting process in college football. With eight days until
the Feb. 2 national signing day, the Britts and other families are
discovering that rumors appear to be picking up more steam as the
Internet has become a major player in the recruiting game.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Britt determined that the Internet was one of the ways she
could find out what was going on in recruiting, and she quickly
became proficient on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would check out the school's history, the coaching staff,
who a particular school was recruiting,'' she said. ``I felt the
more we knew, the better decision Wesley could make.''
</P>
<P>
   Darius Williams, a senior at Avondale High in DeKalb County,
used the Internet to his advantage as he was contemplating his
college choice. The 6-6 tight end ultimately decided on Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see who else had committed, what position they
played, and who else the schools were looking at,'' he said. ``I
was on it today, and I down-loaded a picture of myself. I've become
a fan of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Andrews, rated the 16th-best defensive back in the
country, says he uses the Internet to check out what people and
schools are saying about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to find myself and other players in the state of
Florida,'' said Andrews, a Tallahassee native. ``I looked at it to
see where I was needed the most. Alabama needed help in the
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, don't put much stock into the Internet as a
means of recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would look at it from time to time, but I didn't get into it
that much,'' said Houston County senior Hobie Holiday, who
committed to Georgia Tech on Monday. ``I know a lot of people get
into it, but for me it came down to where I felt comfortable
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill O'Brien, the recruiting coordinator at Georgia Tech, says
the Internet has been both a blessing and a curse.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much is going around on recruiting (on the Internet),''
O'Brien said. ``If you're recruiting, let's say, a wide receiver
and the kid finds out that you're recruiting three other receivers,
he'll want to know what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always explaining things. The Internet helps and it
hinders.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama recruiting coordinator Ronnie Cottrell, rated as one of
the top recruiters in the nation, says he's very aware of what's
happening on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that there are very few secrets, because of
the Internet,'' Cottrell said. ``In a matter of minutes, you can
get good solid information from a university's Web site, but there
are so many Web sites out there that deal in rumors, and many times
the recruits get misled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very rarely go in for a home visit when I'm not confronted
with something they've seen or heard on the Internet,'' he said.
``I'm always having to dispel some rumor. And it's very seldom
positive; it's usually negative.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wesley Britt cut his choices to Florida and Alabama, he
initially said that Alabama was in the lead. ``I got on the chat
rooms for Alabama and Florida,'' Wesley said. ``The fans just talk
to each other, and they seemed like they knew me.''
</P>
<P>
   The winds of recruiting can change fast, as Wesley found out.
``One time, when Alabama was in the lead, people at Florida said
things (on the Internet) like, `That's all right; we don't need
people from Alabama, anyway.' And another one said, `People from
Alabama should stay the hell out of Florida.'''
</P>
<P>
   But then the younger Britt decided that perhaps Florida was the
best place for him. ``Florida had fair-weather fans,'' he said.
``They started liking me again. But the Alabama fans said nice
things the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Britt has committed to the Crimson Tide and said he
is firm in that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Britt says the Internet recruiting grapevine amazes her
still. ``After Wesley got off the phone to tell Alabama he was
coming and to tell Florida he wasn't,'' she said, ``I went upstairs
to post it on the Internet, and it was already on the Internet. How
could that be? How could they know that quickly?''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that she took the opportunity to tell people
Wesley's side of the story. ``I wouldn't post anything while Wesley
was still going through the recruiting process,'' she said. ``As
soon as he committed, I went in to set some people straight. I told
them the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is there's a lot of misinformation out
there,'' said Lance Thompson, former Georgia Tech recruiting
coordinator and now defensive-line coach at Alabama. ``But
sometimes it's useful. A lot of these kids will tell a recruiting
analyst something they might not want to tell a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans get on the Internet and run down other schools,''
Thompson said. ``When I go see somebody, I tell them I work for the
University of Alabama, and I talk about our school. It's hard
enough for me to keep up with what's going on at our place, much
less worry about what other schools are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the Internet is almost entertainment,'' Thompson said.
``The thing I find amusing is that people rate kids and give them
numerical value, but they're just making money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's written down, we have to answer to that,'' Cottrell
said. ``It's something about having it written on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is just another scource of information for me,''
O'Brien said. ``I'm seeing what people are saying. Sometimes you
learn what to address and what not to say. The way I see it,
there's no disadvantage to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
