<SLUG> BC-TV-MIDSEASON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WINGS FOR MIDSEASON 
(ACCOMPANIES TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX)
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
What's coming up for midseason:
Clerks, ABC
<TEXT>
<P>
   Animated version of Kevin Smith's theatrical movie about a pair
of buddies stuck in dead-end convenience- and video-store gigs. Was
funny at the theaters to the independent crowd. But network TV? And
animation?
</P>
<P>
   Wonderland, ABC
</P>
<P>
   Straightforward, hour-long drama examining the staff and
patients of a psychiatric hospital. Peter Berg of Chicago Hope fame
is executive producer. A hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Me, ABC
</P>
<P>
   Kyra Sedgwick is a radio talk-show host who lives with her
sister and pals around with her radio colleagues. Traditional
sitcom; Sedgwick is charming.
</P>
<P>
   Then Came You, ABC
</P>
<P>
   Sitcom about a thirtysomething woman and her twentysomething
beau was on the fall schedule. ABC couldn't be that high on this.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine, CBS
</P>
<P>
   Single-camera sitcom that once aired in 1992. It returns with
new batch of twentysomething stars. Kristy Swanson is in it. The
pilot was interesting, and different.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone, CBS
</P>
<P>
   FBI agent goes undercover. Jason Gedrick is the Fed who puts his
life on the line as mob informant. In post-Sopranos world, this
seems like a lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   M.Y.O.B., NBC
</P>
<P>
   Precocious teen-ager rooms with uptight high school principal
who may or may not be her aunt. Teen-agers will relate to the sassy
teen; parents will write the network in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   The Others, NBC
</P>
<P>
   Ragtag team of supernatural thrill seekers. They communicate
with the dead to solve the problems of the living.
</P>
<P>
   God, the Devil and Bob, NBC
</P>
<P>
   Animated fantasy about a guy who, like the Others, enjoys close
relations with ``the other side.'' God looks like Jerry Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy, NBC
</P>
<P>
   Animated parody of Hollywood focusing on a hot young actor and
his estranged father.
</P>
<P>
   Battery Park, NBC
</P>
<P>
   Cop comedy in the spirit of Barney Miller. Stars Elizabeth
Perkins as a hard-edged police captain.
</P>
<P>
   Titus, Fox
</P>
<P>
   Written and produced by Christopher Titus, and based on his
one-man show about his dysfunctional family. If you liked Married
With Children, you'll like this.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Blues, WB
</P>
<P>
   Animated series about parents with children trying to get from
one day to another without going mad.
</P>
<P>
   Brutally Normal, WB
</P>
<P>
   Single-camera series about a group of high school friends in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   D.C., WB
</P>
<P>
   Five college grads looking to change the world come to
Washington, D.C., to work in politics, news media, law, etc.
Produced by Dick Wolf ``(Law and Order)'' with WB sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Young Americans, WB
</P>
<P>
   New England boys' prep school is the setting for this serial,
which focuses on a group of friends, including a girl who's
attending the all-boys school as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The Beat, UPN
</P>
<P>
   Traditional cop show spiced up with unusual visuals. Produced by
Tom Fontana ``(Homicide),'' who uses his gritty sensibilities in
story lines. But the camera work is MTV.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
