<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-SBOWL-HUMMER-COX     01-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SBOWL-HUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Super Bowl 2000: A tale of at least four cities
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let us unfurl the Super Bowl banner across Atlanta's
Peachtree Street, saluting the participating owners and their happy
followers:
</P>
<P>
   Welcome Carpetbaggers!
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta used to treat this breed of opportunist like the boll
weevil. Now the city bids for their presence and parties them up
for a solid week.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Cleveland-Los Angeles-Anaheim-St. Louis Rams vs. the
Houston-Memphis-Nashville Titans. You can figure out all of Martin
Sheen's kids easier than untangling the family tree of this game.
</P>
<P>
   The first Super Bowl of the 2000s is the perfect working model
of what professional sport has become _ a business where they pack
loyalty in bubble wrap and move it along to the next bunch of
personal seat license-buying saps. And isn't Atlanta the perfect
setting for the first Relocation Bowl, being that most everyone
here understands what it is to be from somewhere else?
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Frontiere and Bud Adams _ never married but often linked
to what's wrong in the NFL _ find themselves justified by the
events of this week. The lesson is clear. No amount of aimless
wandering, past meddling, or hard-hearted brokering of their teams
can keep an NFL owner from his or her turn at the Super Bowl head
table.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Fronteire if she felt for those left behind in
Southern California in 1995. ``The fans can still watch on TV. They
were watching on TV and not coming to the games anyway,'' she
reportedly answered. Once more, the bouquet she tossed them was
more thorns than roses.
</P>
<P>
   How appropriate that Adams, who started up the AFL Oilers in
Houston in 1959 and eventually moved them to Tennessee in 1997, got
to the Super Bowl through Jacksonville. He had long history of
playing that city. Back in 1987, he teased those desperate folk
with the idea of moving the Oilers to the bank of St. John's. But
once Adams wrangled a few concessions from Houston, he dropped
Jacksonville like a one-night stand.
</P>
<P>
   Both owners have been easy targets. Frontiere for her
eccentricities since inheriting the team upon the drowning death of
one of her former husbands. Adams for the shameless shopping of his
team. Then they discovered what the Atlanta Falcons' Smith family
did _ just leave the on-field stuff to football minds and
everything eventually will work out. Now it is their moment to try
on the strange role of beloved and benevolent overseers.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a Super Bowl tale of at least four cities. As amazing as
it is that St. Louis and Tennessee are here, it is just as stunning
that anyone in the jilted cities would celebrate. It would seem
like paying alimony to the ex-wife, even after she remarried. But
some did (a Houston Chronicle poll last weekend showed two-thirds
of the respondents rooting for the Titans).
</P>
<P>
   Each year now the Pro Football Hall of Fame honors one fan from
each franchise considered to be the most devoted.
</P>
<P>
   This year's addition to the Visa Hall of Fans for the St. Louis
Rams was a house painter from Santa Monica, Calif. Lance Goldberg
used to go L.A. Rams games with a carved watermelon on his head.
When he got married, he wore a Rams sticker on the sole of his
shoe, to flash it when kneeling at the alter. He was in the Trans
World Dome Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall's representative for the Tennessee Titans was a trucker
from outside Houston. Edward Gifford took a load to Jacksonville
last weekend so he could attend the AFC Championship, just as he
works it for all the Titans home games. He's angling for one that
will get him to Atlanta, no matter that he has no ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed like everyone else (when the Oilers bugged
out),'' Gifford explained . ``But I still didn't want to root for
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some kind of loves you just can't stomp out, no matter
how big the boot.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
