<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-STATUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONUMENTAL DEBATE RAGES OVER PROPOSED CONFEDERATE STATUE IN TEXAS
TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSON, Texas _ Since 1994, Dal Dreher has sought a statue of
a Confederate soldier for the tiny grounds of the Grimes County
Courthouse, facing south in honor of Civil War dead.
</P>
<P>
   He has raised more than $30,000 for a six-foot bronze
infantryman gripping a rifle that could be replaced with a
Confederate flag on special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But of late, Dreher's efforts have been blasted by black
ministers and others who believe the statue symbolically looks to
the past as an unwarranted reminder of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   And the passionate skirmish could force Gov. George W. Bush to
face a debate he has sidestepped in his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Bush has not got involved in the debate over the
Confederate flag flying atop the South Carolina Capitol. That is a
state's rights issue that doesn't warrant outsider opinion, he has
stated.
</P>
<P>
   But in Bush's home state, if Dreher and his compatriots with the
Grimes County Greys are to get the statue they desire, they must
get permission from the Texas Historical Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Dreher was scheduled to make his formal application to the
commission staff Tuesday. But late Monday afternoon, the meeting
was postponed until next week so Commission Executive Director F.
Lawrence could attend, a commission official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something of this magnitude or importance needs the attention
of the executive director,'' said commission acting deputy director
Terry Colley.
</P>
<P>
   If the staff rejects it, Dreher said he will appeal to the
18-member commission, which includes 12 Bush appointees. A
spokeswoman for Bush said the governor has no formal position on
the statue nor will he influence the historical commission's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's governing style is to appoint capable and
qualified people to the hundreds of state boards and commissions,
and trust them to make the best decisions for the state of Texas,''
said spokeswoman Linda Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Frying eggs sunny-side up in his grandmother's iron skillet last
week, Dreher, 72, is surrounded by the past in his home near
Singleton, 10 miles east of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   He lives on the last square mile of 32 square miles of a former
cotton plantation his German ancestors bought for 10 cents an acre
in 1852 after moving from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The aging wood from a former family home covers his current
house. On a window sill overlooking the back yard rests an oil lamp
Dreher used to read by at night as a child. A shelf is filled with
history books, many about the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Dreher believes that once again, the South will
lose because of the pressures mounting against the statue.
</P>
<P>
   And that's unfair, said Dreher, commander of the Grimes County
Greys camp of the Sons of Confederate Veterans. The statue is meant
to honor his forefathers, not trump up white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   He displays a bumper sticker with a Confederate flag and the
phrase ``Heritage Not Hate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so wrong for hate groups to use this flag for their
purposes,'' Dreher said. ``When I see the (Ku Klux) Klan using it,
I want to walk up and physically remove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This statue is to honor those people who fought for their
land,'' he said, noting that more people from Grimes County died in
the Civil War than all other wars combined. ``If we don't defend
our heritage, then we will lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a common belief among local minorities that Dreher and
most Greys are not racially motivated, black leaders here say you
cannot strip the racist connotations from the statue or the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``It upsets those who have had their parents and their parents
and their parents tell them about slavery,'' said the Rev. James
Mable of the Missionary Camp Baptist Camp and vice president of the
Grimes County Ministers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Eating a cheeseburger in his small house, Mable said he holds no
animosity toward Dreher, who he believes is well-intentioned. In
Mable's back yard is a float the 43-year-old preacher and farm
worker used in the town's recent Martin Luther King Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Mable and his allies have drawn some criticism for opposing the
statue only in recent weeks, because the Grimes County
commissioners approved the concept six years ago _ contingent upon
the Greys getting state approval and raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Only two weeks ago did a more organized opposition come from the
ministers' group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's wrong, then it's wrong and it shouldn't be at the
courthouse,'' Mable said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rhetoric in Grimes County, the debate will be
settled in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Texas Historical Commission helped fund a previous
renovation of the courthouse, it must approve all future changes.
</P>
<P>
   In a Nov. 16 letter to County Judge Ira E. ``Bud'' Haynie, a
commission staffer criticized the proposal because it would clutter
the grounds of the small courthouse. The 1894 building is somewhat
an island with just 15 feet of land between it and a surrounding
road. The staffer suggested the statue be placed in a nearby park,
which offers more space.
</P>
<P>
   Haynie, Mable and other Grimes County residents have no problem
with placing the statue elsewhere, as the commission staffer
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't mind if it's in a cemetery or park, but not at the
courthouse where we have to go every day,'' Mable said. ``It's
offensive there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dreher said it would force him to return money he has
gathered on the promise the monument would be placed on the
courthouse grounds. He contends the commission staff is using the
issue of space to cloak the bigger racial concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In Dreher's mind, that is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Confederate statues and memorials sit on government land in 62
sites across Texas, including three on the state Capitol grounds
and six at the University of Texas at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state distributes a flier with a map showing
Civil War museums and related sites.
</P>
<P>
   Dreher, who has advertised his project as ``the last Confederate
memorial'' in fund-raising efforts, says it will be harder and
harder to win approval for such projects ``as the wave of political
correctness covers the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are losing so many of our freedoms, and this is one of
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has stirred up heartburn for residents of this
community an hour's drive northwest of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in Navasota, the county's largest city with about 20,000
people, fear racial discourse could make it difficult to lure
businesses and residents from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And there is another factor at work.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes County is competing with other counties for a grant to
renovate its aging courthouse. County Judge Haynie, whose wife,
Joy, has spearheaded the renovation project, believes the
commission might be shy to grant money if the statue is placed
there.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists hope to get another $50 million from the Texas
Legislature in 2001. If the historical commission gives Grimes
County a grant after the statue is erected, black legislators might
oppose future funding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This statue came up at the wrong time,'' Haynie said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
