</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE MOVES TO GIVE CUBAN BOY US CITIZENSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerned for the little boy's plight and not
unmindful of the political clout of the Cuban-American lobby,
Congress returned Monday from a long recess with plans to make
six-year-old Elian Gonzalez a US citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the GOP-controlled Senate said they intended to
indefinitely block the child's return to Cuba by exercising its
very rarely used power to pass a law granting citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure, known as a ``private bill,'' is on a fast
track, and a vote on it could come as early as Wednesday. Sponsors
said they thought its prospects for passing were good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this bill is to move the decision-making about
the little boy's future out of the hands of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service and into the hands of the courts,'' said
Senator Connie Mack, a Florida Republican who introduced
legislation that would make Elian a citizen, Mack said, to protect
his best interests.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say Congress has acted on citizenship bills only
for the most extraordinary individuals _ to honor Winston Churchill
or Mother Teresa, for example _ or in noncontroversial cases, where
lawmakers have unanimously agreed on the need to cut red tape.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has never granted citizenship to a six-year-old,
particularly one whose parent hasn't requested it and whose case is
anything but noncontroversial.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was rescued off the Florida coast Nov. 25 after the boat
that had brought him from Cuba capsized, killing his mother and 10
other exiles. Ever since, he has been a symbol and a celebrity and
pulled between two political forces: the strong anti-Castro,
Cuban-American lobby, which protests his return to communist Cuba,
and the Clinton administration, which hoped to quietly settle the
case so it wouldn't ruin its efforts to improve relations with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The INS, an arm of the US Justice Department, reviewed the
situation and the law and ruled on Jan. 4 that Elian should be
returned to Cuba and placed in the custody of his father. Lawyers
for the boy's relatives in Miami, backed by the Cuban American
National Foundation, have sued the Justice Department to keep the
child in the United States and want a Florida family court to grant
the family custody.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Monday the president
would ``wait and see what they have in mind before making any
decisions'' on whether to sign or veto a citizenship bill. But he
warned Congress to be cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a real danger here that this can become a
political issue, that this young boy will be a political
football,'' Lockhart said,``and I think the president has made it
very clear to everyone that they ought to stay away from politics
and stick to what the facts and the law dictate.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics are, of course, central to the case, but the fault
lines on the emergency legislation aren't strictly partisan. Mack's
bill has the blessing of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott plus the
sponsorship of Democrats Bob Graham of Florida; Robert Torricelli
of New Jersey, who chairs the party's Senate re-election committee;
and Charles Robb of Virginia, who is in a tough race against a
conservative opponent this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Majority Whip Tom DeLay has joined with three
Florida Republicans to propose a version of the citizenship bill,
while three Democrats, including Representative Patrick Kennedy of
Rhode Island, Monday offered a bill that would grant permanent
residency status to the little boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS decision to return Elian Gonzalez to Cuba did not give
him the opportunity to exercise his legal options or to have a day
in court,'' said Kennedy, who chairs the Democrats' House
re-election committee and has made no secret that he thinks Castro
was behind the assassination of President Kennedy, his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the various bills say that if Elian is a US citizen,
the federal government will lose its jurisdiction to treat his as
an immigration case and then a state court will be free to settle
it as a custody issue. Mack says his legislation ``doesn't dictate
an outcome,'' but it is clear that he has strong personal feelings
about where the boy belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard for me to believe that a court in the United
States, the freest country in the world, would make a decision
saying that they think its in the best interest of the little boy
to go back to Cuba, a totalitarian country, where he will be told
by the state what he will learn, what he can speak, what he can
believe, and what he'll become.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Keely, a professor of international migration at
Georgetown University, says the ``citizenship gambit'' on Capitol
Hill comes because many members of Congress are frustrated with the
government decision to return Elian. They disagree with it and
understand it was properly made under the law. ``This is clearly an
end run around the INS, and everyone knows it is purely
political,'' Keely said.
</P>
<P>
   Keely believes that granting citizenship to the six-year-old may
not solve the problem for Elian's Miami family, since his next of
kin _ his father in Cuba _ would have to request or accept for
Elian the new status that Congress by law conveyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
