<SLUG> BC-STATES-WIFE-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        Damages limited by judge, not by husband's bill   By Laura
J. Winter   c. 2000 States News Service   WASHINGTON (January, 24)
<TEXT>
- A Virginia judge said Karen Santorum's pain and suffering
amounted to $175,000, half of what the jury awarded Karen Santorum,
wife of Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., in a medical malpractice
lawsuit.
<P>
   Virginia Judge Arthur Vieregg, calling the original award of
$350,000 ``excessive,'' set it aside. He then order the senator's
wife to settle the suit or face a new trial to determine the
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum has accepted the $175,000, but it has not been
confirmed whether she will seek the other half at a later date. She
sued the Virginia chiropractor claiming the specialist had caused
serious injury to her back.
</P>
<P>
   In December, when the jury set the damages, Senate democrats
labeled their Pennsylvania colleague a hypocrite, pointing to his
1994 campaign. As one of his centerpiece issues, the freshman
senator said he would seek legislation that would cap all
non-monetary damages in medical malpractice lawsuits at $250,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
