<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-ELECT-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUNOFF IN CROATIA'S PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION SCHEDULED FOR FEB. 7 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: References to Tuesday in this Prague-datelined story are
correct.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ A witty former communist leader took a
commanding lead in voting on Monday to replace the late president
of Croatia, Franjo Tudjman. But results released early Tuesday
morning mean that a runoff will be necessary between the two top
finishers.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff, on Feb. 7, will be between the front-runner, Stipe
Mesic, and another opposition politician, Drazen Budisa, who came
in second. The winner has to gain an absolute majority of the votes
cast.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing badly in third place was Foreign Minister Mate Granic,
candidate of Tudjman's once-dominant Croatian Democratic Union,
which ran the country since it became independent after Tito's
Yugoslavia splintered in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In results were issued by the state electoral commission early
Tuesday morning. With 95 percent of the votes counted, Mesic had
41.6 percent, Budisa 28 percent and Granic 21.7 percent. The
fourth-place finisher, Slaven Letica, a writer and independent
candidate, took 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All three main candidates, out of the nine who ran, promised an
open, democratic Croatia, less authoritarian and fervently
nationalist, with closer ties to the European Union and the United
States. All also promised to dismantle part of the monarchic
all-powerful presidency that Tudjman left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of kitsch culture,'' Budisa said. ``Medals,
pomp, presidential guard. All of that will have to be abolished.''
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's party thus suffered a second crippling defeat, having
lost parliamentary elections on Jan. 3 to a six-party opposition
coalition. The party was so badly wounded, after having so
throughly dominated Croatia, that Granic, a moderate in the party,
had pledged in the campaign to quit all his party posts if he won
the election. He had ignored Western advice to run as an
independent, and he suffered badly from his connection to a party
beleaguered by economic difficulties, recession, an overvalued
currency, high unemployment and widespread corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly likely that Budisa, 51, a nationalist and a former
dissident, will pick up many of Granic's votes. But it will be
difficult for him to deny Mesic victory next month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, the nationalist strain in Croatian life is strong and
will not be easily ignored by the new leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's aggressive nationalism isolated Croatia from the
European mainstream. He was reluctant to cooperate fully with the
tribunal in The Hague that works on war crimes in the former
Yugoslavia, refusing to hand over specific indictees, often on
medical grounds. Zagreb also intervened in Bosnia, financing and
promoting a separate Bosnian Croat entity despite formal support
for the Muslim-Croat federation that Washington demanded.
</P>
<P>
   All of Tudjman's likely successors promised to cooperate more
fully with the tribunal, to allow Serbian refugees who fled to
return more easily and to stop meddling in Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
