A5182 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HEIDRICK-MARKETPLACE-     01-24 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEIDRICK-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETPLACE: EQUITY AS SERVICE FEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of Internet-based companies remain the currency of the
realm in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Neoforma.com kicked off the 2000 season for dot.com stock
offerings Monday and the deal looked like another bonanza for a
variety of investors and suppliers who got in ahead of the general
public, including the firm that found the company's chief
executive, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles International. Shares of Neoforma,
a start-up that operates electronic marketplaces for new and used
medical equipment, tripled to $52.375 in their first day of trading
on the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   That gain showed that investors haven't lost their voracious
appetite for new Internet stocks and it could translate into a huge
payday for Heidrick &AMP; Struggles. When the time came last fall for
Neoforma to pay Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, a Chicago-based executive
search firm, for recruiting Robert Zollars, a seasoned health care
industry executive, the search firm accepted a cash fee plus a
bundle of equity in the young company.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for top executive search firms traditionally run to about
one-third of an executive's first-year cash compensation. In
Zollars' case, that would have amounted to about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   But, as on Wall Street, in Silicon Valley cash salary and
bonuses often amount to less than half of a chief executive's total
compensation. So, on top of its traditional fee, Heidrick &AMP;
Struggles has often demanded equity equal to one-third of the
executive's stock and options that vest in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   For placing Zollars, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles received a warrant
convertible into 436,623 shares of Neoforma stock at 10 cents a
share. As of Monday's close, that warrant was worth about $22.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd probably choose column B here,'' said John Thompson, a
vice chairman of Heidrick &AMP; Struggles in Menlo Park, Calif., who
recruited Zollars away from a senior management position at
Cardinal Health.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he had accepted a mix of cash and equity for all
of the searches he has conducted for more than two years. All told,
Heidrick &AMP; Struggles has taken equity stakes in more than 70
companies and has commitments for equity in another 200 searches it
is conducting. The firm has sold shares in less than 10 of those
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Neoforma stake ``is one of the larger ones and, hopefully,
it's going to be worth a lot more,'' Thompson said. He said that
Heidrick &AMP; Struggles can't sell its Neoforma shares for several
months because they are subject to the same restrictions as shares
held by the company's managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want an opportunity to participate in the long-term
performance of the CEOs we place,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the firm, which itself went public last year, is taking
a gamble every time it accepts stock in an untested company instead
of cash. Heidrick &AMP; Struggles sometimes hedges its bets, however,
according to a prospectus for a 3 million share secondary stock
offering it is currently marketing. In the case of one company that
paid Heidrick &AMP; Struggles with a warrant, Covad Communications, the
firm used stock options to limit the potential decline in the value
of its stake. Still, Heidrick &AMP; Struggles took in more than $10
million for recruiting that company's chief executive in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good strategy on their part,'' said Tom O'Halloran,
an analyst at Warburg Dillon Read. ``It's part of a trend among
professsional-service firms to either invest cash in companies or
take warrants from them in addition to the standard fee, or, in
lieu of fees.''
</P>
<P>
   So far for Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, O'Halloran said, ``this has not
shown up as a big number on their financials but it could very well
be a big number at some point in the future.'' If the firm proves
it can repeatedly reap big gains from these stakes, investors will
place a higher value on the firm's shares, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some top executives of Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, including its chief
executive, Patrick S. Pittard, plan to sell shares in the firm's
secondary offering. But Thompson, who owns more than 1 percent of
the firm, is hanging on. ``I'm predicting it's going to be a major
part of our company's financial future,'' Thompson said of the
practice of accepting equity for fees.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Thompson and his colleagues believe so strongly in their
ability to pick winners among managers and companies that Heidrick
&AMP; Struggles is branching out into the venture capital business.
Borrowing a stratagem used by investment banks, the firm plans to
use $25 million of its own money and its employees' money to start
a fund that will invest in private companies, primarily those that
hire Heidrick &AMP; Struggles to find executives for them.
</P>
<P>
   O'Halloran said investing in companies ``presents a conflict of
interest, but it could be a tool to strengthen client relationships
and could be an effective tool to recruit'' its own employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
