<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS DROP AMID FEARS OF HIGHER INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices fell sharply in very heavy trading
Monday, as investors shed positions in a wide array of sectors,
especially technology, in advance of meetings next week that are
expected to produce an increase in short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about a move by the Federal Reserve Board to raise
interest rates have preyed on the stock market for weeks, but share
prices climbed early in the session _ with the Dow up more than 100
points. The selloff began abruptly at around midday. Other than
worries about the Fed, there were no adverse developments during
the session that were seen as factors in the steep decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks are not going down because of bad news,'' said Thomas
M. Galvin, chief investment strategist at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We remain in a volatile marketplace, and when you
are at high valuations and stub your toe, people want to make a
quick run for the exits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average recorded its fifth consecutive
loss, falling 243.54 points, or 2.2 percent, to 11,008.17. During
the morning, the Dow was up as much as 113 points. Big blue-chip
names like General Electric, Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Wal-Mart Stores
led the decline.
</P>
<P>
   High-flying technology issues like Cisco Systems, Oracle and
Qualcomm pulled the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index down 39.83
points, or 2.8 percent, to 1,401.53. At one point during the
morning, the S&AMP;P 500 was up more than 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was hammered, falling 139.32 points,
or 3.3 percent to 4,096.08. The drop was the third-biggest point
loss ever for the index, and came on a day when trading volume on
the Nasdaq stock market hit a record 1.96 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the vast majority of investors thought the
Nasdaq could get to this point,'' said Thomas M. O'Neill, chief
investment officer at Fleet Boston Investment Advisors. ``Now
Nasdaq has had a comeuppance.''
</P>
<P>
   Small cap stocks, which recently have been outperforming
companies with much larger market valuations, were pummeled as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small cap stocks fell 10.99, or 2.1
percent, to 522.95.
</P>
<P>
   The selling was broadly-based: Stocks that fell in price
outnumbered those that gained by a ratio of nearly 2-to-1 on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the action magnified underlying trends that were
apparent last week but were masked by further advances in
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excluding about 35 technology names, last week was a very
sloppy week for the market,'' said Jonathan Olesky, head of block
trading at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``Now you are getting a
continuation of the weakness that is being felt very broadly across
the whole market.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were reluctant to speculate how long the selling might
continue, or how severely stock prices might fall.
</P>
<P>
   But they noted that with Federal Reserve Board policy-makers
scheduled to hold important meetings next week, investors are
likely to remain on edge.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely expected that Fed governors will vote to push up
short-term interest rates at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Market interest rates actually fell a bit Monday, a development
that could have bolstered stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, interest-sensitive financial-service stocks were
victimized by Monday's downdraft along with many others.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter slumped 4{, to 128. Citigroup dropped
1\, to 55 3/16. And American International Group fell 2 3/8, to 101
9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, General Electric was a big loser. It fell 6,
to 138[. Johnson &AMP; Johnson dropped 6 3/16, to 83 11/16. And
Wal-Mart declined 3 1/16, to 59].
</P>
<P>
   There were small pockets of strength.
</P>
<P>
   Intel gained ~ to 98 after a Robertson Stephens analyst said
demand for computers would rebound in the first quarter after a
slowdown caused by fears of problems related to year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And Procter &AMP; Gamble rose 7/16 to 103[ after the
consumer-products giant said it was abandoning talks to buy
Warner-Lambert and American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was a very rude session for high-flying, well-known
technology names.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems fell 6 3/16, to 109 1/16. Microsoft dropped 2{, to
101\. Qualcomm slumped 14~, to 140 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology companies, which have been on fire since the start
of the year, cooled off a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex shed 21 9/16, to 110 1/16. Millennium Pharmaceuticals
dropped 28~, to 171}. Genentech fell 5 7/16, to 161 13/16. And
Biogen fell 6 13/16, to 85 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill at Fleet and other analysts said a slide in the widely
watched market averages could be healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now getting to the point where these relatively
unscathed popular market averages will correct,'' said Richard
McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``But so many stocks are down so much that this may be an ending
of what has been a piecemeal rotational phase that has been taking
place for the last 18 to 21 months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
