<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-PLAYS-COX     01-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-PLAYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coryell tree shakes loose Rams' Martz
 &HT;    (EDS: This story was to be a short sidebar on the officials team
for the Super Bowl. The content was changed and will now be a
feature on St. Louis's Mike Martz.)
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eight years ago, Mike Martz was out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's the architect of the NFL's hottest offense and is
assured of following Dick Vermeil as Rams coach.
</P>
<P>
   Martz was unemployed in 1992 after Arizona State coach Larry
Marmie and his staff were fired. Martz had a few offers, but they
were a step down on the college-football totem pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' he said. ``I was frustrated, because I wanted
to go forward, not backward. And I ended up without a job.''
</P>
<P>
   So he began an unlikely path through the NFL. At 40, he
persuaded Chuck Knox, then coach of the Los Angeles Rams, to hire
him as an unpaid tight-ends coach. Martz was still receiving a
paycheck from Arizona State when Knox promised to hire him, or find
him a job in the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an easy decision for me,'' Martz said. ``It was a great
opportunity to get in the NFL, which I'd always wanted to do. I was
40 years old. I was at just the right age, I think, to make that
move. And it just worked out really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Martz, 48, was born in Sioux Falls, S.D., but attended high
school in San Diego. Still, he didn't know Rams offensive
coordinator Ernie Zampese, who had been an assistant coach under
former San Diego State and Chargers coach Don Coryell.
</P>
<P>
   During his five years with the Rams, Martz coached tight ends,
receivers and quarterbacks. Zampese also helped Martz develop his
offensive philosophy, which is built in part on the well-known
``Air Coryell'' passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   When current Falcons defensive coordinator Rich Brooks and his
staff were fired by the Rams after the 1996 season, Martz was hired
by Redskins coach Norv Turner, also from the Coryell coaching tree.
Turner had coached with Zampese in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   In his second season in Washington, Martz coached quarterback
Trent Green, who threw 23 touchdowns and only 11 interceptions
after taking over as the starter in the second game. When Green
signed with the Rams as a free agent in February 1999, Vermeil
hired Martz as his offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Martz) runs the show,'' said Green, who suffered a
season-ending knee injury in an exhibition game. ``Coach Vermeil
has given him the freedom to do the things he wants to do. He's
really just unbelievably creative in coming up with ways to spread
the ball around.''
</P>
<P>
   After Green suffered torn knee ligaments, the Rams' season
seemed hopeless. But former Arena League star Kurt Warner stepped
forward, throwing an NFL-high 41 touchdowns with 4,353 passing
yards. St. Louis scored 526 points, the third-highest season total
in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Martz surfaced as a candidate with the Saints, Patriots and
Packers, all of which were searching for head coaches after
firings. But the Rams ended all speculation last week by signing
Martz to a contract extension guaranteeing that he will replace
Vermeil in at least two years, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect talent, and I know my job is to win, and we have a
person here who is helping us win,'' Vermeil said. ``With all these
jobs coming open, I've been in that situation before. Sometimes you
think the grass is greener somewhere else. The greenest grass in
the country right now is in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
