<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ATLANTA-ICESTORM-COX     01-24 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-ICESTORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storm recovery continues in Georgia
 &HT;    By Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Armies of power-line workers, emergency personnel,
road crews, and prisoners restored electricity and cleared roads
across North Georgia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   They made significant progress: Only 100,000 or so homes and
businesses remained without power late Monday, down from 500,000 at
the peak of the fallout from Sunday's freak ice storm. More schools
planned to open Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the news wasn't all encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes declared emergencies in another 14 counties,
raising the total to 34 counties hit hard by the season's first
serious winter storm. Almost one in five Georgia counties now carry
that unwelcome distinction. Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine
estimated insured losses at $25 million, and rising.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of a Roswell, Ga., family suffered carbon monoxide
poisoning, police say, when fumes from a gas-powered generator
seeped into the house. A 10-year-old Rockdale girl's back was
broken when a four-inch thick limb hit her in the head and
compressed several vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of more windy weather worried some. ``Some of these
trees have been weakened. They may come down if the winds pick
up,'' said Lt. Mark Gresham of the Cobb County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters predicted the next bout of icy weather could arrive
Friday. Rain is on tap for the Atlanta area; ice and snow for the
northern, mountainous counties.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was the prediction last weekend. Even if the
worst of the weather remains north of Atlanta, legions of Tennessee
Titans fans bound for the Super Bowl will plow through it as they
come down I-75.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League is concerned about the weather,
mainly its effect on players. ``Teams are obviously sensitive to
it. We want to know if we're able to practice outside or not,''
said Jim Steeg, who is in charge of game-day preparations for the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans plan to practice, starting Wednesday, at college
campus. The St. Louis Rams will use the Atlanta Falcons training
camp in Suwanee, Ga. Neither offers an indoor practice field.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Dome, where Super Bowl XXXIV will be played Sunday
is undergoing significant preparations. Allowing the teams _ their
penchant for privacy _ to practice there would be a logistical
headache, Steeg said.
</P>
<P>
   Damage varied across the region, depending on population
density, tree canopy and the further north from Atlanta one
traveled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   An ice-coated tree limb fell 30 feet before hitting the Rockdale
County girl. The limb struck with such force that either the spine
or a broken rib punctured a lung. The girl, whose name wasn't
released, is not believed to be paralyzed, but she remained in
severe pain Monday night at Children's Healthcare of Atlanta at
Egleston.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power deployed 3,000 linemen in response to the ice
storm, which knocked out power to 340,000 of its 1.8 million
customers. Utility crews from across Georgia, Alabama and the
Southeast responded. About 75,000 Georgia Power customers remained
without electricity Monday afternoon. Some customers may not be
back on line until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going house to house to house and it's slow going,''
said Georgia Power spokesman Tal Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Another 21,000 customers of electric membership cooperatives,
primarily in the northern Georgia, were also without service late
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross planned to open 10 shelters Monday evening across
the Atlanta region, a couple more than the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Also at work were some inmates from state and local jails. They
were issued garden tools, chainsaws, rakes and other road-clearing
paraphernalia and fanned out across the region. Summerville,
Demorest, Canton and other towns availed themselves of the free
labor.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks still without power Monday evening lived beneath
metro Atlanta's lush canopy of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
