<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE'S FATHER, NO STRANGER TO CAMPAIGNING, HITS THE TRAIL
AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The role of stump speeches for candidates is
clear _ criticize the other party's candidates while avoiding
saying anything that will offend anybody in your own party. But the
role for a candidate's parents _ particularly if the parent is a
former president _ is murky.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush's latest interpretation of that
role, in a speech here to the National Automobile Dealers
Association, featured occasional digs at the Clinton presidency and
a gentle vouching for his son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
front-runner for the Republican nomination for president. To
lighten things up, he even did his imitation of comedian Dana
Carvey imitating President Bush on Saturday Night Live _ ``not
gonna do it, wouldn't be prudent,'' Bush joked on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He subtly criticized President Clinton's dalliance with a White
House intern by saying first, ``We must respect the institution of
the presidency,'' and later predicting that in the 2000 race, ``one
of the issues is going to be respect for the institution of the
presidency.'' He won thunderous applause each time.
</P>
<P>
   And he talked about the pride he felt in his two sons, both
governors now, calling them, ``two honest, courageous guys out
there fighting for their beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke late on Monday afternoon, Bush had his mind on the
votes being counted in the Iowa caucuses. ``We're going to know
something tonight,'' said the former president. ``If I look a
little nervous as I stand here now, it is because by 9 o'clock
tonight central time, 10 o'clock here, we are going to know who
wins on the Democratic side and on the Republican side _ this is
the Iowa caucuses _ the first expression of the people, which is
different from the polls that tell us what's going on every single
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered his own reading of the political tea leaves. ``If
Bradley is the nominee for the Democrats, and say, my son wins for
the Republican nomination, or John McCain does, then you're going
to have a Bush-Dukakis race, which is largely conservative and
liberal,'' Bush said. ``Remember back in 1988 _ the issues were
drawn very, very clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is pulling toward the left,'' and if Gore is the
Democratic nominee, Gore would be able to move further towards the
political center,'' Bush said. If Gore wins, ``then you're going to
have a different kind of race.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the former president's gentle support for his son's
presidential candidacy hardly came as a surprise, and was something
most car dealers could relate to. Harold B. Wells, a dealer from
Whiteville, N.C., introduced Bush by telling the several thousand
car dealers present that, ``He's doing what you or I would do _
he's helping his son get into the family business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was, as he pointed out ``preaching to the choir,'' since
the nation's car dealers generally lean Republican, viewing
themselves as hard-working entrepreneurs who are active in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Spitzer, who said he plans to vote for Governor Bush for
president, summarized the views of many car dealers. ``He's
conservative like his dad and as he said in his speech, he believes
in entrepreneurs and that's the lifeblood of our industry,'' said
Spitzer, chairman and chief executive of Spitzer Management Group,
which owns 24 car dealerships in Florida, Pennsylvania and Ohio.
``A majority of the dealers nationally would support Governor Bush
or at least a Republican candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president tried not to give the stump speech of a
proud father, however, even when asked about the 2000 presidential
race. ``I've got my own hopes, of course. It is so hard for me to
be constrained in talking to you about this, because this isn't a
political convention,'' said Bush, ``but when your own son is
involved, you've just gotta excuse me if I cross that line.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the car dealers did not mind. They gave him two
standing ovations.
</P>
</TEXT>
