<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2000-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN FOCUSES ON NEW HAMPSHIRE DURING IOWA CAUCUSES 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, N.H. _ While the other presidential candidates were
trying to drum up last-minute support in Iowa on Monday, Republican
John McCain campaigned alone in New Hampshire, where he debuted a
new television commercial that heavily promotes his military
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator, who skipped the Iowa caucuses to gamble on
a strong showing Feb. 1 in New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation
primary, made five campaign stops in the Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   Attending his 100th New Hampshire town hall meeting at a
National Guard Armory in Plymouth, McCain told about 200 people
that the Iowa caucuses were the ``preliminaries'' of the
presidential nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The finals are right here in New Hampshire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that McCain, a former prisoner of war in Vietnam,
is locked in a tight race in New Hampshire with GOP front-runner
George W. Bush. Many observers believe McCain needs a victory in
New Hampshire or at least a strong second-place finish to keep his
candidacy for the White House alive.
</P>
<P>
   In a foreign policy discussion with reporters, McCain said that
rather than use U.S. troops to dislodge unfriendly dictators, such
as Yugoslavia's Slobodan Milosevic, he would ``arm, train, equip
(and) encourage opposition'' from within the affected countries.
</P>
<P>
   That opposition, he said, could include the possible
assassination of the offending leader, as long as the killing
wasn't directly sponsored by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they do is up to them as they evict the dictators,'' he
said. ``I'm saying that I do not support U.S.-sponsored
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really have a peaceful world as long as you have
governments that are controlled by despots,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic right now is stirring up trouble in Kosovo. We all
know that. If you replace Milosevic and at least have some progress
towards democracy and freedom you will face a much less threat to
the stability there, which is fragile as we all know, than we would
with him in power.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has been campaigning across the country, McCain has
been concentrating most of his effort on New Hampshire and South
Carolina, which will hold a primary Feb. 19. A spokesman said
McCain has made 30 trips to New Hampshire and spent 64 days
campaigning here since kicking off his presidential race last year.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's new TV ad cites more than 12,000 military families on
food stamps, veterans unable to get benefits, and ``international
tensions, hot spots and uncertainties around the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one man running for president who knows the
military and understands the world _ John McCain,'' an announcer
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Navy pilot and POW he's seen the horrors of war. As a
senator, he's already one of the nation's leaders in knowing how to
keep the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain adds, ``If America is to lead, then America's leader must
be prepared for that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain told reporters he was not highlighting Bush's
inexperience in foreign policy, despite the Texas governor's short
resume on international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) has been a fine governor. He's a good man, and I
think he would make a good president of the United States,'' McCain
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator said he was ``better prepared'' than Bush for
the free world's top job because of his total life experiences and
his ``vision for the future of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he made only three trips to Iowa _ to participate in
two recent debates of Republican presidential candidates and attend
a congressional hearing last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope in the Iowa caucuses we will break half a percent,'' he
joked. ``We will try to convince everyone that's a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
