<SLUG> BC-BEN&AMP;JERRYS-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARING A TAKEOVER, SHOPS RALLY TO THE BEN &AMP; JERRY'S CAUSE(S) 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream shop owners plans to rally in
various cities on Tuesday to protest what they say is the threat a
corporate takeover would pose to the company's socially responsible
image.
</P>
<P>
   Ben &AMP; Jerry's was founded in 1978 by Ben Cohen and Jerry
Greenfield and quickly developed a quirky but warm-hearted image by
billing itself as a practitioner of ``caring capitalism'' and
aligning with causes like saving rain forests and helping the
homeless. But last month, the company announced that it had
received ``indications of interest'' from an unidentified company.
Ben &AMP; Jerry's, based in Burlington, Vt., said at the time that the
offer was subject to conditions, but that its board would consider
it.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said that any takeover of Ben &AMP; Jerry's would have
to meet a number of unusual criteria, including agreeing to
continue manufacturing the product in Vermont. Politicians in the
state have said Ben &AMP; Jerry's should remain independent, and a Web
site was launched last month _ by a Web page designer in
Massachusetts who had worked with the company on various causes _
that urges people to fight the sale by buying shares in the company
so they can vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   One store owner said on Monday that she feared a takeover could
mean the end of Ben &AMP; Jerry's highly regarded involvement in causes
that aid disadvantaged groups _ something that drew her to the
company in the first place. ``I got involved with Ben &AMP; Jerry's
because I liked the way they mixed business with their social
mission,'' said Lori Johnston, who owns two stores in Washington.
With a takeover by a larger corporation, she added, ``a large part
of what Ben &AMP; Jerry's stands for would disappear, and I think that
would be a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's stores are among 198 that sell Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice
cream for profit. Eight additional stores are run as partnerships
with nonprofit organizations. Nearly all of the store owners are
protesting the proposed takeover, said Judy Wicks, the founder of
the Social Venture Network, which has organized the Coalition to
Save Ben &AMP; Jerry's.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Ben &AMP; Jerry's said on Monday that the company
had no additional comments to make on the offer. ``With regard to
the rallies, those are independently owned franchisees, and the
company respects their right to voice their opinions,'' said the
spokeswoman, Chrystie Heimert.
</P>
<P>
   Rosanne Haggerty, the founder and executive director of Common
Ground, which has operated a Ben &AMP; Jerry's store for the last five
years near New York's Times Square and plans to open a second in
Rockefeller Center later this year, recalled how Ben &AMP; Jerry's
promised to support her even before the group was formally
organized. Common Ground provides housing and employment counseling
to people with low incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of the business is in the image of Ben &AMP; Jerry's
remaining a spirited outsider compared with the typical business
operation,'' she said. ``They seek out nonprofit groups to run some
of their shops. There is no other company we've come across that
has a vision like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Haggerty, whose store is one of the rallying sites, said she
received a mailing from Ben &AMP; Jerry's about the Dec. 2 announcement
of the acquisition offer. While there had been rumors of such
things in earlier years, she said, ``we have never received any
notification of an official nature from the company in the past.''
That, combined with a discussion of the merger-and-acquisition
trend in the ice cream business that was part of a franchisee
meeting in Florida this month, made her and other franchisees feel
that ``there is a whiff of the decision nearing a resolution
here,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
