<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-FEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vermeil loses control, loosens up for Rams
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time Dick Vermeil was in this position, he
had issues _ control issues.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, though, the 63-year-old coach of the Rams is very
little like the 44-year-old man who led the Eagles to Super Bowl
XVI in January, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   New millennium, new man.
</P>
<P>
   That means no curfew as his team gets ready to play the Titans
in Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   The old, younger, Vermeil drew attention for all the discipline
he used to embrace, not to mention the curfews he put in place for
the Eagles when they were in New Orleans getting ready to play the
Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work. First, several Raiders players were supposedly
spotted out and about on Bourbon Street. Later, they were
definitely seen running roughshod over Vermeil's Philadelphia
squad, 27-10.
</P>
<P>
   But the new, older, Vermeil said Monday his team won't have a
bed check this week, other than a mandatory Saturday meeting at 9
p.m. That doesn't mean he wants his players spotted behaving like
the Raiders 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any curfews scheduled,'' Vermeil said. ``I just
told them that anybody out screwing around that gets in trouble,
I'll send home. I don't think I've got any people like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Rams players believe the fact there is no extra week
between the conference championship games and the Super Bowl makes
it more likely everybody will buckle down.
</P>
<P>
   Most years, Super Bowl teams put in at least part of their game
plans in the off week, leaving less hard work the week before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   This year, schmooze time was limited largely to Monday night,
when some players hit Atlanta clubs and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time management is going to be critical,'' said Pro Bowl
cornerback Todd Lyght. ``These next six days are very important.
Personally, I think it's helpful to get right back out there. If
you have too much down time, you might lose your edge.''
</P>
<P>
   One guy guaranteed not to do any rabble-rousing is St. Louis Pro
Bowl quarterback Kurt Warner, who's about as straight-laced as they
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to wait two weeks to play that first game,'' he said.
``It's great to just get back out there and play football.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still early in the week, but the Rams don't sound like a
team that might grow tense, as many suspected the Eagles did under
a week under the formerly iron-fisted Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm different,'' he said. ``I'm older, I'm a grandfather of
11. Hopefully, I'm not as blind.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Vermeil is completely without control
issues.
</P>
<P>
   He left most of his staff behind in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to go about game-planning much as they would in a
normal week. The staff will fly into Atlanta tonight, and everybody
will meet at 7 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   So not everything has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the way we do things,'' Vermeil said. ``I felt that
this would be best for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
