<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BBDO-AD-COLUMN-NYT     01-24 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBDO-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBDO WORLDWIDE SHUFFLES ITS TOP MANAGERS IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ranks of top managers at the flagship New York
office of BBDO Worldwide, the largest agency in the Omnicom Group,
are being revamped in an effort to identify a next generation of
leadership and increase the attention paid to important tasks like
landing more clients and broadening offerings beyond traditional
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, being formally announced on Tuesday, raise some
questions as they answer others, primarily in regard to when Philip
B. Dusenberry, the longtime chairman at BBDO New York, might begin
making succession plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take away anything from the announcements,''
Dusenberry said in a telephone interview, ``but I can assure you
I'm not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still active,'' said Dusenberry, 63. ``I'm still coming in
every day and will continue to for the foreseeable future.''
Dusenberry is also scheduled to take over as chairman of the
American Association of Advertising Agencies in May; that would be
for a one-year term expiring in spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when Dusenberry relinquished his duties as co-chief
executive and chief creative officer at BBDO New York to Ted Sann,
billings have doubled, the office estimates, to more than $2
billion in 1999 out of a BBDO Worldwide total of $13.5 billion.
Among new clients are Dell Computer, the New York Stock Exchange,
the New York Yankees, Charles Schwab and Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are mostly on the account management or ``suit''
side of BBDO New York with a couple involving the creative side.
Because the office is dense with layers of senior executives,
replete with titles beginning with ``co- '' and ``senior
executive,'' the changes will be outlined below in steps to try
minimizing confusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the account-management ranks, one major change is the
promotion of William L. Katz, 45, who had been president and chief
operating officer, to president and co-chief executive. He assumes
the title of co-chief executive from Thomas H. Carey, 55, who
continues as president at BBDO North America and takes on new
duties at BBDO Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Carey is relinquishing his oversight of BBDO New York a year
after he relinquished supervision of the agency's Los Angeles and
San Francisco offices to Katz and Sann, 54, the other co-chief
executive at BBDO New York who is also chief creative officer.
</P>
<P>
   Carey, however, continues to oversee the BBDO North America
offices in Atlanta, Chicago, Minneapolis and Canada. The BBDO
offices in the Detroit area, home of the billings- and revenue-rich
DaimlerChrysler account, are supervised by J. Thomas Clark.
</P>
<P>
   In another account management change, Jeffrey A. Mordos, 42,
executive vice president and managing director on the Pepsi-Cola
account, is being promoted to chief operating officer, assuming
much of Katz's previous operational duties. Mordos has been
identified as an up-and-comer at BBDO New York and not just because
he once bested an older, more muscular creative executive in a
hallway tussle over some disputed Pepsi commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving Jeff a lot more responsibility,'' Dusenberry
said, because ``he has established himself as one of the great
operations guys in terms of administrative abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Murray, 41, who had been executive vice president and
senior account director on the Campbell Soup account, becomes
senior account director on Pepsi-Cola, part of PepsiCo Inc., taking
over Mordos' day-to-day duties for North America; he will remain
involved with that important client.
</P>
<P>
   As for tasks meant to receive additional attention, one is
landing new clients, known as business development. Janet Lyons,
42, who had been senior vice president and senior creative director
on accounts like Duracell, HBO and Texaco, is being named to the
new post of business development director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we need to put someone in place there,'' Dusenberry
said, ``and Janet will bring a creative aspect to new business in
terms of putting our best foot forward when we're putting pitches
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Sann acknowledged that it was unusual to name a creative
executive to pursue new business, but ``we're a creative-driven
agency and we need someone who understands coming at clients'
problems from that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The other task in the spotlight is widening the BBDO New York
expertise beyond its specialty of glitzy, big-budget television
commercials as symbolized by the office's lengthy annual list of
Super Bowl spots. (The BBDO New York clients to be seen during the
game on Sunday are Federal Express, Pepsi-Cola's Mountain Dew soft
drink and Visa.)
</P>
<P>
   To that end, John Osborn, 33, who had been senior vice president
and worldwide senior account director, is being named director for
integrated marketing services, which include services like
interactive marketing and direct marketing. He succeeds Susan
Ellis, 46, who joined BBDO New York only 15 months ago in that
capacity from Hill, Holliday, Connors, Cosmopulos, a unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a final change in the management side, Simon Marlow, 53,
executive vice president and managing director on the Duracell and
Gillette accounts, is being named to an additional, new post as
director for multinational account services. In that capacity, he
will take on duties for the account of another PepsiCo unit,
Frito-Lay International.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the creative side at BBDO New York, Michael Patti,
46, vice chairman and executive creative director, is being
promoted to senior executive creative director, continuing to
oversee creative development for clients like Federal Express, HBO,
Pepsi-Cola and Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has done some remarkable work,'' Sann said, ``and we
want to recognize that.'' Patti joins Charles R. Miesmer, 53, as
vice chairman and senior executive creative director. Dennis
Berger, 53, and Al Merrin, 53, continue as vice chairmen and
executive creative directors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
