<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-AD-NYT &LR;      01-24 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN UNVEILS NEW AD IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MCCAIN-NYT) 
(nk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a 30-second spot that began running Monday in New Hampshire,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona advances the argument that he is the
most qualified of all the candidates to be the nation's next
commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Stevens Reed Curcio &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The commercial careers early on between patriotic
images and the horrors of war. It begins with a slow-motion image
of a soldier who is hugging his wife, with the words spoken by the
narrator and superimposed on the screen, ``12,000 Military Families
on Food Stamps.'' Next, a group of veterans are saluting the flag,
an image accompanied by the words, ``Veterans Failing to Get
Benefits.'' A series of quick cuts show tanks firing, smoke
billowing and a Chinese soldier. The camera pans from the soldier's
ominous expression to a huge banner of Mao. As the narrator says,
``There's only one man running for president who knows the military
and understands the world,'' the music softens and the camera shows
McCain speaking forcefully with a battleship for a backdrop. As the
narrator describes McCain's Vietnam War background, the camera
shows a black-and-white photo of a young McCain in his flight suit
preparing for a combat mission over Vietnam and black-and-white
film of McCain recovering in a military hospital. Back in color,
McCain is seen walking with President Ronald Reagan at the White
House, an image that fades into a shot of the sun setting behind
the Iwo Jima memorial. The spot climaxes with a close-up of McCain
speaking with the title: ``Ready to Lead.'' Behind him, American
and prisoner-of-war flags flap in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: All but the last sentence of the commercial is
spoken by a narrator. ``Over 12,000 military families on food
stamps. Veterans failing to get the benefits they were promised.
International tensions, hot spots and uncertainties around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one man running for president who knows the
military and understands the world. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a navy pilot and POW, he has seen the horrors of war. As a
senator, he's already one of the nation's leaders in knowing how to
keep the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial closes with McCain saying, ``If America is to
lead, then America's leader must be prepared for that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: In nearly all his previous campaign spots, McCain has
prominently featured his heroic past as a gutsy prisoner of war in
North Vietnam. He endured five and a half years of torture and
solitary confinement in Hanoi after his Navy fighter plane was shot
down in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning his chief rival, Gov. George W. Bush, this
latest advertisement is intended to make the case that McCain is
better prepared than the Texas governor to lead the nation in a
dangerous world.
</P>
<P>
   The spot offers no details on what McCain proposes to do in
foreign policy, but manages to reinforce McCain's image as a war
hero and influential shaper of military and foreign policy. And it
includes several images from previous biographical commercials,
like the photograph of McCain as a young Navy pilot and the footage
of the senator walking outside the Oval Office with Reagan. To some
viewers, the advertisement may not appear to be a new one.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: Advertisements for McCain are available from The New York
Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/politics.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
