<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-ART-2T     01-24 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PLANETARIUM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL COUNTDOWN FOR A COSMIC LANDMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT18 and NYT19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: spelling of Gugenheim is cq.) 
(fb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stepping over the battered orange extension cord
snaking from a 16-gallon Shop Vac, Ellen V. Futter, president of
the American Museum of Natural History, pointed to the floor of the
sleek new $210 million planetarium about her. ``Right now, it's all
about wires,'' she said, her voice competing with a symphony of
power tools.
</P>
<P>
   To her left, three electricians were unwinding 21 spools of red,
white, blue and green wire, activating a wall of video monitors on
a recent afternoon. Upstairs, technicians were tuning the new $3.5
million Zeiss projector. And next door, interviewers were filling
the last of 289 new planetarium jobs, including 37 security guards
and six switchboard operators.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, these days, the museum braces for the onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 19, the first of as many as a million extra visitors
over the next year will descend on 81st Street and Central Park
West to see the new Rose Center for Earth and Space.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the planetarium had not been a New York City icon for 65
years, this debut would be no ordinary opening. Expressing
everything from jubilation to intense concern, city bureaucrats,
tourism czars, culture sachems and neighborhood naysayers have at
last found themselves in agreement about something: that the impact
of the new building will be off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of the Rose Center ``is perhaps the single most
important attraction in the city this year,'' said Cristyne F.
Lategano, president of NYC &AMP; Co., formerly known as the New York
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a tremendous impact on the city's economy,'' she
said, ``and there will be spinoff benefits to restaurants, retail
shops, hotels and theaters as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the new planetarium is expected to generate an
extra $76 million in retail sales and an additional $5.8 million in
tax revenue for New York City, according to an economic impact
statement prepared for the museum by a consultant, Hamilton,
Rabinovitz &AMP; Alschuler.
</P>
<P>
   To Schuyler G. Chapin, the city's cultural affairs commissioner,
the very-2000 planetarium _ an 87-foot-wide aluminum-clad sphere in
a titanic glass cube _ will be nothing less than ``a new symbol for
New York City,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the postcards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it has to open first. ``There have been moments when we
thought we'd never get it done on time,'' Futter, 50, said of the
six-year construction project.
</P>
<P>
   Work proceeds, feverishly, including moving the speakers inside
the 432-seat Space Theater to eliminate dead spots. And printing
enough floor plans to guide visitors until next May. Cleaning the
construction dust off the touchable bronze model of the moon.
Laying the red-shifted rainbow carpeting on the Cosmic Pathway,
where, at 50 million years a step, visitors can stroll down a
350-foot ramp recapitulating the 13.2-billion-year evolution of the
universe. (Signage designates one spot where the entire span of
human history is represented by a single hair.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the museum is anticipating planetarium lines so
long that astronomical lecturers are being hired to entertain
standees with impromptu talks on science and space. The spielers
will be kept busy _ according to preliminary estimates _ by about
4.5 million museum visitors next year, a million more than last
year's attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Such a total, exceeding the population of Los Angeles, will come
close to the 5 million yearly visitors to the Metropolitan Museum
of Art, across Central Park. ``Undoubtedly there has been a sibling
rivalry,'' said Chapin, referring to the 19th-century opening date
shared by both institutions (the American Museum was founded in
1869, the Met in 1870), ``but they are a perfect pair, the cultural
anchors of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when the Met has reigned supreme, will the new hoopla
accorded the long-stodgy American Museum revive this 130-year
rivalry?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy to be bookends on a beautiful park,'' Futter
said diplomatically, adding that the increasing number of tourists
coming to the planetarium could benefit the Met's admissions as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Met ``doesn't consider other museums competition,'' Harold
Holzer, the museum's vice president for communications, commented,
``and we think the Rose Center is a perfect addition to the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   That opinion is hardly shared by some in the neighborhood. Three
years after courts rebuffed community law suits trying to block the
new building's construction, the museum still faces opposition from
a dwindling but vocal band of neighbors, some of whom are opposed
to the aesthetic of the new planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have put the new Zeiss projector in the original
landmarked Hayden Planetarium and preserved it,'' said Samuel H.
Leff, president of the Community Alliance for Responsible Museum
Development, one of two groups that unsuccessfully sued the museum.
``The city could have saved tens of millions of dollars, but now we
have a glass box with a ball in it that looks like a high-tech
tumor.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``They wanted to put something in there that was very
flashy, so they'd have something like the Pyramide at the Louvre
and get a lot of attention,'' he said, referring to I.M. Pei's
acclaimed addition to the Louvre in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   His organization has substantially declined from 350 members
during the salad days of planetarium insurgency, but Leff claimed
that many in the neighborhood opposed what he called ``the traffic
disaster'' caused by automobile and bus visitors ``and the
additional congestion and pollution in an already densely populated
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Although dozens of school buses could park in the old
street-surface lot on the planetarium grounds, there is room for
but 10 of them in the Rose Center's new 370-space garage.
</P>
<P>
   School buses, tour buses and the cars of visitors unable to fit
in the garage ``will cruise the neighborhood, parking up and down
the local streets and avenues, causing gridlock,'' Leff said.
``There's a pedestrian safety issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, ``the buses will leave their motors running,
causing pollution,'' he said. ``At the museum they make much of all
their exhibits about ecology and biodiversity, but they're
polluting the community right outside their buildings. They should
be ashamed of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But another local group, Friends of Museum Park, insists that
since the population of the West Side has actually declined 25
percent since the 1950s, and since museum attendance was
considerably higher 25 years ago than it was last year, ``the fears
of overcrowding are unfounded,'' said Peter M. Wright, the
organization's president and co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neighborhood can support more museum visitors,'' Wright
said. But like Leff, Wright is worried about bus parking and
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about traffic have also been raised by residents of the
Beresford building on 81st Street and Central Park West, who have
another complaint about the museum's future as a much-sought-after
party venue.
</P>
<P>
   At the planetarium's sneak-preview opening party for 1,700 on
New Year's Eve, ``they had outdoor music, which I could hear in my
apartment, and the cheap and ugly psychedelic lights made the
planetarium look like a theme park,'' said Richard Lieb, a lawyer
and Beresford board member who unsuccessfully sued to stop
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa J. Gugenheim, the museum's vice president for government
relations and community affairs, said that since 1995 she and
others at the museum have ``met more than 250 times with members of
the community,'' adding that ``we have, together, modified the
museum's plans where appropriate and possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugenheim said the museum regretted ``any inconvenience'' caused
by the New Year's Eve celebration, which was a ``once in a lifetime
event.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the museum would ``limit the use of outdoor amplified
music'' in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Gugenheim claims that the museum has adequate plans to unload
and store the average of 41 school buses each weekday that visit
the museum between 9:30 a.m and 1:30 p.m. She said there is room
both in the Rose Center garage, in legal street-parking spaces and
in a 25-vehicle overflow parking center at 60th Street and West End
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the 20th Precinct has assigned a traffic
enforcement officer to ticket buses that are illegally parked or
are idling their motors.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is also mounting a joint $1 million advertising
campaign with the Metropolitan Transportation Authority to
encourage museum visitors to take public transportation, while
sharing half the $20 million cost of renovating the 81st Street
subway station and the museum's ground floor to accommodate more
visitors and school groups.
</P>
<P>
   Futter said the museum was equally focused on people-moving
inside the Rose Center, because the planetarium ``will change the
nature of how people visit the museum, how long they spend here,
and how often they come back.''
</P>
<P>
   As people swarm into the planetarium from eight entrances,
managers are projecting what they call ``throughput'' that averages
two hours per customer. The museum designers are preparing for
three kinds of visitors: ``streakers, strollers and studiers,''
Futter said.
</P>
<P>
   Streakers, of course, race through; strollers amble about at a
steady pace, and studiers insist on reading every word of every
label.
</P>
<P>
   One nightmare is that ``there will be no throughput,'' said
Barbara D. Gunn, senior vice president for government relations and
community affairs, adding: ``if they find everything fascinating in
the planetarium, they won't want to leave,'' she said, half
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But some just might go on to study the universe. ``The Rose
Center will be an inspirational venue for communicating science to
young people,'' said Daniel S. Goldin, the administrator of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration in Washington. ``I'll
never forget my first time at the Hayden Planetarium when I was
7,'' said Goldin, who was raised in the South Bronx. ``For me it
was, well, eureka! It launched my interest in space and
astronomy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
