<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFC-NOTES-C     01-24 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SBOWL-AFC-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC NOTEBOOK: Kearse makes presence known even on slow days
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Titans defensive end Jevon Kearse, who set an NFL
record for rookies with 14 1/2 sacks this season, didn't have a
sack in Sunday's 33-14 victory over the Jaguars in the AFC
Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kearse barely showed up on the stats sheet with only
one solo tackle and an assist.
</P>
<P>
   But Kearse's presence was felt throughout Sunday's game. He
pressured Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell on several plays,
including a knock-down hit in the fourth quarter that seemed to
irritate Brunell's sprained left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jevon is certainly affecting games,'' said Titans coach Jeff
Fisher. ``They are trying to account for him, adjusting to him.
He's having an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, a first-rounder from Florida, nearly had too much of an
impact in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With the Titans leading 26-14, the Jaguars were facing
third-and-19 at the Jacksonville 24. Titans defensive tackle Kenny
Holmes knocked the ball out of Brunell's hand as he started his
throwing motion.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse scooped up the loose ball and ran for the end zone. Near
the five-yard line, Kearse tried to lateral the ball to cornerback
Samari Rolle. But Jags receiver Keenan McCardell recovered the ball
at the Jacksonville 11, giving the Jaguars a first down since the
ball changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically tried to do too much,'' Kearse said. ``I should
have just gotten out of bounds, but I was thinking I wanted to put
the nail in the coffin and try to get to the end zone. It didn't
turn out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety measures
</P>
<P>
   The Titans set an NFL record in the third quarter when they
sacked Brunell in the end zone. It gave Tennessee two safeties in
the postseason. With a club record four safeties during the regular
season, the Titans have six in 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bulldog chasing blood,'' said Titans tackle Josh
Evans, who sacked Brunell with tackle Jason Fisk. ``We smell blood.
We go and get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Deja vu
</P>
<P>
   Titans owner Bud Adams, who co-founded the AFL in 1959 with
Kansas City Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt, was presented the Lamar Hunt
Trophy on Sunday by _ who else? _ Lamar Hunt. The trophy goes to
the AFC champion each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken me 40 years to get this far, and at least I won't
have to go to the Super Bowl in a wheelchair,'' said Adams, 77.
``We have great fans in Nashville, but we had great fans in
Houston, too. We miss our Houston fans, and we appreciate their
support through the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Last of the originals
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee became the eighth and final of the original AFL
franchises to advance to the Super Bowl. The Titans did so in their
40th season and after relocating from Houston to Nashville and
changing their name from the Oilers. The other seven are the Kansas
City Chiefs, Raiders, New York Jets, Denver Broncos, New England
Patriots, Buffalo Bills and San Diego Chargers. Coincidentally, the
Jets once were known as the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Home away from home
</P>
<P>
   The Titans have had so many homes in recent history _ four
stadiums in as many years _ that they might not know the difference
in playing at home and on the road. They've won three games in a
row at Jacksonville's Alltel Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say we own it,'' Kearse said. ``But we've put down
a down payment.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the Titans had already taken out a mortgage on their
second home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of (our homes),'' Evans said. ``Jacksonville, Houston
and Memphis.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuses
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars were playing without All-Pro left tackle Tony
Boselli, who missed all of the playoffs after tearing a knee
ligament in the regular-season finale. But left guard Ben Coleman,
who moved over in Boselli's absence, wasn't using it as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony does not catch the ball,'' Coleman said. ``Tony does not
fumble the ball. Tony does not turn the ball over. We felt they
didn't stop us all game, but when you turn the ball over, you can't
win. If Tony was out there, all the fire in the world could not
have kept the ball in our receivers' hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should call it the Mayflower Bowl. Both Super Bowl
franchises, until they won their respective conference
championships, were known more for their relocations than their
performance _ the St. Louis Rams from Anaheim; the Tennessee Titans
(formerly the Houston Oilers). . . . One San Francisco area writer
walking through the Hyatt Regency media center Monday while snow
flurries were pelting Peachtree Street: ``I should have brought my
skis.'' . . . With warm weather being so important at a Super Bowl
for so many people, has Atlanta struck out twice? Temperatures were
mild early in the week in 1994, then dropped to the 40s. This year
we'll be lucky to top 40 degrees. . . . Something you never saw
Chuck Noll or Tom Landry doing: Fisher was walking through the
locker room with an AFC champions T-shirt over his Titans coaches
shirt Sunday afternoon in Alltel Stadium. . . . The Titans are the
most likely to lead in press conference late arrivals or no-shows.
The AFC team drew the early shift and will meet with the media at
their Buckhead Grand Hyatt headquarters Wednesday and Thursday from
8:15-9:30 a.m. The Rams need not report until 10:15 a.m. . . .
Titans cornerback Dainon Sydney, a third-round draft choice in
1998, is an Atlanta native who played at Riverdale High School. . .
. Titans linebacker Eddie Robinson almost sounded like he felt
sorry for the Jaguars _ three time losers this year who beat
everyone else they played. ``I hope one day they can get there,''
Robinson said, referring to the Super Bowl. ``They have a great
owner and great fans. I feel real close to those guys.'' . . .
Jaguars offensive tackle Leon Searcy's advice to the St. Louis Rams
in regard to McNair: ``His scrambling will kill you. He's a 6-4,
245-pound quarterback. You can't tackle him high.'' . . . Titans
17-year guard Bruce Matthews, on inspiration they received from the
Nashville fans, in spite of the team's nomadic existence: ``We got
the spark going, and a little flame, and they just poured fuel on
it.'' . . . Phil Simms of CBS after the Titans took control of the
AFC title game in the third quarter: ``I don't know what Jeff
Fisher does at halftime, but I want a copy of that speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution writers Tom Stinson, Glenn Sheeley
and Mark Schlabach contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
