<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-DONATE-455&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL GATES AND HIS WIFE DONATE $5 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation said Monday that Bill
Gates, the billionaire founder of Microsoft Corp., and his wife
have donated $5 billion to their philanthropic foundation, making
it the world's wealthiest foundation, with assets of $21.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   With the gift, the Seattle-based foundation squeaked past
Britain's Wellcome Trust, which has assets of $21.4 billion,
according to the Chronicle of Philanthropy, a publication that
covers nonprofit organizations and ranks them by the size of their
assets. The second-largest foundation in the United States is the
Ford Foundation, with assets of $13.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Palmer, editor of the Washington-based publication, called
the gift ``really quite staggering'' and said it reinforces the
foundation's position as a trendsetter in the philanthropic world.
``It's only in the past year that people have taken their
philanthropy very seriously,'' Ms. Palmer said of Gates and his
wife. ``They plan to continue to put their money in, and, I think,
that's what will make them so exciting to watch in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which the Gateses established last year through
the merging of other foundations of theirs, has in recent months
received worldwide attention with news of its large commitments.
</P>
<P>
   In September the foundation pledged at least $1 billion to pay
for full scholarships over the next 20 years for minority students
in the fields of education, math, science and engineering. Then in
November the fund said it would donate $750 million over five years
to help international health organizations vaccinate children in
developing countries against deadly diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the foundation gave about $800 million last year and
made commitments of more than $2 billion, said Trevor Neilson, a
spokesman for the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson said that the foundation's mission is, in large part, to
improve health conditions in poor countries and further educational
opportunities for disadvantaged students in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, in an interview with The New York Times last September,
said he hoped his philanthropy would provide opportunities to
minorities, who he noted were underrepresented in high-tech
industries. ``Nobody can deny that there is a huge gap,
particularly in these key areas, for minority students, and the
financial barriers are a substantial element in that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the foundation said the Gateses plan to give more.
``Bill and Melinda have always said that they're committed to
giving away the vast majority of their wealth, and this is just a
part of that process,'' said Neilson. To keep its tax-exempt
status, the fund must give away at least 5 percent of its endowment
each year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Palmer of the Chronicle of Philanthropy said the foundation
is very different from other traditional foundations in that the
main donors _ Bill and Melinda Gates _ are alive and active in
deciding who receives benefits. ``It's pretty significant
involvement,'' Ms. Palmer said. ``The reason you see them doing
such ambitious projects is because the donors are alive and they
say, `Yeah, that looks like a good project.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5217 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-AILEY-TROUPE-TEX     01-24 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AILEY-TROUPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILEY DISCIPLE CONTINUES THE TRADITION OF HIS MASTERPIECES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his autobiography, ``Revelations,'' choreographer Alvin Ailey
described himself as ``a man from small-town Texas who never forgot
walking through dirt with his mother as a child, looking for a
place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   It is these memories of a poor, rural childhood _ oppression,
religion and the resilience of the human spirit _ that Ailey used
to ignite one of the most acclaimed modern dance troupes of our
time. In his most famous work, ``Revelations,'' Ailey turned the
images of people swept up in the movements of small-church gospel
and praise _ for example, the power of Jesus pushing a woman
through the aisles like a locomotive _ into one of the most widely
performed works in modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 10 years after his death, the vitality of the
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater is an artistic force that lives
on. The renowned modern dance company returned to Fort Worth, after
an absence of two decades, for two performances at Bass Performance
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ailey was an incredibly brave genius _ an African-American who
had the gumption to create a modern dance company in New York in
1958, during the civil rights struggle, in an age of racial
stereotyping. He died of AIDS in 1989, already a living legend, but
disturbed, depressed and estranged from many of the people who had
been closest to him.
</P>
<P>
   One of those people with whom he had worked, quarreled, parted
and reconciled is devoted to making sure that his name lives on.
Judith Jamison, whose legendary reputation in the modern dance
community nearly rivals that of her mentor, directs the Alvin Ailey
Dance Theater and is determined to carry the Ailey tradition well
into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison was both a disciple and an inspiration for Ailey. It was
for her that he created several of his masterpieces. But her own
accomplishments as a dancer and choreographer extended far beyond
her association with Ailey; her range extends from ``Sophisticated
Ladies'' to the mythical Medea. It was for her own accomplishments,
not for her association with Ailey, that she was named a 1999
Kennedy Center honoree.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Philadelphia, Jamison arrived at the company in 1965,
full of adoration for Ailey but with a firm, anchored personality
that contrasted sharply to his. ``My relationship with Alvin was
based on total awe of his accomplishments as a director,
choreographer and human being,'' Jamison wrote in her
autobiography, after his death. ``Alvin could be as loving as he
could be insulting.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Ailey, eventually found to be
manic-depressive, continued to have an erratic, creative and
brilliant career, with his company periodically rescued from
financial ruin and disorganization by devoted patrons; Jamison
moved on to dance with other companies and on Broadway in the
1980s. However, seeing the end coming, Ailey asked Jamison to take
over as artistic director after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Talking by telephone between New York performances of the Alvin
Ailey company in New York a few weeks ago, Jamison, 56, exuded
electric energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great things about the Alvin Ailey American Dance
Theater is that we know where we come from, the legacy that Ailey
left,'' Jamison says. ``We have one foot in the past and one in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company can hardly be described as simply
African-American, though Jamison says that ``the African-American
experience and the modern dance experience'' are the troupe's two
basic themes. It even transcends the label ``American'' in its huge
influence on modern dance. And the company is a titan in the world
of modern dance. While modern dance companies typically run on
shoestring budgets, the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater operates
with a staff of 31 dancers, an annual budget of $12 million, a
monthlong annual season at City Center in New York and an
impressive national and international touring schedule every year.
</P>
<P>
   And through the years, under Ailey until his death and under
Jamison since then, the company has been a major force in
redefining modern dance. Modern dance repertory has traditionally
been short-lived, but Ailey and his company built a large repertory
of ``classics'' _ including, most notably, the company's enduring
signature piece, Ailey's own ``Revelations.'' And ``Revelations''
represents a direct link to Ailey's own Texas origins.
</P>
<P>
   Divided into three segments, ``Pilgrim of Sorrow,'' ``Take Me to
the Water'' and ``Move, Members, Move,'' ``Revelations'' is set to
traditional spirituals that Ailey heard in church while growing up
in rural Texas, and it draws on memories of people he saw and knew
in those ecstatic, small-town African-American church services.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers who participated in the creation and premiere of
``Revelations'' later recalled for Ailey biographer Jennifer
Dunning how Ailey, years and miles away from the church services of
his childhood, talked about the amply bosomed church ladies who had
to lean forward and spread their legs to stay cool in the hot
church building, and about the lady who would periodically rise
from her seat and churn through the congregation like a train in
motion. These vivid memories were transformed into a choreography
that captured, and continues to capture, the public imagination in
what has become one of the most widely performed dance pieces of
all time.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kreiman, executive director of Contemporary Dance/Fort
Worth, remembers the first time she saw ``Revelations,'' as a
student at the American Dance Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get up and dance,'' Kreiman recalls. ``It's
one of the dance masterpieces of the 20th century. It's a beautiful
piece with a wonderful series of group dances, solo dances, trios
and duets. It's wonderful in its portrayal of religion, spirit and
community. And it's truly American.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2031EST &QL; 
