<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-AILEY-TROUPE(2ndTake)     01-24 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AILEY-TROUPE(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: xxx truly American.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Born in 1931 in Rogers, Texas, Ailey absorbed those generous
doses of the local culture before moving to Los Angeles at age 10
during the wartime economic boom. There, he entered the world of
professional dance while still a teen-ager, falling under the
influence of iconoclastic choreographer Lester Horton.
</P>
<P>
   New York inevitably followed, with more study and teaching,
dancing on Broadway and with modern dance companies _ and a
bohemian lifestyle that was a long way from Rogers. Already
well-known on Broadway by the late 1950s, Ailey turned in a
completely different direction for the creation of the Alvin Ailey
American Dance Theater, a company described by Dunning as ``a
harmonious mix of extroverted show dancers and `serious' modern
dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's first performances at the 92nd Street Y in New
York stand as one of the most significant moments in the history of
American dance, both as a turning point for all modern dance and as
the foundation of the emergence of serious, artistic
African-American dance.
</P>
<P>
   The company today remains devoted to Ailey's principles. Its
large repertory of 182 works continues to balance permanent works
such as ``Revelations,'' now approaching its 40th anniversary, with
new pieces, such as Jawole Willa Jo Zollar's ``C-sharp Street _
B-flat Avenue,'' and Ron Brown's ``Grace.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Ailey's ballets will always be an important part of the
reportoire of the company, and are among the great classics of the
modern dance repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alvin's ballets are terrific because they're human and humane,
like he was,'' says Bruce Wood, founding director of Fort Worth's
Bruce Wood Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jamison's personality is different from Ailey's, she
shares his focus on the dancers. He called them his gods and
goddesses, she praises them for their versatility and
voraciousness.
</P>
<P>
   As Jamison wrote not long after assuming the mantle of artistic
director of the company, ``I don't feel as though I'm standing in
anyone's shoes. I'm standing on Alvin's shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Ailey never forgot his childhood, and transformed those
experiences artistically. And because he never forgot, he will not
be forgotten. ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the background material for this article came from
``Dancing Spirit: An Autobiography,'' by Judith Jamison (with
Howard Kaplan); ``Revelations: The Autobiography of Alvin Ailey''
(with A. Peter Bailey); ``Alvin Ailey: A Life in Dance,'' by
Jennifer Dunning; ``Judith Jamison: Aspects of a Dancer,'' by Olga
Maynard.
</P>
