A5219 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-NOTEBOOK25-COX     01-24 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-NOTEBOOK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOWA NOTEBOOK: Candidates pack up, head to New Hampshire
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Iowa caucuses over, everyone is heading to New
Hampshire. Unlike Iowa, New Hampshire's races on both the
Republican and Democratic sides are too close to call _ thanks to
independent voters and effective appeals from well-funded
insurgents.
</P>
<P>
   The polls suggest both John McCain and Bill Bradley post strong
challenges to the respective national front-runners _ George W.
Bush and Al Gore _ in part because they have spent so much time
there and have surged in fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa and New Hampshire are potential momentum machines to propel
candidates through contests in other early primary states. This
year, the sprint is especially intense, because about
three-quarters of the parties' national convention delegates will
be chosen by March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Gore plays down report of pot use
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore denied Monday that he smoked marijuana regularly, even
daily, with a Tennessee friend as late as 1976, as the man now
contends. The question came up when a reporter said to Gore at a
diner: ``It's been reported that after you came back from Vietnam
you were smoking on a daily basis.'' Gore responded, ``No. When I
came back from Vietnam, yes, but not to that extent. ... This is
something I dealt with a long time ago. It's old news.'' The
Tennessee man, John Warnecke, was quoted by the online magazine
Salon.
</P>
<P>
   Weather no factor in wintry state
</P>
<P>
   The weather wasn't a problem for Monday's presidential caucuses.
It was chilly across the state, with a smattering of snow here and
there, but that's to be expected _ since it's winter. The
temperature highs were in the teens in northeast Iowa, with some
light snow. In the southeastern part of the state, it got up into
the low 40s _ considered downright balmy for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   This, folks, is what it's all about in Iowa
</P>
<P>
   Morris Smith, a 70-year-old farmer from Creston, Iowa, has
participated in the Democratic caucuses for 20 years, at times
holding them in his home, and he's a believer in the system because
it gives him a chance to hear firsthand from the candidates or
their supporters. ``It's great politics. It's grass-roots. It's not
somebody off in Washington telling you why you should be supporting
this person,'' Smith says. ``I don't think politics can get any
better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Students' choice: mix and match
</P>
<P>
   Students at Iowa State University in Ames had a caucus-day
choice beyond just voting. On one side of the student union was a
rally for Republican George W. Bush. Across the hall was a similar
turnout for Democrat Bill Bradley. The two campaigns intersected
for a moment. Sen. Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.), who is backing Bradley,
went over to Bush. He wasn't looking for trouble; he just wanted to
shake hands and say hello.
</P>
<P>
   Interest lagging in rest of country
</P>
<P>
   In the week before today's caucuses, a poll by the Shorenstein
Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy found that
two-thirds of the voters nationally were paying only a little or no
attention to the campaign, and that 70 percent said they had no
favorite candidate. If the race is declared over before they tune
in, many political observers suggest it could only further voter
disaffection and the decline in turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about how to talk about it
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's campaign got caught in a contradiction about
how the candidate will be made available for future questioning.
One spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker, said formal meetings between
reporters and Bush were being cut back because they can harm ``the
message of the day.'' Later, Bush communications chief Karen Hughes
said no, Bush would continue to be available, but on an informal
basis that befits a ``much more drop-in, much more drop-by''
campaign style.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
