<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC NETWORK CHIEF NAMED NO. 2 AT DISNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DISNEY-IGER) 
(mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Michael Eisner, chairman of Walt Disney Co., on
Monday named Robert A. Iger, the ABC network chief, as his
second-in-command in a restructuring of Disney's top management.
</P>
<P>
   In appointing Iger as president and chief operating officer,
Eisner sent a clear signal that he viewed the 48-year-old chairman
of the Disney-owned ABC Group as a potential heir to run the Disney
empire.
</P>
<P>
   The succession issue at Disney has bothered Wall Street and
shareholders since Eisner's heart surgery in 1994 and the death of
his longtime No. 2, Frank Wells, in a helicopter crash the same
year. Eisner sought to replace him with Michael Ovitz, but the
former agent was dismissed after 16 months in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Disney has seen an exodus of potential heirs,
including the former chief financial officers, Stephen Bollenbach
and Richard Nanula; former ABC executives Geraldine Laybourne and
Steve Burke, and Joe Roth, former chairman of Disney studios, who
left last month.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, who promoted several other Disney executives on Monday,
made it evident that the new job was a test for Iger. ``This is the
first step in shuffling the chairs at court,'' said Christopher
Dixon, an entertainment analyst at Paine Webber. ``The challenge
for Bob is to demonstrate that he can manage the very strong
individual unit heads and implement the strategy of the board and
Michael Eisner.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's decision to name Iger, a silken, charming and
well-liked executive, who also served as president of Walt Disney
International, came after a troubled year of executive defections
at Disney and stagnant stock prices. The company has been beset by
slumping home video earnings, declines in licensing and
merchandising and a drop-off in store sales.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday Disney posted some positive financial news. With
strong performances from its theme parks, broadcasting and cable
operations _ including the No. 1 television show in the nation,
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' and the hit sequel film ``Toy
Story 2'' _ Disney posted a 9 percent rise in fiscal first quarter
profits. This excluded the company's Go.com Internet business,
which is expected to post a loss. Revenue rose 5 percent to $6.8
billion. Operating income increased 8 percent to $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's stock fell 1/4 to 32 1/2 on The New York Stock
Exchange, but jumped in after-hours trading. The announcements came
after trading ended.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the succession issue, Eisner, who is 57, said in an
interview that the appointment of Iger ``was not about that at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said, ``I guess the media may make something out of it,
but my view is we needed a president and chief operating officer
and that job should be on the board of directors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in America is better trained for this job than Bob,''
said Eisner. He said Iger would serve as his ``partner'' at Disney,
and that the two men had been discussing the new job for about two
years. He said Iger had played a central role in the integration of
ABC into the Disney organization, following Disney's $19 billion
merger with Cap Cities, which owned ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Eisner said, ``it became apparent that I
needed Bob.'' He said, ``ABC was strong, we had consolidated the
Disney studio and ABC. ABC was strong in management and
performance, and selfishly I wanted Bob at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner also announced the promotion of Disney's chief strategic
officer, Peter Murphy, and chief financial officer, Thomas O.
Staggs, to senior vice presidents. They will become members of a
new executive committee that will include Eisner, Iger, Disney vice
chairman Stanford M. Litvack and heads of individual business
units.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new corporate structure, Murphy will report to Eisner
and Iger. But vice chairman Roy E. Disney, Litvack and Staggs will
report to Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   Iger, asked about the challenges he faces, declined to discuss
too many specifics about the new job. ``I'd be wrong to say it
wasn't a big challenge,'' he said. ``But I can't point to any one
specific direction. There are ongoing challenges, but I don't view
this as daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Eisner said that Disney's involvement with digital
technology was certainly a factor in Iger's appointment. ``We have
to define where we'll be in the Digital Age,'' said Eisner. ``As
far as strategy and maintenance of what we have, Bob will be the
key planner in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, who also spoke to financial analysts on Monday,
cautioned them that he maintains ``conservative'' expectations for
the year. But he added, ``It's nice to start 2000 on a positive
note.'' Disney's strong profits were paced, in part, by the ABC and
ESPN-TV divisions that Iger had overseen.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner also sought to end speculation that Disney may merge with
an Internet company. ``I don't feel the need for anything but being
independent,'' said Eisner. ``We are big enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts said Monday evening that the Iger appointment
was a positive one for Disney, but that Eisner's aggressive
personality and his seeming reluctance to yield too much power
makes the No. 2 position difficult. But strengthening management at
Disney was crucial, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic world of media and online opportunities is
changing so rapidly that Disney needs to have a stronger senior
management footprint to capitalize on these changes,'' observed
Jill Krutick, an entertainment analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krutick said, ``Being president doesn't mean Iger's the
definite successor.'' She added: ``He certainly looks as if he has
a much better shot. But everyone's being constantly tested and
performance is what counts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
