<HEADLINE>
AMGEN TO RELEASE QUARTERLY EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Analysts believe Amgen Inc. will only meet the
expectations of Wall Street rather than exceed them as the company
has done for five quarters running.
</P>
<P>
   The company based in Thousand Oaks north of Los Angeles reports
its fourth-quarter results after the markets close Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen is expected to show earnings of 25 cents per share for the
quarter and 97 cents per share for the year, according to Thomson
Financial's First Call service.
</P>
<P>
   If Amgen exceeds estimates, it will have been caused by patients
stocking up for the year 2000 changeover, said Doug Christopher, an
analyst with Los Angeles-based Crowell Weedon &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation among analysts that the company is
close to seeking federal approval for two of its in-development
drugs: red blood cell stimulator NESP and the rheumatoid arthritis
drug Kineret.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will file when they're ready,'' Christopher said. ``We're
talking about people's lives and the long term. We're not talking
about filing just to please investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Meirav Chovav of Salomon Smith Barney issued a research
report in December stating her belief that the company already has
filed with the FDA for approval of the two drugs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Chovav increased her price target to $70 from
$56. The stock price has since surpassed that mark, but slid
$5.4375 lower in trading Monday to close at $69.25 per share.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
