<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FLU-ANTIBIOTICS-COX     01-24 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-ANTIBIOTICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overuse of antibiotics not a good idea with flu
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The cold and flu season brings an increased use
of antibiotics just as surely as December brings heavier jackets.
The difference is, the heavier jackets actually help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antibiotics only work on bacteria. The flu and colds are
viruses,'' says Kim Massie, regional pharmacy manager for United
Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say antibiotics are useless for winter miseries.
Bacteria still cause a lot of infections, particularly in
children's ears. Antibiotics are even appropriate for the infirm
elderly with flu and colds, or chronic heart, asthma and diabetic
patients who also are more susceptible to secondary infections.
</P>
<P>
   But they're widely overused, research shows. Besides wasting
money, unnecessary antibiotics also can cause new symptoms, weaken
a person's defense against future bacterial infections and help
breed super germs that no medicine can treat.
</P>
<P>
   Barely half of the 145 million prescriptions for antibiotics
outside hospitals each year are medically justified, National
Academy of Science researchers concluded in a 1997 study. In a
Gallup poll of 1,000 adults last year, seven of 10 said they had
received antibiotics to treat the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heightened publicity about antibiotics and viruses,
Massie says United's customers used 11 percent more antibiotics
last year than in 1998, without any evidence of increased bacterial
infections. For the peak of last year's flu season from Feb. 1 to
March 15, the increase was 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When people go to the doctor, Massie says, they want to come
home with something more than a pep talk on fluids and bed rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to just hear the stuff their grandmothers told
them,'' says Dr. Norman Schneiderman, medical director of Miami
Valley Hospital's emergency and trauma center. Every doctor gives
in at times and writes the prescription instead of arguing, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a lot of pressure,'' Massie says. `` `I have a 101
fever. I've had this headache for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
