<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FLU-DRUGS-COX     01-24 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-DRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FDA gets in on flu drug action
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ This is the first flu season when Americans have
access to drugs that treat most forms of influenza without many
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   So naturally the Food and Drug Administration already has found
it prudent to issue a warning on the drugs' misuse.
</P>
<P>
   While some doctors have used them in cases where they're
useless, others have used them instead of different treatments that
seriously ill patients needed. Three elderly flu patients had died
of untreated complications when the FDA announced its warning Jan.
12.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of Relenza and Tamiflu have publicized their new
drugs so heavily that Dr. Heidi Jolson, the FDA's antiviral chief,
said she was concerned that doctors were considering them to the
exclusion of everything else. Antibiotics, she said, still are
necessary to prevent secondary infections in chronically ill and
weakened elderly patients, such as the three who died.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA also said it had ordered Relenza's manufacturer in
November to stop showing television ads that overstated its
effectiveness. And it warned that Relenza inhalants should not be
prescribed to anyone with asthma or other lung diseases because
they could trigger asthma attacks or wheezing.
</P>
<P>
   Both new drugs must be administered within 48 hours of the first
flu symptoms to be effective at all.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, they've been shown to shorten the duration of
symptoms by no more than a day and a half. The nasal Relenza also
is allowed to claim a 28 percent reduction in complications, while
oral Tamiflu can claim a 30 percent to 40 percent reduction of
symptoms' severity.
</P>
<P>
   The British National Health Service doesn't pay for Relenza, the
only one approved in Great Britain, saying it's not cost-effective.
Locally, UnitedHealthcare imposes its highest co-payments on the
drug because its benefits appear to be so limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a couple of very good anecdotes, but those are from
physicians who put themselves on it,'' says Dr. Norman Schneiderman
of Miami Valley Hospital. ``Physicians tend to recognize their
diseases early.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to the drugs' effectiveness is the 48-hour
window. Only 28 percent of Americans saw a health care professional
the last time they had the flu, according to a recent Gallup survey
of 1,000 adults for the maker of Tamiflu. ``And those who did
waited two days or more after they developed flu symptoms,'' said
the manufacturer, Hoffman-LaRoche.
</P>
<P>
   The new drugs aren't viral equivalents of antibiotics, says
Schneiderman. While antibiotics kill bacteria, Relenza and Tamiflu
merely disable the enzyme that enables the influenza A and B
viruses to spread to new cells.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the new drugs effective for the many maladies with
flulike symptoms that aren't actually influenza, Schneiderman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that people aren't going to get flu shots or worry
about the flu because they think they've got this magic bullet,''
he says. ``It's not. The final verdict is not in yet on these
drugs, but they do not appear to have the miraculous efficacy or
safety of antibiotics.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
