<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-HEALTH-LAMB-COX     01-24 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-LAMB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't confuse mental illness with character weaknesses
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Major League Baseball's order that repulsive
Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker undergo psychological testing is
not just appalling because it's trying to cure bigotry the way the
Soviets used to cure capitalism or individuality.
</P>
<P>
   The order also is shameful because it reinforces the bigoted
misconceptions that mental illness is a character weakness and that
psychology is at odds with personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Those myths underlie the stigma and insurance inequities that
are primary reasons that most Americans with legitimate mental
disorders don't seek treatment, as Dr. David Satcher announced two
months ago in the most significant U.S. Surgeon General's report
since the one saying tobacco was not a healthy vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Mental illnesses, from anxiety disorders to schizophrenia, are
not moral flaws any more than diabetes, another disease of
imbalanced body chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   And psychological treatment of mental disorders _ outside the
hands of lawyers _ increases a person's responsibility instead of
absolving it. Good treatment provides tools, not excuses. If you
gave a wastebasket to a family with trash all over the floor, can
you imagine someone saying you were excusing and encouraging the
family's filth?
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's insults of women, Japanese, foreigners, homosexuals,
blacks and New Yorkers in Sports Illustrated last month were
contemptible and indefensible, compounded by his belligerent lack
of contrition. He deserves the public condemnation he's getting.
But if anything about his comments betrayed a mental illness, it
wasn't bigotry. Prejudice is sadly universal, based on people's
size, shape, age and motor skills if not race, ethnicity and sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly expressing these prejudices, however, could indicate a
mental illness ``that affects your ability to control your actions
or your ability to understand reality,'' psychiatrist Dr. Walter
Reich of George Washington University wrote online in Slate
magazine. But MLB's order had less a spirit of ``Let's get this guy
some help'' than of ``Let's punish this guy for staining our good
name.''
</P>
<P>
   The broader problem with baseball's action is that it presumes
to police thoughts. The recent history of centrally prohibited
thoughts has been one of death camps, not increased tolerance. Even
today and even in churches, there are places where belief in the
equality of women and gays is frowned on.
</P>
<P>
   The medical problem here, Reich writes, is that bad people
aren't necessarily mad. ``The widespread tendency to turn to
psychiatry when dealing with moral transgressions . . . damages not
only society but also psychiatry.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of accepted psychiatric diagnoses rose from 60 in
1952 to 410 in 1994, not in order to give lawyers more ways of
getting criminals off but to give doctors and therapists more
specific ways of treating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   So ``rage disorder'' is diagnosed not so a person can say, ``I
can't help it,'' but so he can say, ``I can find out how to help
it,'' by using new coping strategies and medication. Only by
manipulating these diagnoses with unconscionable cynicism do people
try to absolve a cad or criminal by citing ``lottery stress
disorder'' or ``gay panic.''
</P>
<P>
   But people tend to mistake explanations for excuses, as Hillary
Clinton learned last year. When she attributed her husband's skirt
chasing partly to family conflicts in his childhood, her
explanation was ridiculed as rationalization.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that President Clinton sought pastoral counseling
instead of psychotherapy for his problem shows how thoroughly
stigmatized is mental health treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fastest-growing diagnoses is
attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder, for which drug
prescriptions from 1990 to 1995 nearly tripled, to one of every 30
U.S. children from 5 through 18. It was wonderful that some people
received badly needed help and dreadful that others received an
unneeded crutch. ``Hundreds and perhaps thousands'' of well-to-do
kids are converting questionable diagnoses into extra time for
taking college board tests, the Los Angeles Times reported this
month.
</P>
<P>
   When psychology is abused this way, it hurts kids who really
have ADHD by suggesting it's not really serious and by discouraging
effective treatment. The criminal justice system has done the same
thing to people with serious psychiatric disorders, so that we
execute people who couldn't grasp reality if it came with a handle,
while at the same time indulging the defense of violent stalking
because of ``Internet intoxication.''
</P>
<P>
   Mental illness isn't a weakness. Using its science for excuses
instead of improvement is a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
