r l BC-MENSTRUATION-TEX     01-24 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENSTRUATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDOMETRIOSIS: HOW MARILYN MONROE AND I ARE LINKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am convinced that stopping my menstrual periods long ago made
it possible for me to be a mother.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe was not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   After my open-abdominal surgery for severe endometriosis 17
years ago, my gynecologist prescribed birth-control pills to be
taken continuously, without stopping for a menstrual period each
month, until I was ready to get pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   In some women, menstruation leads to endometriosis, a sometimes
painful disease in which fragments of the lining of the uterus can
be scattered throughout the pelvic area and even up to the lungs.
The fragments continue to grow wherever they land and can cause
pain, bleeding and infertility.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe battled the debilitating agony of endometriosis
for more than 10 years. She knew not only the cramping pain, but
also the infertility and miscarriages that often result.
</P>
<P>
   Until about 1970, the treatment for severe endometriosis was to
remove the ovaries and put an end to the periodic stimulation of
endometrial tissue. Now, in most cases, we have far-less-formidable
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe underwent seven operations to remove hemorrhagic
endometrial tissue from her pelvic and abdominal organs, but she
refused a hysterectomy, most likely because she desperately wanted
to become a mother, says Dr. Elsimar Coutinho in his new book, ``Is
Menstruation Obsolete?''
</P>
<P>
   And doctors didn't know back then that menstruation could be
suppressed to prevent endometrial tissue from reappearing. Instead,
they gave Monroe greater and greater quantities of narcotics to
numb the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course she was unhappy, but why was she unhappy? Ten days a
month she was absolutely out of it, suffering intolerable pain or
on high doses of narcotic pain relievers and hypnotics,'' Coutinho
said in a recent telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you treat patients with endometriosis or have had
endometriosis yourself, you understand this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is probable that Marilyn Monroe's death, caused by an
overdose of prescribed narcotics, was accidental,'' Coutinho
contends. ``One cannot escape the conclusion that her endometriosis
was a determining factor in the drug dependency that made her
accidental death predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Birth-control pills, now widely used to suppress menstruation in
the treatment of endometriosis, first appeared just two years
before Monroe's death in 1962, and the injectable progesterone
DepoProvera was discovered a year after she died.
</P>
<P>
   Coutinho pioneered the use of DepoProvera for the treatment of
endometriosis soon after it was introduced to prevent late-term
miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not endometriosis that took the life of Marilyn Monroe,
but it certainly contributed substantially to her enormous mental
and physical suffering, leading to her dependence on painkilling
drugs, which ultimately killed her,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   I have been taking DepoProvera shots once every three months the
past 13 years for endometriosis.
</P>
<P>
   The hormone not only prevents pain, but also prevents periods
and premenstrual syndrome. When friends hear about the side
effects, they tell me how lucky I am to have endometriosis. If not
for that, I would not have been prescribed DepoProvera years before
it became widely used in this country.
</P>
<P>
   And after talking with Coutinho and thinking about Monroe and
her pain, I realize just how lucky I am.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
