A5233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FLU-TIPS-COX     01-24 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Folk remedies accelerate immune system
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Despite recent advances in drugs for influenza,
treatment of colds and the flu is essentially a matter of
suppressing symptoms. Medical doctors and pharmacists recommend
using over-the-counter medications that target a person's specific
cough, congestion, aches and pains, runny nose or fever.
</P>
<P>
   Naturopathic and herbal practitioners approach colds and flu
from another direction, accelerating the immune system response
that causes the unpleasant symptoms. Their therapies tend to be
gentler, although herbal medicines also can have unwanted side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `wet socks treatment' is a great way to stimulate the
immune system and draw congestion away from the upper body,'' says
Dr. Judith Boice, a Portland, Ore., naturopath who grew up in
Centerville.
</P>
<P>
   The patient starts by soaking his feet in water as hot as he can
tolerate for five to 10 minutes. Then, after drying his feet, he
drenches a pair of cotton socks in cold tap water and wrings them
out so they are damp but not dripping. He then puts on the damp
cotton socks, covers them with dry woolen socks, gets into bed and
goes to sleep. Sometimes it takes more than one night, Boice says.
</P>
<P>
   People respond differently to specific folk remedies, but using
them quickly and aggressively ``will sometimes limit severity or
even abort a cold,'' says Dr. Mary L. Hardy, a Los Angeles
internist at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center and member of the American
Botanical Society and the American Holistic Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific research has shown that hot chicken soup, for
example, ``not only helps break up nasal congestion but also
contains garlic, which has antibiotic properties,'' Hardy says.
</P>
<P>
   Goldenseal, ginger and thyme also have some antibiotic value,
she says, while lemon balm and licorice are somewhat antiviral.
There is evidence that echinacea and goldenseal boost the immune
system both preventively and after symptoms appear. And few can
dispute the ability of pepper, ginger and horseradish to help clear
sinuses.
</P>
<P>
   Boice suggests going a day without solid food. That not only
diverts the body's energy from digestion to fighting infection, but
also encourages drinking more fluids. Drinking water is an
effective decongestant and also keeps the mucous membranes moist,
better able to ward off germs.
</P>
<P>
   A salt water gargle, with two teaspoons per glass, ``is
excellent for soothing a sore throat and also kills bacteria and
viruses,'' Boice says.
</P>
<P>
   One area where medical and naturopathic doctors agree is that
nothing beats rest for putting respiratory illnesses behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us try to push and push and push,'' Boice says. ``You
should rest until the fever's broken, and then for another 24
hours. If you get up before then, you'll probably be sick again
within six weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Web site for naturopathic physician Judith Boice is
www.drjudithboice.com
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
