A5234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFC-NOTES-COX     01-24 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC NOTEBOOK: Rams ready to bring Georgia to Georgia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Rams' travel plans are complete. The NFC
champions' charter will depart at 2:30 p.m. today and is scheduled
to land at Hartsfield International shortly around 4 p.m. The top
name in their travel party will be there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said a long time ago we wanted to take Georgia to
Georgia,'' coach Dick Vermeil said, smiling at Rams owner Georgia
Frontiere after Sunday's 11-6 victory against Tampa Bay put the
Rams back in the Super Bowl for the first time in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday night in the Georgia Dome, Georgia's Rams will
reunite with Tennessee. The AFC champion Titans beat St. Louis
24-21 Oct. 31 in Nashville, the Rams' lowest point total this
season until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little revenge factor to this whole deal,'' Rams
cornerback Todd Lyght said. ``I remember leaving Tennessee with a
sick feeling in my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Ugly ending
</P>
<P>
   The game was as contentious as it was close and physical. It got
ugly near game's end; after Shaun King's last pass was batted away,
Rams strong safety Billy Jenkins nearly got into a fight with Trent
Dilfer, the Bucs' starting quarterback at the beginning of the year
but on the sidelines in street clothes after breaking his clavicle
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of feeling going through the whole game,''
said Jenkins. ``Obviously, they were mad. I was just waving 'Bye'
to him (Dilfer). He came out there and butted into his teammates'
business. It got a little out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said Dilfer came out on the field because Bucs right
guard Frank Middleton had been yelling at the Rams all game,
calling them ``cheap-shot artists, going for knees.''
</P>
<P>
   First things first
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive week, St. Louis set the tone on its
first play from scrimmage. This time, though, it nearly
foreshadowed disaster.
</P>
<P>
   When Kurt Warner dropped back and tried to hit Marshall Faulk on
a screen pass, Bucs right defensive end Steve White jumped,
deflected the ball with his right hand, then intercepted at the
Rams 20. That led to Martin Gramatica's first field goal and was in
stark contrast to last week's divisional playoff win. That day,
Warner hit Isaac Bruce for a 77-yard touchdown on the Rams' first
play.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, who threw just 13 regular-season interceptions, threw
three against Tampa Bay, his only three-interception game all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly kicking himself
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil's decision to go with kicker Jeff Wilkins nearly
backfired. With Wilkins suffering from patella tendinitis in his
nonkicking knee, Vermeil brought in three kickers to audition
Tuesday and nearly went with retiree Nick Lowery, 43, who'd last
kicked in 1996. Vermeil was satisfied Wilkins could kick after
practicing Thursday. Wilkins did kick a 24-yard field goal in the
first quarter, but he missed a 44-yarder in the second and would
have faced a 47-yarder had Ricky Proehl not caught the winning
30-yard TD pass.Last things first
</P>
<P>
   How rare was the Rams' five-point first half? The last time they
hadn't scored a touchdown at home in the first half was Nov. 29,
1998, in a 21-10 loss to the Falcons. That was 11 home games ago.
</P>
<P>
   The last time this season St. Louis hadn't scored a first-half
touchdown? Game 7, at Tennessee. The last time a conference
championship game was this low-scoring? When these teams met in the
1979 NFC title game, the Rams getting three Frank Corral field
goals to win 9-0.Georgian on my mind
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Clemons, the Rams' backup linebacker from Griffin, Ga.,
who played for the University of Georgia in 1992-93, had a big sack
in the divisional playoff win and an even bigger one Sunday. With
Tampa Bay facing a third-and-3 at the Rams 26 late in the second
quarter, Clemons sacked King and forced a fumble. Tampa Bay
recovered but lost 12 yards, was taken out of field goal range and
had to punt.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch
</P>
<P>
   Rookie wide receiver Torry Holt bruised his ribs while falling
on the ball after catching a quick hitch pattern late in the first
quarter and being tackled by Donnie Abraham. The X-rays were
negative and Holt returned for the Rams' first possession of the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
