A5236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHIO-GANGS-COX     01-24 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GANGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio launches anti-gang effort
 &HT;    By Michael C. Bender
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ The first meeting of a statewide anti-gang
committee met Monday and announced 22 more meetings will be held
from February through May.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Against Gangs, a statewide gang prevention and suppression
committee, has $314,000, including $235,000 from a federal grant,
for its program, Ohio Attorney General Betty Montgomery said. The
money will be used for salaries and summits planned over the next
four months, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to build a wall around violence, one brick at a
time,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton and Urbana are two of the 22 cities chosen for meetings.
Montgomery said the meetings will ``alert communities that have
failed to see problems that are gang related and help them come up
with local solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since gangs are a local problem, the best solutions will also
be local,'' Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton does not have a significant gang problem but the police
department is investigating allegations of gang activity in the
city, police Lt. David Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Montgomery, Ohio has the nation's fourth highest
gang population after California, Illinois and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gangs are a part of a national epidemic of violence,''
Montgomery said. She then listed several violent video games
including ``Kingpin: Life of Crime,'' which, she said, specifically
glorifies gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main problems with investigating gangs is the thin
line that separates common sense and fear, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really easy to get so into the process (of identifying
gangs) that you think everybody wearing a certain hat or shoe is in
a gang,'' the lieutenant said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that Ohio law makes a witch hunt almost
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Revised Code defines a gang as a group of at least
three people with a common name or common signs or symbols who have
engaged in a pattern of criminal activity.
</P>
<P>
   Michael C. Bender writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio. E-mail: mike_bendercoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
