<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RENO-DEVELOP-ART-NYT     01-24 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-DEVELOP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RENO RISES, ITS ONCE-GRAND CASINO HOTEL IS MARKED FOR
DESTRUCTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(fb) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. _ The second floor of the Mapes Hotel had been
gutted. Mayor Jeff Griffin stood ankle deep in the wreckage of what
had been a suite, bits of red-velvet-wallpapered walls all around
him, and glanced out a gaping window.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see from here where Reno is going,'' he said,
gesturing toward a construction site for the expanding Holiday
Hotel. ``We have big plans for this place, and whatever will be on
the Mapes property will be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, anchored by the Mapes, the first resort-casino hotel in
the nation, Reno had contended with Las Vegas as the premier
gambling arena in the country. Then Atlantic City went neon, Vegas
exploded into a gambling Disney World and casinos opened on
seemingly every road and riverboat west of the Mississippi. Reno,
with its quaint neon arch proclaiming itself the ``biggest little
city in the world'' began to look very small indeed. Casinos began
closing and the city found itself way down on the list of places
vacationers ventured to lose their money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, signs point to a resurrection. A 12-theater cinema opened
in the fall. So did a promenade and park along the Truckee River.
Artists' lofts are in the works. New galleries and antique stores
dot the downtown. The convention center is doing brisk business. A
summer arts festival on the river draws huge crowds. Casinos that
closed over the last five years, like the Holiday, are reopening,
bigger than before, and those that rode out the rough times, like
Harrah's, are expanding.
</P>
<P>
   But then there is the Mapes.
</P>
<P>
   For many here _ 57 percent of all residents, according to a
recent poll commissioned by preservationists _ it is hard to cheer
for a future Reno without the 12-story Mapes Hotel. Built in 1947
by Charles Mapes with 1920s Art Deco architectural plans, it was
the first hotel in the country designed to provide rooms, a casino
and live entertainment under one roof. Its Sky Room, a glass-walled
promenade on the top floor with vast views of the Sierra Nevada,
was the place to go in the 1950s, when Reno was a destination for
people from all over the country. The Marx Brothers, Tony Bennett,
Marilyn Monroe and the Rat Pack all played the Sky Room, with Sammy
Davis Jr. making his debut there. Later, locals clamored to book
the room for proms and weddings.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, which closed in 1982 after years of decline, became a
national landmark in 1984, and in 1998 it was placed on the
National Trust for Historic Preservation's list of the 11 most
endangered historic sites in the country.
</P>
<P>
   For years, as prospective developers came and went, pigeons
roosted on the top floors and the building, hard by the river,
stood dark and forbidding, the tallest, saddest building on Reno's
main street.
</P>
<P>
   It is to be imploded on Jan. 30, Super Bowl Sunday, and when it
falls, Reno will become the first city in the country to fail to
preserve a site since the National Trust began issuing its list of
endangered sites 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while preservationists have dropped a federal lawsuit to
stop the demolition, the National Trust insists that the hotel can
still be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuing to pursue any and all options to stop what
we consider to be a needless demolition of a truly historic
American landmark by the city of Reno,'' said Gary Kozel, a
spokesman for the National Trust. ``We've proven that the majority
of the citizens of Reno wanted it saved, and that a reputable
developer stands ready to save it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the Mapes has dominated the news in northern Nevada
for months, and continues to do so. Over the weekend, the National
Trust began a campaign to have residents flood City Hall with
telephone calls insisting that the Mapes be spared.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger issue raised by the fight is at what price should
a city save a historic building? Reno officials say that after 17
years of developers coming in with grand plans, then backing out,
enough is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Officials, who voted to demolish the building in September,
after rejecting as unworkable six proposals to rehabilitate the
hotel, also say they are frustrated that the story of Reno's
redevelopment has been lost in the flap over a 52-year-old hotel
that had 7-foot ceilings, rooms barely big enough for a double bed,
and so much patched-together terra cotta construction that it would
cost at least $25 million to bring the building up to code.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the National Trust to call the Mapes the most historic
building in Nevada is disingenuous, I think,'' Griffin said. ``This
is not a grand building. It was the first hotel with a casino in
the country, it was the tallest building you could find in the
entire state for 10 years, and it had a magnificent Sky Room. It
was a big deal. Then it started to go into decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The city bought the hotel for $4.5 million in 1996, he said, in
the hopes of finding a white knight to rescue it from certain
destruction. It will have spent $6 million on the building after
the demolition.
</P>
<P>
   A $23 million proposal by an Oakland developer, Nationwide
Capital Services, to turn the building into housing for the elderly
was rejected by the city as inappropriate for the site, the mayor
said. The developer, Karl Diaz-Hoffmann, said the city had not
appeared interested in saving the building. Others have wondered
whether the city had a deal lined up with one of the casino owners
to buy the property.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor said Diaz-Hoffmann's plan simply did not work. ``A
senior citizens building does not fit in there, in the prime corner
at the beginning of the city's casino area,'' Griffin said. ``Not
to mention that whatever stands here will not be 12 stories tall.
The building is too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists say the plans would have fit quite nicely and
defend the building's historic value.
</P>
<P>
   ``That building was put on the national register because it was
so significant that it didn't even have to wait 50 years to become
a landmark,'' said Toni Mollett Harsh, president of the Truckee
Meadows Heritage Trust.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Reed, dean of the business school at the University of
Nevada in Reno, said that many Reno citizens had become weary of
the Mapes and the on-again, off-again plans to save it. With Reno
on an upswing, new residents and new businesses moving in, and many
residents familiar with the Mapes only as the old boarded-up
building too tall for its neighbors, the nostalgia for the hotel is
not as great as the die-hard fans think, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the contractor hired to demolish the building announced
that he would sell the building's bricks for $1 each on Super Bowl
Sunday, potential customers began going to the construction site to
reserve their souvenirs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
