<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NY     01-24 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN, TAKING AIM AT BUSH, PLAYS UP CHARACTER AND EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (With MCCAIN-AD) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, N.H. _ Going right to the heart of Gov. George W.
Bush's biggest potential vulnerability, Sen. John McCain portrayed
himself Monday as the only candidate who ``understands the world''
and who is ``fully prepared to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   In comments on the stump and in a new 30-second television
commercial, McCain touted his military and government experience as
providing the necessary preparation for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one man running for president who knows the
military and understands the world _ John McCain,'' the new ad
says. ``If America is to lead, then America's leader must be
prepared for that challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain denied to reporters that he was suggesting that Bush was
not ready to be president, and he joked that ``I'm always put in
the terrible position where I'm defending Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet no matter how much McCain tried to slide away from it, the
new commercial and other statements he made Monday suggest an
aggressive move against the Texas governor on what many critics
consider his greatest weakness, foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Several times Monday McCain repeated that the nation needed ``a
steady hand on the tiller.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the day brought McCain's campaign full circle, away
from the recent fights with Bush over tax cuts and back to
character and personal biography, which is how McCain, a one-time
prisoner-of-war in North Vietnam, began his run for president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain long ago made a decision not to compete in Iowa and to
concentrate instead on winning the Republican primary in New
Hampshire, a state with a history of falling for underdogs and
mavericks. So as the other candidates made their final Iowa
appeals, he alone traversed New Hampshire's snowy byways, Monday
drawing dozens of television cameras along the way.
</P>
<P>
   All through the grueling day, his campaign used visual touches
to remind voters of McCain's devotion to New Hampshire. The Arizona
senator's midday stop here in a chilly, cavernous room at the
Plymouth Armory was his 100th New Hampshire town hall meeting. And
he celebrated by cutting a big white cake with an icing silhouette
of the state on it as loudspeakers blared ``Johnny B. Goode.''
</P>
<P>
   As McCain walked into the hall he was greeted by blaring music
and the booming bass-voiced tones of an announcer, touches that are
usually staples of general election campaign rallies and that have
been missing from McCain's lower-key chat sessions with voters.
</P>
<P>
   It was in front of students at Moultonborough Academy on Monday
morning, after he was grilled on issues like family planning,
abortion, the Confederate flag and China, that McCain gave his most
full-throated appeal to voters to make their choice less on issues
than on a candidate's experience and character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I am better prepared than any of the other
candidates,'' he told the high school students. ``I will stack my
experience, my position on issues, everything I've done, against
those other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``What really matters is your impression of what we
talked about here today _ not about specific issues such as Planned
Parenthood or China _ but how you leave this room and say `gee, I
believe I can place my confidence in that old geezer to lead this
country.'''
</P>
<P>
   Across the day McCain also hewed to his signature theme of
campaign finance overhaul. When a man asked whether he supported
term limits, he objected, ``My problem is that we throw out the
good people as well as the bad.'' But he said that overhauling the
campaign finance system would have an effect similar to term limits
by ending the ``the incumbency protection racket.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get the government out of the hands of the big
money special interests that keep all these people in office and
give the government back to you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator often says that one of his greatest hopes is to
inspire young people and combat the cynicism that has left fewer
and fewer of them voting. But his town hall meetings usually draw
high proportions of the elderly, who are attracted to his military
themes and pledges to help veterans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Monday morning at Moultonborough Academy, McCain seemed
uncomfortable at times, particularly when the first three questions
were about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   His very first question, from a young man, was whether he would
reinstate the Reagan era rule that prevented international family
planning clinics that receive federal funds from discussing
abortion. ``I don't believe they should advocate abortion with my
tax dollars,'' McCain said, adding that he opposed abortion except
in cases of rape and incest. Then a young woman asked how he would
determine whether someone had in fact been raped.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping his arms tightly around his chest, McCain said, ``I
think that I would give the benefit of the doubt to the person who
alleges that.'' In answer to another student, he said he did not
think women would lie about being raped in order to be eligible for
an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Tom Webster, wanted to know whether McCain
cared more about victory in South Carolina than for the people who
were offended by the Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I do not,'' McCain answered.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old asked, ``You think the flag should be taken
down?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said, ``I think that's up to the people of South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   And the senator repeated his answer as the teen-ager twice
persisted in asking, ``But is it right or wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Webster said, ``I thought he was dodging the issue. I
thought it was kind of cowardly.'' He said that if he were old
enough to vote he would pick Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the time, McCain, who is repeatedly introduced as a
hero, has been drawing unsolicited tributes from his audiences as
people implicitly contrast him with President Clinton. ``I don't
have a question,'' one woman told McCain, standing to speak at the
Plymouth Armory. ``I just want to thank you for your integrity.
It's extremely important to me that the next president of the
United States tell me the truth no matter what.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NIH-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      01-24 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIH-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CANDIDATES FOR HEAD OF HEALTH INSTITUTES EMERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two brain scientists have emerged as the leading
candidates to be director of the National Institutes of Health at a
time when Congress is pouring money into the agency in hopes of
unlocking the secrets of many diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Monday that Donna Shalala, the
secretary of health and human services, had identified the two
neuroscientists as her candidates to lead the agency, the chief
sponsor of biomedical research in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The contenders are Dr. Gerald D. Fischbach, director of the
National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke, and Dr.
Steven E. Hyman, director of the National Institute of Mental
Health. Both have taught at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Fischbach and Hyman were appointed to their current jobs by Dr.
Harold E. Varmus, who stepped down last month as director of the
National Institutes of Health to become president of Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will select a nominee and send the name to the
Senate for confirmation. Ordinarily, a president in the last year
of his term would have little hope of getting the Senate to approve
a nominee for so important a job. But administration officials said
they had consulted Congress and found that lawmakers wanted to have
a strong manager in charge of the agency as its budget grows by
nearly 15 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has begun a five-year effort to double the budget of
the National Institutes of Health. The budget was increased by $2
billion last year, and by another $2 billion this year, to $17.8
billion. Clinton will propose a further increase of $1 billion when
he sends Congress his 2001 budget request next month, the White
House said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may again provide more than Clinton requests, as it has
in each of the last few years. But some lawmakers said they would
insist on a detailed explanation of how the agency was spending the
extra money it has received.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers told Shalala that the nominee must have impeccable
scientific credentials and no strong identification with either
political party. Administration officials said that Shalala's
candidates met those requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Fischbach, 61, was chairman of the neurobiology departments at
Harvard Medical School and Massachusetts General Hospital before he
became director of the neurological institute here in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A former president of the Society for Neuroscience, he has
studied synapses, the connections between brain cells or between
neurons and muscle. He devised methods to study outside the body
the link between nerves and muscles, and he identified a protein
that is secreted by nerve cells and induces the formation of
synapses.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman, 47, played a large role in the White House Conference on
Mental Health last June and in the landmark report on mental health
issued last month by the surgeon general of the United States. He
is an expert on the molecular biology of psychiatric disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking his current job in April 1996, Hyman studied the
way in which drugs like cocaine and morphine cause long-term
changes in brain circuits. He searches for genes that may, with
environmental factors, make people vulnerable to mental disorders
like schizophrenia and manic-depressive illness.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth L. Kirschstein, who has worked at the NIH in various
positions for over 40 years, has been acting director since Jan. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
