<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-FIRSTELECT-COX     01-24 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FIRSTELECT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush vows to bring 'honor, dignity' back to White HouseBy Ken
Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERRY, Iowa _ On the day that a Bush was on a presidential
ballot for the first time since the nation ousted one in 1992, Gov.
George W. Bush on Monday continued to score stump-speech points by
zinging the man who beat his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the beginning of the end of the Clinton era in
Washington, D.C.,'' he said Monday, drawing loud applause with the
line in Ames and Perry as he made a final campaign swing en route
to a season-opening win in the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The applause swelled again with the Clinton-related punchline
that has punctuated the Bush stump speech for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I be the person that America chooses to become the
president, when I put my hand on the Bible, I will swear to not
only uphold the laws of the land, I will swear to uphold the honor
and dignity of the office to which I have been elected,'' Bush
said. ``So help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Texas governor, the Iowa victory marked a big day that
can be linked directly to one of the worst days in his life: Nov.
3, 1992, when Bill Clinton made the elder George Bush a one-termer.
</P>
<P>
   If the elder Bush had won re-election, there is little chance
his son would now be the odds-on favorite to win the GOP
nomination. But on Monday, the younger Bush refused to buy into the
theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think my victory in '94 against Governor (Ann)
Richards was the first step toward being here. I really don't dwell
on my dad's defeat. I think what started me in my political march
was winning the governorship in '94 and doing in office what I said
I would do, and winning re-election,'' said Bush, always wary of
anything that might make his candidacy look like family revenge.
``So I don't quite see the connection. Nice try.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's last day in Iowa began early with the morning sun on his
face as he headed into a Des Moines restaurant to chat with the
breakfast crowd and give the TV cameras something to show all day.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Bush headed to a rally at Iowa State University _
site of the August straw poll that gave Bush a big, early win and
sent several candidates spiralling toward oblivion. Two of those _
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former American Red Cross
President Elizabeth Dole _ are now Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   The Ames rally marked a campaign crossroads in Iowa, a common
occurrence in a state overrun with candidates, with Democrat Bill
Bradley speaking at another rally in the same building.
</P>
<P>
   After Ames, Bush headed to Perry where students and locals
packed a high school gym in which the Bush signs were on the walls
next to banners marking the school's 1930 girls state basketball
title and 1936 state football championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced he is going to return dignity and honor to the
White House,'' Iowa Sen. Charles Grassley, who traveled with Bush
for several days, told the Perry crowd.
</P>
<P>
   From Perry, Bush, who also did several local radio interviews
during the day, headed back to Des Moines where the schedule called
for him to nap and exercise before showing up to declare victory at
a rally.
</P>
<P>
   After acknowledging cheering backers at the Des Moines Marriott,
Bush headed to the airport for a flight to New Hampshire where he
will campaign toward the crucial Feb. 1 primary.
</P>
<P>
   That effort began with an airport rally planned for 2:30 a.m. at
the airport in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, it was a solid day that began with him noting that
among his biggest hurdles has been high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great expectations surrounding me ever since I got
started, so I'm used to it,'' he said. ``But this is a long
process. Tonight is a very important night in the process. It's the
beginning of the nominating process and I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
