<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-IGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DISNEY NO. 2 KNOWN FOR COOLNESS UNDER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With DISNEY-APPOINT) 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What put Robert Iger on a hyperfast track as an executive at ABC
in the late 1980s was his coolness under a heat wave in very
unexpected circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the Olympics in Calgary,'' said Daniel Burke, the
president of Capital Cities-ABC, as that company was known before
its acquisition by Walt Disney Co. ``We knew going in that we were
going to lose a lot of money. And then one day, of all things, it
was warmer in Calgary than it was in Miami. The bobsled and luge
runs were starting to melt. We watched Bob in the middle of that,
reorganizing our plans for the broadcast that night. He was totally
cool and collected.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a year Iger, a sports programming executive, became an
assistant to the then-president of ABC, John Sias. A year later he
was running ABC Entertainment division, though he had never been to
a Hollywood party in his life.
</P>
<P>
   According to current and former associates and co-workers,
Iger's unflappable exterior covers a hard-driving, exceedingly
high-energy executive, known throughout ABC and Disney for working
from before dawn until late at night, for mastering details of
business with creative flair, and for amassing and synthesizing
prodigious amounts of often complicated information.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Eisner, the Disney chairman who appointed Iger president
of Disney _ and effectively his second-in-command _ on Monday, said
Iger's broad resume from working in sports, entertainment and cable
at ABC and in the international division of Disney made the
appointment all but inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the easiest, most obvious thing I've done in a
while,'' Eisner said. Indeed, he added, he first broached the idea
of bringing Iger in as president two years ago. ``But we had just
completed a $19 billion acquisition of ABC. I'm a believer in
keeping your eye on the ball. I couldn't move Bob until ABC was in
a strong position.''
</P>
<P>
   After a period when that goal seemed to be elusive for both
Eisner and Iger, ABC has become, in the last several months, one of
the most impressive turnaround stories in the media world, with the
company on track to improve profits dramatically, thanks in
considerable part to the amazing impact of one hit, the game show
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior ABC executive said that series alone could contribute
an additional $250 million to ABC in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Iger praised the executive team now in place at ABC, most of
whom have close ties to him. None goes back as far as Pat
Fili-Krushel, however, the president of ABC, who first shared a
work space with Iger 25 years ago. `'I was a secretary and he was a
production supervisor at ABC Sports,'' she said. ``We shared the
Xerox machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Iger's road through sports production toward corporate
leadership was marked by what Ms. Fili-Krushel called an unusual
ability to ``manage up and down with equal skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, among the occasional criticisms that have attached
themselves to Iger during his rise, is one that centers on his
ability to ``be the best at managing upward that anybody has ever
seen,'' as one senior executive who has worked with him put it.
This executive said that ``presentational style'' has always been
among Iger's strengths. ``He is flawless at that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the executive added that it occasionally hurt Iger with
people who questioned ``how good a good-looking executive can
really be.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said of Iger, ``People enjoyed propelling him forward and
watching how successful he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Iger was one of the earliest executives in the traditional
television business to anticipate the coming intersection with the
wired world, and he remains, as one colleague put it, ``the
earliest adapter of every gadget technology can produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner emphasized how important that knowledge will be in Iger's
new role at Disney, saying that finding the way for Disney to
maximize the value of its entertainment content in a digital world
is ``the single biggest issue on Bob's agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Iger said he looked forward to the challenge. ``I get excited by
a lot of the details of what has to be done.'' He said that finding
``value for Disney's great content'' will be his prime priority.
</P>
<P>
   First he will deal with the details of his personal life. Iger
currently lives a dual-coast, multi-network existence. His wife is
Willow Bay, the anchor of the daily ``Moneyline'' program on the
Cable News Network.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is a unit of Time Warner, which, if the
recently announced merger goes through, will be a unit of AOL-Time
Warner. Eisner said of the AOL chairman, `'Steve Case will just
have to find a way to move Willow's show to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Will his wife move with him? All Iger would say was, ``I'm
certainly going to live full time with my wife.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
