<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SCOTUS-REACT-NYT     01-24 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT'S RULING HEARTENS SOFT MONEY'S OPPONENTS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Mo., Wis., Ky., Mass., Conn., Vt.)  (With SCOTUS-FUNDRAISING) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advocates of new federal limits on campaign contributions,
especially the unregulated big gifts known as soft money, said
Monday that the Supreme Court's decision upholding Missouri's
donation ceiling strengthened their hand.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has made a ban on soft money a
centerpiece of his presidential campaign after failing to win its
passage in Congress, said of the ruling Monday while campaigning in
Plymouth, N.H.: ``I think it's marvelous, and it will help us in
our efforts to enact meaningful campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the decision leaves Congress free to curb campaign
donations, most supporters of new legislation have complained that
what Congress lacks is not constitutional authority but political
will.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell D. Feingold, D-Wis., McCain's chief ally in the
Senate effort to prohibit soft money, said Monday night that the
decision, combined with political success for McCain and former
Sen. Bill Bradley, another presidential candidate running against
big money's influence, might provide that will.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a tight race,'' he said, ``it's almost a no-brainer to be
against soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 decision said nothing directly about soft money. Rather,
the court reaffirmed the rationale it had set out in 1976, when it
barred limits on spending as a denial of free speech but upheld a
$1,000 contributed to a given federal candidate as a
constitutionally permissible precaution against corruption or the
appearance of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee and the National Republican
Senatorial Committee had called on the court to use the Missouri
case to throw out contribution limits, and Justice Clarence Thomas
urged that course Monday in dissent. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination, had no
comment Monday, but in a television interview on Sunday, agreed
with an earlier comment to that effect by Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Such urging had worried some advocates of tighter limits. Rep.
Chris Shays, R-Conn., who was a main sponsor of a campaign finance
overhaul bill that the House passed before a Senate filibuster
killed it Oct. 19, said, ``We were all kind of holding our
breaths.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the ruling, though not dealing with soft money, has
encouraged supporters of a soft-money ban with its approval of the
limit on hard-money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for instance, talking to reporters on his campaign bus
in New Hampshire, said, ``If they had invalidated the $1,000
contribution limit, then you're finished. Then it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affirming the $1,000 limit is a major, major thing. How many
times have we had the argument that money is free speech!''
</P>
<P>
   Bill McCarthy, deputy director of communications for the
Republican National Committee, said: ``We are disappointed by
today's decision. We believe that strict contribution limits
impinge on free speech, and the issue does deserve further
consideration by the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who heads the senatorial
campaign committee, insisted Monday's case was inconsequential and
had no relation to the soft money battle. He called it a ``narrow
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The case had no direct bearing on this year's federal elections,
and during oral argument on Oct. 5 the court showed little
inclination to reach as broadly as the Republicans wanted. But if
the court had thrown out Missouri's limit, the federal limit would
clearly have been imperiled in the long run, and some candidates
might have chosen to evade it this year.
</P>
<P>
   As matters stand, the issue has helped McCain and Bradley,
especially in New Hampshire, where neither makes a public
appearance without raising the subject, to frequent applause.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, The Nashua Telegraph wrote: ``We endorse Bradley and
McCain to send a message. Both men promise to tackle one of the
political system's worst features, the vast system of campaign
financing that amounts to shameless influence peddling. It's time
someone tackles that conduit of rot that so taints our political
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Other advocates of tighter limits joined McCain and Feingold in
praising the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one more weapon in our arsenal,'' said Rep. Martin
Meehan, D-Mass., who worked with Shays in the House. ``Today's
decision will strengthen the hands of the majorities in both houses
who voted against soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, a longtime supporter of tighter limits, ``This
decision peels away the phony argument that the Constitution can be
used to protect corrupting campaign spending.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas Mann, of the Brookings Institution and an expert on
Congress, said the importance of the decision was what it did not
do _ invalidate the contribution limits from the federal Election
Campaign Act of 1974. If it had done that, he said ``the entire
remaining edifice of campaign finance regulation would have crashed
to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, ``the current court believes that corruption
and the appearance of corruption is a compelling rationale for
restricting the flow of money,'' and Congress can do so if it has
the will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
