<HEADLINE>
COUP STAINS REPUTATION OF ECUADOR'S MILITARY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: This is an analysis) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Ousted President Jamil Mahuad wasn't the only
victim of last week's military uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the coup tarnished the reputation the Ecuadorean
military, long considered one of Latin America's most enlightened
armies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They now represent a danger to democracy,'' said Bertha
Garcia, a political science professor at Catholic University in
Ecuador's capital of Quito.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the military came to its senses just in time.
</P>
<P>
   After forcing out Mahuad on Friday, the general in charge of a
provisional junta stepped down early Saturday, allowing Vice
President Gustavo Noboa to claim the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a tendency to view this as a traditional coup,
but it's more complicated than that,'' said a U.S. military officer
who monitors Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high command did what it could to avoid violence and to
bring the country back as close as it could to constitutional
channels,'' said the officer, who spoke on condition that he not be
named.
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's uprising, thousands of Indians descended on
Quito to protest Ecuador's worst economic crisis since the Great
Depression. They occupied the Congress building and demanded that
Mahuad resign.
</P>
<P>
   Idealistic military officers were intrigued, and nearly 200
joined the revolt. Many were familiar with the Indians' plight.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers have long been dispatched to the poorest pockets of
Ecuador to build schools, vaccinate infants and plant trees. Such
civic-action programs have put troops in close contact with
Indians, who make up 25 percent of Ecuador's 12 million population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't just sit there with our arms crossed,'' said one
officer who joined the rebellion, according to the Quito newspaper
El Comercio.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that by forcing out Mahuad, the army pulled off a
coup, plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   But former Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Mendoza, a member of the
junta that briefly replaced Mahuad, said that army commanders were
simply trying to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Monday, Mendoza argued that by joining the
junta then stepping down three hours later, the effect was to
short-circuit the protests. In turn, civilian rule was restored and
the armed forces addressed its badly divided officer corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (army officers) were responding to a number of
pressures but high on the list was the need to reunify the
military,'' said Shelley McConnell, a Latin America expert at the
Carter Center in Atlanta. ``In Latin America, one thing that
militaries do not tolerate well is disunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Ecuador's military governments gave way to civilian
rule in 1979, the armed forces have generally supported democratic
rule.
</P>
<P>
   But democracy has often failed the people. Corruption has become
rampant, and poverty has increased. Thanks to brutal infighting _
often called ``political cannibalism'' here _ Ecuador has gone
through four presidents in the past three years. As a result, polls
regularly list the military as the nation's most popular
institution.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Ecuadoreans despised Mahuad, they were shocked
Friday to see military officers apparently taking over the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must be jailed so we never go through this circus
again,'' said Francisco Alarcon, president of the Chamber of
Industry in Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will review the issue this week, but so far just one
colonel has been detained. And Monday, President Noboa named Gen.
Telmo Sandoval, who many observers believe was part of a conspiracy
against Mahuad, as head of the military high command.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Fernando Bustamante said the new president
owes his job to the military and is unlikely to push for a purge of
the institution. Instead, the president may have to watch his own
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to keep an eye on the barracks much more than any
other president,'' Bustamante said.
</P>
<P>
   Others point out that neither the air force nor the navy took
part in Friday's rebellion. The vast majority of the officer corps
remained loyal to Mahuad to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard nothing from responsible senior leaders to indicate
that they want the burden of trying to run the country,'' said the
U.S. officer.
</P>
<P>
   Alarcon, the Chamber of Industry leader, suggested that
ambitious officers should simply quit the military and form a
political party.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Venezuela, Army Lt. Col. Hugo Chavez led a failed coup
attempt in 1992. He spent two years in jail, then ran for president
in 1998 and won.
</P>
<P>
   But few Ecuadorean military men have fared well in electoral
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Paco Moncayo, for example, was perhaps this nation's most
respected military leader. He later retired and won a congressional
seat. But on Friday, he joined the coup plotters and on Monday
resigned his seat in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you wear officer's bars doesn't mean you can run
the country,'' Alarcon said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials denounced the coup, but a cutoff of aid to the
Ecuadorean military is unlikely, said Adam Isacson of the Center
for International Policy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.S. Army's elite Special Forces have trained
more than 1,000 Ecuadorean troops in the past two years. And the
Pentagon is spending millions of dollars to upgrade a key military
base on the Pacific coast that will allow U.S. pilots to fly
anti-drug missions in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any real push to the make Ecuadorean military
more democratic because the line here is that they did the right
thing,'' Isacson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
