<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-STATES-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES ON REDISTRICTING AND MINORITY VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (lb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Monday in an important
voting-rights case that the Justice Department must approve
districting changes, even those adopted with a discriminatory
purpose, as long as the changes leave minority voters in no worse a
position than before.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision addressed a question that arises often in the
government's enforcement of the Voting Rights Act of 1965: What
should be done about a jurisdiction that chooses to entrench the
status quo in refusing, for example, to draw district lines that
would make it more likely for a black candidate to be elected where
none had been elected before?
</P>
<P>
   The section of the law at issue ``prevents nothing but
backsliding,'' Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the majority,
adding that the federal government's role in approving a change
``affirms nothing but the absence of backsliding.''
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion for the four dissenters, Justice David H. Souter
objected that the majority had adopted an ``exceedingly odd'' and
implausible interpretation that would leave the Voting Rights Act
``substantially diminished.'' The government, Souter said, would be
forced to approve ``unconstitutional voting schemes patently
intended to perpetuate discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, affirming a ruling by a special three-judge
federal district court panel here, upheld the 1992 redistricting of
the school board in Bossier Parish in Louisiana. The board's 12
districts included none with a majority of black voters, although
two majority-black districts could have been drawn under an
alternative plan that the local leadership of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People had presented to
the board.
</P>
<P>
   Section 5, the section of the 1965 law at issue, requires
``covered jurisdictions'' _ state and local governments across the
South as well as parts of some northern cities with histories of
low minority participation in voting _ to seek ``preclearance''
from the Justice Department or the federal district court here
before putting any voting change into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the jurisdiction has the legal burden of proving
that its change ``does not have the purpose and will not have the
effect of denying or abridging the right to vote on account of race
or color.'' After the Justice Department refused to preclear the
school board lines on the ground that Bossier Parish had not met
that burden, the county exercised its right to seek preclearance in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In approving the new lines, the district court said that all
that mattered was the absence of ``retrogression''; that is, even
if the school board had a discriminatory purpose, black voters
would fare no worse than they had before the change. The question
for the Supreme Court was whether Section 5 could be satisfied so
easily: whether the law's ``purpose'' test could be met, even if
the purpose was discriminatory, as long as there was no
retrogression.
</P>
<P>
   The decision rejected an approach to Section 5 preclearance that
the Justice Department had used for 30 years, under which
jurisdictions were required to prove not only a lack of effect, but
also the absence of a discriminatory purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the eve of the 2000 census, which will inevitably be
followed by a wave of redistricting and hundreds or thousands of
preclearance requests, the decision is likely to have a substantial
effect on the administration of the Voting Rights Act.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Civil rights lawyers have maintained that local governments are
much less likely now than in the past to adopt overtly
discriminatory strategies that, for example, actually reduced
existing black voting strength.
</P>
<P>
   A more subtle refusal to adopt available improvements is a more
likely strategy that can be shielded by the ``no retrogression''
test, lawyers who have handled these cases say. In its brief to the
court, the Justice Department said the standard that the district
court had adopted ``threatens seriously to impair enforcement of
the act.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Individual Rights, a conservative public interest
law firm here that represented Bossier Parish, said in a statement
Monday that the decision meant the Justice Department ``may no
longer use the preclearance provision of the Voting Rights Act to
force local jurisdictions to artificially maximize the number of
minority districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvin, the lawyer who argued the case, said the court
had ``effectively ended the Clinton Justice Department's efforts to
force localities to racially gerrymander under the Voting Rights
Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine DiBartolo, a spokeswoman for the department's civil
rights division, said the department was ``disappointed'' by the
decision but was determined to ``continue to use all means at our
disposal to ensure that all voters have an equal opportunity to
participate in the electoral system.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision did not involve another section of the law, Section
2, which applies nationwide and which provides another route to
challenging obstacles to full participation by minority voters. But
Section 5 has always been seen as the more powerful enforcement
tool in the circumstances in which it applies, because
jurisdictions have the burden of proof under Section 5 while
challengers have the burden of proof under Section 2.
</P>
<P>
   The case, Reno vs. Bossier Parish School Board, No. 98-405, has
been a particularly troublesome one for the court over the last
three years. After an initial decision in 1997, which sent the case
back to the lower court for further analysis, the justices heard
arguments last April without deciding the case. A second argument
was held in October.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia's majority opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and by Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy
and Clarence Thomas. Thomas wrote a concurring opinion pointing out
that three black candidates had been elected to the school board
from majority-white districts after the lawsuit was filed, thus
showing, he said, that majority-black districts were unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Justices John Paul Stevens, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.
Breyer joined Souter's dissenting opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
