<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SAYS CAMPAIGN IS ON RIGHT PATH
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Despite concerns among some aides about the state
of his campaign, former Sen. Bill Bradley said Monday that he was
more convinced than ever that the course he chartered for his
presidential campaign more than a year ago was fundamentally
correct.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bradley's insurgent campaign has been battered
by negative news coverage and falling poll numbers, and many
political analysts have argued that he has not been sharp enough in
drawing distinctions with Gore or aggressive enough in responding
to the vice president's repeated attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of his aides have recently raised questions about the
campaign's tactics in Iowa, complaining that it had been late
getting organized, slow to respond to Gore's criticisms and
inadequate in preparing Bradley for debates. One adviser described
Iowa as a ``shakedown tour'' for the Bradley organization.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Monday just before the Iowa caucuses,
Bradley suggested that if anything he had been too negative in his
battle with Gore, arguing that the ``rat-a-tat-tat'' of the race
might have turned off voters and drawn attention from his own
idealistic call to reform politics and end poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were trying to do a cookie-cutter campaign where you go
negative on somebody, there's a little textbook that you take that
says, chapter four, going negative, here are the five things you
do,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What adds to cynicism in politics is negative campaigning and
attack ads,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Bradley contends that he will try to stay above the
messy fray, his aides said they recognized that they, and Bradley's
prominent supporters, will need to strike back faster and perhaps
more fiercely against Gore when he goes on the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he realized his campaign had drifted from its
moorings last week when he heard the story of a New Hampshire woman
whose teen-age son apologized for getting sick because the family
had no health insurance. Her story, which brought tears to his
eyes, ``recentered'' him on the reasons he had entered the race,
particularly to create a system of near universal health insurance,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in the rat-a-tat-tat of politics, in the rush of the
media and the emphasis on tactics, you lose sight of why you're in
this,'' he said. But there may also be political reasons for
Bradley's wanting to step back from attacking Gore. Two weeks ago,
Bradley had been sharpening his criticism of the vice president,
even attacking a 15-year-old Senate vote by Gore that helped the
tobacco industry. But many analysts said Bradley's attacks gave a
sense of desperation in his camp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also toned down his criticism of Bradley in recent
days. Asked whether he would return fire if Gore started attacking
him again in New Hampshire, site of the nation's first primary next
Tuesday, Bradley replied, ``You always have the option, of course,
to adopt the atomic bomb. But the point is, I'm going to try to
keep this thing positive.''
</P>
<P>
   To both his critics and supporters, Bradley's refusal to
aggressively attack Gore recalls his 1990 re-election campaign,
where he was very slow to respond to criticism by his opponent,
Christie Whitman, and almost lost the New Jersey Senate race. Some
political analyst argued that the race showed that Bradley was too
headstrong to adjust his campaign strategies to deal with
unforeseen or shifting circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley denied that he was inflexible, saying: ``I think
there should be a distinction drawn between being inflexible and
being rooted. I'm rooted in what I know what I believe and what I
know I want to do. I'm flexible in how I want to achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no plans to change significantly his basic stump
speech in the coming weeks. But Bradley offered a glimpse Monday of
the message he intends to emphasize in New Hampshire: that he would
be better at maintaining the nation's prosperity because he has a
track record of predicting changes in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been on the point, meaning I have been there a few
years before other people,'' he said, referring to his early
support in the 1980s for cutting the deficit, reducing Third World
debt and simplifying the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also sought to cast himself as the best candidate for
managing the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he would increasingly highlight the economic
benefits of his health-care proposal, which he said would provide
the equivalent of a $25 billion-a-year tax cut for people earning
less than $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is those families don't know yet what I'm trying to
do,'' Bradley said of lower-income voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
