<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CAMPAIGN-KAN &LR;      01-24 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 High court upholds Missouri campaign contribution limit   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY and WILL SENTELL  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a decision that sent election-year ripples
across the country, the U.S. Supreme Court on Monday upheld
Missouri's $1,075 limit on campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled 6-3 that the Missouri limit, passed in 1994,
does not inhibit free speech. A different finding could have
undermined limits in nearly 30 other states as well as the $1,000
cap in presidential and congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   The court essentially reaffirmed a landmark 1976 ruling that the
federal campaign limit was an appropriate way to keep big donations
from corrupting politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little reason to doubt that sometimes large
contributions will work actual corruption on our political system
and no reason to question the existence of a corresponding
suspicion among voters,'' said Justice David Souter, writing for
the majority.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is seen as a boost for further campaign reform, such
as limits on so-called soft money that is spent indirectly to
benefit candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This a tremendous day in the history of the reform effort,''
said Sen. Russ Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat who wants to tighten
the financial reins on campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   More campaign-funding limits has been a rallying cry for
presidential candidate Sen. John McCain, a Republican from Arizona
and Bill Bradley, a Democrat and former senator from New Jersey.
McCain is co-sponsor of a bill with Feingold.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said the $1,075 limit in Missouri and the $1,000 limit
nationwide are too low, especially in light of inflation since
1976, when the court upheld the federal limit in Buckley vs. Valeo.
Congress imposed the federal limit in the wake of the Watergate
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's limit began at $1,000 in 1994 and increases with
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, a Kentucky Republican who has bucked
campaign finance reform, said a limit is warranted but should be no
lower than $3,000. The court ruling doesn't derail those hopes, a
lawyer for McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that remains clear is that Congress could legislate
a higher limit if it chooses to,'' said Bobby Burchfield, who filed
a brief in the case for McConnell and the Republican Party. ``They
may even be emboldened by the realization that the court is not
going to do it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Congress took sides in the Missouri case, and 29
states joined Missouri in defending the limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's opinion keeps open the door for states to pass
reasonable contribution limits,'' said Scott Harshbarger, president
of Common Cause, which advocates campaign spending restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon argued the case before the
high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big win for the state of Missouri in a landmark
decision that turns the tide nationally for campaign reform
efforts,'' he said. ``Quite simply, elections are not auctions and
candidates are not to be sold to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri limits were challenged by St. Louis resident Zev
David Fredman, who wanted to run for state auditor in early 1998.
He got one donation of $1,075 from a political action committee
called Shrink Missouri Government, and then went to court to test
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Fredman won before the 8th Circuit Court of Appeals in St.
Louis, which ruled 2-1 that there was no evidence that unlimited
contributions were corrupting.
</P>
<P>
   Fredman, a 37-year-old certified public accountant, said Monday
the court ruling works in favor of incumbent politicians because
they can raise more money from more sources than can a challenger
who may have to rely on a few major backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the politician's interest to reduce competition, and I
can't think of anything that reduces competition in a more
effective way than campaign finance limits,'' Fredman said.
</P>
<P>
   Souter said Missouri did not have to prove that unlimited
donations would cause corruption and that capping donations did not
limit free speech. That brought sharp rebukes from the three
dissenting justices _ Clarence Thomas, Anthony Kennedy and Antonin
Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the nation's founders believed that a self-governing
people depended upon free speech and free exchange of political
ideas. ``And that free exchange should receive the most attention
when it matters most _ during campaigns for elective office,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice John Paul Stevens argued that freedom to speak out
on issues and to inspire volunteers for the campaign is not the
same as the freedom to donate unlimited amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is property; it is not speech,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's Nixon said he interpreted the ruling to mean that
contributors who already have given the maximum under the law for
candidates in the primaries _ $1,075 for statewide offices _ cannot
contribute again until the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, candidates who have received contributions over the
limits are not obliged to return the money. ``It is up to the
individual candidate,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon noted that the state tried to persuade the courts to keep
the contribution limits in effect while judges reviewed the law.
But when the courts rejected that request, the way opened for
candidates to accept unlimited contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result, the Missouri governor's race is on a record
financial pace. Democrat Bob Holden recently reported that he had
raised $3.9 million, and Republican Jim Talent said he had
collected $3 million. Gov. Mel Carnahan spent $4 million for his
entire campaign when he was elected governor in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Holden and Talent camps said they would adhere to the limit
but had no plans to return money already received.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do what the law requires; nothing more,
nothing less,'' said Richard Martin, Holden's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Boriss, spokesman for Talent, said the congressman will
follow the law.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Martin nor Boriss said they knew how much their
candidates had collected in donations of more than $1,075.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said he understood the court ruling to mean Missouri's
limit on contributions to state senate candidates is $525 and $275
to candidates for state representative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
