u s BC-JETS-GROH-NYT &LR;      01-24 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETS-GROH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS AND GROH ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT JETS' FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Al Groh wanted to make it very clear on
Monday: He is not just the New York Jets' transition coach, but is
in it for the long haul. And while Groh put on a commanding
performance as he was introduced as the 14th head coach in Jets'
history, Bill Parcells hinted that he himself is a short-termer.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, the only coach to have a winning career record with
the Jets, said that he would remain as the club's director of
football operations but would eventually reassess his future with
the new owner, Woody Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to act in a support role,'' Parcells said, ``and
basically going to try to be a consultant to Al and a supporter and
an adviser, and will do that until such time as Woody and I get a
chance to revisit my status much later on.'' According to Johnson,
that meeting will take place in midsummer, or about the time
training camp begins.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the 58-year-old Parcells said he was ceding the
powers of personnel selection to Groh, who has never been a head
coach in the NFL. Parcells said that Groh, 55, who received a
four-year contract worth $800,000 annually, will have the last word
on trades, the draft and free-agent acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Parcells is assigning to Groh powers that Parcells
never enjoyed with the New York Giants _ his first head coaching
job _ or the New England Patriots, whom he left after control of
personnel matters became a contentious issue with the owner, Robert
K. Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of you know that I have a very strong belief in
that a coach must be allowed to shape and form his team the way he
wants to,'' Parcells said. ``I've been an advocate of that. I think
it's important, I think he has enough experience coaching and has
seen enough programs in operation to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21 days that shook the Jets may have come to an end with
Monday's announcements, or at least muffled the rattling. It began
on Jan. 3 with Parcells' decision to step down as head coach after
three seasons that transformed the club. He was replaced
immediately by Bill Belichick, whose contract called for his
ascension if Parcells gave up the coaching reins.
</P>
<P>
   But a day later Belichick himself quit, citing the uncertainty
over the as yet unknown owner and the role Parcells would play. Now
the loose ends aren't as critical: On the home front, Groh will
choose his assistant coaches; on the Belichick front, the Jets have
a federal court date on Tuesday, along with the NFL. They will
answer Belichick's charge that they are stopping him from making a
living by holding him to his Jets' contract. Belichick wants to go
to the Patriots, but must negotiate a deal with the Jets over his
services. According to New England, the Jets have demanded a
first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll grow to like this guy,'' said Johnson, speaking
of Groh. Johnson paid $635 million for the Jets and was approved as
the new owner a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good introduction to football because things
go right, things go wrong, and this is just the way it is,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that went right, he claimed, was getting Groh.
Johnson had said he was not going to limit the search to current
Jets' coaching, and claimed he and Parcells looked around the
league before choosing their linebackers' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very intelligent,'' Johnson said. ``He's been around
football, and I think he's capable of giving this team what it
needs, which will keep the progress growing in the development of
the championship team.''
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session filled with quips and serious
intentions _ Groh asked the news media not to describe his talks as
``rambling,'' as it did Belichick's stunning, long-winded
retirement announcement _ the new coach addressed the questions of
most fans:
</P>
<P>
   _ On following the future hall-of-famer Parcells: ``This staff
and this team will be my staff and my team. I did not want to be
the continuity candidate. I didn't want to be the stability
candidate because we are dealing with the future.'' Groh added that
he and Parcells have similar attitudes toward fielding a team.
</P>
<P>
   _ On putting together a staff (he needs a complete body of
defensive coaches and possibly a new offensive coordinator and wide
receivers coach): ``Our staff is quickly falling into place both
with people currently here, and we have been both aggressive and
expedient in making contact with a number of people around the
league.'' He did not expect this to be completed for at least a few
days. He was noncommittal on Charlie Weis' status as offensive
coordinator-receivers' coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ On what the Jets will be like: ``I think the common threads to
all the teams that we've had _ we've been a physically strong team,
we've been a strong team. That owes a lot to the commitment of the
off-season training program. We've been an extremely well-prepared
team. We've been a disciplined team and we've been a team that has
been very, very game-alert, very game-smart and very game-aware.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh admitted that he anticipated the questions about being in
Parcells' shadow, that Ray Handley failed following Parcells with
the Giants and Pete Carroll was unable to escape it at New England.
</P>
<P>
   Groh claimed he has thought about it so much, and anticipated
all the inquiries about it, that he said he had ``a 67-page
memorandum to hand out.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, seriously, ``The best way to replace Bill Parcells
is with a Parcells guy. There's been a firm hand on the rudder of
every team that Bill's been on. The players are used to being
coached and prepared in a particular way. They get used to that and
they've had success with it, and to change that sometimes kind of
throws them off compass. I think that was certainly a difficult
situation for our successor s at New England.''
</P>
<P>
   His promotion from linebackers' coach to head coach caps a
football career that began as the freshman coach at West Point 32
years ago. It included stints with Parcells at two colleges and
three NFL clubs. It included the usual amount of moving and
uprooting that is the lot of most assistant coaches. He has been at
seven colleges and five NFL teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Thomas, one of his old high school coaches at Chaminade,
in Mineola, N.Y., remembered the intense young Groh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would yell at the guys at half-time,'' Thomas said. ``He'd
be giving them pep talks.''
</P>
<P>
   And Groh's immediate plans? He said he would not be going to
next Sunday's Super Bowl _ though he has twice been to the big game
as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not going,'' he said. ``The next time I go, I'll be
working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
