<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WEATHER-SUN-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST CONCERN FOR FLIERS: BAD WEATHER ON THE SUN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af) 
By MATTHEW L. WALD  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forget the recent wild storms in Europe; scientists
say that another kind of weather is about to turn bad, the weather
in space, which can produce a variety of effects on earth,
including radiation doses for people on jets.
</P>
<P>
   The doses are not an issue for occasional travelers or even
those who fly fairly regularly, but are of some concern for flight
crews, passengers who fly dozens of times a year and for pregnant
women, radiation experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much they are at risk is not certain, but beginning in
May, by order of the European Union, European airlines will begin
treating their flight crews as radiation workers, teaching them
about the effects of low-level radiation doses _ which are believed
to increase the risk of cancer and of birth defects _ and
monitoring their exposures. Some airlines will automatically ground
flight crew members who say they are pregnant. For now, no American
carriers are doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The sun produces storms on its surface in 11-year cycles. In the
next year or so, according to physicists, solar activity will peak,
with an increase in sunspots and solar flares, during which the sun
throws off vastly increased numbers of subatomic particles. This
activity may become obvious to the general public through
electrical blackouts and disruptions in radio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Solar peaks have been observed for over 200 years _ in fact,
scientists refer to this as Cycle 23, because it is the 23rd time
the 11-year event has been measured. Until the mid-1900s, the solar
maximum, as the peak activity period is known, was mostly a
scientific curiosity, since the earth's atmosphere and magnetic
field shield the surface from most of the radiation. But it has
become more significant in the last few decades, as people have
built machines that are vulnerable to radiation, including big
electric power grids, communications satellites and jet planes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for people on planes is that at high altitudes,
there is less atmosphere to shield them. And the particles from the
sun are directed by the earth's magnetic field toward the poles,
and most airliners go close to the North Pole to take the shortest
route between cities like New York and London, or Los Angeles and
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doses are fairly trivial for an ordinary flight, even for
a pregnant person,'' said Dr. Robert J. Barish, a medical radiation
specialist and author of the 1996 book ``The Invisible Passenger,
Radiation Risks for People Who Fly,'' (Advanced Medical Publishing,
Madison, Wis, 1996). But in an extreme solar event, he said, the
dose could become 5,000 times larger. And for people who fly for a
living, he said, doses are ``up there with the guys crawling around
the reactors.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts dispute the effects of radiation in planes. Dr.
Michael Bagshaw, the medical director of British Airways and the
chairman of a European Union committee on in-flight radiation, said
in a notice to his airline's staff that members of British Airways
cabin crews live ``on average up to five years longer than a
comparable nonflying population.'' He added that risks from
radiation doses to unborn children are minimal when compared with
other risks during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   But to comply with European Union regulations, British Airways
is immediately assigning employees who say they are pregnant to
nonflying duties.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bagshaw, the doses aboard the Concorde are twice as
large per hour than on other commercial aircraft, because it flies
higher, but the Concorde's speed cuts the period of exposure in
half. For most passengers, there is little reason for concern. It
would take 100 hours on the Concorde or 200 hours on subsonic jets
a year to reach the exposure limit set by international authorities
for members of the public, Bagshaw said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But the limit for business travelers, he contends, should be
much higher _ the same as for nuclear-plant workers and flight
crews _ because their exposures are an essential part of their job.
The limit for nuclear-plant workers, he said, amounts to 3,600
hours of flying _ or 41 percent of the hours in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Barish, who was a professor of radiology at New York University
Medical School from 1976 to 1991, then chief radiotherapy physicist
at the Cancer Institute of Catholic Medical Centers of Brooklyn and
Queens, takes a more concerned view of the health risks, but
focuses on another point: the inconsistency of regulations among
industries and govenment agencies. Although the Federal Aviation
Administration recommended it in 1994, he said, American airlines
do not train their flight crews in radiation issues or monitor
their doses.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last solar maximum, observation of the Sun by
satellites has improved. The National Oceanographic and Atmospheric
Administration, a part of the Department of Commerce, publishes
updates on solar conditions at www.noaa.gov (follow the link for
space weather).
</P>
<P>
   Barish, who campaigned unsuccessfully during the last solar
maximum to have planes stay on the ground or fly at lower altitudes
during solar events, has set up an automated telephone service that
advises travelers, for a fee of $3, on radiation levels and
sometimes, whether to consider delaying a trip. The number is (877)
786-3527.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
