<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ill., Ariz., Ohio) (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER WORDS: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is expected soon to
begin broadcasting Spanish-language television advertisements in
Arizona, home turf of his chief rival, Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
Bush speaks Spanish, televised Spanish advertisements when he was
running for governor and during the current campaign has used
Spanish advertisements in Spanish-language newspapers and on
Spanish-language radio stations in Iowa and New Hampshire. But the
new advertisements are believed to be the first televised in
Spanish in a Republican presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOME MORE FRONT-RUNNING: Bush and Vice President Al Gore are
well ahead of their rivals in Illinois and Ohio, two recent polls
have found. An Ohio Poll survey conducted from Monday to Wednesday
of last week and a Market Shares Corp. survey in Illinois, whose
results were also issued last week, found that each man had the
support of more than 50 percent of his party's registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUTHWEST  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERVING UP POLITICS: Former Gov. Fife Symington of Arizona is
working in a restaurant kitchen in Scottsdale and has a semiregular
radio show with cooking lessons and political commentary. He was
forced to resign the governorship two years ago after being
convicted on federal bank- and wire-fraud charges stemming from his
days as a developer. An appeals court overturned the conviction
last year.
</P>
<P>
   THE MIDWEST  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IT'S MARGARET, MISTER: The only woman in the Republican field in
Illinois' 10th Congressional District, outside Chicago, is hoping
that tweaking her name will help her stand out among the 10 men in
the race. The candidate, Shawn Donnelley, won a small victory last
week when election officials ruled that despite some inconsistency
in her election filings, she could use her middle name, Margaret,
along with her first on the ballot for the March 21 primary. The
winner will run for the seat being left vacant by Rep. John Edward
Porter, a Republican who will retire this year after two decades in
the House.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY'S SCHEDULES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Hudson and Manchester, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Bedford and Manchester, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STEVE FORBES: Nashua, Hooksett and Portsmouth, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Manchester, N.H. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Sunapee, Henniker, Hillsboro and Londonderry, N.H. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
