reliever acetaminophen, popularly called Tylenol, its first
over-the-counter trade name, is a very safe drug for children as
well as for adults. However, as with any medication, the dose makes
the poison. And in the case of acetaminophen, which has properly
replaced aspirin as the drug most often given to infants and
children, there is a relatively small window of safety. (Naum
Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 24, 2000 -- SCI-VITAL-SIGNS -- Recent
research appears to establish that finasteride and minoxidil, known
more commonly as Propecia and Rogaine, do help stabilize hair loss
and in some cases reverse it. But when the men in one trial
involving Procepia and a placebo were asked to rate the cosmetic
value of the treatment, the response from those who got the drug
was not much more enthusiastic than from those who did not. (Naum
Kazhdan/The New York Times)
</P>
