<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN RETAIL CONGLOMERATE BUYING REST OF COMPUSA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A retail group controlled by the Mexican
billionaire Carlos Slim Helu announced Monday that it is buying
CompUSA Inc., the biggest chain of personal computer stores in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   His leap into U.S. retailing marked one of the biggest Mexican
purchases of a prominent U.S. business. It also is part of Slim's
drive to transform Telefonos de Mexico, the formerly state-owned
phone company that is controlled by Slim and is his flagship
business, into a fast-paced, web-savvy multinational giant.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Sanborn's SA, Slim's retailing chain, already owned about
14.8 percent of the common shares in CompUSA, the Dallas-based
network of computer stores that has been struggling with losses and
declining sales. Grupo Sanborn said it would purchase the rest for
$797.7 million or $10.10 a share, about 50 percent more than the
Friday closing price.
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA shares surged 40 percent on the news to close at $9.50
but remain far below the price of a few years ago, before the
company began to feel the pain of competition from direct sellers
of personal computers and from other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year CompUSA announced that it would eliminate 1,500
jobs or nearly 7 percent of its work force as part of a turnaround
strategy. It remained unclear Monday whether Grupo Sanborn's
takeover of CompUSA would lead to more job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If Slim is right about CompUSA's potential, the deal would mark
another victory in his record for picking a bargain. It also
represents a test of his skill in extending the potential of
Telefonos de Mexico, or Telmex, which he bought in the early '90s
when it carried the legacy of a lumbering state monopoly. Slim's
strategy has been to acquire both latest-model telecommunications
technology and retail outlets to make that technology available to
everyday consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The move was also consistent with Slim's bid to dig into the
huge Spanish-speaking telecommunications markets in the United
States. In addition to selling personal computers, CompUSA has been
expanding services to teach consumers how to use them and to
explore the Internet, with an emphasis on drawing customers from
American minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that his strategy is to make Telmex into an
enormous global communications network, rather than just a national
phone company,'' said Geoffrey Dennis, director of Latin American
equity research at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Slim, 59, originally built both his reputation and fortune in
turning around sagging retail companies in Mexico. The cornerstone
of Grupo Sanborn's is a string of old-style soda shop restaurants
that are a cherished feature of a Mexican family's Sunday
afternoon. But under Slim's management Sanborn's has become
Mexico's leading electronic commerce company.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Slim in running cost-efficient companies at home
has emboldened him to try the novel concept of bringing
Mexican-style retailing to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of experience from the many years we have been
in the retail business and the wide variety of businesses we have
run,'' said Carlos Slim Domit, Slim's 32-year old son who is the
head of Grupo Sanborn's.
</P>
<P>
   Slim Domit said he will focus on building CompUSA's sales
through electronic commerce. He cited the advantage of having 217
giant stores in 84 cities across the United States for filling
orders quickly and aiding customers who feel overwhelmed by
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Sanborn said that CompUSA will ally with Telmex, Microsoft
Corp., SBC Communications, the Southwest telephone company, and
Prodigy Communications Corp., the American Internet provider that
Slim owns.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Telmex announced a venture with Microsoft to
create a Spanish-speaking Internet gateway for Latin America,
building on Slim's experience with Prodigy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
