<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-US-ELIAN-0125-1STLD-C     01-24 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-ELIAN-0125-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: rewrites top to update with grandmothers leaving Miami
without seeing Elian ...
 &HT;    ELIAN'S GRANDMOTHER FLY TO MIAMI, REUNION UNCERTAIN
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After 60 days of posturing and rhetoric, the power of a
grandmother's love brought Elian Gonzalez achingly close to a
reunion with his Cuban family.
</P>
<P>
   But then fear overwhelmed that love.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another bizarre twist, the two Cuban grandmothers of the
boy at the center of an international tug-of-war flew from New York
to Miami on Monday. However, they stopped short of driving to the
Little Havana home where the boy has been living with his Miami
relatives since he was found floating in an inner tube off Fort
Lauderdale on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not confident of the security arrangements,
particularly when we found out the family wanted to make this a
circus,'' said Bob Edgar, general secretary of the National Council
of Churches, which arranged the grandmothers' trip to the United
States. ``The grandmothers felt that if they could not effect a
meeting tonight in a neutral place, then they were safer returning
to Washington D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, after touching down at Tamiami Airport about 4 p.m. EST,
the women's chartered jet took off again about 8:30 p.m. EST,
headed for Washington. They were to meet Tuesday with Congressional
representatives who are sympathetic to sending the boy back to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the first day of the new congressional session,
Florida Republican Sen. Connie Mack introduced a bill to give Elian
U.S. citizenship, which would free him from INS jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the bill is to move the decision-making about
the boy from out of the hands of the (Immigration and
Naturalization Service) and into the hands of the court,'' said
Mack, whose bill was one of three filed in both the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami developments outraged Elian's relatives here, who were
on their way to the airport to negotiate with the grandmothers when
the jet took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a travesty,'' said Spencer Eig, one of the family's
attorneys. ``To add insult to injury ... as we were coming to the
airport, these poor women were hustled onto a plane that took
off.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Elian, it was unclear how or when he heard the news that
his beloved grandmothers _ one of whom took a major role in raising
him _ were only 15 miles away, but departed without seeing him. The
boy's Miami relatives had told Elian that his grandmothers were
coming to see him.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another sad chapter in a case that has seen the
passion of politics overwhelm blood ties.
</P>
<P>
   While Edgar remained in Miami to be available for negotiations
with the family for a possible reunion in the coming days, the
Miami family was clearly stung badly by the developments.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers _ Raquel Rodriguez and Mariela Quintana _ were
reportedly afraid of going to the Little Havana house, which was
surrounded by dozens of journalists and hundreds of Cuban exiles.
In the past, the exiles have vowed to form a human chain around the
boy to keep him from returning to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday their leaders promised that the women would be met
with a warm reception. As word filtered out that the grandmothers
were headed to Miami, a crowd began gathering in the street outside
the home, and exile leaders exhorted them to be on their best
behavior. They handed out carnations and other flowers for them to
wave as the women arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show the world that we are a community that can
show love and respect and that we aren't violent like Fidel Castro
says we are,'' said Ramon Saul Sanchez, leader of the anti-Castro
Democracy Movement. ``Wave your flowers when they arrive, don't
throw them. And remain silent.''
</P>
<P>
   But the moment never came.
</P>
<P>
   And as the grandmothers jetted away into the cool Miami night,
it was unclear whether the stalemate would ever be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Monday's bizarre events, both sides of the family
had been critical of the other in comments to the media.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers have said the Miami family is controlled by
Miami's exile extremists and that they are cashing in on the boy's
celebrity. Elian's Miami relatives have said the grandmothers are
controlled by Cuban dictator Fidel Castro and that they haven't
shown remorse for the boy's mother, who drowned on the crossing
from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers _ here representing Elian's father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez _ arrived in the United States from Cuba on Friday, flying
to New York as the guest of the National Council of Churches, which
favors returning the boy to Cuba. They met in Washington with U.S.
Attorney Janet Reno Saturday, making a tearful plea to at least see
their grandson, if not take him home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sides of the family told media over the weekend
that they had not communicated, Reno apparently got in touch with
the Miami family's attorneys and brokered the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what bearing the reunion might have on other
facets of the case. The Miami family's lawsuit to keep the boy here
was expected to move forward this week, with government lawyers
filing a response to the family's complaint. U.S. District Judge
William Hoeveler is expected to schedule a hearing on the matter
once he receives the government response.
</P>
<P>
   Also undaunted, members of Congress took up Elian's case Monday,
all in an effort to block efforts by the INS to return the boy to
his father in Cuba prior to a state court hearing pitting his
relatives in Cuba and Miami in a custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said ``neither the president of the United States, his
attorney general, nor the dictator ruling Cuba are qualified to
decide the fate of this little boy.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., who filed a companion to Mack's bill
along with Reps. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen and Lincoln Diaz-Balart _ both
Miami Republicans born in Cuba _ said ``the best interest of Elian
must be our top priority. Any decision made by a governmental
agency is contrary to his best interest and clearly against his
mother's desires. While this legislation does not dictate an
outcome, it ensures that the rule of law is applied, upheld, and
enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Clinton is
concerned that congressional action may become ``a political
debate, rather than the substantive debate that it should be,'' but
he added that ``if they pass something, obviously, we'll take a
look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Mack noted his bill was being sponsored by three Republicans and
three Democrats, including _ Bob Graham, Florida's senior senator.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he supported the bill because the INS decision that
only Elian's father could speak for him was unfair to the boy and
others like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It denies them the opportunity to have their options weighed
by an experienced child custody jurist using the standard of 'what
is in the best interest of the child.' `` he said.
</P>
<P>
   The competing House bills offer young Elian either U.S.
citizenship or permanent residency status by waiving numerous
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The residency bill filed by Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., with
support from Reps. Peter Deutsch, D-Fla., and Patrick Kennedy,
D-R.I., would waive a provision in immigration law that would
cancel Elian's permanent residency status if he returned to Cuba
for more than six months.
</P>
<P>
   Menendez said his bill would avoid questions about granting
citizenship to a person who had not requested it. A Menendez
spokesman said that if the competing citizenship bill appeared to
have enough support to pass the House, Menendez would support it.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers Caribbean/Latin America correspondent Mike
Williams reported from Miami. Cox Newspapers National
correspondents Larry Lipman and Angel Wilson both contributed to
this report from Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
