<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DRUG-MERGER-ART-NYT &LR;      01-24 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MERGER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE ENDS DRUG MERGER NEGOTIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With DRUG-OUTLOOK) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON and MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, the consumer products giant that makes Crest
toothpaste and Tide detergent, ended merger talks Monday with drug
concerns Warner-Lambert and American Home Products after investors
panned the combination and Procter suffered its worst stock price
decline since the market crash of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about a combination of the three companies surfaced
last Wednesday when it was reported that they were in merger
discussions. But as the prospects for a deal became more promising,
jittery investors feared that Procter's earnings would suffer
because of it. As a result, Procter's management was pressured
either to call off the talks or watch its stock tumble for a fourth
consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   When one adviser was asked about what killed the talks, he did
not offer the usual explanations like price or executives' clashing
egos. It was much simpler: ``The stock market opened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And so, with a vengeance. Procter's stock plummeted from the
start, hitting a low of $94.8125 by midmorning Monday, down 8.2
percent from Friday's close and 19 percent since last week. But by
11:45 a.m. word began to spread on Wall Street that Procter &AMP;
Gamble was calling off talks. Investors cheered and the company's
stock price shot up almost 15 percent from the day's low to
$108.875, before closing at $102.875, down 37.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement, Durk I. Jager, Procter &AMP; Gamble's chief
executive, said the three companies ``could have been a blockbuster
combination of technology, marketing and scale capabilities.'' But
``we have concluded that leaks and resulting speculation on a
possible transaction have created an environment in which we cannot
continue meaningful discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   American Home, the maker of Advil and Robitussin, and
Warner-Lambert, which is best known for Schick razors and its
cholesterol-reducing drug Lipitor, announced last November that
they would combine in a stock deal now valued at $56.4 billion. But
that deal was thrown into immediate uncertainty when drug company
Pfizer Inc. made a hostile bid worth $76.4 billion for Warner
Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   With Pfizer's bid more attractive, Warner acknowledged that it
would pursue talks with the company. At the same time it began
seeking a white knight, including Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Jager said it was not too surprising that he
would cancel talks after his company lost more than $20 billion in
market value in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jager is an aggressive guy, but nothing in his mind is worth
watching the stock fall,'' said one person who talked with Procter
&AMP; Gamble officials over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But even the officials acknowledge that Jager, a tough-minded
executive, underestimated just how much Procter's investors would
punish his move to turn one of the world's largest consumer
products companies into a pharmaceutical concern. ``He thought he
was immune to all of this,'' said one person involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Procter is extremely secretive and executives were stunned that
news of the talks became public and caused a revolt among
shareholders. The company isn't the quickest of deal-makers either,
a particular disadvantage in these times when mergers are
negotiated in days instead of months. Last August, for instance,
Jager suggested that Procter was becoming more savvy, boasting that
it took the company only two months to negotiate the $2.3 billion
acquisition of Iams Co., the premier pet food maker. ``In our old
structure, an idea like this would have been much more difficult to
bring to life,'' he said. That deal was a fraction of the $142
billion merger that was attempted now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the companies involved seemed caught off guard by
Procter's actions. Even as late as Sunday night, executives at
Warner-Lambert and American Home were confident that merger
discussions would proceed, especially after Procter's board gave
management the green light last Friday. Executives from the Pfizer
camp, who have been extremely confident that they would prevail,
also were worried that a deal was in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   Procter's announcement put Warner-Lambert in the same spot it
was in a week ago _ seeking another suitor or forced into the arms
of a partner it is less than thrilled with. Neil B. Sweig, a
pharmaceutical company analyst at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co., said that he
believed that Pfizer, which makes Viagra, would now push to
complete a deal quickly with Warner-Lambert. Pfizer could sweeten
its offer, but not as much as it would have paid in a bidding war
with Procter. And now that Procter has backed away, he said, it is
less likely that another company will step in and try to outbid
Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warner-Lambert has put up a great fight,'' Sweig said. ``But
it will still be Pfizer that owns Warner-Lambert.''
</P>
<P>
   With Procter gone as a potential suitor, American Home becomes
the target of other bidders too, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   American Home makes an attractive partner, said analysts,
because of promising new drugs it has just begun to sell or will be
selling soon. But a cloud hangs over the company because of
thousands of pending lawsuits filed by people who said they were
harmed by taking fen-phen, the diet drug combination that the
company marketed.
</P>
<P>
   American Home also stands to get about $2 billion from Pfizer or
any other company that emerges to break up its initial deal to
merge with Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Home is sitting there, waiting to collect,'' Sergio
Traversa, a pharmaceuticals analyst at Mehta Partners, said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, American Home failed to complete two other proposed
mergers, first with SmithKline Beecham and later with Monsanto. But
analysts said that American Home's almost certain failure to merge
with Warner-Lambert cannot be compared with the two unsuccessful
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier proposed marriages fell apart largely because the
companies' chief executives could not agree on who would run the
new combination. But John R. Stafford, the chairman of American
Home, has now made it known that he is willing to give up some
power.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell B. Weiner, a spokesman for American Home, said that he
could not comment on any of the speculation about the company's
future. ``We still have a deal,'' he said. ``Our business remains a
solid pharmaceutical business and we look forward to introducing
our rich pipeline of products.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
