<HEADLINE>
FREQUENT-TRAVELER MILES  
 AIRPORT TO LAKE COMO  
 ARGENTINE FARM SHOW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Questions may be italicized) 
(af) 
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there a Web site that calculates one's frequent flier
miles on various airlines, or at least gives a formula for doing
so? _ Joan Gross, New York, N.Y. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Among the companies that provide the service you're looking
for are MaxMiles and Biztravel.com. Each can be reached directly at
its own home page _ www.maxmiles.com or biztravel.com _ or through
links on other sites.
</P>
<P>
   You will very likely find MaxMiles the more convenient of the
two since it tracks miles and expiration dates, if any, for 32
programs regardless of where you booked your flight, hotel stay or
car rental. In addition, mileage reports are available on
designated Web sites and by e-mail as well.
</P>
<P>
   Biztravel.com, which is a travel agency, tracks miles for six
frequent-traveler programs _ British Airways Executive Club,
Northwest WorldPerks, TWA Aviators, Midwest Express, Starwood
Preferred Guest and Hilton HHonors. Beyond that, Biztravel.com
compiles information only for travel it has arranged on any of
40-plus frequent-traveler programs. A log of accumulated miles is
free on its Web site and affiliated sites, but there are no e-mail
mileage reports.
</P>
<P>
   How much subscribers pay for information compiled by MaxMiles
varies. It depends on which of many sites they signed up with. But
cost does not necessarily reflect how much information is provided.
</P>
<P>
   For example, by logging on to a personalized www.excite.com home
page, a subscriber can get mileage totals for each program free.
For a more complete report _ showing individual transactions,
expiration dates, mileage and special deals _ there is a charge:
$2.95 a month or $29.95 a year. Under this arrangement, subscribers
get reports on the Web and by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   If one joins through www.expedia.com, the first year is free.
After that, it's $9.99 a year, which provides a full statement
online and e-mailed reports. But if three tickets are bought within
a year of enrollment, the charge is waived.
</P>
<P>
   If you are an American Express cardholder, access to the
information gathered by MaxMiles is free as are the mileage reports
found at www.rewardsmanager.com or www.americanexpress.com.
</P>
<P>
   The best deal of all is offered by www.skymalltravel.com:
Complete reports both by e-mail and on the Web free, period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does Malpensa Airport outside Milan offer transportation to
Lake Como, where visitors can board boats and hydrofoils to
Bellagio and other places? Traveling south from Milan and then
heading north to Lake Como seems to be a roundabout and less
appealing route. _ Jerry Kline, Alexandria, Va. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Thanks to bus and train service from Malpensa to Como on Lake
Como, you can be spared the time-consuming route you mention.
Though the scenery may not be breath-taking, it does avoid the trip
back to Milan of 25 miles _ and then doubling back.
</P>
<P>
   Buses as well as trains stop near the Piazza Cavour in Como,
where you can catch a boat or a bus to Bellagio and other stops
along the lake. Lining the shores are grand villas amid luxuriant
gardens alternating with picturesque villages, and in the distance
rise low mountains, green and lush almost all the year round. In
the summer, the lake is awash with flotillas of sailboats.
</P>
<P>
   Trains depart from Malpensa Terminal 1 for Saronno, where
passengers must change, 5 minutes and 35 minutes past the hour. (A
shuttle bus connects Terminals 1 and 2.) From Saronno, trains
usually run twice an hour to Lake Como, a trip that takes 40
minutes. The train fare is $5.25 from Malpensa to Saronno and $2
from Saronno to Como, calculated at 1,911 lire to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer the bus from Malpensa to Como, there are
departures daily from Terminal 1, platform 13, in front of exits
3-4 at 9:25 a.m. and 12:15 p.m., and four minutes later from
Terminal 2. Buses also depart every day but Sunday at 11 a.m., 4:25
p.m. and 7:30 p.m. The trip takes an hour and a one-way ticket is
$10.20. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the city of Como, there are both buses and boats to other
towns on the lake. Buses run hourly, stopping in the towns on the
west shore. From Como to Bellagio takes about 1 hour and 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For sea dogs, or lake dogs in this case, there are both boats
and hydrofoils that stop in most of the villages that dot the lake.
The boats run only during the summer, and the trip from Como to
Bellagio takes two hours; the fare is $5.75.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, it is possible to navigate the lake only by
hydrofoil, and the trip to Bellagio only takes 50 minutes.
Hydrofoils run eight times a day; the fare is $8.40.
</P>
<P>
   The Como tourist board can be reached at (39-031) 3300111 or
(39-031) 269712. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are planning a trip to Argentina in March and want to
visit the large Farm Progress Show supposedly west or northwest of
Buenos Aires. We need the location and dates, but have drawn a
blank. _ K.L.M., South Pasadena, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. What you may have in mind is a show known as ExpoChacra 2000
to be held from March 16 to 19 at the Estancia San Patricio. The
estancia, or ranch, is on Provincial Route 18, 16 miles from
Rosario in the Province of Santa Fe. From Buenos Aires, there are
both daily flights from Aero-parque Metropolitano Jorge Newbery
($95 round trip) and frequent bus service ($50 round trip). The
flight takes one hour, the bus four. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show will focus on livestock, crops, machinery, the role of
aviation (in pesticide application and fire protection, for
example) and telecommunications (as in satellite and Internet use).
Admission is $10; the hours are 8 a.m. to 7 p.m. Information:
www.expochacra.com.
</P>
<P>
   Packages for the show are being offered by the Transatlantica
travel agency, based in Rosario. It can arrange for tickets to the
show, lodging in Rosario or Uranga, which is closer to the Estancia
San Patricio, and for transportation. Rates range from $133 to $268
for three nights per person per day, double occupancy. Information:
(54-0341) 424-5013; fax (54-0341) 425-9860; on the Web at
www.transatlantica.com.ar.
</P>
<P>
   Aerolineas Argentinas can be reached at (800) 333-0276, (305)
648-4100 or www.aeroargentinas.com. If you plan to take a bus,
Chevallier is probably the most reliable. It leaves from the main
terminal at Retiro, in downtown Buenos Aires. Departures are hourly
starting at 4:45 p.m. until midnight. Information: (54-11)
4-301-0181.
</P>
</TEXT>
