<SLUG> BC-DRUG-OUTLOOK-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
P&AMP;G LIKELY TO STAY WITH CONSUMER PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With DRUG-MERGER) 
(lb) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After ending merger discussions with Warner-Lambert and American
Home Products, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. will probably stick to consumer
products rather than court another big pharmaceutical company
anytime soon, investors and stock analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though investors pushed down the stock price on the possibility
of a drug acquisition, they are bracing for more change. P&AMP;G's
talks with the drug companies signaled a surprising aggressiveness
from its top executive, Durk Jager. Since taking the helm a year
ago, Jager has said he will find ways to grow beyond selling more
diapers, paper towels and other household products. Now investors
seem to believe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was historically the ultimate white-shoe firm,'' said Tim
Ghriskey, a senior portfolio manager at Dreyfus Corp., a big P&AMP;G
shareholder. ``P&AMP;G has always tested everything to death before
bringing something new to market, or trying a new commercial or
anything, and he has just cut through that bureaucracy and really
invigorated the company and modernized it, and you have to applaud
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the company needs to speed products through
its notoriously sluggish pipeline. ``My guess is we will see very
solid results from the fundamental business over the next 12 to 18
months and see yet another acquisition,'' said Heather Hay, an
analyst with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Procter may take its time to look for the right fit. Ideal,
industry observers say, would be a business that could benefit from
its marketing expertise and strong distribution channels and add a
high-margin category in which it does not already dominate, like
razors, beverages and foods.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was much speculation Monday about how long it would
take P&AMP;G to find another potential partner, ``there is no rush to
the altar with anyone,'' said Ken Harris, who is a partner with
Cannondale Associates, a consulting firm that advises
consumer-product companies and supermarkets. ``It isn't as though
this is going to derail anything they are doing. In fact many
people believe it was a distraction potentially.''
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G management disagreed. ``We believed Warner-Lambert, American
Home Products and Procter &AMP; Gamble could have been a blockbuster
combination in terms of technology, marketing and scale
capabilities,'' Jager said when announcing that talks had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Without a deal to announce, P&AMP;G is expected to emphasize its
progress in reorganizing the company, when it releases quarterly
earnings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Management will probably accelerate the planned overhaul, in
which it is closing outdated plants, developing seven global
business units to focus on product segments and cutting years off
the time it takes to bring a product to market. The streamlined
process has produced recent hits like Fabreze, which removes odors
from fabrics, and Dryel, a home dry-cleaning kit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually felt increasingly confident about P&AMP;G's core
business,'' said Ghriskey. ``They have really invigorated it within
the last year in terms of the speed of product to market. It
surprised us that they felt they had to do a huge deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But P&AMP;G's goal is annual profit increases of 13 percent to 15
percent, a target that would be difficult to reach with its current
group of products, from Crest toothpaste to Tide detergent. The
company's profit has been disappointing recently, falling slightly
last year after a charge.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring the pharmaceutical companies would have significantly
bolstered revenues, aided in particular by Warner-Lambert's
cholesterol-lowering drug Lipitor. Snapping up the two drug
businesses would have made P&AMP;G No. 2 in U.S. drug sales behind
Glaxo Wellcome and SmithKline Beecham, which last week announced
intentions to merge.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that P&AMP;G was seriously considering a big acquisition
``is indicative of a company that doesn't feel it can consistently
grow its business in a solid double-digit manner organically,''
said William Steele, an analyst with Banc of America Securities.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G said in a statement, however, ``Even without Warner-Lambert
and American Home Products, we're on track to meet our growth
goals.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company also defended its decision to take a look at the
drug makers. ``Exploring a potential deal with Warner-Lambert and
American Home Products made sense for several reasons,'' the
company said. In addition to making P&AMP;G a leader in prescription
and over-the-counter drugs, it would have accelerated its growth
rate by one to two percentage points, added to earnings per share
in two years and provided opportunities for growth synergies.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, though, never warmed to the idea of P&AMP;G making such a
huge push into a category it does not know well. P&AMP;G has struggled
with a small drug business of its own for years without a a hit
product. Prescription drugs accounted for less than 1 percent of
revenue in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G's stock began to tumble last week on the rumor that it was
in talks with Warner-Lambert and American Home. After punishing the
stock, investors eased up on Monday after the company announced
that it had walked away from negotiations. The stock fell 38 cents
to $102.875 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with pharmaceuticals is that it is a hit-driven
business just like the movies,'' said Ghriskey of Dreyfus.
``Procter can instead keep innovating the diaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors had other concerns. Primarily with Warner-Lambert,
``that dated term `synergies' just wasn't there,'' Ghriskey said.
Moreover, he said, ``what we saw this escalating into would be a
bidding war.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has favored acquisitions in categories it knows
well, namely goods sold on grocery-store shelves. And though it has
made a couple of sizable acquisitions in recent years, most have
been cash deals far smaller than the proposed acquisition of the
drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G bought Iams Co. last August for $2.3 billion to move into
the premium pet-food business. And in 1997 it bought Tambrands for
$2 billion to strengthen its feminine-hygiene business. To buy
Warner-Lambert and American Home, P&AMP;G would have had to put up much
more than the $78 billion that Pfizer is bidding for Warner-Lambert
alone.
</P>
<P>
   So while three weeks of negotiations did not pan out for P&AMP;G,
going to the party is proof of something afoot under Jager.
</P>
</TEXT>
