<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Museum Tours Explore High and Low &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since 1953, the American Museum of Natural History in New York
has been running tours to exotic places, with experts as guides.
This year, the museum's Discovery Tours program has added a more
adventurous category, including a 16-day trek to the Pamirs in
central Asia, and a submarine safari off western Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Pamir expedition will gather in Beijing on Aug. 10 and meet
its study leaders, Bob Jones, an Asian art and Silk Road scholar,
and Cynthia Wilder, an anthropologist at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art. The group _ no more than 25 _ then will fly to Urumqi on the
edge of the Taklimakan Desert and the Tian Shan, the Celestial
Mountains, in remote western China.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites in that area to be visited are the Turpan
Depression _ 505 feet below sea level, the lowest point in Asia _
the Bezeklik Caves to see their Buddhist art, the ancient Tang
Dynasty ruins at Gaochang and the Heavenly Lake.
</P>
<P>
   A flight to the Silk Road city of Kashi precedes a road trip
through the northern cord of the Pamir Knot _ from which five
mountain systems radiate _ into Kyrgyzstan, with a night in a yurt
camp in Naryn. The group spends several days in Uzbekistan and a
day in Bangkok before returning to the United States on Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The submarine safari is offered July 10 to 14 and July 12 to 16.
Participants will make three dives in two- or three-person vessels
in the Strait of Georgia off Vancouver, as much as 600 feet down.
They should see giant octopuses, king crabs and the primitive
sixgill, or cow, shark, rarely observed because it prefers habitats
thousands of feet deep (experts believe it visits these waters for
seasonal feeding and mating). The trip will be led by Marcello R.
de Carvalho, an icthyologist at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Pamir trip costs $8,390 a person, double occupancy, or
$6,590 without air fare from the United States, and includes most
meals. The submarine expedition costs $3,890, with all meals and
accommodations on Hornby Island, but no air travel. Rates include
$2,500 medical and $30,000 evacuation insurance.
</P>
<P>
   For more details, call (800) 462-8687, or fax (212) 769-5755.
</P>
<P>
   _Ray Cormier &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High-Tech School For Golf on Maui &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golfers seeking lower scores and warmer temperatures may be
interested in the new 23-acre Kapalua Golf Academy at the entrance
to the Kapalua Resort on Maui, Hawaii. Overlooking Honolua Bay and
designed by Hale Irwin, the Senior PGA Tour star, the academy is
designed for players of all ages and abilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grand opening of the academy has been set for March 1 as the
turf on its 18-hole putting course grows. But the practice range _
with an 85,000-square-foot tee area _ is scheduled to open Tuesday
and the academy has begun to make use of its 3,500-square-foot
learning center. The center features a 24-seat classroom, an
exercise room targeted to golfers, and a digital video bay for
coaching.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Students in the two- and three-day schools will be videotaped
and, working with one of the resort's more than 25 PGA
professionals, analyze their techniques. Private lessons and daily
clinics are also offered, and golfers can hone their skills on the
Kapalua Resort's three 18-hole layouts _ the Bay, the Village and
the Plantation courses, the last the site of the Mercedes
Championships, won this month by Tiger Woods. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $35 for a half-hour of instruction for a
junior player (under 15 years old) to $795 for the three-day golf
school, which includes 15 hours of instruction, a digital video
analysis and 27 holes of golf at the resort. Information: (808)
669-6500.
</P>
<P>
   _Melissa A. Trainer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Code-Share Plan Adds South Africa Flights &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delta Airlines is entering into a code-share agreement with
South Africa Airways to offer nonstop service to South Africa from
New York and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, the airlines will fly Boeing 747s from
Hartsfield International Airport in Atlanta to Johannesburg and
Cape Town, and from Kennedy International Airport to Johannesburg.
Flights will leave Kennedy daily at 5:55 p.m., arriving in
Johannesburg at 3:30 p.m. the following day, except on Tuesdays,
when the plane drops cargo off on Sal Island, Cape Verde, and
arrives at 5 p.m. Flights depart Johannesburg at 9:20 p.m. and
arrive at Kennedy at 7:20 a.m. the next day.
</P>
<P>
   From Atlanta, departures on Monday, Wednesday, Friday and Sunday
will be at 10:30 a.m., arriving in Johannesburg at 8:35 a.m. the
next day, and continuing to Cape Town, arriving at 11:35 a.m. On
the other days, flights go to Cape Town first, then to
Johannesburg. Flights to Atlanta, on Wednesday, Friday and Sunday,
will depart Johannesburg at 5:50 p.m., stop in Cape Town and arrive
in Atlanta at 8:20 the next morning. On other days, flights leave
Cape Town and stop in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Round-trip fares start at $747 for travel completed by April 30.
For information and reservations, call (800) 221-1212. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bourbons Are Back (In the Louvre, Anyway) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seven newly renovated galleries on the first floor of the
Richelieu wing of the Louvre opened last month, reuniting the
museum's early 19th-century art objects as part of a project to be
finished in 2002. The renovated galleries, totaling 10,000 square
feet, now display 175 objects, most acquired since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms 75 through 77 display objects from the Restoration period
(1814-1830), when the Bourbon monarchy under Louis XVIII returned
to power after the downfall of Napoleon I. This change of regime
did not break with the pervading neo-Classical style favored by
Napoleon. Louis XVIII moved easily into the Tuileries Palace (now
the Louvre), merely swapping Napoleon's signature N and eagle
trademarks for his own crown and fleur-de-lis.
</P>
<P>
   A notable exception to this redecorating austerity is the king's
bedroom, which was refurnished under both Louis XVIII and Charles X
and which is reconstructed in Gallery 75. Restoration-period
objects of note include the Duchesse de Berry's crystal and bronze
vanity table, Charles X's elaborately sculptured and gilded walnut
bed, and several Sevres porcelain pieces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the July Monarchy (1830 to 1848) under Louis-Philippe,
Duke of Orleans, began with much the same neo-Classical bent, it
quickly acquired a more eclectic style. The display in Rooms 78
through 81 reflect neo-Gothic, Renaissance and Louis XV styles.
Exhibits include a desk (1839) by the Grohe brothers of heavily
sculptured rosewood, a Sevres Chinese tea set (1840), and
silverware and gilded furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the Louvre, which is closed Tuesday (these new
galleries are also closed Monday and Thursday) is $7, $4 after 3
p.m. and on Sunday. Information: (33-1) 40.20.51.51 or
www.louvre.fr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wall St., Rooms Fit for a Robber Baron &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In its storied 158-year existence, the massive limestone
structure at 55 Wall Street has served as the New York Merchants'
Exchange, the United States Customs House and headquarters for
National City Bank, which has evolved into Citigroup. Now, it has
yet another new occupant and identity: The Regent Wall Street, the
financial district's first luxury hotel, opened quietly just before
Christmas and will celebrate its grand opening upon its completion
in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Designed in 1842 by the architect Isaiah Rogers and renovated in
1908 by the architectural team of McKim, Mead &AMP; White, the landmark
building in the heart of the financial district is a study in
robber-baron chic. With a wall of mammoth Ionic columns, the
exterior looks like a titanic temple of commerce; only a discreet
sign identifies it as a hotel. And it's easy to imagine the Italian
Renaissance-style ballroom as the cavernous marble-walled banking
hall it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the 12,000-square-foot ballroom, behind the lobby,
can gaze up at the magnificent 80-foot ceiling with its gilded dome
ringed with handsome Wedgwood jasperware panels depicting the signs
of the zodiac and the four points of the compass.
</P>
<P>
   The 144 guest rooms are also on a fairly grand scale. The
smallest is 525 square feet, suites start at around 1,200 square
feet, and all have large dark green and beige marble bathrooms,
with big tubs and ample stall showers. Tradition wins out over
trendiness, with comfortable furniture in rich woods and fabrics
like silk damask and velvet, in shades of beige and green.
</P>
<P>
   Room toys include 39-inch televisions, DVD and CD players (with
a library for each) and portable telephones. There is a restaurant
and a fitness center, and a spa is being built.
</P>
<P>
   An unusual feature of the building is the eight 19th-century
jail cells in the basement, where people who couldn't pay customs
fees were incarcerated. The hotel may turn the jail into a cigar
bar, but until then, the cells might come in handy for guests who
can't pay their bills: rooms cost $425 and suites $525 until March
31, then will start at $545 and $850. Reservations: (800) 545-4000,
(212) 845-8600; fax (212) 845-8601.
</P>
<P>
   _Terry Trucco
</P>
