<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WILL NOT ALLOW TATTOO OF CONFEDERATE FLAG INTO EVIDENCE IN
RACE BIAS CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ U.S. District Judge Nancy Atlas ruled Monday that she
would not permit the tattoo of a Confederate flag on the forearm of
a manager into evidence in a employment race discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas ruled the tattoo, which is on the arm of Chief Inspector
Dan Petrash of the city of Houston's Department of Public Works and
Engineering, is too controversial a symbol to be introduced to the
jury in the trial against the city that began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Two black inspectors who work for the public works department
have sued the city, claiming they were passed over for promotions
two years ago because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors, Louella Henderson Jones and Herbert Williams
III, contend that Petrash, who had the hiring authority, made
racist remarks and told other employees he wanted a white man for
the job as senior inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson and Williams claimed the tattoo was evidence of
Petrash's attitude toward blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas allowed the tattoo of the flag into evidence during the
first trial, which ended in a hung jury last week.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of the controversy in South Carolina over the
Confederate flag that flies over the state Capitol, Atlas said she
was reluctant to admit the tattoo this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas also said it was unclear what the Confederate flag means
to Petrash today since he had the tattoo applied decades ago when
he was 19 years old. She added there was no proof Petrash was
showing the tattoo off at work.
</P>
<P>
   Don Fleming, assistant city attorney, said he didn't want to
comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ahmad, who is representing Jones, also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
