<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER BARRIERS FOR THE DISABLED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A number of changes making travel more accessible for people
with disabilities have unfolded in recent days. Here are some of
these developments. The world's largest economy lodging chain, Days
Inns of America, reached an agreement with the federal government
last month that should mean an increase in motel rooms adapted for
disabled guests.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between Days Inns of Parsippany, N.J., a division
of the Cendant Corp., and the Justice Department ended a dispute of
more than five years. The chain will require that owners who plan
to open motels bearing its name must certify the places comply with
the Americans With Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   It will also pay for a survey to identify problems at places
built since 1993 that have already opened, and establish a $4.7
million interest-free loan fund to help franchise holders at these
hotels make needed renovations. The chain also paid the United
States $50,000 in penalties. Days Inn has 152,000 guest rooms in
1,800 properties in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   John L. Wodatch, head of the department's disability-rights
division, said he hoped that the agreement would serve as a model
for other franchising companies that play a role in the design of
independently operated hotels and motels. Wodatch said it was a
difficult agreement to reach because the company said it was not in
the hotel business but in the franchising business.
</P>
<P>
   The disability act, signed by President George W. Bush in 1990,
requires that motels built after Jan. 26, 1993, meet particular
rules: public areas and a percentage of bedrooms must be accessible
by wheelchair; alarms, telephones, bathroom fixtures and the like
must accommodate guests with vision or hearing impairments or other
disabilities. In 1994, the Justice Department began investigating
newly built Days Inns; Wodatch said then that consumer complaints
against the chain outnumbered those against other companies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the department sued five new Days Inns, their
architects and contractors as well as Days Inns of America and its
parent company, now Cendant, saying that the motels did not provide
equal access for disabled guests.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other properties originally on the lawsuit list
reached settlements before they were sued. The parent company
responded that it had no responsibility for individual motels'
compliance with the law, that it merely licensed the brand name and
provided certain services for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   The department found some problems recurring throughout the
chain, among them, insufficient accessible parking, inaccessible
entrances and walkways; inadequate signs for those with limited
vision; bathroom doors too narrow for wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's settlement, filed in federal court in Kentucky,
where one of the five motels was situated, came after 13 months of
mediation. Days Inns said it believed the settlement was ``good for
our customers, the traveling public and the hotel industry.''
Attorney General Janet Reno said that she hoped other hotels and
hotel-franchise companies would make similar changes to assure full
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   The law says that properties built before 1993 need make
accessibility alterations only in areas being renovated; this means
that landmark properties and other historic hotels that do not
renovate can still have lobbies with a lot of steps and no ramps,
registration desks too high to reach from wheelchairs and other
features that may thwart disabled guests.
</P>
<P>
   London theater will be more accessible for travelers with
hearing loss during a tour scheduled for March by the Theater
Access Project of the Theater Development Fund. This nonprofit
organization, sponsor of the TKTS discount-ticket booths in
Manhattan, believes this is the first London theater tour for
hearing-impaired Americans. The League for the Hard of Hearing and
its affiliated Advocates for Better Communication have joined to
sponsor the trip for 25 participants.
</P>
<P>
   The group will take along a screen that displays dialogue in
two-inch-high electronic captions. This display was developed by an
American, Don DePew, using court-reporting computer programs. It
has been used in Broadway and Off Broadway theaters for three
years, according to Lisa Carling, the project's director.
</P>
<P>
   The script for ``Antony and Cleopatra,'' as presented by the
Royal Shakespeare Company at the Barbican, and for a West End play
will be transcribed into the system ahead of time, along with notes
on offstage sounds and the like. In the theater, the device is
placed at the side of the orchestra and an auditor scrolls three
lines at a time as the dialogue is spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Although amplification devices are available in London theaters,
the Theater Access Project believes that this will be the first use
of open captioning there. The London theaters are advertising the
performances, and seats may be reserved in the caption-viewing
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-night trip, leaving March 25, has other events and
tours scheduled. The cost is $1,999 a person with two in a room at
the Strand Palace Hotel on the Strand. Air fare on British Airways,
departure and hotel taxes and transfer of one piece of baggage are
included.
</P>
<P>
   A single room costs $430 more. The reservation deadline is Feb.
10. Theater Access Project, (212) 221-0885, extension 257; the TTY
(teletypewriter) number is (212) 719-4537; www.tdf.org. The League
for the Hard of Hearing is at www.lhh.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Denver airport, I encountered a group of wheelchair users
waiting to board. I was amazed to learn that they were a team going
to play Quad Rugby, a fierce game played by quadriplegics. ``It
becomes clear that wheels are weapons, and pity should be checked
at the door,'' a Denver Post reporter said in describing a game in
November.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment of disabled passengers aboard planes is governed
by the Air Carrier Access Act, a law older than the
disability-rights act, but it looked complicated to me getting a
batch of wheelchair passengers onto one plane. The act anticipates
this possibility, requiring that any group of 10 or more with
disabilities give the airline 48 hours' notice.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Theisen, who works at the Craig Hospital in Englewood,
Colo., and is coordinator for the group I met, the Denver Harlequin
Rugby Club, said that United Airlines gave her a lot of help in the
eight trips her 15-member team made in a season. She avoids
connecting flights, and United can get the team nonstop to most
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   She orders bulkhead seats for the players and the accompanying
people, she said, and generally this works out. The players are
boarded ahead of the other passengers, reaching their seats in the
airline's narrow aisle wheelchair and getting into them by boosting
themselves over any fixed chair arms. Ms. Theisen said that
although the players were quadriplegics, they had varying degrees
of upper-body mobility and were strong.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers' own wheelchairs are the last things to be
checked into the luggage compartment, as the law requires, she
said, and they come out first and are ready at the Jetway. Ms.
Theisen said that the team usually got off the plane last.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Theisen, who has dealt with other airlines in the West, and
not always so successfully, believes that United's agents are well
trained in the legal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelchair users or their companions often find that they do not
have the law's provisions at hand, as Ms. Theisen does, when
talking to boarding agents. To assist them, the Eastern Paralyzed
Veterans Association has just published two new pocket cards
summarizing the act.
</P>
<P>
   These note, for example, that batteries on wheelchairs are not
to be drained under any circumstances and that 48 hours' notice is
required if an electric wheelchair is going to be transported on a
plane with fewer than 60 seats.
</P>
<P>
   A single set of the cards and an air-carrier leaflet are
available free from the Eastern Paralyzed Veterans Association,
75-20 Astoria Boulevard, Jackson Heights, N.Y. 11370; (718)
779-8377.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises are feasible vacations for those requiring kidney
dialysis, who may otherwise be limited in their ability to go far.
</P>
<P>
   A new vessel, the 513-passenger Deutschland of Peter Deilmann's
EuropAmerica Cruises, has a dialysis center aboard to accommodate
12 kidney patients on a cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The liner's itinerary this spring and summer ranges from the
Mediterranean to the North Sea and the Baltic, to Scandinavia,
across the Atlantic and through the Panama Canal to the Pacific.
Many cruises on the Deutschland, which is luxurious, are 7 to 18
nights long.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive 14-night cruise costs $4,040 a person,
double occupancy. Dialysis is about $280 a treatment extra (at 1.93
marks to $1), which is paid at the time of treatment. Kidney
patients and their doctors must provide medical records in advance
to Bauer, a medical firm in Kiel, Germany, that arranges for
treatments and medical personnel on board.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Deilmann Ocean Cruises, 1800 Diagonal Road, Suite 170,
Alexandria, Va. 22314; (800) 348-8287; on the Web:
www.deilmann-cruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dialysis Traveller-Dialysis at Sea, a Florida organization in
business for 20 years, has arrangements with many cruise lines to
provide on-board treatments. Steve Debroux, the president, said
that he booked 600 clients a year aboard cruises. There are 100
cruises listed for the coming 15 months in the catalogue; a minimum
booking is 8 dialysis passengers and a maximum is 12. The charge
per treatment is $425.
</P>
<P>
   The list of cruises by region appears on the Web site,
www.dialysis-at-sea.com. Dialysis Traveller-Dialysis at Sea
Cruises, 801 West Bay Drive, Largo, Fla., 33770; (800) 544-7604.
</P>
<P>
   Another resource on accessible travel is found at a Web site
maintained by a California couple, Candy B. Harrington and Charles
Pannell, who have been gathering information on the subject for
three years and who also publish a quarterly newsletter, Emerging
Horizons. The site, emerginghorizons.com, recently had a detailed
article on San Diego. The newsletter, which carries no advertising,
prints lists of motels with roll-in showers that guarantee a
reservation for an accessible room. The winter 2000 issue has a
list for Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The main article in this issue of the newsletter talks about
accessibility in Florence; it tells which entrance to the Uffizi to
use, the width of the elevator door at the Palazzo Vecchio museum
entrance (29{ inches) and which door to get unlocked to see the
Boboli Gardens. The author, Cornelia Danielson, a Florence
resident, is described as founder of Barrier Free Travel/Viaggiare
Senza Barriere, a nonprofit organization in Tuscany. A year's
subscription to the newsletter costs $11.95 in the United States.
Checks, Visa and MasterCard are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging Horizons, Post Office Box 278, Ripon, Calif. 95366;
(209) 599-9409.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
