<HEADER>
A5303 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBA-BOY-580(2TAKES)-     01-24 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-580(2TAKES)-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMOTHERS FAIL TO SEE CUBAN BOY IN MIAMI STOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN with ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After waiting nearly five hours in a suburban airport
here Monday, the two Cuban grandmothers of Elian Gonzalez gave up
their effort to meet the boy and flew to Washington as their
custody battle moved to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers were scheduled to meet on Tuesday with members
of Congress, who have helped turn their fight into an international
tug of war.
</P>
<P>
   Their private twin-engine Learjet, provided by the National
Council of Churches, left Kendall-Tamiani Executive Airport just as
three of the grandmothers' relatives and their lead lawyer arrived
to talk with them _ without the only person they wanted to see,
Elian.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami police official said the plane was heading for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers' departure, after a late-scheduled trip from
New York to Miami Monday morning, was the latest leg of their
four-day odyssey to bring the boy home to his father, who was
divorced from his mother. His mother drowned two months ago during
an escape from Cuba, but Elian survived, clinging for two days to
an inner tube in the Atlantic off Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's grandmothers became ``frightened and scared'' about
coming to Miami, said Bob Edgar, general secretary of the National
Council of Churches. With other council officials, Edgar has been
shepherding the women since their departure from Havana on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the thousands of people here in Miami,'' he said,
``marching and protesting, and you can imagine as very simple,
loving, caring grandparents that they would be frightened to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier plans had called for the grandmothers to have dinner
with relatives who had been caring for Elian, but the 6 p.m. EST
dinner date came and went without the grandmothers' leaving the
airport. At 8 p.m., three of the relatives and their lead attorney,
Spencer Eig, left the house and headed for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really love him, they will come see him,'' said Elly
Carrera, 17, a Cuban-American who supports Elian's great-uncle
Lazaro Gonzalez in his appeal for custody of the boy and who was
standing outside the Gonzalez home, where the grandmothers were to
have dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they don't love him,'' Ms. Carrera said. ``They are
speaking Castro's words. Castro wants to win. But we won't let him
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, scores of onlookers and media waited outside
the house. Inside, a cousin said Elian was watching a video of
``Home Alone 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's case started as a family feud and has erupted into an
international incident with anti-Castro Cuban-Americans urging that
he be reared in the United States and that his father be denied
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress, and in particular those from Florida,
seized upon the issue Monday, the lawmakers' first day back at work
after a two-month recess. Sen. Connie Mack and Rep. Bill McCollum,
both Florida Republicans, introduced bills to grant the boy
citizenship or permanent residency. Meanwhile, several House
Democrats offered other bills blocking them.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives, led by Lazaro Gonzalez and his family, have
claimed custody of the boy in defiance of the Clinton
administration and the pleas of the father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
to repatriate him. The grandmothers, who flew to New York on
Friday, are Raquel Rodriguez, mother of Elizabet Brotons Rodriguez,
Elian's mother, and Mariela Quintana, the father's mother.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All day Monday, plans had unfolded to bring the grandmothers to
the Little Havana home of Lazaro Gonzalez, a paternal great-uncle
of Elian, and his wife, Angela, and 21-year-old daughter,
Marisleysis.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Florman, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said
authorities had tried to arrange a meeting of family members at a
more neutral location.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grandmothers were not comfortable with a meeting at
Lazaro's house,'' Ms. Florman said. ``They want a private meeting
with the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Gonzalez family here and its publicists
had been going to some lengths to establish the impression of an
ideal, welcoming home for Elian. Rather than calling another
protest in support of the relatives, leaders of the Cuban-American
groups carpeted the sidewalk outside the house with pink, yellow
and red carnations.
</P>
<P>
   Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Republican member of Congress from Miami,
said while visiting the home early Monday: ``The family's looking
forward to the grandmas' coming. It's always been a family full of
love.'' Like other leaders of the exile community she urged that if
the father and grandmother wanted custody they come to Miami and
``testify in court where it can be decided impartially.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Elian's grandmothers plan to meet Tuesday in Washington with
members of Congress, including Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn.,
who every year sponsors legislation to ease the trade embargo with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Just before embarking on their trip to the United States, which
led to a meeting with Attorney General Janet Reno and with Doris
Meissner, commissioner of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, the grandmothers had predicated any trip to the United
States, their first off Cuban soil, on retrieving Elian.
</P>
<P>
   But theirs and the administration's hands are tied by suits
filed in federal court here last week enjoining the administration
from repatriating Elian and asking for the right to apply for
political asylum. So instead they asked Ms. Reno to help organize a
visit with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers introduced three bills Monday, two in the House and
one in the Senate, to grant Elian citizenship or permanent
residency. They said their legislation would put the decision in
the hands of a Florida state judge instead of the federal
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who sponsored the Senate bill with five other lawmakers,
said he wanted to take politics out of the decision. But state
judges in Florida are elected, and any judge in the Miami area,
where Elian is living with relatives, is likely to face tremendous
pressure to rule that the boy stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The lead sponsor of a companion bill in the House, McCollum,
said, ``Any decision made by a governmental agency is contrary to
his best interest and clearly against his mother's desires.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill proposed by House Democrats, including Reps. Robert
Menendez of New Jersey and Patrick J. Kennedy of Rhode Island,
would grant permanent residency instead of citizenship, to allow
Elian to decide his citizenship on his own when he is older.
</P>
<P>
   But another group of House members, including Reps. Charles B.
Rangel, D-N.Y., Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Ray LaHood, R-Ill.,
introduced a nonbinding resolution to block the citizenship bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that this 6-year-old boy who lost his
mother in a tragic accident at sea should be reunited with his
father,'' Rangel said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In suing for custody in federal court here, Lazaro Gonzalez
maintains that he and his family can assure Elian a happier
upbringing than his father and the grandmothers, who live in the
Cuban town of Cardenas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-CHIEFS-THOMAS-NYT     01-24 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHIEFS-THOMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS' THOMAS PARALYZED IN LEGS AFTER ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Derrick V. Thomas, the lightning-quick linebacker for the Kansas
City Chiefs, was flown from Missouri to a hospital in Florida on
Monday with his spine fractured in two places, his legs paralyzed
and the chances of his continuing his 10-year career in doubt, the
Chiefs said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a very severe injury,'' Carl Peterson, the
team's president, said in a news conference in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 33, was injured Saturday afternoon when he lost control
of his car on an icy stretch of Interstate 435 north of Kansas
City, skidded onto a median and flipped over at least twice, the
Missouri Highway Patrol said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and a friend, Michael D. Tellis, were not wearing seat
belts and were thrown from the car. Tellis, 49, died at the scene.
A third passenger, John C. Hagebusch, 34, walked away from the
accident with minor injuries. He had been wearing a seat belt in
the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The three men were headed to Kansas City International Airport
to catch a plane to St. Louis, where they had tickets to the
National Football Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was taken to Liberty Hospital in Liberty, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs' team doctor, Dr. Jon Browne, said Thomas' spine was
broken at the base of the neck and in the middle of the back. He
can still move his arms, shoulders and upper chest, but appears to
be paralyzed from the waist down, at least for now, Browne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time to check these things out,'' he said.
``Improvement can come slowly or in rapid bursts.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was awake and alert Monday morning, in fairly good
spirits and joking with nurses, said his agent, Leigh Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas also had some feeling in his toes, which his doctors said
is a good sign, Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next few days will tell how much damage was done to his
spine and what the prognosis is,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence that Thomas had been drinking, the state
police said, though investigators said he had been traveling too
fast for the icy conditions that suddenly developed Saturday
afternoon after a cold north wind froze a layer of melting snow.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, the Chiefs flew Thomas to Miami, his
hometown, where he was to be transferred to Jackson Memorial
Hospital, which has one of the best clinics in the world for spinal
injuries, Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Thomas', who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said doctors had told the linebacker that the break to the fifth
vertebrae of his neck might be successfully treated with surgery to
fuse two vertebrae together. But the second spinal fracture could
be more problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the spinal cord is completely severed
or whether it's still got some life in it,'' the friend said. ``The
doctors are not real optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   For 10 seasons, Thomas has been the mainstay of the Chiefs'
defense, a hard-hitting linebacker who stands 6 feet 3 inches,
weighs 255 pounds and is known for one of the quickest first steps
in the league. He has more sacks than any other player in the last
decade, recording 116.5.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Thomas has become almost as well known for his
charitable works as for his exploits on the field. He founded the
Third and Long Foundation, which sends tutors into inner-city
schools to combat illiteracy. He also started a successful roofing
business and invested, with Tellis, in a limousine service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got remarkable skills outside the realm of athletics,''
Steinberg said. ``He'll be fine in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors may consider surgery to lift pressure off the spinal
cord. But even if surgeons can restore Thomas' spinal cord to
working condition, it remains an open question whether his back
would be able to take the punishment of playing in the National
Football League, spinal experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably unlikely,'' said Dr. Michael Weinberger of St.
Vincents Hospital in New York. ``The issue is whether he's going to
walk again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
