<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FORBES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES HOPES FOR THREE-MAN RACE IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Aiming for a strong showing here that could lift
him into the top tier of Republican presidential candidates,
millionaire publisher Steve Forbes hoped to create a three-man race
in New Hampshire against Texas Governor George W. Bush and Senator
John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes hit the Iowa airwaves Monday, conducting more than two
dozen radio and television interviews as he pitched his message of
social and economic conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   With his campaign manager publicly anticipating a showing in the
``mid-20s'' in Monday's Iowa caucuses, Forbes sought to energize a
campaign that has lagged in the polls and to establish himself as a
conservative alternative to the more moderate Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the true conservative in the race,'' said Forbes,
appearing with his wife Sabina and three of his five daughters
outside Scruffy's Pizza &AMP; Deli in downtown Des Moines. ``A strong
conservative running against two moderates.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' Iowa campaign was anything but scruffy, however,
spending $3.2 million in media ads in the state since June.
Overall, Forbes has spent more than $31 million, including $25
million from his personal finances.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on CNN Monday, Forbes' campaign manager repeated his
prediction that Bush would finish third in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' spokesman, Greg Meuller, explained that Forbes expects
to make an even stronger showing in New Hampshire as Bush and
McCain divide the votes of moderates and Forbes consolidates the
support of social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Meuller said Forbes would focus on taxes in New Hampshire,
hammering Bush and McCain's proposals as too modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relishing the tax debate that's waiting for us when we
get up there,'' Meuller said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and McCain plans would lower marginal tax rates, but
maintain a multitiered tax system based on income. Forbes would
replace the tax code with a 17 percent flat tax, exempting up to
$36,000 of income from taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Forbes bragged that his flat-tax plan has already
influenced the campaign. He also said Bush was a timid and
visionless candidate who could not inspire voters and would cost
his party the White House if nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said Bush's approach was to ``say as little as possible,
use a slogan, do winks and nods, and hope that gets you by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After losing two presidential elections through that _ trying
to muffle the differences, trying to stifle debate _ I think we
need to go to what we did in the 1980s, where we did have a clear,
lucid, inspired message based on principle,'' Forbes said. ``That's
how we won then, that's how we're going to win in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes dismissed questions about whether he was concerned that
two other conservative candidates, Alan Keyes and Gary Bauer, might
make it harder for him to unite the party's right wing. Forbes
noted he has received endorsements from prominent conservative
leaders like Phyllis Schlafly, Paul Weyrich and Brent Bozell,
saying ``I think conservatives are rallying around my cause.''
</P>
<P>
   With Forbes enjoying his most prominent moment in the race so
far, the mood within his campaign was upbeat. Returning from a tour
of the state on a chartered jet late Sunday, giddy Forbes aides
cracked open beers with reporters and hauled out a speaker to blast
music into the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Even the typically reserved Forbes seemed loose, predicting that
the St. Louis Rams would defeat the Tennessee Titans in the Super
Bowl. Forbes was careful to note that the Titans had recently
relocated from Texas _ home state of George W. Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
