u k BC-EDIT-ECUADOR-NYT &LR;      01-24 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ECUADOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ECUADOR'S ENDANGERED DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Tuesday, Jan. 25: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Military meddling in politics has become rare in Latin America
during the past two decades. But Ecuador is a conspicuous and
worrisome exception. Last weekend's forcible removal of President
Jamil Mahuad is disturbing, especially since it is the second time
in less than three years that an elected Ecuadorean leader has been
prematurely ousted from office. Ominously, on both occasions the
army played a decisive role in shaping the presidential succession.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a confused weekend of maneuvering capped by strong
warnings from Washington against the establishment of a military
regime, Vice President Gustavo Noboa has been sworn in as
president. Ecuador's government thus remains in civilian,
constitutional hands. But democracy's future there looks tenuous.
Washington must be ready for further turmoil as Ecuador steers its
way through a difficult economic and political crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad, who won a majority in presidential runoff elections
barely 18 months ago, saw his popularity plunge to 9 percent as
Ecuador's chronically ailing economy slipped beyond his control.
Blocked by an impasse with a politically fractured Congress from
enacting needed tax increases on the wealthy and reforms of an
inefficient public sector, Mahuad stood by helplessly as inflation
raged, unemployment soared, banks tottered and half of Ecuador's
foreign debt passed into default.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, Mahuad announced earlier this month that he
would replace Ecuador's battered currency with the dollar. Many
Ecuadoreans, especially the large and impoverished Indian minority,
feared that converting to dollars would lead to painful reductions
in their already low living standards.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, thousands of Indians marched on Congress. Army
guards stepped aside, leaving Mahuad besieged in the presidential
palace. Two military-civilian juntas were named in rapid
succession. Then, after the Clinton administration strongly
condemned the unfolding coup and threatened the new regime with
economic isolation, the military handed power back to Noboa, the
elected vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's timely diplomatic intervention was constructive.
But real stability will not return until Ecuador's leaders,
starting with Noboa, address the country's fundamental economic
problems. Tax revenues must be fairly increased, corruption
prosecuted and public-sector subsidies sharply reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Austerity measures such as these will be hard to apply until the
government broadens its popular legitimacy and wins the confidence
of the Indian population. Meanwhile, Ecuador's political parties
have to recognize that their incessant infighting is discrediting
civilian rule and dangerously increasing the political power of
military commanders. They must show themselves capable of serious
reforms before outside creditors can be approached for further debt
relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0445 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-IOWA-NYT &LR;      01-24 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IOWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IOWA STARTS THE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Tuesday, Jan. 25: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victories by Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore
finally move the 2000 presidential campaign to the phase of real
results. For the next six weeks and perhaps longer, numbers will
speak more loudly than all the earlier prognostications about the
battles for the Republican and Democratic nominations. But the Iowa
verdict, while sustaining Bush's and Gore's front-runner status,
hardly insulates them from New Hampshire's upset-minded voters. The
strong showing of Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes means that the Texas
governor will face competition for the conservative vote in New
Hampshire, weakening his ability to contest Sen. John McCain for
the moderate vote. Former Sen. Bill Bradley suffered a setback in
Iowa but remains a formidable challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, for its part, showed the differing dynamics between the
one-on-one Democratic contest and the six-candidate race on the
Republican side. Once Bradley decided to contest the state, Gore
was able to revitalize his campaign by casting himself as a fighter
able to survive without the protective cloak of inevitability. He
was also able to use his union and party backing to stretch
Bradley's thinner resources.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley's efforts in Iowa faltered toward the end, he has
considerable support in New Hampshire. He may also do well in other
states. Whoever ends up as the Democratic nominee will be tougher
and more skilled, and he will still be camped out in the party's
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican field, McCain's GOP insurgency has slowed a
bit as well. But the failure of Bush to do better against Forbes
and Keyes could give him an opportunity to open up a lead against
Bush in New Hampshire, the first fight he has chosen to contest.
One of the interesting paradoxes of that state now is that Bradley
and McCain will be battling across party lines for the independent
voters who make up 37 percent of the New Hampshire electorate.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how well Bush does in Iowa, his performance there
could be costly in terms of ideological positioning. The governor
had sought to present himself as a moderate determined not to be
tagged as an anti-abortion extremist. He had said that he would not
apply a litmus test for Supreme Court nominees. But the Iowa result
portends a continuing necessity to appeal to Christian evangelicals
and harden his opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference before the weekend, Bush said that he would
appoint justices who strictly interpret the Constitution and then
asserted that the right to abortion was not guaranteed by the
Constitution. With each new question he has become more querulous,
with his press spokesman finally declaring that he would no longer
hold press conferences unless they were in his interest. This was
not a positive sign for Bush's professed determination to appeal to
moderates in the general election, should he win the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has time and probably the dexterity to move back to the
center. The pressures on all the candidates underscore both the
seriousness and the value of this new phase of the process. Over
the next few weeks, delegates will be won and candidacies will
either strengthen or die. And a process that sometimes seems
irrational, debilitating and endless will quickly show its value in
shaping the choice voters will face in November. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
