<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CRASH-SNOW2TAKES-KAN &LR;      01-24 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SNOW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A BLINK OF AN EYE, ROAD TURNED DEADLY IN MULTICAR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL, BILL GRAHAM and MATT CAMPBELL  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was early Sunday afternoon, the wind whipping snow across
Interstate 29.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Purkey, an emergency medical technician for MAST, was
off-duty and driving on southbound. She'd been in St. Joseph
shopping with her 15-year-old daughter but cut the trip short when
the weather turned nasty.
</P>
<P>
   They were minutes from home as she topped the crest of a hill
just north of the Missouri 273 overpass. The snow suddenly fell
heavily and everything went white.
</P>
<P>
   ``One minute I could see OK and within the blink of an eye, I
couldn't see anything,'' she said. ``I slowed down as the
visibility got worse. I slowed down more when I saw people driving
northbound flashing their lights. I knew that meant something was
going on up ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Up ahead, cars and vans and trucks and semi-trailers had begun
to slide and pinwheel on the black ice and snow on I-29. A semi
tractor-trailer hauling potatoes tried to dodge the swerving
vehicles and jackknifed, skidding sideways, finally stopping and
blocking the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   More cars and trucks followed, drivers blinded by the flying
snow, able to see nothing but brake lights.
</P>
<P>
   A second tractor trailer truck driver told Joe Maddick,
assistant director with the Northland Regional Ambulance District,
that he heard of the initial pileup on his CB radio and began to
slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he could see the semi cross ways and he was able to
stop about 30 to 40 yards short of the tractor trailer,'' Maddick
said. ``He said he started feeling people hitting his trailer and
then saw another tractor-trailer coming over the hill. He said it
was obvious it was not going to be able to stop, so he drove his
truck about 50 yards off the roadway.''
</P>
<P>
   The approaching semi crashed into the pile of already wrecked
vehicles, squashing them against the truck jackknifed across the
road. The impact punctured gas tanks and a fire began. Stoked by
the leaking gas, the blaze blossomed, its flames leaping 50 feet
into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more cars and trucks were crashing into the second
semi, which was hauling cleaning supplies. The supplies included 80
pounds of diluted hydrochloric acid. Those vehicles caught fire.
Two other semis swerved across the median into the northbound lanes
to avoid the fiery mess. Other vehicles slid into the median or off
the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Then more crashes. On the embankment next to I-29, a pickup
smashed into a tractor-trailer and became wedged beneath it,
crushing the cab's roof and trapping the driver. It took
firefighters an hour to free him. He was treated at a hospital and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to miss the wreck, a grandfather from Florida drove off
the interstate. His car overturned and he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   When the accident began, Willard Wiley was tending his antique
store at the interchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard a banging sound out there, and it sounded like
thunder in here,'' Wiley said. ``I went outside...(and) saw a
semitruck coming up the grassy area and I knew something was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Black smoke rose from the wrecks. There were explosions.
</P>
<P>
   It was then Laura Purkey managed to stop her car and get out.
MAST units were already there and she ran to one to grab supplies
and help the man trapped under the semi-trailer.
</P>
<P>
   MAST field supervisor Eric Dooley said the terrain may have
contributed to the wreck's severity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You crest the hill and boom, there it was,'' he said. ``By the
time you saw a wreck, you were in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene looked like a war zone. Flames shot up from the
twisted and melting metal. Rescuers watched in horror as victims
burned in their vehicles. Other victims _ dazed and shaken _
staggered in the swirling snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the worst traffic accident scene I have ever been at
in my 33 year career,'' said Sgt. Jack McMillen of the Missouri
Highway Patrol. ``It looked like someone dropped a bomb on the
interstate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten would die in the fire and wreckage. Officials said those
involved in the wreck either died or had only minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the ten victims were burned beyond recognition, caught
in the fireball between the semis. Authorities were able to
tentatively identify eight of the dead through evidence left in
their vehicles. Five were Springfield residents returning from
weekend trip in Nebraska; two were from the Dakotas heading back to
college in Bolivar, Mo.; and one was the Florida grandfather in
town for his 16-year-old grandson's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had few clues to identify the other two victims
because their bodies and vehicles were burned so completely.
</P>
<P>
   McMillen said the patrol requested dental records from the
families of the eight tentatively-identified persons and flew the
records into town Monday to try to positively identify the victims.
The process could take several days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Causes of death were not available Monday. McMillen said it
appeared some of the victims died instantly but others likely
burned to death in the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   The fire prevented the rescue of any of the badly hurt victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't get out of their vehicles themselves and no one
could get to them to help them,'' McMillen said. ``One citizen told
me he tried to get people out but was driven back by the fire. The
victims didn't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Steve Johnson of the Platte County Sheriff's Department
saw people trying to help others escape their vehicles, despite the
flames and occasional explosions from tires and fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers described the initial minutes after the crash as
chaotic and a scene from ``Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Central Platte Fire Chief Larry Bigus said firefighters ``were
climbing on cars, putting out fires and we could see bodies inside.
And you think about how there was nothing you could do to help
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Camden Point Fire Chief Jeff Zion, holding a fire
hose, clambered onto the top of the burning tractor-trailor that
contained hydrochloric acid. The concussion from an explosion,
possibly a drum within the truck, blew him backward off the vehicle
but into the arms of a West Platte firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters fought the blaze for about an hour. There are no
fire hydrants along the interstate so tankers had to haul water to
the scene. Most of the firefighters were volunteers, working the
worst accident they had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with your emotions,'' said Walt Stubbs, chief
of the Camden Point Fire Protection District, ``wanting to sit
there and throw up, or just turn around and walk away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
