<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICAN RETAIL GROUP BUYS REMAINDER OF COMPUSA
</P>
<P>
   A retail group controlled by Carlos Slim Helu, the Mexican
billionaire, said it was buying CompUSA, the U.S. chain of
personal-computer stores, marking one of the biggest Mexican
purchases of a prominent U.S. business. Slim's retailing chain,
Grupo Sanborn, already owns 14.8 percent of the common shares in
CompUSA, a Dallas-based network of computer stores that has been
struggling with losses and declining sales.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a drive to transform Telefonos de Mexico, the
formerly state-owned telephone company that is controlled by Slim
and is his flagship business, into a fast-paced, Web-savvy
multinational giant.
</P>
<P>
   RALLYING AROUND BEN &AMP; JERRY'S CHAIN
</P>
<P>
   A group of Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice-cream shop owners plans to rally in
various cities Tuesday to protest what they say is the threat that
a corporate takeover would pose to the company's image of social
responsibility. Last month the company announced that it had
received ``indications of interest'' from an unidentified company.
Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, which was founded by Ben Cohen and Jerry
Greenfield, said at the time that the offer was subject to
conditions but that its board would consider it.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO OFFICE REVAMPS MANAGEMENT
</P>
<P>
   The ranks of top managers at the flagship New York office of
BBDO Worldwide, the largest agency in the Omnicom Group, are being
revamped in an effort to identify the next generation of leadership
and increase the attention paid to important tasks like landing
more clients and broadening offerings beyond traditional
advertising forums.
</P>
<P>
   INSURER'S STOCK PLAN QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   A handful of policyholders of Metropolitan Life Insurance argued
that the proposed terms for the company's conversion to ownership
by stockholders from ownership by policyholders were unfair. Under
the plan, policyholders are to be given shares representing their
contribution to company profits in exchange for their ownership
stake in the company.
</P>
<P>
   EVENT TICKETS FROM A HOME PRINTER
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster-Online CitySearch said that beginning in April it
would allow customers to print tickets to events directly from
their computer printers.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS &AMP; SPENCER NAMES CHAIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   Marks &AMP; Spencer, Britain's august but ailing retailer, broke
with a long tradition and reached beyond the nation's shores to
hire a new executive chairman, offering a $22 million package to
lure the Belgian-born Luc Vandevelde from Promodes, a leading
grocery chain based in France.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK POSTS PROFIT OF $475 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak said it earned $475 million in the fourth quarter,
exceeding analysts' forecasts and setting off a rally in its stock
price, which jumped $1.3125, to $62.0625. The company's
fourth-quarter sales totaled $3.8 billion. Losses in Kodak's
digital business narrowed to $17 million from $91 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic and BellSouth said strong demand for data,
wireless and telephone features lifted their fourth-quarter profits
to meet or beat Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb's fourth-quarter profit rose 16 percent as
sales rose for its diabetes, heart disease and cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   MORGAN STANLEY IS FINED
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage firm Morgan Stanley was censured and fined
$495,000 by a self-regulatory brokers' group for manipulating the
prices of nine stocks in the Nasdaq 100 Index.
</P>
<P>
   GATES FOUNDATION GETS $5 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation said that Bill Gates, the
billionaire founder of Microsoft, and his wife have donated $5
billion to their philanthropic foundation, making it the world's
wealthiest foundation, with assets of $21.8 billion. A spokesman
for the foundation said it gave about $800 million last year and
made commitments of over $2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
