<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SNOW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A BLINK OF AN EYE, ROAD TURNED DEADLY IN MULTICAR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL, BILL GRAHAM and MATT CAMPBELL  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of the burned victims were unrecognizable beyond general
size and shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all the patients that could go to the hospital
out,'' Robert O'Dell, Deputy Chief of the Central Platte Fire
Protection District, said. ``We've got the fire out...Now we've got
to start extrication of dead people. That's when it really starts
to take its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Many rescuers arrived as the fire was began to dwindle.
``Walking-wounded,'' victims with minor cuts and scratches,
wandered around the interstate. Some waited in Wiley's antique
mall. Others sat in the warmed cars of those caught in the traffic
jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone seemed scared to death because of the fire,'' Maddick
said. ``In a normal accident, people stay in their cars, but these
people got out and ran as far as they could. I don't blame them.
The fire was absolutely intense.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire fused many of the crashed vehicles. It took workers
hours to pry them apart.
</P>
<P>
   Four victims went by ambulance to area hospitals, but others got
their own rides. Ambulances were scarce because of countless other
wrecks in the area, including an unrelated 20-car pileup north and
east of Platte City. No one was seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers said the wreck could have been avoided or
minimized if motorists had slowed down during snow storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was to point blame, it would be the speed,'' Maddick
said. ``People in four-wheel drives especially, have a false sense
of security. That's not going to help them from sliding.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bishop, executive director of the Northland Regional
Ambulance District, said people are unrealistic if they think they
can stop a 2,000- pound car in a few feet in a snow storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're doing 45 mph, you're not going to realize your
brakes aren't grabbing until you need to stop,'' Bishop said. ``And
then it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The snowstorm caught Missouri Department of Transportation
officials off-guard. Streets were not treated until after the
deadly crash.
</P>
<P>
   With unseasonably warm temperatures on Saturday and a weather
forecast Sunday that only called for light snow, MoDot officials
said they were not expecting any pavement to reach freezing
temperatures until Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But freeze they did. The area reported about 800 wrecks Sunday
with dozens of people injured.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal pileup was just one of at least five separate
multi-vehicle wrecks within a four-mile section of I-29 on Sunday
afternoon, stretching from the Platte River to the rest area at
mile marker 27.
</P>
<P>
   No serious injuries were reported in the other accidents, which
officials attributed to blowing snow and icy pavement. But three
Camden Point firefighters were treated for injuries. One of their
trucks was rammed from behind on I-29 by a motorist who could not
stop. Another Camden Point fire vehicle left a county road and
rolled over in the a ditch to avoid a collision.
</P>
<P>
   MoDot began calling in crews around 1 p.m. But by the time crews
were ready to hit the roads, the Platte City crash and other
serious pileups had already occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We responded very quickly.'' said Warren Roberts, MoDot's area
engineer for Platte and Clay counties, ``Unfortunately, some of the
roads turned icy before we could get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writers Mike Mansur, Mike Rice and Shawna Hamel
contributed to this report. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
