<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN'S NEW JERSEY BUDGET IS BIGGER, WITH TAX CUTS TOO
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Saying New Jersey's sustained economic boom and
the state's mounting surpluses had created an ``unprecedented
opportunity,'' Gov. Christie Whitman proposed her most generous
budget yet on Monday, a $21.2 billion plan that increases spending
by $1.3 billion for a host of new programs, tax cuts and ambitious
school and highway construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, a Republican, asserted that her spending plan, which
she titled a ``Prosperity Dividend,'' would actually strengthen her
record as a fiscal conservative. She boasted that she had
completely eliminated so-called one-shot revenues and that her
budget would leave yet another record surplus while keeping the
average yearly growth in spending during her two terms to the
lowest level of any governor in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who likes to remind voters how often she has
lowered or eliminated taxes, proposed three new tax cuts on Monday,
including an earned income tax credit for which nearly 280,000
residents would be eligible. Under the program, families earning
$15,000 would receive a $338 check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, and in case anyone's counting, it will make for tax cut
No. 40,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also proposed a two-year suspension of employees'
contribution to unemployment insurance, which now is capped at
$42.40 a year each, as well as the employers' share, which ranges
from $440 for a small business to $44,000 for a large company. The
state's unemployment insurance fund, has ballooned to the nation's
third largest, at $2.9 billion, enough to pay for two and a half
years of anticipated benefits without any additional collections.
</P>
<P>
   Acting to shore up the area in which she has been most
vulnerable to criticism _ her propensity to borrow _ Whitman called
for a new fund to begin to retire the state's debt. But she set
aside no money in her budget for that purpose, and Democrats
roundly criticized her proposal as disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget is the latest exercise in spending for an
administration that has never seen a line of credit it didn't
like,'' said the Assembly minority leader, Joseph Doria, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   There was real money in the budget, however, for a broad array
of constituencies: $70 million for health insurance for the working
poor and $55 million for the disabled, $100 million for hospitals
and more than $45 million for colleges, $25 million for high-tech
entrepreneurs and $10 million for cancer researchers, to name a
few.
</P>
<P>
   Immediate complaints came only from those who got something but
wanted still more. A coalition of antismoking groups known as New
Jersey Breathes lamented that Whitman had only allocated $30
million for tobacco prevention efforts. ``We're shocked,'' the
group's chairman, Paul Wallner, said, adding that an additional $15
million could make New Jersey's program as effective as any in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The budget includes two long-awaited capital programs, and each
entails an important concession to a Republican contender to
succeed Whitman as governor. She proposed to spend $9.4 billion to
rebuild the state's crumbling schools, including $5 billion for
inner-city districts to comply with a court order. But she agreed
to a demand by the Assembly speaker, Jack Collins, a likely
candidate for governor, that she set aside $100 million to finance
such construction from the $300 million a year in anticipated
receipts from the nationwide tobacco settlement. The governor had
sought to reserve the tobacco money for health care programs.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech on Monday, Whitman sounded a note of caution about
the tobacco money, which is certain to come under pressure from
lawmakers during the budget negotiation process, which by law and
tradition must end with passage of an appropriations law before the
end of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``With $7.4 billion over the next 25 years, we have to set a
good example _ avoid the raid-the-cookie-jar mentality _ and spend
this money responsibly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Education lobbyists praised the governor's concession, saying a
stable source of revenue was needed to pay for such an ambitious
statewide construction effort. But Whitman's budget acknowledges
that after five years, additional revenue sources will be needed to
generate annual increases of $50 million in debt service costs.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also proposed a refinancing of the state's depleted
transportation trust fund to pay for $1 billion in new projects
each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
