<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTER LEAD-IN TIME HAS POSITIVES, NEGATIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Without the customary two-week break between the NFL
conference championship games and the Super Bowl, those inclined to
weighty analysis will bombard you in the upcoming days with
insufferably tedious opinions on what effect the briefer interlude
will have on the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I don't think the outcome of Super Bowl XXXIV between
the St. Louis Rams and Tennessee Titans or the tone of the
proceedings would be any different if it were played on Feb. 6 at
the Georgia Dome instead of Sunday when the game to end all games
for hype, ticket scalping and crass commercialization will be
staged.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, perhaps the Titans' star receiver, Yancey Thigpen, nursing a
bum foot, would be healthier in two weeks, but I'm not sure his
status will determine the ultimate fate of his team.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm sure a 14-day layoff would have given the owner of the
Rams, Georgia Frontiere, a greater opportunity to undergo one of
her celebrated nip and tuck cosmetic makeovers in London before
making her grand Super Bowl appearance at a stadium that was not,
contrary to propaganda now being disseminated by her PR minions,
named after her for her Mother Teresa contributions to humankind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's indisputable that the shorter break will have a
dramatic impact both positive and negative on peripheral
developments affiliated with the Super Bowl:
</P>
<P>
   Positive: Blessedly, we'll only have to endure a week of the
Georgia Frontiere Story, a heart-warming saga that reached its
watershed moment on April 1, 1979, when her sixth husband, Carroll
Rosenbloom, ran afoul of a riptide in the Atlantic Ocean off the
coast of Florida, which resulted in Georgia inheriting the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Negative: America's most enduring entrepreneurs, ticket brokers,
won't have their usual cushy two weeks to procure and move their
precious commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Positive: We will be spared 14 consecutive days of shameless
self-promotion by Fox Sports of the All-Madden team, named in honor
of a once entertaining fellow who's been retired for years even
though he and those still propping him up on the Fox network aren't
aware of such a fact.
</P>
<P>
   Negative: Investigative reporters won't have enough time to do
an in-depth piece on Dominic Frontiere, Georgia's one-time hubbie
who did a stretch in the federal pen for income tax evasion growing
out of a Super Bowl scandal in which the only dots ol' loyal Dom
connected were to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Positive: The phoniest soothsayers this side of your friendly
neighborhood palm reader, football handicappers, will have only a
short time to con their gullible customers with their ``sure winner
selections'' even though the only surefire thing in the NFL these
days is for the referee to blow at least one important instant
replay call a game.
</P>
<P>
   Negative: The Super Bowl players won't have the two-week luxury
to sit on their tickets and wait for the prices to skyrocket out of
sight. Why, some might become so disillusioned that they might even
be moved to actually share their ticket allotment this time with
family members beyond mom and dad and even with some old high
school chums.
</P>
<P>
   Positive: America's most fiercely original thinkers, radio disc
jockeys, will shockingly all come up with the same enlightened idea
of reviving one of the great disco songs of all time, Rick James'
``Super Freak'', in tribute to the Titans' extraordinary 6-5,
265-pound rookie defensive end, Jevon Kearse, whose nickname is The
Freak.
</P>
<P>
   Negative: Reporters will be in a mad scramble to come up with
exotic angles and some inevitably will extricate from well-deserved
obscurity Buddy Ryan, Mike Ditka's one-time sparring partner with
the Chicago Bears who would have you believe he invented the art of
coaching football. You see, the Tennessee head coach, Jeff Fisher,
once served as Ryan's assistant for five seasons with the
Philadelphia Eagles, although Fisher somehow avoided picking up
Ryan's egotistical habits.
</P>
<P>
   Positive: One of the most unsteady quarterback performances in
recent playoff history Tampa Bay's Shaun King's wobbly labors
against the Rams will be quickly forgotten, much to the benefit of
King's psyche. If the Rams were true sportsmen, they should give
Mr. King a share of their Super Bowl earnings because they'd have
never made it to Atlanta without his invaluable assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Negative: One of the fabled coaching jobs in all seasons of the
NFL Tony Dungy's masterpiece with a Tampa Bay team that came within
an eyelash of upsetting the Rams even though it endured under the
daunting handicap of operating with a sandlot player at quarterback
will be blithely overlooked because of time limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Positive: We'll only be subjected a brief while with the Bud
Adams Story, a stirring narration about a spoiled son of a Texas
millionaire oilman who played a vital role in changing the
landscape of professional sports in 1960 when he and the Kansas
City Chiefs' Lamar Hunt started a fledging enterprise called the
American Football League. Adams might now be a hero in Tennessee,
but the Titans' owner remains a despised figure in Texas for moving
the Oilers out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Negative: John Shaw, Georgia Frontiere's notorious financial
hitman who choreographed the Rams' scandalous dissipation in
Southern California, will have a greater opportunity to hide from
his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Positive: Dick Vermeil, a control freak by nature, won't have
that extra week to keep the media from prying on his players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
