<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5322 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-IOWA-CAUCUSES-ART-2TA     01-24 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-CAUCUSES-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GAINS A CLEAR VICTORY IN IOWA; FORBES AND KEYES RUN STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas won a clear
victory in the Iowa Republican caucuses on Monday night, but his
two closest competitors, Steve Forbes and Alan Keyes, who both
appealed to religious conservatives, drew strong support in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Returns in the Democratic contest, between Vice President Al
Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, were slower to come in.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Bush, a two-term Texas governor in his
first try for national office, surpassed the 37 percent record that
Bob Dole drew in a six-candidate field in Iowa in 1988, a number
that Bush had said was his goal.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring victory based on early tallies barely an hour after
the caucuses began across the state, Bush said in a television
interview, ``I am thrilled with this record-shattering victory. I
am grateful and I'm humbled.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``My message of compassionate conservatism resonated
loud. The people of Iowa want a leader who can unite our party and
our country _ and that's exactly the signal they have sent.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, the wealthy magazine publisher who had pumped millions
from his family fortune into the race here, finished a strong
second place, roughly tripling the 10 percent he drew here four
years ago. Alan Keyes, a former State Department official, ranked a
distant third, outpacing Gary Bauer, the prominent religious
conservative, Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Sen. Orrin G. Hatch
of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not compete here, preferring to concentrate his
campaign in New Hampshire, where the nation's first primary will be
held Feb. 1. McCain is neck and neck with Bush in the polls there.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Bush has towered over the Republican field
because of his record-breaking fund-raising, impressive poll
numbers and vast endorsements. Monday night, for the first time,
actual voters affirmed his position as front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   While Forbes had long been viewed as Bush's toughest competitor
here, Keyes' showing was particularly striking because he has run a
low-budget campaign and many Republican had dismissed him as more a
protest candidate than a serious vote-getter. But he drew
particular attention for his stand-out role in many of the
Republican debates.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent victory for Gore was important for the vice
president because he and Bradley were locked in an aggressive,
competitive race here.
</P>
<P>
   Though Iowa has been at the epicenter of American politics, the
results are far from a reliable indicator of who will end up at the
White House _ or even win the first primary in New Hampshire next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The last candidate to win a contested caucus and be elected
president was Jimmy Carter in 1976. In 1988, the eventual nominees,
Michael S. Dukakis and George Bush, placed third in the caucuses.
The two victors, Dick Gephardt and Bob Dole, had quit the race by
the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, there was no contested Democratic race. Dole won
the Republican caucuses, but he was followed closely by Pat
Buchanan, who then triumphed in New Hampshire but lost the
nomination to Dole. In recent years, the voting here has been more
important for narrowing the field.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many other states have derided Iowa for all the attention that
it draws from the contenders, and from the press, because the state
is overwhelmingly white and not particularly representative of the
nation. Of the 1.8 million registered voters in Iowa, no more than
200,000 had been expected to participate Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, those who participate are not especially
representative even of Iowa. They are among the more politically
active residents and they tend to be the more conservative or
liberal members of their party. To a large measure, the outcome
reflects the organizational prowess of candidates and interest
groups in prodding people to give up a Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But the caucuses have become high profile events because the
national press covers them heavily, which in turn prompts the
candidates to spend more time here.
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses started at 7 p.m., when residents went to schools,
church basements, meeting halls and private homes across the state.
The voting marked only the beginning of a months-long process of
selecting delegates to the Republican and Democratic conventions,
where the nominees would actually be chosen. The Republican vote
was merely a straw poll and would have little impact on the
selection of actual delegates to the convention, who will be chosen
at county conventions, congressional district conventions and state
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, the voting Monday night will have more
influence on the selection of actual delegates. Iowa would
eventually account for 56 of the party's 4,337 convention
delegates. The state will send 25 of the 2,169 delegates to the
Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   For months _ years in some cases _ Iowa has served as a second
home for many candidates. They poured millions of dollars into
television commercials, and they campaigned from hog farms to high
schools, making their pitches to a relatively tiny number of
voters. Even before the intense campaigning of the past month,
Forbes had ben here 69 days; Bradley, 62 days; Bauer, 54 days;
Keyes, 51 days; Gore, 35 days; and Bush, 19 days. This was the
first time since 1988 that both parties had competitive contests.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before Iowans voted, the contenders devoted one last day to
trying to persuade and cajole the undecided and the uncommitted.
Bush got an early start, striding into a restaurant here at 7:45
Monday morning and competing with eggs and pastries for the
attention of the scattered diners.
</P>
<P>
   ``No rest for a while,'' he told a diner. ``It's like running a
marathon. I ran a marathon in 1993, and it just requires patience
and discipline and focus, and this is mile six.''
</P>
<P>
   At a subsequent stop in Ames, where he delivered a speech at
Iowa State University, Bush was upbeat and folksy, offering a
homespun riff on how hard it has been to spend so many days on the
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the cats,'' he said. ``They don't miss me. I miss the
dog. She does miss me.'' But his playfulness had its limits. When
the documentary filmmaker, Michael Moore _ who has been traveling
through Iowa with a ``mosh pit'' in which people roll around _
asked Bush to participate, the governor said, ``Behave yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes spent his last day pretty much as always _ with a heavy
dose of radio interviews on conservative programs. By 3 p.m., he
had appeared on 20 radio programs and 14 television programs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters as he campaigned with two of his five
daughters, Forbes asserted that he was the leading conservative in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Gore on Monday played down reports that he used marijuana more
extensively in his mid-20s than he has admitted. Asked whether he
had smoked marijuana almost daily in the early 1970s, Gore told the
NBC affiliate here, KWQC, ``No, when I came back from Vietnam, yes,
but not to that extent. This is something I dealt with a longtime
ago _ it's old news.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who is 51, added: ``When I was young, I did
things young people do. When I grew up, I put away childish
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley held his only public event at Iowa State University,
where he told several hundred students and faculty members that
politics in America had lost touch with the needs of ``real''
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics to too many young people, to too many Americans, has
become nothing other than tactics,'' Bradley said. ``It's become
tactics and not belief. It's become spin and not truth. It's become
fund-raising and not reaching out to people where they live their
lives. It has become all of the things that are artificial in our
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
