<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SCORING IN IOWA, A QUICK FLIGHT TO N.H. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Governor George W. Bush was looking forward to one
thing Monay night. And it wasn't the caucus results.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Iowa caucuses even began, the Texas governor and his
aides were predicting his victory and thinking ahead to the Feb. 1
New Hampshire primary and beyond _ speaking in confident terms, and
even anticipating the end of the campaigns of Bush's two chief
competitors, Senator John McCain of Arizona and millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the beginning of the decision of who ought to carry our
message,'' Bush told a rally in the afternoon. ``It's also the
beginning of the end of the Clinton era in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same speech, he declared himself to be ``a free trade
president.'' Then, after 10 seconds of applause, he added: ``To
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent the day traveling throughout the state by bus, first
stopping for coffee at a diner in Des Moines before addressing
crowds in the neighboring towns of Ames and Perry. His speeches _
which sounded at times as much like victory addresses as
last-minute pleas for votes _ drew sizable crowds, as Bush's
appearances did throughout his final five-day swing through Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, a crew of Bush supporters worked
throughout the day to urge voters to get out to the caucuses,
fearing Bush's lead in recent polls would leave supporters
uninspired to turn out. A group of approximately 30 state
legislators flew in from Texas to spend the day calling undecided
voters and supporters to talk them into participating, said senior
aide Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rove was hardly fearful for the night's results. Unmoved
by the well-financed campaign of Forbes _ who has run negative
advertisements about Bush, and to whom even a modest showing in
Iowa would be seen as a success _ Rove said: ``This is a five-week
rush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not organized, if you're not competing, if you're
not up in South Carolina, if you didn't have an organization in
Arizona and Michigan, you're nowhere,'' he said. ``And the fact of
the fact of the matter is, Forbes is on the tube in three states _
Delaware, New Hampshire and Iowa _ and he has an organization
virtually nowhere else in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has advertisements running in nine early primary states,
and his $71 million campaign coffer is poised to run them in all 50
states, Rove said, ``when the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rove stated the obvious: That a Bush victory
in Iowa would bolster his chances in New Hampshire, where he faces
a much tighter race against McCain. ``People want validation,''
Rove said. ``Bush has high numbers all around the country...But
people want to know in the first test, `Can he do well?' People
will be paying attention to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, spoke even more confidently.
``The time advantage Senator McCain has enjoyed is gone as of 2
a.m.,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was planning to leave Des Moines just three hours after the
caucuses began to fly to Manchester, N.H., where his campaign had
organized a rally for 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Laura, Bush's wife, flew in from Austin early Monday morning.
But their twin 18-year-old daughters, Barbara and Jenna, did not
join them. Bush explained: ``The girls are in school. They're
camera shy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's humor did not extend to filmmaker Michael Moore, who has
been traveling the state during recent days. Moore approached Bush
Monday and invited him to join in a mosh pit _ a group of people
slamming into each other _ but the governor declined.
</P>
<P>
   He told the filmmaker: ``Behave yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
