<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-JILSANDER-RESIGN-ART-     01-24 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JILSANDER-RESIGN-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIL SANDER IS DIVORCING PRADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 BY GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of corporate mergers and acquisitions, matches are
often made between companies as they are between men and women in
Woody Allen movies: according to the rule of opposites. The
buttoned-up marry the buttoned-down, the glitzy wed the discreet.
But when Prada acquired a 75 percent stake in the house of Jil
Sander late last August, the union seemed to be one of like minds.
Both labels stand for sanity in fashion and a kind of postmodern
good taste. And both Ms. Sander and Patrizio Bertelli, Prada's
chief executive, are thought of as intelligent, visionary sorts who
live far removed from the world of the laid-back.
</P>
<P>
   Mind-meld, though, is clearly no guarantee of happiness. Monday,
Ms. Sander surprised the fashion industry by resigning as
chairwoman of her company. The fall 2000 women's collection she is
scheduled to show in Milan next month will be her last. Under
Prada's stewardship, the Jil Sander line will continue, presumably
with a new creative head.
</P>
<P>
   Though no one from Ms. Sander's company or the Prada Group would
comment on the shift, several people in the fashion industry
closely associated with Ms. Sander and Bertelli say that the two
had developed a strained working relationship over the direction
Ms. Sander's company should take. Following her men's-wear show in
Milan earlier this month, Ms. Sander addressed rumors of a clash.
``With a merger, there are always different cultures,'' she said.
``This is a training period,'' she added, referring to her first
months as part of the Prada Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem of personalities,'' said one fashion executive
who has been following the partnership closely. ``They're
different, but they're also exactly the same. They want to run
their own shows.'' Ms. Sander, the executive added, ``thought she'd
continue her rein at Jil Sander.'' Bertelli, he said, ``has clear
ideas of where the company should go.''
</P>
<P>
   A news release issued Monday by the Sander company and Prada
Group announcing the split declared that the five-month-old
partnership had resulted in a ``new strategic policy'' with the aim
of ``improving sales and profitability and thereby the shareholder
value of the company.'' The stock price of Ms. Sander's company,
which is traded on the Frankfurt exchange, rose from $312 to $352 a
share in September after the Prada deal but has since fallen to
$226 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sander partnered with Bertelli in large part to expand her
accessories business, she said earlier this month. Ms. Sander is
the rare designer who does 90 percent of her business in clothing,
as opposed to the shoes, handbags and other accessories that are
the mainstays of most luxury-goods houses. Prada's investment was
part of its strategy to build a premium-brand empire by buying
control of small companies and expanding their product lines. It
also purchased Church &AMP; Co., the British shoemaker, and 51 percent
of Helmut Lang last year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although it is unclear exactly what Ms. Sander and Bertelli
could not agree on, some in the fashion industry believe that Prada
was trying to expand Ms. Sander's accessories business at a rate
she was not comfortable with or at the expense of her ready-to-wear
line. Ms. Sander is known for the use of wildly expensive fabrics
and manufacturing methods that leave items like simply cut
lightweight sweaters costing $800 or $900, higher than similar
pieces in other designer collections. Prada might have been
encouraging a price restructuring, industry insiders said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as Ms. Sander was selling an early portion
of her fall 2000 women's line in Hamburg to retailers from around
the world. Sales of Ms. Sander's clothes in the United States have
done consistently well, retailers here say. Linda Dresner, who has
carried the Jil Sander line for 12 years in her Park Avenue store,
said the designer ``is the most important brand in our store.'' Ms.
Dresner, who dined with Ms. Sander in Hamburg Monday night, said
she would continue to carry the line ``for now.'' Jeffrey Kalinsky,
the owner of Jeffrey in New York and Atlanta, as well as a Jil
Sander shop in Atlanta, said that Ms. Sander's clothes have
``exceeded my needs,'' in terms of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys New York has also done a consistently good business with
Jil Sander, said Judy Collinson, the store's general merchandise
manager. The Sander line is not doomed, Ms. Collinson said. ``She
built a tremendous design team,'' Ms. Collinson added. ``I think
her product will occupy the same place in the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
