<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5334 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-MCCAIN-COX     01-24 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-MCCAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain's shunning of Iowa reflected in caucuses
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, N.H. _ Iowa got no respect Monday from Sen. John
McCain (R-Ariz.).
</P>
<P>
   And the Senator didn't get much in return from Iowans, with a
finish well back in the pack of contenders in the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said he was pleased by the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 5 percent more than I thought I was going to get, and I'm
very pleased that we saved ourselves a lot of money and assets''
McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could view it as a good showing by both Forbes and
Keyes,'' he said of the results.
</P>
<P>
   McCain sees little correlation between the Iowa outcome and what
will happen in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure they are going to be affected much by what
happens in Iowa,'' he said of New Hampshire voters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, at his 100th town hall meeting in New
Hampshire, McCain described Monday's Iowa caucuses as unworthy of
his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's the preliminaries (being held in Iowa), and the
finals are right here in New Hampshire in seven days, 12 hours and
16 minutes, not that I'm counting,'' McCain said at the local
armory, where his campaign marked the occasion with a huge cake and
the playing of Jerry Lee Lewis' version of ``Johnny B. Goode.''
</P>
<P>
   His choice of terms may seem odd for the first primary in the
nation, but McCain's words conveyed the importance of making a
strong showing in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   While the other five Republicans and two Democrats were in Iowa
for last-minute campaigning, McCain did what he has done on 63
other days in the past year. He campaigned in New Hampshire, where
he hopes to defeat Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in next week's
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The state is crucial to McCain's chances, the first of four
states that McCain has chosen to try to pierce the notion that
Bush's nomination is inevitable. The other states are South
Carolina, Arizona and Michigan, all of which hold primaries later
in February.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
