<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERUP-URANIUM-IRAQ-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLETED URANIUM: THE EVIDENCE LIES DYING IN BASRA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Note `Editor's Backgrounder' _ and 13th graf)   (This provocative 525-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 (EDITOR'S BACKGROUNDER: ``INDEPENDENT'' CORRESPONDENT ROBERT FISK
HAS LONG DENOUNCED THE USE OF DEPLETED URANIUM (DU) SHELLS IN BOTH
THE GULF WAR AND NATO'S CONFLICT IN KOSOVO LAST YEAR. AFTER
REPEATEDLY CITING EVIDENCE OF AN ALARMING INCREASE IN CANCER CASES
LINKED TO DU, PARTICULARLY IN THE SOUTHERN IRAQI CITY OF BASRA _ AS
WELL AS ITS POSSIBLE LINK TO THE DEADLY ``GULF WAR SYNDROME'' IN
ALLIED TROOPS _ FISK AND SEVERAL HUMAN-RIGHTS GROUPS HAVE NOW
PRESSURED SCIENTISTS FROM BRITAIN'S ROYAL SOCIETY TO CARRY OUT AN
INDEPENDENT INVESTIGATION INTO THE DANGERS OF DEPLETED URANIUM.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ In Iraq, there are doctors aplenty who would like to
meet the six scientists from Britain's Royal Society chosen Monday
to investigate the damage, human and environmental, wreaked by
Western use of depleted uranium (DU) shells in both the Gulf War
and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the main Basra teaching hospital, the cancer sufferers who
live near the fields where depleted uranium shells (DU) were fired
by the hundreds in 1991 queue at the door of the tiny cancer clinic
each morning.
</P>
<P>
   But will the British scientists meet them? Will they go to Iraq
and study the documentation of Basra's leading cancer specialist,
Dr. Jawad al-Ali, who has maps showing the rate of leukemia growth
in the areas where Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's tanks were torn
apart by DU in the last days of the war?
</P>
<P>
   I think not.
</P>
<P>
   When Iraq asked the World Health Organization to investigate DU
two years ago, a team of experts arrived to see if such a study was
feasible; but no investigation took place.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Kosovo? The U.S. used DU rounds last year in its
attacks across the Serb province _ and then arrogantly refused to
tell U.N. investigators the location of its attacks. British
Foreign Secretary, Robin Cook, admitted as much in the Commons last
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Why cannot we be told where these rounds were fired? Will
the Royal Society's experts visit Kosovo? Will they ask NATO for
the information it refused to give to the U.N.?
</P>
<P>
   And what if NATO treats them with the same disdain? They could
do worse, for example, than to visit the bombed-out paramilitary
police barracks in Djakovica, where DU fired by American A-10
aircraft exploded in the very center of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But will they go to other parts of Yugoslavia? Will they visit
the areas around Belgrade where DU was also used? Will the British
government, indeed, allow them to go there?
</P>
<P>
   And what kind of brief is it that tells the scientists they are
to ``review the available evidence?''
</P>
<P>
   If this is to be anything more than a palliative to shut up the
Gulf War veterans who suspect they are dying of DU poisoning, these
six experts have to find the available evidence lying in the fields
of Kosovo and southern Iraq, not just trawl through published
reports and military denials.
</P>
<P>
   At one of NATO's May press conferences last year, spokesman
James Shea stated that there was no evidence suggesting DU was
dangerous, citing a report which turned out to be inaccurate. Is
this the sort of stuff the experts will be ``reviewing?''
</P>
<P>
   For almost two years, British Defense Ministry officials have
been claiming in letters to MPs that ``the Government has not seen
any peer-reviewed epidemiological research data'' on affected
populations _ mentioning my own reports in ``The Independent'' of
deformities, cancers and birth defects in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Is this, then, what this team is meant to do _ to provide the
Government with some ``peer-reviewed'' data without any serious
on-site inspection?
</P>
<P>
   I rather suspect it is. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: For related story, please refer to the story
slugged BC-NEW-LOOK-GULFWARSYNDROME-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF: ``Veterans
of Gulf War Welcome New DU Poisoning Tests'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this compelling 525-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
