<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JAN. 25
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CHURCHILL-DEGAULLE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Jan. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Jan. 5,
about telegrams critical of Gen. Charles de Gaulle sent from
Washington by Winston Churchill to his cabinet during World War II,
and the cabinet's response, referred incompletely to the documents'
secrecy classification. While the British Public Record Office kept
them classified secret until Jan. 4, they in fact became known
publicly. They were cited in a 1981 biography of the two leaders,
``Churchill and de Gaulle'' by Francois Kersaudy.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SWISS-BANKS-HOLOCAUST-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Dec. 6,
about an audit of Swiss banks conducted by a commission led by Paul
A. Volcker referred incorrectly to the findings. The commission
said that nearly 54,000 bank accounts had a ``probable or
possible'' link to victims of Nazi persecution, not that all the
accounts were probably linked to victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
