<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, January 25, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; HOUSE  &LR; _ When their landlord told Sidney and Arlene Lerner last
summer that he wouldn't renew their Foster City apartment lease,
the couple decided that the time had come to buy a house. Time was
limited, because the landlord gave them only a month's notice.
Unable to afford a house in Foster City, they booted up their
computer and began exploring several Internet Web sites that list
homes for sale throughout the Bay Area and beyond. They entered
parameters into the search engines, specifying four bedrooms, three
bathrooms, a swimming pool and a price in the vicinity of $200,000.
They were directed to 10 homes in the Vacaville area. By Arthur M.
Louis
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEYBAG  &LR; _ Commission-free account a good deal. By Arthur M.
Louis
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PACBELL &LR;  _ San Francisco resident Dennis Lewis said he was
startled last week when he received a warning from Pacific Bell in
the mail:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have equipment connected to your telephone?'' the
notice asked. Fax machines, answering machines, alarms and modems,
the letter warned, ``may need to be adjusted'' so they will work
with the company's new digital switching equipment. It also said
features like speed dialing and call forwarding may need to be
reprogrammed. By Todd Wallack
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; INTUIT &LR;  _ Intuit Inc. announced yesterday that it has named GE
Capital Executive Vice President Stephen M. Bennett as its new
president and chief executive. By Peter Sinton
</P>
