A5344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SETON-HALL-FIRE-ART-N     01-24 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SETON-HALL-FIRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
AFTER CAMPUS FIRE IN NEW JERSEY, A YEARNING FOR NORMALITY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(fb) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. _ Josie Roscigno and Lauren Covino sat in the
cafeteria of Seton Hall University on Monday afternoon giggling,
gossiping and making the kind of off-color jokes that only an
18-year-old undergraduate could appreciate. The two freshmen _
Giants fans, shopping addicts and best friends _ had not seen each
other in almost a week and there was plenty of catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   But the laughter and small talk could not conceal what both
women were really experiencing: dread, anxiety and emotional
exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say I'm freaking out a little bit,''
Roscigno said with a frayed smile. ``I'm not sure what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days after a fire killed three students, injured 54 and
forced hundreds of others into the frozen night air, residents of
Boland Hall, the six-story freshman dormitory where the blaze broke
out, were allowed to return to their rooms on Monday. It was the
first time many had stepped on campus since the fire on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day that the three dead students were buried in
separate funerals, many survivors of the fire said they were trying
to see beyond the events of last week, even as they found
themselves talking about it incessantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all sick of the topic,'' said Covino, who along
with Roscigno escaped injury by running down a stairwell as their
third-floor room began to fill with smoke. ``We just want to get
back to a normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   But normalcy may be fleeting for the near future. Five students
remained in critical condition on Monday, four of them with severe
burns, and reminders of the blaze dotted the 56-acre campus _ from
the blue-and-white memorial ribbons many teachers and students
pinned to their lapels to the cafeteria bulletin board that was
filled with personal tributes to the dead and injured.
</P>
<P>
   Although cleaning crews have spent the last few days trying to
erase evidence of the fire, the smell of smoke still hangs in the
hallways and the most heavily damaged parts of Boland Hall remain
closed, its students relocated to other dormitory rooms, nearby
college campuses and a local motel.
</P>
<P>
   Like many students, Ramone DeJesus said he had mixed feelings
about moving back into the the white brick building, which was
fully staffed with grief counselors, resident assistants and
priests on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I'm not sure what to do,'' he said. ``It's
tough to move in after what happened, but I'm going to give it a
week to see how it goes and then if I'm not happy or don't feel
good about it, then I will commute.''
</P>
<P>
   As they waited to enter, many students could not help but peer
up at the darkened windows of the third floor, their screens torn
out, a smudge of soot marking the facade. Out of view, on the other
side of the building, sat a pair of snow-covered mattresses that
panicked students had thrown to the ground, hoping they might break
their falls.
</P>
<P>
   The unease on campus Monday was heightened by a lack of new
information from investigators, who continued to interview Boland
Hall residents about what they might have seen or heard in the
building on the night of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Smith, a spokeswoman for the Essex County prosecutor,
Donald C. Campolo, who is heading the investigation, declined to
discuss the inquiry but said that neither arson nor accident had
been ruled out. For now, all that the investigators know is that
the fire began around 4:30 a.m. in a third-floor lounge and quickly
consumed three sofas, carpeting and ceiling tiles, producing thick
black black smoke that sent dozens to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the victims, Aaron Karol and John Giunta, were found
burned to death in the lounge, while another, Frank Caltabilota,
was found in his room, killed by the toxic smoke.
</P>
<P>
   All three men, just 18, were buried on Monday in separate
funerals in New Jersey. Hundreds of people gathered at each
ceremony, and the outpouring of grief was immeasurable. Seton
Hall's president, Robert Sheeran, attended all three funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time of immense loss,'' he said after arriving at
his third, that of Giunta.
</P>
<P>
   An aspiring public school teacher, Giunta was recalled as
generous and loyal at a funeral Mass at St. Francis Roman Catholic
Church in Vineland. The service, celebrated by a dozen priests and
the archbishop of Camden, was attended by three busloads of Seton
Hall students.
</P>
<P>
   Giunta's father, Phil, read a letter to his son, each line
beginning the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody wants to hold your head,'' he said. ``Somebody wants
to give you a hug. Somebody thinks you are great. Somebody
thousands of miles away is looking at one of your Web sites.'' As
tears overtook him, Giunta finished. ``Somebody will be crying when
they read this, and that somebody is me.''
</P>
<P>
   In West Long Branch, the sobs of mourners echoed through St.
Jerome Roman Catholic Church as the body of Caltabilota was carried
in by his friends. An honor student and accomplished athlete,
Caltabilota had hoped to study medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a hero to everyone you've ever known,'' his 15-year-old
brother, Thomas, said at the start of the service. ``You're a hero
to me. I love you. May you rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of grief was the same in Dunellen, where hundreds
gathered to bury Karol, a criminal justice major who talked about
working for the FBI. As his friends read poetry, former teammates
from the Watchung Hills Regional High School, all of them wearing
their black soccer jackets, cried and hugged one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learn from the loss of this young man how precious life is,''
said the Rev. John Morley, a Seton Hall priest. ``And it does not
come with guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service for all three men has been scheduled for
Tuesday at Seton Hall's gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they were attending the funerals or were simply too
traumatized to return, many of Boland Hall's residents did not rush
back to school when the dormitory's side doors opened at 2 p.m.
Monday. About two dozen students, many accompanied by their
parents, gathered in the thawing sun as a carillon tolled the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Some carried duffel bags, others fresh bedding and shopping bags
stuffed with junk food. Any sense of the ordinary was broken by the
sobering sight of an elderly priest who wandered through the crowd,
gently calling out: ``Counseling. Anyone need counseling?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
