<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTUIT-INTUIT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intuit Names GE Capital EVP As New Chief  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Intuit Inc. announced yesterday that it has named GE Capital
Executive Vice President Stephen M. Bennett as its new president
and chief executive.
<P>
   The Mountain View company, best known for its Quicken and
TurboTax software and Quicken.com Web-based financial services, has
been looking for a new CEO since September. Former CEO Bill Harris
resigned to pursue more entrepreneurial ventures and Intuit
Chairman Bill Campbell filled in as acting CEO until a permanent
replacement could be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredible opportunity to lead a Silicon Valley
company that will help shape the future of e-finance,'' said
Bennett. ``Intuit is well-positioned serving 5 million small
businesses and 12 million consumers and our challenge will be to
expand services and broaden our value proposition to get more
revenues per customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 45, will move to the Bay Area from Connecticut where he
was a member of the Office of the CEO at GE Capital, the financial
services subsidiary of General Electric Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With $330 billion in assets, GE Capital is the world leader in
private label credit cards, commercial equipment leasing and vendor
finance and accounts for 42 percent of General Electric's overall
profits.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent position, Bennett oversaw a portfolio of five
different companies whose more than 20,000 employees last year
generated $15 billion in annual volume.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, as president and CEO of GE Capital e-Business, he
pioneered the company's efforts to tap the Internet across GE
Capital's worldwide portfolio of businesses. He also launched GE's
small business Internet site which focuses on serving businesses
with from &LR; 20 to 500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted someone with service industry knowledge, who had led
large, complex organizations and with proven ability to produce
fast growth,'' said Campbell, 58. ``Steve is the ideal choice to
take Intuit to the multibillion-dollar level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
