<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-PACBELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pac Bell's Mailer Worries Some Consumers  &HT;     By Todd Wallack 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco resident Dennis Lewis said he was startled last week
when he received a warning from Pacific Bell in the mail:
<P>
   ``Do you have equipment connected to your telephone?'' the
notice asked. Fax machines, answering machines, alarms and modems,
the letter warned, ``may need to be adjusted'' so they will work
with the company's new digital switching equipment. It also said
features like speed dialing and call forwarding may need to be
reprogrammed.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned, Lewis called the toll-free number listed on the
notice and spoke to a customer representative who told him older
equipment might malfunction. But she couldn't tell how old was old,
or why there would be a problem. (A reporter received a similar
response when he called.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Lewis probably has nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell said it routinely sends out hundreds or thousands
of such notices when it upgrades old equipment in its switching
offices _ just in case something goes wrong. In reality, Pacific
Bell spokesman John Britton said he'd never heard of a case where a
residential customer has had a problem.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis called the mailing irresponsible. ``Why can't they
just say that problems are rare (in the letter)?''
</P>
<P>
   Britton, however, contended the wording was clear. ``It says MAY
need to be adjusted,'' he said. Britton said customers should only
contact the phone company if they experience a problem with their
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company has sent out more than 8 million notices
over the past six years, and only received a handful of complaints
about the mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was among as many as 60,000 Pac Bell customers in San
Francisco who recently received the notice because the company is
updating its equipment in a San Francisco central office next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said the California Public Utilities Commission requires
the mailings. ``We're playing by the rules,'' he said. (The PUC did
not return a call seeking comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Other telephone companies also send out similar notices because
of occasional glitches, said Nortel Networks, which built the new
Pac Bell equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, an alarm system might have trouble automatically
dialing a certain phone number. Or if someone has multiple lines,
voices might be too faint.
</P>
<P>
   But spokeswoman Joanne Latham said the problems are ``rare.''
And generally, she said, phone companies or customers can fix the
glitches with minor adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a phone company being cautious,'' said
Nortel spokeswoman Joanne Latham.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
