r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     01-24 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTHUR M. LOUIS/MONEYBAG 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Commission-Free Account a Good Deal 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: American Express is advertising a commission-free brokerage
account for customers with at least $100,000 in assets. What's the
catch?
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: I talked to an American Express spokesman about this. There
are some catches, but not enough to bother most prospective
customers.
</P>
<P>
   One catch is that you aren't allowed to day-trade for free. If
you buy a stock and sell it on the same day, you will be charged a
$14.95 commission on the sale, says spokesman Dave Kanihan.
However, you won't pay a commission on the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the commission-free provision applies only to
online transactions, and is limited to purchases and sales of
stocks. There will be commissions if you buy or sell other types of
securities.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like a terrific deal if you have a computer and don't
happen to be a day-trader. And even some day-traders might not mind
paying $14.95 for a round-trip trade, although it is possible to do
somewhat better at a few other brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think that American Express has gone soft, Kanihan
concedes that the company does have a financial motive here. It
wants you to patronize its ``field force of financial advisers, who
do planning and consulting for clients.'' Those guys charge fees,
and the commission-free brokerage account serves as a loss leader
to bring you into their orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to hook up with the advisers. You can simply
buy and sell stocks without paying commissions, and there won't be
any hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Well ... maybe a few hard feelings, but don't let that stop you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: I am a software engineer. I worked beyond regular office
hours many times last year, but the company I work for does not
recognize overtime, so I have not received any overtime
compensation. I would like to know whether I am eligible to receive
overtime pay under California law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: Your question can't be answered from the limited information
you have supplied, says Dean Fryer, a spokesman for the state
Department of Industrial Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Although most California workers are entitled to extra pay for
overtime, he observes, there are exceptions for managers and
supervisors, employees in the ``licensed professions'' _ such as
lawyers _ and others who have ``a lot of independence in their
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Mead, an official of the Software Engineering Institute in
Pittsburgh, Pa., says that U.S. software engineers generally are
not entitled to overtime pay. However, she says, exceptions
sometimes are made for people in entry-level positions.
</P>
<P>
   People who aren't getting overtime pay but think they might be
entitled to it can apply for an official ruling from the office of
the state labor commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each case has to be looked at on an individual basis, taking
into account the work and responsibilities of the employee,'' Fryer
says.
</P>
<P>
   You can obtain a claim form by telephoning the department's San
Francisco district office at 415-557-7878. Or, you can visit the
office at 455 Golden Gate Ave., 8th floor. There also are Bay Area
branch offices in San Jose, at 100 Paseo de San Antonio, Room 120,
and Santa Rosa, at 50 D St., Suite 360.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  Q: My wife and I live in Pinole, where last year the voters
approved a measure to help save our police force. The money is
collected as a tax on everyone's gas, electric and telephone bills.
Can this be claimed as a deduction on our income-tax form?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: No, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller.
</P>
<P>
   If it qualified as a property tax, it would be deductible. But
this is a utility tax, and therefore not deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the tax was not levied solely to shore up the
police department. You probably got that impression from campaign
signs that were posted before the ballot was taken. This actually
was an attempt to avert a general cutback in municipal services.
The city's political leaders expect the tax to add $1.1 million
annually to the general fund.
</P>
<P>
   Pinole isn't the only California municipality to impose a
utility tax. Many others _ perhaps most _ also have them. You
non-Pinoleans out there might want to take a close look at the
itemized charges on your next utility bills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
