<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HOUSE_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 Dream Houses Online  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
When their landlord told Sidney and Arlene Lerner last summer that
he wouldn't renew their Foster City apartment lease, the couple
decided that the time had come to buy a house.
<P>
   Time was limited, because the landlord gave them only a month's
notice. Unable to afford a house in Foster City, they booted up
their computer and began exploring several Internet Web sites that
list homes for sale throughout the Bay Area and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   They entered parameters into the search engines, specifying four
bedrooms, three bathrooms, a swimming pool and a price in the
vicinity of $200,000. They were directed to 10 homes in the
Vacaville area.
</P>
<P>
   They hooked up with an agent in Vacaville, and within a day made
a successful offer on a $230,000 house that includes not only a
pool, but also a Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of scenario is being played out again and again these
days. When it comes to home buying, computers are living up to
their reputation as time-savers.
</P>
<P>
   Gone _ or going _ are the days when prospective home buyers
spent a long succession of weekends chugging from house to house in
their agent's BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The California Association of Realtors found in a survey that 35
percent of the people who bought homes in the state during the
third quarter of last year used the Internet to explore their
options. That was up from only 26 percent at the beginning of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the tech-savvy Bay Area, the percentage probably is much
higher. Brian Santilena, a broker with Prudential California Realty
in the Oakland/Montclair office, says that about 80 percent of his
clients do preliminary research on the Internet to narrow their
choices.
</P>
<P>
   He observes: ``It is very common that someone calls and says `I
saw a property on the Net and want more information on it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Internet home-buying sites were practically nonexistent five
years ago, but now there are many dozens of them. Among those with
the biggest followings are www.homeadvisor.com, www.cyberhomes.com,
www.realestate.yahoo.com, www.iown.com and www.homes.com.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many real-estate firms _ and even many individual
agents _ have their own Web sites. Some choice examples include
www.stewarttitle.com, www.mcguie.com, www.alainpinel.com,
www.coldwellbanker.com, www.century21.com, www.rondavis.com and
www.ebayrealtor.com.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely used home-buying site of all, according to the
Media Metrix data-gathering service, is www.realtor.com, sponsored
by the National Association of Realtors. It lists 1.3 million homes
being offered through all the local Multiple Listing Services.
</P>
<P>
   But no site is all-inclusive: Many of them list homes that can't
be found on other sites.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some sites offer bonus features, such as virtual
tours of a home's interior, or useful social and economic
statistics about the community in which the home is located.
Prospective home buyers would do well to rummage through a lot of
sites, rather than relying on any particular one.
</P>
<P>
   While the Internet has made buyers less dependent on agents, it
certainly hasn't eliminated the agent's function.
</P>
<P>
   Through your computer, you can find practically every house
currently for sale. But almost invariably, you will be steered to
an agent, whose aid you will need if you want to tour the premises
and present an offer.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception to that rule is if you find the house of your
dreams on a Web site _ such as www.owners.com _ that lists homes
for sale directly by the owners. If you do, you probably can get
the house at a bargain, because the seller won't have to factor a
broker's commission into the price.
</P>
<P>
   Kojo Yeboah, a software engineer with Cisco Systems, used the
Owners.com site last fall to find a four-bedroom home in San Carlos
Hills. He previously had cruised the area with an agent, without
success.
</P>
<P>
   Yeboah paid about $600,000, which he figures was at least
$50,000 less than he would have paid if an agent was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the selection of homes on owners-only sites is
sparse. Fewer than 5 percent of all home sales are transacted
without an agent.
</P>
<P>
   Often you will need an agent just to learn the street address of
a house you find on the Internet. That crucial piece of information
is omitted from many, if not most, houses listed on home-buying Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the listings are provided by the agents, many of
whom are reluctant to give buyers the opportunity to deal directly
with sellers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, of course, many sellers don't want to be pestered.
</P>
<P>
   Internet home-buying can have other shortcomings as well.
</P>
<P>
   If you are searching during a particularly hot seller's market _
such as the one the Bay Area experienced a year or so ago _
Internet listings can be rendered nearly useless.
</P>
<P>
   In such a market, by the time you see a house on the Internet,
it very likely will have been sold. Houses that remain unsold for
any length of time are apt to be dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But even doggy houses have their day.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Chong, chief executive of a startup company called
Virtual Boardwalk, which provides technology services to
conventions, says she used the Internet to find a home with ``no
curb appeal'' in the Richmond District of San Francisco in late
1998, ``during the height of the bidding wars.'`
</P>
<P>
   It had five bedrooms and was priced at less than $500,000, but
it had been passed up by other buyers because it needed a paint job
and plumbing repairs and was ``one of the ugliest houses I saw.''
But it was structurally sound, and had a nice view of the Marin
Headlands.
</P>
<P>
   Some home buyers complain that even in less-inflamed markets,
the listings they find on the Internet often turn out to be
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Data about home listings must pass from real estate agents to
the Web sites to the technical people who actually enter the data.
So, listing delays are inevitable, both arriving and leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Houses sometimes remain pictured on a Web site, in all their
multicolor glory, long after they have been taken off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Villaflor, a paralegal, and her husband, Leonard, an
accountant, who live in a rented apartment in San Bruno, discovered
this last November when they began looking for houses in San Mateo
and Foster City.
</P>
<P>
   They drew up a list of 15 houses on the Internet that looked
promising, and submitted it to an agent. The agent reported back
that all the houses had been either sold or pulled off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Villaflor says that one of the Web sites that was partly
out of date was the NAR's vaunted www.realtor.com.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this, an NAR spokeswoman referred the matter to
Homestore.com, a publicly held company in Thousand Oaks, which
manages the Realtor.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Fulton, a spokeswoman for Homestore.com, says that
complaints about outdated material are ``not something we hear very
frequently.'' She says that about 1 million of the 1.3 million
Realtor.com listings are updated daily. The rest, she says, are
updated weekly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
