<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAUCUSES-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      01-24 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAUCUSES-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN IOWA INDUSTRIAL TOWN, IT'S A SWEEP FOR GORE AND BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Iowa _ The Democratic caucus meeting for Ward 2,
Precinct 3 in this northeastern Iowa city had been going on for 30
minutes Monday, and already it was not a good night for Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the caucus on one side of the West High School
cafeteria were asked to divide into groups _ all those for Vice
President Al Gore at one set of long lunch tables, all those for
Bradley at the other. Gore has 29 Iowans in his corner while
Bradley had eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blue-collar precinct,'' sniffed Sharon Hyke, a
supporter of Bradley, a former senator from New Jersey. ``That's
why its for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Organized labor, which supports Gore, turned out
the votes in a city where 30 percent of registered Democrats are
union members.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bitter irony for Hyke. Her father lost his job when the
Rath Co. pork production plant went belly up in 1984. He lost his
health insurance and finished out his career as a minimum-wage
kitchen worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had it comfortable,'' said Hyke, 34. ``Bill Bradley
knows that. He understands everyone in America doesn't have it
cushy; that the economy's not great for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, as Gore won the predicted victory across Iowa, so did he
score big here in this union town.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ward 2, Precinct 4 meeting on the other side of the
cafeteria, Gore won 44 votes to Bradley's 14. John Carson, Gore's
24-year-old paid organizer here, paced the halls of cavernous West
High nervously at first, but relaxed and smiled as the meetings
broke up.
</P>
<P>
   Who were these Gore people? Gore's precinct captain in 2-3, as
the precinct is known in political parlance, was Kevin Powers, the
local president of the letter carriers' union.
</P>
<P>
   But the votes were coming from people like Carla Madson, a home
economics teacher in nearby Hudson, who sat quietly at the Gore
table while her daughter, Marissa, 7, drew on paper with
felt-tipped pens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore supports education and its important for classes to be
small and teachers respected,'' Madson said. ``That's the root of a
lot of problems we have with children. They're disruptive because
they don't get the attention they need and they're too crammed
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, down the hall in the student center, the Republicans
of Ward 2, Precinct 4 were giving Texas Gov. George W. Bush part of
his big night in Iowa. When the paper ballots were counted just
after 7:30 p.m., Bush had 39 votes; publisher Steve Forbes 9;
conservative activist Gary Bauer 9; radio commentator Alan Keyes 8;
Arizona Sen. John McCain, 3; and Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of losing elections to the liberals,'' said James
Kirkpatrick, 39, a pension administrator for Principal Financial
Group. ``We need George W. Bush to broaden the base of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Denny Nordorft, a 50-year-old dealer in classic
rock records challenged Kirkpatrick, asking him why Bush was such a
great ``Democratic'' governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After some back and forth, Nordorft sat down without speaking up
for his candidate, Keyes, a State Department official in the Reagan
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out here tonight because this could be the end of the
Republican Party,'' Nordorft said. ``This country's on a downhill
slide. And Alan Keyes represents what this country needs: A return
to basic values.''
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses at West High School mirrored the region's political
economy.
</P>
<P>
   This area's economic mix of manufacturing and service industries
has yielded a fairly even division in political strength. Black
Hawk County, where Waterloo is located, has 23,586 registered
Democrats and 20,372 registered Republicans. With such an even
divide, the caucuses at West High represent a broad cross-section
of all the hopes and anxieties of voting Iowans.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa caucuses involve a process in which each party holds
precinct-by-precinct meetings for the purpose of electing a
presidential nominee. The caucus votes are several steps removed
from the actual delegate-selection process in the state, but they
have symbolic value as the first voting exercise in the 2000
presidential election. New Hampshire holds the nation's first
primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Des Moines Register poll published last weekend put Gore ahead
with 56 percent and Bradley trailing with 28 percent. On the
Republican side, Bush led with 43 percent against his closest
competitor, Forbes, with 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bigger win for Al Gore than anyone else because he
is no longer the defender of the Clinton administration,'' said
Dave Nagle, a Democrat who served as the area's congressman from
1987 to 1993 and now practices law here. ``He's now the next leader
of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Carson, who headed Gore's operation in Waterloo, worked with
organizers from the AFL-CIO and the American Federation of State,
County and Municipal Employees. They blanketed the area with phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign organized rides for supporters and arranged to
bus residents in the predominantly African-American east side to
caucus sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's backers conceded there was little there could do
against such an overwhelming organization.
</P>
<P>
   About 160 miles northeast of the capital Des Moines, Waterloo
developed as an ``industrial railroad suburb of Chicago,''
according to Allen Brierly, a political scientist at the University
of Northern Iowa in nearby Cedar Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Waterloo is where Iowa's farm and manufacturing economies become
united. Its five Deere and Co. plants employ just under 5,000 in
the production of tractors. The sprawling IBP Co. outside of town
employs 2,200 in one of the world's largest pork production plants.
</P>
<P>
   When Iowa's farm economy went into a tailspin in the 1980s,
Waterloo looked deep into an economic abyss. The huge Rath Co. pork
plant, which at its prime employed 8,000, closed in 1984, and Deere
laid off thousands of workers. Unemployment went as high as 20
percent, the highest in the nation for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   The sting was on par with the Great Depression of the 1930s,
according to Brierly. No permits for new housing construction were
issued between 1982 and 1986, he said. Waterloo's population sank
from 90,000 to 60,000 as young people sought jobs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the economy bounced back in the 1990s as factories retooled
and an array of service industries moved in giving jobs to an eager
and anxious work force. The growth of the service industries such
as Principal Financial Group, a pension fund manager, came at time
when manufacturing was slimming down its labor force.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, with unemployment in the region at 2.5 percent,
the IBP plant had to recruit workers from Bosnia and Mexico to keep
its three shifts fully staffed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
