<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5353 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-BAXTER-COX     01-24 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-BAXTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates take different lessons from Iowa, to New Hampshire
 &HT;    (EDS: CQ ``today'' in second graf as Tuesday.)
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ The helium had not seeped from the last party
balloon in Des Moines when the descent of the survivors on New
Hampshire began.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, sorely needing to make up for lost
time after a disappointing showing in Iowa, was due to land here at
1:45 a.m. today. Texas Gov. George Bush, the easy winner Monday but
facing a tougher test here, was due to land less than an hour
later. Arizona Sen. John McCain, sticking to his strategy, was here
already.
</P>
<P>
   The rest _ with the likely exception of Sen. Orrin Hatch, who
may have had enough _ will not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   From a reporter's viewpoint, the frenzied week of campaigning
leading up to the New Hampshire primary will be a more satisfying
exercise. The outcome in both parties is in doubt here, and the
contest _ pretty much like primary elections anywhere _ is much
easier to understand than the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But in the long run _ which in this crazed gallop of a
nominating process only means a few weeks from now _ it is more
likely to be the results from Iowa that tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   The solid wins that Bush and Vice President Al Gore put together
in Iowa followed a formula both frontrunners will be returning to,
as soon as the New Hampshire spree comes to an end. In both cases
it consists of tons of establishment support, undergirding the
desire of voters in both parties to go with a proven commodity.
</P>
<P>
   The voters in New Hampshire are a more rambunctious lot, and
they aren't likely to take their cue from the caucus results. But
Iowa still may have a large impact on what happens here next week.
</P>
<P>
   There's bound to be a lot of talk this week about whether
Bradley should have done as McCain did and passed on Iowa. In a
two-man race, it would have been tougher to ignore an early state,
but by committing so much money and time on a losing effort,
Bradley returns to New Hampshire in weaker condition than he left
it a short time ago.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be noted that McCain paid a price for skipping
Iowa. He spotted Bush a victory when he can't afford to give up
many. There was talk McCain would finish third without even trying
_ but he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone surpassed expectations on caucus night it was Steve
Forbes, who got more than 20 percent of the Republican caucus vote.
That's likely to encourage Forbes to pour more resources into New
Hampshire, where he's been gaining strength.
</P>
<P>
   That could put more pressure on Bush. But in a perverse way it
could also make the going tougher for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   The two challengers draw their votes from different parts of the
Republican Party. But if Forbes ups his margin here, the overall
outcome will be more diluted. So even if McCain does hand Bush a
defeat in New Hampshire next week, it's less likely to be the
clear-cut win he needs to catapult into the big-state primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes' third-place finish in the Republican caucuses may be
due in part to the money he poured into advertising in the last few
days of the campaign, but it deserves some examination. It would
appear Keyes fired up religious conservatives more than his rival
Gary Bauer, and he probably also benefited from the experience of
running for president four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What the two-three-four finish of Forbes, Keyes and Bauer seems
to say is that religious conservatives still play a dominant role
among the Republican hard-core.
</P>
<P>
   Religious conservatives are not expected to be in as prominent a
role when the campaign swings into a national focus. But never
discount the resolve of people willing brave the Iowa cold to vote
for candidates they know aren't going to finish first. They may
have more to say about this election than has been generally
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
