<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-2TA     01-24 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE MODELS DO THEIR TURNS, PUBLICISTS DO THEIR SPINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A designer whose career hangs in limbo requests a
meeting with a journalist in the hope of receiving more
``personal'' consideration. A press agent for a French house
invites reporters to preview its collection, so the designer can
explain his ideas; and a few days later their reviews are cozily
full of those very ideas. In Milan, still another publicist reacts
to a bad review by primly scolding the writer for not attending a
preview, where she would have ``understood'' the designer's finer
points.
</P>
<P>
   All these are nothing more than crude attempts to spin a story _
something political columnists and Hollywood reporters face
everyday, but with this difference: the fashion spin doctors are
better dressed and they can say ``chic'' without sounding like
Farmer Brown going out to inspect the henhouse.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, an undertaking as superficial and already
guaranteed of a certain amount of breathlessness as a fashion show
(``Darling, those  &UR; knits &LR;  ... '') would hardly seem to require
spin. Every season, designers trot out their latest clothes, and if
it is a big show, 1,500 editors and writers scrutinize them,
eventually turning out thousands of pages and columns of fashion
news. The process itself is not very objective, nor does it
encourage editorial independence, since even the most flagrantly
banal designer knows he will get some coverage in the magazines if
he is a big advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is trickier for writers with newspapers and
serious magazines, although some of their attempts to outfox the
hounds and go around the process are practically legend. John
Fairchild, the former publisher of Women's Wear Daily, once put a
man with a telescope and a sketchpad up in a room opposite
Balenciaga's studio, so the paper could get the scoop on the
master's collection. Eugenia Sheppard of The New York Herald
Tribune was known to tomahawk many a tender ego, and Kennedy
Fraser, following the acerbic Lois Long at The New Yorker, coolly
addressed a general suspicion about fashion journalists when she
wrote, ``Haute couture is a degenerate institution propped up by a
sycophantic press.''
</P>
<P>
   There are signs now of greater independence, with journalists
scrutinizing the shows much as entertainment or cultural critics
would. Yet, as designers reach wildly for ideas, as the shows
themselves become forms of theater and the houses see the unlimited
potential for exploiting brands through new media, the need for
spin control becomes greater.
</P>
<P>
   One has only to look at the recent round of men's shows in Milan
and the haute couture collections in Paris to see how this works _
and more to the point, how a well-placed word or slick reference
can influence opinion and what mere mortals inevitably read in the
fashion columns.
</P>
<P>
   At her men's wear show on Jan. 8, Donatella Versace told
reporters the clothes were inspired by the raw style in ``Fight
Club,'' the recent Brad Pitt movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Donatella knew what she was talking about, to be
honest,'' said Tim Blanks, who, as the host for the cable
television show ``Fashion File,'' is a regular backstage presence.
And indeed, the behind-the-scenes talk among design assistants at
the Versace show was that the inspiration had been the Mine Shaft,
the notorious New York gay sex club _ hardly the sort of image a
top _ even a racy _ Milanese fashion house wants to put across.
</P>
<P>
   But a Brad Pitt movie was. And even though a couple of critics
took the idea apart, the ``Fight Club'' reference became the
dominant sound bite of the shows. You could tell, by the following
week in the London papers, that some writers didn't have a clue
what the movie was about. They just wanted to be on the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one can argue that such information is useful, even
interesting. In the old days, back in the hushed era of Balenciaga
and Mme. Gres, designers seldom spoke to the press, and they
certainly never had to confront a barrage of those television
cameras that make clever repartee essential. But successful
designers and sharp-eyed publicists know that catchy phrases are
being passed out along with the facts.
</P>
<P>
   A similar situation occurred last week when Christian Dior
invited a handful of senior writers, one by one, to preview John
Galliano's spring haute couture collection a few days before the
show. The practice of previewing collections is not new; it largely
serves magazine editors who want a heads-up so they can plan
photography sessions. It also serves the promotional interests of a
fashion house, which can use the informality of a preview to get
across obscure or controversial themes, like those in Galliano's
tramp show, which caused a sensation in the French press.
</P>
<P>
   To a lesser extent, previews are also an undisguised attempt by
a house to establish, as a Dior press agent once told me, ``a more
personal contact'' with a journalist, especially one who has been
critical. Think of it as an attempt to diffuse a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   But this can also backfire. Last September, Calvin Klein invited
me to preview his spring line, which was based in part, he said, on
the nerdy style of London teen-agers _ skinny belts and so on. But
as he spoke, my attention was drawn to an elegant portrait of Nicky
de Gunzburg, the famous Vogue editor, who had been Klein's mentor.
I couldn't help wondering why he'd look to London teen-agers when
he had his own remarkable history and style to drawn upon. It was
just spin.
</P>
<P>
   As it was at Dior. Galliano had compiled books of pertinent
photographs, including some by Diane Arbus, and other pictures and
drawings that were mounted on the walls of the Dior studio in a
collage of the down-and-out inspiration. The images, and the
clothes themselves were intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days after the show, it was hard not to feel that the
journalists who duly reported Galliano's themes without bothering
to analyze them had, in effect, become his accomplices. They were
making the outrageous and the weird seem utterly acceptable, even
important, by peppering their reviews with those spoon-fed arty
references to tramp balls and Egon Schiele as though they had just
sprung to mind.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Most designers don't need to explain their collections. They are
what they are, and anyone looking at, say, Jean Paul Gaultier's
spring couture show would know, from the cut of the cloth to the
twist of the turbans, that it is about modern French chic.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, whether its methods are right or wrong, Dior is ahead of
the game. Christian Dior himself once said that he didn't care what
critics wrote as long as his clothes made the front page. Bernard
Arnault, the chairman of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, which
owns Dior, has pushed that further. The last thing he wants for
Dior's brand image is bourgeois-looking clothes. And it's
interesting that of all the shows last week, the one that looks the
best on television _ that sustains interest beyond mundane matters
of taste and beauty _ is Dior's. By contrast, even Gaultier's
ineffable chic looks strangely inert.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Arnault, dressed in weekend jeans, was up in
Dior's showroom, where members of the sales staff were having their
first look at Galliano's early-fall collection, which accounts for
70 percent of Dior's ready-to-wear sales. The clothes incorporate
the hobo themes, but in sanitized ready-to-wear versions.
</P>
<P>
   When Galliano was over to the side talking to someone, Arnault
made a comment that said a great deal about himself and the fashion
business. He said of the controversy surrounding Galliano's couture
collection, ``People are not smart enough to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the public may not understand the economics of
couture _ how, in effect, the spin has become the story,
transforming headlines into money-making purses with jangling Dior
logos. But neither are people so gullible as to believe everything
they hear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
