<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER MAJOR STEP FOR CAPRIATI: SEMIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE _ Beyond burnout? Burst from the bonds of
embarrassment, uncertainty, even ridicule?
</P>
<P>
   Can this be Jennifer Capriati emerging from her very own horror
show to rub strong shoulders again with the elite on that narrow
precipice, the semifinals of a major tennis championship, the
Australian Open? Four survive at Melbourne Park, and Capriati _ a
survivor of too much bad press, over-hype and under-care,
self-doubt and drug-store psychiatry from all directions _ is among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years have passed since her last visit to a major semi:
the US Open of 1991, when she slugged it out mercilessly with
another teen-ager, the champ-to-be Monica Seles, and came within 2
points of winning.
</P>
<P>
   After flailing plucky Japanese Ai Sugiyama, 6-0, 6-2, the
unseeded Capriati beamed as she said, ``Let's see, I've been in the
semis of the French (1990), Wimbledon, and the US (1991) as a kid.
Now the Australian at 23. That's OK, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked her if she was pinching herself at this unlikely
stroke of good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' she said. ``There's still a way to go. The pinch can
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The punch couldn't. She seemed the Jennerator of almost
forgotten distinction in hammering her groundies past No. 23-ranked
Sugiyama after digging out of a break point in the opening game
resoundingly with an overhead smash. There was no holding Capriati
after that, although the game Sugiyama ran ceaselessly in trying.
Sugiyama had won their last two meetings, and had knocked off an
ex-champ, No. 5 Mary Pierce, in the fourth round, but her fourth
clash with Capriati was a Tuesday morning nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati begged reporters at last year's US Open to quit
bringing up her past, then melted away in tears. A vain, probably
foolish cry for relief. It would be just as easy for Red Sox
chroniclers and loyalists to stop recalling the Curse of the
Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   Hers was the curse of growing up in public too early. It started
from the moment her father, Stefano Capriati, turned her
professional in the carnival atmosphere of a tour tourney at Boca
Raton, Fla., a decade ago. She was not yet 14, but her parents,
agents, and the Women's Tennis Association led her on board a
roller coaster that took the inevitable downward rush when she
rebelled against it all in 1993, and was caught up in youthful
mistakes a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The joy was gone. It appears to have returned, not just the
restoration of a winning athlete, but a young woman, composed and
comfortable with herself. She's creating a new present to dim the
past she flees (although it wasn't as bad or extraordinary as the
headlines screeched). Having written numerous painful
Capriati-crash pieces centering on teen-age trauma, I'm delighted
to go in another direction.
</P>
<P>
   She had tried several comebacks that didn't stick. Then, last
March, she took a very right turn by hiring Harold Solomon as her
coach. The first contact was made by her father, but Solomon (``I
didn't believe Jennifer genuinely meant it'') told him, no way
unless he heard from Jennifer herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She convinced me over the phone and has been convincing me
ever since that she was sincere about working,'' said Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   It's a three-pronged effort at a renaissance: Capriati plus
Solomon plus physical trainer Karen Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karen has worked me like you wouldn't believe,'' said
Capriati. ``Really hard. I thought I worked at tennis when I was a
kid, but it came pretty easily at 15. This is really work. But
Karen does it in a way that it's fun, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said cautiously, ``She's not the player she was at 15 or
16. Yet. But she's moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   And, undeniably, moving better on court, maturing in her tennis
approach, thinking out points instead of just thumping powerfully,
letting the shots fall where they may.
</P>
</TEXT>
