<HEADER>
A5358 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-IOWA-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      01-24 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIUMPH OF THE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ The breeze that blew across the great American
prairie Monday night was cool but moderate.
</P>
<P>
   With the eyes of the nation monitoring the political climate of
Iowa, caucus-goers in both major parties sent an unmistakable
message. From the middle of the country came a firm endorsement of
the middle of the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   In towns and crossroads and urban centers from the Missouri
River in the west to the Mississippi in the east _ from Ackley to
Zwingle, communities that comprise not only the heartland but the
heart of the heartland _ the verdict was clear and in its way
unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of the center is not an unusual American political
phenomenon, to be sure. But the public usually works its way back
to the center in the autumn after probing the far extremes in the
winter and spring, and for that reason the twin victories of Vice
President Al Gore in the Democratic caucuses and of Texas Governor
George W. Bush in the Republican caucuses send an important message
to the two coasts and the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The voices of this year's Iowa caucuses, held in far-flung
community centers and church basements and coffee shops, were the
voices of contentment.
</P>
<P>
   Now the race moves to New Hampshire, the graveyard of political
assumptions and the charnel house of frontrunners, with a reminder
that the Monday night victories of Bush and Gore _ baby-boomers
from different dynasties and possessed of different temperaments _
are only a tentative signal. They are indicative of the public _
but not binding on the public.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, and with remarkable speed, as campaign planes took
off from Des Moines throughout the evening, the focus already has
shifted from the midwest to the northeast, and a week from today
the voters of New Hampshire will have their say and sway.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of the candidates, the campaign retinues, the
correspondents and the commentators from Iowa to New Hampshire is a
symbol of the beginning of the next scene in America's greatest
civic drama. In the next week the certainties of the plains can
swiftly become the uncertainties of the mountains, the surefooted
can stumble and the verities of this morning can be set aside with
ease, sometimes with glee.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two frontrunners have been under siege in New
Hampshire, battered by two candidates whose performances Monday
night in Iowa were disappointing. Senator John McCain of Arizona
barely competed in Iowa but hoped for a stealthy insurgency in
Republican caucuses; it never materialized. Former Senator Bill
Bradley of New Jersey conducted a spirited campaign here and had
counted on a surprisingly strong showing; that didn't occur,
either.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican race, Bush is also now facing a more serious
challenge from Steve Forbes, who now can legitimately claim to be
the repository of the hopes of conservatives who have not embraced
the Texas governor. That position is buttressed by the endorsement
of the Manchester Union Leader, a strong voice of conservative
sentiment in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   However, the major beneficiary of the Forbes surge could be
McCain, who appears best positioned to exploit any weakness that
may emerge in Bush.
</P>
<P>
   All the challengers now are conducting underdog campaigns in an
atmosphere far different from the one that prevailed only hours
ago. The new presidential race is a lot like the old presidential
race except for one important change. The insurgents' targets have
actual public victories to their credit and some measure of what
Governor Bush's father, himself an insurgent Iowa victor in 1980,
described as the ``big mo,'' or momentum.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the Republican Party, publisher Forbes' strong showing
makes him a bigger factor in New Hampshire than he was considered
only hours ago.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of presidential race, however, isn't as streamlined as
it suddenly seems.
</P>
<P>
   The two establishment candidates won big victories in a state
which is finding prosperity in new ventures but suffering
widespread economic distress in the old, particularly in the farm
regions that are the heart of the state's heritage. Now those two
establishment candidates face insurgencies in a state that is
ablaze with economic growth and abloom with economic contentment.
</P>
<P>
   So while Iowa, with key sectors of its economy and way of life
under attack, chose the safe candidates and turned away from the
populists, New Hampshire is giving a close look to the populists
and is resisting the safe candidates.
</P>
<P>
   And yet a measure of the contentment that prevails in the
country is that the four figures at the top of the heap _ the safe
and the populist both _ are, in truth, figures of the center
themselves. One of the insurgents is a third-generation Navy man in
a country where the military has never been an outsider political
force. The other is a graduate of one of the Ivy League's Big
Three, a Rhodes Scholar and a professional athlete. Neither
represents a threat to the public order _ though both say they
would change the game forever for big money campaign contributors
and the candidates who depend on them.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth figure in the campaign, Forbes, is himself a
multi-millionaire publisher and a sturdy pillar of the conservative
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are so firmly planted in the middle that the
insurgents _ one a Democrat, the other a Republican _ are
effectively competing in next week's primary in part against each
other. The prize: independent voters who pride themselves on their
position in the center, and their willingness to move from one
party to the other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
