<HEADLINE>
AT NEARLY $22 BILLION, GATES FOUNDATION NOW WORLD'S BIGGEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Five short months ago, the Bill and Melinda Gates
Foundation was merely the wealthiest philanthropy in the country.
Now, it's the biggest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation confirmed Monday that a $5 billion contribution
from the Microsoft founder and his wife boosted the foundation's
assets to $21.8 billion. That pushed it ahead of the Wellcome Trust
in Britain, which has assets worth about $21.4 billion in U.S.
dollars, according to The Chronicle of Philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The Gates Foundation's ranking as the leading philanthropy in
the world gives them an extra measure of status as the
trend-setters in charitable giving, said Stacy Palmer, editor of
The Chronicle of Philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more in the symbolism,'' said Palmer, whose Washington,
D.C.-based publication reports on nonprofit organizations. ``It
just makes them sort of more important.''
</P>
<P>
   To those at the Gates Foundation as well, the new ranking is
viewed as largely symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the size is less important to us than the
tremendous responsibility that comes with using the resources in an
effective way,'' said Trevor Neilson, communications director for
the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary value of the philanthropy has grown rapidly in the
past year. The Gateses poured $15.1 billion in assets into the
family's philanthropic entities last year. In August, the family
consolidated two foundations into a single philanthropic powerhouse
worth $17.1 billion at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal tax laws, the foundation is required to give away
at least 5 percent of its assets each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bill (and) Melinda Gates Foundation will continue to focus
on helping to improve people's lives primarily through health and
learning,'' foundation co-chair Patty Stonesifer said in a
statement. ``Particular attention will go towards accelerating the
development and distribution of life-saving vaccines.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is staffed by about 120 people, the bulk of them
dedicated to the foundation's project to wire all of the nation's
public libraries. To manage the exponential growth, the Gates
Foundation has relied largely on outside experts for advice and
established organizations for implementation of their
multi-billion-dollar giving, Neilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of trying to build massive amounts of expertise
in-house, we rely on other organizations to come to us with
proposals and help us implement programs,'' Neilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion Gates Millennium Scholars Program, for example,
is being administered largely by the United Negro College Fund. The
scholarships, announced in September, are designed to increase the
number of minority students completing undergraduate and graduate
degree.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the foundation gave $750 million to establish The
Global Fund for Children's Vaccines, which will pay for vaccines
and immunization programs in developing countries and support
research into new vaccines and therapies. The fund will be guided
by a consortium led by the World Health Organization, UNICEF and
the World Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
