<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-KEYES-BOS &LR;      01-24 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-KEYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWANS ARE SYMPATHETIC TO CONSERVATIVE MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   URBANDALE, Iowa _ The message was met with generous applause,
even if the caucus votes had not gone to the messenger.
</P>
<P>
   At St. James Lutheran Church, Jack Sullivan put his hands
together hard for Alan Keyes, the radio talk-show host who aspires
to be the Republican presidential nominee. But he cast his ballot
for George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's articulate and he has a lot of good things to say,'' said
Sullivan, 37, a building contractor. ``I just don't think he has
the broad base to go to the next level, unfortunately. As bad as it
sounds, the No. 1 goal for me is to get someone elected tonight who
I think can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day and and into the early evening, the Keyes
campaign stuck to its one hard and fast rule: No predictions on the
balloting. First place or third place in Iowa, campaign workers and
supporters said again and again, the conservative Keyes is in the
race for the long run.
</P>
<P>
   As Anne Breiling, the candidate's deputy chief of staff, put it,
``As the saying goes, work like it depends on you. Pray like it
depends on God.''
</P>
<P>
   God and the moral fiber of America were major themes of the
Keyes campaign as he criss-crossed the state, themes that resonated
with voters here and appeared to give him a boost in recent days.
Monday night, Keyes registered in the mid-double digits _ better
than many had expected but still not enough for the second-place
showing ahead of Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, in part, blamed Keyes' third-place finish out of a
GOP field of six on what they called the media's refusal to
highlight his conservative positions, which include opposition to
abortion and the federal income tax. In Iowa, his campaign has a
list of 4,000 volunteers to draw on, said John Block, an advance
man for the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I like about him? Everything,'' said Tom Hoefling, who
took a leave of absence from his job as political director for the
Iowa Conservative Coalition five weeks ago to become a volunteer
field organizer for Keyes. ``The way he speaks from his heart
appeals to everyone. People who hear him become converts. We've
just got to make sure more people get a chance to hear him.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes spent much of Monday being heard on Iowa radio, starting
the morning at a station that typically plays heavy metal music and
then moving on to a program hosted by someone even more
conservative than he is. He used his few minutes at the church,
where both Bush and Forbes had placards prominently displayed and
he had none, to stress the problems confronting the country and
that only Republicans can solve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have an economic crisis; we do not have an
international crisis,'' Keyes said. ``We must address the moral
crisis of our country. . . . If it is to be saved, Republicans must
save it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' comments won a standing ovation from the audience, which
tended toward the older side. Back at the Holiday Inn, where Keyes
supporters were gathering in a modest banquet room decorated with
small bunches of balloons, the enthusiasm was just starting to grow
mid-evening, although it was unlikely to top a Sunday night event
that drew 1,000 people and had Keyes falling backward into a
``mosh'' pit of young supporters in order to win a dare.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of campaign,'' Block said. ``Alan Keyes often
gets pegged as a stiff, right-wing guy. Constitutionally and
morally he's right on every issue. But he's also a fun guy, and
people are just starting to see who he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2228EST &QL; 
