<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-BUSH-COX     01-24 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush thankful for victory, but unwilling to speculate on New
Hampshire
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ George W. Bush said he was ``grateful'' for a
``solid victory'' in the Iowa caucuses Monday night, but he
resisted predictions of how it would affect his next contest in New
Hampshire, where he was scheduled to head late Monday night in time
for a 2:30 a.m. rally at the Manchester, N.H., airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``That remains to be seen,'' he said when asked if the Iowa
results would help him next week. ``The people of New Hampshire are
independent-minded voters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, however, worked hard to counter Steve Forbes'
effort to claim success in a second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message (to Forbes) is 'Bush is the frontrunner and you
had your best shot,' `` said Karl Rove, Bush's top adviser. ``You
took your best shot and you came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his high watermark,'' Rove said of Forbes. ``New
Hampshire might be the same for John McCain. It's the state in
which he has spent a lot of time and energy and effort. He is
spending as much money as we are and it's going to be a competitive
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also declined to read much into partial returns showing
McCain garnering 5 percent of the Iowa vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``John didn't campaign here,'' said Bush. ``I don't think we
should hold him to a high standard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is important for the Republican nominee to
campaign in all the states, but he made a different decision. You
need to get him to explain why he made that decision,'' Bush said.
``John's a good man. I look forward to campaigning with him and
against him in the state of New Hampshire. We've got a great race
going on there and I'm looking forward to getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
