<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DECLINES TO HALT PAPER'S DISTRIBUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story does not carry a byline) 
(js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge refused to issue a temporary restraining order
Monday that would have limited distribution of a new free newspaper
in Philadelphia only to areas where other papers are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal, if it stands, would eventually allow the newspaper,
Metro _ which is sponsored by the regional transportation agency _
to be distributed on station concourses, bus platforms and subway
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those areas are off-limits to other publications, and
three newspaper companies brought the suit to halt Metro's
distribution. But Judge Robert Kelly in Philadelphia ruled that the
plaintiffs had failed to show that they would suffer immediate and
irreparable harm if the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation
Authority, or Septa, allowed distribution on subway platforms, at
bus stops or other sites where it does not now permit other
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schwartz, a lawyer for Philadelphia Newspapers Inc., the
unit of Knight Ridder that publishes The Philadelphia Inquirer and
The Philadelphia Daily News, said he was preparing a notice of
appeal and would ask Kelly for an injunction pending the appeal.
Like the other plaintiffs _ The New York Times Co. and the Gannett
Co. _ Philadelphia Newspapers argued that Metro's relationship with
Septa, a regional agency, was unconstitutional and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Metro _ distributed by 140 vendors in stations from 69th Street
to the downtown Suburban station Monday _ is not yet available in
any areas barred to other publications. But that should change by
early next month, unless the courts intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid paper is owned by the Modern Times Group of Sweden,
which publishes transit-based free papers in several European
cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
