<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-PETITIONS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN REMOVED FROM PRIMARY BALLOT IN TWO DISTRICTS  
(lb) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After petition challenges by the Republican State
Committee, election officials have thrown Sen. John McCain off the
ballot in the New York presidential primary in one congressional
district in the South Bronx and another in Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions are the first in the effort by the state's
Republican establishment, which is vigorously supporting Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, to try to fend off McCain by asserting
that his campaign has not gathered enough signatures to comply with
the complicated rules for winning a spot in the March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   The state party has filed challenges to McCain's nominating
petitions in 16 of the state's 31 congressional districts. In the
New York system, Republican presidential candidates are required to
qualify for the primary, district by district.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, New York City election officials disqualified McCain
in the 16th congressional district in the South Bronx, which is
represented by Jose E. Serrano, said Henry Berger, a McCain
campaign lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the campaign withstood challenges in two districts
in Queens _ the 6th, represented by Gregory W. Meeks, and the 7th,
represented by Joseph Crowley. But the campaign has been
disqualified from the 2nd district in Suffolk, represented by Rick
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions on the McCain campaign's fight against challenges in
one city district _ the 12th in Brooklyn, which is represented by
Nydia Velazquez _ as well as in Nassau County and upstate are
expected by the end of the week. Both sides are likely to continue
the fight over some of the districts in state court.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican candidate, Steve Forbes, has spent $750,000
on petition gatherers and a lawyer in an attempt to get on the
ballot across the state. The state Republican Party did not
challenge the Forbes petitions, but some Republican officials on
Long Island who are supporting Bush did successfully challenge
them. In response, the Forbes campaign has filed some challenges
against the Bush campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
