<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-IOWA-REPUBS-NYT &LR;      01-24 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 FOR FORBES, ORGANIZATION AND MONEY PAY OFF IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With IOWA-CAUCUSES and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DES MOINES, Iowa _ After spending more time in Iowa than
any other candidate and digging deeply into his own pockets to
finance his campaign, Steve Forbes' bet on the Iowa caucuses seems
to have paid off.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference four years makes. In 1996, he entered the
state late, had little organization and came in a distant fourth.
This time, learning from that episode, he mounted a lavish
campaign, organized a formidable grass-roots organization and
positioned himself as the champion of the conservative wing of the
Republican party.
</P>
<P>
   And, though he had plenty of competition for the conservative
vote, Forbes' twin messages _ anti-tax and anti-abortion _ were
strong enough to propel him into a strong second-place showing and
give him the bounce he sought to carry him into New Hampshire for
its primary next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the results trickled in, a balloon-festooned room began to
fill up with Forbes supporters wearing the orange T-shirts and blue
baseball caps that the campaign had distributed over the last few
months. Close to 9 p.m., as they heard that the candidate was about
to arrive, many carried little platters bulging with food and
plastic cups of beer and soda from an ample buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Two large television screens beamed the election results down to
the crowd. ``We believe in Steve! We believe in Steve!'' the crowd
chanted as it heard of Forbes' impending arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic,'' said Keith Appell, a spokesman for the
Forbes organization. ``This has shattered our expectations. Steve
Forbes proved that he's the conservative who can go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as voters were going to the caucuses, the Forbes campaign
was broadcasting its television commercials _ a sign of the lavish
spending and attention to detail that has characterized the Forbes
campaign in Iowa. Over the last year, Forbes dipped into his
personal fortune of more than $440 million to spend $25 million of
his own money. That came on top of the $37 million he spent on his
1996 bid.
</P>
<P>
   In the August straw poll, Forbes gained 21 percent of the vote.
He was hoping to get at least that on Monday. But it was unclear,
given the fact that three other candidates were fighting for the
conservative vote, how much beyond that he could get.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Blackwell, Forbes' national chairman, worked the crowd and
crowed: ``We're delighted with this showing. Our goal was to get
over 23 percent. To have 31 to 32 percent is a tremendous
statement. You add up the conservative vote and it's a clear
statement that Bush is out of step with the conservative wing of
the party and, as he is going into New Hampshire, that is not a
nice place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' staff attributed his strong showing to his highly
organized and well-financed campaign and his ability to unite
social and economic conservatives behind him.
</P>
<P>
   They said that his showing here made him the only viable
candidate among the four conservatives in the upcoming New
Hampshire primary, where the moderate Republican vote will be
divided between Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go into New Hampshire, we won't have the same challenge
as in Iowa,'' said Greg Mueller, the Forbes campaign communications
director. ``In New Hampshire, with our strong No. 2 showing here,
we will be unopposed by any other conservative. We will have a
broad-based neo-Reagan message.''
</P>
<P>
   To shore up his support among conservatives, Forbes continued to
hit hard at the abortion theme in the final days of the campaign,
bringing in Phyllis Schlafly and Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia, both
conservative anti-abortion leaders. He also flooded the airwaves
and filled mailboxes in an anti-abortion advertising blitz.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he kept up his signature anti-tax theme, an attack
that continued to get rousing applause as he crissed-crossed the
state in a two-bus caravan and, later, in a chartered DC-9.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes consistently proposed far more drastic tax cuts than
either Bush or McCain, whom Forbes repeatedly termed the ``timid
twins on taxation'' in his stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   But as persuasive as Forbes' message may have been, his
formidable organization and his seemingly endless campaigning here
were at least as important.
</P>
<P>
   He spent 77 days here, more than any other candidate, Democrat
or Republican. And, dipping into his personal fortune of more than
$440 million, he spent $31 million in 1999 seeking the presidency _
$25 million of his own money and $6 million in donations.
</P>
<P>
   That money helped pay for a grass-roots effort in which no
detail was spared. More than 90,000 Iowa families were identified
as ``Forbes-friendly.'' A formidable databank was created that
tapped into a whole new constituency for Forbes _ conservatives who
had never before participated in a caucus. The Forbes campaign
estimated that between 30 percent and 50 percent of the eligible
voters at Forbes rallies had never voted in caucuses before.
</P>
<P>
   The organization was so sophisticated and high-tech that by the
time people signed cards identifying themselves as Forbes
supporters, that information was put into a computer and the people
were contacted by day's end. On caucus night, Forbes supporters
with e-mail were sent personalized directions to their caucus site
by computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to find voters that the pollsters couldn't find
because they were motivated and nontraditional conservatives who
had never really been active before,'' said Steve Grubbs, Forbes'
Iowa campaign chairman. ``And that became a really energized
base.''
</P>
<P>
   The main challenge facing Forbes in Iowa, and one he will not
face in New Hampshire, was that he was forced to fight with three
other candidates _ Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes and Orrin Hatch _ for
conservative voters, while Bush _ once such candidates as Elizabeth
Dole and Dan Quayle dropped out of the race _ had the entire
moderate field to himself.
</P>
<P>
   To counter this, Forbes outcampaigned and outspent his
conservative rivals, while continuing to take positions that moved
him further and further to the right.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, where there are fewer social conservatives,
more economic conservatives and a greater propensity for contrarian
views, the Forbes strategy may shift somewhat, campaign officials
said..
</P>
<P>
   Forbes will present himself as the only conservative choice and
will make special efforts to focus on other groups, like gun
owners, while hitting hard on the tax issue. Already, one of that
state's leading anti-tax groups, the Granite State Taxpayers, has
endorsed Forbes and is working on his behalf. In addition, Forbes'
endorsement by the state's leading newspaper, The Manchester
Union-Leader, which has a conservative philosophy, is also seen as
a boost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
