<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5371 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-THOMAS-CRASH-KAN &LR;      01-24 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-CRASH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS MOVED TO MIAMI, HAS FEELING IN TOES 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY KENT PULLIAM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chiefs linebacker Derrick Thomas, who suffered serious spinal
cord injuries in an auto accident Sunday afternoon, was transferred
to Jackson Memorial Hospital in Miami on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas arrived at the hospital about 6:30 p.m. Eastern time
Monday night and underwent examination at the hospital's trauma
center. To stabilize the fractures, he had surgery late Monday
night that was expected to last into early morning.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Thomas had reported feeling sensations in
his toes, according to a source close to the family. Thomas
suffered a fractured neck and fractured back in the accident that
occurred on the icy roads in Kansas City on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Many friends and members of the Chiefs family _ players and
staff _ visited Thomas before he left Liberty Hospital. As they
struggled to deal with the tragedy that may leave Thomas paralyzed,
he seemed to be upbeat and ready to attack this crisis with the
same ferocity he displayed while chasing quarterbacks during his
11-year NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derrick is...Derrick,'' Chiefs President Carl Peterson said
after talking with Thomas on Monday morning. ``He is positive. He
is awake and knows what is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs coach Gunther Cunningham said Thomas' spirits ``were
tremendous. He had a smile on his face _ as he always does.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas made the decision to be transferred to Jackson Memorial
Hospital after he consulted with doctors, Chiefs personnel and his
family. Thomas grew up in the Miami area, and his mother still
lives there. Jackson Memorial Hospital is affiliated with the
University of Miami School of Medicine, which operates the Miami
Project to Cure Paralysis. It is the nation's largest spinal-cord
research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the best place for his continued medical care and
rehabilitation will be in Miami,'' Peterson said. ``His family is
there. His mother is there. We think it is the most appropriate
thing to do at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Browne, the Chiefs' team doctor, said Thomas suffered
fractures in his spinal column at the C-5 and T-5 locations. Browne
said Thomas had good use of his upper extremities and upper chest
area. But he does have some ``neurological impairment, which is
continuing to evolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne, Peterson and Joe Waeckerle, another Chiefs doctor who
specializes in trauma, accompanied Thomas on the air-ambulance jet.
Thomas' family members returned to Miami on commercial flights
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback James Hasty and former Chiefs defensive end Neil
Smith, Thomas' running mate for much of his career, also were
traveling to Miami to be with Thomas on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Browne would not speculate on any prognosis for Thomas'
recovery, saying it was too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   It appears certain that his football career is finished, but
Peterson refused to accept any questions regarding the Chiefs
without Derrick Thomas. Thomas was the first player drafted by
Peterson when he arrived here in 1989. Thomas is the player most
identified with the team's resurgence in the 1990s, when the club
won more than 100 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are not going to address that,'' Peterson
said. ``So little time has transpired.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas suffered the fractures when he was ejected from his car
near I-435 and Woodland Avenue in Kansas City, North, about 1:30
p.m. Sunday. He was taken for treatment to Liberty Hospital, where
he was placed on a strict protocol designed to minimize the
swelling and pressure on his spinal cord. According to sources
close to the family, he had no feeling in his legs at the scene of
the accident or later Sunday _ though he did tell friends that he
had feeling in his feet Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said: ``We are not going to get into any specifics about
what he does and doesn't have,'' referring to Thomas' inability to
move his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said this type of injury has no clear timeline for
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are aware of other patients, family members and
loved ones who have had these types of injuries,'' Browne said.
``Typically, the cases that have injuries like this are very
difficult to predict. You might move along at a snail's pace and
all of a sudden make a jump (big improvement) or vice versa. It's
important to take each day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Palermo, the former baseball umpire who suffered a spinal
cord injury, visited with Thomas before he left for Miami. Palermo
is a member of the board of directors of Thomas' charitable
foundation Third and Long. But he also has first-hand experience in
what Thomas faces over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I had to tell him very much,'' said Palermo, who
was told he would never walk again but now walks with the aid of a
cane. ``He has met a lot of challenges in his life. This is a very
good and stern test. But he's of the spirit that he is up to the
test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not rule anything in. Do not rule anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said Thomas told him to thank all the people who have
tried to make contact with him since the injury. ``He is sincerely
grateful for that,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson also acknowledged the tragic accident on I-29 that
affected many other families in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here at Liberty Hospital have been magnificent,''
Peterson said. ``Yesterday was a very strenuous day for doctors
throughout North Kansas City. Yet they have been special with
Derrick.''  &LR; tag1:To reach Kent Pulliam, reporter for The Star, call
(816)-234-4370 or send e-mail to kpulliam &LR; kcstar.com
</P>
</TEXT>
