<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL DEVOTED TO THE DUKE OF DECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J.MONTINI 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   enough to get John McCain elected to Congress in 1982, and he
knew it. To make it in Arizona politics, McCain needed the support
of ``The Arizona Republic,'' and for that, he needed Darrow
``Duke'' Tully, the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Tully came to Phoenix in 1978 and, within a few years, was the
most powerful man in the state, using his position to promote
causes and protect _ or punish _ politicians. He was a big,
blustery figure who strode into a room like a referee measuring off
a penalty. He and McCain hit it off from the start.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was the well-known former POW. Tully had stories to tell
of combat service in Korea and Vietnam. They were such close
friends that when McCain's daughter, Megan, was born, he asked
Tully to be her godfather.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late 1985, at the height of his power, Tully was
exposed as an imposter. County Attorney Tom Collins, whom Tully had
vilified in print, discovered that Tully's military career was a
fabrication. The uniforms and medals he wore to formal affairs had
been purchased at military supply outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Tully ``does not deserve his position as a community leader,''
Collins said, and just about everyone in town agreed. Tully
resigned as publisher and disappeared from public view, eventually
taking a job at the ``Williston Daily Herald'' in North Dakota.
Since then, Tully hasn't talked publicly about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   He's retired, now, and living in Florida. I reached him there
Monday, and asked how he felt about his once dear friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to get into interviewing about this
thing,'' Tully said. ``Everybody calls me, from the ``Washington
Post'' on down. That's old business. A long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He did speak recently to a writer from ``Editor &AMP; Publisher''
magazine, Tully said, but that was because ``he called in an old
card, so I paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   But are you still friends with the senator?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have maintained contact,'' Tully said. ``I pulled away from
being real active with John because I felt like our association in
the long run could prove to be embarrassing to him, and I wouldn't
have embarrassed him for anything in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was one single thing I would say about John and my
relationship,'' Tully said, ``it's that his loyalty and friendship
to me has always been there, and I always knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   We're told as children you can judge a man by the friends he
chooses. But that's only part of it. You can tell a lot more by the
way he treats a friend who has let him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the person who pulled away,'' Tully said of McCain. ``I
didn't want to be a deterrent to his political future. Now, there
still is a relationship, obviously. I'm still godfather to Megan.
We still exchange birthday greetings, Christmas cards, presents,
those sorts of things. I never took that lightly. That was very,
very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And it still is.
</P>
<P>
   During the worst days, just after he was exposed, Tully
remembers McCain telling him, ``This too shall pass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him where that came from,'' Tully said, ``and he said
he used to think it in the prison camp. I believe his sense of
those type of things runs deeper than most.''
</P>
<P>
   During a long presidential campaign, a candidate is reduced to a
business suit with sound bites. McCain is no different. The more he
talks, the less we know about him.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily there are some issues, like friendship, like loyalty,
for which years of silence tell you all you need to know. &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
