<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ANONYMITY TO SPOTLIGHT FOR NEW BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Who knew Bill Parcells had such colorful
assistants? Come to think of it, who knew Parcells had assistants?
</P>
<P>
   For three years here at Weeb Ewbank Hall (not yet renamed
Parcells' Place), it was the great, giant Tuna and his minnowlike
minions, in all matters except size of the workload. While Parcells
got the attention and credit for building a dynasty that won one
playoff game, Bill Belichick locked himself in a room with his best
friend, the videocassette recorder.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Jets' staff was muted and invisible, under
Parcells' meaty thumb. Upon his retirement from coaching, they all
emerged and the Jets immediately turned into a soap opera of
X-and-O guys. All My Assistants.
</P>
<P>
   For Parcells _ who typically embraced the maxim that there is no
``I'' in ``team,'' only in ``Bill'' _ the strange turn of events
that has beclouded the Jets can best be described as wickedly
ironic, and better make that with a capital ``I.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this to be categorized as rambling,'' Al Groh
said, as he embarked on a final point Monday during the news
conference at which the incoming owner Robert Wood Johnson IV
officially appointed him head coach.
</P>
<P>
   This wry and promising humor, at the expense of Belichick,
simply delighted his audience and further demonstrated that the
former linebackers coach is perfectly comfortable with his unlikely
casting for the Al Groh Show. Again: Who knew these last three
years while Parcells was performing his ongoing monologue that
there were so many other voices crying to be heard?
</P>
<P>
   When Belichick was finally allowed to speak, he unleashed at
least 10,000 words between ``good'' and ``bye.'' When the offensive
coordinator Charlie Weis was called to testify at last week's
league hearing on the Belichick contract matter, this Charlie
wasn't afraid to say, sorry Tuna, Little Bill should be let off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   And when the defensive line coach Romeo Crennel had a choice of
similar positions for the Jets and the Cleveland Browns, Romeo fell
in love with the idea of working for a team whose heart wouldn't
always belong to Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom of expression _ it's amazing the things people will say
and do when they have it.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday, who knew that the man in charge of the blitz was
the type to tell urination jokes? We don't know if Groh will leave
'em laughing or crying as head coach, but here's what we do know:
You've got to start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was once an unheralded assistant. So were Pat Riley and
Phil Jackson. So was Jeff Fisher, of those Super Bowl Titans, and
Jeff Van Gundy and _ in a variation on the theme _ there was a
journeyman manager named Torre whose appointment here was
practically met with the lowering of 22 World Series flags to
half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   Promoting a career assistant is risky, but it usually helps when
the guy has a profile, a persona, if only for the sake of
mollifying the news media and fans, and easing the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's organized, he's focused and he knows what he wants,''
said Joe Thomas, who was Groh's high school coach at Chaminade High
School. ``Al isn't trying to please anybody. He's a coach from down
deep, in here.''
</P>
<P>
   The proud 84-year-old, no doubting Thomas, gently patted his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Every man has a mentor, a family, a story. For three years with
the Jets, Groh has been nothing more than a yearbook photo and bio,
thanks to Parcells' ridiculous policy of gagging his assistants.
Can you imagine Joe Torre ordering Mel Stottlemyre into the shadows
of the Yankee clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   With his assistants divulging state secrets, Parcells somehow
won two Super Bowls. In New England, which was about the time he
became a certified genius, Parcells became the puppeteer. These are
grown men, with pride and self-respect. Maybe it was unavoidable
that it was going to end so divisively for this Jets' staff.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Parcells did a wonderful job bringing
credibility and hope to the Jets. The fact also is that rebuilding
overnight is not the miracle (see Indianapolis and St. Louis) it
once was in a league of unrestricted free agency and salary caps.
Groh deserves a chance without having Parcells, who did not finish
the job, thrown in his face every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Bill has often said, you are what you are, and we were
8-8,'' said Groh. ``We have work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a legend to elude and new hires to make. He said he has
not addressed the issue of the assistant coaches' news media
policy. Let 'em speak. Let 'em ramble, if that's what keeps them
happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
