<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: IOWA, AND ABORTION, AS EARLY DEFINERS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ In the long run, the most important
consequence of the Iowa Presidential caucuses this year may be the
impression they leave of Gov. George W. Bush on voters across the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   His entire candidacy has been predicated on the determination of
many Republicans, chafing after eight years of Democratic control
of the White House, to put party unity and solidarity ahead of
ideology. That determination gave him fund-raising success and
leadership backing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor will of course have many chances between now and
November to modify his image and fine-tune his position on the
issues. But first impressions count, as countless mothers have told
countless children, so the Bush camp must hope their man will not
be further hammered by his Republican rivals on abortion and other
divisive issues in the weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, when Jimmy Carter first put the Iowa
caucuses on the national political map by winning the state's 1976
presidential caucuses, the only thing that really mattered was who
won.
</P>
<P>
   Today the nation sees not only the Iowa results but the campaign
that produces them. Journalists have swarmed across the state since
last August, when the Republican straw poll took place, pumping out
data. The candidates in both parties have debated each other on
national television.
</P>
<P>
   This time, significantly, the nation knows that Bush had to
speak more about abortion during the Iowa campaign, and more
specifically, than he had hoped. That could have a big impact not
only on the primaries to follow, but more importantly, on the
general election this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Many Iowans knew what Carter had said and done during the months
that preceded his victory _ the long, grinding months of talking to
individual voters and to tiny crowds here in the Farm Belt _ but
most of the rest of the country did not. Only a few national
reporters had bothered to come here. The broadcast networks were
largely absent. And, of course, things like CNN, MSNBC and
political Web sites had not even been invented.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was free to define himself in the later stages of the
campaign, and to keep his party reasonably united behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican politicians, and certainly most of those around
Bush, take it as given that the abortion issue has the capacity to
split their party and scare away independents. But Bush's main Iowa
rivals, Steve Forbes, Alan Keyes and Gary Bauer, saw it as the one
issue that could set them apart from the front-runner, and honed in
on it in the final weeks.
</P>
<P>
   All three identified themselves strongly with the religious
right, which is more powerful in Iowa than in most states, and
among them they polled roughly half of the vote. That may well
encourage them _ and especially Forbes, who has spent millions but
has millions more to spend _ to hammer away at abortion in New
Hampshire, which votes a week from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   One question is whether Forbes, who has so far avoided the kind
of personal attacks he engaged in four years ago, will change
course in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a uniter, not a divider,'' Bush said before leaving for
New Hampshire, as if to send a message that he would not been drawn
into a slugging match with his party rivals. ``The people of Iowa
want a leader who can unite our party and our country, and they
showed that today.''
</P>
<P>
   The main threat to Bush in New Hampshire, Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, did not campaign in Iowa and drew few votes here.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's Republican results had something for almost
everyone. Bush won, and won reasonably convincingly. Forbes did
much better than the polls had suggested he would, and much better
than he did four years ago. Keyes broke into double digits. But it
is hard to imagine that Iowa decided very much; it has decided very
little since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   This state's winners often turn into losers later, either in
subsequent primaries or in the general election. The last candidate
in either party to win a contested Iowa caucus and go on to victory
in November was Carter in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's latter-day role of winnowing the field, of getting it
down to manageable proportions, happened this year before a single
caucus vote had been cast. Four years ago, for instance, Sen. Phil
Gramm of Texas was knocked out of the Republican race by the voting
itself. This time, Lamar Alexander and Dan Quayle failed to survive
the straw poll, and Elizabeth Dole was so weakened that she dropped
out not much later.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey
came out of the caucuses without much to show for a massive
television campaign and intensive personal efforts during the last
two weeks. Among Democrats, support from trade unions and party
officials has always counted for a great deal, and it apparently
did again this year, with Vice President Al Gore benefitting from
the links he forged here with White House help.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his best efforts, on subjects ranging from farm policy
to health insurance, to suggest that he differed markedly from
Gore, Bradley was unable to make that case with enough caucus-goers
to count. Initial figures suggested that the attendance at the
Democratic meetings had been relatively low, whereas the New
Jerseyan had hoped to attract large numbers of people who had not
previously taken part in caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will go on to New Hampshire, where polls have shown him
running neck-and-neck with Gore, without the kind of boost he had
hoped for. It is Gore, if anyone, who will get the bounce from
Iowa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
