<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-BRADLEY-COX     01-24 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-BRADLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley campaign glad to be heading to New Hampshire
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Several hundred supporters of Bill Bradley
crowded into a ballroom in a downtown Des Moines hotel Monday to
watch the caucus returns. Despite the fact that Bradley was losing
to Vice President Al Gore, his supporters remained upbeat about
their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the fire in the belly,'' said Marcia Moore, a Des
Moines voter who caucused for Bradley and was elected one of his
precinct delegates.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on ABC, Bradley displayed some of that fire as
the results were still being counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now in the stage where the citizen is deciding. This
thing is moving up,'' he said. ``We told the people what we
believed. We got new people in the process. I think this could be a
longer evening than people imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said, ``We are doing well. The bar was 31 percent.''
That's the figure Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.) achieved in his
insurgent campaign in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Berman, Bradley's campaign chair, said the campaign was
relieved to be heading toward New Hampshire for a ``fresh start. We
are turning the page on Iowa, starting tonight,'' he said. ``Our
challenge is now in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire clearly had been on Bill Bradley's mind throughout
the day.
</P>
<P>
   At a small rally at Iowa State College in Ames, Bradley focused
on some of the the newer themes that he will stress inthe Granite
State, where the latest polls show him losing his edge to Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics, to too many Americans and too many young people, has
become nothing other than tactics,'' Bradley said. ``It's become
tactics and not belief. It's become spin and not truth. It's become
fund-raising and not reaching out to people where they live their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign announced a new 30-second television ad that will
begin airing in New Hampshire today, echoing similar messages.
</P>
<P>
   The ad features the widow of Sen. Paul Tsongas (D-Mass.), who
won the New Hampshire primary in 1992. ``What disappoints me now is
_ just as with Paul _ Bill's record is being distorted,'' Niki
Tsongas says in the commercial.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the rally at Ames, Bradley spent the rest of the
day appearing on local television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he had the bankroll to fight on for the nomination
in next week's New Hampshire primary and in the cluster of state
primaries on March 7, which he called the first ``national
primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
