<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-IOWA-MAIN-COX     01-24 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As expected, Bush, Gore score in Iowa caucuses
 &HT;    By Ken Herman of The Austin American-Statesman
 &HT;    Ken Foskett of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
 &HT;    and Scott Shepard of Cox News Service
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ George W. Bush and Al Gore drew first blood
in the young presidential campaign Monday night with convincing
victories in the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Both results were highly expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled with this victory,'' Bush said on national
television. ``I'm grateful, and I'm humbled.''
</P>
<P>
   With his victory just minutes old Monday night, Gore was already
looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get to New Hampshire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gore won about 63 percent of the delegates, handily
beating former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley. The well-funded Bush
campaign captured 40 percent of the vote, beating Republican
publisher Steve Forbes, who has poured millions of his own money
into his second bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore are expected to face tougher challenges one week
from today in the New Hampshire primary, where Arizona Sen. John
McCain leads Bush in some polls and Bradley has tied Gore in other
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight isn't the end,'' Bradley said. ``It's just the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa launched the presidential race into a frantic six-week
stretch expected to narrow the field considerably, perhaps down to
each party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes mounted a vigorous campaign in Iowa, calling on
fundamentalist and conservative support and trying to position
himself as the strongest alternative to the more moderate Bush.
That strategy seemed to work in the crowded six-man field as Forbes
received 30 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, he was clearly satisfied with his strong
second-place showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your faith has been vindicated tonight,'' Forbes told cheering
supporters in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We vastly overperformed the polls and have emerged as a
conservative candidate,'' said Forbes, who had indicated earlier in
the day he would ``feel good about a good, strong second.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes, in third with 14 percent, said he also felt good
about the results. He based his finish ahead of Gary Bauer and Sen.
Orrin Hatch on his firm stance on moral issues _ most notably his
strong opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-place finisher McCain basically skipped the Iowa caucuses,
putting most of his efforts and money into the New Hampshire race.
Forbes' strong finish in Iowa actually could help McCain in New
Hampshire because some undecided voters could feel that Bush is
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can really do this,'' McCain assured his supporters in New
Hampshire on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He also dismissed the importance of the Iowa vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of New Hampshire don't pay a great deal of attention to
what happens in Iowa,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch finished last with 1 percent but said he will soldier on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get discouraged,'' he said. ``If you get discouraged
in this business, you don't get a lot done.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Bradley suffered his first defeat in 22
years of politics, hurt in large part by failing to respond
aggressively to Gore's TV and radio ads. That's not a mistake he
will repeat in New Hampshire, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also indicated Gore is in for a long battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the competition goes, the better chance that
candidate is going to have ... in the fall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition apparently motivated many Democrats, with
officials reporting record turnouts at many of the state's 2,100
precincts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed confidence, particularly since his showing in
Iowa was the best-ever in a contested GOP field.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole set the previous record at 37 percent in 1988 when he
won Iowa but eventually lost the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel tremendous,'' Bush said. ``We've put a lot of work into
it. My message of compassionate conservatism is a message that this
state heard. I look forward to bringing it to other states. Ours is
a message that resonates beyond Iowa to New Hampshire and South
Carolina and all across our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to cheering supporters in a Des Moines hotel ballroom,
Bush declined to portray the results as anything
</P>
<P>
   but a major victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven months ago I came to Iowa on a plane dubbed 'Great
Expectations,''' he said. ``Tonight, Iowa has exceeded them.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Iowa political scientist Arthur Miller said the
caucus results were positive for several contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty impressive that Forbes was able to do as
well as he has,'' said Miller. ``But the governor goes out of the
state with a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller noted that the vote total for Forbes and Keyes would wind
up about the same as Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people on the right definitely turned out and they voted
the conservative line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa campaign was one of the most expensive in history.
Forbes spent far more than anyone _ about $3.2 million, according
to aides from the Forbes and Bush campaigns. Bush spent about $1
million less.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats spent about $1.5 million each _ closer to $2
million for Bradley, according to the Gore camp.
</P>
<P>
   The parties conducted their caucuses in slightly different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats elect county convention delegates reflecting their
presidential preferences, discuss platform issues and elect
precinct leaders. Republicans elect precinct leaders, hold a straw
poll for president, elect delegates to the county conventions and
consider platform issues.
</P>
<P>
   After Iowa and New Hampshire, Democrats turn their attention to
an avalanche of primaries from New York to California on March 7.
Republicans will compete in several states before March 7,
including Delaware on Feb. 8, South Carolina on Feb. 19 and Arizona
and Michigan on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the number of delegates selected, Iowa's impact is
relatively small.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa will eventually send 25 delegates to the Republican
convention in Philadelphia, where 2,066 representatives will pick
the party's candidates in August.
</P>
<P>
   And 56 Iowans will go to Los Angeles for the Democratic
convention, out of 4,337 total delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Goldford, chairman of the politics and international
relations department at Drake University in Des Moines, says the
caucuses mostly serve to narrow the field of contenders.
</P>
<P>
   By this morning, when the candidates wake up in New Hampshire,
this first election of the season will probably have done just
that.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
