<HEADLINE>
VICTORIOUS BUSH SETS SIGHTS ON NEW HAMPSHIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush hardly savored his
victory in the Iowa Republican presidential caucuses Monday before
flying to New Hampshire to see if he can break the lead rival Sen.
John McCain has grabbed in the Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Hampshire, I don't plan on losing it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush got more bad news from New England on Monday as a
CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll reported that McCain is leading Bush 43
percent to 34 percent among likely New Hampshire Republican primary
voters. That poll was conducted Jan. 20-22, after almost a full
week of Bush attacking McCain's tax cut proposal in local
television advertising
</P>
<P>
   Despite the polls, McCain still sees himself as ``the underdog
... in a close race. I take nothing for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not campaign for Iowa caucus votes and received only
5 percent. But as Bush campaigned in Iowa, New Hampshire was never
far from his sights. He took daily shots at McCain, who has turned
the New Hampshire primary into a higher hurdle for Bush than the
GOP front-runner expected.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has defined the race on his $483 billion tax-cut plan
against McCain's $240 billion plan. Bush has contended that McCain
has revised his plan repeatedly, and that the plan would pay for
tax cuts with some tax increases. McCain has responded that Bush is
misleading voters and breaking his promise against negative
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also plans this week to draw critical
differences between Bush and McCain on education. Bush spokesman
Karen Hughes said Bush has an education record as governor of Texas
and has laid out a federal plan in the presidential race. She said
McCain has yet to make his position on education clear.
</P>
<P>
   Besides McCain, Bush faces a potential threat from Steve Forbes,
who ran second in Iowa. He has concentrated on scoring well in
Iowa, but also obtained the editorial endorsement of New
Hampshire's influential Manchester Union Leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush consultant Karl Rove noted that since November the Bush
New Hampshire volunteers have delivered more than 200,000 pieces of
literature to state voters, while Forbes has done little outside of
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his (Forbes') high-water mark. New Hampshire might be
the same for John McCain,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   While not conceding New Hampshire to McCain, Rove said Bush
eventually will win the GOP presidential nomination because of his
national organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a rough spot in the road. But as the
front-runner, we have the organization and the national standing to
continue the campaign everywhere and win,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been losing the battle of newspaper editorials in New
Hampshire. McCain has the backing of 15 state newspapers and Bush,
three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think it says a lot about the campaign Bush has run
here,'' said Mike Pride, editor of the Concord Monitor, which threw
its support to McCain after Bush failed to meet with the editorial
board. ``New Hampshire is a place where you are supposed to make
yourself available to voters. Bush hasn't done that. He's been
quite sheltered.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has not always been friendly to the Bush family in
presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   While New Hampshire voters came through for Bush's father,
former President Bush, when he won the GOP nomination in 1988, the
weakness of his 1992 re-election campaign was exposed when Patrick
Buchanan got 37 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1980, after winning the Iowa caucuses, Bush declared he
had the ``Big Mo,'' or momentum, going into the New Hampshire
primary, but he lost to ultimate party nominee Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Mo didn't work,'' the younger Bush said last week,
downplaying the role Iowa may have in helping him defeat McCain in
New Hampshire. ``Sometimes victory does not mean victory. I hope it
does in my case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rove said Bush can count on a bounce from his Iowa victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at four years ago. The day before the Iowa caucus,
Bob Dole was at 19 percent in New Hampshire and three days later he
was at 26 percent...which is where he ended up on election day,''
Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A CBS poll showed the fluidity of the 2000 New Hampshire race.
Fifty-eight percent of the New Hampshire voters said they could
still change their minds. Only 40 percent of Bush's supporters said
they were sure to vote for him, and just 44 percent of McCain's
support was solid.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Bass of New Hampshire, a Bush backer, said the
Texas governor can all but wrap up the nomination if he defeats
McCain in New Hampshire. But if Bush loses New Hampshire, ``it
means it will be a long winter.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
