<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA CAUCUS COVERAGE PORTRAYS AN ELECTION IN A TIME WARP 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ It was like watching an election in reverse
gear, first the results, then the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Live on C-SPAN at 8:10 p.m. ET, Monday night, some 84
participants in a Democratic caucus in Ames, Iowa, were beginning
to take their seats. At virtually the same moment, Brian Williams,
the anchor on MSNBC, was reporting, ``NBC News projects Al Gore
will be the winner and will go on to New Hampshire with his first
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers could be forgiven for wondering whether one of these
channels was on tape delay. But the reality was, it was just
another of the peculiarities of the Iowa caucus process. On most
election nights, news organizations rely on surveys of voters as
they leave the polls. Because Iowans all gather at the same
appointed time in the early evening at the 2,000 caucuses around
the state, the polling is conducted before a single vote has been
cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, you are asked as you are walking into your
caucus, `Who are you going to support?' '' explained John Ellis,
head of the decision desk that analyzed the so-called ``entrance
polls'' for the Fox News Channel, one of MSNBC's chief competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the caucus-goers in Ames, a university town of 50,000
about 30 miles north of here, did not actually cast their votes
until about 8:45 p.m., when, before the C-SPAN cameras, the caucus
chairman, Jim Hutter, declared, ``It's time to divide it up!'' Ten
minutes later, the supporters of each of the Democrats having
assembled, Hutter announced the results: Bradley, 37; Gore, 47.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast in the reports of the real event and the
statistical voting projections could not have been starker. The
three all-news cable channels _ Fox News Channel, MSNBC and CNN
engaged in a fierce 15-to-20-minute battle to call the races in the
first half hour of their wall-to-wall coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Fox claimed the first call of the evening, at 8 p.m., declaring
Gov. George W. Bush the winner of the Republican caucuses, but in
truth, all the cable networks led their 8 o'clock special reports
with the advisory that Bush was leading and the likely winner.
(MSNBC officially called it at 8:25 and CNN at 8:27).The
traditional broadcast networks, meanwhile, kept to their normal
programming, running the projections on a crawl from time to time
at the bottom of the screens. They also reported their calls
rapidly on their respective Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore was also projected the winner in the
first few minutes of coverage. But the results on the Democratic
drew less interest at the anchors; for days, there had been reports
that Bill Bradley's fortunes in Iowa were sinking. The polls, it
turned out, were pretty much on the money, and the news people were
hard pressed to identify the kind of Iowa surprise that has
stimulated discussion on previous caucus nights.
</P>
<P>
   The only mild surprise was a trend that many news organizations
had picked up on in the previous 24 hours, that Alan Keyes was
gaining strength. He finished third on the Republican side, behind
Steve Forbes and ahead of Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Greenfield, the CNN analyst, said that the numbers
indicated that Keyes ``was able to convince a fair number'' of
former supporters of Pat Buchanan and Pat Robertson, ``to `Stay
with me,' which kind of held back Bush. ``He got a good victory but
not a blowout.''
</P>
<P>
   On CNN, Judy Woodruff declared it ``a sweet night for the Bush
family: 20 years ago, another Bush won the Republican caucuses in
Iowa.'' A few minutes later, candidate Bush was being interviewed
by Larry King, calling his win a ``tremendous victory'' in a
``crowded field.'' On MSNBC, Tim Russert predicted that John
McCain, who had bypassed Iowa and ended up in fifth, would use
Bush's victory in New Hampshire to urge voters ``to give me a
chance and keep it going beyond New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on C-SPAN, the caucus-goers were still meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
