<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MURPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERALD MURPHY, 65, DEVELOPER OF CANCER TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., N.Y., Mont., Calif., Texas)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gerald Patrick Murphy, a urologist whose research led to the PSA
test, widely used to help in the early detection of prostate
cancer, died on Friday in Tel Aviv, Israel, while attending a
conference on cancer. He was 65 and lived in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, reports from Israel said. Murphy
had undergone several heart bypass operations.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was a longtime secretary-general of the International
Union of Cancer, the coalition of health professionals that held
the conference. He was also a former president of the American
Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Murphy was affiliated with a long roster of
research centers, foundations and other institutions dealing with
cancer. From 1970 to 1985 he directed the Roswell Park Memorial
Institute for cancer research and therapy in Buffalo, N.Y., and
helped build it into an internationally recognized center.
</P>
<P>
   He worked in Buffalo in the urology laboratory of the State
University of New York Medical School, leading the researchers who
established that cancer tumors of the prostate generate prostate
specific antigens, or PSAs. Antigens are substances to which the
body responds with antibodies in an effort to protect itself.
</P>
<P>
   That discovery eventually led to the development of the PSA
test; high levels of the substance can point to the presence of
prostate cancer at an early stage. The test is now widely used as a
diagnostic tool in combination with a rectal exam.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, the PSA test has been used on millions of men
worldwide to help look for early prostate cancer, and it can often
show the presence of the disease before it would otherwise be
detected, permitting early treatment. But it does not distinguish
between fast-growing, life-threatening cancers and others, and like
any test it fails to detect cancer in some men who have it, while
other men receive false-positive results.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Murphy was born in Havre, Mont., and graduated summa cum
laude from Seattle University in 1955. He received an M.D. at the
University of Washington in 1959. He conducted research at Walter
Reed Army Hospital before joining the staff of Roswell Park
Memorial in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy helped lobby Congress for passage of the National Cancer
Act of 1971, which created cancer research centers across the
United States. He wrote more than 1,000 papers and was an editor of
scientific journals; he also taught at institutions in the United
States and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Roswell Park, Murphy became the chief medical
officer of the American Cancer Society, directing its programs in
clinical education, service and patient care. He moved to Seattle
in 1993 and at his death was clinical professor of urology at the
University of Washington and research director of the Pacific
Northwest Cancer Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is survived by his wife of 40 years, Mary Bridget
Cunningham Murphy; four daughters, Anne Marie Banner of Seattle,
Margaret Olivares of Santa Monica, Calif., Maureen Anderson of
Seattle and Bridget Neill of Washington, D.C.; two sons, George of
Issaquah, Wash., and Gerald of Austin, Texas; a sister, Lois
Spellman of Seattle, and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
