<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TENN-MCNAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: RACE AND HISTORY WILL INTRUDE ON MCNAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tennessee quarterback Steve McNair may not know it
yet, he could not know it yet, but he is walking into a hurricane,
and this one does not possess a calm eye. He will be held up as a
symbol of what is right and wrong with professional football. He
will be held up as a symbol of what is good and bad about the
sports media.
</P>
<P>
   McNair should bring his helmet to those annoying early-morning
question-and-answer sessions all week leading up to Super Bowl
XXXIV on Sunday. He will have microphones shoved up his nose and
stupid questions tossed his way like bricks. It is a scene that
will occur every day. The sports media will stick to him like glue,
and not because he is handsome or tall.
</P>
<P>
   But because he is black.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, because he is a black quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   McNair becomes only the second black player to start at
quarterback in Super Bowl history. He has a million other stories
to tell, of course. How he overcame a devastating back injury this
season. How he played in the American Football Conference
championship game with a painful turf toe injury. How he can master
an offense like a skilled captain, even though people are still
trying to pigeonhole him as nothing more than a souped-up fullback.
</P>
<P>
   He may get to discuss those things, but most of his time with
the sports media will be spent answering questions in regard to the
color of his skin. Let's hope he will not get the query Doug
Williams once received from a reporter in 1988. Williams was the
first black quarterback to start in a Super Bowl and was asked
perhaps the single dumbest question in championship history: how
long have you been a black quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those delicate balancing acts for both the
National Football League and members of the sports media. McNair's
being here, on this stage, is a great moment, an emotional one, and
one that thousands of blacks, if not hundreds of thousands, across
the country will follow closely. This is a simple fact: McNair
could become a folk hero in the black community the same way
Williams did after Super Bowl XXII by leading Washington over
Denver by a score of 42-10. Williams was named the most valuable
player in the game, and for years afterward, he would sometimes be
stopped in the street by black fans, no matter what city he was in,
who would tell him how much his victory meant to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Racism, for decades, kept blacks from playing quarterback, which
is why Williams, and now McNair, are such important historical
figures. Jimmy Raye, now an assistant with the Kansas City Chiefs,
was a quarterback who led Michigan State to two Big Ten titles and
a Rose Bowl appearance in 1966. But since most NFL executives,
influenced by a hearty dose of prejudice, did not think Raye and
other blacks were smart enough to play the position, he went
undrafted and was converted to cornerback by Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Moon was asked by teams to consider switching to
defensive back after leading the Washington Huskies to a 27-20
upset of the University of Michigan in the 1978 Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, of the 1,379 players in the league, only two blacks,
James Harris and Vince Evans, were on rosters as quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   So McNair walks into what will be a charged atmosphere, a
mountain of history on his shoulders. Like it or not, that is the
case, and he will be asked about it, constantly. And the questions
will come from the sports media that love to chastise the NFL for
its lack of black coaches and even quarterbacks but rarely shine
the spotlight on their own questionable hiring habits, their own
prejudiced opinions, their own private racist jokes.
</P>
<P>
   McNair has been belittled by journalists who make such veiled
remarks as ``he cannot run an offense.'' Yet he is 11-2 as a
starter this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Steve does,'' center Bruce Matthews said, ``is win.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the quandary that football, mirroring society, finds
itself in. We must note how important McNair's start in the Super
Bowl is, and the progress the sport is making. Last April, three
black quarterbacks, Daunte Culpepper, Donovan McNabb and Akili
Smith, were picked in the first round of the NFL draft. Shaun King,
who came close to leading the Tampa Bay Buccaneers to an upset over
the Rams on Sunday, was selected in the second. Before that draft,
a total of four black quarterbacks had been picked in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Thus accomplishments are being made. But that the subject of
black quarterbacks will be discussed repeatedly this week _ here in
Atlanta, and on planes, trains and automobiles across the country _
is also a sign that there is still a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   McNair is already attempting to play down the talk of race and
his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't worry about that,'' he said after Tennessee beat
Jacksonville, 33-14, on Sunday. ``I'm a quarterback in the Super
Bowl. That's the way I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``But I know all about history.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
