<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-TRIAL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO FAMILY ASKS THAT U.S. MONITOR STATE TRIAL OF OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The parents of Amadou Diallo, accompanied by the Rev. Al
Sharpton and Congressman Charles Rangel, met Monday with Justice
Department officials in Washington to press for federal monitoring
of the state murder trial of the four police officers charged with
killing Diallo last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, a Democrat, and Sharpton had been pushing for the
meeting with Deputy Attorney General Eric H. Holder Jr. and Bill
Lann Lee, the assistant attorney general for civil rights, since an
appellate court ordered the trial moved from the Bronx to Albany
last month. The lawyers representing the Diallos in a civil case
stemming from the shooting also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said the Diallos wanted the Justice Department to use
the monitoring report as the basis for convening a federal grand
jury if the state prosecution is unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he presented Holder with a copy of the medical
examiner's autopsy of Diallo. Sharpton said he believed that the
autopsy showed that many of the 19 bullets that struck Diallo hit
him while he was already on the ground. He also said he gave Holder
a census report showing the racial differences between Bronx and
Albany counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been involved in many cases, and I think this is the
first time I've been given this level of audience,'' Sharpton said
of the meeting. ``It shows how seriously they're taking the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine DiBartolo, a spokeswoman for the Justice Department,
said the department would monitor the state criminal case but that
no decision had been made about details.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen C. Worth, a lawyer for one of the defendants, Officer
Edward McMellon, noted that Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney for
the southern district, had been monitoring the case from the start.
``It would appear,'' he added, ``that Reverend Sharpton is
attempting to ensure that there will be two bites at the apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Replying to the assertion that Diallo was on the ground when
many of the shots were fired, Worth said, ``We believe that the
evidence at trial will reveal a different forensic analysis than
Rev. Sharpton's.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, Assemblyman Keith Wright said Monday that the state
Legislature's Black and Hispanic Caucus was pushing for the trial
to be televised by closed circuit to another courtroom in the
Albany courthouse and possibly to a location in New York City.
David Bookstaver, a spokesman for the state Office of Court
Administration, said showing the trial in a second Albany courtroom
was being seriously contemplated ``because of the media and
community interest in the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial courtroom has only 80 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Court TV has filed a motion seeking to televise the trial,
although doing so would require approval by the Legislature.
Current state law does not allow trials to be broadcast, and there
has been no indication that legislative leaders are planning to
reinstate a past law that allowed cameras in courtrooms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Robert Johnson, the Bronx district attorney, and Eliot
Spitzer, the state attorney general, have indicated that they
support televising the Diallo trial in particular and trials in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general believes strongly there should be cameras
in the courtroom and would urge the Legislature to renew the law
permitting trials to be televised,'' said Scott Brown, a spokesman
for Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The jury pool for the trial has already begun to be winnowed,
said John A. Diamond, Albany County commissioner of jurors.
</P>
<P>
   A good number of the 2,000 jurors who received letters ordering
them to report on Monday have been calling with excuses, ranging
from business appointments to children's school holidays, and
asking for an alternate date to serve. Diamond said few of the
callers had mentioned the Diallo trial or indicated that it was why
they did not want to serve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
