<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-AUSTRALIA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPRIATI REACHES SEMIFINALS IN CRUSHING DISPLAY AGAINST SUGIYAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ She was a semifinalist at the French Open
at 14, a semifinalist at the U.S. Open and Wimbledon at 15. But
Jennifer Capriati had to wait until adulthood to reach the
semifinals at the other Grand Slam tennis event.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she rounded off her resume with an ease that belied
the difficulties she has experienced off court in recent years.
Shrugging off a stomach injury that required treatment early in the
match, she overpowered Ai Sugiyama of Japan, 6-0, 6-2, in the
Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll pinch myself after the tournament,'' the 23-year-old
Capriati said in an interview with Australian television.
</P>
<P>
   She needed only 55 minutes to defeat Sugiyama, whose play
Tuesday admittedly bore little resemblance to her performances
earlier in the tournament. The match was played indoors after Open
organizers closed the roof over Rod Laver Arena because of rain.
Sugiyama walked on court with her left thigh wrapped tightly and
did not move or control the ball as well as she had in her upset of
fourth-seeded Mary Pierce on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she had played on center court yet, and I had
played a few there already,'' Capriati said. ``It takes some
getting used to. The speed is a little different than on the
outside courts.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Capriati had difficulty recognizing Sugiyama's game, the
Japanese must have had difficulty recognizing hers, as well.
Capriati is no longer the same erratic and uncertain player whom
Sugiyama had beaten in their two most recent matches. With the help
of her coach, Harold Solomon, and her physical trainer, Karen
Burnette, she has regained her confidence and improved her fitness.
She is getting to the ball early, which allows her to use her
natural power to full effect.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she is back in a Grand Slam semifinal for the first time
since 1991, when she lost to Monica Seles at the U.S. Open in one
of the most intense and hard-hitting women's matches in memory, one
that ended in a final-set tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer can't hit the ball much better than she did today,''
Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati will face either second-seeded Lindsay Davenport or
ninth-seeded Julie Halard-Decugis of France. Davenport and
Halard-Decugis were to play later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's unbelievable,'' Solomon said of Capriati's
run. ``Our goal in the fall was for her to gear for this
tournament. We thought she could get herself ready to go and be a
real threat to win here. We thought if she could put in the work,
this would be a great time to get a good start to the season,
because this tournament comes shortly after Christmas and not
everybody is able to put in the same kind of preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Capriati's return to prominence has not been sudden.
</P>
<P>
   The groundwork was laid last year, when she played in all four
Grand Slam events for the first time in six years and reached the
fourth round at the French Open and the U.S. Open. At Flushing
Meadows, she broke down in tears at a news conference after
announcing that she wanted to put her past behind her and not
discuss the personal problems that caused her to leave the tour in
1993 and kept her from playing another Grand Slam event until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati is now guaranteed to return to the top 20 for the first
time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she definitely has grown off the court,'' Solomon
said. ``She's an introspective young lady who thinks about things a
lot and has matured and developed in a lot of different ways. I
think her development off the court is reflected on the court. Not
the other way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with Serena Williams' loss on Monday, top-seeded Martina
Hingis and Davenport remain the favorites to meet in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost to her three times, so I would love to play her
actually,'' Hingis said about Davenport after the Swiss player
scored a 6-1, 7-6 (7-3) victory over Sandrine Testud of France on
Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
