<SLUG> BC-DEMS-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RETURNS GIVE GORE EASY WIN IN IOWA CAUCUSES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore easily won the Iowa
Democratic presidential caucuses Monday, complicating the task of
challenger Bill Bradley as the campaign turns toward the New
Hampshire primary a week from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns from across the state in the first meaningful test
of the 2000 campaign pointed to Gore scoring a victory of slightly
less than 2-to-1. With most of the precincts reporting, Gore had 63
percent to Bradley's 35 percent. The final result will set the
presidential preference of the 47 regular delegates from Iowa to
the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles in August.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's first public reaction came in a telephone conversation
with his top supporter in the Granite State, Gov. Jeanne Shaheen:
``We have a big win here. My message to you in New Hampshire is, we
have just begun to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, addressing supporters in a Des Moines hotel ballroom,
recalled he had always said that running for president required a
combination of humility and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, I have a little more humility but no less confidence
that I can win and do the job,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's victory was widely predicted in pre-caucus polling, and
his margin in initial returns was close to expectations in the most
significant last-minute surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a solid victory,'' said political analyst Stuart
Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's defeat was magnified by the fact that he spent more
time campaigning in Iowa than Gore, doing the one-on-one
politicking for which the state is famed, and apparently at least
matched the vice president's television ad budget.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, perhaps still best known for his years as a
professional basketball star, had hoped to stun Gore _ and
political observers _ with a closer outcome in Iowa that might have
fueled his insurgent bid in the eight days before the New Hampshire
vote. Bradley's lead in New Hampshire polls was slipping even
before the Iowa caucus Monday.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire voters are often unimpressed with decisions made
in Iowa, and Gore will be careful not to sound too triumphal or
suggest that the Iowa results mean that the race is, in effect,
over. But the burst of media coverage focusing on Gore's victory
seems certain to have some effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very independent place,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass., a Gore supporter who has spent several days lately
campaigning for him in New Hampshire. ``The vice president will not
go to New Hampshire with any presumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley, who spent Monday urging Iowa supporters to go
to their caucus, left before midnight to fly to New Hampshire so
they would be in place for the early morning news shows and a full
day of campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   By being damaged in Iowa, Bradley now faces the prospect of
losing support of moderate independents in New Hampshire to Sen.
John McCain, the Arizona Republican who did not formally campaign
in Iowa and leads Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in polls in the next
major stop on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the caucuses, some Bradley supporters were
questioning whether he, like McCain, should have skipped Iowa and
begun his campaign in New Hampshire, where grass-roots organizing
and support of party regulars counts for less.
</P>
<P>
   In the last days of the Iowa campaign, Bradley began to lower
his sights _ and, he hoped, the media's expectations _ by saying he
would be satisfied with the 31 percent that Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., got against President Carter in Iowa in the 1980 caucuses.
Kennedy belittled that scenario in a weekend appearance in Cedar
Falls for Gore, recalling his showing 20 years ago and remarking:
``I don't ever remember making a victory statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The caucuses, in more than 2,000 precincts across the frigid
Midwestern landscape, were not only the beginning of the nominating
process but the conclusion of one of the most frenetic preseason
campaigns in many years.
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear that other potential Gore challengers were
staying out of the race, the two-man Democratic contest formed
quickly and sharply. The two former Senate colleagues dueled not
only about substantive issues, especially an appropriate federal
health care plan, but also presidential style and leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 56, sought to picture himself as a potentially bolder
leader than Gore, 51, whom he pictured as a creature of Washington
_ having grown up in the capital as the son of a senator and
quickly entering national politics himself. Gore, on the other
hand, faulted Bradley for leaving Congress in 1996 just as the
Democrats needed stalwarts to ``stay and fight'' the Republican
majorities in the House and Senate, especially then-House Speaker
Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Gore quickly lined up not only the support of a big majority of
major Democratic elected officials who have taken a position in the
race but also the AFL-CIO, one of the major building blocks of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   As Bradley first began his rounds in Iowa almost a year ago,
Gore's campaign seemed unfocused, and the situation got worse for
the vice president as the year progressed. But even with his effort
in some disarray, Gore's connections to the White House allowed him
an institutional edge and garnered endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Gore's approach to Iowa was a classic example of
how one-time state Democratic chairman David Nagle said a
presidential campaign in the state should be run: ``Organize,
organize, organize. Then get hot at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's caucus victory had a historical twist. In his first
presidential race in 1988, Gore refused to campaign in the state,
which he called ``a ridiculous test'' and ``an arcane procedure
that produces crazy results.'' But over the seven years that he has
been vice president, Gore has so assiduously courted Iowa Democrats
that Bradley could make little use of the earlier criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, by the end of the campaign, it was Bradley who was
complaining that the Iowa caucuses rewarded ``entrenched power,''
an acknowledgment of Gore's upper hand with the party elite.
</P>
<P>
   And Bradley lost some of his anti-politics image when he accused
Gore of starting the racially divisive attacks on Massachusetts
inmate Willie Horton in 1988. Gore had raised the furlough system
but never mentioned Horton by name.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said ``he wasn't going negative, and he went negative.
It made him look like a politician,'' Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was also bedeviled in the final days of the Iowa
campaign by questions about new bouts of an irregular heartbeat, at
least some of which may have been brought on by the stress of
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   More problematic for Bradley in rural, farm-oriented Iowa seemed
to be his voting record as a senator from New Jersey, the nation's
most densely populated state.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a single turning point in the Iowa Democratic
campaign, it came Jan. 8 during a debate in which Gore, pointing to
a farmer in the audience, asked Bradley why he had voted against
increased emergency aid for the flood-stricken Midwest in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Alan Bernstein and Patty Reinert contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
