<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-580(2TAKES)-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMOTHERS FAIL TO SEE CUBAN BOY IN MIAMI STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with new 6th graf to add comment from Lazaro Gonzalaz; new
9th, 10th grafs to expand explanation from Edgar; in 3rd graf from
end, deletes word `nonbinding') 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN with ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After waiting nearly five hours in a suburban airport
here Monday, the two Cuban grandmothers of Elian Gonzalez gave up
their effort to meet the boy and flew to Washington as their
custody battle moved to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers were scheduled to meet on Tuesday with members
of Congress, who have helped turn their fight into an international
tug of war.
</P>
<P>
   Their private twin-engine Learjet, provided by the National
Council of Churches, left Kendall-Tamiani Executive Airport just as
three of the grandmothers' relatives and their lead lawyer arrived
to talk with them _ without the only person they wanted to see,
Elian.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami police official said the plane was heading for
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmothers' departure, after a late-scheduled trip from
New York to Miami Monday morning, was the latest leg of their
four-day odyssey to bring the boy home to his father, who was
divorced from his mother. His mother drowned two months ago during
an escape from Cuba, but Elian survived, clinging for two days to
an inner tube in the Atlantic off Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez was clearly miffed by the women's departure.
``We feel very happy that they were here in Miami,'' Gonzalez said.
``We have tried to greet them with love. They have acted in a very
disappointing way toward the family. Elian got dressed up to meet
his grandmothers, and it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's grandmothers became ``frightened and scared'' about
coming to Miami, said Bob Edgar, general secretary of the National
Council of Churches. With other council officials, Edgar has been
shepherding the women since their departure from Havana on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see the thousands of people here in Miami,'' he said,
``marching and protesting, and you can imagine as very simple,
loving, caring grandparents that they would be frightened to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were safer to be out of harm's way, and that's why they
left. They have returned to Washington, D.C., and they will remain
there ready to come back at a moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar said he would stay in Miami another day to meet with the
relatives if they agreed to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier plans had called for the grandmothers to have dinner
with relatives who had been caring for Elian, but the 6 p.m. EST
dinner date came and went without the grandmothers' leaving the
airport. At 8 p.m., three of the relatives and their lead attorney,
Spencer Eig, left the house and headed for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really love him, they will come see him,'' said Elly
Carrera, 17, a Cuban-American who supports Elian's great-uncle
Lazaro Gonzalez in his appeal for custody of the boy and who was
standing outside the Gonzalez home, where the grandmothers were to
have dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously they don't love him,'' Ms. Carrera said. ``They are
speaking Castro's words. Castro wants to win. But we won't let him
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, scores of onlookers and media waited outside
the house. Inside, a cousin said Elian was watching a video of
``Home Alone 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's case started as a family feud and has erupted into an
international incident with anti-Castro Cuban-Americans urging that
he be reared in the United States and that his father be denied
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress, and in particular those from Florida,
seized upon the issue Monday, the lawmakers' first day back at work
after a two-month recess. Sen. Connie Mack and Rep. Bill McCollum,
both Florida Republicans, introduced bills to grant the boy
citizenship or permanent residency. Meanwhile, several House
Democrats offered other bills blocking them.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives, led by Lazaro Gonzalez and his family, have
claimed custody of the boy in defiance of the Clinton
administration and the pleas of the father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
to repatriate him. The grandmothers, who flew to New York on
Friday, are Raquel Rodriguez, mother of Elizabet Brotons Rodriguez,
Elian's mother, and Mariela Quintana, the father's mother.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All day Monday, plans had unfolded to bring the grandmothers to
the Little Havana home of Lazaro Gonzalez, a paternal great-uncle
of Elian, and his wife, Angela, and 21-year-old daughter,
Marisleysis.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Florman, a Justice Department spokeswoman, said
authorities had tried to arrange a meeting of family members at a
more neutral location.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grandmothers were not comfortable with a meeting at
Lazaro's house,'' Ms. Florman said. ``They want a private meeting
with the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Gonzalez family here and its publicists
had been going to some lengths to establish the impression of an
ideal, welcoming home for Elian. Rather than calling another
protest in support of the relatives, leaders of the Cuban-American
groups carpeted the sidewalk outside the house with pink, yellow
and red carnations.
</P>
<P>
   Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Republican member of Congress from Miami,
said while visiting the home early Monday: ``The family's looking
forward to the grandmas' coming. It's always been a family full of
love.'' Like other leaders of the exile community she urged that if
the father and grandmother wanted custody they come to Miami and
``testify in court where it can be decided impartially.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's grandmothers plan to meet Tuesday in Washington with
members of Congress, including Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn.,
who every year sponsors legislation to ease the trade embargo with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Just before embarking on their trip to the United States, which
led to a meeting with Attorney General Janet Reno and with Doris
Meissner, commissioner of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, the grandmothers had predicated any trip to the United
States, their first off Cuban soil, on retrieving Elian.
</P>
<P>
   But theirs and the administration's hands are tied by suits
filed in federal court here last week enjoining the administration
from repatriating Elian and asking for the right to apply for
political asylum. So instead they asked Ms. Reno to help organize a
visit with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers introduced three bills Monday, two in the House and
one in the Senate, to grant Elian citizenship or permanent
residency. They said their legislation would put the decision in
the hands of a Florida state judge instead of the federal
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, who sponsored the Senate bill with five other lawmakers,
said he wanted to take politics out of the decision. But state
judges in Florida are elected, and any judge in the Miami area,
where Elian is living with relatives, is likely to face tremendous
pressure to rule that the boy stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The lead sponsor of a companion bill in the House, McCollum,
said, ``Any decision made by a governmental agency is contrary to
his best interest and clearly against his mother's desires.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill proposed by House Democrats, including Reps. Robert
Menendez of New Jersey and Patrick J. Kennedy of Rhode Island,
would grant permanent residency instead of citizenship, to allow
Elian to decide his citizenship on his own when he is older.
</P>
<P>
   But another group of House members, including Reps. Charles B.
Rangel, D-N.Y., Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Ray LaHood, R-Ill.,
introduced a resolution to block the citizenship bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that this 6-year-old boy who lost his
mother in a tragic accident at sea should be reunited with his
father,'' Rangel said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In suing for custody in federal court here, Lazaro Gonzalez
maintains that he and his family can assure Elian a happier
upbringing than his father and the grandmothers, who live in the
Cuban town of Cardenas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0510 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETH     01-24 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SAYS CAMPAIGN IS ON RIGHT PATH
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: ADDS sentence to 2nd graf with Bradley trailing Gore in Iowa;
adds new 7th graf, With that ..., with Tsongas' widow appearing in
Bradley ad.) 
 (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ Despite concerns among some aides about the state
of his campaign, former Sen. Bill Bradley said Monday that he was
more convinced than ever that the course he chartered for his
presidential campaign more than a year ago was fundamentally
correct.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bradley's insurgent campaign has been battered
by negative news coverage and falling poll numbers, and many
political analysts have argued that he has not been sharp enough in
drawing distinctions with Gore or aggressive enough in responding
to the vice president's repeated attacks. With about a third of the
precincts reporting, Bradley was trailing Gore badly in the Iowa
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of his aides have recently raised questions about the
campaign's tactics in Iowa, complaining that it had been late
getting organized, slow to respond to Gore's criticisms and
inadequate in preparing for debates. One adviser described Iowa as
a ``shakedown tour'' for the Bradley organization.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Monday just before the Iowa caucuses,
Bradley suggested that if anything he had been too negative in his
battle with Gore, arguing that the ``rat-a-tat-tat'' of the race
might have turned off voters and drawn attention from his own
idealistic call to reform politics and end poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were trying to do a cookie-cutter campaign where you go
negative on somebody, there's a little textbook that you take that
says, chapter four, going negative, here are the five things you
do,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What adds to cynicism in politics is negative campaigning and
attack ads,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Bradley contends that he will try to stay above the
messy fray, his aides said they recognized that they, and Bradley's
prominent supporters, will need to strike back faster and perhaps
more fiercely against Gore when he goes on the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Bradley campaign began running a
television advertisement in New Hampshire on Monday in which Niki
Tsongas, the widow of former Sen. Paul E. Tsongas, D-Mass., accuses
the Gore campaign of distorting Bradley's record. During the 1992
presidential campaign, Tsongas made similar accusations against
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he realized his campaign had drifted from its
moorings last week when he heard the story of a New Hampshire woman
whose teen-age son apologized for getting sick because the family
had no health insurance. Her story, which brought tears to his
eyes, ``recentered'' him on the reasons he had entered the race,
particularly to create a system of near universal health insurance,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in the rat-a-tat-tat of politics, in the rush of the
media and the emphasis on tactics, you lose sight of why you're in
this,'' he said. But there may also be political reasons for
Bradley's wanting to step back from attacking Gore. Two weeks ago,
Bradley had been sharpening his criticism of the vice president,
even attacking a 15-year-old Senate vote by Gore that helped the
tobacco industry. But many analysts said Bradley's attacks gave a
sense of desperation in his camp.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also toned down his criticism of Bradley in recent
days. Asked whether he would return fire if Gore started attacking
him again in New Hampshire, site of the nation's first primary next
Tuesday, Bradley replied, ``You always have the option, of course,
to adopt the atomic bomb. But the point is, I'm going to try to
keep this thing positive.''
</P>
<P>
   To both his critics and supporters, Bradley's refusal to
aggressively attack Gore recalls his 1990 re-election campaign,
where he was very slow to respond to criticism by his opponent,
Christie Whitman, and almost lost the New Jersey Senate race. Some
political analysts argued that the race showed that Bradley was too
headstrong to adjust his strategies to deal with unforeseen or
shifting circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley denied that he was inflexible, saying: ``I think
there should be a distinction drawn between being inflexible and
being rooted. I'm rooted in what I know what I believe and what I
know I want to do. I'm flexible in how I want to achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no plans to change significantly his basic stump
speech in the coming weeks. But Bradley offered a glimpse Monday of
the message he intends to emphasize in New Hampshire: that he would
be better at maintaining the nation's prosperity because he has a
track record of predicting changes in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been on the point, meaning I have been there a few
years before other people,'' he said, referring to his early
support in the 1980s for cutting the deficit, reducing Third World
debt and simplifying the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also sought to cast himself as the best candidate for
managing the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he would increasingly highlight the economic
benefits of his health-care proposal, which he said would provide
the equivalent of a $25 billion-a-year tax cut for people earning
less than $50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is those families don't know yet what I'm trying to
do,'' Bradley said of lower-income voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
