<HEADLINE>
BUSH CLAIMS `RECORD-SHATTERING VICTORY' IN IOWA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush emerged the clear
winner in the Iowa Republican caucuses Monday night, the first
official vote in the 2000 nominating contest for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's victory was tempered by a stronger than expected
showing by businessman Steve Forbes and a respectable finish by
former Reagan administration official Allen Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   With most precincts reporting, returns showed Bush, son of the
former president, receiving 41 percent of the Republican vote,
Forbes with 30 percent and Keyes, 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer received 9 percent of the
caucus vote; Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, 1 percent; and Sen. John
McCain, who did not campaign in the state, &UR;  &LR; 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's finish ahead of Forbes was less than forecast by
some of his top Iowa supporters, the governor claimed ``a
record-shattering victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never dreamt I'd be able to get such a high vote,'' Bush
told reporters at his hotel in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to supporters before setting off to New Hampshire,
Bush described his vote as ``a victory of a message that is
conservative and compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey of caucus participants by Voters News Service on Monday
evening found Bush supporters saying that moral values and taxes
were their top criteria in choosing which candidate to support.
</P>
<P>
   The VNS survey also found that many of Bush's caucus supporters
picked him because they believe he can defeat the Democratic
nominee in the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, according to the survey, did better than Bush among
voters whose top priority was conservative values.
</P>
<P>
   For all the energy and money candidates pour into Iowa, the
record of those who finished ahead in recent years shows none
reaching the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Keyes' third-place, double-digit showing, the
candidates' finishing order has been forecast for more than five
months, since Bush's convincing victory in the Iowa GOP's straw
poll in August.
</P>
<P>
   The display of Bush's organizational strength in the straw poll,
along with his record-setting fund raising, drove three nationally
known Republicans from the race. With the exit of Lamar Alexander,
Elizabeth Dole and Dan Quayle, only Forbes remained with pockets
deep enough to challenge Bush in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Although Forbes invested millions here _ mostly from his
personal publishing fortune _ he made no predictions about
upsetting Bush. Instead, the New Jersey businessman forecast that
his showing would surprise observers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's name was on the ballot, but he did not campaign in Iowa
or attempt to build the kind of organization needed for a good
showing in the state's caucus system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just very pleased that 5 percent would come out in the
cold to vote for us,'' he told reporters in New Hampshire. ``That's
five percent more than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's decision not to join the farm-state fray put off the
GOP's first truly competitive presidential contest until New
Hampshire, where McCain on Monday held his 100th town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator has front-runner status over Bush in some
recent New Hampshire polls. Forbes runs third.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was unfazed about the prospects of his rivals picking up
momentum in Iowa that might propel them past him in the Feb. 1
Granite State primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of New Hampshire don't pay a great deal of
attention to what happens in Iowa,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in Hanover, N.H., his fifth public event of the day,
McCain told several hundred supporters,``the preliminaries are
over. The playoff starts tomorrow, and we are going to win that
playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced we are in for a history making seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   The distant sixth-place finish by Hatch almost certainly doomed
his bid for the Republican presidential nomination. Early Monday he
said he must finish fourth or better in the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've contributed to this race,'' Hatch said.
``There are a lot of issues (in) the forefront (now) that were not
being discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   Since December, Forbes has aggressively accused Bush of breaking
a no-tax pledge in Texas. The publishing magnate even recruited a
Houston woman to appear in a television commercial criticizing the
governor for proposing a sales tax increase after his promise not
to.
</P>
<P>
   Although Iowans look dimly on what they consider negative ads,
one campaign's poll showed Bush's rating for honesty being cut in
half in Iowa over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   In the final week before the caucuses, Bush found himself
answering repeated questions on abortion, a testament to the
strength of social conservatives in the Iowa GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been pressed on his anti-abortion commitment to the
point that one staff member told reporters to expect less access to
the candidate so he could talk about other issues his aides believe
are less volatile.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned, Bush has confirmed his commitment to a
constitutional amendment banning abortions as outlined in the
Republican Party platform since Ronald Reagan was president.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush has refused to say he would appoint only
anti-abortion justices to the Supreme Court or select a vice
presidential running mate based on his or her position on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's showing in Iowa was better than the 37 percent,
historically the high water mark, received by Bob Dole in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, George H.W. Bush led Ronald Reagan in Iowa. But Reagan
went on two terms as president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Pat Robertson and the Christian Coalition roared into a
strong second-place finish ahead of Vice President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Pat Buchanan nearly defeated Bob Dole here, then went
on to upset him in New Hampshire, stopping Dole's momentum and
raising doubts about the strength of his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
