<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SUPERSONICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER PAYTON'S EARLY EXIT, KNICKS MAKE IT INTERESTING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORk _ After all the yearning for an All-Star point guard in
New York, Gary Payton's annual visit to Madison Square Garden
lasted less than 11 minutes Monday night. The floor leader of the
Seattle SuperSonics was ejected after two straight technical fouls
in the first quarter, a development that on paper appeared
incredibly lucky for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But then this Shammond Williams character came off the bench, a
virtual unknown who started knocking down long 3-pointers and
throwing down monstrous dunks. And Vin Baker and Brent Barry became
flammable from the outside. Just like that, one of the more
entertaining games of New York's season unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell helped the Knicks eventually
wake from their slumber, combining for 51 points in a 112-106
victory over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing (18 points in 30 minutes) was clutch, too, putting
back a missed shot with 2 minutes 26 seconds to play to give the
Knicks a 6-point cushion and then helping push the lead to 105-96
with 1:14 left when he found Houston for a 3-pointer as Ewing drove
down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Barry finished with 21 points apiece, and Williams led
the Sonics with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won their fifth straight at the Garden with a superb
finish, but not before a wild incident in the first quarter
severely tainted the game.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was ejected with 1:28 left in the first quarter by the
referee Ted Bernhardt, who was maybe 25 feet away from Payton when
he threw him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Without one of the top players in the game, the Sonics could
have wilted. But they regrouped and played as well as possible
until the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle closed to 93-91 with a 4-point play. Barry made a
3-pointer and Kurt Thomas was charged for a foul against Ruben
Patterson, who made the free throw with 5:01 left to raise serious
concerns as to whether the Knicks could hold on.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Payton had the appearance of a gift for the Knicks. But
Williams, the diminutive second-year point guard who had scored
only 12 points all season (with a career high of 3), was
scintillating in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Fearless and spry at barely 6 feet tall, he went through the
heart of the Knicks' defense at one juncture in the third quarter
and dunked hard.
</P>
<P>
   Baker was also doing what he could to share the scoring burden,
dipping his shoulder into Marcus Camby and Ewing until he found a
sliver of light in which to release his soft jump hook. The Knicks
were doing their fair share to give the Sonics confidence, too,
failing to block out on defense and allowing some of the easiest
put-back dunks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   With less than eight minutes to play, Seattle led by 3 points
before the Knicks came alive. Houston's shots began falling, his
teammates passed the ball to the open man on the fast break and
instantly they transformed themselves into a transition team to
combat Seattle's resilience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
