<SLUG> BC-IOWA-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIFFICULT CHOICE FOR IOWA DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ About half of the standing-room-only crowd in
a math classroom at Hoover High School were wearing Bradley
stickers, and half had Gore buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was no discussion of the two Democrats' relative
merits at the caucus here, and the only drama of the evening came
when one woman's cell phone rang at a quiet moment: Would her young
neighbor be able to baby-sit at short notice? (Yes, as it turned
out.)
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, by a simple head count, the precinct chairman
tallied 43 people for Vice President Al Gore and 50 for former Sen.
Bill Bradley, meaning that three of the precinct's delegates went
to each man. Then, polite applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle is beforehand,'' said Peter Larsen, a retired
Lutheran pastor who supports Bradley. ``Most of us had been to five
or six rallies and made up our minds before we came.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet like all but one of a couple of dozen people interviewed at
the caucus, Larsen also said he liked both men and found the
decision a close call. ``I could have supported either one of
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Bradley supporter, John Hunt, a 68-year-old investment
banker, said all his years of caucus-going had been similarly, and
quite pleasantly, dull. ``It's never very confrontational; we're
Iowans,'' he said, adding: ``Albert Gore's a fine man. So is Bill
Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   The two camps certainly looked exactly the same, with both
including men and women of all ages, and both nearly all white;
They split the minority vote, one and one.
</P>
<P>
   All of the caucus-goers seemed to have been extensively courted
by both candidates. One woman, Christine Marchand, a 27-year-old
market researcher, said she made up her mind the previous evening
to vote for Bradley, after a call from an old New Jersey friend of
the senator. When he couldn't answer one of her questions, he put
Marcia Aronoff, Bradley's senior policy adviser, on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   A number of those who ended up choosing Bradley said they did so
because of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about how easy it's going to be for the Republicans to
paint Gore as evil and run clips of all the nice things he said
about Clinton,'' said Stuart Klugman, 51.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supporters, on the other hand, more often pointed to
specific issues of interest to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a research scientist and Gore has always been strong on
funding for research,'' said Don Mattson, 49. ``It was that and
Gore on the environment, though I wouldn't have been disappointed
with Bradley, either. It wasn't quite a flip of a coin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
