u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUDGET-     01-24 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHAT HAPPENS IF THE BUDGET SURPLUS IS REAL? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has been a large dose of unreality to the presidential
debates from the start. Each of the major candidates proposed
paying for initiatives by tapping surpluses that were more
speculative than real. True, the Congressional Budget Office had
told them that the federal surplus, outside the Social Security
program, would equal about $1 trillion over the next 10 years. But
that estimate was based on a highly debatable assumption _ that
Congress would adhere to onerous spending caps it set in 1997 to
achieve a balanced budget. Those caps were broken open this year, a
measure of the difficulty in meeting them. If scrupulously observed
the next two years, the caps would require Congress to cut
non-military discretionary programs by an astonishing 30 percent
and then maintain the programs at that level for the next decade.
Virtually no one expects Congress to inflict that much pain. Under
the more reasonable assumption that Congress keeps current programs
intact, there will be no federal surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bill Bradley said that future surpluses would pay for his
$650 billion, 10-year program of universal health insurance. George
W. Bush's plan would cut taxes by more than $1 trillion, courtesy
of the surplus. Even the fiscal moderates, Al Gore and John McCain,
proposed paying for slimmed-down versions of their opponents' plans
with future surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Misleading proposals all _ perhaps until Wednesday at about 10
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   At that time the Congressional Budget Office, Congress' official
scorekeeper, is expected to turn the presidential debates upside
down with revised estimates of projected surpluses that do not
depend on future spending cuts. Nobody knows for certain what the
new estimates will be. But a range of informed observers expect the
budget office to tell the politicians that because of the hot
economy, they will have hundreds of billions more, and perhaps as
much as $1 trillion more, to allocate over the next 10 years. In
this new estimate, the surplus could hit $1 trillion even if
Congress does not cut spending by a dime.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's big-spending health plan and Bush's generous tax cuts
would no longer look so extravagant. The Gore and McCain programs
might look a tad meek. Thus the budget office numbers could change
the tenor of Wednesday night's debates in New Hampshire. Gore and
McCain will find it harder to label their opponents profligate.
Bradley can say, with the budget office as his authority, that his
health plan no longer threatens to eat into Medicare, Medicaid and
all the other federal programs that Gore has charged that Bradley's
plan would shred. Bush can ask McCain why he opposes a big tax cut
that not only robs the Democrats of money for their spending plans
but also could leave billions for deficit reduction, another cause
popular among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even a new $1 trillion surplus _ if the number turns
out to be that high _ would not be impervious to congressional
spending plans. The new estimates do not take account of the fact
that Congress is virtually certain to spend more on the military
and farmers. They take no account of the cost of extending tax
credits for corporate research and development and for other
popular purposes. The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a
liberal research group, estimates that these items alone could
knock about $200 billion out of the 10-year surplus.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Medicare costs are projected to double, as a
share of economic output, over the next 30 years, so Congress will
need to pass a major overhaul. Subtract hundreds of billions more
for that purpose, and the surplus grows steadily smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Though it is hard not to rejoice at a $1 trillion surplus, it
does pose political dangers. The money could encourage Congress to
put off reforming Medicare, making future changes all the more
wrenching. It could give cover for Congress to pass tax cuts as
large as, or larger than, those Bush proposes, making it
politically impossible to recover the money once it is needed for
Medicare, covering the uninsured or fixing the nation's schools. So
while the extra money represents opportunity for Bradley supporters
to spend it on liberal causes and for Bush supporters to return it
in a tax cut, it poses political dangers for many politicians in
between.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the revised estimates are issued, voters will find
themselves facing pretty much the same choices tomorrow that they
face today. Vote for Bradley if you want to pursue big-ticket items
like universal health insurance while letting most other
initiatives slide. Vote for Bush if you think the best thing to do
with federal revenue is to return it to taxpayers even if that
means shredding some existing federal programs. Vote for Gore or
McCain for programs that pose less fiscal risk if sunny budget
estimates turn out wrong. But even if the broad choices remain
familiar, an extra $1 trillion added to the budget office estimate
will inject a new element of passion into the primary debates.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
