<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUTOWSKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERBERT S. GUTOWSKY, 80, MEDICAL PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert S. Gutowsky, who pioneered the use of the technique
of nuclear magnetic resonance for determining the structure of
molecules, died on Jan. 13 at a hospital in Urbana, Ill. Dr.
Gutowsky, who lived in Urbana since 1948, was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The technique gave chemists a new analytical tool to join X-ray
crystalography and other advanced techniques. A substance
undergoing NMR analysis is placed in a magnetic field and exposed
to electromagnetic radiation. The radiation is partly absorbed by
the substance, and analysis of the spectrums of the absorbed
radiation permits a chemist to determine the molecular structure of
the target substance.
</P>
<P>
   A similar technique was developed for clinical use, allowing
medical technicians to obtain detailed images of parts of the body.
</P>
<P>
   Gutowsky, an emeritus professor at the University of Illinois,
was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and a fellow of
the American Association for the Advancement of Science. Among his
awards were the 1977 National Medal of Science and the 1983 Wolf
Prize in Chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-24-00 2338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000124.0516 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-24 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ANIMAL-MUTILATION-NYT     01-24 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-MUTILATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE SHEDS LIGHT ON ANIMAL-MUTILATION VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLIP TERRACE, N.Y. _ When law enforcement officials searched
the bedroom of a 27-year-old in this Long Island suburb one night
in 1998, it was not the collection of a half-dozen semiautomatic
rifles and shotguns that most unnerved them. Nor was it the poster
of a Nazi storm trooper.
</P>
<P>
   What stunned them, they said, were the fish tank full of mice, a
pair of high heels coated with dried blood and the contents of 71
animal-mutilation videos with titles like ``Vanessa's Frog Stomp''
and ``Debby the Destructor.''
</P>
<P>
   In one videotape, officials said, a woman's foot impaled a
writhing frog with a stiletto heel. In another, a woman's hand
reached down to burn a mouse with a cigarette. ``In all my years on
the job, I've never seen anything this sick before, this
depraved,'' said Roy Gross of the Suffolk County Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, which charged the man, Thomas
Capriola, with animal cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, now 29, was investigated after his ex-girlfriend
called Gross' agency to say she had helped Capriola produce the
videos. A trial date for the misdemeanor charge has not been set.
But the case, along with a similar one in Los Angeles scheduled to
go to court Tuesday, is calling attention to a subculture of
animal-mutilation videos that prompted Congress to pass a law
banning the sale of such films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that these charges ultimately have very little
merit to them,'' said Capriola's lawyer, Paul Gianelli. His client
has pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But the authorities say Capriola was a maker of so-called crush
videos, which cater to a male sexual fetish in which viewers become
aroused by watching women, usually in high heels, stomp on small
animals. Capriola, they say, filmed female friends as they killed
hundreds of small animals, then sold the videos and bloodied high
heels through a Web site called ``Crush Goddess'' and classified
ads in pornographic magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Crush films and videos have been made since the 1950s, but only
in the last five years or so have they emerged from the
underground, as advertisements for them have spread from
pornographic magazines to the Internet. The Humane Society of the
United States has counted about 2,000 titles since it began its
monitoring in 1997. They sell for $30 to $300 each.
</P>
<P>
   The videos' increased visibility has even extended to
television, where ``NYPD Blue'' and ``The Practice'' have featured
subplots about crush fetishists. Meanwhile, animal rights advocates
have staged protests and lobbied Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Richard C. Richards, a philosophy professor at California State
Polytechnic University in Pomona who has studied perversions, said
that about 1,000 American men have the crush fetish. ``I think it's
wrong to demonize these things,'' he said. ``These people won't
stop. They can't. Very few of them want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Artwork from Pompeii shows the crush fetish may have existed as
far back as ancient Rome, Richards said. But modern technology has
allowed crush videomakers to sell their products on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The law Congress passed in November makes it a federal offense
to create or distribute ``a depiction of animal cruelty'' for
``commercial gain,'' with penalties ranging from a fine to five
years in prison. Exceptions are made for ``educational'' and
``artistic'' works. ``We tried to get to the folks who are
distributing these things,'' said Rep. Elton Gallegly, a Republican
from Ventura County, Calif., who introduced the bill. ``Let's face
it. It is an economic-driven activity.''
</P>
<P>
   But both Capriola and Gary Lynn Thomason, the defendant in the
Los Angeles County crush video case, will not be tried under the
new federal law because they were arrested before it passed.
Thomason has pleaded not guilty to misdemeanor charges of animal
cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Capriola's lawyer, Gianelli, has asked the judge to dismiss the
case against his client on several counts, including lack of
evidence and technicalities related to the search warrant,
according to court records. He said Capriola would not talk about
the case. Capriola could face up to one year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the seized tapes, officials said, they found shipping
records to hundreds of individuals. ``If you want to go on a diet,
these videos are the way to go,'' Gross said. ``You'll lose 20
pounds after watching one of these.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
