<SLUG> BC-NY-SOCCER-THIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANCY FOOTWORK FAILS THIEF, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The police say Ben-Msyly Gil-Elie was a quick-footed
street criminal with a cosmopolitan touch. He dressed well. He
spoke four languages. He worked the streets of midtown, preying on
Japanese tourists and businessmen in a most unusual way: by
imitating a renowned soccer star while picking their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Gil-Elie, 29, of Queens, was charged with grand larceny and
attempted grand larceny Monday after the police said they caught
him trying to steal a wallet from a merchant mariner in midtown
Manhattan on Sunday afternoon. Since his arrest, the police said,
he has been identified in lineups as the culprit in four similar
thefts and is a suspect in 10 others.
</P>
<P>
   The police said his method was bizarre and always the same.
Canvassing the streets near midtown hotels, he approached his
victims and flashed a telephone calling card with an image of
Hidetoshi Nakata, a midfielder for a Rome soccer club whose career
is closely followed in his native Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know this player?'' he would ask, and then begin a
series of soccer moves, circling his victims, feinting kicks at
their shins and knees and bumping them as if trying to slip past
them on a soccer field. ``Like he was dribbling a soccer ball,''
said Sgt. James Molloy of the grand larceny unit of the Manhattan
North Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gil-Elie slipped past his victims, the police said, he
had taken their wallets. He made off with cash and credit cards,
many of which were swiftly run up to their debt limits with illegal
purchases or cash advances, Molloy said.
</P>
<P>
   The police said he was so confident in his technique that he
often merely strutted away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't even run,'' Molloy said.
</P>
<P>
   The police had been trying to catch the pickpocket, who became
known as ``the soccer guy'' in the precinct, since his antics were
first reported in October. He was arrested Sunday after Molloy and
Officer Tito Ramos saw him trying the routine and jostling a
Japanese sailor who was in Manhattan on shore leave.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos caught him after he fled from an accomplice's car into a
subway tunnel. Gil-Elie was arraigned Monday on two counts, but his
accomplice remains at large. Other charges were being reviewed.
``He is a suspect in other crimes,'' said Sgt. Andrew McInnis, a
police spokesman, ``and the investigation is ongoing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
