<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-STEVENS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELONY DRUG CHARGE FILED AGAINST RANGERS' STEVENS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Stevens of the New York Rangers was charged with a felony
Monday, one day after his arrest at a Collinsville, Ill., motel
with what the police said was crack cocaine in his possession.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, 34, was charged with unlawful possession of a
controlled substance of less than 15 grams, a Class IV felony, in
Madison County Circuit Court in Edwardsville, Ill., a suburb of St.
Louis. Class IV is the lowest felony charge under Illinois law. He
was released on $15,000 bail, and he and his lawyers declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum penalty for a Class IV felony is a jail term of one
to three years, said Maj. Ed Delmore, the assistant chief of the
Collinsville Police Department. It is not unusual, however, for
first-time offenders to receive probation of one to three years, or
to have their record expunged, if they complete a substance abuse
program, Delmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens also met Monday with Dan Cronin, an employee of the
National Hockey League and the NHL Players' Association substance
abuse program. Stevens will begin treatment, said Frank Brown, the
league's vice president of media relations.
</P>
<P>
   According to one hockey official, it will take at least six to
eight weeks for Stevens to complete the program. Stevens must then
complete outpatient treatment, the official said. The regular
season ends on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens was in St. Louis on Saturday night for the Rangers' game
against the Blues. Afterward, the police said, he and several
teammates, who were not identified, went to a nightclub in Sauget,
Ill. Stevens later took a cab to the Travelodge in Collinsville and
had three to five grams of crack cocaine when he was arrested there
at 7 a.m. Sunday, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Three people arrested with Stevens remained in jail Monday on
$15,000 bail.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to two hockey officials, Stevens will enter the second
phase of the substance abuse program run by the league and the
players association.
</P>
<P>
   Several people in the Rangers' organization said privately that
this was a cry for help on Stevens' part.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the problems he has,'' the team captain Brian Leetch,
who is a close friend of Stevens and his family, said Monday.
``He's been educated about them. When he comes out, he'll be in the
same situation as he was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Smith, the Rangers' president and general manager, said
Monday that he did not know whether Stevens would rejoin the
Rangers once he completed his treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is scheduled to make $3.2 million this season, the last
of his contract, according to figures provided by the players
association.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Checketts, the Madison Square Garden president, was upset
with the way the Collinsville police handled Stevens' arrest,
citing what he called a sensationalistic news release about the
arrest with the headline, ``Hockey Player Charged With Soliciting
Prostitute and Possession of Drug Paraphernalia; Drug Charges for
Crack Cocaine Possession Are Pending''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
