<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``A VAST CONSPIRACY'' &QL; 
By Jeffrey Toobin (Random House, $25.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toobin's last book was about the O.J. Simpson trial. We've had a
hard time deciding whether he has come up in the world or plunged
to new depths by taking on this more recent tangle of thorns, the
Clinton sex scandal. In the end, of course, he has traded up _
there was no blood shed in the White House, merely a shedding of
judgment and esteem and familial accord. We spoke with Toobin after
the Simpson book was released, and he told us that as a lawyer he
was both horrified and fascinated by the trial, like a passing
motorist gaping at a terrible accident. This time, Toobin has
jumped out of his vehicle and is selling tickets, tour guide
extraordinaire. He covered the Clinton saga for ``The New Yorker,''
and he offers all the details, including Paula Jones' relentlessly
explicit descriptions of Clinton's flawed anatomy. And, of course,
we knew as we read it that we, like Toobin, were no longer just
driving by. We became part of the ghoulish scene. &QL; 
``AMERICAN FAN'' &QL; 
By Dennis Perrin (Spike, $23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   errin offends just about everybody in this look at sports in
America, and it's great fun watching him do it. Christians take a
beating in the section about ``religious'' athletes. Radio
talk-show hosts are taken to task for being ``White, male,
heavyset, obsessive, egomaniacal, brusque,'' and only once removed
from the people who call them. Shaquille O'Neal, Nike and college
basketball coaches (with ``Nike bucks stuffed in their G-strings'')
come under scrutiny in a chapter on sports marketing. Even Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa suffer under Perrin's analysis of the home
run race, during which ``Big Mac was the All-American boy . . .
(and) Sosa the Dominican was made his comic sidekick: less Sancho
Panza (McGwire was no wayward Quixote), more a smiling Tonto to
McGwire's Lone Ranger.'' Women are left out altogether, and we
should be grateful. ``I deal almost exclusively with male sports
and male fans,'' Perrin writes, ``for the simple reason that this
is where the true lunacy lies.'' &QL; 
``THE COMFORTS OF HOME'' &QL; 
By Merritt Ierley (Potter, $30) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1799, the family of a Philadelphia woman named Elizabeth
Drinker purchased a ``shower bath'' _ a framework holding a
container of water that would fall on a bather's head when she
pulled a cord. It was an odd luxury. ``I bore it better than I
expected,'' Elizabeth wrote in her diary, ``not having been wett
(SIC, CORRECT) all over att (SIC, CORRECT) once for twenty-eight
years past.'' When Thomas Jefferson moved into the White House in
1801, there was only a privy out back. Jefferson, who had witnessed
innovations in modern convenience in France, requested that a water
closet be installed (it was, but not until 1804, leaving Jefferson
to suffer in the privy for three long years). Ierley charts the
evolution of comfort and convenience in the American home,
beginning with the turn of the 19th century; jumping to 1860,
before the mass-production spurred by the Civil War; and ending
with 1920s to the present, with America on the cutting edge of
household convenience. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``JAMES JOYCE'' &QL; 
By Edna O'Brien (Viking, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all its great writers, James Joyce's relationship with
Ireland is the most contradictory. ``He determined to reinvent the
city where he had been marginalized, laughed at and barred from
literary circles,'' O'Brien writes. ``He would be the poet of his
race. In one of his early verses he likened himself to a stag,
antlers charging upon the land.'' That sets the tone for this
wonderful volume from the ``Penguin Lives'' series of short
biographies. O'Brien reveals Joyce's tumultuous ties to his mother,
who bore 16 children, and to the Catholic Church; his sexual
appetite for Nora Barnacle, the common girl from Galway who would
be his wife (and who would never read beyond the first pages of
Ulysses; his attractions to other women; his struggle to find
acceptance for his work; and his self-absorption and eccentricity.
``He was a tragic man with a staggering genius for whom humor was a
weapon,'' O'Brien says. Or, as another writer put it, he was ``a
Dante who had lost the key to his own inferno.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
