<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO SPEND ING MAY BE UP TO VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   voters on how to spend the state's tobacco settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Key lawmakers say it's not that they don't want to decide how to
spend the $3.1 billion; it's that they're afraid any decision they
make will be irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   That's because two initiatives are headed for the November
ballot that, if passed, would nullify anything the Legislature
might do.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers are still a long way from agreeing on a plan. The
debate promises to be one of the biggest fights of the session,
along with growth controls and taxes for a new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It starts this week, as Gov. Jane Hull, House Speaker Jeff
Groscost and Senate President Brenda Burns begin serious
discussions. Groscost said he's nearly ready to unveil his plan
that he wants to go directly to the ballot, and Burns and Hull have
their own ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a contentious issue. Everybody has an idea
how it should be spent,'' Groscost said. ``I don't have any desire
to shed the blood, sweat and tears on our floor for a proposal that
in the end is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost wants to spend the money in three areas: tobacco use
prevention, especially among kids; public health; and some benefit
to taxpayers, such as a tax cut or college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said he prefers the scholarship program to tax cuts.
Michigan has devoted $86 million of its settlement to scholarships,
while Nevada will spend 40 percent of its money on a similar
program. Children would have to meet specific academic standards
and agree not to use tobacco _ and illegal substances _ to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where that tax cut might filter back to me as two or three
dollars a year . . . by the time the average household has a child
go to college. . . . You could see a benefit that's sizable to the
taxpayers at a point when they could actually use it,'' Groscost
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships would be an easy sell with voters, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, however, wants to put most of the money in a trust fund,
as Kansas, Louisiana and Minnesota have done. The money, except for
about $175 million in upfront cash, would be protected in the fund,
meaning only the interest would be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Burns, R-Glendale, and Hull have been reluctant to take the
matter to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer a legislative solution,'' Burns told GOP colleagues
in a meeting last week. But she said she's still willing to
consider putting the issue on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest concern is the rush to spend money that's not there.
The state will receive the money over 25 years, and there's no
guarantee that all of the money will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is writing us a check for $3.1 billion,'' she said.
Burns would like to spend some of the money on health care for the
elderly and medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, meanwhile, said she wants all of the money spent on health
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, she supports funding for a new state health lab,
rural and community health care and behavioral health care. She
also wants to add health coverage for the state's uninsured and put
some money in a trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   She does not support Groscost's scholarship proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's preference still is to direct it to health
care,'' said Debi Wells, Hull's health adviser. ``But you can't
ignore the fact the door has been opened to education.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said Hull wants a comprehensive solution that could head
off one or both of the initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, called the Healthy Arizona Initiative 2, would
fully fund a law passed by voters in 1996 to pay for preventative
health-care programs for children and add health-care coverage for
the uninsured and working poor. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Chris.Moeser(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(602) 444-8069.
</P>
</TEXT>
